<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE ISN'T SO THIN FOR DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It took the Anaheim Mighty Ducks two years to
get back to the Stanley Cup playoffs and now, after only three
games, they are one loss away from elimination.
</P>
<P>
   But the the Ducks weren't looking for any sympathy at Disney Ice
on Monday even though they head into tonight's Game 4 trailing the
Detroit Red Wings 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated,'' forward Paul Kariya said. ``There is no
sense getting down. There are a lot worse things going on in the
world then losing a hockey game. You have to keep things in
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, tragedies such as those in Kosovo and at Columbine High
School have a way of putting even the playoffs in their proper
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching the Columbine High School thing for five
days now,'' said Guy Hebert. ``It (hockey) is our job, but at the
end of the day I went home and kissed my wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of bad things happening in the world. I may
have had a bad day, but I'm fine and my family is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks are in a seemingly impossible hole _ the New York
Islanders were the last team to rally from a 3-0 series deficit, in
the second round of the 1975 playoffs against Pittsburgh _ but
Hebert insists he's having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you before the season that I was going to play every
day, go home and come back the next day with a smile on my face,''
he said. ``I see no reason to change that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the playoffs) are what you play for and that's why I'm
still excited to play tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks would love to make at least one more trip to Detroit
(for Game 5 on Thursday), especially since it would mean that they
snapped the Red Wings' playoff winning streak against them at seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it tough on Detroit,'' Ducks coach Craig
Hartsburg said. ``We can't be down, we want to show some pride and
make it as hard as we can. There are only two things we can control
_ our attitude and work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer the Ducks hang around, the more valuable playoff
experience they gain, to say nothing of some confidence heading
into next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would give us a sense of accomplishment,'' Kariya said.
``That we've gotten better and learned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great season to this point and we want to try and
finish it off right,'' Hebert said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Grimson grounded: The Ducks will be without Stu Grimson, who
was suspended for one game by the NHL for his cross-check on Kris
Draper on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Salei to try: Ruslan Salei said he hopes to play despite a
right- shoulder injury that limited him to less than six minutes on
the ice Sunday. The young defenseman said he has something to
prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to come back and prove to myself and the coach that I
can play better than the first two games,'' he said. ``I want to
come back and play the way I did the whole season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
