<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS WIN A BIG ONE OVER CHARLOTTE, 91-84 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ All of the adversity the Knicks have weathered
this season may have served as a primer for this playoff push.
After all of the ultimatums and roster unrest they have faced,
little seems to disturb a rhythm that has developed at just the
right time.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were just unflappable enough in a game that may end
up having as much impact on their playoff fate as any other this
season. Needing to create separation and tuck a potential
tie-breaker under their belts, the Knicks carried on without
Patrick Ewing and had just enough cushion to hold off the Charlotte
Hornets, 91-84, Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with 19 points from Latrell Sprewell _ who hit a
game-sealing bank shot with 47 seconds left _ and seven blocked
shots from Marcus Camby as part of a defensive effort that held the
Hornets' Elden Campbell to just 3-for-14 shooting and 8 points. The
Knicks are 24-21, and their third straight victory put them solidly
in eighth place, a half-game out of seventh, and left them a game
and a half over the ninth-place Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   But the finish did not come without some drama. The Knicks, who
held a 16-point lead with 5 minutes 40 seconds left in the game,
came unglued once Camby went to the bench to rest with 3:50
remaining. Without Camby, the Hornets' David Wesley drove the lane
uninterrupted. After three turnovers by the Knicks, Wesley capped a
17-4 run that left the Hornets within 3, at 84-81, with 1:05 left.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell returned by driving the baseline and banking a jumper
over Bobby Phills, who led the Hornets with 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   The suspense over how the Knicks would react after their
dramatic 20-point comeback victory in Miami on Sunday ended in the
first two minutes of the game. Instead of rolling out of bed with a
hangover, they came out as energetic as neon and simply turned the
tables on what the Hornets did to them in this same building on
April 7.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the Knicks' most humiliating moments of the season,
the Hornets took a 29-12 lead in the first quarter in that game and
the night was quickly over for the Knicks. This time, a more
desperate Knicks team came out with crisp ball movement, lively
defense from Patrick Ewing's replacement, Chris Dudley, and led
30-16 after the first quarter and 43-30 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   They knew better than to feel good about their edge. Just last
week, at Madison Square Garden, the Knicks held an 18-point
third-quarter lead against the Hornets, which crumbled to 1 before
Ewing's game-deciding runner with 24.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to protect their halftime lead, the Knicks came out and
maintained the same edginess to their game in the third quarter.
Each time the Hornets threatened to get into this game with a
3-pointer, the Knicks leaned on someone new. In the first quarter,
it was Allan Houston, in the second it was Sprewell, and in the
third, it was Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   After missing his first eight shots, Johnson hit his next three
to sustain the Knicks' double-digit lead in the third quarter.
Meanwhile, Dudley, Kurt Thomas and Camby took turns keeping
Campbell to just 8 points through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Much more unpredictable without Ewing, the Knicks moved the ball
swiftly and unselfishly until they found the open man in the first
quarter. Charlie Ward sprung open off screens for three 3-pointers,
while the unlikeliest source of points, Dudley, bounded around for
tip-ins and an out-of-character reverse layup for 7 first-half
points.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Coleman effectively took Dudley to the perimeter and
launched a series of jumpers to help pull the Hornets within 8
points in the first three minutes of the second quarter. But the
Knicks, using their defense to pressure the Hornets into 13
first-half turnovers, bounced back on the frenetic shooting of
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   At times, his frantic shooting _ which left him six for 11 in 17
minutes off the bench _ seemed out of step with the selfless nature
of the Knicks. But when Sprewell continued to knock down his
contortionist's shots, no one could have been happier than the
Knicks when his 12 first-half points filled the void left once
Houston got into early foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks knew how fragile cushions could be. And that's
why they played this game like everything could fall apart if they
lost. They knew the weight of this game on the playoff standing and
the pressure they'd be under if they fell out of the final spot
with just five games remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
