<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD CURB ONLINE WEAPONS SALES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an aide sitting at a computer clicked through Web sites
showing automatic handguns, assault rifles and other weapons for
sale on the Internet, Sen. Charles Schumer of New York on Monday
urged Congress to enact a law to further regulate the on-line gun
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, a Democrat, introduced the bill, the Internet Gun
Trafficking Act of 1999, in March and received little attention.
But on Monday, he said the high school shooting in Littleton,
Colo., had given urgency to the bill, and he hoped it would win
swift support.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that two students responsible for the
Colorado shooting purchased their guns on-line, but Schumer said he
believed that the Internet offered children the easiest means for
circumventing state and federal gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two glaring loopholes that allow kids and criminals
to get guns,'' Schumer said, ``and those are gun shows and the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts say such shows in states with lax gun laws are of
greater concern for guns being bought and sold outside the law.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's measure would require Web sites dedicated to gun sales
to be maintained by a federally licensed firearms dealer. The sites
would have to be registered with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms, and would prohibit the sites from encouraging private
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law was denounced on Monday by gun dealers who said
that nearly all of Schumer's concerns were addressed by existing
laws. Richard Feinberg, a licensed dealer in Norton, Mass., who
operates We Are Guns, one of the Web sites discussed by Schumer on
Monday, said he was required to follow all state and federal laws
for sales by computer and in person.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, interstate gun sales, whether conducted through the
Internet or not, are regulated by the Brady gun control law and
other federal regulations, and intrastate sales are governed by
state and local laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws are already in place,'' Feinberg said, adding that
the lack of consistent laws nationwide was a more important
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is not really an easy source for guns,'' Feinberg
said. ``The easiest source is a lax state, a state without strict
gun laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see no difference between a gun sold on-line and a gun
sold through a newspaper or magazine advertisement or by mail-order
catalogue. ``It's hard for me to understand why the Internet would
make in essence an illegal transaction easier or harder to do,''
said Eric J. Johnson, the director of the Forum for Electronic
Commerce at the Wharton School of Business, at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
