<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT HAS ROUGH DAY AT OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Kobe Bryant's jumpshot was ailing, his left thigh
throbbing from a week-old injury and his ears nearly chewed through
from a fourth-quarter lecture by his coach.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, a painful night for the 20-year-old
star-in-training.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant missed his first 11 field-goal attempts against the
Rockets and was scoreless until hitting a 15-foot jumper with 2:14
left in the third quarter. He finished with nine points _ his
lowest output in the last 24 games _ on 3-of-14 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, he and coach Kurt Rambis exchanged heated
words during a timeout late in the fourth quarter, the game already
far out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis was upset that Bryant strayed from the defensive plan
against Charles Barkley in the low post. Bryant tried to explain
his decision, but that only irritated the coach more. ``Don't do
it,'' Rambis shot back several times, then finally threw up his
hands: ``Fine, you're right. Do whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis wouldn't comment afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I had a feel for the game, as far as how we were gonna
play Charles,'' Bryant told reporters, explaining that Houston was
anticipating the double team and exploiting it. ``(Scottie) Pippen
had a back-door play set up, so I waited.''
</P>
<P>
   And drew Rambis' ire.
</P>
<P>
   As for his horrific shooting, Bryant had no explanation.
However, his thigh, deeply bruised in a collision with Golden
State's Felton Spencer last week, is heavily taped and aching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said it didn't hurt,'' he said. ``But I've
played plenty of games like that. It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   So the shooting line?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just missing (shots),'' he said. ``Just throwing up brick
after brick _ I was building projects out there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ What's the point?: Rambis continues to reserve a final
decision on who will start at point guard in the playoffs, but he
has conceded that rookie Tyronn Lue _ despite some exciting
performances _ will play only a bit role in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher, the current starter, and Derek Harper, the primary
backup, will continue in their present roles, though Harper might
return to the starting lineup. Lue will be ``a speciality guy,''
Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure at some point in time, he's gonna be a very good
guard in this league, but he still has a lot to learn,'' he said.
``You feel a lot more comfortable (with veterans).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
