<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MATTER WHAT, GLAUS CAN'T WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Troy Glaus for AL Rookie of the Year? Not
going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Glaus' hot start, he won't become the Anaheim Angels'
second Rookie of the Year because he played too much last season.
Glaus had 165 at-bats in 1998, exceeding the 130 at-bat limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that would come up at some point,'' Glaus, 22, said
of his nonrookie status. ``You don't play the game for rewards, and
I don't either. I play the game to win games. Having too many
at-bats to be eligible doesn't even bother me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be acknowledged for your accomplishments, but I
would give up that for a championship in a heartbeat. I'd rather be
known as a champion than a Rookie of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Monday's game, Glaus ranked among the league leaders
in five categories, including first in doubles (12) and extra-base
hits (15).
</P>
<P>
   The only Angels Rookie of the Year was Tim Salmon in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mo at DH: Mo Vaughn started at designated hitter for the
fourth game since being removed from the disabled list April 22.
Angels manager Terry Collins said there is no timetable to get
Vaughn back to first base because there is no reason to put any
extra strain on his sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who thinks you can put anybody at first base, you're
kidding yourself,'' Collins said. ``There's a lot to do over there.
What about stopping and starting, bunt plays, going over to the
tarp in foul territory to catch a popup? Outside of the catcher,
they handle the ball more than anybody on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Monday's game, Vaughn was hitting .273 (3 for 11)
since returning from the DL.
</P>
<P>
   __ Big stretch: The Angels began a homestand Monday night that
actually is going to be longer than three games. Their first two
homestands consisted of one three-game series each.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Angels get a chance to get comfortable at home, playing
eight games _ four against the Blue Jays and four against the White
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting to see how we react to that,'' Collins
said. ``You're comfortable here. You're used to the field so you
see the ball better. And most of the time you have people rooting
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Also: Salmon stands a good chance at being named the A.L.
Player of the Month for April. Going into Monday's game, he was
tied for seventh in the league in batting average (.373), tied for
third in homers (6) and second in RBIs (20). He also ranked among
the league's top 10 in seven other offensive categories. . . . Jeff
Huson started in place of Andy Sheets at shortstop Monday, and Todd
Green got the start in left field. . . . The Angels' magic number
this year so far is 4. When they score 4 or more runs, they're 7-3.
When they score 3 or fewer, they're 0-8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
