<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BO     04-27 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANES BEAT BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Uh oh.
</P>
<P>
   No one thought it was going to be an easy series. No one thought
it was going to be a short series. No one thought it was going to
be a one-sided series. It's not time to panic, but Bruins have to
be concerned about their situation. It's not grave but it sure
isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Kovalenko was credited with the go-ahead goal at 2:54 of
the third period Monday night and the Bruins wound up falling, 3-2,
to the Carolina Hurricanes in Game 3 of this Eastern Conference
quarterfinal. The Hurricanes have won two in a row and lead the
best-of-seven series, two games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Boston continues to struggle at home in the postseason. Since
1994, the Bruins are 2-12 at home in the playoffs and have lost
four straight.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding goal wasn't spectacular by any means. Fluky is a
much better description. Robert Kron, behind the net, threw the
puck out and it appeared to bank off goalie Byron Dafoe into the
cage. The play was reviewed because Kovalenko was in the crease,
but the puck was in there and under Dafoe before Kovalenko even
went in. It didn't appear that Kovalenko was even a factor in the
goal, though Bruins defenseman Darren Van Impe, who drilled
Kovalenko and sent him down on all fours, said the puck might have
gone off Kovalenko's skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was coming out in front of the net,'' said Van Impe. ``I
just got my stick into him and he fell. (Kron) must have passed the
puck out and it hit him and went in the net. That's all I saw. The
puck was in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of nonfactors, on the Bruins' side of things Dmitri
Khristich continues to be invisible. Pat Burns used him for only
nine shifts (7 minutes 21 seconds of ice time through 40 minutes)
and only 2:16 over three shifts in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be better, there's no two ways about that,'' said
Burns. ``He has to elevate his game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins dug themselves a hole early, falling behind just over
a minute into the game. Jeff O'Neill fired a shot from in tight
that Dafoe saved. But Gary Roberts was there for the rebound, and
his shot went off the goalie and into the net at 1:05. It was the
fastest playoff goal in Carolina/Hartford franchise history,
beating by one second Dean Evason's score for the Whalers against
Quebec in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:48, the Bruins finally broke through, at even strength, on
Sergei Samsonov's second playoff goal. Landon Wilson drove
defenseman Dave Karpa into the boards with a thunderous check,
opening room for Joe Thornton, along the right boards, to find
Samsonov skating down the left circle. He fired the puck past
Arturs Irbe to pull the Bruins even, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, the Bruins took the lead on the power play. They
had been 0 for 5 on the man advantage heading into the game and
went 0-2 in the first period despite moving the puck well.
</P>
<P>
   It was Anson Carter who finally cashed in, at 13:07. Ray Bourque
dished the puck across to the left point for Jason Allison, who
blasted a one-timer. Carter, who had been battling for position in
front of the net with defenseman Steve Chiasson, tipped it past
Irbe.
</P>
<P>
   That advantage lasted just over two minutes, as the Hurricanes
responded with a power-play goal of their own after Boston was
caught with too many men on the ice. Keith Primeau, who was a
favorite target of the FleetCenter faithful, spun in the right
circle and his shot went to Ray Sheppard in the left. Sheppard was
wide open with all kinds of time and snapped the shot past Dafoe at
15:20. That was the one that seemed to take the wind out of the
Bruins' sails.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard, who has played on six NHL teams, has been ferocious
against the Bruins in the playoffs. In eight games, he has 11
points, seven of them goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``As bad as this is, we have to regroup,'' said Dafoe. ``The
guys in here aren't down on each other and they shouldn't be.
Unfortunately we didn't get a win tonight but we have to come back
and definitely get 2 points Wednesday and go down and take one out
of there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
