<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METH-LABS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS GETS TOUGH ON METHAMPHETAMINE MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ The Kansas Bureau of Investigation has a message
for those who persist in making methamphetamine:
</P>
<P>
   You will be found. Your cooking laboratories will be seized.
</P>
<P>
   The proof, agents believe, is in the numbers. Already this year,
193 meth labs have been busted, more than in all of last year. And
with agents raiding two to three laboratories a day, the KBI
expects to reach the 500 mark before December.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics stagger agents who remember a meager four
seizures in 1994 and seven in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible accomplishment,'' said KBI Director Larry
Welch. ``It's been the KBI's top investigative priority for the
last three consecutive years, and I have no doubt it will continue
to be the top priority for the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The surge is explained by the wildfire spread of methamphetamine
in rural areas, as well as intensified law enforcement efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In Topeka, legislators are discussing ways to tighten Kansas
laws. A bill could bring Kansas' laws closer to those in Missouri,
which levies more serious sanctions for makers of illicit drugs. A
Missouri manufacturer could get a life sentence for making more
than a pound of meth, while a first-time Kansas violator could
spend less than four years in prison, under current law.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said it is difficult to say whether the Missouri law has
driven meth cooks into Kansas. But agents expect to hear that
argument when the Legislature returns to work on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the drug spreads through the state, Welch said, agents are
struggling to keep up with the burden meth is placing on the
state's laboratory investigation resources.
</P>
<P>
   The KBI has investigation laboratories in Topeka and Great Bend,
and this year added a lab in Pittsburg to respond to meth's rapid
growth in southeast Kansas. That's a hot spot because it is easy
for meth cooks to get chemicals in Oklahoma, agents believe.
</P>
<P>
   And if Welch and others have their way, another investigation
laboratory will be added at Kansas City Kansas Community College.
Kansas lawmakers are considering the proposal, in which the agency
would use two college chemistry labs. Updating the labs would cost
about $964,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also this year, the KBI added a third mobile lab that allows
agents and chemists to do preliminary processing in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Meth is inexpensive to make, using a recipe of cold medicine and
other easily obtained ingredients. Agents have found meth labs _
most of them booby-trapped _ hidden in suitcases, a coffin and in
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, federal investigators searched a laboratory
at an Overland Park, Kan., apartment complex. Another lab was
discovered last week by a maid cleaning a Lenexa hotel room. After
a short course from local investigators, hotel supervisors knew
what to look for.
</P>
<P>
   KBI Senior Agent Bruce Coffman said he would train anyone who
would listen about the dangers of meth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's just teaching awareness so responders will have
the sense to back out the door and call for help,'' he said. ``It's
as nasty as you're going to get in the drug market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
