A4433 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-EVANS-2NDTAKE-KA     04-27 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EVANS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-AMERICA ATHLETE, KANSAS CITY CIVIC LEADER RAY EVANS DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KENT PULLIAM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... the best back on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that season KU tumbled to Texas Christian in Fort Worth,
Texas, and the Fort Worth Star-Telegram praised Evans with this
headline: ``TCU 41, Evans 6.
</P>
<P>
   Sports columnist Grantland Rice once wrote: ``Evans is as
brilliant as anyone. All the Kansan can do is run, pass, kick,
block and tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans was all-conference in football in 1942, '46 and '47. He
was all-conference in basketball in 1942-43.
</P>
<P>
   Evans was elected to the College Football Hall of Fame in 1964.
He also was selected to the Helms Basketball Foundation Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always talk about the fact that he was an All-American
in two sports _ and that was truly amazing,'' said Bob Frederick,
KU athletic director. ``But the time I was around him, he was an
all-world gentleman. He was so gracious and so kind and
overwhelming in his concern for other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember very well the night we hung his jersey in Allen
Fieldhouse. I know he was moved by that. But in his typical
fashion, he was very humble, very modest, almost embarrassed about
it _ but proud for his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, a first-round draft choice of the Chicago Bears in 1943,
turned down offers to join the Bears and San Francisco 49ers after
the war when he returned to Kansas. He signed with the Pittsburgh
Steelers on April 27, 1948. He played one season in the NFL and
then turned down a contract offer the second year to return to
full-time work at the City National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm serious when I say I'm not crazy about playing pro
football,'' Evans said when he left the NFL. ``I wanted to finish
my eligibility at KU. A lot of people thought I was crazy to do it.
I didn't want to let our team down. I never want to be known as an
athletic bum because I'm not. The thing I want most is a job in
Kansas City where I can earn a living and settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   After one year in the NFL, Evans returned to Kansas City and
became active in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was active in a broad range of things,'' said Donald Hall,
chairman of Hallmark Cards Inc. ``He is one of the finest gentlemen
you will ever meet, a kind, gentle soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillingham, who also has served as president of the board of the
American Royal, called Evans ``a great asset in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Commerce Bancshares Chairman James Kemper Jr. said he
was never a big sports fan, but he can remember a game at the
University of Missouri where Evans almost single-handedly beat the
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a man of great integrity,'' Kemper said. ``He
was a presence in Kansas City all during his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his involvement in Kansas City, Evans served on the
National Council of Youth Fitness, was past president of the
University of Kansas National Alumni Association, was a trustee of
the Dwight D. Eisenhower Foundation and served for 12 years on the
Kansas State Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, born Sept. 8, 1922, on Strawberry Hill, in Kansas City,
Kan., was the youngest of six children of Czechoslovakian
immigrants. The family name was Ivanco.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by Edith Marie Darby Evans, his wife of 50 years;
daughter Julia Evans Fromm and her husband, David Fromm; daughter
Rita Evans Stark and her husband, Benjamin Stark; son Ray Darby
Evans and his wife, Sarah Evans; all of the Kansas City area,
daughter Lisa Evans Tuchtan and her husband, Ken Tuchtan of
Bethesda, Md.; eight grandchildren; and a sister, Helen Carr of
Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services will be 1:30 p.m. Wednesday at St. Agnes
Church, Fairway; private burial in Highland Park Cemetery, Kansas
City, Kan. Visitation will be 6:30-8:30 p.m. Tuesday at the church.
</P>
<P>
   The family requests no flowers and suggests memorial
contributions to the University of Kansas Endowment Association,
c//o The Williams Fund, P.O. Box 928, Lawrence, KS 66044-0928; the
Heart Institute Foundation of St. Luke's Hospital, P.O. Box 11900,
Kansas City, MO 64111; or a charity of your choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
