<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-27 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 HKN-RYAN COLUMN-BOS  
 FAMILIAR SURROUNDINGS, RESULT
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, what's with these guys? They're home, right? Home is not
only where the heart is. It's also supposed to be where the W's
are.
</P>
<P>
   For someone else, maybe, but not the Boston Bruins. They have
now played six home playoff games since moving from the cozy Garden
to the sterile Fleet, and they are 1-5. What home ice advantage?
Since they can't bring back the Garden, maybe they should play Game
4 in Matthews Arena. Or Ristuccia, up there in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, unlike the Celtics, they're having a postseason, so
we should at least be grateful for that.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of gratitude, weren't those boos we heard as the
Bruins skated off the ice at the conclusion of Monday night's 3-2
loss to the Carolina Hurricanes? Boos? Hey, people. It wasn't as if
your team stunk up the joint. They got beat on a cheap goal.
They're down, 2-1, in a seven-game series. What kind of support is
that?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bad yet,'' reassured Ray Bourque. ``If we lose the
next one, that's gonna be bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't heard, this is the Eastern Conference, where
1 can lose to 8, 2 can lose to 7, and so on down the line. In this
case, 6 is losing to 3, except that most people thought the real
seeding should have been the other way around. Typical arrogant
Original Six talk, eh?
</P>
<P>
   So what if it was? It won't make any dfference if, starting
Wednesday night, the Bruins don't win a home game.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure that Pat Burns doesn't think this home/road
business has anything to do with anything. Here, there, or
anywhere, the Hurricanes are gonna do what they're gonna do, which
means they will forecheck and forecheck, and, when they can't think
of anything else to do, they will forecheck some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no secret,'' said the Boston mentor. ``That's what
they do all the time. They're a good forechecking team. There's no
two ways about that. Plus, they got a break. A couple of breaks,
actually.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the first and third Carolina goals, neither
of which had much to do with artful stickhandling or shooting. The
first, a mere minute and five seconds into the game, was credited
to Gary Roberts. Let's just say that Jeff O'Neill made the play and
that the hand of fate somehow managed to direct it off Roberts and
past a somewhat startled Byron Dafoe. A thing of beauty? Uh, no. A
thing? Yup.
</P>
<P>
   As for the game-winner, which was credited to Andrei Kovalenko,
there is not much to say other than to hope that somehow or other
things even out in the long run. Kovalenko still hasn't touched it.
The puck was accidentally Dafoed in, even as Kovalenko came
crashing into the goalkeeper. For a fleeting moment, Burns &AMP; Co.
hoped for a reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was (i.e. Kovalenko in the crease),'' said Burns,
``but when I looked at it on TV, it wasn't. The puck was already
in. It was another break. The puck bounced off Byron's glove and
went into the net. That's a break we'd like to get. But you have to
make your breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   You do, indeed, and so it's somewhat sad to report that in at
least two very prominent instances the Bruins did exactly that, and
yet still managed to lose. Both Boston goals came as either the
direct or indirect result of tremendous prolonged pressure exerted
on the Hurricanes. Sergei Samsonov tied the game at 1-1 after
taking a superb right-to-left centering feed from Joe Thornton not
long after the expiration of a first-period power play that itself
was due to hard work and diligence on the part of the Bruins that
caused Curtis Leschyshyn to be sent off for obstruction. More
fierce pressure led to a second-period Keith Primeau tripping
penalty. Anson Carter made him pay by redirecting a Jason Allison
blast past Arturs Irbe to give the Bruins a 2-1 lead at 13:07.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was the end of the Boston scoring. They were
unable to convert any of their good scoring opportunities in the
final 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if Irbe had to, as they say in this game, stand on
his head. He was good, not great, but clearly good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to do anything too spectacular,'' acknowledged
Carolina coach Paul Maurice, ``but he did make some real nice
decisions with the puck. He helped out in our back end.''
</P>
<P>
   We didn't hear anything out of Burns we didn't expect to hear.
As he said, there are no secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to bury our chances,'' he declared. ``If we don't,
then we start looking at all the things we're doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing a whole lot wrong,'' he continued. ``We just
have to bury our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins really aren't doing too much wrong, where does
that leave the Hurricanes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played a very solid road game,'' said Maurice,
who looks young enough to be proofed at Disney World. ``We've got
to be real pleased with this win.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice is of the opinion that no one should be surprised at
anything that goes on in this, or any other, Eastern Conference
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great parity,'' he said. ``There are no good matchups
for anyone. Four teams are going to go away in a bad mood. Four
general managers can say to their coach after he loses, `Your team
is as good as the other team.' We're up, 2-1, but Boston could be
up, 2-1, or even 3-0. Your stomach is always swirling.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe I got this far without even mentioning the
second Carolina goal, a power-play job. The penalty was for _
you'll love this _ too many men on the ice. Rob DiMaio thought
Carter was coming off the ice, and, oh, it's just too painful to
ponder.
</P>
<P>
   So is all this going to happen again? Two goofy goals. Too many
men on the ice. That stuff has to be out of their system. Don't you
like the Bruins' chances in, you know, a normal game?
</P>
<P>
   They can't keep losing at home, can they? You heard the captain.
Cut them just a little slack. If they lose Wednesday night, you
have number 77's permission to boo. One more chance, OK?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
