<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-EVANS-TWOTAKES-K     04-27 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EVANS-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-AMERICA ATHLETE, KANSAS CITY CIVIC LEADER RAY EVANS DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KENT PULLIAM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Ray Evans, one of the most celebrated
athletes in Kansas City history and a longtime civic leader, died
at his home Saturday night. Evans, a two-sport All-America at the
University of Kansas, was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Evans had suffered heart problems in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a damn good citizen, that's for sure,'' said Jay B.
Dillingham, a former president of the American Royal.
</P>
<P>
   Evans gained his greatest fame at KU, where he was the school's
first-ever All-America player in football in 1947 and a two-time
All-America basketball player in 1942 and '43.
</P>
<P>
   He also was an active civic leader in the Kansas City area long
after his on-field exploits. He was president of the Traders
National Bank until he retired in 1975, was a former chairman of
the board of the American Royal and a former vice president and
director of the Kansas City Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   He also remained active in sports _ though on the civic side. He
was instrumental in helping bring the Chiefs to Kansas City and
served as president of the Chiefs Club. He was a member of the
Royal Lancers since its inception in 1967 and was a part-owner of
the former Kansas City Kings NBA franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray was one of those rare individuals who comes along once in
a century,'' said Otto Schnellbacher, a basketball and football
teammate of Evans at KU. ``Not only was he a great athlete, he was
a great person with it. Ray was an achiever. He was the type of
player who always made the great play at the time it was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things got tough, he was somehow right there on the front
row to make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Fambrough, former KU football coach, also was Evans'
teammate. The two met during World War II when they were stationed
together in the Army Air Forces. Evans' college career was
interrupted by the war. He played athletics at KU in the early
'40s, then returned for the 1946 and '47 football seasons,
finishing up his basketball eligibility in the spring of 1948.
Evans recruited Fambrough to come to KU.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the hardest things I ever had to do was leave the
University of Texas,'' Fambrough said Sunday. ``But I wanted to
play my football days with Ray. I remember having the feeling that
any time he was on the field I felt like we could beat anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who also had led Wyandotte High School to the state
football championship in 1940, had turned down offers from several
major-league baseball clubs to attend KU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard it said a thousand times about individuals
leading with their actions rather than their words,'' Fambrough
said. ``Whoever said that the first time had Ray Evans in mind. I
have always said that here at the University of Kansas there were
two categories of athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was for Ray Evans. The other was for anybody else. Nobody
else was even close when you consider him as an athlete, a person,
a friend and someone you could count on.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents felt the same way. In 1942, when the Iowa Navy
Pre-Flight team was beating Kansas 61-0, coach Bernie Bierman said:
``Kansas was swamped and outclassed, but that Ray Evans was the
best back on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
