<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HN     04-27 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Cuttino Mobley could not help himself. Scottie Pippen would rather
the precocious point guard make everything else he did Monday a
habit. But not this.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For one night, however, when a painful three-game losing streak
had been extinguished and a likely first-round playoff opponent
whipped, Mobley celebrated by planting a wet one on top of Pippen's
head. And just this once, Pippen said he had to let it go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind,'' Pippen said, ``as long as he plays like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that sort of night for the Rockets, with a lot of love in
the room after a start-to-finish 102-80 rout of the Los Angeles
Lakers at Compaq Center. In ending their longest skid of the year,
the Rockets recorded their second-largest victory of the season and
dealt the Lakers their second-biggest loss.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley set the tone, Pippen turned it up, and Charles Barkley
brought it home, the Lakers never challenging less than two weeks
before they will likely meet the Rockets in the first round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But more than whom they beat, the Rockets were cheered by how
they beat them, solving each of the problems they said had caused
their fall in consecutive losses to the Mavericks, Clippers and
Suns.
</P>
<P>
   They played outstanding, aggressive defense against the league's
second-most prolific scoring and most accurate shooting team. They
ran their break expertly and shut down the Lakers' bench. They even
controlled the boards more completely, save the obligatory rout of
Vancouver, than they had against anybody else this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think today's game showed how good we can be,'' Pippen
said. ``I still feel we're a championship-caliber team. We just
have to come out, play hard and lay it all on the line every night.
If we do that continuously, after a while it becomes routine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets would love for such a night to become routine. But
under the circumstances, it clearly was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our biggest game, our most meaningful game of the
year,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said, having taken his 350th
career win but thinking of bigger concerns. ``Considering the
situation we're in, we came up big.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' renewed swagger might have been most clear when
Barkley tossed a length-of-the-court pass to Pippen, then raised
his arms Joe Montana style as Pippen dunked.
</P>
<P>
   And the transformation might have been most obvious when Barkley
backed in Robert Horry for 60 feet before scoring, then extended a
hand thigh-high to the Lakers' bench, indicating the ceiling on
their place in the Western Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   The win left the Rockets (28-17) 1{ games ahead of the Lakers
(27-19) and two up in the loss column. The Rockets have five games
left, the Lakers four.
</P>
<P>
   Though Barkley maintained there was no message sent, especially
considering the Lakers still hold two wins against the Rockets this
season and neither has won on the other's court, he knew what the
win meant in the playoff chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was two teams that have been struggling,'' Barkley said.
``We outplayed them tonight. We had to win tonight to keep the
two-game lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concentration is on trying to keep home court (in the first
round of the playoffs), and we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious sign of the Rockets' rejuvenation was their
sudden enthusiasm for defense from the outset. Determined to apply
defensive pressure and intensity sorely lacking in the past week,
the Rockets all but choked the life out of LA. The Lakers have been
struggling every bit as much as the Rockets, but if there is one
thing they can do, it's score.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rockets' defense attacking swiftly and confidently,
though, the Lakers made just seven of 26 (26.9 percent)
first-quarter shots. Mobley, having begun the defensive effort with
two quick steals, had 12 points in the quarter as the Rockets
rushed to a 28-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to set the tone defensively,'' Mobley said. ``I
always try to set the tone defensively, but I wanted to be
aggressive offensively, too.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Pippen began to take over. He had 12 points and four
steals in the second quarter and finished with 26 points, his third
consecutive 20-point game. Until Sunday, he had not had consecutive
20-point games all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being more aggressive offensively, and teams have to honor
my outside shot,'' Pippen said. ``When I shoot like I did tonight,
it makes the rest of my game much easier.''
</P>
<P>
   It made the night easier for the Rockets, who led by 23 points
one Michael Dickerson jumper into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   They have made a habit of blowing such leads. But Barkley, who
finished with 20 points, 16 rebounds and six assists, grew
increasingly dominant, too strong inside for Horry and too quick
for J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us out there (in Los Angeles) and were dancing and
high-fiving,'' Mobley said. ``I was mad about that. I was ready to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us confidence. We know we can beat them. We can see
their weaknesses and go from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
