<SLUG> BC-MINCER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENT `ANGEL' EXTENDS A SECRET HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not your typical business card. But then again, it's not
your ordinary business.
</P>
<P>
   The card says ``Silent Angels'' above a drawing of a cherub's
face and a fax number.
</P>
<P>
   There is no name and no telephone number. That's the way the
founding ``Angel'' likes it. The faxes come to her with requests
for help _ clothing, shelter, jobs. And without fanfare she
responds, sometimes with assistance from others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Batman,'' she said. ``I like to stay behind the
mask. I don't want people to know who I am. That's not important as
long as people are getting the help.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, this Belton, Mo., woman has quietly worked
behind the scenes, helping hundreds, perhaps thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't smoke, I don't drink,'' she said. ``This is my
addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   She works two part-time jobs, one at UPS and one at The Kansas
City Star, to support the work she does, spending about 80 percent
of her earnings on her volunteer efforts.
</P>
<P>
   A co-worker at UPS learned about her work, and the Angel
recently received the Jim Casey Community Service Award. She was
selected from among 300,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Angel was so surprised that she assumed she was being fired
when a supervisor asked her to gather her belongings and come to
the office.
</P>
<P>
   The Angel is a mother of four children and grandmother of eight,
and she can't explain why she spends about 30 hours a week working
at shelters, soup kitchens and wherever else she's needed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because of the way she was raised. Even as a
teen-ager, she would help relatives deliver produce and meat to
shelters and the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 years ago, when her oldest child was in preschool, she
dressed up as the Easter bunny.
</P>
<P>
   That tradition grew, and she now spends months making baskets
with volunteers and weeks delivering them to child-care centers,
nursing homes and individual children.
</P>
<P>
   While she volunteers at a soup kitchen every Saturday, much of
her time is spent responding to the faxes. Her garage and those of
friends are packed with donations of toys, clothing and furniture,
which she distributes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't call it a handout, I call it a hand up,'' she said.
``They need the help, and I just give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her most recent endeavors is the Children of the Arts.
The idea is to provide free music and art lessons for youngsters
who would otherwise not be able to afford them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for kids who can't afford to do anything,'' she said.
``If we can get them involved, they'll have something to look
forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Her dream is to open an all-purpose community center where
someone could go for food, clothing or job training.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really no big deal,'' she says about her volunteer
work. ``It all fits in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
