<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HENDRICKS-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-27 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENDRICKS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLERANCE IN SCHOOLS WOULD BE A LIFESAVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MIKE HENDRICKS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ]You knew it wouldn't be long before a few school districts
banned black trench coats, and within days of the killings at
Columbine High some American teen-agers risked suspension for their
choice of outerwear.
</P>
<P>
   We are human. We respond irrationally at times such as these. We
act, even if those actions are as pointless as outlawing an item of
clothing worn by the killers in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of tragedies such as last Tuesday's massacre,
we scramble to understand causes, assess blame and take corrective
action.
</P>
<P>
   We want a quick fix _ a simple formula to end this rash of
school violence that's seemingly as unstoppable and unpredictable
as lightning strikes in a thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   What causes two teen-agers to kill and maim their classmates by
the dozen?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the culture? Should we blame it all on the video games and
the movies and the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Others say it's America's fascination with guns _ too many
firearms too easily obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Others lay it all on mom and dad. It must be the fault of
parental permissiveness in our culture of affluence, we're told by
people who have no clue about how those boys were raised.
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know what combination of society's ills spawned this
evil. Yet we must look for ways to keep such horrors from happening
again.
</P>
<P>
   Strict gun control? Some of us have been advocating that since
Robert F. Kennedy and Martin Luther King Jr. were assassinated in
1968, and no doubt we'll still be saying it in another 30 years, to
little effect.
</P>
<P>
   More school security? Sounds good to some, but metal detectors
would not have prevented the attack in Littleton, and the security
cameras did nothing but provide evidence for after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   As for arming teachers and filling the schools with police, we
have to ask whether that's the kind of society we want to live in.
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing seems clear: We need to put a stop to the anger
that propelled Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris into murder and
suicide. A stop to the anger that motivated the school killings in
Jonesboro, Ark., Pearl, Miss., West Paducah, Ky., and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   That means going one step beyond the many fine
conflict-resolution programs developed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do parents, teachers, ministers and friends need to
keep a close eye out for the warning signs of troubled youth, but
we need to teach our kids to be tolerant of each other's
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Not just tolerance of racial and ethnic diversity, but tolerance
of those who simply look or act differently. We need tolerance
across the many cliques that exist in every high school.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold and Harris weren't always bad kids, but it's been said
they turned angry because jocks and others considered them outcasts
and losers for the way they dressed and acted.
</P>
<P>
   Not in any way to excuse their crimes, but how might things have
changed had their classmates reached out to them instead of
treating them like freaks for wearing the black clothes and makeup?
How many other tragedies might be averted if our children learned
to accept each other, rather than mock those at the bottom of the
social pecking order?
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Costello sang a song some years ago that seems applicable.
It was called ``(What's So Funny 'Bout) Peace, Love And
Understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's funny about it, man. Without it, there's only grief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 0107EDT &QL; 
