<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4443 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HKN-DUPONTCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-27 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TYPICALLY UPSETTING DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-DUPONT COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Kevin Paul Dupont  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surprised, aren't you? Once again, the playoffs aren't going the
way Black-and-Gold Country expected. The Bruins were supposed to be
able to handle the Hurricanes and move on fairly handily to Round 2
of the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Well, take ``supposed'' and stick it in, oh, how about that
steam plant down in Hartford? Yeah, that's it, Hartford. Who knows
better than those folks in the Nutmeg State _ once home of the
Whalers _ that rarely do things go according to the book, according
to form, play out the way they are supposed to play out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, here in the 1999 Stanley Cup playoffs, the unexpected
has become the expected in the Eastern Conference. As of this
morning, three of the four series favorites _ Devils, Senators, and
Bruins _ are on the wrong side of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, the top seed in the East, were supposed to breeze by
the once-mighty Penguins. When Pittsburgh superstar Jaromir Jagr
moved to the injured list (groin pull) in Game 1, leaving him out
of Games 2 and 3, Las Vegas opened a betting line on whether
bankruptcy court would call for liquidation of the financially
strapped franchise before the Penguins could lose their fourth
game.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? Even without Jagr, the most talented player in
today's game, Pittsburgh won Games 2 and 3. The Devils' offense hit
a vapor lock. And, lo and behold, Alexei Kovalev showed up looking
like the world-class player he was projected to be in the '92
Olympics. Maybe the Penguins won't win the series, but they already
have two more wins than they were supposed to . . .
</P>
<P>
   And the Senators. Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   They led the conference for much of the second half, but
softened up some in the final two weeks, allowing the Devils to
capture the East. With that hitch already in their swing, they took
on the Sabres, only to find Dominik Hasek programmed with his full
Czech Republic-gold-medal program. Translation: Forget about it,
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senators lose Tuesday night, it's over in four. A sweep.
They've got speed, youth, depth, and a neat attack that is based on
the quick transition out of a trap defense. Big deal. They've got a
neat story line: a small-market Canadian squad with a rabid fan
base. So much for neat stories. In 60 ticks of the clock tonight,
they could be the best thing that's happened to Buffalo since the
invention of galoshes and rock salt.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Bruins, they finally were moving on up in the world
with the late-season coming together of two pretty decent offensive
line combinations, and they were supposed to beat up on the 'Canes
as if they were their Forever .500 forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone out there remember just what those line combinatons were?
</P>
<P>
   Jason Allison was in the middle of one. Jumbo Joe Thornton
played the No. 2 pivot. Three games into this series, which
Carolina now leads, 2-1, the Bruins can't roll so much as one line
over the boards that can play through the 'Canes defense and
commanding presence once over the offensive blue line.
</P>
<P>
   In times like these, coach Pat Burns usually turns to his
reliable checking line of Rob DiMaio, Tim Taylor, and P.J.
Axelsson. But those aren't the go-to guys who made the late-season
run so exciting. Where in the world are Steve Heinze, Anson Carter,
Sergei Samsonov, and Dmitri Khristich? By the end of Game 3, Burns
clearly had given up on Khristich, who has had one shot on goal in
the series.
</P>
<P>
   Given Khristich's performance _ a real stretch of the word _
Burns has every reason to dress Cameron Mann in his place Wednesday
night for Game 4. No one knows for sure, but word had it at the
Vault Tuesday night that the Hood photographer shot Monday night's
game and Khristich's face will be seen on the side of milk cartons
later this week.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, Flutie Flakes were the rage. Here we've got a case
of a Khristich Kidnapping. He's a free agent as of July 1 and it
will take at least $2 million a year to bring him back next season.
The bigger trick would be to find something that would bring him
back in time for Wednesday night's faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that is going according to the book in the East
right now is the Toronto-Philadelphia series. After dropping the
opener, the favored Maple Leafs have won two straight, including a
2-1 triumph Monday night. The Flyers don't have Eric Lindros
(recovering from a collapsed lung) and Mark Recchi is struggling
with symptoms of a migraine headache (after two concussions in 23
days). The Leafs entered as the favorites and they're living up to
the billing.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the Hub, where the Stanley Cup has been absent some
27 years, nothing is as it was supposed to be. The best little
hockey team in North Carolina is a lot better than a lot of people
expected _ maybe even better than the 'Canes themselves imagined _
and the Bruins look like they don't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   What do you suppose they're going to do about that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
