<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4446 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILINGUAL-EDUCATION-K     04-27 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILINGUAL-EDUCATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN CITY SCHOOLS MEET CHALLENGE OF BILINGUAL EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, Kan. _ Javier's intense brown eyes dart between his
kindergarten teacher and a piece of paper where he has written
``HOLE'' in large letters.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Walker pronounces a letter and draws it on an easel, and
Javier and his classmates repeat the sound. It may look like a
simple English lesson, but to tiny Javier it's a foreign language.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks earlier, the 5-year-old had arrived from Mexico to
live with his mother in Garden City. He speaks only Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   In most Kansas school districts, Javier would be a special case,
but not in this southwest Kansas town of 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many speak only Spanish in your house?'' Walker asks her
class at Victor Ornelas Elementary School, and 12 of her 14 pupils
raise their hands.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the families in the Garden City school
district speak a language other than English at home.
</P>
<P>
   From Spanish to Vietnamese to Lao, a visitor at a Garden City
playground could hear as many as 11 languages. In five years, the
number of students who speak little or no English has risen from
550 to 1,600, or about 20 percent of the district's enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   With the diversity of its student body, the Garden City School
District looks more like Southern California than western Kansas,
said Linda Trujillo, who leads the district's bilingual effort.
</P>
<P>
   More than five years ago, the school district decided to tackle
the challenge of educating its diverse student population using an
approach known as English as a Second Language, or ESL. Three of
the district's 12 elementary schools employ the program, and an
expansion into other schools is planned for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Under this approach, children at first are taught to read and
write and do other schoolwork in a language they understand. At the
same time, they begin to learn English, which eventually becomes
the primary language.
</P>
<P>
   The ESL approach is used from kindergarten through third grade.
At each grade level, English lessons are woven into the curriculum
as a supplement to the student's native language.
</P>
<P>
   In third grade, pupils begin the transition to English.
</P>
<P>
   In fourth grade, English becomes the primary language. The
student, according to the theory, should make the transition
easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at 17 to 18 years' worth of studies,'' Trujillo
said. ``They said this is the way it should function if you do it
right. We followed the recipe precisely, and when it came time to
switch, the kids did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the fourth year for the students who began in the
new program as kindergartners.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, fourth-graders in the ESL classes scored as
high on assessment tests as classes made up of students who spoke
only English.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of Hispanic and Asian immigrants into Garden City
began with the construction and expansion of two beef-packing
plants in the mid-1980s. With a low unemployment rate in the area,
these plants regularly recruit workers in Mexico and other Central
American countries.
</P>
<P>
   With them come children needing an education.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Kreicker, a bilingual education program consultant with the
Kansas Board of Education, said the only districts ``where true
bilingual education is taking place'' are in Wichita and Garden
City.
</P>
<P>
   In Garden City, the learning and teaching challenge for local
educators was staggering, said Milt Pippenger, the district's
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The district became a revolving door for students. Turnover
rates in some Garden City schools reached 100 percent. Academic
expectations were low as teachers and administrators struggled to
teach English to immigrant students.
</P>
<P>
   Within nine years, the district had five superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   Students were learning English, but content was being
sacrificed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of kids who could speak English fluently, but
they were dropping out of school because they couldn't read or
write,'' said Trujillo, the district's director of supplemental
programs.
</P>
<P>
   There had to be a better way.
</P>
<P>
   Enter English as a Second Language.
</P>
<P>
   At Alta Brown Elementary, Principal Leticia Porter said student
appetites for learning have increased dramatically. She said a few
pupils have read every book in the school library.
</P>
<P>
   Book checkouts have soared from about 100 to 500 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Parent involvement has skyrocketed while the student turnover
rate has plunged. When their children are doing well in schools,
parents are not as quick to move somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want very much for their children not to have to work as
hard as they have,'' Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   The school also is teaching English to the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman was so desperate to learn English she borrowed a
baby from another family so she could take the classes,'' Porter
said.
</P>
<P>
   The district also has taken steps to address another problem _
middle school students who arrive with little or no English skills.
</P>
<P>
   They wind up in Gayla Myers' ``intake'' class. Each new arrival
is evaluated, and a program is designed to prepare the student to
enter regular classes. That may take an entire semester if the
student arrives without any formal education.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take a student who already is literate in his own
language and teach him English pretty easily,'' Trujillo said.
``For students who are not literate in any language, you not only
have to teach him English but literacy skills as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo said the teachers try to do as much as they can for
these older students and then move them into a beginning-level ESL
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the nonliterate student, we know that unless something
extraordinary happens, they probably won't graduate from high
school,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring enough bilingual teachers to meet the district's needs is
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, college scholarships are given to six Garden City
High School graduates who agree to obtain an education degree and
return to teach in Garden City schools for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grow our own,'' Trujillo said. ``We're always looking for
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
