<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4461 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-ASTROS-HNS     04-27 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Jose Lima went on a national sports talk show this spring and
boldly predicted he would win 20 games.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three down, 17 to go.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem a little far-fetched, considering that only two
years ago Lima was struggling as a reliever and close to a demotion
to the minor leagues. But after Monday night's 5-2 victory over the
Arizona Diamondbacks at the Astrodome, who can argue with him?
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to win 20 games. Be careful. I can win some more,''
said Lima, who allowed two runs in eight-plus innings. ``I'm not
trying to act like I'm all that, but I know I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima (3-1) struck out four and walked two, reducing his ERA to
3.33 and coming within three outs of his fourth career complete
game. He retired 11 of 13 batters to begin the game and on several
occasions worked out of jams to keep the Diamondbacks under
control.
</P>
<P>
   With a run in and a man on in the ninth, Billy Wagner replaced
Lima and struck out the final three batters for his sixth save. The
second of those victims was Kelly Stinnett, whose line drive off
Wagner's head provided one of 1998's scariest moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I expected nothing less than a win,'' said Lima, who
won a career-high 16 games last season in his first full-time
chance as a starter. ``When I go out there, I feel like I can win
every game. That's the kind of confidence I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona righthander Todd Stottlemyre wasn't as fortunate.
Stottlemyre, one of the big acquisitions in the Diamondbacks'
offseason spending spree, lost for the first time in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   After holding the Astros hitless through 3 innings, Stottlemyre
became his own enemy with three of his season-high five walks
during the Astros' two-run fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre (2-1) allowed five runs _ three earned _ and six
hits in six innings. He walked five and had four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Derek Bell reached on an error by shortstop Tony
Batista, stole second base and scored on Jeff Bagwell's single to
center. Stottlemyre struck out Ken Caminiti but followed with
consecutive walks to Carl Everett, Richard Hidalgo and Tony
Eusebio, the last with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who went 2-for-4 with two RBIs, drove in a run with a
double in the fifth, and Hidalgo added a two-run single three
batters later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some nights you have to tip your hat. I got outpitched,''
Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Lima worked out of a sticky situation in the fourth when the
Diamondbacks loaded the bases with two outs. Former Astro Luis
Gonzalez, who extended his hitting streak to 12 games, and Travis
Lee singled, and Batista walked.
</P>
<P>
   Lima got out of the inning when Stinnett popped to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks scored once in the sixth and threatened to get
more.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams singled with one out, and Gonzalez drove in a run
with a double to right-center. Lima coaxed the next two batters
into groundouts to minimize the damage and help the Astros maintain
a four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker credited Lima's success to staying ahead in the count
and changing speeds on his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't throw fastballs over the plate for them to
hit,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona entered the game hitting .275, fourth-best in the
National League. The D-Backs outhit the Astros 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Lima said his game plan centered on limiting the damage by Jay
Bell and Williams. Bell has seven home runs, and Williams was
coming off a 5-for-9 weekend series with San Diego in which he
homered twice.
</P>
<P>
   The two went 1-for-8 Monday off Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to stay away from Matt Williams and Jay Bell,'' Lima
said. ``I respect all of their hitters, but those two have been
swinging the bat real well. I let (catcher) Tony Eusebio call the
game for me. I hardly shook him off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks got their second run off Lima in the ninth,
when Gonzalez walked and scored on a double to right-center by Lee.
Then Wagner entered and put a blazing end to the night's activity.
</P>
<P>
   The victory enabled the Astros to pull even at 5-5 at the Dome,
and Dierker said the victory was even more satisfying coming
against a Diamondbacks club that had won six of its previous seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to be a championship team, we are going to
have to establish ourselves as a team that's hard to beat in our
own ballpark,'' Dierker said. ``We haven't done that yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Diamondbacks are as good a test as any of the
teams we've played yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
