<HEADLINE>
HEALTH MIDWEST APPOINTS GENERAL COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Health Midwest, the Kansas City area's
largest health-care system, has appointed Joseph L. Hiersteiner
senior vice president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Hiersteiner will start his job this summer, said Richard W.
Brown, Health Midwest's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe will be an extraordinary addition to our management
team,'' Brown said. ``We have long valued his leadership as a
member of the boards of directors in the Health Midwest system, and
we look forward to adding his leadership strengths to our senior
management team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiersteiner, 46, is a member of Health Midwest's board and the
board's executive committee. He also serves on the boards of Health
Midwest-Johnson County, Menorah Medical Center and the Jewish
Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Hiersteiner is a partner in the Kansas City office of the Bryan
Cave law firm. Hiersteiner will continue to be associated with
Bryan Cave on an ``of counsel'' basis, in which he will be
available to work with certain clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting opportunity for me to work with and learn
from extremely talented people at Health Midwest,'' Hiersteiner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hiersteiner is replacing Gina Kaiser, who has served as Health
Midwest's vice president and in-house counsel since 1992. Kaiser
plans to travel, do volunteer work and spend time with her family.
Kaiser also has accepted an appointment to the board of Menorah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
