A4465 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSC-KAN &LR;      04-27 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSION STAFF SEES FLAWS IN PROPOSED MERGER OF WESTERN
RESOURCES, KCP&AMP;L 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A merger of Western Resources Inc. and Kansas
City Power &AMP; Light Co. would be against the public's interest,
unless substantial changes are made in the proposal, the staff of
the Missouri Public Service Commission has concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The staff, which disclosed its views in testimony filed Monday
at the commission's headquarters in Jefferson City, said its
concerns ranged from the lack of benefits for consumers to the
amount of market power wielded by the two utilities if they merged.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the information supplied by the two utilities to
Missouri regulators was often insufficient in providing necessary
details about how the merged company would operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an inadequate filing,'' said Terry Featherstone, a
regulatory auditor for the Public Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The staff's views will be considered by the commission, which
will hold formal hearings on the proposed merger in July. The
commissioners are not obligated to accept the views of their staff.
</P>
<P>
   But the Missouri regulatory staff, the Missouri Office of Public
Counsel, the staff of the Kansas Corporation Commission and that
state's Citizens' Utility Ratepayer Board have all conveyed the
view that the merger is seriously flawed for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A KCP&AMP;L spokeswoman said she had no comment on the Missouri
staff's testimony. Carl Koupal Jr., an executive vice president
with Western Resources, said he was limited in what he could say
because he had reviewed only a brief summary of the Missouri
staff's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   But Western still firmly thinks the merger is in the best
interests of employees, ratepayers and shareholders, Koupal said.
He also reiterated that the merger agreement couldn't survive
serious financial tinkering by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger will occur only if any conditions are consistent
with what is sound from a financial standpoint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Western Resources and KCP&AMP;L agreed to merge in February 1997 in
a transaction valued at $2.2 billion. If the deal is completed,
Western's utilities, KGE and KPL, will join KCP&AMP;L in a new company
called Westar. It would serve 1 million electric customers.
</P>
<P>
   But substantial concessions are being recommended by the staff
of the Missouri Public Service Commission. As now configured, they
conclude, the merger would give little or no rate relief to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The two utilities estimate that the merger will save $950
million over 10 years, a figure that the Missouri staffers think is
inflated. But whatever the savings, it's far from certain that
consumers would see any of the money, said Mark Oligschlaeger, one
of the commission's auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the utilities' proposal, they would keep revenue equal to
a 13.5 percent return on equity. Anything over that would be split
with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Oligschlaeger said the formula would allow the merged company to
keep all or nearly all the cost savings. The staff is recommending
that the formula be scrapped and that, if approved, the merged
company submit to traditional utility rate regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers and the utility should split any savings resulting
from the merger, the staff recommended. In addition, the testimony
said, none of the $885 million premium paid by Western for KCP&AMP;L
should be collected from Missouri consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Koupal said that consumers should benefit and that Western had a
record of saving money for consumers. One example is the
acquisition of KGE in the early '90s, when a rate increase that had
been expected was avoided.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's staff also expressed concerns about the power
of the merged company to control the market for electricity in the
area. Those concerns should be dealt with by the commission, the
staff said, perhaps by making the merged company divest some of its
generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
   On some issues the commission staffers said they did not get
enough information to reach conclusions. One concern was that
Western Resources, the holding company for Westar, would be in
Kansas, and assurances need to be made that Missouri regulators
will have access to that company's records.
</P>
<P>
   Various corporate and operational details about how the merged
company would operate were not provided. Steve Dottheim, a chief
deputy and legal counsel for the commission, said companies in past
mergers had submitted more requested information than Western and
KCP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   On another issue, the Missouri staff said any merger benefits
should not be used to create rate parity for Missouri and Kansas
customers. KGE customers pay higher residential rates than KPL or
KCP&AMP;L customers, and they have argued that the disparity should end
if the companies merge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
