<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4466 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTOR-KAN &LR;      04-27 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS LOOK TOWARD JOINING UNIONS FOR BARGANING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ While grinding through a 34-hour shift at the
University of Kansas Medical Center, resident radiologist Peter
Peer dreams of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   He dreams of the day when he will complete his five years of
postgraduate resident training and go to work in a private
practice, perhaps in a small town.
</P>
<P>
   But Peer nurtures another dream, one that challenges medical
traditions: carrying a union card. He thinks a union can help him
get better working conditions, such as shorter hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one step above indentured servants,'' Peer said. ``I
would like to have some bargaining power.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. More doctors _ whether employed or in private
practice _ are looking to unionization as a means to gain clout.
</P>
<P>
   The move coincides with a growing feeling among doctors
nationwide that their power to make decisions and their ability to
relate to patients have been eroded by cost-conscious managed-care
companies and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that 35,000 to 45,000 of the nation's 680,000
doctors are union members. According to the March 15 issue of
American Medical News, 10 unions are competing for the allegiance
of physicians who are employed by hospitals, HMOs or other
entities.
</P>
<P>
   The publication says the new National Doctors Alliance of the
Service Employees International Union leads the field with 15,000
practicing physicians and residents. It has promised to spend at
least $1 million a year to recruit more salaried doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The next-largest group, the Union of American Physicians and
Dentists, has about 5,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is visible in Kansas City, where the American
Federation of Government Employees recently won an election to
represent doctors and other health-care professionals at Veterans
Hospital. Also, the Federation of Physicians and Dentists, based in
Tallahassee, Fla., says it has met with some Kansas City area
orthopedic surgeons in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Pending before the National Labor Relations Board are several
cases involving the organizing rights of doctors. A bill in the
U.S. House of Representatives filed by Rep. Tom Campbell, a
California Republican, would allow private-practice doctors and
other private health-care professionals to collectively bargain
with health insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Unions give doctors ``the kind of voice necessary to speak out
for themselves and their patients,'' said Mark Levy, executive
director of the National Doctors Alliance in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Levy's viewpoint resonates with doctors such as Mark Davidner, a
Kansas City area oncologist. ``I think we should have been
unionized years ago,'' Davidner said. ``We're seeing a systematic
discreditation of medicine in this country by insurance companies
and by government. Physicians can no longer make decisions about
how patients should be cared for.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, flinch at the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not certain a union would make a lot of sense,'' said
Brent Steward, a chief surgery resident at KU Medical Center. ``It
would seem that a union would make an `us and them' out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trustees of the American Medical Association recently decided
against forming a doctors union, saying their members needed more
time to consider the proposal. The trustees said they wanted to
have the issue brought before the association's House of Delegates
in June before deciding.  &LR; brk:A different era  &LR; tx:Most health-care
industry observers agree that unionized doctors are a far cry from
the idyllic images of yesteryear, when doctors were looked upon as
saintly father figures. Who could have imagined Marcus Welby down
at the union hall, rallying with his fellow workers against the
abuses of greedy bosses?
</P>
<P>
   But our current health-care system is a far cry from the one
that spawned the Marcus Welby myth. Managed-care companies scrap
over market share and scramble to control rising medical costs,
even as some of their chief executives are paid millions. The
government is tightening the purse strings of Medicare and
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Cost cutting puts pressure on doctors and hospitals to provide
care for less money. At the same time, many doctors say they are
losing control over patient-care decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it (unionization) has shown up on the radar screens
of doctors is the drastic change in the way the business of health
care is conducted,'' said John Wisner, a psychiatrist at Veterans
Hospital, who is taking a wait-and-see attitude about the union
there. ``All are increasingly aware of changes in which physicians
make decisions, are remunerated and relate to their patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers would benefit if unions helped doctors ``take back a
little extra power,'' said Peter DeSimone, executive director of
the Missouri Association for Social Welfare, a nonprofit citizen
advocacy group in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   That extra power would enable doctors to ``use their best
judgment and not have to beg insurance company bureaucrats and
government bureaucrats to be able to do what they think is right
for the patient,'' DeSimone said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about doctors' losing their independence long have been
expressed by Richard Hellman, a Kansas City area endocrinologist
and president-elect of the Metropolitan Medical Society of Greater
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But Hellman has mixed feelings about doctors taking up the union
label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope they would be unnecessary,'' Hellman said. ``In
situations where physicians are self-employed, I would like to see
different kinds of bargaining groups. I would like to see legal
rights extended to allow physicians to bargain collectively on
non-economic issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellman said unions were more appropriate for salaried doctors,
including physicians in resident training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there have been situations where the physicians were
exploited in residencies, and the unions have helped in that
respect,'' Hellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Peer, the resident radiologist at KU Medical Center, agrees.
 &LR; brk:`Afraid to doze off'  &LR; tx:On a typical day, Peer works from 7
a.m. to 5 p.m. But every six days, he goes in for a shift that
lasts from 7 a.m. to 5 p.m. the next day, a total of 34 hours. He
might get a couple of hours of sleep during that time or none at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your adrenalin is pumping and you're constantly waiting for
that beeper to go off,'' Peer said. ``You're afraid to doze off.''
</P>
<P>
   When he finally gets home, he's usually too pumped to go to
sleep. The situation makes him angry.
</P>
<P>
   Peer, who receives a stipend from the state, said residents in
surgery and ob-gyn programs had it even tougher in that they work
even longer without a break. And he said the problem was not unique
to KU Medical Center, but extends across the spectrum of medical
training institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see the point to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a point to it, said Glendon Cox, professor of
radiology and associate dean for graduate medical education at KU.
</P>
<P>
   Once they have completed their training, doctors in certain
specialties still face situations in which they must work more than
24 hours at a stretch, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can deny that medicine is a very stressful
profession,'' Cox said. ``The stresses that occur during residency
prepare you for the stresses you will experience as a practicing
physician.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Cox said, residents are still in training and in a
sense are still students, even though they have medical degrees and
are paid. He said a union agreement would make it difficult to
dismiss a resident who didn't perform up to standards.
</P>
<P>
   Unionization poses the possibility of strikes in situations in
which laws do not prohibit them. But even some doctors who
sympathize with unions blanch at the thought of walking a picket
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're professionals and we have an obligation to our
patients,'' Peer said. ``We wouldn't want to do anything to
jeopardize patient care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
