<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-27 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WE already knew Randy Johnson spent the offseason working on his
fielding.
</P>
<P>
   Or have you forgotten how Johnson sat in his desert palace last
winter entertaining huge free-agent offers like they were
candy-hops off a fungo?
</P>
<P>
   But we learned something else about Johnson on Monday night,
when he straight-faced the minicams and notepads with a big
announcement that he had decided after all to pitch against his
former team in this four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, we would realize only later, was simply working on his
wicked curveball. It was all a ruse.
</P>
<P>
   He told a gaggle of reporters before Monday night's series
opener that Astros skipper Larry Dierker had ``inspired'' him to
pitch in this four-game set. He said his decision had been prompted
by Dierker's comments about how the Astros might find consistent
emotion and passion by facing their former teammate.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all just made-for-TV jocularity, much like Johnson's
Mark McGwire-inspired home-run swing in the Nike commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It was all just the Big Unit suddenly becoming the Big
Diamondback Who Speaks With Forked Tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy after my own heart,'' Dierker said of Johnson's pre-game
caper.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did Johnson walk away from the cameras than he began
to giggle. No sooner was Arizona manager Buck Showalter approached
with news of Johnson's announcement than Showalter shook his head
and squelched the idea with a resounding, ``Uh, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the game went on and Johnson sat in the dugout, like he
will in all four games this week. The Astros won it 5-2 in much the
same fashion they did so many games a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   And a good time was had by all.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, folks: Exactly what will it take for the Astros
to begin stringing together performances such as Monday's? What
will it take for this season of high hopes and great expectations
to begin taking shape the way last season did at this exact point?
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, it's really been just a little of this and a little of
that for us,'' Dierker said. ``We haven't really been good. And we
haven't really been bad. We haven't really established a whole
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Monday's game can only be called the latest flowing Astros
performance in a season that has had almost as many disappointing
ebbs.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Jose Lima was tough and sharp. He got out of a
bases-loaded jam in the fourth, moving his pitches here and there
like they were doing the merengue. He fought off a tough start to
the sixth with terrific pitches against the D-Backs' Travis Lee and
Tony Batista.
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately missed his first complete game of the year by
three outs after giving up a walk and a run-scoring double to begin
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner sprinted in and looked better than ever, striking
out the side to earn his sixth save of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell continued his torrid 1999 with a 2-for-4
performance that included a double and two RBIs. Craig Biggio
doubled and scored. Derek Bell scored a pair of runs.
</P>
<P>
   It was flowing and impressive. But was it the start of something
big? The Astros must begin providing that answer soon, and the
schedule might indicate that this is their best opportunity yet.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Monday's game, the Astros possessed the exact record
they did after 17 games in 1998 _ 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Astros followed that start with 10 wins in their
next 12 games, taking over first place in the 12th game of that
stretch and never relinquishing it again.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Johnson arrived in August and the Astros went on to
102 wins.
</P>
<P>
   And a good time was had by all.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's win, the Astros follow with three more against
the well-stocked Diamondbacks and then a potentially significant
stretch. If the Astros can win this series, the next four series
are against the Florida Marlins, New York Mets, Montreal Expos and
Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are legitimate East Division contenders, but the
remaining three opponents are a combined 19-34.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Dierker doesn't take any wins for granted. But
reminded of the upcoming stretch, he added, ``You might look at the
schedule and say, `There's a place where we can win a few if we're
playing well.' The key is, you have to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is: Was Monday's opener against the
Diamondbacks the start of something big or just a ruse like the one
Johnson pulled before the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on both sides of the fence this year,'' Biggio
said. ``It seems like every time we've been about to get something
going, we haven't played well, or there's been a rainout. But it's
a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure. This is the time of year when it's still easy to laugh and
kid. But the Astros can use a nice run of wins, and now might be a
good time to start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
