<SLUG> BC-TRANS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVES OFFERS UP NEW TRANSPORTATION PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ In hopes of breaking a stalemate that has blocked
approval of a comprehensive transportation plan, Gov. Bill Graves
on Monday presented a new proposal and asked legislative leaders to
test support for it.
</P>
<P>
   His latest suggestion carries a 4-cent-a-gallon gasoline and
diesel fuel tax increase but no change in vehicle registration
fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a tax increase is not part of a plan, I don't think there
will be a plan this session,'' the governor said at a news
conference that followed two meetings with about 20 lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel taxes would be phased in. A 2-cent increase would come
July 1, followed by a 1-cent increase on July 1, 2001, and 1 cent
on July 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 12 percent of state sales tax collections eventually would
be shifted to the plan, which would provide $2.2 billion in
transportation funding over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The latest proposal would fund the major projects offered in
Graves' original proposal, including reconstructing U.S. 169 south
of Spring Hill, adding lanes to Interstate 435 in Overland Park and
rehabilitating Interstate 635 through Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   After a flurry of criticism in recent weeks about the governor
sitting on the sidelines while his pet issue was being discussed,
the action puts Graves at the forefront of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers return to Topeka Wednesday for a wrap-up session. With
a wide array of issues still pending, the session threatens to
stretch well into next week.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders of both parties were asked to take the
governor's plan to their caucuses to gauge support for it. They
also were asked to determine what changes their members might
support.
</P>
<P>
   Graves made it clear he isn't prepared for an extended battle
over a transportation plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the four caucuses don't report back by midweek or so that
there is continuing strong support for this plan or for some
permutation of a plan, I don't think we should allow the session to
get bogged down on the transportation issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without support for his plan or for some other compromise, he
said, ``My recommendation is probably going to be we quit beating
each other around the head and shoulders over transportation and
focus our attention on JJA (Juvenile Justice Authority) and foster
care, children's issues and the budget generally and higher
education and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic Lifelines, the statewide transportation lobbying
organization, will try to focus attention on the issue today with
six news conferences around the state, including one in Overland
Park.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, it will sponsor a rally of transportation
supporters at the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the session, the House approved a pay-as-you-go
transportation plan that tapped the state treasury for support
without increasing taxes or issuing bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate responded with a plan that increased the motor fuel
tax and car and truck registration fees and authorized nearly $1
billion worth of bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Each house rejected the other's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Graves' first plan, which was financed by a large bond issue and
no tax increases, drew almost no support in either house.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's new plan was designed to thread its way between
the House and Senate approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Initially it appeared that the governor's proposal would attract
more support in the Senate than in the House.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-member panel of House and Senate negotiators is working on
the issue and is scheduled to meet on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Ballou, an Olathe Republican who is one of the House
negotiators, said he couldn't support the governor's plan because
of the tax increase and the authority to issue $995 million in
20-year bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he would vote to send the proposal to the House
floor for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Like the governor, Ballou said he sees no need for extended
debate on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by Thursday night or Friday if we don't have
something, it's all over with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Robin Jennison, a Healy Republican, said House
Republicans still don't like the idea of a gas tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what the Democrats do,'' he said. ``I can't get
63 votes on this plan (from Republicans).''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the governor's actions may help the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he called everyone in ought to break things
loose,'' Jennison said.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Jim Garner, a Coffeyville Democrat, said
his members are split on transportation. ``I can't tell which way
the wind is blowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Dick Bond, an Overland Park Republican, said
Graves' plan could be the basis for an agreement, ``and I'm
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's chief negotiator, Sen. Audrey Langworthy, a Prairie
Village Republican, said the governor's plan ``goes a long way
toward breaking a stalemate. He's just kind of showing the way for
a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the governor's support of a tax increase for roads and
bridges could provide some political cover for lawmakers who have
dodged tax increases in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
