<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW EXPECTATIONS AWAIT DISNEY RESULTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Sluggish performance in broadcast and home video
operations are expected to lead to a sharp decline in The Walt
Disney Co.'s quarterly earnings this week.
</P>
<P>
   Profits for the entertainment giant's second quarter ended March
31 are expected to come in at 13 cents a share, according to First
Call's survey of 19 brokers. That represents a decline of 31
percent from earnings of $384 million, or 19 cents a share, in the
1998 period.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank-based Disney has not disclosed when it will release
results, but analysts believe the report could come as early as
today. Analysts believe most of the decline will come in the
creative content segment, which includes films, TV programming and
home video, with cash flow expected to decline about 30 percent
from the $389 million in the year-earlier quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Video received a boost last year from the ``The Little
Mermaid,'' while this year's period will include costs of pulling
3.4 million copies of ``The Rescuers'' because of a prankster
inserting nude photos on two frames.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcasting segment, which includes ABC and ESPN, will see
cash flow fall between 10 percent and 15 percent from $374 million
in the year-ago period. ABC has been a drag on earnings since being
acquired in 1996 due to lagging ratings brought on partly by viewer
migration to cable.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research Partners said Wall
Street has grown accustomed to sluggishness in Disney's
broadcasting. ``It's a very competitive business for generating a
reasonable return on capital,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Theme parks and resorts, the strongest segment in recent
quarters, is expected to increase cash flow by 10 percent from last
year's $375 million. ``Theme parks are what Disney is good at,''
Skislock said. ``They've managed to differentiate the Florida
complex by opening Animal Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney stock, which hit a record $42.375 last May, closed up
43.75 cents at $34.9375 on Monday. The issue, a component of the
Dow Jones industrial average, has trailed other media conglomerates
such as Time Warner and Viacom in recent months, Skislock noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations have really been tempered on Disney so
there's a lot of room for an upside surprise if they beat
estimates,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
