</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SLIDE CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It turns out that little ditch the Lakers fell into a
few weeks back isn't just a shallow divot. It's a deep, dark,
bottomless pit. And they're plunging rapidly, dragged down by two
awesome forces _ gravity and their own negative momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have fallen so far they can't even compete for one
quarter with a team that, until Monday, was arguably as disjointed
and disastrous as they are. Instead, the Houston Rockets, inept in
recent losses to the Clippers and Mavericks, looked like world
champions in a 102-80 victory that was never in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Worse for the Lakers, they will almost certainly return to
Compaq Center in less than two weeks for the first round of the
Western Conference playoffs. The Rockets' victory pushed them 1{
games ahead of the Lakers for the fourth and final home-court slot.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lost for the third straight time, their sixth defeat
in eight games. Afterward, it was all blank stares and profanity.
But no one had much of an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much to say,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``We just
have to play better team ball, a little bit better defense and just
get out of this little so-called funk.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other thoughts, but O'Neal held them back, too
frustrated to give his typical ``we just have to play smart''
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of saying the same (bleeping bleep),'' he said,
looking at the floor.
</P>
<P>
   How did he feel? ``Like a (bleeping) bum. Like a bum.''
</P>
<P>
   In all corners of the locker room, the sentiment was the same.
The Lakers are burning with anger, directed at themselves and at no
one in particular. For some reason, the NBA's star-studded glamour
team has a losing record in April, with five straight losses to
playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's a little upset, everybody's a little (ticked) off,
and we have a right to be,'' Kobe Bryant said. ``We're getting our
butt kicked every day.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more, those losses are secured in the first quarter.
The Rockets quickly exploited the Lakers' new Achilles' heel _ the
fast break _ converting turnovers and defensive rebounds into easy
transition baskets for a 28-14 lead heading into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   By early in the second quarter the deficit had bulged to 20
points, but by late in the half the Lakers had cut it to 11. They
never got closer than that, though, and by halftime the Rockets had
already scored 18 fast-break points for a 51-38 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen (26 points) ran unchecked at both ends of the
floor _ grabbing five of his six steals in the half and hitting
four 3-pointers. Charles Barkley (20 points) and Hakeem Olajuwon
(14) rounded out the three-pronged execution.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' Big Three was no match. O'Neal's 19 points matched
his lowest output of the season, his worst total in two months.
Same for Bryant, who missed his first 11 shots and scored just nine
points. Glen Rice scored 16 but was torched by Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a better shooting night from Bryant would have helped. But
in the end, the Lakers' still-dysfunctional defense would have
doomed them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``No defense. Just no passion to play the game,'' Derek Harper
said. ``Just no fire to come out and play a team that we're gonna
face in the playoffs probably. How do I explain it? It's very, very
difficult to explain. . . . How do we get it? You tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they do, it has to happen soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep saying, well (bleep), we're gonna wait until we
get to the playoffs. That's bull,'' Rice said. ``You keep saying
were gonna go out and play hard and hope we turn it around in the
playoffs. We gotta turn that (bleep) around now. We need to go into
the playoffs with some type of positive momentum. Going out and
having ourselves in the hole, down 20 points, that's not right.
You're not doing the team any justice, you're not doing yourself as
an individual any justice. It's just not right. It's a (messed) up
experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
