<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BICKLEY-COLUMN-HEROES     04-27 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BICKLEY-COLUMN-HEROES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL FILL VOID AS OUR HEROES RETIRE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Off they go, into the sunset, parting like it's 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A year that will live in infamy. Not for who won, but for who
left.
</P>
<P>
   There goes Michael Jordan, the best basketball player the world
has ever known, the fiercest competitor in the history of sports.
</P>
<P>
   There goes Wayne Gretzky, the elegant king of puck, the maestro
who opened America's eyes to the game of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   And there goes John Elway, poster boy for durability and
resiliency and courage.
</P>
<P>
   Three men who collectively embody every trait worth championing
in athletics. Three faces for a modern-era Mount Rushmore of
sports. And it may be a while before the monument is complete.
</P>
<P>
   As our heroes disappear, we are reminded that nothing moves
faster than time, how minutes are soon memories, and how not even
the fantasy world of sports is exempt. But in this year of closure,
the sense of loss seems profound, outweighing the inclination to
celebrate another farewell speech.
</P>
<P>
   In a previous era, there were always successors, a natural
continuum that couldn't be denied. But sports has become
complicated and messy, and so, too, have its athletes.
</P>
<P>
   They have the advantages of physical evolution and technological
advancements. One example is the wonderful career of Bobby Orr,
which was cut short due to knee injuries in the 1970s. Today, he
would've been in and out of the hospital and back in the lineup
within a week. But the mind-set has changed for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   No secret that athletes have become increasingly self-centered,
detached, overly concerned with getting paid. But you can't blame
them for following the path set before them, and every sport is
guilty of irreparable sin: marketing greatness before it is
reached, anointing and packaging heroes that don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the athletic culture is now focused on microwave
celebrities, undercooked athletes who arrive before they achieve.
And, really, what incentive is there to chase greatness when the
label is pre-packaged, diluted, oversold, handed out prematurely
and with reckless disregard?
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has already deemed Shaquille O'Neal one of its top 50
players of all time, a child who has been swept four times in the
postseason. In the midst of Gretzky's goodbye laps in Madison
Square Garden, the NHL couldn't wait to describe his handshake with
Jaromir Jagr as a symbolic passing of the torch. And in Maryland,
there is much commotion over a high school senior named Tamir
Goodman. He is deeply religious. He wears a yarmulke on the court.
He observes the Jewish Sabbath, and will never play basketball from
sundown on Friday to sundown on Saturday. He will arrive at the
University of Maryland with ungodly pressure, already nicknamed
``Jewish Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   So who can rise above the muck and transcend their sport in the
next 20 years?
</P>
<P>
   Scott Rolen? Paul Kariya? Alex Rodriguez? Jake Plummer? Jason
Kidd? Randy Moss?
</P>
<P>
   Your guess is as good as mine.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Jordan retired, he couldn't hide his disdain for how
the values have changed. The league hasn't exactly perished, but in
the last three months, we have learned what Allen Iverson wants on
his tombstone: Misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky retired, the stories were endless. Like the time he
skated up ice on a rush, passed a referee and, without looking up,
calmly told the official that the opposing team had six skaters on
the ice. The referee quickly did a head count, and sure enough,
Gretzky was right. But more than anything, over the course of 20
magical years, Gretzky remained untouched by scandal or a negative
word from anyone. Like Jordan, he understood the traits that lead
to greatness.
</P>
<P>
   And now Elway. Once, he was laughable, the Charlie Brown of
football. Once, Terry Bradshaw called him a baby on national
television, challenging him to finally produce in a Super Bowl.
Elway responded by throwing his first pass into the ground, walking
off the field a 45-point loser.
</P>
<P>
   But he persisted, won two Super Bowls and leaves at the
pinnacle. He never had a Jerry Rice, a Bill Walsh or a system ahead
of its time. He took more hits than any quarterback in history, yet
missed only 15 starts in 16 years. He did more by himself than Joe
Montana ever could. For everything he endured, he became a man, the
best quarterback in history.
</P>
<P>
   For everything he conquered _ the stigma, the humiliation, the
jokes _ he walks away a genuine hero.
</P>
<P>
   And in the on-deck circle, Cal Ripken Jr. Certainly not in the
same stratosphere, an athlete whose fame is more longevity than
accomplishment. But nonetheless, he embodies the work ethic of
yesteryear and the sturdy professionalism of another era.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they're leaving us. And leaving behind a few vacant
thrones. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
