<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST FINISH ONLY TEASES CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like Clark Kent whipping off the glasses and
loosening the knot in his tie, the Los Angeles Clippers have been
on the prowl for justice.
</P>
<P>
   It's the NBA way. But on Monday night, they showed the San
Antonio Spurs all the truth they'll ever need.
</P>
<P>
   After winning 25 of their 29 games, the Spurs (32-12) rolled
into the Sports Arena, built a 33-point lead, watched a motley
platoon of Clips knock it down to six in the fourth quarter, then
held on to win 94-88 in front of 8,260.
</P>
<P>
   It was San Antonio's seventh consecutive victory and corrupted a
Clippers winning streak that had peaked at two.
</P>
<P>
   But the home team, up to its ears in grit lately, rallied behind
Eric Piatkowski (27 points) and a few irregulars from the Clippers'
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Before the excitement, the Clips (9-36), who had won six of
their last 11 games, jumped out to a 7-0 deficit and acted like
they'd never look forward. They did squint for a bit, achieving a
20-20 deadlock at the 3:09 mark in round one when Piatkowski nailed
a 3-point push off a fast-break feed from Troy Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, who was liberated from the CBA several weeks ago, was
making his first NBA start because of the bum ankle of point guard
Sherman Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Douglas might have contributed to the Clippers'
33-percent field-goal disaster in the opening half, but the Spurs'
defense should absorb most of the guilt.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, let's look up at San Antonio's Twin Towers,
7-foot-1 David Robinson and 7-0 Tim Duncan. Robinson, by the way,
was making his last appearance at the Sports Arena, where he scored
71 points in a victory over the Clippers on April 24, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers countered with their Split-Level Condos, 6-8
Maurice Taylor and 7-0 rookie Michael Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   While Robinson didn't exactly intimidate Olowokandi (10 points,
seven rebounds in the first half), Duncan, who turned 23 on Sunday,
was quite the obstruction for Taylor. Carrying a 26-point-per-game
average over the last five games, Taylor missed nine of his 11
shots in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs ended the half when Duncan _ their
MVP-on-training-wheels _ tipped a 50-foot pass to Antonio Daniels,
who was fouled but converted the layup and free throw to make it
62-37 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter was just as ugly at the beginning, with the
Spurs' lead reaching 33 at 77-44. But with rookie Brian Skinner _
whose wife, Rebecca, gave birth to Avery Ann Alexes Skinner early
in the day _ providing a nasty presence inside, the Clippers did
manage a 16-0 run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4478 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-JAZZ-AZR &LR;      04-27 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-JAZZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD, SWEAT, CHEER  
 PHYSICAL PLAY GIVES SUNS BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The Suns did more than win a game here Monday
night. And their 99-85 drubbing of the Utah Jazz represents more
than just a nice road victory over the team with the NBA's best
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns also may have shed a label.
</P>
<P>
   Never regarded as one of the NBA's tougher, more physical team,
the Suns showed at the Delta Center they're willing to bang with
the best.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing without power forward Tom Gugliotta, the Suns
did more than match Utah's physical style. They beat the Jazz up at
their own game.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns whipped the Jazz on the boards, they gummed up Utah's
offense by fighting through picks and jamming cutters, and on the
offensive end they took the ball strong to the basket, outscoring
Utah, 36-24, in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rex Chapman torched them from afar, hitting three of four
three-point shots and nine of 16 shots overall, leading the Suns to
their third straight win with 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had that soft label for a long time,'' said Suns guard
Jason Kidd, who was so exhausted by effects of a cold that he
almost vomited late in the third quarter. ``We're going to get rid
of that `Valley of the Sun soft' label.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took their best shot and kept going after them. I think
everybody talks about Utah being physical, and we're not known for
it. But we're changing that. When we're the instigators, like we
were tonight, we win a lot of ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the physical tone to be set.
</P>
<P>
   Bad blood existed before the game. Last time the Suns visited
Utah, Phoenix lost center Luc Longley for seven games because of a
hypertextended left knee. Longley accused Utah's Karl Malone of
intentionally going after the knee.
</P>
<P>
   They picked up their discussion early, exchanging words after
Longley was called for an offensive foul for ramming into Malone.
Then with just over a minute to go in the first quarter, Longley's
backup and buddy, Joe Kleine, took a hard elbow from Malone as
Malone put up a shot near the basket.
</P>
<P>
   No foul was called on either Malone or Kleine, but Kleine's face
was a bloody mess. He stalked down court, caught up with Malone,
yelled at him and gave him a shove, steaking Malone's jersey with
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Kleine was called for a technical, and Malone had to leave the
floor to change his jersey. Kleine probably wished he had gotten
off so easily. He was taken to Lakeview Hospital in nearby
Bountiful, where Dr. Richard Kjar,
</P>
<P>
   a plastic surgeon, used 30 stitches to repair Kleine's lower
lip. He also was to be checked for a broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go into it,'' Longley said of his encounter
with Malone. ``I've said my piece. I will say this is my favorite
place in the world to get a win. I don't want to continue that
rubbish talk.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of Malone's elbow to Kleine's chops?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was fairly typical,'' Longley said. ``We just
heard Joe is having plastic surgery, getting his face repaired.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he didn't know what happened to Kleine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to the basket and he stuck his nose in there,''
Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Suns Coach Danny Ainge refused to comment on the incident,
saying he didn't see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe needed plastic surgery anyway,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad they didn't call the foul on Joe for hitting
Karl in the elbow with his face,'' Chapman added. ``I loved what
Joe did.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident seemed to inspire the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's part of the family,'' Kidd said. ``He thought it was a
cheap shot, so we all feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it was Malone and the Jazz who backed off. After
scoring 10 first-quarter points, Malone would get only 11 more. The
Jazz, who shot 71 percent in that first quarter, shot 35.6 percent
the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They trapped us and did a lot of things to take us out of our
offense,'' Utah Coach Jerry Sloan said. ``We never could get
anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns used a 19-4 burst in the final six minutes of the third
quarter to take control. Kidd scored 10 of his 19 points in the run
and was doubled over as the period ended.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:53 to play, Chapman popped open and hit a 22-foot jumper.
Ainge yelled from the bench, ``Ballgame!''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Utah was through. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
