<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4479 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     04-27 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD HOMER WINS FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn hit, Chuck Finley pitched, but the
rest of the Angels could do little Monday night _ until the 11th
inning, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad hit a leadoff homer off Nerio Rodriguez to give the
Angels a 4-3 victory over the Toronto Blue Jays before 17,324 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Troy Percival got the victory for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Through nine innings, the Angels were 2 for 12 with runners in
scoring position _ both hits belonging to Vaughn and worth two RBI.
The Angels' other run scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Finley gave up three runs and five hits in 62/3 innings, his
best outing of the year, but did not figure in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The first few innings were similar to the just-concluded road
trip for the Angels _ plenty of scoring opportunities that were
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, the Angels had runners on first and third
with one out. On a 3-2 pitch, Tim Salmon hit the ball up the
middle. But because Randy Velarde broke from first on the pitch,
second baseman Pat Kelly was at the bag to field the ball, step on
second and throw to first for the inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, the Angels had runners on first and second with
two out when Troy Glaus grounded a single to right field. The
problem for the Angels was that the player on second was Vaughn,
who _ on a tender left ankle _ was held up by third-base coach
Larry Bowa.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Greene then struck out with the bases loaded to end the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels finally broke through on Vaughn's two-out single to
left field in the fifth, making manager Terry Collins look like a
prophet.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Collins talked about Vaughn as a hitter: ``One
thing that impressed me in spring training was I don't know how
many times he hit the ball to left field with two outs to drive in
a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who went from first to third on Vaughn's single, scored
on a wild pitch later in the inning to give the Angels a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Finley rolled along. He set down the Blue Jays in
order the first three innings. Through six, Finley allowed only one
Blue Jays baserunner to reach second base. He struck out the side
in the third and did not walk anybody. He even got a Jim
Edmonds-like catch from center fielder Garret Anderson, who robbed
Mike Matheny of extra bases with a running catch while crashing
into the fence.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley got his first taste of trouble in the seventh. He
began the inning by hitting Carlos Delgado with a pitch, then
walked Tony Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   After pitching coach Dick Pole paid a visit to the mound, Finley
struck out Alex Gonzalez for the first out of the inning. But
Anthony Sanders, who got his first career major-league hit earlier
in the game, lined a 3-2 pitch into the left-field corner for a
two-run double to tie the game at 2.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek replaced Finley but gave up an RBI single to
Shannon Stewart and the Blue Jays had a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, though, wouldn't allow Finley to get the loss, his RBI
double in the bottom of the seventh scoring Velarde from first to
tie the game at 3. Vaughn, who hobbled to second, was replaced by
pinch runner Tim Unroe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
