<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4480 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_HEROES-AZ     04-27 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_HEROES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTUDIES UPSTAGE STARS  
 REPLACE INJURED COYOTES, KEY WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ After the first wave of television cameras and
microphones began to pull away, Louie DeBrusk thought he'd finally
be able to stop holding that towel around his waist and get to
scoot into the shower.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't happen for at least another 45 minutes. There was a
second wave of interviews, then a third and a fourth. It was the
longest post-game chat session of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In another corner, right wing Stephen Leach held court for a few
minutes here, a few minutes there, and then for quite a few more
after he shaved and showered.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the locker room door, center Brian Noonan was
stopped and grilled by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   And while all this was going on, after the Coyotes managed to
stave off a torrid rally Sunday by the St. Louis Blues in Game 3 of
their Western Conference quarterfinal series, the team's general
manager, Bobby Smith, was cornered by another media mob asking him
questions about all three of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Noonan, Leach and DeBrusk. Three role players and reserves. A
trio of veterans who spent most of the regular season in different
minor league cities, playing in relative obscurity. A Tom, Dick and
Harry who quietly slip out of the locker room unnoticed after
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all Stanley Cup playoff heroes tonight,'' Smith
said, beaming after the three players helped the Coyotes to a 5-4
victory and a 2-1 series lead over the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 is today at 4:30 p.m. in the Kiel Center, and if the
Coyotes can get another performance from their growing band of
unsung upstarts, they can put St. Louis on the brink of elimination
with Game 5 scheduled for Friday at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. Three players dumped and forgotten by other NHL
teams, relocating in the right place at the right time, and giving
this franchise a shot in the arm to do something it hasn't done in
12 years _ win a first-round playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   All, for the most part, because they're getting a chance to play
because of injuries to Jeremy Roenick, Juha Ylonen and Greg Adams,
who might be back tonight after missing Games 2 and 3 because of a
pulled groin.
</P>
<P>
   But they say that's how it happens sometimes in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, absolutely,'' said St. Louis defenseman Al MacInnis, who
just completed his 18th season in the league. ``You need all four
lines trying to contribute. It's not always the (Pavol) Demitras
and the (Keith) Tkachuks. It's guys chipping in from all over, and
that's how you're successful and that's what you need to win in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need guys chipping in like those guys did for them, and we
need guys from our third and fourth lines chipping in as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach, 33, signed as a free agent in January three months after
being released by the Ottawa Senators, got the Coyotes running in
Game 3 here on Sunday. He set up Dallas Drake with a perfect drop
pass, which Drake buried for the first of four goals that would
chase goalie Grant Fuhr by the start of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played great, hasn't he?'' Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld
said. ``Unbelievable. High energy, he's finishing his checks, he's
been very responsible in the defensive zone, and he's created some
good offensive opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goal he set up for Dally was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   So was the first of two scores Noonan set up for DeBrusk that
gave the Coyotes a 4-0 lead. Noonan slid the puck right where
DeBrusk needed it, and the tough guy who hadn't scored a goal since
1997 _ and just six since 1994 _ ripped a slap shot that went
between Fuhr's legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got caught moving out on that one,'' Fuhr said.
</P>
<P>
   When Noonan fed DeBrusk a second time for a long, bouncing shot
he fired from near the red line, Fuhr was speechless. So was
DeBrusk, 28, who joined the Coyotes last summer from Tampa Bay as a
virtual throw-in player when Phoenix traded away center Craig
Janney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm always surprised when it goes in the net, you know
what I mean?'' DeBrusk said. ``I think I'm the first one to say,
`Is it really in?' It takes me a second to kind of register, `Yeah,
it's in the net. I scored a goal.' I'm not a big scorer, obviously.
If you look at my stats, they don't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBrusk had zero points in 15 games with the Coyotes amid 13
call-ups, demotions and reassignments.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto with Noonan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get a chance to contribute,'' Noonan said.
``Obviously, you don't like to see anybody get injured. But when
somebody does get hurt, it's chance for someone like myself to get
to play. It's nice to be out there again. I haven't been in the
playoffs the past couple years, and it's nice to be a part of it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same for Leach. When Smith brought him to Phoenix, he
told Leach there were no guarantees, that he might have to spend
the rest of the year down on the farm. But Leach has played as well
as anyone in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a chance to play, you have to play hard,'' he
said. ``But it's a long series. You just have to stay focused. All
of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
