<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-27 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BASED on the way the two contestants had been stumbling down the
stretch run of the NBA's add-hot-water-and-eat Cup O' Season, this
was a case of the lame beating the infirm. Or the see-no-evil
monkey getting the better of the speak-no-evil monkey.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rockets-Lakers in a national cable encounter on the (We'll Soon
Be) History Channel. The producers could have simulated the game by
shoving a piano and a safe off the roof of a 10-story building to
see which would hit the ground first and break into more pieces.
</P>
<P>
   For the scientific record, it would be a tie. Newton's law. For
the basketball record, it was the Lakers who had to be swept up off
the floor with a broom after getting shattered into so many tiny
bits. Which can happen when one team plays like a bear and the
other barely plays. Naismith's law.
</P>
<P>
   So put the jumper cables on the bandwagon and get ready to
string those championship banners from the street lights again.
</P>
<P>
   There was Cuttino Mobley setting the tone for the evening by
stealing a pass from Shaquille O'Neal and hustling to the other end
to convert a three-point play. Then Mobley came right back to pick
the pocket of Derek Fisher and go all the way in for a fast-break
dunk.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Rockets running all night long like they were
being chased by hounds from hell. Scottie Pippen active, alive,
jumping and sparking all over the court like a live wire to get in
the passing lanes with those long arms, reaching in with those
quick hands to disrupt so much of what the Lakers were trying.
Pippen getting his own offense started by taking _ and making _
3-pointers on his way to a 26-point night.
</P>
<P>
   There was Charles Barkley acting like a bowling ball smashing
into a set of tenpins, controlling the boards, dominating on the
inside, bending and then folding Robert Horry more than a piece of
origami. Chuck took Horry down on the blocks and spun by him. He
pulled up right in Horry's face and double-pumped in a banker from
20 feet. He even grinned at a one-on-one challenge against the
mountainous Shaq and then drilled a step-back jumper.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Rockets playing defense like they were a bunch of
kids who had just unwrapped their newest birthday toy. They
displayed energy and enthusiasm and the kind of intensity that made
them look like the halftime entertainment _ Destiny's Child.
</P>
<P>
   But it will matter only if they can do it again the next time
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't come out focused for this one,'' said coach Rudy
Tomjanovich, ``then we don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely.
</P>
<P>
   This had all the trappings, every bell and whistle you could ask
for. A game against a high-profile (though underachieving) team
with the Rockets feeling mad and a bit embarrassed at what had
preceded it. Namely three straight losses to the Mavericks,
Clippers and Suns that would barely have registered on a heart
monitor.
</P>
<P>
   This was Shaq, Kobe Bryant and the rest of NBC's team coming
into the Laptop trying to sort out their own problems with a likely
playoff matchup between the teams looming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not big on sending messages,'' Rudy T said. ``We just
needed a win.''
</P>
<P>
   So they applied a tourniquet and stopped the femoral artery from
spurting like a fire hose. Now the question remains how to keep
burning the fire that allowed the Rockets to smoke LA on fast-break
points 26-4 and win the battle of the boards 42-36.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Rockets the way we have seen them on several
occasions this year, most recently against Portland on April 15.
They are quite capable. They are very dangerous. In fact, if the
fight for the NBA championship were just one game, it would be
unwise to pick against them. As this night proved.
</P>
<P>
   But it matters only if they carry the momentum out of this one
through the last five games on the regular-season schedule. Only if
they don't feel like they got the puzzle figured out and keep on
striving.
</P>
<P>
   The precocious Kobe will not miss his first 10 shots in every
playoff game, and Glen Rice won't shoot just 2-for-5 on treys
throughout the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very big game for us,'' said Hakeem Olajuwon. ``But
it wasn't the last game. Just like if we'd lost, it wouldn't have
been the end of the season, winning doesn't mean we are done moving
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``A championship team continues to grow and build upon a
foundation. We have thought we had the foundation other times this
year, then we slacked off. Not purposefully. Still, it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   For an evening, they were every X and each O drawn perfectly.
They were the lab experiment that came off flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   But the mighty Mavs come back to town Thursday, then Utah on
Friday. This matters only if it wasn't a one-night show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
