<HEADLINE>
FANS CAN HEAR, NOT SEE, KENTUCKY DERBY ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the events that lend themselves to dynamic streaming
video presentation, the Kentucky Derby has to be one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   It's a two-minute race, perfect for online viewing. And with
cameras all over Churchill Downs, the technology is in place.
</P>
<P>
   But expect audio only for the 125th Run for the Roses on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Schmitt, senior vice president of communications at
Churchill Downs, said ABC TV's broadcast rights prohibit the use of
a cybercast on the track's official site (www.kentuckyderby.com).
</P>
<P>
   And that's a shame, said Schmitt, who also believes that a
cybercast of the race would make for good online video.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think so,'' he said. ``Someday we'll be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Derby site will have to settle for an audio
description of the race, available through Dallas-based
Broadcast.com. Last year, the site attracted 10,000 listeners,
Schmitt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works out great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Audio is only one of the attractions at the track's 5-year-old
site. Schmitt said the site's traffic has doubled in the past year
because of better design, more updates of Derby contenders and
stakes races and the introduction of a historical section. Schmitt
also said he hopes that the site will have a Java-powered tote
board with live odds.
</P>
<P>
   Other features include a daily poll, tips for Derby parties, a
horse racing primer, a tutorial available for downloading on how to
read a racing program, workout information and a link to the Derby
auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who come to our site in the past have demonstrated they
want updated information about the horses, some historical
information, and they want to experience the beauty and splendor of
the Derby, and even how to put on a Derby party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DERBY SITES: More about the Derby can be found at the Daily
Racing Form's site (www.drf2000.com) and Blood-Horse Interactive
(www.bloodhorse.com).
</P>
<P>
   At drf2000.com, users can access statistics, future book odds
and commentary. Blood-Horse Interactive is devoted to breeding and
blood lines.
</P>
<P>
   BEST LIVING BALLPLAYER: Now that Joe DiMaggio has passed on, CBS
SportsLine has decided that the title of ``Greatest Living
Ballplayer'' is up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than let sportswriters wax on about this, CBS SportsLine
is letting readers decide with a Historical Matchup Tournament.
Fans can vote for eight seeded position players in a bracket format
(No. 1 vs. No. 8, No. 2 vs. No. 7, and so on).
</P>
<P>
   The players are Ted Williams, Willie Mays, Stan Musial, Hank
Aaron, Ken Griffey Jr., Mike Schmidt, Frank Robinson and Joe
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
