<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS2-LADN-(WRITETHROUGH) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD BLOW WINS FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Finally, someone other than Mo Vaughn got a
hit when it mattered for the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad hit the first pitch thrown by Toronto Blue Jays
reliever Nerio Rodriguez over the right-field fence in the bottom
of the 11th inning to give the Angels a 4-3 victory Monday night
before 17,324 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Through 10 innings, the Angels' offense consisted of an RBI
single by Vaughn, an RBI double by Vaughn and a run that scored on
a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Erstad's homer _ his second of the season _ left no doubt,
easily clearing the fence in right at an estimated at 400 feet. It
was the first game-winning homer by an Angel at Edison Field since
April 23, 1997, when Jim Edmonds homered in the 10th inning against
the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival (1-1), who pitched a scoreless 11th inning, got
the victory over Rodriguez (0-1).
</P>
<P>
   Erstad said he hopes his home run was worth more than just one
victory, that it is an indication that things will turn around for
a team that entered Monday's game 1-6 in one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any win's big, but we've been playing poorly without intensity
or heart,'' he said. ``After getting a win like this, in a tough
game, it's a good sign we're headed in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight the whole team came out with intensity, which is
something we've been lacking. We've got to go out every night and
play like this. It's something we haven't had this year.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't appear to have it early, however. The first few
innings were similar to the just-concluded road trip for the Angels
_ plenty of scoring opportunities that were wasted.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, the Angels had runners on first and third
with one out and didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, the Angels had runners on first and second with
two out when Troy Glaus grounded a single to right field. The
problem for the Angels was that the player on second was Vaughn,
who _ on a tender left ankle _ was held up by third-base coach
Larry Bowa. Todd Greene then struck out with the bases loaded to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hitting is going to come along,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``The guys are working hard, hitting early (in
batting practice), looking at tape. That's one thing we can do _
swing the bats.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels finally broke through in the fifth on a two-out
single to left field by Vaughn. Erstad, who went from first to
third on Vaughn's single, scored on a wild pitch later in the
inning to give the Angels a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Angels starter Chuck Finley rolled along. He set down
the Blue Jays in order in the first three innings. Through six,
Finley allowed only one Blue Jays baserunner to reach second base.
He struck out the side in the third and did not walk anybody. He
even got an Edmonds-like catch from center fielder Garret Anderson,
who robbed Mike Matheny of extra bases with a running catch while
crashing into the fence.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley got his first taste of trouble in the seventh. He
began the inning by hitting Carlos Delgado with a pitch, then
walked Tony Fernandez. One out later, Anthony Sanders lined a
two-run double to left to tie the game at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek replaced Finley and gave up an RBI single to
Shannon Stewart as the Blue Jays took a 3-2 lead. Finley's line was
his best of the season _ 62/3 innings, three runs, five hits, seven
strikeouts, two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn tied it with his RBI double in the seventh, setting the
stage for Erstad to win it. A sign of things to come?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Erstad said. ``We've been pretty flat lately. We
haven't been playing very well, myself included.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
