<HEADLINE>
TWINS BEAT RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-TWINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ One bad pitch is all it takes to ruin Tim
Wakefield's day. The Red Sox knuckleballer threw a dandy Monday
night, and a Minnesota Twins rookie made him pay.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect offering _ a high knuckler _ took wing with the
bases loaded in the fourth inning. Center fielder Torii Hunter's
grand slam sent the Twins on their way to a 6-2 victory at the
Metrodome, ending Minnesota's four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Hunter's third of the season and first major
league grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made one mistake,'' said Wakefield, who gave up all six
Minnesota runs on five hits over 5 1/3 innings. ``And it cost me a
ballgame. I threw some good pitches, but the one that didn't come
out right got hit. It just happened to be a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wakefield, the loss was his third in a row after a
season-opening victory.
</P>
<P>
   Though he did himself in by giving up the slam, Wakefield didn't
get much help from his teammates. The Red Sox had eight hits
against Brad Radke in six innings, but could get only one run
against the Twins starter. Boston took a 1-0 lead in the first
inning on a single by Jose Offerman and a double by John Valentin.
They didn't score again until the ninth, when Reggie Jefferson hit
a homer off reliever Mike Trombley. It was Jefferson's first homer
since June 26, and his first ever in the Metrodome. Boston left 12
runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the ball good,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``And
we're going in the right direction in that we're hitting the ball
hard and we made some hard outs. Radke pitched good when he had to
and changed speeds. He can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also was impressed by his own starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Wakefield was pretty good,'' said the manager. ``He
came back and struck out two guys in that (fourth) inning. But the
ball he threw to Hunter was up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter followed the advice of his manager, Tom Kelly, in
swinging at the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``T.K. keeps telling us about an old saying about
knuckleballs,'' said the rookie. ``He told everybody, `If it's
high, let it fly. If it's low, let it go.' This one was up, so I
swung.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield left in the sixth _ with two runners aboard, for whom
he was responsible. Ron Coomer led off with a single, and after a
one-out walk to Terry Steinbach, Wakefield was replaced by Tim
Harikkala. The reliever retired Chad Allen but proceeded to give up
run-scoring singles to Hunter and Denny Hocking.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield did not consider the night a total loss, saying he
threw longer and better than in his last two outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked with (pitching coach) Joe Kerrigan on my mechanics,
and I was solid tonight,'' said Wakefield. ``I was getting a better
turn. Obviously, the ball was moving quite a bit. Jason (Varitek)
had a lot of trouble behind the plate.'' The Sox catcher had two
passed balls.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of hope for the Red Sox came in the form of a
fifth-inning single by Trot Nixon, who started his first game in a
week and ended an 0-for-24 streak.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon tried out a new batting stance in which his hands are down
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried it for the first time today and I feel very
comfortable,'' he said. ``I just eliminate all the movement I had
before. That's probably where the problems were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
