<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOEHLER PROVES A PAIN TO MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After a fairly relaxed weekend in Florida, the
Mariners returned to face the Detroit Tigers at the Kingdome Monday
night. They should have gone straight to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   They had this Moehler that was bugging them _ Detroit's Brian
Moehler.
</P>
<P>
   For seven innings, the home club couldn't bite down on anything
hard against the thickly built right-hander from North Carolina and
went on to lose 7-0 to open an eight-game homestand before a crowd
of 25,465.
</P>
<P>
   Moehler outdid the Mariners' new $15 million man, Jamie Moyer,
who was making his first appearance since agreeing to a rich
two-year contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers pitcher was much cheaper and better, scattering seven
harmless singles over his seven innings of duty. He was so
efficient, he threw just 87 pitches, 55 for strikes, and didn't
walk anyone. No one even reached third base on him.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Moehler (3-2) didn't do was go the distance. He
was fine with that. The Mariners certainly weren't sorry to see him
sit down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe with a seven-run lead, there's no point in throwing
another 40 pitches,'' the pitcher said. ``I could have finished.
I'll save it for my next start.''
</P>
<P>
   Moehler changed speeds. He hit spots. He even balked several
times _ and got away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the fourth inning, the Mariners accused Moehler of
balking during his windup. They said he separated his arms while
toeing the rubber and looking for the catcher's sign, a baseball
no-no.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey was the first to complain. Mariner manager Lou
Piniella was next. Detroit manager Larry Parrish walked out on the
field three times to chat with the umps before everything
apparently was settled to everyone's satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they weren't going to call it a balk, we were going to keep
letting Moehler do it,'' Parrish said, explaining that his starter
was trying to keep from tipping his pitches as he had in pervious
outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said technically I was balking,'' Moehler said. ``They
were right.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Huskey: ``He owes us at least four bases. I'm not a
base-stealer, but it was throwing me off when he got set.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners needed more than four more bases to make it a game
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 235-pound Moehler was in trouble only twice, and
they were mild disturbances. He got out of both with relative ease.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Moehler put two runners on base for the
first time, with two outs. He quickly snuffed that threat by making
David Segui pop out to third baseman Dean Palmer, who circled and
made the catch on the top of the pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling Mariner frustration, Segui flung his black bat away
with such disgust it bounced all the way to the backstop,
ricocheting off the padded wall.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, the Mariners had runners on first and second
with one out, but Moehler got out of it with a pair of lazy
groundballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing bothers him too much,'' Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was changing speeds,'' said Huskey, who got three of the
Mariners' seven hits off Moehler. ``That's a couple of our
pitchers' game. Move the ball up and down. He was on tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer (1-3) was not. Seattle's highest-paid pitcher ever gave up
solo home runs by Juan Encarnacion and Karim Garcia among the five
runs he permitted. He left after seven innings, responsible for 11
of Detroit's season-high 15 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't particularly sharp,'' Piniella said of his starter.
``I've seen him pitch better.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the long ball, Moyer also gave up runs on an Encarnacion
single in the second inning, Bobby Higginson's run-scoring single
in the fifth and Garcia's RBI single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Moyer beat Moehler twice in head-to-head matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbingly, the Mariners now have just one victory in 10
starts this season by their top two pitchers, Moyer and Jeff
Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   From this tepid effort, there was one encouraging play by a
Seattle guy. Right fielder Jay Buhner, showing no sign of offseason
elbow surgery, threw out his first runner of the season, Dean
Palmer, who was trying to score from second base in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, it was just a temporary filling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
