 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2537 - April 26, 1999  NEWS &AMP; FEATURES
SUMMARY N0 2537 - April 26,1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability in your
country. Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. MILOSEVIC'S CLOSEST ENEMY by BLAINE HARDEN From The New York
Times Magazine The Balkans region desperately needs a hero, and
Montenegro's President Djukanovic is perhaps the one leader whom
the West can rally around. Yet NATO bombs have changed all that.
They have belied Djukanovic's promise to voters that a turn to the
West would produce peace and wealth. Instead, the bombs have
emboldened his enemies, possibly tipping the balance in the wicked
game of chicken he is playing with the Serbian dictator Slobodan
Milosevic.
---------------------------------------------------------------- 2.
``A MILITARY ALLIANCE, AND MORE'' by Tony Blair, an Op-Ed from the
New York Times In commemoration of NATO's 50th anniversary
celebration, the British prime minister writes that there is every
reason for the current action in Kosovo inasmuch as the group
should be a moral federation, not just a military alliance.
----------------------------------------------------------------3.
EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW WITH RUSSIAN PRIME MINISTER EVGUENI PRIMAKOV by
MAREK HALTER - text in French only
----------------------------------------------------------------4.
CARVILLE WORKS THE TEL AVIV WAR ROOM by ADAM NAGOURNEY From The New
York Times Magazine
</P>
<P>
   James Carville and Arthur Finkelstein are two of the most famous
- and different - American political consultants in international
demand today. Both of them are top operatives in the May 17 Israeli
elections - Carville representing Ehud Barak, the main opponent to
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who is, in turn, a client of
Finkelstein. (And yes, Mary Matalin is for Netanyahu.)
----------------------------------------------------------------5.
REPORTING LIVE, FROM A WAR ZONE By PETER GODWIN From The New York
Times Magazine ``The backstage truth is that no matter how
tenderhearted reporters may be at the outset, any capacity for
empathy is all but drowned by the sheer flow of suffering during
wartime. Most war reporters must cultivate a controlled
schizophrenia to survive. We develop a sang froid, a mordant humor
and a studied machismo, much the same way that cops and ER doctors
do.''
----------------------------------------------------------------6.
CHILE WAITS FOR THE PINOCHET VERDICT By Tomas Eloy Martinez 70% of
the Chileans do not feel any compassion toward the ex-dictator, 10
% are indifferent, and another 20% want him to return untouched to
London. It is difficult to discern if those who defend Pinochet do
so because they believe in justice or because they are looking out
for their own interest.
----------------------------------------------------------------7.
DURING TRAGEDIES, THE TV REPORTER IS NOT A LOVING FRIEND by Janna
Malamud Smith - an Op-Ed from the New York Times The author, a
clinical social worker, writes on how television has taken up the
longstanding role of confessor in our culture and wonders whether
this will have any longterm psychological effects on the children
of Littleton, Colorado.
----------------------------------------------------------------8.
``WE ARE GETTING CLOSER TO OUR GOAL'' From Der Spiegel - An
in-depth interview with German Defence Minister Rudolf Scharping on
the moral justification of the war, the aims of NATO and Yugoslavia
without Slobodan Milosevic.
----------------------------------------------------------------9.
LOST FOR WORDS by Julie Clayton From New Scientist Reading is a
nightmare for millions of children. Dyslexia seems to be caused by
a breakdown in the way sensory nerves develop in the fetal brain.
Can a controversial new theory explain why? Could the mother's
immune system be to blame?
