 (l and f coding)  
 SOUNDS SHADY, BUT DESIGNER SUNGLASSES ON NET A REAL DEAL
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ If we told you we could get you a pair of designer
sunglasses at 30 percent off retail, you'd probably say, ``What's
the catch?''
</P>
<P>
   The catch is you have to buy them over the Internet, as we did a
couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now we know this doesn't sound so bad, given that companies
these days are selling everything from books to mortgages over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But most manufacturers of high-priced sunglasses warn customers
to stay away from Internet sales. They view Internet retailers as
the cyber equivalent of the street-corner hustler hawking
merchandise of dubious origin and quality out of a suitcase. They
scorn the dozens of Web sites selling big names like Serengeti,
Ray-Ban, Revo, Vuarnet, and Maui Jim at steep discounts.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, Bausch &AMP; Lomb, the maker of Ray-Bans, says it
prohibits the sales of its sunglasses over the Internet. The
company warns consumers that they may end up with counterfeits or
defective merchandise if they buy from anyone other than an
authorized retailer, which in the Boston area is the chain of
Sunglass Hut stores. Other manufacturers refuse to honor warranties
if their product is purchased over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But as we found out, not all designer shades on the Internet are
fakes. We also learned that Bausch &AMP; Lomb, at least, had no idea
how much cyberspace peddling of its products was going on, even
among groups with links to its authorized dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, we bought two pairs of Ray-Ban Predator 9
sunglasses (model number W2967) from two randomly selected Web
sites _ apairofshades.com and shadesrus.com. We paid $71.95 and
$69.95, respectively, for sunglasses that would have cost more than
$100 each at Sunglass Hut.
</P>
<P>
   The sunglasses looked like the real thing, but just to be sure
we sent them off to Bausch &AMP; Lomb, and the Rochester, N.Y., firm
confirmed their authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got lucky,'' said Barbara Kelley, vice president of
communications at Bausch &AMP; Lomb, after her staff examined them.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley still insisted Internet retailers shouldn't be trusted
because they are either acquiring their Ray-Bans through improper
channels or selling fakes or discontinued styles. She said the
company may investigate, but it's a time-consuming process to trace
counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
   The two cyber-retailers we bought our sunglasses from said they
sell only the real thing. They say Bausch &AMP; Lomb and other
manufacturers have mounted a campaign against Internet sales to
protect their hefty profit margins and maintain the snob appeal of
their products.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Piazza Jr., who runs apairofshades.com out of Warwick,
N.Y., said he is authorized by Bausch &AMP; Lomb to sell Ray-Bans, even
though the corporation insists that all of its authorized vendors
must sign statements agreeing not to sell over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, 36, said his Web site is getting 15,000 hits and ringing
up about 400 sales a month. A licensed optician, Piazza offers a
30-day money-back guarantee and also sells Wanger watches, Tasco
binoculars, and Swiss Army knives.
</P>
<P>
   Phong Ly and John Passarelle, who started running their
shadesrus.com Web site out of Bergenfield, N.J., last month, say
they buy their Ray-Ban sunglasses from an authorized Ray-Ban
distributor. They know Bausch &AMP; Lomb frowns on what they do, but
they say the business looks promising.
</P>
<P>
   How can you tell an authentic pair of Ray-Bans? Before sending
them, we noticed some distinctive tiny ``BL'' markings on the lens,
as well as codes along the temple or sidepieces of the frame.
Kelley refused to give details, saying she doesn't want to help any
potential counterfeiters.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after verifying the authenticity of our shades,
Kelley called to tell us that they ``just recently'' decided to
allow Sunglass Hut to use its Web site to sell Ray-Ban shades. No
longer scorning e-commerce purchases of Ray-Bans, she said the
company is exploring the possibility of allowing other authorized
dealers to peddle Ray-Bans on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing, given that a subsidiary of Sunglass Hut, a
Web site called www.shades.com, is already doing it. And they offer
good bargains, compared to their parent company's stores. At
www.shades.com, you can't buy the Predator 9 style Ray-Ban shades,
but you can buy the Predator 8 and 5 styles.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunglass Hut stores, each pair sells for $100. At
www.shades.com, each pair sells for $59.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Tune-out calls. As another barrier against telemarketers and
other unwelcome callers, Bell Atlantic this summer plans to unveil
a program that gives Caller ID customers the option of accepting
calls only from those they know. With this service, phone numbers
that are blocked (thereby showing up ``private'' or ``unavailable''
on the screen) cannot get through without the caller identifying
themselves by name or affiliation. The customer can then accept or
decline the call. Another future program will allow customers to
block calls during specified hours of the day or put them all into
voice-mail.
</P>
<P>
   --Spring cleaning. The US Consumer Product Safety Commission has
announced a spring recall round-up, calling on consumers to get
hazardous products out of their homes. The panel has sent out
recent alerts on unsafe playpens, battery-powered Power Wheels
vehicles, toaster ovens, infant car seats, mini-hammocks, and
infant swings. For more details, contact the commission through its
hotline at 1-800-638-2772 or its Web site at www.cpsc.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
