<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-EYES-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      04-27 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EYES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME MAY BE AT HAND TO FIX YOUR EYES SURGICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laser eye surgery has become so effective and widely accepted
for correcting vision problems that more than 1 million Americans
are expected to have the procedure done this year and next. But
it's no surprise that many people still get squeamish hearing the
words ``eye,'' ``laser'' and ``cut'' in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the US Food and Drug Administration approved
what may be an attractive new option for some mildly nearsighted
people leery of having part of their eye burned off: tiny plastic
rings that are inserted on the edges of the cornea to flatten it
and sharpen up the patient's view of distant things.
</P>
<P>
   European and Canadian doctors have been implanting the Intacs
rings for up to three years already. The main selling point is
that, unlike laser surgery, the procedure can be undone if patients
are unhappy with their new vision.
</P>
<P>
   However, many national eye specialists are skeptical the
implants will ever become more than a narrowly used alternative to
laser surgery. They cite several reasons: The rings cost as much or
more (roughly $2,000 per eye), installation hurts more, and for the
foreseeable future they will fix only a small range of mild
nearsightedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantages are few, and I bet in Boston it's going to be
something that really doesn't take off,'' said Carmen A. Puliafito,
director of the New England Eye Center in Boston and chairman of
the Tufts Medical School ophthalmology department, who performed
Massachusetts' first laser eye surgery in December 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dimitri T. Azar, a top surgeon at the Massachusetts Eye and
Ear Infirmary who has been to Paris to learn the procedure, said,
``Our plan is to start very carefully and not jump into it, because
there could be some hidden surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   At least for the first several months, Azar said, the infirmary
will require patients choosing rings to go to an operating room
with an anesthesiologist assisting, because of the pain of one
motion where the eye is simultaneously pulled and turned. The laser
eye surgeries can be done in a room set up like a dentist's office
with a reclining chair.
</P>
<P>
   The potential market for any of the operations is immense.
According to American Academy of Ophthalmology estimates, a quarter
of all Americans are nearsighted and another 22 percent are
farsighted. Nearly 150 million people, the academy says, wear some
kind of eyewear, including non-prescription reading glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, an estimated 500,000 Americans have paid for laser
surgery _ which virtually no health plan covers _ to reduce or
eliminate the need for contact lenses or eyeglasses. Currently, the
two most frequently performed visual correction surgeries are
called Lasik, which stands for laser-assisted in-situ
keratomileusis, and PRK, for photorefractive keratectomy.
</P>
<P>
   People have trouble seeing either near or far because their eyes
have less than the optimal curvature to focus images on the retina,
the membrane at the back of the eye that receives visual images.
Both Lasik and PRK slightly reshape the surface of the eye, making
it either flatter to improve distance vision or more steeply
pitched to improve near vision.
</P>
<P>
   In PRK procedures, lasers guided by computer calculations shear
off very thin layers of tissue _ a fraction of the thickness of a
piece of paper usually _ from parts of the cornea surface to
produce a shape that yields clearer vision.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik has been dubbed ``flap and zap'' because it involves a
surgeon using an automated cutting device like a carpenter's plane
to slice an ultrathin flap from the surface of the eye, which is
peeled back to allow a laser to vaporize tissue underneath.
</P>
<P>
   The flap is then replaced and patients heal much faster than
with PRK, in perhaps two days instead of a week. Also, immediately
after leaving the operating chair patients see better instead of
having to wait up to 20 days to know how their vision has been
improved, which is the case with PRK.
</P>
<P>
   Neither technique is foolproof, however. Flap complications
occur in about 1 to 2 percent of Lasik cases, but usually can be
surgically fixed. A comparably small percentage of people
undergoing both types of operations complain about blurry vision,
halos, glare, problems seeing at night or are simply disappointed
the procedure didn't yield the improvement they hoped for,
according to several US studies.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik is considered best suited to people with high to severe
nearsightedness or farsightedness. It has boomed to more than 80
percent of all eye surgeries since it was introduced in 1996,
according to Irving J. Arons, managing director of Spectrum
Consulting in Peabody, Mass., a leading authority on the
eye-surgery market.
</P>
<P>
   KeraVision, the Fremont, Calif., company that produces the new
Intacs implants, apparently sees a market among people who dislike
the idea of making a permanent, irreversible change in their eyes
or fear complications, which are rare.
</P>
<P>
   The rings, made of a polymer used for decades in cataract
surgery, are inserted about 1/3 of an inch from the center of the
eye through two small incisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best selling point seems to be the fact that they are
removable, there's a second chance and all your marbles aren't in
one basket,'' said Dr. Richard L. Abbott, codirector of corneal and
refractive surgery at the University of California at San Francisco
Medical Center, who was a principal investigator in Intacs trials
at 11 teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   However, Abbott said that he sees the rings as only ``a niche
product. The idea is that this technology would be expanded'' for
use on more myopics as well as people with hyperopia
(farsightedness) and astigmatism. However, studies are only
beginning overseas on adapting the rings to these uses and it could
be years before they can be more broadly used in the US, Abbott
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting technology, but its use right now is limited,''
said Dr. Ernest Kornmehl, medical director of the Center for Laser
Vision Correction in Brookline, Mass., who is on the faculties of
the Harvard, Tufts and University of Massachusetts medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   In people with especially large pupils that dilate widely at
night, the rings may obstruct vision on the periphery. About 1 in
10 people in early trials complained about seeing halos or glare
after getting the corneal rings, but that figure should drop as
surgeons master the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 0951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4662 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-EYES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BO     04-27 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EYES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... the procedure.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New England Eye Center's Puliafito is especially skeptical
about Intacs, saying: ``Is it better than laser? No. Is it easier
for the surgeon to do? No. Is it easier for the patients? No...I
think it's a very clever device, but it addresses a problem that
doesn't exist,'' Puliafito said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, as KeraVision began investing a reported $100
million in developing Intacs, there will still widespread doubts
about whether laser surgery would prove workable and a market would
develop for a reversible procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't seen anyone who wants theirs reversed,'' said
Puliafito, who said at his center, 30 laser eye surgeries are
performed a week.
</P>
<P>
   One reason rings may be slow to catch on is that there is no
shortage of medical centers licensed to do the laser work.
Consumers in eastern Massachusetts, for instance, can choose from
among a half-dozen, and the Department of Public Health estimates
another 12 or 13 Bay State hospitals and facilities are licensed to
perform the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Azar, the Eye and Ear Infirmary's associate chief of
ophthalmology and director of several surgery services, is also an
associate professor at the University of Paris medical center. He
has been to Paris to learn how to insert the rings _ European
authorities approved their use in 1996 _ and says he thinks the
results ``are beautiful,'' but comparable to what lasers can do.
</P>
<P>
   But Azar notes that one drawback is that the rings come in three
fixed sizes, while lasers can be minutely modified, like the
difference between wearing a tailored shirt or one that comes only
in small, medium or large.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik began as a procedure used only on severe cases of
nearsightedness, but as surgeons have learned to improve the
technique, it is being used on progressively milder cases as an
alternative to PRK because people heal faster and see better sooner
with Lasik.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Azar said, the only reason for choosing PRK over
Lasik is if you have a tissue condition in the eye that makes
slicing a flap dangerous or if you need less than about 2.5 to 3.5
diopters of vision correction, depending on the threshold a
particular surgeon has set for doing PRK instead of Lasik.
</P>
<P>
   Direct comparisons between diopters and the more commonly
understood 20/20 system of describing poor vision are difficult.
But roughly speaking, someone with 20/40 vision (the minimum to get
a driver's license) needs 0.75 to 1.25 diopters of correction to
get to 20/20, Azar said. Two diopters corresponds to 20/100, and
three diopters 20/400.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Azar said, he performed Lasik only on people
needing more than 6 diopters of correction. Now he routinely does
it on cases of people who need only 2.5 diopters, and it is likely
the ``flap and zap'' procedure will supplant even more use of PRK.
</P>
<P>
   The corneal rings, in contrast, have been approved only for
correcting 1 to 3.5 diopters of vision in myopic people, and not
yet to fix farsightedness or astigmatism.
</P>
<P>
   In the US, the practice of surgically changing the eye to
correct vision dates back to the late 1970s when a pair of American
doctors travelled to the then-Soviet Union to learn about a
procedure called radial keratotomy, in which incisions are made in
radial patterns around the cornea to flatten it.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, RK procedures, counted as one for each
eye, peaked at about 300,000 in 1994 and 1995, but have since
dwindled as lasers have promised more precise, less painful, easier
healing correction, according to Arons, the consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Every year since 1996, the number of laser eye surgeries has
roughly doubled, according to Arons' figures. He projects 850,000
eyes will be operated on this year _ overwhelmingly Lasik, and
overwhelmingly two eyes per person _ and another 1.2 million in
2000. Arons does not see rings taking more than 3 to 5 percent of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Sumers, a private-practice ophthalmologist in Ridgewood,
N.J., who is a spokesperson for the ophthamology academy, said it
is important for people considering any eye surgery to keep in mind
that ``it doesn't make your vision better than what you have with
contacts or glasses. It's basically just a procedure for
convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   One drawback to all surgeries, including rings, is that people
have to choose whether they want to see well near or far.
</P>
<P>
   Because people's ability to change focus with their eyes
declines with age, if you are older than 40 and get laser surgery
to improve your distance vision, you almost certainly will have to
get reading glasses, even if you do not use them now, Sumers said.
Or if you choose the surgery to make it easier to read a book or
work at the computer, you are likely to need glasses for driving or
night vision.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, at about $4,000 out-of-pocket per pair of eyes, the
cost of laser work or rings easily cover decades or a lifetime
worth of contact lenses or eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston area, regular eyeglass lenses run an average $75
plus the cost of frames, which are generally about $100 but can
cost much more. Bifocals lenses are about $110, Azar said.
</P>
<P>
   For two eyes, regular contacts run from about $140 for a
high-quality permanent or six-month pair up to $600 for contacts
you throw out every day, not counting the cost of cleaning
solutions, according to Dr. Sheri Morneault, director of the Eye
and Ear Infirmary's contact lens service.
</P>
<P>
   Another option rolled out this month is a disposable bifocal
contact lens made by Johnson &AMP; Johnson. About 1 percent of the 33
million contacts sold in the last year were bifocals, and no one
with the marketing might of J &AMP; J has entered the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Acuvue lenses have five concentric rings that alternately
correct near or far vision. No one can control where a lens sits on
the eye, but the brain selects the appropriate focus. The contacts
cost about $350 to $500 per year for two eyes.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone with reservations about any of the surgical
approaches, ``The safest choice is still to get a good pair of
glasses,'' Sumers said. One unchallenged upside of glasses and
contact lenses is that they can be readjusted every year, Sumers
said, while repeated surgery on the eye is both costly and
potentially risky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
