r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-HOUSE28-COX     04-27 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-HOUSE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motley cast seeks House seat
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ When for- mer U.S. Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.)
resigned amid scandal the same day President Clinton was impeached,
folks from every walk of life rushed to fill his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nine candidates in the special election to be held
Saturday: A wizard, a virgin, and a Monica.
</P>
<P>
   The wizard is David Duke, a former state representative, a
former presidential candidate, and a former Ku Klux Klan leader.
The virgin is Patrick Landry, a 33-year-old, unmarried electrician
who makes his sex life, or the lack thereof, public to distance
himself from the recent sex scandals in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Monica, but not that Monica. It's Dr. Monica
Monica, an ophthalmalogist, and her name is not a campaign trick to
cash in on the fame of Clinton's former intern paramour, Monica
Lewinsky. Her father, says this Monica, loved her so much, he named
her twice.
</P>
<P>
   Among the seven Republicans and two Democrats running in this
suburban New Orleans district, former governor and U.S. Rep. Dave
Treen is leading in most polls. He is selling himself as the only
candidate who can pick up where Livingston left off. Treen served 7
1/2 years on Capitol Hill in the 1970s, and he says his previous
stint in Washington will prevent him from being a powerless
freshman when he's elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can hit the ground running,'' Treen said. ``I have
relationships with the chairmen of committees that will keep our
programs going.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument is a convincing one for many voters who became used
to having a senior lawmaker working for them. Livingston served for
21 years and was chairman of the Appropriations Committee. He
almost became speaker of the House, but he resigned in December
after Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt said he was about to
publish accounts of Livingston's extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   D. Bruce Smith, who works at the Lockheed Martin technology
center here, a pet project of Livingston's that receives federal
money, said he is leaning toward Treen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost so much, losing Livingston,'' he said. ``Treen is
the closest way to inject immediate experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Another leading candidate, Republican state Rep. David Vitter,
counters that Treen is too old to cultivate a long career like
Livingston's. Treen is 70. Vitter is 37. Moreover, Congress has
changed a lot during Treen's 20-year absence, so he may not know
the ropes as well as he thinks he does, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   Vitter also distinguishes himself from Monica, who he says won't
be able to develop any seniority because she has signed a pledge
limiting her stay in Washington to six years, or three terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to think about electing a new, young person who can
build experience,'' Vitter said. If no one gets more than 50
percent of the votes Saturday, the two top vote-getters will face
off in a runoff May 29. With Treen in first place _ at least for
now _ the race for second place has grown increasingly bitter, said
John Maginnis, publisher of the Louisiana Political Fax Weekly.
Vitter and Monica have run ads attacking each other.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is sure, Maginnis said: This is the Republicans' race
to lose. Only two of the nine candidates are Democrats _ state Rep.
Bill Strain and perennial candidate Darryl Ward. Strain has a small
chance of getting into a runoff with Treen if voters become
disgusted with the Monica-Vitter battle.
</P>
<P>
   But in the unlikely scenario that Duke, whose poll numbers have
been running in the single digits, gets into a runoff with a
Democrat, many Republicans have said they would vote for the
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The other Republicans running are minor-league baseball team
owner Rob Couhig and retired orthopedic surgeon S.J. LoCoco. The
field is wide and confusing for many voters who see a lot of
similarities among the candidates. The district covers the
conservative, mostly white, suburban and rural areas of Orleans,
Jefferson, St. Tammany, Tangipahoa and Washington parishes, as well
as an affluent section of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Dupuy is typical of a lot of voters here: He can't decide.
An attorney from Jefferson Parish, he has a Rob Couhig sign in his
yard because ``he's the kind of guy who does business on a
handshake.'' He thinks Vitter is the brightest of the candidates
but too conservative, and he likes Monica because she is a ``mom
and wife and not a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know who I am not going to vote for _ David Duke,'' Dupuy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the candidate who has gotten the most national
attention is Duke, a self-described ``white civil rights
activist.''Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
