<HEADER>
A4709 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-DUKE28-COX     04-27 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-DUKE28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke sounds familiar themes in Congress run
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMMOND, La. _ The crowd at the Holiday Inn off the interstate
numbered around 100. They were all ages, dressed in blue jeans,
boots and ``gimme'' caps. A few had Confederate flags on lapel pins
or hats.
</P>
<P>
   And every single one clapped and cheered when David Duke entered
the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``People either love me or hate me,'' said Duke, the former Ku
Klux Klansman who is making his sixth run for public office, this
time trying to replace U.S. Rep. Bob Livingston in Louisiana's
First Congressional District. ``It's really nice to be in a room
full of people that love me.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, 48, looks a little older than he did when he made national
headlines running for governor and then president. His hair is
greying, the mustache is gone, but his surgically-altered face is
still camera-ready. And although he keeps saying he regrets being
in the Klan, his rhetoric still rings of racial bias.
</P>
<P>
   At his rally at the Holiday Inn, Duke said, ``It's not evil,
it's not wrong and it's not hateful for people to want to associate
with their own kind.'' His audience applauded and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   At public appearances, he peddles ``My Awakening,'' his 717-page
book that talks of an Aryan revolution. He calls blacks less
intelligent and criminally inclined, and attacks Jews as having
taken over the govern- ment.
</P>
<P>
   Other things have changed, however.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, when Duke ran against former Gov. Edwin Edwards,
Louisianans, especially blacks, stood in lines, sometimes for
hours, to register to vote against Duke, even if that meant voting
for Edwards, whose alleged corruption was legendary. A favorite
bumper sticker from the race was ``Vote for the crook. It's
important.'' Duke lost the race, but he won 55 percent of the white
vote.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Duke's poll numbers have been in the single digits,
and there are many strong Republicans running against him in the
nine-candidate race. Residents and politicians who don't like Duke
are angry with the national media for paying attention to a minor
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little angry with NBC-TV for giving him publicity,''
said Tony Currera, a Republican from Duke's district, speaking of
Duke's appearance on ``Meet the Press.'' ``The national news is
giving him a forum for his hatred, as if this is what the people of
Louisiana are like. And he's not even a contender.''
</P>
<P>
   But Duke is confident he will at least make it into a runoff
with one of his Republican opponents, noting that in past races,
more people voted for him than the polls predicted. And his
supporters remain passionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like everything he says,'' said Brian Kelly, a 45-year-old
electrician. ``I've been denied three jobs that went to black
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks Duke is a racist, Kelly said, ``Absolutely
not. That's a misconception.'' Duke contends that his ideas are not
on the fringe, but very mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the first major candidate to talk about getting rid of
affirmative action, about workfare instead of welfare, about a flat
tax,'' he said. ``Those are all Republican ideas now.''Anne Rochell
Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
