<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4710 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-SHELTER28-COX     04-27 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SHELTER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battered women's shelter soon will lose anonymity
 &HT;    By Margo Rutledge Kissell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENE CO., Ohio _ For 20 years, the Greene County Domestic
Violence Project has closely guarded the secret location of its
shelter for battered women. The safe haven has been kept so
confidential that even victims who call for help are not given the
address until after they are directed to the police.
</P>
<P>
   But the nonprofit agency plans to take a bold step out from the
shadows next spring when it breaks ground for a new shelter whose
location will be publicized deliberately to the community.
</P>
<P>
   The new secure facility in Xenia will have a sign out front and
its address listed in the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, locations of shelters have traditionally
been kept confidential and the vast majority still are, mainly to
keep shelter victims safe from batterers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have depended on that anonymity for security,'' said
Cindy Minton, executive director of the Greene County Domestic
Violence Project. ``But there is a beginning of a movement across
the country to kind of take the step to say, `No, it's time that
this problem be recognized by the community and the community take
ownership of the problem.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the Domestic Violence Project started the public phase
of a capital campaign to raise $1.5 million for the new two-story
shelter that will accommodate 20 women and children, but have the
ability to expand to 25 with bunk beds.
</P>
<P>
   Minton said the agency has received more than $771,000 in
pledges _ more than half of its goal _ from corporate and
charitable foundations and others during a ``quiet phase'' of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.7-acre property was purchased by the Community Improvement
Corp. for $275,000 in February and last month turned over to the
agency at no cost. It is currently the site of Xenia Grace Chapel.
The agency plans to renovate the chapel for administrative offices,
educational and counseling areas. An existing annex will become a
police substation and the new shelter will be built behind the
chapel.
</P>
<P>
   By disclosing the new location, agency workers hope to reach
more victims, increase public awareness about domestic violence and
raise more money for their programs, Minton said.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Smith, executive director of Denver-based National
Coalition Against Domestic Violence, said advocates for years have
been asking themselves: Are we assisting battered women by hiding
them? Can we provide safety if we're not confidential?
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually believe local communities need to make that
decision. The local community and service provider have a better
idea of whether they have police support, community support and
safety mechanisms in case something happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they are the best judges of whether it is a good
idea to move to a non-confidential location or not. The bottom line
is, if a batterer is obsessed enough and he wants to find that
location, he'll find it whether it's confidential or not,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Janine Poppa, director of shelter services for the YWCA of
Dayton, which operates a domestic violence shelter in a
confidential location in Montgomery County, said she believes
revealing a shelter location puts victims and shelter workers at
too much risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the advantage of disclosing the location is.
I can tell you a million disadvantages,'' said Poppa, whose shelter
housed 278 women and 314 children last year. It is not uncommon for
the YWCA and Artemis Center for Alternatives to Domestic Violence
to receive threats from batterers in jail, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Minton said the new facility will be built with safety in mind.
``When we move into a public site, we plan to build the site with
security so it will be open so a victim can drive up to the front
door, but will also be secured so that particularly at night, it
almost shuts down to a little kind of fort,'' she said. National
and state domestic violence officials believe a proposed police
substation at the site may be the first of its kind and could serve
as a model for others.
</P>
<P>
   Xenia police Chief Eric Prindle said a police sergeant whose job
focuses on domestic violence complaints will work out of the
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sends the message we are supporting domestic violence
efforts and also are there to protect them . . .,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minton said the agency began studying the issue two years ago
because the existing shelter inside a 100-year-old home was being
outgrown. They visited a couple of other disclosed sites in Ohio
and Kentucky before reaching the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The new shelter, scheduled to open in late 2000 or early 2001,
will have five bedrooms, an apartment accessible to someone with
disabilities, a kitchen, dining room, lounge area, children's play
area, counseling offices and an area for those operating the
24-hour crisis hotline.
</P>
<P>
   The existing shelter, which serves 150-200 people a year, can
house 17 women and children and is often at capacity. It is not
handicap-accessible and its kitchen and bathroom facilities are
inadequate for that number of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're just busting at the seams,'' Minton said,
adding that renovations and additions are not options in the
historic home.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Carlson-Riehm, executive director for Columbus-based
Action Ohio Coalition for Battered Women, said she is aware of two
other disclosed locations in the state: in Newark, where the
shelter is across from the busy post office, and in Fostoria, where
a sign is posted outside the First Step Family Violence
Intervention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cheatham, licensed social worker and residential program
manager at the 10-year-old Fostoria facility, said: ``We find a lot
of security in community awareness. The police are very aware of
our location, the townspeople are very aware. We have never had a
major incident on these premises. We tried something different and
it worked well.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheatham, whose clients' information is kept confidential, said
the shelter still exercises ``utmost security,'' but ``abusers are
very wary to come near here because of the public awareness of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue that if victims are aware of and see the
facility, they may be more inclined to seek help. Opponents argue
that if a shelter is made public, victims will be less likely to go
there out of fear of being located.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a worker leaving her shift at a disclosed Crown Point,
Ind., women's shelter was raped outside by the husband of a woman
who was taking refuge in the shelter with her children .
</P>
<P>
   Four million women are victims of domestic violence in the
United States each year and 1,500-2,000 women die in such incidents
every year, Smith said. In Greene County, Minton said, four people
died as a result of domestic violence last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go into a public site we have to be prepared for the
worst-case scenario,'' she said, ``but from a day-to-day
standpoint, the majority of domestic violence is not killing.''
</P>
<P>
   Margo Rutledge Kissell writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
