r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLAN-COLUMN28-COX     04-27 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLAN-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You can tell a lot about a person from the way he drives
 &HT;    By Leigh Allan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ I came, I saw, I figured it out. Feel free to
thank me later.
</P>
<P>
   Before moving here, I'd read the paper for several months,
including an editorial page column on bad local driving and the
dozens of reader responses to it, most of the verbal road rage
type. Scary stuff.
</P>
<P>
   My experience is that wherever you are at the moment has the
worst drivers in the world. Except for you, of course. Whenever you
move, the new place is worse. Except for you.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I've had trouble spotting the definitive Dayton
driving dumb-dumb, perhaps because I got my first license in Ohio
and the driving oddities you grew up with are the ones you're
comfortable with through life, like it works with music. I haven't
had that problem elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, where I lived the past 18 years, turn signals are
surgically removed at the border. You could drive weeks in Kentucky
without seeing a blinking light that's not promoting a Bingo game.
</P>
<P>
   When I read remarks suggesting drivers around here are bad on
turn signal use, I scoff. The smart money says 90 percent of the
offenders are ex-Kentuckians who still shout ``How 'bout dem
Cats!'' at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, I lived in Indiana, home of the Indiana Turn, aka the
Hoosier Head-on. That's a left where the driver cuts into the
oncoming lane first, then jags to the right.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell an experienced Hoosier driver because he not only
suddenly appears headed right at you, but also glares you down,
obviously enraged that you have the audacity to be where you're
supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers in a lot of Southern states will tell you the dominant
Ohio trait is meandering in the left lane of multi-lane highways,
even when the right is empty, an offense deemed dire by a West
Virginia legislator this month. This observation is probably
skewed, though, because of the preponderance of Florida-bound
Ohioans who can refer to John Glenn as ``that young
whippersnapper.''
</P>
<P>
   So I checked with the experts. Montgomery County (Ohio) Sheriff
Gary Haines said he gets the most complaints about drivers who are
not only using cell phones, but munching or glugging something from
their other hand.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Highway Patrol Sgt. Mike Marchek instantly said the biggest
problem on local interstates is tailgating. Marchek said on other
roads the fault of choice is running red lights, there being an
apparent local belief the first 10 seconds of red don't count.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with new knowledge, I engaged in in-depth study from both
roadways and sidelines. I noted all the mentioned misdemeanors,
plus a whole slew of ``right on red after roll'' adherents, but no
single sin stood out.
</P>
<P>
   Thus I was in despair while awaiting a bus in Centerville one
morning last week, but I was rescued. Along came a line of 15
tailgating vehicles in the left lane, with nothing to their right,
with two-thirds of the drivers eating breakfast and three of them
on the phone, the last seven or eight zipping through a bright red
light.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's something to be proud of. Other states may dominate
on any single offense, but, by golly, we're the ones who have put
it all together.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make a man quietly proud to be a Buckeye again.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Allan writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
