r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN28-COX     04-27 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents need to know when to stop pretending
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Parents should quit pretending all's
well.
</P>
<P>
   It is the witching moment at our house, the homework hour, and I
am watching my 8-year-old. He is using both head and hands to blast
through the intimidating columns of double-digit numbers. And while
his arithmetic is correct _ we are blessed with a math-happy child
_ some of the details are all wrong. His writing is sloppy. His
name's not on his paper. All his threes are backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' I say in my best I'm-your-mother tone. ``Pay attention
to the little stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to the details.
</P>
<P>
   I know how he feels, though. The details in life can be so
unpleasant. Overdue bills, a marriage that's turned distant,
problems at work. It's so much easier, isn't it, to glaze over all
that bad stuff and move right on to the fun.
</P>
<P>
   It's so much easier to pretend.
</P>
<P>
   Around our house, we call this The Macaroni Syndrome, a wistful
look back to the fabled days of Leave it to Beaver and Father Knows
Best. Those families never had big problems. Good golly, no! And if
they did, maybe something awful like the Beav didn't take out the
trash, then the TV mom would just put on her apron with the
bright-red bing cherries printed all over it and she'd make a big
casserole of macaroni. Macaroni is swell, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Why, just this week I macaronied my way through my day after a
certain math-crazy second-grader sat at the breakfast table looking
all forlorn. ``What's wrong?'' I asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go to school today,'' he said. ``I feel lonely
there.''
</P>
<P>
   And while my heart dropped and my mind whirled, while I went to
work and sat there and worried my head off, he went to school that
day without my having gotten to the bottom of things. I still don't
know why he said that. He's fine, I've told myself all week.
Macaroni!
</P>
<P>
   But at some point we do have to face things. That's why we're
the grownups and they're the kids. At some point we do have to
balance the checkbook and attend to the marriage and console the
confused child.
</P>
<P>
   And while it's hard to pay attention with so much tugging at us
_ at least that's our excuse, right? _ it's our job to stand vigil
over our family's lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's our job to know when to quit pretending.
</P>
<P>
   The pretending's all over out there in Littleton, Colo. Those
parents, the two mothers, the two fathers, are locked away with
their grief, reliving every little warning. Reliving every little
detail of the two lives that are now gone.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us, our problems won't lead to the kind of carnage
we saw at Columbine High School last week. For most of us, our
lives can be understood once we slow down _ stop even _ to focus on
all the little warnings.
</P>
<P>
   And as I sit here and stare and think about the unattended
details of my life _ the warnings, if you will _ my mind can't help
but wander to theirs. To the two young men who dressed in black and
saluted Hitler. Two young men with so much hate, so much confusion,
so much in need of help, they bombarded the people around them with
the bizarre details of their disjointed lives. Day after day after
day. Still, no one listened. They were too busy putting on their
aprons to make the macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
