<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN28-CO     04-27 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Build a core of investments ...
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Younger readers frequently ask whether they ought to fiddle with
their investments, now that the stock market is so high and so
wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   Sell stocks? Stop putting new money into the market? Buy only
the most conservative stocks?
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no simple, concrete and achievable answer
for everybody. But there is a general concept that will lead a lot
of neophyte investors to their own answers: core investments.
</P>
<P>
   These are the inexpensive, more or less predictable selections
you are prepared to buy today and to leave alone for many, many
tomorrows. You buy them to achieve a specific goal and refuse to
touch them for any other reason.
</P>
<P>
   Think about core investments as your anchor. Once you have
dropped that anchor, you can quit worrying about it, no matter
where the stock market goes today or might go tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people get wrapped up in very short-term things,
like which stocks are hot and whether the market is overvalued,''
observed Mark W. Riepe, the chief of Schwab's Center for Investment
Research. ``By building a core of investments that are consistent
with your long-term objectives, you make sure these short-term,
opportunistic distractions don't make you swerve too much from your
long-term path.''
</P>
<P>
   Developing a core can be relatively simple. If you are doing it
yourself, it's a process of analyzing your goals and what they will
cost, the amount of time you have to save and invest, and how much
risk you're willing to take to get to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The first two steps are pencil-and-paper exercises. Assessing
your tolerance for risk is a spongier process. If you have years or
decades to save, you will get better returns with stocks or stock
mutual funds. But if the volatility of the market makes you
anxious, you probably need to search out alternatives or
compromises.
</P>
<P>
   You can get some help figuring out your needs- vs.-nerve
quotient from some of the commercial financial planning software
packages. You can get a rough idea by filling out worksheets on the
Internet. Fidelity Investments has a good one at
www.401k.com/cgi-bin
</P>
<P>
   /invprof.exe. You can get similar programs, either electronic or
in booklet form, from other brokerages and mutual fund families.
</P>
<P>
   The other alternative is to hire a professional, such as a
certified financial planner, to help you get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe an adviser is the best place to start,'' said Jan
Holman, a vice president of American Express Financial Advisors in
Minneapolis. ``That doesn't necessarily mean you will use an
adviser throughout your whole investing life. But as a place to
begin and to get some one-on-one training, you're paying a pretty
low price when you use an adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   An adviser _ assuming he or she acts as a coach rather than a
salesperson _ can be particularly helpful with the problem at hand:
avoiding panicky decisions if the market gets too high _ or too low
_ for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you'll need to pick the individual investments that
will become your core. You will need to diversify your portfolio,
which suggests mutual funds for many investors.
</P>
<P>
   Within the mutual fund world, it's a good idea to minimize both
upfront sales fees and annual operating expenses. That suggests
index funds, which usually have very low costs.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of index funds: You can be sure they won't
switch around, chasing hot stocks or market trends.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off, of course, is that an index fund will go down
just like the index it tracks. You are assuming that over a period
of years, stocks will continue to appreciate faster than other
investments, just as they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't find a 20-year period when stocks have lost money,''
said Riepe. ``There are some 20-year periods when they haven't been
all that great, but they are at least positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
