<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COLU     04-27 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN28-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A world of dreams lives alongside one filled with death's
finality
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Off on yet another dawn patrol, the intrepid
World War 1 flying ace is alone, high above the fields of France.
The strap of a worn flying helmet flaps jauntily under his ear as a
long white scarf trails in the prop wash. Man and machine throb as
one.
</P>
<P>
   Resolutely, the intrepid aviator's flinty eye scans the sinister
skies, straining for a glimpse of a gaudily painted Albatros, the
flying machine that strikes terror into the hearts of valiant young
men. He spots it. His gut churns. Just above him at 11 o'clock, the
dreaded Red Baron is on the prowl.
</P>
<P>
   Snoopy, Charlie Brown's delusional dog, is deep in yet another
food-induced reverie where single-handed he patrols the skies of
France in his never-ending quest to out-shoot and out-fly the
legendary German ace, Manfred Von Richtofen. Invariably, his fancy
flying work and daring agility pay off. Snoopy saves the day. The
free world can sleep securely for another night.
</P>
<P>
   World War 2 was in full swing during my fantasy years. I was
weaned on John Wayne movies where for a couple of hours each week,
good and evil were clearly defined for me by Hollywood. The enemy
was evil. In the Pacific he wore an inscrutable sneer as he shot
down our family loving, clean-cut American boys. Over Europe, the
enemy was taller, and though he died just as often, he did it with
a minimum of fuss. And there wasn't much blood.
</P>
<P>
   Dying was tidy in the days of black and white movies and I, like
millions of other kids, bought into the notion that death was a
temporary transition. A hit, a spin, a gasp, and the pilot was
history. Of course, a couple of months later in a different movie,
the same actor would be digging a trench on Corregidor or paving a
runway on Saipan. My young, homegrown version of mortality was a
whole lot skewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're off again!'' my geography teacher, Miss Fecser would
bellow when she'd catch me focused out the window and on the little
airport a couple of blocks away from our fifth-grade classroom. I
meant to pay attention, but I really didn't give a fat rat's
backside about Iowa's average annual rainfall. The only thing that
interested me was airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   More than penny candy or Lana Turner coloring books, I wanted to
fly. Every one of my youthful fantasies centered around me in a
cockpit. I flew bombers, fighters, anything with wings. In fact,
that's the way most of my childish daydreams began.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, everybody's up today,'' my commanding officer (who most
often bore a striking resemblance to Alan Ladd and was invariably
madly in love with me) would order as he came through the door of
the pilots' ready room. ``We need every man, and Elizabeth, for
this mission. The enemy will soon be arriving over the playground
of Memphis Elementary and it's up to you to save the kids.'' We'd
all salute.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ladd never kissed me goodbye or anything, because then I
wouldn't have been just another one of the boys. But he did look
worried as I adjusted my parachute and headed for the ramp to kick
some tires and crank up my Mustang. Sometimes I flew a P-38, but
the twin boom kind of wrecked the silhouette for me.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely did I survive a mission, but I would be profoundly
mourned by Alan Ladd, my fellow pilots, and all of the kids at
Memphis Elementary. My youthful naivete assured immortality. I knew
I'd be back to fly another day.
</P>
<P>
   Snoopy's just a beagle and I was just a kid. Lucky for a lot of
folks that we had no access to airplanes _ in my case at least
until I was old enough to know that dying is forever and once my 15
minutes is up, I'm gone. For good.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad guns aren't as tough to come by as airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431; e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
