<HEADER>
A4718 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUSSYBABIES-WEB28-COX     04-27 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUSSYBABIES-WEB28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calming fussy baby may be a mouseclick away
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ As a new father, Mike Lampkin searched for
something that would calm his fussy daughter, especially during a
changing when it is not possible to hold her.
</P>
<P>
   So with the help of a friend and a little research, Lampkin
found what he calls a ``simple but effective solution'' in The
Lampkin Fussy Baby Help Page Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a freebie site I keep up to help other parents
out,'' said Lampkin, of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin, a graphics designer, developed a poster and a slide
show with `` . . . a series of pictures and patterns which are more
attractive to babies from the age of newborn and up.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the poster and the slide show feature simple shapes in
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read that the part of the brain that develops first is the
part that recognizes shapes,'' Lampkin said. ``So I made it very
basic and very easy to see. The circles, squares, triangles, stars
and even the happy faces can be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin said he hung the poster next to his daughter's changing
table and she was easily distracted by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works best on babies that are grumpy or tired,'' Lampkin
said.
</P>
<P>
   For extreme emergencies, Lampkin offers a ``panic button'' on
the Web site. When pushed, the slide show starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just hold the baby up next to the computer and (the images)
will distract them; they become mesmerized,'' Lampkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin said he also has found it helpful to keep a copy of the
poster in the car and the diaper bag for those inconsolable moments
away from home.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site (www.lampkindesign.com/fussybaby/) was created in
1996, and so far Lampkin said he has received many affirmative
comments from parents who have tried it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just put it on the Web for fun and got a huge response,''
Lampkin said. ``The site gets several thousand hits a day, and I
get e-mail and letters from people telling me how they've used it.
I recently got an e-mail from a nurse in New York who wanted
permission to hang the posters up in the nursery she works in.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin admits that he's not sure exactly why the images from
the poster and the slide slow work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's like giving a little kid a toy _ it keeps them
occupied,'' Lampkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pat Lambden, clinical nurse specialist in pediatric
education at Scott &AMP; White Children's Health Center, said she can
see how Lampkin's poster could work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes at 3 to 4 months, babies tend to get bored and need
extra stimulation,'' Lambden said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lambden was quick to add that when a baby is fussy, parents
should rule out hunger, a wet diaper, gas, sickness or pain before
chalking it up to ``crying for no apparent reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Crying is a baby's way of communicating, Lambden said.
``Sometimes it depends on their temperament. Sometimes they're
bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Motion is one of the best things to calm a fussy baby, Lambden
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking them for a car ride or putting them in a swing can be
very soothing,'' Lambden said. ``Also, just picking them up,
holding them upright and walking around from room to room with them
can help calm them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Lambden found stroller rides to be helpful with her
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the parents and the child have `cabin-fever,' so
just getting them outside in the stroller can calm them and the
parents down,'' Lambden said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Lambden's suggestions for calming a fussy infant are
tried-and-true methods that have been passed on for as long as
women have been having babies. But with today's technology, parents
have even more choices when it comes to dealing with a fussy baby.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Polster, Toys ``R'' Us store manager, said the
best-selling baby calming devices produce noises or light. There's
the Mommybear, a plush toy that makes a heartbeat sound; the new
``Bear and Bunny'' device that makes nature sounds; and Lullaby
Globes, which produce light images on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually sell out of the Mommybear,'' Polster said. ``Some
people say it works hands-down, and some people say it doesn't work
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambden said finding the right thing to soothe a baby is not
always easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of trial and error,'' Lambden said. ``Some
things don't work on some babies _ you have to find what works for
your baby.''
</P>
<P>
   And when all else fails and the baby still won't quiet down,
Lambden suggests calling in members of your support staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they just won't calm down, and at that point it is
good to have someone else to hand them off to,'' Lambden said.
``This can be helpful by allowing you time to regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambden also said parents should consult a physician if the
baby's crying is constant and lasts for more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Kincheloe writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
