<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4720 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRONIC-TOYS28-COX     04-27 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-TOYS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electronic gadgets prove it's a new (kids) world
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Forget the Barbies, Beanie Babies and action
figures. If it doesn't talk, beep, ding or dong, it may get left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   An onslaught of electronic toys and gadgets seem to be taking
over the toys of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interactive toys are probably more important to kids than
something else,'' said Barbara Rystrom of McGregor, as she and her
daughter, Stephanie, 9, shopped for electronic toys recently at
Toys 'R' Us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids today are used to using mechanical, hand-held-type
things, and they don't play as much imaginarily like with a doll.
They always have to have something that does something in order to
entertain. A doll just sort of sits there.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic gadgets attracting the attention of girls include the
electronic diary, talking watches and pens, toy beepers that send
messages to nearby friends and voice-activated bedroom door passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Friend.link (beepers) and the talking watches,''
Stephanie Rystrom said of the gadgets that have LCD screens and
virtual characters that say all sorts of things. ``I came in to
look at the watch, but now I also like the password journal and the
door pass, which you have to say the password before it lets you in
your room.''
</P>
<P>
   Nina Parton's day just wouldn't be the same without her
electronic diary.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year-old keeps track of her schedule and homework, reads
her daily horoscope, gets advice from an internal match-making
device and takes care of an internal giga-pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write in it a whole lot about guys I like and personal phone
numbers and the things I've done that I don't want other people to
know about,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She likes her electronic diary much better than its predecessor
_ pencil and paper diaries she used to write in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost everyone of them before I got this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the big plus _ it's private. Only she has the code
that allows her to fire up the diary, which means her sisters can't
get into it.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly one of the biggest electronic phenomenons to hit lately
is drawing the attention of millions of young boys throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Move over yo-yos. Pokemon passion is taking over.
</P>
<P>
   The Nintendo Gameboy game, pronounced po-kee-mahn, is
essentially a derivation of the ancient low-tech game of rock,
paper, scissors. Inside the game, 11-year-old Ash Ketchum captures
and trains 151 Pokemon, or pocket monsters, each of whom has a
special ability.
</P>
<P>
   Since last fall, Nintendo has sold more than 1.5 million of the
game cartridges, and young viewers are tuning into a daily TV
cartoon and searching for Pokemon memorabilia, such as trading
cards.
</P>
<P>
   If your children sound like they are speaking in code, they've
probably been bit by the bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this, we're probably going to trade a Flareon, which is
an evolution of the Eevee if you give it a fire stone,''
12-year-old Jorge Colmenares said. ``I don't know what I'm going to
trade for the Flareon, yet, though.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two versions of Pokemon _ a red and a blue version _
and in order to capture all 151 Pokemon, kids link red and blue
Pokemon games together with a cable to trade Pokemon and battle
other players.
</P>
<P>
   What's refreshing for many parents is that the game isn't
violent like many of its counterparts. Even though there are
battles, Pokemon don't throw punches, shoot each other, bleed or
die.
</P>
<P>
   Once captured, they just faint or teleport away. The rotund
little creatures _ including the popular Pikachu, a bright yellow,
rodent-like creature with ``shocking'' powers _ are actually kind
of cute, especially before they evolve into larger creatures and
become more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect that appeals to parents is the fact that this
game may help sharpen memorization. Each Pokemon evolves twice and
changes names and attains various capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Colmenares, who has captured 147 Pokemon, says he remembers
who's who by memorizing each Pokemon's physical appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you play for a while, you remember the names,'' added
Rocky Shen, 13, who captured all 151 Pokemon in less than two
months before starting the game over. He now has another 118 under
his belt.
</P>
<P>
   The Pokedex also helps players keep track of the game. ``Every
Pokemon you get, it shows you in your Pokedex,'' said Max Silver,
12, who recently started playing the game. ``If you trade somebody,
it will show you on the Pokedex that you own it but you really
don't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game also enforces sharing and working together since the
only way a player can get all 151 Pokemon is by hooking up to a
friend's Gameboy.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of advice: when you ask a Pokemon player why it's a great
game, get ready for an earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun trying to catch all of them, and there's different
cities and you can fly different places, and you can trade with
your friends if you don't have something, and sometimes there's two
Pokemon you have to catch at one time and if you don't catch them,
you have to trade with a friend because there's two different kinds
of games, a blue version and a red version, and there's Pokemon you
can't get in the red version so you have to trade for the blue
version,'' Silver blurted out in one long, breathless sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Silver plays seven or eight hours a week, after his homework, of
course, and endless hours on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I forget to read, and Mom has to stop me from
playing and make me read,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest torture of all is when he gets grounded and
there's no more Pokemon for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is torture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Colmenares guesses he plays about five hours a day and admitted
he once snuck the game to bed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the sound down,'' he said. ``I've only done it once and
never been caught.''
</P>
<P>
   With a chuckle, he says he thinks he's addicted to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I've got a Pokemon battle now,'' he says turning his
attention to his Game Boy, his face growing serious.
</P>
<P>
   Shen says he's not ``addicted to the game'' but admits he'll
play from the time he gets home from school until bedtime if he
doesn't have any homework.
</P>
<P>
   He said his parents think he plays too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always sitting there playing, and they tell me to read a
book or something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shen said the appeal to Pokemon is that the game lasts longer
than others he's played and is more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more exciting and has much more than just men
(fighting),'' Colmenares said. ``And the time just goes by fast
because you're so hooked on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver agrees, adding that he likes the fact that after he
captures all 151 Pokemon, he can start over and the game will be
completely different.
</P>
<P>
   Experts expect Pokemon to be as popular or even more so than
games like Super Mario Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   But even with all the hype of new games like Pokemon, there are
still some traditionalists hooked on good-ol' standbys. Devon Hunt,
13, has been hooked on Donkey Kong for years and plays about three
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something to do and fun way to waste time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for what's next in the world of electronic toys, employees of
Toys 'R' Us said ``it's anybody's guess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only imagine,'' said Scott Cressman, store director.
``They'll keep updating graphics and certainly color on these
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Meador, sales manager, said many of these new interactive
toys evolved from the virtual pet toys that were huge several years
ago, including Tamagotchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets a little different every year,'' he said. ``We never
know what to expect or what's on a company's drawing board.''
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
