<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4724 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASK-THE-DIETITIAN28-C     04-27 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASK-THE-DIETITIAN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ask the dietitian column
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is gout related to diet?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gout is a disease in which the body either produces too much
of a substance called uric acid, or excretes too little, causing
blood levels to rise. Uric acid can then be deposited within joints
and tissues, causing severe pain.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, doctors recommended that those with gout avoid foods
high in purines (organ meats and a few other foods) because purines
are broken down into uric acid. But further research has shown that
uric acid is formed from a variety of substances and for most
people does not seem much affected by these diets.
</P>
<P>
   Medications are the main treatment for gout today. Avoid (or at
least limit) alcohol, since it increases production and decreases
excretion of uric acid. Eat regularly and drink plenty of fluids.
Weight loss usually helps those who are overweight, but should be
accomplished with healthfully balanced meals, since high-protein
fad diets can raise uric acid levels.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can someone know if they are getting enough fiber?
</P>
<P>
   A: Current recommendations call for 20 to 35 grams of dietary
fiber each day to help lower risk of cancer, prevent heart disease
and promote overall health. One way to make sure you're getting
enough is to check nutrition labels on all packages of grain
products (including cereals, bread, crackers, and pasta), fruits,
vegetables, beans, and mixed dishes. Be sure to adjust the fiber
content listed for how your portion compares to the one listed.
</P>
<P>
   Since fresh produce is not labeled, approximate its fiber by
counting two or three grams for each half-cup serving; lettuce and
juice should not be counted as supplying any fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to check the fiber in your diet is to simply make
sure you eat at least the minimum recommendations for a mostly
plant-based diet: five standard-size servings of fruits and
vegetables, and six servings of grain products, of which three or
more should be whole grains.
</P>
<P>
   If you reach this basic nutrition goal, you'll average 21 grams
of fiber or more, which meets recommended goals. By eating more of
these healthy foods, or including beans or a high-fiber cereal,
it's easy to get to 30 or 35 grams of fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Questions answered by Karen Collins, M.S., R.D. of the American
Institute for Cancer Research.
</P>
<P>
   Story filed by The Austin American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
