<P>
   ALLAN-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Before moving here, I'd read the
paper for several months, including an editorial page column on bad
local driving and the dozens of reader responses to it, most of the
verbal road rage type. Scary stuff. My experience is that wherever
you are at the moment has the worst drivers in the world. Except
for you, of course. Whenever you move, the new place is worse.
Except for you. (Allan, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ Parents should quit pretending all's well. The
pretending's all over out there in Littleton, Colo. Those parents,
the two mothers, the two fathers, are locked away with their grief,
reliving every little warning. Reliving every little detail of the
two lives that are now gone. For most of us, our problems won't
lead to the kind of carnage we saw at Columbine High School last
week. For most of us, our lives can be understood once we slow down
_ stop even _ to focus on all the little warnings. (Minor, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Inasmuch as the NRA has always insisted guns
have nothing to do with gun crime _ indeed, has argued the more
guns the better _ wouldn't greater respect be paid to the citizens
of Denver by going on with its convention as planned _ firearms
exhibits, rousing pro-gun speeches and all? The whole shootin'
match, as it were. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ It's been a while since I vowed that I was
not going to be early all the time. Everyone else seemingly is late
but I have this awful affliction that causes me to arrive early. I
wanted to be just on time or a few minutes late to weddings, bar
mitzvahs and funerals, instead of arriving preceding the honorees _
present and passed. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News
Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ When Joe Bob Crowley was given the
American Legion Award, the highest to a student, I cheered.
Cheering for someone felt good. Thanks, Joe Bob Crowley.
(Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ I used to dream of becoming a pilot, just like
Snoopy used to. But Snoopy's just a beagle and I was just a kid.
Lucky for a lot of folks that we had no access to airplanes _ in my
case at least until I was old enough to know that dying is forever
and once my 15 minutes is up, I'm gone. For good. Too bad guns
aren't as tough to come by as airplanes. (Schuett, Cox News
Service) MOVED.
</P>
