<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4730 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-KIDS28-COX     04-27 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-KIDS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fashions get brighter for the younger crowd
 &HT;    (Eds: Story has accompanying art _ Call CoxNet at 404-526-5456.)
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It's hard to miss the eye-stopping colors and
styles of kids' clothes for spring.
</P>
<P>
   Young girls' clothing aisles are spattered with the pinkest of
pinks, opulent oranges, vibrant violets and brilliant blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely wanting brights,'' said Jan Koskela, who
works at Kid's Korner clothing store at Doc and Laddy's.
</P>
<P>
   Lime green is currently the No. 1 color choice, store owners
report. Paired with lemony yellows, the vibrant colors brighten up
even the dreariest day.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get a little tired of the pastels,'' said Jackie Howk,
store team leader for Gymboree at Richland Mall. ``People kind of
go with pastels in February, March and April. Then parents get real
tired of seeing that after Easter. I have some customers who won't
buy anything but a primary color.''
</P>
<P>
   But just because the colors are bold and bright doesn't detract
from the cute and playful looks many parents still want in young
girls' clothing. Frilly lace, floral prints, fashionable
embroideries and even bloomers dress up fashions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want their 5-year-old in things that 18-year-olds
are wearing,'' Howk said. ``Most people, I think, want
age-appropriate clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   For active girls, look for dresses with matching bike shorts or
leggings. One-piece jumpers made from lightweight material, such as
cotton seersucker, are a popular standby with children and mothers
alike. For a more dressy look, A-line cotton-knit or sheer dresses
are items to look for this spring.
</P>
<P>
   For two different looks, Gymboree has a new reversible dress in
several colors _ one side features a solid-colored dress while the
other has a floral pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get dirty or just feel like having fun, they can turn
it over,'' Howk said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides flower and butterfly patterns, which are perennial
favorites, look for prints with chickens, lollipops and even
angels, said Sheila Saucedo, co-owner of Kid's Korner with Donna
Dowell.
</P>
<P>
   She reports that her customers are always scoping out clothes
that are ``unique and different,'' including an exclusive line of
hand-painted girls' clothing she carries called Balu Essentials
from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Boys are fit to be tied this spring in cargo pants and shorts in
khaki and other trendy colors, Howk reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even starting with the little-bitty boys, mothers want to buy
cargo shorts for their newborns,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The older boys get, the more their clothing begins to resemble
daddy's ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to make it more like what daddy wears or
something they're seeing their football and baseball heros in,''
Howk said. ``They used to make (boys) clothes kind of cutsie. I
don't think (cute) goes over as well as with girls clothes.
(Parents) don't want cute once their sons reach 3 or 4 years of
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for shirts with stripes or golf motifs for little boys this
spring, as well as overall shorts and pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can wear overalls with something under it or if it's
really hot, they can wear it by itself,'' Howk said.
</P>
<P>
   Mix-and-match pieces work well for young boys, who often need
different sizes for tops and bottoms, said Sherena Barrett, owner
of Jelly Beans children's clothing store on Lake Air Drive. Olive
drab, khaki and navy are top colors for boys and anything with
safari, tropical or bug prints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big, popular thing to do right now is accessorize,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many young boys' clothing manufacturers are attaching fun
toy-like accessories to some boy's clothing, like a pair of
binoculars attached to a safari shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the clothes more appealing since little boys don't
get as excited about clothes as little girls,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
