A4731 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-SOUND28-COX     04-27 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-SOUND28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A bigger sound for `Star Wars'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When George Lucas' fourth ``Star Wars'' film debuts
May 19, it won't sound at some theaters like any movie you've ever
seen and heard before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' has been recorded in Dolby
Digital Surround EX, the latest in movie sound systems. And at
least one theater chain is installing the system at its newest
metro Atlanta megaplex.
</P>
<P>
   Regal Cinemas is working extra hours to complete its new
Hollywood 24 theater by mid-May, before ``Phantom Menace'' opens.
The megaplex had been set to open in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   At Hollywood 24, the two largest screening rooms, each seating
about 500 patrons, will be equipped with Surround EX. And another
chain _ United Artists _ is considering the technology for some of
its screens.
</P>
<P>
   Dolby Digital Surround EX, developed by Lucasfilm's THX division
and Dolby Laboratories, involves installing four speakers on the
back walls of a screening room at a cost of between $2,000 and
$4,000. Moviegoers already are used to sound emanating from
speakers at the right and left  theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds another level of surround sound,'' says Phil
Zackaretti, senior vice president of marketing and advertising for
Regal. ``Instead of left and right, you have left, right and
rear.''
</P>
<P>
   The intent is to envelop audiences in sound. They could, for
example, hear a spaceship come in from behind them, pass overhead,
then head into the distance in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   The system will ``open up new possibilities and place sounds
exactly where you would hear them in the real world,'' says Gary
Rydstrom, the Oscar-winning sound designer who devised the new
format.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Phantom Menace,'' the next film set to be recorded in
Surround EX is Dreamworks' ``The Haunting,'' directed by Jan De
Bont (``Speed'') and due out July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
