Supercab.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ It has rubber floor mats, no air bags, no 5-mph
bumpers and a sticker price of $97,100. I've never felt safer in
any vehicle in my life. What is it? It's a Hummer, of course. When
offered the opportunity to test drive the Hummer, I halfheartedly
accepted. But after a week with my competition yellow civilian
version of the same vehicle that our troops are using around the
world, I came away a fan. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
Includes 1-column color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ Making cars childproof _ especially the trunk _
can be a difficult job. The best bet is for parents to make sure
children don't play in or around cars. MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ Getting your car's air-conditioning system
serviced has become more complicated and expensive in the past few
years for a number of reasons. Primarily, the transition from
environmentally unfriendly R-12 to an ozone-safe refrigerant opened
a Pandora's box. MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FACELIFT _ Last year, 61,692 people across the country decided
to fight sagging chin lines and pooching jowls by going under the
surgeon's knife for a facelift. In the last decade, doctors have
come up with dozens of new ways to touch up your looks. They can
zap wrinkles with lasers or peel away mottled skin with chemicals.
They can suck fat out of chins, or deposit it in lips. But when it
comes to seriously overhauling one's visage, the facelift is still
the mainstay. This story details what it's like to go through such
a transformation. 60 inches. (Isger, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FUSSYBABIES-WEB _ WACO, Texas _ As a new father, Mike Lampkin
searched for something that would calm his fussy daughter,
especially during a changing when it is not possible to hold her.
So with the help of a friend and a little research, Lampkin found
what he calls a ``simple but effective solution'' in The Lampkin
Fussy Baby Help Page Web site. (Kincheloe, Waco Herald-Tribune)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-TOYS _ WACO, Texas _ Forget the Barbies, Beanie
Babies and action figures. If it doesn't talk, beep, ding or dong,
it may get left behind. An onslaught of electronic toys and gadgets
seem to be taking over the toys of yesteryear. ``Interactive toys
are probably more important to kids than something else,'' said
Barbara Rystrom of McGregor, as she and her daughter, Stephanie, 9,
shopped for electronic toys recently at Toys 'R' Us. ``Kids today
are used to using mechanical, hand-held-type things, and they don't
play as much imaginarily like with a doll. They always have to have
something that does something in order to entertain. A doll just
sort of sits there.'' (Mays, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
