<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-BOOKSIGNING28-     04-27 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-BOOKSIGNING28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewinsky manages to charm curious at bookstore
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ She's been dumped by a president,
deposed by a special prosecutor and betrayed by her best friend.
</P>
<P>
   But Monica Lewinsky can still unleash a smile to outshine a
paparazzi's flash.
</P>
<P>
   According to the famous First Intern, Clinton was attracted to
her bubbly personality. To the way, he supposedly told her, that
she lit up a room.
</P>
<P>
   So I drove to her book signing in Fort Lauderdale not to cluck
or chide or talk politics or morality or other Big Issues.
</P>
<P>
   I went solely to check out the charmisa factor; her ``wattage,''
if you will. Does she burn brightly enough to light up a room? Or
does she unleash barely enough amps to power an electric
toothbrush?
</P>
<P>
   I can report this: Monica shines.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know. I'm supposed to be cynical and hard-edged and
dislike this 25-year-old whose shaky morals almost toppled the
presidency. But the way she treated the almost 500 people who
waited in line to buy her best-selling ``Monica's Story'' won me
over.
</P>
<P>
   She did all the right things: She made eye contact with everyone
who paraded before her and often added a cheery ``Hi there!'' She
made quick small talk with some. When she was presented with gifts,
she was careful to explain that she was giving the presents to
security for safe-keeping, not merely casting them aside.
</P>
<P>
   People responded.
</P>
<P>
   One woman presented her with a rhinestone barrette and reacted
with teenybopper glee when Monica clipped it on her impossibly
shiny, jet black mane. ``I have such thick hair,'' Monica said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your hair is beautiful,'' assured the barrette woman.
</P>
<P>
   Monica turned her head to model. ``Does it look OK?''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to tell if Monica was born with the star power
to attract a president or if it comes courtesy of her recent
media-ready makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Friday she wore slimming black _ from chunky platforms to capri
pant to v-neck tee. She must have read _ and believed _ her own
press, because she appeared to be wearing the same makeup thousands
of women clamored for after the famous television interview with
Barbara Walters.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there weren't some things about the event that
seemed symbolic or ironic or just plain goofy. Like the fact that
after meeting Monica, book buyers at Liberties exited the signing
area between shelves holding ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to the
Impeachment of the President'' and ``The Lady is a Tramp'' sheet
music.
</P>
<P>
   Or how she coaxed wary autograph seekers over _ and conjured up
unfortunate mental images _ with a chirpy ``I don't bite.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of the assembled, a passing glimpse at one of the
world's most famous women seemed to be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the back of her head!'' said Ann Porter of Davie as
Monica and her entourage strode by 20 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She saw the back of her head. I saw her face,'' said Porter's
friend, Kristin Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   A passing glimpse is probably enough. After all, if you look too
long, you might get burned.
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
