<HEADER>
A4736 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHIZOPHRENIA-HELP28-     04-27 1856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHIZOPHRENIA-HELP28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New hope for schizophrenia's bewildered victims
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASTROP, Texas _ A man sits on a couch in his duplex, not
smoking. Junk mail, loose papers and a Bible piled on the coffee
table in front of him, a set of 1970 World Books on a shelf against
the wall behind. Short brown hair a little mussed on the right
side. Alert eyes set deep in a pillow of a face. This man tells an
old and familiar story in an autopilot monotone, then looks up,
smiles and says: ``I'm just a Pentecostal preacher who had some
hard times.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Exactly. A Pentecostal preacher who had some hard times,
makes $5.65 an hour as a courtesy clerk at the H-E-B store here and
has a six-year-old cat named Rosie. Rosie's litter is supposed to
be the odorless kind, but you can smell it.
</P>
<P>
   If you were just looking at the man not smoking, you wouldn't
know any of that. Nor would you know that when he smokes _ always
out on the back slab porch next to the garbage can _ he inhales
down to his toes.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't know that the man has seen the apocalypse and what
comes after.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would you know that when he takes his meds, the voices and
visions and delusions stop and he can get down to the business of
maintaining an existence within the parameters of what the world
defines rather narrowly as sanity. He goes to his job, checks the
oil in his car, listens to his Christian CDs, prays and struggles
to understand why this happened to him. The man is trusting, kind,
utterly without irony _ a discarded, forgotten part of you.
</P>
<P>
   The man is named Wesley Duty _ onetime preacher, would-be family
man, consistent hard worker. He's had schizophrenia for more than
half of his 37 years. Mental health advocates estimate some 11,700
Texans are receiving the medications, but some 34,000 _ again, an
estimate _ are still waiting. This year, the Texas Department of
Mental Health and Mental Retardation asked the Legislature for $150
million over two years to dispense the new drugs and services. (The
final amount, if approved, is likely to be less)
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the same anti-psychotics have been prescribed to
schizophrenics, but the drugs produced side effects in two-thirds
of those who took them _ facial tics, muscle spasms, tremors,
panting and grimacing among them. This frequently led to patients
taking themselves off the medicines, which in turn led to another
stay in the hospital. A new generation of ``atypical''
anti-psychotics offers schizophrenics at least a shot at a more
independent life. Two of the new drugs, risperidone and olanzapine,
received FDA approval in 1996 and 1997, respectively, and others
are on the way. Side effects are generally rarer and more
manageable in the new generation of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Wesley's apartment is a world away from the Capitol and the
suits, the powerful pharmaceutical companies and social
policymakers and budget appropriators. In Wesley's apartment sits a
man who knows how far he's come and how far he has yet to go.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy from Lubbock who was never quite right
</P>
<P>
   A woman and her husband sit on a couch in their northeast
Austin, Texas home, talking about schizophrenia as a family
affliction. The woman is Anita Glass, Wesley's sister. The husband
is Joe. They got married 20 years ago this summer, about the time
that Wesley started acting strangely.
</P>
<P>
   Anita: ``I liked him. He was my baby brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe: ``Always a nice man. A little hard to talk to, a little
self-absorbed, I guess. He had an imaginary world. He had all the
aspirations and goals of an average person and he wasn't achieving
them. He wanted the nice girlfriend and the car and the house, but
it was escaping him, and I don't think he understood why. I think
he spent a lot of time trying to figure out why everybody else was
getting those things and he wasn't. . . . When he's on his
medication, he sees the world more as it really is. And that ain't
all that pretty. He starts to realize his life is not all that
great, and he's not happy with that. So when he stops taking his
medication, he's happier for a while, but then he loses
functionality. He's smart enough to know what's going on around
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Schizophrenia advances with stealth and patience. But eventually
there's a line of demarcation, if only one that's recognized in
hindsight, between that's-just-Wesley-being-Wesley and
there's-something-really-wrong-with-Wesley. He was always, shall we
say, eccentric, and he didn't excel in school. Still, when his
father got him those World Books he inhaled them, reading about
other countries. In high school he was in French and German clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Wow, this world is magnificent. It's really
starting to show itself to me,' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then the tremors started. And the voices and delusions. And
Wesley's mind slammed the door shut.
</P>
<P>
   So, why is it that, in the abstract, we romanticize this thing _
mental illness, insanity, craziness, whatever we call it somehow
seems inaccurate, hurtful or unnecessarily obfuscatory? How can we
make songs out of craziness? How dare we use it to describe
ill-advised choices in love (``Crazy,'' Willie Nelson) or an excuse
to party down (``Let's Go Crazy,'' Prince) when those who have been
through it and out the other side can't even put it into words?
</P>
<P>
   Why is it we do that on the one hand, and then when suddenly
mental illness becomes the elephant in our living room we pretend
we don't see it. Because we don't understand, don't want to think
it might be hereditary, don't want to entertain the notion that
maybe it has something to do with the time when we dropped the baby
on her head. Because we can't stop thinking, Why won't he just stop
acting like that?
</P>
<P>
   Wesley's mother was dying in the hospital, and he took a little
break from reality _ noncommunicative, utterly withdrawn. And,
because he wouldn't be diagnosed as schizophrenic until four years
later, all Anita could think was what a self-obsessed jerk her
brother was being.
</P>
<P>
   One of his mother's last requests before she died on May 6,
1989, was that Wesley see a doctor. Wesley thought she wanted him
to be a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Bible school, Vegas and the crack-up
</P>
<P>
   What Wesley wanted to be, always, was a man of God. Clinging
white-knuckled to a fierce faith made it easier to handle objects
moving around the room by themselves. And so Wesley went to a Bible
school in an obscure corner of an obscure Midwestern state. One of
those places where they teach you that if you hear the Devil
talking, you've got a real problem.
</P>
<P>
   Once he tried to cook his Bible and eat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Devil can confuse you,'' he says, before adding, ``I
realize schizophrenia and demon possession are two different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesley values skills such as deductive reasoning he learned at
the school, but they didn't teach him how to get through everyday
life in a cramped little Lubbock efficiency with his father, a man
for whom tough love was the only kind he knew or could express.
</P>
<P>
   At his sister's urging, Wesley had been making efforts to get
help through MHMR, but he wasn't good about keeping appointments.
</P>
<P>
   And then in January of 1993, ``I cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a journey that would be called, in hindsight, his
major episode. He ran to Denver. ``Well, I didn't run, I took a
bus,'' he says. He stayed there a few days, then went to Las Vegas,
where the Bad Wesley took over and partook of . . . well, you know,
Vegas. And he did a heroic job of running through money but had
enough to get to Burbank, where he toured Universal Studios before
flying back to Vegas, blowing the rest of his stash, staying in a
shelter and calling his sister with the few quarters he had left in
his pocket. And the family fetched him home and talked with him,
and Wesley agreed that the hospital would be an OK place to stay
for a while. Then he went to the state hospital in Big Spring,
where he became attached, and arguably engaged, to a fellow patient
whom he never saw after her discharge. He traded a coat for a ring.
</P>
<P>
   She went back to El Paso, I guess,'' he says. ``She was nice. We
went to dances together.''
</P>
<P>
   A place of his own
</P>
<P>
   Because schizophrenia frequently emerges in late adolescence,
the disease frequently derails education or careers. And those who
suffer from it tend to exhibit less than complete social
development.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who will take advantage. Wesley got the job at
the H-E-B in May of '97, but the heat and stress made him break out
in a rash. He took a leave of absence, a breather. Then he began
forgetting to take his medicine because people were knocking on his
door, demanding money, saying they were the police.
</P>
<P>
   One night he lay in bed, his back to the wall, thinking about
his illness. He heard a gurgling, the cacophony of demons
chattering, dribbling out of his left ear.
</P>
<P>
   The delusions are largely in the past, thanks in part to the new
medications and in part to Wesley's adherence to a schedule that
provides structure. He no longer has to call his sister and ask,
``Did I die?''
</P>
<P>
   One theory of schizophrenia is that those who suffer from it
process information like wide-open open floodgates, unable to
filter the superfluous stuff _ ambient noise, for example. In the
days when Wesley was susceptible to distractions, the smallest
thing could trigger an elaborate delusion: A number on his
apartment key suddenly led to heaven on earth; a bump on his head
made him believe he'd been shot in Dallas; the sound of rain became
applause, and it was always for him; every show on TV was about
him.
</P>
<P>
   When these things would happen, he would isolate himself and
wait for the episodes to pass. It's been a long time since he's had
one.
</P>
<P>
   His care manager and his family seem accepting of Wesley's
progress. He knows he's making gains and he knows he's the one who
has to keep doing the work, taking the medication, working at the
H-E-B, buying his groceries and carton of Winstons on payday. He
plays a home-grown version of the civilization-building PC game
``Sim City'' using an old Slim-Fast can with pieces of paper in it,
an elaborate game involving two imaginary worlds that's been going,
off and on, since the Lubbock days. It takes a lot of time, but
Wesley has learned to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Doubly so in gaining ground with his disease. His sister and
brother-in-law tell him to treat it like diabetes, to never forget
to take his medication. He wants out of the system. He wants a wife
and kids. And he wants to be a missionary. These things may or may
not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that he'll get much better,'' said Steve Lefler,
his care manager. ``I think he's doing as well as can be
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he gets depressed. ``Sometimes I get lonely and forget
to do things,'' he says. ``So I do retreat sometimes into my own
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes in the winter, when it gets very cold, he smokes
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
