<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-FANATICS28-C     04-27 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-FANATICS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Star Wars fans, Only 480 hours to go!
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When you start waiting in line for a
movie 42 days ahead of time, you should expect someone to mock your
zealotry.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes for the two dozen dedicated souls who are waiting for
the next saga in the Star Wars series, Episode 1: The Phantom
Menace, at the makeshift campground outside Mann's Chinese Theater
in Hollywood, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Most passersby toss a quizzical,
what's-that-accident-by-the-side-of-the-road look their way. Others
are less charitable, such as a band of Star Trek fans who drove by
the other day and hurled insults, acting out a mild version of
sci-fi gang warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``A car full of guys yelled, `Get a life, you losers!''' said
fan Rick Carter. ``They went down Hollywood Boulevard a ways,
turned around, came back and yelled it again. Now, who's the bigger
loser? Us? Or the guys driving around shouting, `Loser' at the
supposed losers?''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's been in line since April 6. By the end of the month,
the 42-year-old screenwriter and movie director will have camped
out for 576 hours with several dozen friends. That's 576 hours
down, 480 more until showtime.
</P>
<P>
   He's part of a group that literally crossed oceans for the
chance to see the new flick first. The clan met on the World Wide
Web at a site dedicated to counting the days, hours and minutes
until the movie debuts. (The aptly named http://countingdown.com)
</P>
<P>
   While it has all the makings of a publicity stunt, these folks
aren't messing around. It may have started as a small, quirky idea,
but it's now a multimedia extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   The group is armed with laptop computers, cellular phones and a
host of digital cameras that snap photos and transmit video
glimpses of their line to the Internet. They've created a Web site
about their effort, using a computer powerful enough to run an
office building and attract 500,000 visits a day. (They're on line
on line, so to say.)
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors are providing power and telephone lines, as
well as money for each hour they spend in line. (The group aims to
raise $40,000 for the Starlight Foundation, which helps terminally
ill children.) Five months ago, they began plotting to take turns
in shifts to save their spots. They acquired city permits and a $1
million insurance policy so they could assemble a makeshift urban
campground. They're doing media interviews almost around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   And they're having a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay Leno came by the other day to film a comedy bit with us,''
said Carter, who at 42 is double the age of most in line. ``Jake
Lloyd, the little boy who plays the young Darth Vader in the new
movie, also came by to sign autographs and bring us a box of
candy.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second go-round for Carter. In 1977, he saw the
original Star Wars at the Chinese Theater on opening day. There was
no line _ it wasn't until a week later that word of mouth caused
moviegoers to cram theaters. It won't be that way this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once stood in line at 11 a.m. for a 7 p.m. showing of the
X-Files movie, but this is totally different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of Carter is Lincoln Gasking, a 22-year-old real estate
broker from Melbourne, Australia. The creator of countingdown.com,
Gasking flew into Los Angeles earlier this month, planning to start
the line on April 19. Instead, he jumped in on April 6 when word
got out that two teenagers had already formed a line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lincoln has been doing interviews nonstop,'' said Carter, who
joined the line four hours after Gasking. ``He finishes with one
and another crew steps up.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendees vary according to the time of day. The line diminishes
a bit during the workday but swells to more than 30 at night, when
others drop by to talk about the movie, nosh on junk food and
commune among friends.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at the Mann's theater in the Westwood section of Los
Angeles, 20-year-old software engineer Ilya Haykinson is waiting
with another dozen friends from countingdown.com.
</P>
<P>
   Their accommodations are more subdued. They're just as
technologically wired, but there's less space, so they're resorting
to umbrellas and lawn chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It rained the other night, so we just ducked into our cars,''
Haykinson said. ``The cars were parked right next to the sidewalk,
so we technically were still in line.''
</P>
<P>
   Another technicality: Haykinson and others continue to work. (It
helps that his Internet company in Santa Monica is helping sponsor
the line.) After work, he waits in Westwood, leaves early in the
morning to go home and take a shower and then goes to work again.
Gasking also keeps tabs on his job from the line by phone. Carter
doctors scripts while he waits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also helps that most of the town is about to go on hiatus
and they've bought all the scripts they'll need for next year's TV
season, so I have the time to spend.''
</P>
<P>
   The goofball quotient has been low among the diehard fans. No
one is dressed up like Obi-Wan Kenobi. Only a few people have
brought Star Wars toys or trinkets. A couple have Star Wars
tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one girl in line at the Chinese theater who has been
sitting in line full-time _ except for showering and eating _ only
as a social experiment,'' Haykinson said. ``She's not even going to
see the movie. She's donating the tickets she buys to fans and
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, they've become temporary darlings around town. Shows
such as Access Hollywood and Entertainment Tonight can't get enough
video of the group. During a premiere the other night at the
Chinese theater, a few got to hang with paparazzi so they could
snap digital pictures for the Web site of Sean Connery pressing his
hands and feet into wet cement.
</P>
<P>
   ``And every now and then Mann's brings us a big bag of
popcorn,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is actually flying faster than I wanted it to,''
Haykinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
