<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, April 27, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-LEGISLATOR (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Audie Bock, the nation's
first state official from the Green Party, is a curiosity to the
119 other lawmakers in the California Assembly. She describes her
first three weeks on the job as ``parachuting in.'' By ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-BOYCOTT (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Supervisor
Michael Yaki has urged drivers to not purchase gasoline on Friday
to protest the dramatic increase this year in Bay Area pump prices.
San Francisco has the highest gas prices in the nation, currently
at about $1.74 a gallon for self- serve unleaded. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-SMOKING (San Francisco) _ A sequence of increased fines for
those who repeatedly violate California's smoking ban in San
Francisco bars is expected to force tavern owners to discourage
nicotine fiends from lighting up.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUN-SAFETY (Undated) _ Sun is a major risk factor for skin
cancer and melanoma. And sun is the major cause _ along with
cigarette smoke, by the way _ of premature aging. Photoaging is
what sun damage is called. The results are brown sun spots,
collagen collapse and deep lines and wrinkles. Funny thing, though.
Sun damage is almost totally avoidable, just by taking certain
precautions. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-MAY-SWEEPS (Undated) _ The Top 10 things on television as the
networks jockey for position during May sweeps, which begins
Thursday and ends May 26. By MIKE McDANIEL
</P>
<P>
   PAVAROTTI-FUTURE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Should Luciano Pavarotti
retire? It depends on who's talking. The 63-year-old tenor's
harshest critics, citing the effects of age on one of the century's
great larynxes, say yes. Rabid admirers say no. Opera fanatics say
yes. He says no, at least for now. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   ELLINGTON-COLLECTION (San Francisco) _ Duke Ellington recorded
thousands of jazz numbers, pop songs, soundtrack renditions and
transcriptions for radio. Now RCA Victor has released the complete
collection of his works from 1927 to 1973 in ``The Duke Ellington
Centennial Edition,'' in time for the centenary of Ellington's
birth. By PHILIP ELWOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ELLINGTON-BIRTHDAY (San Francisco) _ Before the end of this
year, and century, there will be polls taken to determine the
``Best of the Century'' for every conceivable activity in the land.
In the ``Greatest American Composer of the Century'' category,
Edward Kennedy Ellington wins, hands down. By PHILIP ELWOOD.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-TARZAN (Undated) _ One of the best-selling authors
of the 20th century, Edgar Rice Burroughs in 1912 created a true
superhero, Tarzan. In ``Tarzan Forever,'' author John Taliaferro
chronicles the lasting impact of the creator of a popular cultural
icon, a writer whose contributions to the American myth are shunned
by academic critics. By DAN R. GODDARD.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-MOTHERS (Undated) _ With Mother's Day around the
corner, there's a great book just out that could be fun for mothers
and children to enjoy together. ``The Rainbow Hand: Poems About
Mothers and Children,'' by Janet S. Wong with illustrations by
Jennifer Hewitson, is a slim collection of poems celebrating the
mother-child bond. By JUDYTH RIGLER.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ Irish writer John Connolly's
debut thriller, ``Every Dead Thing'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25, 395
pages) is a stunner. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Why do Americans take the first room
available when checking into a hotel? Are we in such a rush? In
Europe, customers often reject the first room offered. Sometimes
even the second one, too. Presto! The third room is larger,
brighter and more comfortable. It behooves us to be more demanding.
By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ADVICE (Undated) _ As NATO continues to bomb Yugoslavia,
a reader asks, ``Do you think I should cancel my trip to Italy?'' A
top State Department official offers advice on how to stay safe
when traveling abroad. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Does it seem to you that San
Francisco Mayor Willie Brown is getting smaller? A friend who works
at City Hall asked me that question last week. He meant smaller
physically, as well as pettier in his private dealings and less
noisy in his public appearances. I had to agree that Brown seems to
be disappearing inside his $3,000 suits. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Sometime in the not-too-distant
future: Dozens of tourists listen as a tour guide points at a small
white rectangle, a standard, painted cinderblock. ``That,'' says
the tour guide, ``is the one and only surviving piece of public art
in San Francisco. It's called, `Not Bothersome.' It is the creation
of six people who once served on the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors.'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
