<HEADER>
A4782 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-ADVISORY-NYTSF     04-27 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEALTH EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Tribune News Service offers comprehensive daily
coverage of health news, comment and features Below are summaries
of articles being transmitted to the service's subscribers today
(Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like information about subscribing to this daily
health-news report, contact Bob Farnell at 800-535-4425 or e-mail
him at farnellb(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INHALER-HEART-MED _ SAN DIEGO _ A type of inhaler commonly used
to suppress asthma attacks may bring on a heart attack in some
at-risk patients, according to a report expected to be released
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of more than 4,500 asthmatics, Seattle researchers
found that the use of beta-agonist metered-dose inhalers increased
the risk for heart attack in some patients who also suffered from
heart disease. The risk was highest for new users of the inhalers.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to otherwise healthy asthmatics who did not use
beta-agonist inhalers, those with underlying heart disease who had
recently started on beta-agonist therapy were seven times more
likely to suffer a heart attack, researchers reported at the annual
joint meeting of the American Lung Association and the American
Thoracic Society.
</P>
<P>
   This elevated risk, according to Dr. David H. Au of the
University of Washington, likely involves the fact that new inhaler
users have not yet adjusted to the medication's side effect of
speeding up the heart rate. (500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-GENDER-MED _ SAN DIEGO _ Male and female smokers'
varying mood swings help determine why they reach for a cigarette,
and may help researchers fine tune smoking-cessation efforts to the
sexes, according to a report to be released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating what drives smokers to rip open a pack of
cigarettes, University of California at Irvine researchers asked 60
men and women ages 18 to 42 to record their moods before and after
lighting up. The subjects kept diaries for two days.
</P>
<P>
   While some emotions, such as anger and anxiety, drove both men
and women to scurry for a light, there were marked differences in
their smoking urges, Dr. Ralph Delfino and colleagues found. For
instance, when men were sad, they reached for a pack. Not so with
women, who tended to light up when happy. And anxious men only
worsened stress by smoking, while women found solace in their
cigarettes. (350 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   TRANSPLANT-GENDER-MED _ SAN DIEGO _ Lung transplants may be more
successful if both the donor and the recipient are female, experts
are expected to report here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As early as six months after a lung transplant, women who
received an organ from a man were at greater risk of serious
complications, according to a study of 98 men and women who
underwent the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the operation, the transplanted lung was
functioning in just three of the 16 women who received a lung from
a male donor, according to Dr. Keith C. Meyer of the University of
Wisconsin at Madison. In contrast, the lung was functional in 14 of
25 women who received a lung from another woman.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the American Lung Association and the American
Thoracic Society's annual meeting, Meyer and colleagues are
expected to encourage doctors to take the sex of the donor into
account when making transplant decisions. (DEVELOPING) (500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   VITAMINS-FRACTURES-MED _ EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE TUESDAY AT 4 P.M.
EASTERN _ While many are aware of the calcium's role in maintaining
healthy bones, relatively few know that vitamin D is also needed to
preserve bone strength.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 30 postmenopausal women seeking treatment for hip
fractures, researchers led by Dr. Meryl S. LeBoff of the Brigham
and Women's Hospital in Boston compared the group's vitamin D level
with that of 68 women of a similar age admitted for elective joint
replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Joint replacements are given to people suffering from damaged
joints, usually due to arthritis, while hip fractures are
associated with osteoporosis, a condition in which the bones thin
and weaken, becoming vulnerable to fractures.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published Wednesday in the Journal of the American
Medical Association (JAMA), the researchers reported that the blood
tests of the women with hip fractures revealed lower levels of
vitamin D than in those seeking joint replacements. This was also
the case when the fracture group was compared with 17 of the 68
joint-replacement participants who were also diagnosed with
osteoporosis. (500 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   OZONE-TRAFFIC-MED _ SAN DIEGO _ In cities where highways are
clogged with cars, ozone levels often exceed government standards.
These ``ozone-alert'' days can take a particularly heavy toll on
people with asthma.
</P>
<P>
   According to new research to be presented here Tuesday, cities
can reduce ozone levels by making changes in their citizens'
commuting habits.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta, officials attempted to
reduce traffic congestion in a number of ways, including
encouraging residents to take shuttle buses to and from work in the
downtown area. These efforts resulted in a more than 22-percent
decline in the number of cars on the roads during the morning rush
hour and a 28-percent decline in peak ozone levels, according to
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic-reduction program had a significant impact on asthma
cases in the Atlanta area, the investigators are expected to report
at the American Lung Association and the American Thoracic
Society's joint annual meeting. Compared with the periods four
weeks before and four weeks after the Olympics, hospitalizations
and emergency-room visits for asthma declined by 11 to 44 percent
during the 17 days of the Olympics. (DEVELOPING) (350 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-ADVICE-MED _ Dr. Eric Anderson answers health questions.
This week:
</P>
<P>
   --When spring arrived I began to sneeze and developed what
seemed like a mild cold, along with a slight sore throat. I am in
my 30s and have never had allergies before, but I'm wondering if
this could be hay fever. Do people ever develop these allergies
during adulthood? And how do you tell the difference between a cold
and allergies?
</P>
<P>
   --I recently started weight training and often have pain and
stiffness the day after a session, sometimes quite severe. How can
I avoid this, and what's the best way to deal with stiff muscles?
(500 WORDS)
</P>
