<SLUG> BC-TV-MAY-SWEEPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS SADDLING UP FOR WILD SWEEPS RIDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not the Kentucky Derby, but, ladies and gentlemen, we do
have a horse race as we enter the last month of the 1998-1999 TV
season. As the networks round the clubhouse turn, CBS leads NBC by
a nose in total viewers, and NBC holds a length's lead over Fox
among viewers 18-49.
</P>
<P>
   How they will finish _ and, in turn, how they will help their
affiliates to finish _ is what the May sweeps (Thursday-May 26) is
all about. And in this particularly competitive TV year, the horses
are geared up for what could be a memorable kick to the finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   Six miniseries, four series finales and several
better-than-average TV movies mark the makings of a memorable May.
Not to mention, there are several highly regarded series _ NBC's
``Homicide'' prominent among them _ that have yet to be renewed for
fall and, we can assume, will be strutting their best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Here's our guide to the best of the month _ not just among the
sweeps contestants, but all of television. May the best horse win.
</P>
<P>
   Top 10 handicappers
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Joan of Arc,'' May 16 and 18, CBS. A grand cast delivers
sterling performances in this well-written realization of the life
of the peasant girl ``called'' to lead warriors against Britain in
a quest to unite the provinces of France. New star Leelee Sobieski,
a ringer for Helen Hunt, is impressive in the lead role. Supplying
more than adequate support are Peter O'Toole, Neil Patrick Harris,
Peter Strauss, Shirley MacLaine, Olympia Dukakis, Maximilian
Schell, Jacqueline Bisset, Powers Boothe and Robert Loggia. Were
the battle scenes more grand, this would score higher. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Great Expectations,'' May 9-10, PBS. Ioan Gruffudd, so good
as the lead in A&AMP;E's ``Horatio Hornblower'' movies (and the
lifeboat captain in ``Titanic'' who goes back for survivors),
shines again in this new adaptation of the Dickens story. Charlotte
Rampling is a wonder as Miss Havisham. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Cleopatra,'' May 23-24, ABC. The show is not yet ready for
previews, but there's a good chance this will be worth seeing. A
``making of'' film that critics were shown in January showed
evidence that respected producer Robert Halmi Sr. was sparing
little expense on this project. Reports have surfaced that the
movie exceeded its purported $30 million budget. And Elizabeth
Taylor's not even in this one; instead, it stars newcomer Leonor
Varela (``Man in the Iron Mask''), with Timothy Dalton as Julius
Caesar and Billy Zane as Marc Antony.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Double Platinum,'' May 16, ABC. Diana Ross plays a woman
who abandons her baby girl in pursuit of a singing career. When she
comes back to see her, she discovers her daughter, played by
Brandy, has a voice of her own _ one she uses beautifully in song
and cuttingly as a child long spurned. The story's a bit off-key,
but the music's solid gold. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   5. ``The Unexpected Mrs. Pollifax,'' May 20, CBS. Angela
Lansbury returns in the role of Pollifax, who this time finds
herself involved in a secret CIA mission. Sounds preposterous but
we buy it thanks to Dorothy Gilman's talent as author and
Lansbury's talent playing a sweet but wily widow. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Our Guys,'' May 10, ABC. Heather Matarazzo (``Welcome to
the Dollhouse'') brilliantly portrays a mildly retarded girl who
becomes the victim of a gruesome sexual assault by a group of high
school football players. Ally Sheedy and Eric Stoltz play the cops
who try to nail the assailants. Not helping: The victim, who just
wants to be liked, is recanting right and left. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   7. ``The Simple Life of Noah Dearborn,'' May 9, CBS. Sidney
Poitier plays a carpenter rooted in old-fashioned ways and values
who becomes the target of a greedy developer. Dianne Wiest and
Mary-Louise Parker co-star. Though unavailable for preview, we sure
do like this cast.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``A Lesson Before Dying,'' May 22, HBO. Joseph Sargent's
much-anticipated adaptation of Ernest Gaines' searing novel. Don
Cheadle stars. Unavailable for preview.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Noah's Ark,'' Sunday and Monday, NBC. Producer Robert Halmi
Sr. allows incredible liberties with the Bible (is nothing
sacred?), casting Noah and Lot as old friends and introducing what
appears to be an unknown survivor of the flood. There's some
dialogue we think was intended to be funny (but isn't) and some
special effects that weren't supposed to be funny-looking (but
are). Jon Voight and Mary Steenburgen star. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Atomic Train,'' May 16-17, NBC. This could be the sleeper
hit of the sweeps. Rob Lowe attempts to stop a runaway train loaded
with nuclear waste and, uh-oh, one stolen nuclear bomb. We can't
keep this a secret: He fails, and poor Denver is blown to
smithereens. The special effects are OK to good, and the idea of
focusing on a train loaded with nuclear waste is a good one. The
bomb was one too many hard things to swallow. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
