<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, April 28, 1999. If you have any questions, please call
The Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   WEB (Washington D.C.) _ Presidential contenders for the first
time are waging political combat on the Internet. By David
Goldstein. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   OLDDRIVE (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Evelyn White, 84, has driven
almost every day since she got her license as a teen-ager. And she
never had an accident _ until one chilly day last December. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White didn't see the pickup as she turned left into traffic. The
crash, which barely dented her fender, jolted her into reassessing
her own driving skills. ``I realized I couldn't hear so good
anymore and, well, little things are going wrong with my body,''
she said. ``It was time for me to stop driving.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While White reached that realization on her own, many of this
country's 17 million drivers over age 75 continue to drive long
after they can safely do so. Missouri has a new law that is
becoming a national role model for creating a safe, effective way
to get drivers with impairments (failing vision, etc.) off the
road. By Lee Kavanaugh. With photos. (Story will move in the ``a''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   GUN _ Today President Clinton calls for legislation to make
parents liable if children use their parents' firearms in crimes.
We get local reactions. Johnson County prosecutor says it's a bad
idea, while Jackson County's prosecutor says it's up to the
legislature to make the call. We check with other county officials
as well as both state legislatures to see if there is support for
making parents responsible for their children's violent acts. Ruth
Igoe w/feeds from Topeka and Jefferson City. (Story will move in
the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOATS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Kansas City's gamblers lost a record
$42 million in March, surpassing the $40 million mark for the first
time ever. That puts KC on pace as a HALF-BILLION DOLLAR-a-year
gambling market. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Sprint acquires American Telecasting
Inc., a Colorado Springs company that controls broadcast licenses
that can provide high-speed Internet and data services in 55
markets. The deal is valued at about $450 million. By Ted
Sickinger. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
