<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-COLLECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTION BRINGS TOGETHER ELLINGTON'S PROLIFIC MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP ELWOOD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ No one _ composer, conductor, bandleader,
instrumentalist, classical European or classical jazz, blues,
whatever _ came close to recording as much material as Duke
Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 50 years, from 1924 until 1973 (a few months before
his death) Ellington recorded, for commercial issue, about 3,500
jazz numbers, pop songs, soundtrack renditions and so forth. He
also recorded transcriptions for radio (each containing about a
dozen selections), and the number of Ellington radio broadcasts,
taken (illegally) off the air, then privately issued on LPs and CDs
over the years, has totalled more than 350.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Duke Ellington Centennial Edition: The Complete RCA Victor
Recordings 1927-1973'' (RCA Victor, 24 CDs, boxed set; list price
$407) includes everything that Ellington recorded for the Victor
Talking Machine Co. (after 1929, RCA Victor) starting in 1927.
There are unissued numbers from the vaults as well as second and
third ``takes'' and, of course, all the small-group numbers issued
under the names of Johnny Hodges, Barney Bigard, Rex Stewart and
other Ellington sidemen.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Ellington signed a major-label recording contract, it
was stipulated that his band's principal soloists would make
small-group recordings (with the Duke on piano) for sale on the
major company's cheaper label, in RCA Victor's case, the Bluebird
label; Brunswick-Columbia had its less expensive Vocalion label.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in his early recording years, despite contractual
agreements with one or another major label (Victor, Columbia,
Brunswick, Okeh), Ellington also recorded simultaneously for
smaller ``dime-store'' labels, under various pseudonyms. For the
cardboard ``Hit of the Week'' discs, Ellington's band was the
``Philadelphia Melodians'' or the ``Ten Blackberries.''
</P>
<P>
   For Okeh, the title was ``The Harlem Footwarmers'' or ``Harlem
Hot Chocolates.'' Brunswick used ``The Washingtonians'' and ``The
Jungle Band,'' and Columbia released some of Duke's 78s as ``Sonny
Greer and his Memphis Men.'' Greer was the Ellington drummer for
nearly 30 years, replaced in 1950 by Louie Bellson.
</P>
<P>
   During the 46 years of Ellington's career covered on this
remarkable RCA Victor set, there were many periods during which he
recorded exclusively for other companies (Brunswick-Columbia,
Capitol, Reprise, for example) as well as thousands of times that
he conducted recording sessions that he kept for future use. Many
of these are still in the can, awaiting possible use by the
Ellington Estate.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1963 radio interview, saxist Russell Procope said, ``Our
rehearsals are in the recording studios; that's where we work
things out.'' Baritone saxist Harry Carney, also in the studio,
nodded his agreement.
</P>
<P>
   This immense package of Ellingtonia is divided six ways: The
Early Recordings, seven discs (1927-1934); The Early '40s, six
discs; Mid '40s, four discs; The Seattle Concert (1952) ends disc
17. Then there are three Sacred Concerts from 1965-1973 (not
including the first, in Grace Cathedral), and the Last Recordings
section (four discs) includes an expanded Far East Suite.
</P>
<P>
   Older Ellington fans will find particular pleasure in the neatly
produced re-mastering of such numbers as ``Black and Tan Fantasy,''
``Creole Love Call,'' ``The Mooche,'' ``Jubilee Stomp,'' ``High
Life,'' ``Harlemania,'' ``Misty Mornin,'' ``The Duke Steps Out,''
``Jazz Lips,'' ``Sweet Jazz o' Mine,'' ``Ring Dem Bells'' and, of
course, ``Mood Indigo,'' ``Solitude,'' ``Rockin' In Rhythm,'' the
strange ``Mystery Song,'' ``Ebony Rhapsody'' and all the rest, most
of which were issued as ``Duke Ellington and his Cotton Club
Orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   RCA Victor recorded most of the best of Ellington's great
1940-42 orchestra, and 140 titles from that grand period, sometimes
called ``The Blanton Years'' for bassist Jimmy Blanton, are in this
set _ such as ``Cottontail,'' ``Harlem Air-Shaft,'' ``Jack The
Bear,'' ``Ko-Ko'' and many more. The early '40s tracks in this set
also include all the great small-combo records already mentioned,
as well as much of the material from Ellington's musical show,
``Jump For Joy,'' which included such tunes as ``I Got It Bad and
That Ain't Good.''
</P>
<P>
   The period after World War II was difficult for big bands, but
Ellington carried on, redoing many older titles, dabbling with pop
novelties, gradually expanding his longer works and eventually
creating religious and global-based concert presentations.
</P>
<P>
   When asked in the early 1950s, when his and all other bands were
losing money, why he didn't break up his orchestra, live on his
considerable royalties and devote his time to composition and the
concert world, he answered: ``Give up my band? Why, without my band
how could I hear my music?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last 10 CDs in the set, covering RCA Victor's issues of
Ellington music from 1944-1973, include material from ``Black,
Brown and Beige,'' the ``Perfume Suite,'' three ``Sacred
Concerts,'' the ``Far East Suite,'' the ``Duke at Tanglewood'' and
``His Mother Called Him Bill'' LPs, as well as a large number of
remakes of earlier classics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Popular Duke Ellington'' LP from 1966 is here in its
entirety (including some unreleased tracks). its digital
remastering improves the original album's beautiful sound.
</P>
<P>
   This Ellington Centennial Edition set, for the most part, is the
work of producer Orrin Keepnews. The large, lavish, 122-page
accompanying book is loaded with photos and the essays and
commentary of Mary Lou Williams, Dan Morgenstern, Stanley Dance,
Patricia Willard, Stanley Crouch, Keepnews and others. Their
contributions, the photos and layout help make this Ellington
Centennial Edition a very special _ in fact, essential _ part of
any jazz fan's library.
</P>
<P>
   Because this set is ``The Complete RCA Victor Recordings,'' it
must, necessarily, include everything in the vaults, including
quite a number of ordinary arrangements of inferior pop tunes,
particularly in the postwar years of the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Also presumably essential is the inclusion of all ``takes'' of a
number, even if there is no discernible difference from one to the
other. Listening to the same selection two or three times in a row
can, to some, become an annoying and frustrating experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
