<HEADLINE>
`THIRD HOTEL ROOM' POLICY WORTH A TRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A colleague was discussing her ``third hotel room'' philosophy
recently during a break from a business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The lodging ritual, she explained, had become all too familiar
and frustrating: At check-in, the registration clerk would provide
a set of keys, smile and offer directions to the assigned room. If
the room didn't meet her standards for safety, ambience and
practicality established during years of frequent travel, she would
return to the front desk and politely request an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Though usually an improvement, the second room, too,
occasionally had deficiencies. So again she would approach the
registration desk, this time more forcefully _ perhaps with the
suggestion that she was prepared to take her business elsewhere _
and, presto, the attendant would find a bigger or brighter or
better room.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now, to save everyone involved time and frustration, when I
first arrive I just ask them to give me the third room they're
going to offer (the best room available),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STANDARD PROCEDURE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This may seem a radical procedure to the majority of other
American travelers, but I've known Europeans who never accept the
first room offered, at least not before making an inspection.
Hoteliers there expect this kind of discriminating attitude from
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Why are most of us less choosy? We pay hard-earned money for
lodging away from home. But I can count on the fingers of one hand
the number of times I've openly rejected a hotel room or uttered
more than a mild complaint (except under my breath) when the lights
were too dim, the pillows too lumpy and the toilet too balky.
</P>
<P>
   One reason we're easily appeased is that we're so often in a
rush. Overnight accommodations are usually a means to an end _ a
place to hang our hats between treasured activities _ and not a
high priority for venting emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, most Americans _ myself included _ are conditioned by
motels and hotels whose cookie-cutter rooms are similar or
identical in design. At a Holiday Inn or Motel 6, usually the only
reason to request different accommodations is if we're too close to
the elevator or laundry room or too far removed from the car or ice
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not every lodging establishment fits a specific mold.
Individual rooms in historic hotels, bed-and-breakfasts, boutique
hotels, resorts and country inns can take on distinct
personalities. And we can enhance our comfort level and overall
enjoyment by trying to match our preferences to a room's
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Even with prefabricated chains, it behooves us to be more
demanding _ in a nice way, of course _ about basic essentials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PERSONAL EXPECTATIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I'll never adopt a ``third hotel room'' policy _ and
my experiences with lodging have been largely positive _ but my
colleague's persistence is prompting me to give new emphasis to
qualities I deem important. A Houston travel agent once forwarded a
fascinating list of about 50 qualities he admires about a good
hotel room; my list isn't that long, but here are some
expectations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Adequate safety precautions. Doors should have multiple locks.
A peephole is essential. Windows should be tightly secured. Fire
evacuation material should be clearly displayed. A sprinkler system
is always welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good lighting, especially beside the bed, in the bathroom, in
the closet and at a desk.
</P>
<P>
   _ A desk or table. I never cease to be amazed _ and irritated _
when a room-service waiter delivers dinner on a tray and asks,
``Where do you want me to put it?'' when the bed and floor clearly
represent the only options.
</P>
<P>
   _ Abundant and conveniently located electrical outlets. Do
hoteliers take delight in placing outlets behind a bed frame bolted
to the wall?
</P>
<P>
   _ Adequate storage space, preferably in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   _ A bathroom in which I can turn around. Extra towels. A toilet
that doesn't drip all night. A shower that doesn't produce water
boiling hot at one moment and icy cold the next. Spare tissue and
toilet paper. Room to place a toothbrush and newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heating and air conditioning that I can control.
</P>
<P>
   _ A no-smoking floor.
</P>
<P>
   _ A comfortable bed with enough pillows that I can sleep with my
head raised.
</P>
<P>
   _ Soundproofed windows, especially at hotels situated near
freeways or airports.
</P>
<P>
   _ Room doors that aren't built 3 inches off the carpet, allowing
noise from hallways to permeate the room.
</P>
<P>
   _ A clock that illuminates in the night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Proximity (at least on the same floor) to an ice machine that
functions properly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cable television. I like to keep up with the Astros and
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   _ A comfortable chair that faces (or can be moved to face) the
TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ A computer-friendly telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Some travelers no doubt would place kid-friendly qualities high
on their priority lists. Others relish being near a swimming pool
(or distanced from the pool). Still others appreciate or require
rooms designed for individuals with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   What are your druthers? Your pet peeves about lodging? When
dissatisfied, do you adopt an alternative to the ``third hotel
room'' philosophy? Write to me at 801 Texas Ave., Houston, Texas
77002; fax 713-217-1369; or send e-mail responses to
harry.shattuckchron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
