<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-BIRTHDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLINGTON EMBODIES AMERICAN MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP ELWOOD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A half-century ago, the U.S. State Department
promoted a series of overseas jazz-concert tours by distributing
hundreds of red, white and blue placards that read: ``What Is More
American Than Jazz?''
</P>
<P>
   This slogan came to mind when it was announced that Duke
Ellington, 25 years after his death in 1974, was the recipient of a
Pulitzer Prize for his contribution to America's musical culture.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the world will celebrate the centennial of Edward
Kennedy Ellington's birth, recognizing the immense contribution
this larger-than-life talent made to America's _ and the world's _
music.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of this year, and century, there will be polls
taken to determine the ``Best of the Century'' for every
conceivable activity in the land. In the ``Greatest American
Composer of the Century'' category, the names of George Gershwin
and Ellington will loom large, but for many of us it's no contest _
Ellington wins, hands down, if for no other reason than the purely
American perspective from which he always viewed his music-making.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin was born in New York; Ellington was from Washington _
can't get much more American than that. Both Gershwin and Ellington
as teen-agers emerged as ambitious, driven piano players in the
wartime, ragtime-to-jazz transition era.
</P>
<P>
   By 1920, Gershwin had scored with a pop tune, ``Swanee,'' thanks
to Al Jolson, and was ready to conquer Broadway with his first hit
show, ``Lady Be Good'' _ as soon as he premiered ``Rhapsody In
Blue,'' with Paul Whiteman (later, an Ellington fan) in Manhattan's
Aeolian Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington was in Harlem to stay by 1922-23, and with his
Washingtonians sextet began recording in 1924. In the mid-1920s,
Ellington's name and music became familiar on the New York scene,
while Gershwin's already was known throughout the Western world.
</P>
<P>
   But though often referred to as ``jazz'' or even ``blues,''
Gershwin's was composed popular (and semi-classical) music,
attractive as hell but having none of the roots that Ellington
automatically and effortlessly dug into on the keyboard, in band
performance and composition.
</P>
<P>
   By 1927-28, both Ellington and Gershwin, good friends and mutual
admirers, were on their way _ Gershwin, with less than 10 years to
live, to Hollywood; Ellington, always New York-based, looking
forward to 50 years of nonstop composing, performing and recording.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin's early scores frequently alluded to ragtimey jazz,
pop-gospel and blues. Ellington's music (as heard on records)
defined jazz, blues, black church music, and African-American
rhythms and harmony as played by a jazz ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to his first Victor record, ``Creole Love Call'' and
``Black and Tan Fantasie'' (1927) _ both astonishing variations on
the blues, with murky harmonies, abrupt dynamic shifts and
astonishingly original, intertwined, melodic lines, some (as on
``Creole Love Call'') sung wordlessly _ the voice becoming an
instrument accompaniment by the woodwinds.
</P>
<P>
   To be appreciated, Ellington's music demanded that his band play
it. From ``East St. Louis Toodle-Oo'' to ``Rockin' in Rhythm,''
from ``Sophisticated Lady'' to ``Satin Doll,'' it was the Ellington
bandsmen's performance, constantly changing, that defined the
composition.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing is more American than jazz, nothing defines jazz more
than Ellington's music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
