<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-TARZAN-HN     04-27 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-TARZAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK EXPLORES TARZAN CREATOR'S SWINGS OF FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN R. GODDARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best-selling authors of the 20th century, Edgar Rice
Burroughs in 1912 created a true superhero, Tarzan, inspiring a
multimedia dynasty in books, comics, radio shows, movies and
merchandising that is still thriving today.
</P>
<P>
   With the Disney animated version of ``Tarzan'' due at theaters
in June, the lord of the jungle is sure to be everywhere, but his
creator remains an enigma.
</P>
<P>
   Austin-based John Taliaferro, former senior editor for Texas
Monthly, has written a timely, highly readable biography of
Burroughs, tracing his career from down-and-out Chicago pencil
sharpener salesman to Southern California conglomerate. Rarely
bogging down in too much detail, ``Tarzan Forever: The Life of
Edgar Rice Burroughs, Creator of Tarzan'' (Scribner, $30) combines
a magazine writer's flair for storytelling with a historian's
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Much as he did in his previous book, ``Charles M. Russell: The
Life and Legend of America's Cowboy Artist,'' Taliaferro chronicles
the lasting impact of the creator of a popular cultural icon, a
writer whose contributions to the American myth are shunned by
academic critics.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs was one of the first writers to incorporate, and that
was wise, since Tarzan inspired a rabid following, complete with
conventions, fan clubs and mountains of memorabilia long before
``Star Trek'' and ``Star Wars'' captured the hearts and the
pocketbooks of millions.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than growing out of the myth of the ``noble savage,''
Tarzan emerges as a product of Burroughs' belief in eugenics _ the
controversial interpretation of Darwinism as ``biological
determinism'' that the Nazis used to justify their Final Solution.
Burroughs was obsessed with his own genealogy and extremely proud
of his nearly pure Anglo-Saxon lineage.
</P>
<P>
   While most people associate Tarzan with the slow-talking,
slow-witted movie character played by Johnny Weissmuller, the
Tarzan of Burroughs' books is a misplaced English lord, self-taught
but fluent in several languages. He is as at home in the city as
the jungle. The movie ``Greystoke'' is probably the most faithful
screen adaptation, although the Disney ``Tarzan'' reportedly
restores the original story line.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney most likely will tone down Burroughs' more racist
tendencies. In the Tarzan stories, black Africans are generally
superstitious and Arabs rapacious. Although frequently interpreted
as an early environmentalist, Tarzan doesn't hesitate to kill rare
and endangered animals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tarzan is such a pliable hero that his appeal is nearly
universal for young males. Tarzan's tales have been published in
more than 30 languages.
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs the man was full of energy, tackling all sorts of
projects and business schemes while churning out 300,000 to 400,000
words a year. He wrote 75 books, 24 featuring Tarzan. But his
best-known works, ``Tarzan'' and ``John Carter of Mars,'' were
written in a hurry, often on deadline and under pressure to
generate money for his profligate spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   With only a couple of exceptions, he never achieved his dream of
graduating from the pulps into the realm of ``serious literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs had the instincts of a businessman, but he never
figured out how to manage his fortune. With some of his early movie
money, he bought a large ranch near Los Angeles that today is the
suburb Tarzana. However, as Taliaferro explains, Burroughs was one
of the few people who failed to make money in Southern California
real estate. Despite a sizable income during the Depression,
Burroughs was always one scheme away from poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Taliaferro ends his story with Burroughs' death in 1950, though
you may wish he had continued to follow the history of the family
business, Edgar Rice Burroughs Inc., which still operates in the
small Spanish-style bungalow on Ventura Boulevard that Burroughs
built as an office.
</P>
<P>
   In a day when fiction has a shelf life of less than six weeks,
Burroughs' novels are all still in print and his first editions are
highly prized collectibles. While he never gained the approval of
critics, his best revenge is the immortal Tarzan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
