<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR MAKES DEBUT WITH A STUNNING THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Irish writer John Connolly's debut thriller, ``Every Dead
Thing'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25, 395 pages) is a stunner.
</P>
<P>
   New York Police Detective Charlie Parker's marriage is on the
skids. One night after another verbal battle with his wife, Susan,
he heads for the local bar. When he stumbles home, he finds the
bodies of Susan and their 3-year-old daughter Jennifer. Both had
been tortured and both have had their faces removed. Consumed by
guilt, Parker leaves the force, works as an unlicensed private
investigator and is determined to find his family's killer.
</P>
<P>
   His hunt takes him to New Orleans, where FBI agent Woolrich
tells him of Tante Marie, a psychic who gets messages from a young
girl who has been murdered in the bayou, but her body has never
been found. Tante Marie also says the girl has no face.
</P>
<P>
   Parker visits Tante Marie, who knows about his wife and child.
She tells him their murderer is ``the Travelin' Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in New York, he is hired by Isobel Barton, a wealthy widow
who runs the Barton Trust, which aids child-related causes.
</P>
<P>
   During a fund-raiser at the Barton estate, a young boy
disappeared and has never been found. Now Barton wants Parker to
find Catherine Demeter, a young woman she had befriended and has
now disappeared. Demeter had been dating Barton's stepson, who has
ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   His investigation leads him to Haven, Va., where he learns that
Demeter's sister and three other children had been brutally
murdered years before. No one in Haven wants to talk about the
past, but someone now is trying to erase any clues to the old
murders by killing anew. Aided by two career criminals, Parker
finds an old warehouse in Flushing, N.Y., and the bodies of many
murdered children.
</P>
<P>
   Parker discovers the identity of the murderer, but before he can
close down his investigation he gets a call from Tante Marie's
niece, who says, ``Mista Parker, she say you gotta come now and you
gotta tell no one you comin'. No one, Mista Parker ... Mista
Parker, she say the Travelin' Man comin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly has created a complex tale that is as riveting and
chilling as Thomas Harris' ``Silence of the Lambs'' and James
Patterson's ``Kiss the Girls.'' Well-paced and character-driven,
``Every Dead Thing'' is a terrific addition to the genre.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Silva's third thriller, ``The Marching Season'' (Random
House, $25.95, 418 pages) is a gripping look at the hatreds that
have fueled the troubles in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after Northern Ireland's people voted to accept the
Good Friday peace accords, a new Protestant militant group emerges
bent on destroying any chance of peace.
</P>
<P>
   In Belfast, a gunman kills Eamon Dillon, Sinn Fein's
third-ranking officer. At the same time, a man walks into the
reading room at Dublin's National Library and sets a timer on a
bomb he leaves behind in a briefcase. But before he can get to
safety, the bomb goes off and he becomes one of the many victims.
</P>
<P>
   In London, a young woman takes a rolling suitcase down the
stairs at the Knightsbridge entrance to the subway. She boards a
train headed for Heathrow, where she exits the train at the first
stop after setting the timer on the bomb in the suitcase. Before
she can get to safety, this bomb explodes and she too dies.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the BBC receives a call saying the murder and the
bombings were the work of the Ulster Freedom Brigade, ``which will
continue its campaign of armed resistance until the so-called Good
Friday peace accord is dead and buried. All those who support this
betrayal of Northern Ireland's Protestant community should regard
this statement as fair warning.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, British Prime Minister Tony Blair asks U.S.
President James Beckwith ``to appoint a superstar to be your next
ambassador to London. Someone all sides can respect ... I want
someone who can help me achieve my goal, a permanent settlement to
the conflict in Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   So Beckwith names his old nemesis, former Sen. Douglas Cannon.
Cannon's son-in-law, retired CIA officer Michael Osbourne, returns
to the agency to head the Northern Ireland desk. On a routine
mission to Belfast to meet with an operative, he learns that the
Ulster Freedom Brigade plans to assassinate Cannon in London.
Osbourne launches a plan to lure the brigade into a trap.
</P>
<P>
   What Osbourne does not know is that the assassin who tried to
kill him and his family the year before is alive and once again
will attack Cannon and the Osbourne family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marching Season'' is a fast-paced read with well-developed
characters. Its one flaw? A couple of scenes that are too
reminiscent of parts of Silva's ``Mark of an Assassin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
