A4897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-27 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO'S FOOT-IN-MOUTH PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometime in the not-too-distant future: A tour
bus pulls up near the newly remodeled Ferry Building in San
Francisco. Dozens of tourists climb down and gather 'round the tour
guide.
</P>
<P>
   She points southward at a small white rectangle. Upon closer
inspection, it reveals itself to be a standard, painted
cinderblock.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' says the tour guide, ``is the one and only surviving
piece of public art in San Francisco. It's called, `Not
Bothersome.' It is the creation of six people who once served on
the San Francisco Board of Supervisors.''
</P>
<P>
   A man from Texas says: ``I don't get it. What's it supposed to
be?''
</P>
<P>
   The tour guide smiles and says, ``Just what its name implies.
The goal of its creators was to make a piece of public art that no
one would notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Incredulous laughter.
</P>
<P>
   A woman from Iowa asks, ``What's the point of having public art
that the public doesn't notice?''
</P>
<P>
   The guide suggests that the group sit down so she can give them
some backround.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1999, she says, a majority of San Francisco
supervisors voted to kill a $475,000 proposed sculpture of a bare
foot. The culmination of 5 1/2 years of planning and the work of a
Seattle artist named Buster Simpson, the statue would have been 18
feet high, balanced on the ball of The Foot. It would symbolize
several aspects of San Francisco's waterfront and history.
</P>
<P>
   The Foot had been approved by several committees, including the
city's Art Commission. But, acting as the San Francisco Transit
Authority (the sculpture was part of an Embarcadero roadway
improvement project) six of the 11 supervisors chose to reverse the
process and amputate The Foot.
</P>
<P>
   Says a tourist from New York, ``What, were they all art
majors?''
</P>
<P>
   No, the guide explains. They responded to many citizens who
called and wrote to say they didn't want a Foot. People gave all
kinds of reasons, from The Foot's purported racism and sexism _ it
was white and seemed male _ to the fact that it might attract
vandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``But somebody always has a problem with any proposed public
art,'' the New Yorker says. ``Isn't that why cities have art
commissions instead of ballot measures to decide this kind of
stuff?''
</P>
<P>
   The tour guide says it was like that in San Francisco until The
Foot controversy. Since then, the Art Commission's job has been to
dismantle every piece of public art in town and find homes for them
in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who'd long disliked this piece or that saw an
opportunity,'' the guide says. ``They mounted similar protest
campaigns and, one by one, got all the sculptures ripped out and
the murals painted over. Now, all of San Francisco is a zone free
of public art.''
</P>
<P>
   The tourists shake their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, what's the point of this thing?'' says the Texas man,
giving a sideways kick to ``Not Bothersome.'' ``You can't sit on
it. It doesn't even have a plaque. It's utterly useless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not true,'' the tour guide says. ``This sculpture doesn't
bother anyone. In San Francisco, that is not only useful, it's
thoroughly representative of the collective aesthetic. We think of
it as post-mediocrity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
