<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4898 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APACHEPILOT-TEX     04-27 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APACHEPILOT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WOMAN JOINS NATO DEPLOYMENT AS APACHE PILOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKESIDE, Texas _ Trying to raise Mandy MacWhirter, according to
her dad, was like trying to restrain a wild horse.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, she was competitive and aggressive, a high
achiever who excelled in math and science and showed little
tolerance for peers who whined or exhibited low standards. She had
a fiery temper and a penchant for defying authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got an attitude a mile long,'' Steve MacWhirter said
over the weekend, joking with pride about his now 26-year-old
daughter. ``Anybody that knows her knows she'd give you the shirt
off her back, but she'll tell you off in a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of attitude that makes a helicopter pilot,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   First Lt. Mandy MacWhirter, an Azle High School graduate with a
``show-me attitude,'' is among the U.S. Army's first female Apache
helicopter pilots and could engage in combat as part of Operation
Allied Force's mission to damage Serbian forces in Kosovo, said Lt.
Col. Lew Boone, an Army spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   MacWhirter, a weapons officer, is one of about 50 Apache pilots
who landed Wednesday in Tirana, Albania. She couldn't be reached
for comment, and it was unknown whether she had any connection to
the Apache helicopter that crashed on a training mission on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not her. I'm worried sick,'' Steve MacWhirter said
last night after hearing of the mishap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had female Apache pilots only for the last five years,''
said Boone, who noted that artillery and cavalry positions were
first opened up to women in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   They flew in Bosnia, but only as top cover, he said. U.S.
attacks on Iraq during Operation Desert Fox late last year marked
the first time that female pilots had dropped bombs in combat.
</P>
<P>
   The brigade of 24 Apaches _ dubbed Task Force Hawk _ has joined
Operation Allied Force at the request of Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's
supreme commander.
</P>
<P>
   A quick-reacting, all-weather gunship that can fly as low as 10
feet off the ground, hide behind mountains and pop up to unleash
Hellfire missiles in a surprise ambush, the AH-64 Apache is the
Army's primary attack helicopter. NATO officials are looking for
the tank-killers to provide a more direct response to Serbian
infantry and armored units than that afforded by the jet fighters
used so far in Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   Apache aviators are ``probably our best pilots,'' Boone said.
Those sent to Albania are based in Illesheim in southern Germany as
part of the 11th Aviation Regiment. ``They're very gung-ho. They
swagger'' when they walk, he said jokingly. ``They have this
fighter-pilot mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve MacWhirter, 49, agrees. ``They're kind of like a bunch of
cowboys, proud and gung-ho ... the kind of people that go to
extremes and you feel like you have to reach out and pull them
back.''
</P>
<P>
   A native Californian, Mandy MacWhirter moved to Lakeside with
her family just in time to start the ninth grade at Azle High
School. After graduating in 1990, she attended Texas Christian
University on a three-year Army ROTC scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Female cadets more often choose nursing, said retired Lt. Col.
Roger Wilson, one of MacWhirter's senior year instructors. When he
met her, ``she had a bit of a chip on her shoulder. ... There
aren't that many female pilots, and you have to have a little bit
of an attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   MacWhirter was a leader, not a follower, he remembered. She
graduated from TCU and its ROTC program in 1995 with a degree in
astrophysics and went on to the Army's flight school at Fort
Rucker, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   She has since taken part in a mission to Bosnia, where she
refueled aircraft; supervised her platoon in Germany; and was
involved in the logistics of moving the Apache pilots' camp to
Albania, her parents said.
</P>
<P>
   The achievements of their outgoing daughter are a source of
pride for the MacWhirters. But they are also acutely aware that the
Apache's heralded ability to fly low is also what makes this
mission inherently dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be in positions where they'll be susceptible to being
shot down'' by Serbian soldiers carrying shoulder-fired
anti-aircraft weapons, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The anguish was apparent on the face of Vivian MacWhirter, 73,
the pilot's grandmother, as she sifted through family photographs
and postcards _ one picturing an Apache helicopter _ and mulled the
risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're filled with anxiety, and on the other hand, we're
trusting in the Lord,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Diane MacWhirter, 49, said her daughter grew up in the church,
and the family realizes that ``you get to a point where you have no
control. It's out of our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But reports of ethnic Albanian women being raped by Serbs and
the capture of three American soldiers bring worry. ``God forbid
she should be taken captive,'' said Mandy MacWhirter's aunt, Janice
Luder.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who has kept in touch with MacWhirter since she left
TCU, imagines that his former student is probably ``looking at it
as a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain amount of anxiety, but it's anxiety that
you've been (preparing) for,'' he said of the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be terrible to have a football team practice for 20
years and not ever play a game. She's getting ready for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
