</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RTBEERFLOAT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: This is part of a three-take package. The others 
 are ROOTBEER and RTBEERFACTS. This take is composed of How to 
 Make a Great Root Beer Float and recipes from the San Francisco 
 restaurant Aqua.  
   
   
 HOW TO MAKE A GREAT ROOT BEER FLOAT  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  To find out how to make a great root beer float,
we went to two experts: the chef at Aqua, a San Francisco
restaurant renowned for sophisticated food and decor, and the owner
of an A&AMP;W restaurant in Lodi, home of the nation's first A&AMP;W root
beer stand.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Aqua, a decidedly upscale root beer float is a signature
dessert. Chefs layer small scoops of house-made root beer sorbet
and sassafras-flavored vanilla ice cream, then pour on Thomas
Kemper root beer. A crisp chocolate wafer and two chocolate straws
top it off. The $8 dessert is served with two homey, warm chocolate
chip cookies.
</P>
<P>
   In Lodi, &UR;  &LR; Peter Knight takes a simpler approach. Knight owns the
A&AMP;W in the town where the nation's first A&AMP;W root beer stand opened
in 1919. Knight started working for A&AMP;W in 1972 and figures he's
poured more than a couple of million floats.
</P>
<P>
   He starts with an ice-cold frosted mug right from the freezer.
He pours the root beer first, down the side of the glass to prevent
building up too much foam, then adds a scoop or two of locally made
butterfat-rich vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   The key is the ice cream, he says. ``Refrain from using a cheap
ice cream. It won't stand up to the sweetness and the vanilla of
the root beer.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;W, the nation's top-selling root beer, has a wintergreen kick
and is not as heavy with vanilla or honey flavors as some of the
gourmet brands. The crispness provides a sharp counterpoint for the
ice cream, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The balance between ice cream and root beer is the key at Aqua,
too. Chef Michael Mina and pastry chef Jason Gingold tasted several
root beers before deciding on Thomas Kemper, made by Pyramid
Brewery in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too sweet,'' Mina says. ``Sometimes root beer can be
too sharp or too sweet, like a cream soda.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternating scoops of sorbet and sassafras-flavored ice
cream based on creme anglaise provide contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the mix is hard to duplicate at home. The root
beer syrup used in the Aqua's sorbet is a commercial product,
unavailable to consumers. In testing the accompanying recipe, we
used Torani root beer syrup, which will be in markets next month.
But with this syrup, the sorbet takes a long time to freeze. An
alternative is to eliminate the sorbet entirely. That's not true to
the Aqua recipe, but we found that the rich ice cream and the root
beer alone made an outstanding float.
</P>
<P>
   Knight offers one last suggestion for enjoying a float: Allow it
to sit for two or three minutes. ``It lets the ice cream melt and
the root beer freeze a little around the ice cream. When the ice
cream just melts into the root beer, that's when you get that
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, by the way, will test his float making skills on a grand
scale June 19 in Lodi when he and his crew attempt to make the
world's biggest float.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kemper Brewing Co. set the record in 1996, with a
2,166-gallon concoction. To smash the record, Knight will mix 400
gallons of ice cream and 2,100 gallons of root beer in a wine vat
during a daylong celebration. The float is expected to serve more
than 20,000 people. The event is free.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aqua, 252 California St. (at Battery), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 956-9662. Lodi A&AMP;W, 216 E. Lodi Ave., Lodi; (209) 368-8548. &LR;   &LR; Find
Knight's A&AMP;W Web site at  &LR; www.awrootbeer.com &LR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; AQUA'S ROOT BEER FLOAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kemper root beer
</P>
<P>
   Sassafras Ice Cream (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Root Beer sorbet (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   For each serving, pour 2 ounces of root beer into a chilled
pilsner glass or ice cream-float glass. Add alternating scoops of
Sassafras Ice Cream and Root Beer Sorbet to fill glass. Carefully
add more root beer.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with Chocolate Chip Cookies (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Nutrition analysis not possible because of general nature of &LR; 
 &LR; recipe. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SASSAFRAS ICE CREAM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vodka
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sassafras powder, or gumbo fil &LR; e &LR;
</P>
<P>
   14 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cream, milk, sugar, vanilla, vodka and sassafras
powder (or fil &LR; e &LR; ) in a saucepan; bring to a boil. Remove from
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg yolks in a bowl; stir in about one third of the hot
cream mixture, then whisk this into the remaining hot cream
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Strain through a fine mesh sieve into a bowl. To chill quickly,
place the bowl into a larger bowl of ice and water. Or, cover and
refrigerate overnight. When chilled, process in an ice-cream maker
according to manufacturer's directions.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER 1/2 CUP: &LR;   &LR; 655 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 31 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 55 g fat (32 g saturated), 540 mg cholesterol, 89 mg sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ROOT BEER SORBET &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups simple syrup (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups root beer syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mix all ingredients together. Process in an ice cream maker
according to manufacturer's directions. Note that the sorbet may
take longer than normal to freeze.
</P>
<P>
   An alternate method is to make a form of granita, which requires
freezing the sorbet base in a shallow metal pan in a 0-freezer.
After 1 hour, mix thoroughly with the tines of a fork, then mix
again every 15 minutes for up to 2 hours. Allow the mixture to
freeze overnight before using.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; To make simple syrup, mix together 3 cups sugar and 3
cups water in a saucepan. Heat over low heat until the sugar has
melted. Cool to room temperature before using. Store leftover syrup
in a covered jar in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER 1/2 CUP: &LR;   &LR; 290 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 g protein, 75 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 0 g fat (0 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 69 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 0 g fiber.  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces butter (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   1 pound chocolate, shaved or chopped (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, cream together the butter, granulated
sugar and brown sugar until the mixture is creamy and light in
color. Add the eggs, one at a time, beating well (high speed) after
each addition.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce mixer speed to low and blend in the vanilla. Add the
flour and baking soda and blend, scraping down sides of bowl from
time to time. Add the nuts and chocolate; mix thoroughly, then
scrape down the bowl and mix again.
</P>
<P>
   Scoop out 1-inch balls of dough and place on a baking sheet.
Refrigerate for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the scoops of dough to parchment-lined baking sheets,
spacing them 2 inches apart. Press down on each firmly.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 13 to 16 minutes, or until edges are slightly firm.
Immediately remove from pan to wire racks to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 20-24 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note &LR; : Jason Gingold of Aqua uses bittersweet chocolate
shavings or chunks, but miniature bittersweet chocolate chips may
be substituted.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 240 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 25 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 15 g fat (7 g saturated), 38 mg cholesterol, 83 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
