<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-ROOT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 
 &HT;     EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel
of 
 professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.    TASTER'S CHOICE: Root Beers Branch Out Too Much in Flavor  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Microbrew root beer may be the latest trend in
beverages. We found several brews on local store shelves and
decided we should get the tasting panel's opinion.
<P>
   We chose only root beer bottled in glass; canned root beer has
more carbonation, which interferes with flavors. We included the
relatively large producer IBC because it's bottled rather than
canned. (We did not choose any brands in the 1-liter plastic
bottles.)
</P>
<P>
   The root beers varied in price by as much as $2 per carton, but
not all of the most expensive brands fared particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   While the panel liked a couple of the beverages, overall they
found many of the root beers too odd with strange flavor components
like maple and star anise.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's favorite was  &UR; Thomas Kemper &LR;  (six 12-ounce bottles,
$4.59 at Andronico's). One panelist described it as ``a
well-rounded root beer'' and especially liked the sweet, spicy
flavors. All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Stewart's &LR;  (four 12-ounce bottles,
$3.19-$3.39 at many supermarkets). Three panelists commented on the
thin flavor, but another thought it epitomized a root beer. Others
liked the carbonation. Three would buy it; two might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IBC &LR;  (six 12-ounce bottles, $3.29-$3.59 at many supermarkets)
came in third. One panelist thought the flavors were complex but
balanced; another found the finish bitter. Others thought the
beverage tasted too heavily of sarsaparilla. Two would buy it, two
might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scores dropped dramatically down to fourth place, which went to
 &UR; Henry Weinhard's  &LR; (six 12-ounce bottles, $4.59-$4.99 at many
supermarkets). The panelists found the honey overpowering and
thought the root beer was too sweet overall. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Journey, Boylan Bottleworks, Natural Brew, Virgil's and
Tommyknocker scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia
Hart, dietitian and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For
All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
