<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but 
 the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is 
 enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff 
 aims to change that. This regular round-up column will make 
 practical sense of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as 
 well as offering offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food 
 news to put on your plate. 
 &HT;       
   
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: California Artichoke Crop Is Best in Years  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO  &LR; _ Artichokes are the big news this week. Growers and
produce brokers are nearly beside themselves because the California
crop of Green Globes is the best the state has seen in four years.
<P>
   ``We're awash in artichokes,'' says Andy Powning of GreenLeaf, a
San Francisco produce supplier. ``There was a lot of rain and some
frost, but the (artichokes) which were affected by the early April
frost are picked. They're gone. Now, we're into a really good
season for 'chokes.''
</P>
<P>
   A good supply means cheaper prices and better quality. At area
greengrocers this week, most large artichokes are selling for just
under a dollar. Prices range from 79 cents at Berkeley Bowl to
$1.39 at Andronico's in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A string of exceptionally wet years since 1995 had drowned
plants and devasted the state's $49 million annual crop, but this
year promises a complete turnaround, says Pat Hopper of Ocean Mist
Farms, the biggest producer in Castroville, Calif., with 4,000
acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the artichokes this year is super,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But artichoke growers and sellers say the crop took longer than
usual to get to marketable size and shape because it had to endure
a cold March and frosts in early April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year it seemed to go from winter to summer with about an
inch of spring in between,'' GreenLeaf's Powning says. ``We had the
coldest March of the decade. What happens with that is, even though
the growing days get longer, plants grow slowly. Now it's hot, so
they're bursting.''
</P>
<P>
   While things are looking good in Monterey County, Half Moon Bay
in San Mateo County is a little slower to recover. Farmers report
December's freeze, excessive rain and lingering effects of El
Ni &LR; n &LR; o have set them back. Earlier this month, Giusti Farms in Half
Moon Bay reported packing only a quarter of what normally is
harvested in April.
</P>
<P>
   But San Mateo County's overall contribution to California's
artichoke crop is small _ less than 450 acres out of a statewide
total of about 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; The Egg Returns &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and order an egg for breakfast. And if you hold the
bacon, you don't have to feel guilty about it.
</P>
<P>
   A study of more than 100,000 healthy individuals shows an egg a
day doesn't appear to increase your chances for heart disease or
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published April 21 in the Journal of the American
Medical Association, concludes that nutrients and so-called good
cholesterol _ high-density lipoproteins _ in eggs probably offsets
the bad cholesterol, called low-density lipoprotein.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for egg lovers who may have been pining since
eggs took on a reputation for being cholesterol bombs and were
banned from the diets of people prone to or suffering from heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent past, the public has been advised to keep
cholesterol intake to 300 milligrams a day. An egg contains 213
milligrams and about 75 calories. But the study shows the two sorts
of cholesterol in eggs likely balance each other, and antioxidants,
folates, B vitamins and unsaturated fat in eggs can be beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your diet is balanced, you don't have to avoid eggs and can
even include them in your diet,'' says Dr. Frank Hu of the Harvard
School of Public Health, the study's author.
</P>
<P>
   The study, based on information taken from two larger ongoing
studies, is notable for its scope. It includes statistics drawn
from 80,000 nurses in 11 states who have been reporting their
health status and living habits since 1976. The other group
includes 37,000 male health professionals who have been followed
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Heart disease prevention should focus on reducing the intake of
saturated fat, Hu says. That includes the kind that remains solid
at room temperature, such as butter, palm oil and fat found in
animal products like bacon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
