<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers, 
 anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary 
 wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field 
 to forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients 
 stocking our larders. As a bonus, Georgeanne Brennan will offer 
 tips for using the bounty in fresh, innovative ways.  
   
   
   
   
 AT THE SOURCE: No Missing Links in Sausage Maker's Repertory  
   
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 NAPA VALLEY, Calif.  _ Don't tell Gerhard Twele any wurst/worst
jokes. The German-born Napa Valley sausage maker has heard them
all.
 &HT;    In fact, before he acquired his company, it had been known as
The Wurst Place, which Twele and his American wife, Nancy, thought
was a little too corny. So they opted for his given name plus the
Napa Valley designation _ Gerhard's Napa Valley Sausage _ which has
just a little more culinary cachet.
 &HT;    Not that Twele has abandoned the bratwursts and other sausages
he learned to make as a teenage apprentice in the small Rhine
Valley town of Mittelheim, but he has expanded his repertoire
beyond these traditionals.
 &HT;    Trained in Europe as a chef and restaurateur as well as a
sausage maker, Twele roamed the world as a merchant marine cook and
a land-locked chef in kitchens from Paris to the Cote d'Azur,
Montreal, San Diego and the Napa Valley.
 &HT;    In Napa in 1985, the Tweles saw a niche to be filled: sausages
leaner and less artery-clogging than the conventional products
while still offering the same strapping, hearty appeal.
 &HT;    Working from a tiny Yountville kitchen, Gerhard Twele developed
sausages with all the time-honored herbs and spices but based on
lean poultry rather than fatty meats. He compensated for the
moisture lost by adding apples, cranberries and vegetables to the
mix.
 &HT;    Eventually, Twele started incorporating Asian and Mediterranean
flavors and added other pork, beef and lamb products (brandied
chorizo, fresh bratwurst, mild and hot Italian sausages and Syrian
lamb sausage), although always with low fat content.
 &HT;    As the menu expanded, so did the business. His Yountville
kitchen, reportedly the smallest establishment ever approved by the
U.S. Department of Agriculture for wholesale production, finally
gave way to a large facility in an industrial park on the edge of
Napa (he retained the Yountville place as retail showcase for some
years). Even the new facility keeps expanding _ most recently to
27,000 square feet _ and the original 400-pounds-a-week output has
grown to more than 50,000 pounds.
 &HT;    In the '80s, Gerhard's sausages were sold to restaurants and
specialty stores. Today, they are found in meat counters at Lucky
stores, Albertson's, Cala, Vallergas, Bell and Trader Joe's
markets, as well as some tony stores on the East Coast (Sutton
Place and New York's Dean&AMP;Deluca, although not at that firm's St.
Helena branch).
 &HT;    The all-natural chicken sausages are still Gerhard's biggest
draw, with chicken/basil/pine nuts giving the original
chicken/apple sausage competition for first place.
 &HT;    Success has not gone to the genial sausage maker's head. He
still supervises everything from the purchase and storage of
ingredients to the mixing of spices, and is a stickler for quality
control.
 &HT;    Like his zesty products, his business philosophy is a blend of
New World know-how and Old Country principles. On the one hand, he
explains his ever-expanding repertoire by saying one has to go with
the times. On the other, he says the secret to success in business
is to ``service even your smallest account as if it were your
largest.''
 &HT;     
 
 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) 
 
 A Sausage for Every Reason  
  
Traditionally, Americans think of sausage as breakfast food or
picnic fare. &HT;    Sophisticated sausages, like those produced by Gerhard's Napa
Valley Sausage, go beyond that. They can fill the bill for just
about any meal and course _ except dessert. Nothing wrong with
serving them for breakfast, of course, but they are equally good as
appetizers and as lunch or dinner entrees.
 &HT;    The packaged sausages have heating instructions. Smoked, fully
cooked sausages can be simply warmed by placing them in barely
simmering water for 10 minutes, or they can be barbecued, fried,
grilled or sauteed. Small fresh sausages can be browned directly in
a nonstick pan with a little oil. Large ones are best when poached
in water, broth or wine, then browned lightly.
 &HT;    Sausages are a must in Alsatian choucroute garni _ try smoked
duck sausage for a taste adventure. Brandied smoked chorizo is
perfect in paella; lamb sausage pairs well with pilaf; chicken with
habaneros and tequila makes great taco and enchilada fillings, and
just about any sausage can lend character to pizzas and pastas _ as
in a hot Italian sausage for a tomato sauce or a chicken sausage
with basil and pine nuts for an alfredo-type sauce.
 &HT;    Needless to say, bratwurst is a natural with red cabbage and
fried potatoes, and smoked Bavarian beerwurst pairs happily with
crusty bread or a German potato salad _ an ice-cold beer doesn't
hurt, either.
 &HT;    Sausage maker Gerhard Twele, who is also a professional chef,
recommends a simple but sophisticated appetizer: Poach curried
chicken sausages in white wine, place them on sheets of phyllo
large enough to enclose each sausage, top with a teaspoon of
chutney, wrap and bake at 375 degrees until golden. Cut sausages
into serving-size pieces.
 &HT;    For a picnic treat, wrap any blanched sausage (chicken Provencal
with leeks would be perfect) in brioche dough and bake at 400
degrees until the bread is done. Cool on a rack. To serve, cut into
thick slices and serve with a couple of interesting mustards.
 &HT;     
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) 
 
 
 GEORGEANNE'S KITCHEN: The All-Too-Versatile Wurst  
   
   
 By Geeorgeanne Brennan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  The selection of sausages available these days
seems limitless, making sausages a more versatile ingredient than
ever. Herbs, spices and all types of meat are fitted into casings
and served up alongside or with aromatic rice, beans and sauces.
<P>
   &UR; Saffron Jambalaya &LR; . Warm a little olive oil in a saucepan and
add 1/4 cup chopped onion, 1 chopped garlic clove, a generous pinch
of saffron threads, a cinnamon stick and 1 tablespoon slivered
almonds. Stir together until fragrant, and add 1 cup basmati rice
and mix. Stir in 1 tablespoon tomato paste, 1 cup chicken broth, 1
cup water, 1/4 cup coarsely chopped dried apricots, 1/4 cup
raisins, salt to taste and 2 chicken-apple (or other fruit blended)
sausage, cut into 1-inch rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a boil, reduce heat to low, cover and simmer about 20
minutes, or until the liquid is fully absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   For a little spiciness, add a coarsely chopped Thai or other
small chile.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Baked Sausage-Filled Cherry Tomatoes.  &LR; Gently trim the tops
from 1 pint cherry tomatoes and scoop out the seeds. Remove the
casing from 1 spicy Italian sausage and spoon a small amount of the
meat into each tomato, mounding it slightly at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Place the tomatoes in a foil-lined baking dish just large enough
to hold them comfortably. Bake in a 400 oven until the juice from
the sausage runs clear, about 25 minutes. Serve as a snack or hors
d'oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rigatoni with Tomato, Olive and Sausage Sauce. &LR;  Warm a little
olive oil in a saute pan; add 1 coarsely chopped garlic clove and
cook, stirring, until fragrant. Add 2 cups diced fresh or canned
tomatoes, freshly ground pepper, 1 tablespoon fresh rosemary
needles, 1 teaspoon fresh thyme, a few pitted black olives and 2
fennel-seasoned sausages, cut into 1/2-inch rounds. Stir together,
cover and cook over low heat until the sausages are done, about 25
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve over rigatoni pasta and sprinkle with freshly grated
Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rosemary-Seasoned Cannellini Beans &LR; . Soak 2 cups cannellini
beans overnight in water. The following day, drain the beans and
place in a large soup pot with 2 or 3 fresh Italian bay leaves and
a bunch of 5 or 6 rosemary sprigs, which have been tied together.
Add 3 cups chicken broth and 3 cups water. Bring to a boil, reduce
heat to low and simmer, salting the beans as they begin to soften.
Cook until very tender but not falling apart, about 11/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with charcoal-grilled sausages and a green salad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roasted Pepper, Zucchini and Sausage Stuffing &LR; . Soak 3 slices
bread in a little milk, then squeeze dry.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together 1 cup coarsely chopped roasted red peppers (about
3 large peppers), 1 pound sausage (casings removed), 1 cup coarsely
chopped zucchini, and salt and pepper to taste. Add the milk-soaked
bread and some chopped Italian parsley. Mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the mixture to a baking dish. Do not spread the mixture
too thinly or it will dry out. Bake in a 400-degree oven until it
just begins to pull away from the sides of the dish and the juices
run clear.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with roasted potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Georgeanne Brennan, a food and garden writer who lives in &LR; 
 &LR; Yolo County, Calif., is the author of ``Aperitif'' and ``The &LR; 
 &LR; Food and Flavors of Haute Provence.' &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; ' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
