</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 
   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles
food-related  businesses more than a half-century old.   BAY AREA CLASSICS: DiMaggio Ate Dinner Here  
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  In the days of Seals Stadium, the nearby Double
Play restaurant and bar on Potrero Hill was a stomping ground for
drinking, smoking and baseball fever.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Joe DiMaggio, Dario Lodigiani, Bobby Layne, Doak Walker _ they
were all in here,'' says Gigi Fiorucci, who bought the Double Play
in 1989 and recalls the sports figures who hung out there when
Seals and Kezar stadiums were home bases for San Francisco sports.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out the front window, he repeats a story that's made
the rounds: ``In the '30s, the ball players would come over here
between innings, get a shot and go back.'' It was an easy play.
Situated kitty-corner from where Seals Stadium once stood, the run
to Double Play was about the distance from first to second base.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fiorucci and Don Russo, a San Francisco firefighter
and baseball-loving friend who grew up near Seals Stadium, Double
Play was opened as a bar in 1909 when Potrero Hill was a commercial
neighborhood dominated by factories. It acquired its baseball-savvy
name after the sports-loving Stanfel family bought it in 1937.
(Dick Stanfel, a son, went on to professional football as a guard
for the Detroit Lions.)
</P>
<P>
   The Stanfels sold the Double Play in the mid-'80s to a group of
partners. Shortly after the sale, a fire broke out, and Double Play
was closed for about 11/2 years. When it reopened, the owners had
expanded the tiny bar and had added a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Double Play is a three-room restaurant-bar filled with
sports memorabilia and old timers who relive sports stories over a
hearty breakfast. The top of the Seals Stadium flagpole hangs over
the bar and every inch of wall space is crammed with sports photos
and baseball mitts, some from professional players.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorucci, a restaurateur who had owned several restaurants in
the city including Maye's Oyster House, was attracted to the Double
Play because it was smaller than his other restaurants and he
wanted to slow down. ``Thirty five years of split shifts,'' he says
in a voice that claims, ``Enough!''
</P>
<P>
   All too familiar with the parking headaches in San Francisco,
Fiorucci says its adjacent parking lot was another reason he bought
Double Play. But he didn't leave the lot entirely to cars. In the
early '90s, he turned a 20-by-60-foot space of it into a dining
room _ ``Seals Stadium'' _ where every wall features a mural that
depicts fans cramming the bleachers. ``We want to rename the room
`Joe DiMaggio Stadium,' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fiorucci likes his work schedule as it is now _
serving breakfast and lunch weekdays, with the bar open until 8
p.m. if the restaurant isn't booked for a private party. Otherwise,
evenings and weekends are devoted to private banquets.
</P>
<P>
   And he's training his son, Gino, in the business. ``I'm going to
be a bum,'' Fiorucci says, ``and take a sabbatical.'' Still, it
will be hard to leave the Double Play, he says. ``This is the only
landmark left from Seals Stadium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
