<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A CHANCE TO SEE THE BIG BEND FROM A CAMEL'S BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been many uncommon sights on the high desert of the
Big Bend _ curanderos packing their medicinal plants, mountain
lions seeking their prey, and chili fiends heading for the
Terlingua cook-offs. The latter is perhaps the scariest of the
three.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there will be another. This summer, those who have often
wondered what Big Bend Ranch State Park might look like from atop a
camel's back will get a chance to see firsthand. The Texas Camel
Corps will begin two-day treks through the rugged, scenic southwest
Texas park in July.
</P>
<P>
   Camels, believe it or not, have a history in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp Verde General Store on Texas 173 south of Kerrville is
all that remains of Camp Verde, a one-time Army post that was home
to the 34 camels and the 12 Armenian drivers and their families who
arrived there in 1856.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment was the idea of U.S. Sen. Jefferson Davis of
Mississippi. When Davis became secretary of war in 1855, Congress
appropriated $30,000 for the training of soldiers to use camels for
carrying supplies and for exploring new territories between El Paso
and the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   The camels, obtained in North Africa, landed at Indianola, near
Port Lavaca, in April 1856. They were then delivered to Camp Verde.
It was to be their permanent base, but the soldiers never came to
adore the camels the way the Cavalry embraced its horses. The
soldiers complained that the camels held grudges, sometimes waiting
for weeks to exact their revenge by kicking or spitting.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Civil War broke out and interest in the camels was
lost. The fort eventually was abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were camels in the area that is now Big Bend Ranch State
Park,'' said David Alloway, a park naturalist. ``In 1859 and 1860,
the Big Bend region was explored by a group of cameleers under Lt.
William Echols.''
</P>
<P>
   Echols had the job of mapping the unexplored region and to test
the camels' usefulness in the rugged terrain. There were also
camels in the Big Bend last year, when the Odyssey Exploration
Society from Calgary, Alberta, trained for a 900-mile camel trek
across Arabia's Empty Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Vision Quest, a youth rehabilitation organization,
held a camel trek on the ranch. Vision Quest moved on to Arizona
this year, but the camels and their trainer, Doug Baum, stayed
behind to establish a tour business in Big Bend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the treks here at Big Bend Ranch State Park will
be more than six to eight miles a day,'' Alloway said. ``It's hard
to find tough camels any more and it hard to find tough people to
ride them.''
</P>
<P>
   Alloway said the most difficult aspect of the ride is getting
used to the height and the constant sway of the camels.
</P>
<P>
   ``These camels are very gentle; it's just an odd sensation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day safaris are scheduled for July 24-25, July 31-Aug.
1, Aug. 7-8, Sept. 18-19 and Sept. 25-26. The trips are limited to
six people and cost $650 per person, which includes park fees,
guides, lodging and meals.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available from Big Bend Ranch State Park,
(915) 229-3416.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column about Texas. You can call
him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: Artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
