<HEADLINE>
PIZZERIA UNO PONDERS THE ROAD AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thank God a slice of pizza can be reheated within a matter of
minutes. Some things don't work that way.
</P>
<P>
   Public shares of local Italian eateries, hot investments in the
early 1990s, went cold years ago and stayed that way even as
business improved.
</P>
<P>
   Now the last of three leading Massachusetts companies, Uno
Restaurant Corp., has formed a committee of outside directors and
hired investment bankers for advice on how to get out of its stock
rut. The usual options: sell the company or organize a leveraged
buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Spencer, the chairman of Uno and owner of a 61 percent
interest in the Boston company, filed documents Monday saying he
was consulting a financial adviser and might propose a merger or
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of moribund stock activity was what drove
Bertucci's Inc. founder Joey Crugnale to make an offer for his
company's public stock last year, a bid that was later topped by
another private investor group.
</P>
<P>
   Then Charlie Sarkis took his Back Bay Restaurant Group private
in a $38 million deal that was completed just three weeks ago. Back
Bay Restaurant Group, based in Boston, owns the Papa-Razzi chain
and other restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Uno has hired BancBoston Robertson Stephens to consider the
company's options and report to three outside directors, including
former Boston Edison chief Stephen Sweeney and former Chelsea
receiver James Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   Uno shares have been stuck in a price band of $6 to $8 per share
for the last three years. The company itself has rebounded from
problems in the mid-1990s, posting an 85 percent earnings gain in
the most recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Uno shares a small value-oriented investment, far out
of style in a market focused on large growth companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``For small, nontechnical companies with no research coverage,
this just isn't their world,'' said Tom Spiro of Spiro Capital
Management Inc., a small New York investment firm that owns Uno
shares. ``I'm not complaining, I think they're doing all the right
things. If it was Uno.com, the circumstances might be very
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer portrays Uno in a similar light, a little stock ignored
in a big-stock world. ``We're a small-cap stock, small is even too
big a word,'' he said. ``We're just little guys and presently this
market is not paying attention to little guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Uno has been a consistent buyer of its own stock under
repurchase programs. Spencer said current prices make the
investment in Uno stock similar to that of opening a new store, in
the range of four times earnings before interest, depreciation,
taxes and amortization.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer bristles at the idea of being lumped together with
companies that stumbled and later went private, though Uno too has
managed through problems.
</P>
<P>
   But the experiences of investors who have owned shares of Uno,
Bertucci and Back Bay Restaurant Group illustrate the power and
occasional excesses of the system that pumps capital into American
companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the decade, investment bankers sold their
customers on the concept of restaurant stocks on a scale never seen
before and raised hundreds of millions of dollars. All those
companies had to expand to put their new capital to work and meet
new growth expectations from Wall Street, roughly at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   They were the ``story'' stocks of the moment, sold on similar
investment themes.
</P>
<P>
   Some stumbled as they tried to grow. Others simply found it hard
to build business as they were competing against a crowd of other,
newly public restaurant companies.
</P>
<P>
   The market had discovered a small industry, pumped too much
money into too many stocks and then abandoned the survivors once
they disappoined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small capitalization restaurants, existing stories without any
kind of fashion sizzle, are just of no interest to anyone,'' said
analyst Bret Jordan of Advest Inc. ``They only way they can
recognize any value is the leveraged buyout or to sell to someone
else buildling a conglomerate of restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it is a cycle that appears to be starting anew, just
as Uno employs financial advisers because investors seem
uninterested in bidding up its public shares.
</P>
<P>
   Buca Inc., operator of a Minneapolis-based chain of Italian
restaurants, launched a $36 million initial public stock offering
last week. The shares, priced at 12, jumped to 18 1/4 in their
first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   P.F. Chang's China Bistro Inc. of Phoneix went public in
December at 12 per share. It finished at 25 1/4 Monday. On deck:
Rubio's Restaurants Inc. of Carlsbad, Calif., considered a hot IPO
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   More will surely follow. The question: how many will be
pondering their own moves to go private a few years from now?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
