<HEADLINE>
BRAEKFAST TRADITION THERE FOR THE TRAVELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditions are one of the more enjoyable aspects of Discovering
America.
</P>
<P>
   One tasty tradition to discover is right in our own New England
backyard _ the May breakfasts of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   The May Breakfasts have become a rite of spring and can be found
in 21 communities in the tiny state. And wherever you go, more than
likely the traditional Rhode Island johnnycake will be on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition began 132 years ago at the Oak Lawn Community
Baptish Church in Cranston as a fundraiser and will again be served
up May 1 by Quaker-costumed hostesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some 25,000 people are expected to participate in one of the
feasts that include fried or scrambled eggs, ham, bacon, baked
beans, muffins, juice, coffee, tea, and milk as well as the
johnnycake.
</P>
<P>
   The johnnycake is derived from an Indian recipe using flint
corn, a variety of hard-kernel corn that thrives in the fog and
salt air of the Ocean State. Early settlers stuffed the small, hard
cakes called ``journeycakes'' into their pockets or saddlebags for
sustenance on long trips, and now when people think of johnnycake,
they think of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   While most breakfasts are held on May 1, others are on May 4,
Rhode Island's Independence Day. Still others will hold their May
Breakfast on April 30, and May 2, 3, 7, 8, and 16. Besides churches
the breakfasts also are held by Rotary Clubs, volunteer fire
associations, and even the Norman Bird Sanctuary (the 11th annual
May Birds and Breakfast on May 16).
</P>
<P>
   For locations, times, and prices, call the Rhode Island Economic
Development Corp. at 800-556-2484.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Virginia for lovers
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, the ``Virginia is for lovers'' travel slogan has
encouraged visitors to discover all there is to love about
Virginia. The slogan has become the longest-running and one of the
most recognized state slogans. To celebrate the anniversary the
state has two sweepstakes with monthly drawings for prizes. One is
the `` `Virginia is for lovers' If You Were Born in 1969
Sweepstakes'' and the other is ``Fall in Love with Virginia
Sweepstakes.'' To enter either contest, go to the Visit Virginia
Website at www.VIRGINIA.org and click on the contest icon. For a
travel guide to the state, call 800-932-5827. By the way, do you
remember any other slogans from '69? Among them were ``It's the
Real Thing,'' ``The Big Mac,'' ``The Silent Majority,'' and ``One
Giant Leap for Mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Spectacular scenery
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Skamania and Klickitat counties in Washington state
are not on most people's destination list. But, since most people
want great scenery, maybe these counties should be. This is the
Columbia River Gorge National Scenic Area, the only place in
America that has been designated by Congress as a ``National Scenic
Area.'' And, there's a lot more to do then just take in the
scenery. To learn more, call the Skamania County Chamber of
Commerce at 800-989-9178 or on the Internet at
www.klickitatcounty.org or www.skamania.org. The area is just 45
minutes from Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Books to discover
</P>
<P>
   ``America's National Historic Trails'' by Kathleen Ann Cordes
(University of Oklahoma Press, $19.95) offers a guide to 12
National Historic Trails ranging from the paths of Lewis and Clark
to those of Civil Rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survival Skills of the North American Indians'' by Peter
Goodchild (Chicago Review Press, $16.95) covers everything from
preparing plant foods and medicines to crafting tools and clothing.
With all the concerns for the Y2K bug, Goodchild's rediscovery of
the ancient arts that sustained the first Americans provides some
good lessons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Volunteer
</P>
<P>
   Another way to discover America is to volunteer some community
service rather than spend time on a more traditional summer
vacation. Global Volunteers has projects ranging from creating a
playground for Indian children in Montana, to helping at a Florida
homeless shelter, or building homes in various communities. The
programs cost $450 and cover food and lodging. Transportation to
the site is extra. Programs are also available for families, and
youths 16 and older. For information, call 800-487-1074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deal
</P>
<P>
   Grand Circle Travel has cut the price on its Danube &AMP; Eastern
Europe river cruise departing May 24 by 40 percent. The 15-day
river cruise has been reduced from $2,995 to $1,800 a person,
including air fare from Boston or New York. For information, call
800-955-1034 and refer to code ABDN365 when calling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coffee milk?
</P>
<P>
   Coffee syrup, the key ingredient in coffee milk, Rhode Island's
official state drink, is now available in nostalgic souvenir-size
bottles. The Blackstone Valley Tourism Council is offering
four-ounce bottles of the syrup as a way to raise funds for the
British canal boat being built in England for the Blackstone
Valley. The canal boat will be used for tours of the Blackstone
River. ``Coffee milk is important to every Rhode Islander,'' said
Robert Billington, president of the tourism council. ``This is a
wonderful way for those not familiar with coffee syrup to sample
its many uses. It's best enjoyed mixed with milk, or as an ice
cream topping.'' The syrup is made by Autocrat Coffee, based in the
Blackstone Valley of Rhode Island. Bottles are $2 and can be
obtained by calling 401-724-2200 or stopping by the Visitor Center
at 171 Main St., Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tiffany exhibit
</P>
<P>
   ``Brilliant Ideas: The Designs of Louis Comfort Tiffany'' will
be on display at the Mark Twain House National Historic Landmark in
Hartford through June 1, 2000. The exhibit features Tiffany pieces
from exquisite lamps and vases to stained glass. The Twain house,
where Samuel Clemens (better known as Mark Twain) lived, was
redecorated in 1881 by Tiffany's firm and is the only
Tiffany-designed interior open to the public. The Tiffany exhibit
in the museum's Visitor Center is free. Admission to the house is
$9 for adults, $8 for seniors, and $5 for children ages 6 through
12. For information, call 860-247-0998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hot destinations
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Las Vegas will be the hottest single destinations for
tours and packages, according to a survey by the United States Tour
Operators Association. On a regional basis, Europe ranked first
internationally, followed by Australia/South Pacific and Asia. For
the fifth year in a row, Italy reigned as the hottest selling
single country worldwide. Tied for second place were China,
Australia, and Spain. Domestically, for the first time Las Vegas
came out on top, unseating perennial favorite Orlando, Fla., which
placed second. The USTOA survey also found that a continued strong
US dollar would have a favorable impact for US travelers to Canada
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dialysis center
</P>
<P>
   The Half Moon Golf, Tennis &AMP; Beach Club has added a dialysis
center to its medical diagnostic facility. The resort is in Montego
Bay, Jamaica. The facility offers patients needing dialysis the
opportunity of a Caribbean vacation while maintaining treatments.
Treatments are $300 each. For information, call 800-408-6031.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean music
</P>
<P>
   The Puerto Rico JazzFest, featuring talents such as the
Manhattan Transfer, the Rippingtons, and the Jazz Messengers, along
with performers Poncho Sanchez and Elaine Elias, will be held June
10-13. For information on Puerto Rico, call 800-866-7827.
</P>
<P>
   Grenada's second annual Spice Jazz Festival will be held May
20-23. Grenada's sister island, Carriacou, will salute the event
with a special program May 24. For island information, call
800-927-9554.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Ocho Rios Jazz Festival in Jamaica is set for June
12-20. Top performers have been booked, including the legendary
jazz pianist Monty Alexander. For more information, call the Jazz
Center at 876-927-3544 or the Jamaica Tourist Board at 800-JAMAICA.
</P>
</TEXT>
