<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SEDONA-BOS &LR;      04-27 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SEDONA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WELCOME SIDE TRIP IN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ It was an unlikely, isolated stop on our
cross-country journey, far off the East-West interstates, almost to
the Left Coast, with a reputation for New Age kookiness.
</P>
<P>
   But in our five years living out West during the 1980s, the town
of Sedona had topped the list of highly-recommended places we never
quite got to. The photo editor at the Denver newspaper that
employed me was a sybaritic marvel: the kind of guy who always knew
the name of the great new French restaurant in Provo, Utah. And
Sedona, he told us, was not to be missed.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, we discovered the old photo dog was right. When
a research trip took me (and my 15-year-old daughter/research
assistant) on a coast-to-coast tour of archives and libraries, I
recalled his advice and planned a break at the ``midway'' point to
explore Arizona's red rock country. We found solitude and comfort,
an increasingly rare combination in today's West.
</P>
<P>
   After crossing Texas and New Mexico, we picked up my wife and
10-year-old son at the Phoenix airport and pointed our now worn and
dirty station wagon north on Interstate 17, for the 120-mile ride
to Sedona. The northern Arizona scenery was immediately rewarding,
with forests of saguaro and stark lunar ranges as we gradually
climbed from the 110-degree heat of the central Arizona basin to
the mile-high rim of the Colorado Plateau. The temperature,
thankfully, dropped 30 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sedona's location on the Mogollon Rim of the enormous plateau _
it is the same massive geologic formation through which the
Colorado River has carved the Grand Canyon _ gives it four mild
seasons and a climate that is, on the average, some 20 degrees
cooler in summer than Phoenix or Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneers and prospectors arrived here in the early 1800s, but
two Pennsylvania Dutch settlers gave Sedona its name. Theodore
Schnebly arrived in 1901 and planned to open the first post office
at the place he called Schnebly Station. His brother suggested that
Theodore's wife Sedona had a name better suited for the beautiful
natural surroundings, thus saving the town from an incongruous fate
as Schnebly, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Geographic and geologic placement give Sedona its spectacular,
signature red rock formations, which were formed as wind and water
shaved the sandstone and limestone edges of the Mogollon Rim. As we
drove into town we identified the red bluffs and spires by name:
Cockscomb, Chimney Rock, Coffee Pot, Bell Rock, Steamboat Rock,
Elephant Rock, Courthouse Butte. The magnificent Cathedral Rock,
which towers over Oak Creek, is one of the West's most scenic
sites. My son was delighted by Snoopy Rock, which unquestionably
resembles the cartoon hero asleep on his doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   Sedona is a dispersed 16,000-soul community of tiny resorts,
vacation homes and modest shopping centers where a small collection
of New Age hippies mingles with retirees, artists, writers, and
outdoors enthusiasts. A shortage of water and privately-owned land
has preserved the town from the curse of development. Surrounded by
the Coconino National Forest, Sedona has but 15 square miles of
private property. We arrived on a three-day holiday weekend, and
found the Y intersection that serves as the center of town jammed
with traffic. But then the work week drew the crowds back to
Phoenix, and left the place with its trademark laid-back feel.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet search had provided us a home for the week: the
terrific Junipine resort on the banks of Oak Creek. The resort's
roots date to a collection of cabins and outhouses built in an
apple orchard in the 1920s, but it now offers 50 wooden
``creekhouses'' _ modern, privately-owned townhomes that come with
big, comfortable beds; equipped kitchens; maid service; fireplaces;
wide decks; and cable television. Some units have lofts and hot
tubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Junipine cafe and grill served three meals a day (room
service available) and Sedona offered several noteworthy
restaurants, but we generally preferred to cook at home _ packing
breakfasts or lunches for our hikes and day trips, and using the
resort's charcoal grills for steaks and chicken at night. Loud, fat
mountain jays welcomed us to the deck each morning, and at dusk my
son took his fishing pole to sit on the rocks along trout-stocked
Oak Creek.
</P>
<P>
   There was too much to do in only a week. We took day trips to
the Grand Canyon, the Meteor Crater, and the old
mining-town-turned-artist-hangout of Jerome, precariously built on
the side of a mountain. I took off for two mornings of golf at the
justly-celebrated Sedona Golf Resort and Oak Creek Country Club,
and joined my son on two afternoons at the pretty nine-hole,
pitch-and-putt course of the Poco Diablo resort. We never got
around to Sedona's famous jeep tours of the surrounding
countryside; at $30 per person per hour, they seemed expensive
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   One stop was a big letdown: the Slide Rock State Park, where Oak
Creek cascades through a series of pools and chutes like a natural
water slide. The parking lot was full; the creek jammed with
people, and the banks of the stream littered with soda cans and
trash. A trickle of dirty water flowed into the creek from an
obviously overburdened latrine. Though the warning signs said that
the e-coli level in the cold creek water was safe that day, my
daughter grew dizzy and nauseous and broke out into hives. It must
have been quite a wonderful swimming hole in its day, but like many
of the West's natural attractions, Slide Rock has been loved to
death: failing under pressure from too many visitors and leaky
upstream septic fields.
</P>
<P>
   We had far happier experiences on our hikes, where we walked for
hours without seeing more than one or two people. The terrain
offered dazzling choices: We hiked among the ponderosa pines and
cottonwoods of the West Fork Trail in Oak Creek Canyon; to the
Native American ruins at the Honanki and Palatki archeology sites;
and up into the red rocks to see (and in the kids' case, fearlessly
dance upon) the towering natural arch called Devil's Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   On one of the last nights of our stay, we ignored the
rattlesnake warning signs (11 species of rattler are native to
Arizona) and joined a ranger for a moonlight hike through Red Rock
State Park. We wandered up a trail through juniper and manzanita as
the sunset threw gold and purple streaks across the sky, and
exchanged greetings with a rancher and his wife, who were out on a
nighttime horseback ride. From an overlook high above Sedona, we
saw the full moon rise into the desert night. The rapid moonrise
was hypnotic, akin to the earthrise filmed by the Apollo astronauts
from the lunar surface, and gave us that same acute perception of
movement through space.
</P>
<P>
   We returned to Red Rock park again on our last day in Sedona,
inadvertently disturbing some graceful, good-natured nude
sunbathers. It was the one time we chanced upon Sedona's
understated New Age community, and the encounter sparked plenty of
conversation on the ride to California.
</P>
<P>
   As we hiked one final time through the shallow pools of Oak
Creek, my daughter put the lessons of her high school photography
course to good use. At Christmas she gave us her portrait of
Cathedral Rock, which now graces our living room, calling us back
to the red rock country.
</P>
</TEXT>
