<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TUITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUITION HIKE SPARKS FIGHT OVER MEXICO UNIVERSITY'S MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Instead of sitting in class last week at the
National Autonomous University, Salvador Gomez Carrillo and Mario
Rivera were in each other's faces.
</P>
<P>
   The two undergraduates have been friends since they began
attending college here in 1997. Now, however, they find themselves
on opposite sides of an explosive issue that has paralyzed the
hemisphere's largest university. For the first time in 50 years,
Mexico's top public institution of higher education is raising its
full-time tuition _ from 20 cents a semester to $120.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't abandon poor families,'' Gomez shouted at Rivera
in a confrontation in front of the administration building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hurt everyone with a weaker university,'' Rivera yelled
back.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the price hike has grown so intense that
the sprawling university, known as UNAM, was shut down last week by
thousands of protesting students, who declared a strike and blocked
access to 30 of the school's 34 departments.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign perhaps of the changing attitudes among Mexican
youths, an equally large number of students have voiced their
support for the higher tuition and have called for an end to the
strike so that they can get back to their studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that higher tuition means better resources for us and
our university,'' said Elizabeth Oliver, a 21-year-old psychology
student. ``Times are different now, and we can't expect that our
education should be free.''
</P>
<P>
   UNAM administrators say the price hike is necessary to make up
for cuts this year in government funding. As much as 90 percent of
UNAM's annual budget comes from the federal government, which has
also scaled back on subsidy programs for consumer products like
tortillas and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the tuition increase will squeeze out the poorest
students, and they blame everyone from university president
Francisco Barnes de Castro, who initially proposed it, to the World
Bank, which has urged many Latin American countries to make
universities less dependent on government funding.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents argue that the proposal violates Mexico's
Constitution, which says public schools are supposed to provide
``free'' education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against the tuition because it's being imposed without any
dialogue,'' said Omar Suarez, a 21-year-old architecture student.
</P>
<P>
   None of the country's other public colleges are free. And when
compared to Mexico's private universities, which on average charge
about $2,000 a semester, UNAM is still a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1940s, '50s, and '60s, the university was Mexico's
foremost training ground for its political, business, and cultural
leaders. But it has lost much of that luster in recent years as
private institutions have grown in prestige and because more elite
students have chosen to study in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Its enrollment of 270,000 makes it nearly five times larger than
the largest US campus, and its home on the southern edge of the
capital is a city within a city, spread over 4 miles.
</P>
<P>
   UNAM offers a wide range of academic programs, from a
high-school-level college prep curriculum to doctoral studies and
schools in law, medicine, and business.
</P>
<P>
   It has often been a hotbed for political and social revolts. In
1966, students protested proposed enrollment restrictions by taking
the rector, or university president, hostage. Two years later,
shortly before the Olympic Games opened in Mexico City, militant
students staged protests that resulted in the massacre of hundreds
of students.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, during a previous attempt to raise tuition, hundreds of
thousands of protesters choked traffic by filling the city's main
avenues up to the government square known as the Zocalo.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the price hike this year isn't unanimous. One
reason may be because the higher tuition will apply only to next
year's arriving class, not to any current students. Those who
cannot afford the higher tuition, Barnes said, will be given
exemptions or scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to disarm your opponents is by taking away their
potential recruits,'' said one administrator at the private Colegio
de Mexico. ``Once they realized that they wouldn't have to pay,
many students would rather get back to class and finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason may be politics. With presidential elections
about a year away, insiders say Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, which is facing serious challenges to its
70-year grip on the presidency, is doing all it can to squash the
protest by helping organize students against the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barnes and his supporters have accused the leftist
opposition Party of the Democratic Revolution of stoking the
disruptions by backing the protesters _ a claim that party leaders
deny.
</P>
<P>
   Still another reason the tuition hike may happen this time has
much to do with the university's image.
</P>
<P>
   Although UNAM remains the country's most influential university,
it no longer has a monopoly on producing the best students. Many
employers say their first preference is for a graduate from one of
the private universities. Some newspaper help-wanted ads have been
known to specifically state that ``UNAM graduates need not apply.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a feeling that you can have more confidence in the
work of a private school graduate than in someone from UNAM,'' said
Carla Avila de Jesus, a department store personnel manager, who
added that raising the tuition may help erase UNAM's reputation as
the ``inexpensive'' university.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``Raising the tuition is one thing. Raising the
quality of students is another. I think that's what everyone should
be arguing about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe researcher Lorena Zarate contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
