<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARD'S HOMETOWN IS LOOKING GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATFORD-UPON-AVON, England _ Who's Shakespeare?
</P>
<P>
   The guy with the hots for Gwyneth Paltrow is one current answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A local boy who made good drama,'' says Ronnie Schwartz, a
visitor completing a sentimental journey from Chicago to see the
Bard's hood for herself.
</P>
<P>
   My Uncle Studley defines him as ``a man who had words for every
situation. He anticipated Red Sox fans with `What fools these
mortals be!' And often evicted his dog from the house with, `Out,
damned Spot!' Centuries ago he gave loan sharks their present day
name: Shylocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stratford, a town of 25,000 beside the gentle River Avon where
swans swim and tourists swoop and swoon at the thought of walking
streets and floorboards trod by himself, Will Shakespeare, the
timeless scribbler.
</P>
<P>
   Though such as Pizza Hut and McDonald's (hardly food for
thought) have intruded, Shakespeare's old hometown of half-timbered
residences and public buildings has held up almost as well as his
works. Yorick _ the ``Alas, poor Yorick'' court jester _ holds up
even better than the original. Bigger than death as a frolicking
bronze figure near the bus depot, the Y Man has had his role
fleshed out by a sculptor from the graveyard cameo, a skull in
Hamlet's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Since Shakespeare Meets Oscar (as well as Paltrow) is one of the
year's catchy stories, the tourist trade, already a healthy
four-cottage industry, soars higher. The four: those of his wife,
the former Anne Hathaway, in Shottery, and his mother, Mary Arden,
in Wilmcote (both close by); and in Stratford, his birthplace, and
the home of son-in-law and daughter, Dr. John and Susanna Hall.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy just about anything bearing a Shakespearean logo _
yes, even your own Shakespeare-model quill pen with which to
scratch out a sonnet to your love. Or a re-write of the Katherina
of Padua story as ``The Blaming of the Shrews,'' co-starring Linda
Tripp and Lucianne Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was a big day hereabouts, April 23, the date of the
Bard's 1564 birth and 1616 death. Naturally some of us softly
hummed, ``Happy birthday to you . . . .'' beside his tomb within
Holy Trinity Church. There his effigy smiles down on those willing
to pay a buck to approach the hallowed spot.
</P>
<P>
   The second floor room of his birth, papered in a cheery floral
pattern, said to be a replica, is crowded with those who may feel
that they are positioned to breathe in literary inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``My post cards will be better composed after this,'' believes
Ronnie Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, ``Fondly wishest thou wert here''? How about, ``Wherefore
art I? In the bosom of the Bard.''
</P>
<P>
   The American writer Washington Irving was not impressed during
his visit in 1815, calling the parental residence of John and Mary
Shakespeare ``a poor house made of sticks and mud.'' But Keats and
Byron were enthralled, signing their names on the ceiling (since
whitewashed over), and other writers etched names, yet visible, on
the window pane. Glorious graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Actually papa John was a man of some means, indicated by the
good stone floors and high ceilings downstairs. He'd come up in the
world after marrying Mary Arden, heiress daughter of a prosperous
farmer on whose land he humbly worked. A Mrs. Court, a butcher's
wife, occupied the Henley Street property between 1806 and 1846,
and showed select visitors around, expecting a monetary
remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, fortunately, the preservation-minded Shakespeare
Trust took over the landmarks. However, not before the Bard's own
residence of later life, New House, was torn down by the owner, a
resentful Rev. Gastrell, who tired of sightseers calling on him,
and didn't have Mrs. Court's knack for making history pay. All that
remains on the corner lot is the attractive flower garden.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most interesting location is the Wilmcote farm of
Robert Arden, where the Bard's mother, Mary, was reared and lived
until she married his father in 1557. It is still a working farm
with longhorn cattle, very hairy Cotswold sheep, a well-inhabited
dovecote and falcons and owls that are trained to hunt by Danielle
Shearsby.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a desirable homestead in its day, the farm, with
stone and half-timbered buildings, endured so well that it was
lived in until about 30 years ago. Its leading asset may be a guide
named Julia Bruce, a source of all sorts of everyday information of
Shakespearean times. While ``Shakespeare in Love'' is a colorful,
romantic film, be grateful that it wasn't accompanied by the odors
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bathed once a year, and never washed their hair,'' says
Bruce, ``although Queen Elizabeth I (currently alias Judi Dench and
Kate Blanchett) was scandalous because she took a bath every month.
June became the marital month because it was mild enough for the
annual bath, and the bride took hers before the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fleas were a problem. Beneath their gowns women might keep a
piece of meat, a small dog or a piglet in an armpit to draw off the
fleas from elsewhere. Spring cleaning meant throwing out the
threshings that covered the floor and by then were covered with all
sorts of garbage and droppings, animal and human. At least the
trash was hard to see because the rooms were smoky from fireplaces,
and the horn windows didn't let in much light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thatched roofs were the haven for all sorts of creatures.
Canopy beds helped keep them off, but it was best to sleep with
your mouth closed, or on your belly. When people traveled they took
their own mattresses. Better the creatures you knew. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   She says, ``The people drank a lot of ale, getting 40 percent of
their nourishment from malt and barley. Even the children, who
drank eight pints a day.'' High times at high school? ``Not exactly
mother's milk, but, well, it was a source of vitamin B.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Robert Arden's chair beside the fireplace. The husband
had the only good chair, with arms _ thus, the chairman. As
chairman of the board, he sat at the head of the table. Over here
is the spooning bench. Shakespeare would have sat on a similar one
while courting Anne Hathaway. To keep a suitor's hands busy he was
given a piece of wood and told to carve a spoon. Thus, spooning.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Will didn't carve enough. His and Anne's first child,
Susanna, was born six months after their marriage. Twins Hamnet and
Judith came two years later, and soon Shakespeare was off to London
to pursue fame, fortune and Gwyneth Paltrow et al.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' says Bruce, ``He sent money home to take care of Anne
and the kids. He wasn't a deadbeat dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. Our hero, Will, didn't want love's labor lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
