<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO DOWNSIZES ITS MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Does it seem to you that Mayor Brown is
getting smaller?''
</P>
<P>
   A friend who works at City Hall asked me that question last
week. He meant smaller physically, as well as pettier in his
private dealings and less noisy in his public appearances. I had to
agree that Willie Brown, the mayor of San Francisco, seems to be
disappearing inside his $3,000 suits.
</P>
<P>
   When I saw Brown at a press conference last week he wasn't his
ebullient, jocular, vicious self. With all the verve of former
Mayor Frank Jordan in his wet period, Brown talked about his
traffic program, elegantly called ``Unclog 2.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what all that vision has come to, signs saying ``No
double parking.'' Even if you're emperor of the city, at some point
you have to get down to the nitty-gritty and roll up the sleeves on
your lack of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad it's about three years too late.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall regulars say Brown seems depressed, as well he should,
with recent polls showing only 28 percent of San Francisco voters
would re-elect him mayor come the November election.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Brown about as popular as the city's mass transit
system, Muni. Coincidence? Even I felt sorry for the incredibly
shrinking larger-than-life mayor.
</P>
<P>
   After the press conference he made none of his usual jokes or
jibes at reporters. A handler hustled him away from the microphones
and notebooks. The idea of Brown being handled is depressing all on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   Brown managed to stop to tell one innocuous story about Ronald
Reagan's trick for giving a speech, using contact lenses with
different prescriptions so he could look at the audience while
reading the TelePrompTer.
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's the visual equivalent of how Brown can talk out
of both sides of his mouth at the same time. But the point of the
story seemed to be ``Reagan and I, we used to be like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an interesting story _ if it was true that Reagan could
zoom in and out of focus and give a speech at the same time. But I
walked away thinking better of Reagan, and worse for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost as if his glory days were behind him, despite the
half-million taxpayer bucks in gold leaf on the City Hall dome
above him.
</P>
<P>
   But he has brought his smallness in the polls on himself, so I
don't feel that sorry for him.
</P>
<P>
   Count the ways Brown has diminished his chances in the next
election:
</P>
<P>
   _ Brown gets all over town for functions and parties, but the
ones he likes best are with the celebrities and socialites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite his wit, there's only so much you want to read about
him in the social pages if you're one of those whose rents have
been blown sky-high by the booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The economic boom that Brown, like President Clinton, takes
credit for has been wonderful for Brown's lobbyist and developer
friends.
</P>
<P>
   _ The face of the city has changed as if at the hand of a
fly-by-night plastic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   _ High-rise buildings have sprouted South of Market. Overpriced
plywood ``live-work'' spaces, the slums of tomorrow, have been
thrown up by a loftwaffe of Brown's builder pals.
</P>
<P>
   The development boom comes at the cost of the destruction of
small businesses and light industry and the loss of thousands of
parking spaces. And Muni is as bad as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Forget being a transit-first city. This is a shoe leather-first
city.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, a smart young amateur ran Muni, qualifying for
the job by having been a Brown aide. As mayor, Brown has always
chosen loyalty over expertise, appointing a variety of hack
loyalists, inexperienced kids and ex-girlfriends (I mean
non-ex-girlfriends) to high-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has dared to disagree with Brown has been fired.
Anyone who has been loyal but a screw-up has been transferred to
another job to screw up.
</P>
<P>
   With the election around the corner, Brown finally appointed a
professional rapid-transit man to run Muni. Timing is everything in
transit and politics, and the appointment of a pro was even later
than the average bus.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is becoming a theme park of attractions _ cafes,
restaurants, the Museum of Modern Art, the new ballpark. The
problem is, you can't get there from here, or from anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   We're developing a new underclass besides the homeless _ the
limoless. Like the homeless, the limoless aren't Brown's sort of
people. They're the middle class. They can't get to their jobs that
don't pay enough from their homes they can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   Even liberals have tired of the so-called liberal mayor who
hangs out with Pacific Heights Republicans. ``Run, Tom, Run''
buttons have appeared all over town urging Tom Ammiano, the
president of the Board of Supervisors, to run for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is scared to death of having the gay, progressive Ammiano
jump into the race against him with the somewhat more conservative
Clint Reilly. So Brown is working hard at looking like a mayor
instead of an emperor. Unfortunately, that makes him look smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The emperor has no clothes, and now they don't fit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
