<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTRIBUTIVE, THY NAME IS WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `In the military, they have `mission creep,' wrote Nat Hefferman
in a recent e-mail. ``In English, we seem to have `usage creep,'
when a word gradually changes its part of speech, e.g. from noun to
adjective.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed we do _ in fact, ``mission creep'' is standard operating
procedure for the English lexicon, though some changes meet more
vigorous resistance than others. The one troubling Hefferman at the
moment is the use of woman as an adjective _ woman doctor, woman
driver _ when female would serve the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Grammatically speaking, woman driver is no more unusual than
chicken farm or business strategy. The first element in each
combination is a noun used ``attributively'' _ in front of another
noun, modifying it as an adjective would. But woman, chicken, and
business haven't turned into adjectives: They can't be used
``predicatively,'' as an adjective could be. The woman is tall, the
farm is huge, the strategy is idiotic all work in English, but not
the woman is driver, the farm is chicken, the strategy is business.
</P>
<P>
   Such modifiers, says language expert David Crystal, ``are no
longer strictly nouns, because (for example) they have lost their
ability to pluralize: we cannot say the gardens party. On the other
hand, they are not strictly adjectives either, because (for
example) the cannot compare: we cannot say the gardenest party.''
</P>
<P>
   They are, however, a fundamental part of the language.
Grammarians make some fine distinctions among such compounds, but
in one form or another they go back to the beginnings of English.
We find woman frend (spelled that way) in 1300, woman politicians
in 1659, and woman-journalist in 1902 (in a quotation that calls
her ``the most loyal, earnest and teachable person under the sun.''
My, how she has changed).
</P>
<P>
   Mission creep has crept even further in the case of an
expression reader Joel Wechsler finds annoying: so fun!, as in
``The party was . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Fun, like many nouns used attributively, moved gradually into
its new role. Originally spelled fon, it was both verb (meaning to
fool someone) and noun (meaning a hoax or joke) for centuries. But
the OED notes the appearance of a fun-room _ the rec room of the
19th century _ in an 1846 citation. With 1959 comes fun person, and
now we can not only have fun, we can be fun. (And fun furs are on
the way.)
</P>
<P>
   Fun as an adjective is still labeled colloquial in my
dictionary, but most people saying the party was fun would call
that fun an adjective, and few would object to it. But if it's now
an adjective, can't we say it was so fun, just as we would say it
was so exciting or so deadly? (All these are elliptical statements,
but no less acceptable for that.) The ``standard'' English today
would be such fun or so much fun, retaining the noun-ness of fun,
and perhaps these versions will prevail. Or maybe so fun will be
less fun when it no longer irritates the grown-ups, and it will go
quietly off to the land of retired slang. Meanwhile, I wouldn't get
majorly upset over it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Were-wolves at the door
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week's item on was and were skipped one variety of
subjunctivitis that troubles several readers. ``In reporting the
direct quote `Are you happy with your run production?' it is
correct to write `He was asked if he was happy with his run
production,' '' writes David Sears. Often, Sears says, the indirect
quotation emerges as ``He was asked if he were happy with his run
production.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently that little if triggers a subjunctive reflex in some
writers. But if doesn't necessarily signal a counterfactual
situation. If I were you is subjunctive, but If I was unfair, I
apologize is not; the if clause is stating the premise on which the
apology depends, not expressing doubt about it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the degree of counterfactuality in a statement
can be hard to determine. ``Even if Naipaul were wrong about all
the many things Theroux suddenly discovered . . .'' wrote a
National Review critic, for instance. I would say ``Even if he
was'' _ just as I'd say ``Whether or not he was'' _ but the writer
may think Naipaul wasn't wrong, and hear his clause as contrary to
fact. In that case, I'd prefer ``if Naipaul had been wrong _ making
it clearly counterfactual. The moral is, Beware of were:You might
be better off with less of it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Write or e-mail word queries to Jan Freeman at The Boston Globe,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com. Include a
hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
