<HEADLINE>
FLYING THE (AIRPORT) COOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few things are as dull as hanging around an airport, especially
when there is an unexpected layover and you have hours to kill.
Even at airports that have upgraded their shops and restaurants,
there is a certain sameness to it all. Fortunately, several
airports are just a few minutes from stellar attractions. For
instance: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --From Atlanta's Hartsfield Airport, the public transportation
system can whisk you to a tour of the new Turner Field in just 25
minutes. Or in 20 minutes you can visit the birthplace of Margaret
Mitchell, author of that smoldering classic ``Gone With the
Wind.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --From Sky Harbor Airport in Phoenix, a 15-minute taxi ride will
get you the Heard Museum, with its extensive collection of Native
American artifacts and fine art. Or in 10 minutes you can go to the
Desert Botanical Garden, featuring 20,000 varieties of desert
foliage. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --From Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, the Grapevine Mills mall is
just five minutes away via a $9 ride by SuperShuttle. And what a
mall it is, with more than 200 stores and a variety of dining and
entertainment. Or a complimentary shuttle can take you in five
minutes from the airport to the Hyatt Bear Creek Golf and Racquet
Club, where you can play a few holes or prctice your swing on the
driving range. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --From O'Hare Airport in Chicago, a 20-minute taxi ride takes
you to the Frank Lloyd Wright Home and Studio, with its
barrel-vaulted playroom and two-story drafting room. Or fitness
buffs can work out at the Hilton Athletic Club in the O'Hare
Hilton, adjacent to the airport. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Let's not forget Boston, with the New England Aquarium just an
eight-minute boat shuttle or 15-minute subway ride or from Logan
Airport. Or Cleveland, where the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame is a
20-minute rail ride from Hopkins Airport. Or Las Vegas, where the
pleasure palaces are a 5- to 10-minute taxi or shuttle ride from
McCarran Airport (which has its own slot machines). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You see, there really are other things to do besides staring
transfixed at those souvenir T-shirts in the airport gift shop. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``America is a vast conspiracy to make you happy.'' _
John Updike. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel bookshelf: ``Travelers' Tales Guide: America!'' (Setterberg,
$19.95) tells the comic, dramatic, and nostalgic stories of
travelers who have walked, paddled, driven, flown, sailed,
galloped, hitchhiked, and otherwise explored parts of this amazing
nation. Topics range from Josewph Lamb's ``Peoria Baseball'' to
Dave Barry's hilarious ``The Walt `You Will Have Fun' Disney
World.'' Other authors include E. Annie Proulx, Calvin Trillin, Jan
Morris, and James Fallows. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grander Canyon: Idaho's Hell's Canyon surpasses the Grand Canyon's
deepest drop of 5,700 feet by 2,200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The poetry of art: ``Georgia O'Keefe: the Poetry of Things'' is
a special exhibition at the Phillips Collection in Washington,
D.C., through July 18. The exhibit, says curator Elizabeth Hutton
Turner, ``invites a closer look at O'Keefe's aesthetic and a new
way of looking at objects by placing her work in proximity to real
objects of the type she collected.'' In all, there will be 69
works. The museum is at 1600 21st St, NW; telephone 202-387-2151. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Washington: Capitol Reservations at 800-VISIT-DC or
www.visitdc.com is a no-charge booking service, and available
discounts vary. But when we tried the service last fall, we were
able to book a moderately priced room at a lower rate than appeared
to be available elsewhere. Even the desk clerk was impressed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Highs and lows: The highest point in Pennsylvania is lower than the
lowest point in Colorado. &QL; 
 &QL; 
What does it all mean? Ohio road sign: _ Prosperity 30 mi _ Clinton
70 mi.'' (With thanks to frequent contributor Mike Schuster of
Foxborough.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Memories of Sammy: Employees at the now-demolished Sands hotel
always made sure that a slot machine was waiting for Sammy Davis
Jr. in his room. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cutting ties in Texas: Ties remain ``illegal'' on South Padre
Island at the tropical tip of Texas, and now socks have been added
to the list of ``outlawed'' clothing. Since June 1997, when
offensive neckwear was banned, Island police have issued polite
warnings to tie-wearers, offering them a South Padre Island T-shirt
for the removal of their tie. More than 100 T-shirts have been
issued.
</P>
</TEXT>
