<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST CAN'T STOP TILTING AT WINDMILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
`Every Man Should Try': Adventures of a Public Interest Activist 
Jeremy J. Stone (PublicAffairs, $27.50) 
 
 By PAUL SCHATT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The butterfly flaps its wings in Paris, setting into motion
events resulting in a storm in New York. That image, straight from
chaos theory, is cited by Jeremy Stone as his explanation for
imagining that his individual activism could help shape events on a
global scale.
</P>
<P>
   He's at the same time a royal pain in the neck of the
establishment and, surprisingly, detached enough to describe his
major failures and egotistical moments.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, for 30 years president of the Federation of American
Scientists, has devoted his life to activism on a grand scale,
working for nuclear disarmament, freedom for Andrei Sakharov,
halting an illegal CIA mail-opening operation, challenging the
Nixon administration on Watergate, fighting the Shining Path in
Peru, proposing a solution to the China-Taiwan problem, attempting
to end the war in Cambodia, . . . etc. And a dozen or so other
causes, many of them of the lost variety.
</P>
<P>
   You can disagree with many of his political stands, yet give
grudging admiration to how tenaciously he has fought for them.
Obviously, the neutrality laws are no longer enforced against
private citizens who stick their noses into foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it should come as no surprise to know that last year he
tried, unsuccessfully, to push a solution to the Kosovo crisis,
proposing that the Kosovar Albanians ``rent'' the area from the
Serbs, providing virtual autonomy to the Albanians while giving
legal recognition to the Serbian ownership. Like many of his
proposals, this one was simple, logical _ and politically naive.
And he admits it.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Stone's honesty is winning, even to a reader who
disagrees with his politics and feels his campaigns used the
authority of `science'' to cover for political judgments. After
reading this candid, fascinating self-portrait of a man who feels
driven to do what little he can do to advance causes he favors,
you'll want to do something, somehow, to make a difference. His
title is taken from a John F. Kennedy quote, ``One man can make a
difference, and every man should try.'' It beats nihilism.
</P>
<P>
   The author's father, the late I.F. Stone, gained fame as a
crusading newsletter editor who challenged establishment truths and
occasionally won a point. However, I.F. Stone's reputation was
marred, after his death, when Soviet KGB files hinted he had
received Soviet money, presumably for propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Stone describes what he does as entrepreneurial activism.
He approaches each cause as a political campaign, seeking to do
whatever he can as an individual to push the needle, even a little
bit. However, he recognizes that one can do only so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every rifle shot in snowy mountains brings an avalanche,''
he writes. ``Similarly, not every activist foray in public life
hits a fracture line that produces important, lasting change.
Indeed, if change were this easy to manipulate, change would come
too fast for all of us to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Here he injects a dash of reality into his idealism, by
admitting some of his publicized charges were just off target. For
example, he fought for a congressional veto over first use of
nuclear weapons, only to be shocked to discover that most
congressmen didn't really want to be responsible for making such
decisions. He confesses, ``I took too seriously the periodic
hypocritical complaints of leading members of Congress that the
executive branch refused to consult them in emergencies.'' He's
almost smelling the coffee here.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, his honesty is compelling. My favorite case
study is his responsible, truly scientific reaction when Carl Sagan
wanted him to call a press conference and scare the bejesus out of
the East Coast. Sagan believed that unexplained booms in Nova
Scotia and off the United States were precursors of massive
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Stone investigated and declined calling a press conference; the
booms were caused by the Concorde. One less hysterical scientific
false alarm may not seem like much, but, like a butterfly flapping
its wings in Paris, it can have an effect. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
