<HEADLINE>
SOME SIGNS OF TROUBLE WERE EVIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF AND LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The SWAT teams fell back, waiting, watching,
deciding how to respond to the deadly threat posed by the rampaging
school gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Helmeted, armored, assault weapons ready, they stood in
jet-black uniforms outside the bullet- and bomb-damaged school last
Tuesday. But by then, authorities said, it was too late to stop
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, though, long before the teenagers strapped on
high-powered weapons and explosive-filled backpacks, there were
numerous opportunities to derail the duo, chances that were missed
or ignored or simply misread.
</P>
<P>
   In the months leading up to the slaughter of 12 students and one
teacher at Columbine High School, Harris and Klebold seemed almost
taunting in their displays of antisocial rage, daring someone to
take note of them and their inner torment, perhaps even daring
someone to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   During an early morning bowling class, they celebrated strikes
with Nazi salutes. Harris idolized Adolf Hitler and salted his
Internet web page with threats of violence. The two made a video
that other students called a prelude to the massacre. They broke
into a car. They retreated into an online world. They joined the
``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' a group of outcasts, and apparently passed
the time making pipe bombs and plotting revenge on rival cliques.
</P>
<P>
   At home, one kept Nazi literature, hate pamphlets and, most
tellingly, materials for explosives in plain view. A shotgun barrel
was found on a dresser. ``A lot of this stuff was clearly visible,
and the parents should have known,'' Jefferson County Sheriff John
Stone said recently. ``I think parents should be accountable for
their kids' actions.''
</P>
<P>
   But time and again, according to dozens of interviews with
friends, teachers, law-enforcement officials, and others, witnesses
to their behavior did little or nothing to help the troubled pair.
Even when someone did something, as when a father complained to
sheriff's deputies about Harris's web site, authorities were
reluctant to follow through, and the opportunity passed. The father
let it drop.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, there was a reason, or at least a rationale, for
not acting. Taken individually, few if any of the duo's troubling
acts could portend what was brewing. And it is difficult to imagine
anyone _ other, perhaps, than their mothers and fathers _ piecing
together enough of the clues to have perceived their downward
spiral and forestalled the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   It is convenient, but potentially misleading, after an atrocity
to pull together disparate threads and weave them into what then
resembles a clearly defined tapestry. It also should be remembered
that the world of Harris, 18, and Klebold, 17, was not pure
darkness. While many Columbine students remembered their anger and
their scowls, some noted flashes of humor, intellect, and kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no mistaking the red flags the two young men
were waving at the world, and no denying that many people missed
opportunities to defuse a rage so intense that the gunmen laughed
at their dying victims before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 funerals to plan, and countless lives to rebuild, there
is a premium in this Denver suburb on unity. But already,
recriminations and questions are seeping through the grief, with
some looking inward and some looking for others to blame, from the
teenagers' parents to school and law enforcement officials, from
the media to the Internet, from the availability of guns to an
overall erosion of morals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we can all look to ourselves in this,'' said Harris's
neighbor, Bill Konen, who silently listened to the two teens
smashing glass the day before the massacre. Authorities now suspect
they were making shrapnel for their bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if I had made more contact with him, maybe if the
neighborhood had made more contact, that might have changed
things,'' Konen said. ``I think probably not, but I've been
thinking about that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the glass-breaking episode, Konen learned that
the shattered glass would lead to a shattered community and a
shaken nation. Others would have to look further back into their
notes, into their memories, to find the overlooked signposts to
murder.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, Randall Brown was among the first to turn to
authorities. After a seemingly minor dispute, Harris had threatened
Brown's then-17-year-old son, Brooks, urging others to kill the
younger Brown in a message posted on the Internet. The two boys had
been friendly classmates. But Harris had changed, becoming
withdrawn and, Randall Brown feared, potentially violent.
</P>
<P>
   Brown reported the threats to the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department. But sheriff's deputies and the local district attorney
said Brown filed only a ``suspicious incident report'' and not a
formal complaint. Brown said he feared that would have escalated
the situation. In turn, the sheriff's department felt it could do
nothing, and that is what it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you call me and say a person is threatening to kill me and
I want it stopped, you have to be willing to file a criminal
complaint,'' said Deputy Troy Gardalen. ``In order to have a
criminal investigation, there has to be a crime reported.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Dave Thomas acknowledged that the threat might
have been examined more closely. ``Maybe we've become desensitized.
We say `no big deal, we've heard that before,' '' Thomas said.
``I'm not saying any red flags were ignored and I've never said
that. What I know is what some of the kids said. They saw signs of
danger. . . . We need to learn what those red flags are.''
</P>
<P>
   Others also saw Harris's homicidal musings on his favorite form
of communication, the Internet, visible to anyone around the world
with a computer and a phone line.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps six months ago, a Web site signed by the Trenchcoat
Mafia and created by Harris caught the eye of two separate Internet
researchers, one in Los Angeles, one in Toronto. Working for the
Simon Wiesenthal Center, which studies on-line hate groups, they
picked it up because of its link to sites urging anarchy and
providing bomb-making instructions, said Rabbi Abraham Cooper, who
coordinates the center's study.
</P>
<P>
   But with no explicit calls for killing, the site was not
``captured,'' or downloaded for further investigation. Only after
the killings was the site reopened for study, now by federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Computers also provided Harris and Klebold with access to two of
their preferred pastimes: violent games, which they played
incessantly, shooting targets and decapitating enemies; and
studying recipes for explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities now believe they have seized from Harris's home the
Internet-generated instructions that taught the pair how to build
bombs with low-cost, everyday household materials. They said the
more than 30 explosive devices discovered at the school could have
been built for about $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of kids get into trouble and the parents don't hear about
it until later,'' said Littleton resident Dennis Wunderlich, whose
eighth-grade son, Victor, is home-schooled. ``But these kids had
that Web site, they were building bombs, they had propane tanks.
Sure there will be finger-pointing, because it seems like there's a
lot of blame to go around, but it's not that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Victor, ``You know you could hide it if you wanted to, but
these people weren't even trying to hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
