<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-WARNINGS-2N     04-27 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-WARNINGS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LITTLETON, Colo.: ... hide it.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In March 1998, not long after their run-in with the Brown
family, Harris and Klebold were arrested trying to break into a
locked car to steal electronics. Charged with felony first-degree
criminal trespass, they were introduced to the Jefferson County
juvenile justice system. Spared jail because they were sentenced to
a diversion program, they succeeded mostly in diverting attention
from their own problems.
</P>
<P>
   During the 11-month program, they apparently passed alcohol and
drug screenings, performed 45 hours of community service, and so
impressed a counselor with their intellect and attitude that two
months ago he released them from the program with accolades.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, the counselor wrote, was ``a very bright young man who
is likely to succeed in life.'' Klebold, meanwhile, was a ``bright
young man who has a great deal of potential.'' The counselor
remains unidentified, but his superiors describe him as
``anguishing.''
</P>
<P>
   As members of the Trenchcoat Mafia, Harris and Klebold sought
strength in numbers, walking Columbine's halls in groups as large
as 10. Sophomore Katie Kirk was among those present last July
Fourth when Harris and Klebold opened the trunk of a car to show
off guns and lead pipes.
</P>
<P>
   The group was founded more than four years ago by Joseph Stair,
a 1998 Columbine graduate who has boasted in interviews about its
bomb-making predilection and anti-social ways. The gang attracted
sullen boys who ridiculed religion and reveled in racism. At a
physical education class held at the FunPlex bowling alley, the
boys celebrated strikes with straight-armed Nazi salutes. It is
unclear whether the teacher reprimanded them or brought their
behavior to the attention of school officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a philosophy class, Harris talked constantly about buying a
gun, said 16-year-old Jennifer Lucero. ``We ignored him,'' Lucero
said. ``Nobody paid them much attention. They were weirdos.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, writings and a video produced by the pair also did
not trigger alarms. Fellow students recalled an essay Harris
recently shared with creative writing classmates in which he
described enemies and explosions, a scene that foreshadowed the war
he and Klebold declared on the school during the lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the school year, Harris and Klebold worked together
to produce a video for a class project that some students said
showed them pretending to shoot classmates, particularly the
student-athletes with whom they feuded. Others said the video was
less specific, touching only obliquely on mayhem. A copy of the
video is now part of the investigation, another clue to be analyzed
too late.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Trenchcoat Mafia, including the presumed killers,
also threatened Columbine senior Isaiah Shoels, according to his
father, Michael. One of the few black students in the school,
Shoels was among the dead, executed in the library while the gunmen
spewed racial epithets. Witnesses said the killers sought him out
and took pleasure in his death.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shoels said that long before the shootings, he
complained about gang members' racism to the principal, Frank
DeAngelis, but nothing was done.
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelis was among the school officials who said they did not
even know the Trenchcoat Mafia existed. ``I did not, or teachers
did not, see these people in trench coats walking down the hall,''
DeAngelis told reporters. ``Hopefully, this will be a wakeup call
for people around the nation. If I had to do it all over again,
that's the message I will say time and time again.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous Columbine students, however, said the hostility between
athletes and the Trenchcoat Mafia was public knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime, the athletes and the outcasts eyed each other with
disdain and hurled insults and threats. Eric Quintana, 16, said
Harris, Klebold, and their friends would repeat two words _ ``just
wait'' _ a threat Quintana and other students did not take
seriously. Stair, the trench coat group's founder, said they felt
``persecuted'' by the athletes, while several athletes said the
rival group courted trouble by taunting students outside its
insular circle.
</P>
<P>
   The missed signs of trouble continued up to the days before the
murders.
</P>
<P>
   Konen, Harris's next-door neighbor, was outside his home Monday
morning, painting the trim on the house, when the pair pulled up in
Klebold's black BMW. For about 15 minutes, the two used a baseball
bat in Harris's open garage to smash what sounded to Konen like
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't sound like a dangerous noise, just an obnoxious
noise,'' Konen said. ``Like everybody, I've listened to the various
reports about how these guys acted, and of course I wish things had
been different.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on male teenage violence said it is not uncommon for
parents, school officials and friends to miss signals from boys on
the verge of hurting themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys won't reach out and ask for help, and won't look weepy or
sad. That means being vulnerable and that leads to shame, and
they'd rather be dead than be ashamed,'' said William Pollack, a
clinical psychologist at Harvard Medical School and author of the
book, ``Real Boys: Rescuing Our Sons from The Myths of Boyhood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to recognize the signs, particularly increased social
isolation, a sense of feeling like or being an outcast, a sense of
being rejected or overly teased, and a lowered sense of
self-esteem,'' Pollack said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost reflexively, parents whose own teenagers had cowered in
the cafeteria, in closets, as the bullets flew, wondered whether
they would have been able to recognize the signs in their own
children. One after another, they insisted they would, or at least
hoped they would.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what their families knew about Harris's and
Klebold's violent obsessions or deep-seated hatreds, despite what
investigators Saturday described as the teens' nonchalance about
concealing their intentions. Their parents' only public comments to
date have been statements expressing sympathy for the victims and
asking for privacy for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But there are suspicions that Klebold's family was at least
somewhat aware of his deadly potential. In the midst of last
Tuesday's siege, a lawyer for Klebold's father called the district
attorney's office asking if he could help. It was not known how
Thomas Klebold knew his son was involved. He was told it was too
late, in part because it was never a hostage situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ellen O'Brien of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
