<HEADER>
A4979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUCK-SAFETY28-COX     04-27 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-SAFETY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDEPENDENT AGENCY PROPOSED FOR TRUCK SAFETY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress needs to set up a new independent agency
to oversee the safety of the nation's trucking industry, witnesses
told a Senate committee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With more motorists dying in crashes with big rigs, the Office
of Motor Carriers (OMC) has gotten too chummy with the industry
that it is supposed to regulate and has failed in its mission to
keep unsafe trucks off the highways, warned Kenneth Mead, inspector
general of the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   This laxity comes at a time when the number of commercial
carriers is growing dramatically, creating pressure for more
enforcement of laws to keep unsafe trucks out of service, Mead told
the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The OMC has shifted emphasis from enforcement to a more
collaborative approach to safety,'' testified Mead. ``This is a
good approach for motor carriers that have safety as a top
priority, but it has gone too far. It does not work effectively
with firms that persist in violating safety rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The OMC ``has pushed lovey-dovey relationships'' with the
trucking industry rather than enforcing safety laws, complained
Joan Claybrook, president of Public Citizen and co-chair of
Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., has introduced legislation in the House
that would move the OMC from the Federal Highway Administration to
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, which regulates
the manufacture of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But Mead and several other witnesses proposed creation of a new
independent agency, with a chairman to be appointed by the
president and confirmed by Congress, would be better suited to
focus exclusively on truck and bus safety.
</P>
<P>
   The new agency would be similar to the Federal Aviation
Administration, which oversees the airline industry, the witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Highway safety, as it relates to trucking, is not improved by
simply moving a box on an organizational chart,'' said Walter
McCormick, president of the American Trucking Associations, which
represents many of the major carriers. ``It requires an agency
committed to a core mission of improving trucking safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman John McCain, R-Ariz., said he was studying
the options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe we need to determine where motor carrier
responsibilities can best be carried out before we legislate
substantial organizational changes,'' he told the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The number of deaths resulting from truck crashes has been
increasing _ reaching 5,300 people in 1997, said Mead. ``This
equates to a major airline crash with 200 fatalities every two
weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fatality rate _ the number of fatalities per 100 million
miles traveled _ has remained constant for the past three years,
but the actual number of deaths has risen as the number of carriers
increased by 36 percent during this period.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
