<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-PROFILE-BOS     04-27 1715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-PROFILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLATILE MIX OF PRESSURES FACES TEENS, SPECIALISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don Ramsey remembers the first time he gave his son
Evan a popsicle. The boy laughed and chased it around the tray of
his highchair with his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey had a sleepless night Tuesday. The rampage at Columbine
High School, in Littleton, Colo., had him thinking about Evan, who
two years ago, as an acne-scarred teenager, marched into his high
school in rural Alaska and used a shotgun to kill the principal and
a popular sophomore basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flashback time, you know,'' said Ramsey, speaking by
telephone from Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey said he still finds it difficult to reconcile the
conflicting images of his son: the innocent toddler and the
16-year-old killer. Although the massacre this week at Columbine
seems equally impossible to comprehend, researchers say it exploded
from several disturbing changes that are occurring simultaneously
in the way children are growing up.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than random events or even copycat crimes, the eight
school shootings since 1996, which have killed 33 and wounded at
least 70, are byproducts of a growing subculture of severely
troubled youth, many researchers say. Inside this mostly hidden
world, millions of teens suffer from serious, untreated mood
disorders _ particularly depression _ and see violence as the
primary means of handling conflict. Their desperate alienation has
been made potentially lethal by guns that now seem as easy to
obtain as a six-pack of beer.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, many adults tend to view teenagers as children in the
midst of losing their innocence, their angst no different than what
they as children went through. Such assumptions are dangerous,
researchers say. ``There's no comparison,'' said Peter C. Scales, a
senior fellow at the Search Institute, a non-profit research
organization in Minneapolis that specializes in youth issues. ``It
was fantasyland 40 years ago. And that forces us into very
difficult questions today. I just hope we have the guts to have a
debate about some of these issues and not just pretend that putting
a metal detector up is the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Alan Unis, a psychiatrist and brain researcher at the
University of Washington, examined Barry Loukaitis, who committed
the first of the school shootings. Loukaitis, a wan 14-year-old,
opened the door of his algebra class at Moses Lake (Wash.) junior
high school, held up a .30-30 deer rifle and opened fire. He killed
two 14-year-old classmates and his teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Unis, who was asked by the prosecution to examine Loukaitis, was
stunned by what he found. Loukaitis was in the throes of depression
so severe he seemed almost catatonic. ``He was cold _ cold and
scary,'' Unis recalled. ``I can't begin to tell you how many times
since then I've thought about him.'' Behind eyes as blank as
marbles, Loukaitis showed no remorse. ``At one point I asked him
what should be done,'' said Unis. ``He told me, `True justice would
be to turn me over to the parents of the kids I killed and let them
do what they want to me.' He was still living by this credo of kill
and be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Unis was unnerved, believing he had gotten a glimpse of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only the beginning,'' he warned prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Unis said he believed that Loukaitis, who wore all black, like
the two Columbine killers, was an extreme example of trends he had
seen in his practice. Although there has been no systematic
analysis of the 10 boys who have committed the recent shootings,
they have shown similar characteristics: severe depression,
isolation, a fixation on death and violence, immersion in violent
video games and, perhaps most striking, an almost total absence of
empathy for their victims. Ramsey, shortly after committing two
murders in his rampage through the halls of Bethel Regional High,
calmly asked state troopers for a sandwich. Witnesses to the
Columbine shootings reported that Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold,
the two apparent perpetrators, gleefully yelled, ``We've waited to
do this our whole lives!''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Gorin, the executive director of the National Association
of School Psychologists, dismissed the theory that the boys were
inherently evil. ``They're not born with different violent
tendencies,'' she said. ``Any more so than kids ever were. It's all
environmental.''
</P>
<P>
   Scales said the difference in adolescence ``these days is the
cocktail that we've got is so much more explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   The mix includes:
</P>
<P>
   --Depression
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Mental Health estimates that 1.5
million children under 18 suffer from serious depression. The
numbers may be much higher, many researchers say, given the
apparent obsession many teens seem to have with suicide.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 Youth Risk Behavior Survey, conducted by the Centers
for Disease Control, more than 1 in 5 students said they had
seriously considered suicide the previous year; 7.7 percent said
they had actually made one or more attempts. Based on Department of
Education figures, the statistics indicate that more than 1 million
high school students attempted suicide last year.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Columbine shootings, in which the killers took their
own lives, most of the school shootings appear to have started as
elaborate plans by the shooters to end their lives in a blaze of
glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just shoot me,'' said 15-year-old Kip Kinkel, after he was
wrestled to the ground at the end of a shooting spree in
Springfield, Ore., last year.
</P>
<P>
   --Video games
</P>
<P>
   The $5.1 billion video-game market, which sold 115 units in
1997, has grown larger than the film industry. Although the vast
majority of the games are non-violent and even educational, some 5
percent are so-called ``point-and-shoot'' games in which the player
employs a full arsenal of weapons to wantonly kill. The systems are
often similar to those designed by the military to break down a
soldier's natural aversion to killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you actually play the point-and-shoot games you are
learning the motor skills to kill,'' said Colonel David Grossman, a
former West Point professor of behavioral sciences and the author
of a 1995 book on how people learn to kill. ``You are being
reinforced, you are being rewarded, not to passively accept the
violence of others, but to inflict the violence yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Immersion in the point-and-shoot games has been a thread
throughout the school shootings, and it surfaced again as a factor
in the Columbine killings. Eric Harris seems to have been an expert
at the so-called Doom series, in which the player's sole mission is
to kill, using everything from a pistol to a grenade launcher to
something called a B.F.G. 2000, which apparently stands for Big
(expletive) Gun.
</P>
<P>
   --Weapons
</P>
<P>
   According to the Youth Risk Behavior Survey, 8.5 percent of
students reported they had carried a gun, knife, or club onto
school property at least once in the previous month. Based on
Department of Education estimates of 14.6 million high-school
students nationwide, the survey indicates that more than 1.2
million students have carried some kind of weapon onto school
property in any given month.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Education reported that 6,093 students were
expelled during the 1996-97 school year for bringing a gun to
school. That number is believed to vastly underestimate the number
of guns in schools; by some estimates, 270,000 guns are taken into
schools each day.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkel, the Springfield, Ore., killer, received a .22-caliber
semiautomatic Ruger rifle, then a .9 mm Glock pistol from his
father. When those were taken away, he bought another gun from a
classmate with $110 he had earned staining his parents' deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The access to guns is unconscionable,'' said Gorin. Referring
to Columbine, she said: ``You can't kill 13 people with a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a first step to respond to the shootings, the Department of
Education issued a list of guidelines last year outlining how to
recognize potentially dangerous students. The guidelines were
issued to 190,000 school principals, but many researchers say the
measures fall woefully short of what is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policymakers have shown an ability to wring their hands, then
tinker around the edges and not face the really difficult issues,''
said Scales.
</P>
<P>
   He and others argue that schools are ill-equipped to deal with
the growing mental health needs of students and should focus on
providing more counselors. But Bill Modzeleski, director of the
Department of Education's safe and drug-free schools program,
questioned whether that was feasible. ``If suddenly we could wave a
magic wand and hire 100,000 more counselors, that would be great,
but that's not how policy is made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Poland, who heads a crisis-management team that treated
traumatized students after shootings in West Paducah, Ky., and
Jonesboro, Ark., has argued that tensions in schools are so high
that students should no longer be left alone after school with so
much time on their hands. ``We may even have to lengthen the school
day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reyne Athanas said answers will be difficult to find. A
former art teacher at Bethel Regional, she tried unsuccessfully to
get Evan Ramsey to give up his shotgun during his rampage through
the halls of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Athanas was sitting in a meeting when someone walked in
and said, ``It's happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   Athanas said she burst into tears. ``I just can't believe it,''
she said. ``It's unbelievable. I feel so, so sorry for those
people. I know what they're going to be going though the next
couple of years. You go through everything from extreme anger, and
then you think about what could have been done and the guilt sets
in. It really runs havoc in your personal relationships, working,
sleeping, and eating. And then everytime it happens, it all comes
back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Athanas said she believed it would.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what it is: It's a mindset, and it's nationwide.
It comes from eveything that seems to be going on in our society
and continues to go on because we're all too apathetic to fix it.
And do I know how to fix it? No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
