u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TENURE-BOS &LR;      04-27 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TENURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS WANTS FEWER TENURED PROFESSORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Noting that the percentage of professors with tenure
is higher at Massachusetts colleges and universities than at
comparable schools nationwide, the state's chancellor of higher
education reducing the number of tenured professors will be a top
priority over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Stanley Z. Koplik stressed that he did not want to
eliminate tenure, which many professors have come to claim as an
inalienable right. But he said, as many college presidents
nationwide have agreed, that the widespread use of tenure has made
it hard for institutions to stay within spending limits and respond
to demands for new courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for greater flexibility,'' Koplik said. ``I don't
think we would compromise the quality of the academic product with
a lower rate of tenure. There are highly regarded institutions
where the rates are lower than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Koplik suggested he and the state's Board of Higher Education
would try to get the state's faculty unions to agree to offer new
faculty the chance to forgo tenure in favor of multi-year contracts
with a higher salary. While a significant portion of schools
nationwide are experimenting with contracts and other piecemeal
changes to tenure, Massachusetts would be the first state system to
institutionalize such a dramatic alternative.
</P>
<P>
   But the suggestion to reduce the ranks of the tenured puts
officials at odds with the state's powerful teachers' unions on
perhaps the most potent issue in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Just under 80 percent of professors at the University of
Massachusetts, state colleges, and community colleges have tenure.
Professors say it gives institutions stability and prestige, by
requiring faculty to prove themselves over six years to earn
tenure. Suggesting that the state is not committed to tenure would
negate the work it has done to improve the quality of public
colleges and UMass, they say, because quality professors would seek
more secure jobs in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Koplik made his comments in an interview Monday discussing the
first annual report on the Condition of Higher Education. New
legislation requires the yearly report to track the state's
progress as it moves toward the goal of making the system one of
the nation's best _ and one of the most affordable _ by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The report documents Massachusetts' widely-touted
accomplishments, most notably the increase in the quality of
students applying to state schools and the consistent decrease in
the cost of attending.
</P>
<P>
   The report shows that schools have pared down administrative
costs and done more to take care of their facilities _ both goals
the Legislature imposed as requirements for getting state funding.
But the high rates of tenure, the report says, present an obstacle
to improvement.
</P>
<P>
   At UMass, 78 percent of faculty have tenure, compared with 70
percent at peer institutions, such as schools in the University of
Wisconsin system and the University of Connecticut. At state
colleges, 76 percent of faculty have tenure, compared with 62
percent of peer institutions, which include public schools in the
New Jersey and New York systems. The contrast is greatest at
community colleges, where 79 percent of Massachusetts faculty have
tenure, compared with 54 percent at peer institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, many systems are making changes in tenure,
which was institutionalized by the American Association of
University Professors in 1915. In 1995, the most recent year with
such data, the rate of faculty with tenure was at its lowest ever,
at 30 percent. Full-time faculty with tenure _ the measure
Massachusetts looks at _ was at 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that about 30 percent of public and private schools
are requiring even those with tenure to undergo periodic reviews.
Last month, the University of Central Arkansas became the first in
the nation to offer new faculty a choice between the tenure track
and a higher salary. In that case, the premium offered was 55
percent. Koplik said Massachusetts would offer somewhere around 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tenure, he said, can make it harder for schools to try to
establish new programs and get rid of ones that are
undersubscribed.
</P>
<P>
   Offering an alternative, he said, ``allows an institution to
make hiring decisions that don't have longer-term consequences. It
allows them to put together programs based upon student demands
much faster.''
</P>
<P>
   The state and community college faculty unions would have to
approve any such change in contract negotiations. With an extension
on their expired contract due to run out June 30, they are under
pressure to come up with a settlement, and are considering a
proposal that would offer some alternative to tenure. But some
union leaders say the discussion of alternatives has driven some
potential faculty to look for jobs in other states. While it is
often portrayed as a cushy lifetime job guarantee, professors say
tenure is their only protection from being fired for unorthodox
views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without tenure, I'd be hard pressed to believe you would not
see firings based on people's different theories about different
issues,'' said Priscilla Lyons, head of the higher education
division for the Massachusetts Teachers Association, which
represents 10,000 professors at UMass and state and community
colleges. ``They say it wouldn't happen but those were the main
reasons that tenure came about _ because those things do happen.
Can somebody seriously persuade me that if we were going to go down
this road that we will attract and retain the best and brightest in
the system? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Professors say it also allows them to resist students' pressure
to inflate grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some kind of protection so we can make evaluations
without repercussions,'' said Brad Art, chairman of the bargaining
committee considering the contract proposal. ``I'm not bothered, I
don't think anybody ought to be bothered, that we have a large
number of tenured professors, because it means we have people
who've proved themselves. Most people want to have experienced
folks doing things for them, their doctors or their lawyers. You
want people who've been in the classroom and doing research. It's
desirable to have more experienced people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
