u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-CRACKS-BOS     04-27 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-CRACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US OFFICIALS SEE SIGNS OF DISCORD WITHIN THE REGIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Events in Yugoslavia over the past two days have
led several US officials to voice a suspicion that the regime of
the Serb leader, Slobodan Milosevic, may be cracking.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing event was a broadcast Sunday by Serbia's
deputy prime minister, Vuk Draskovic, calling on leaders to ``stop
lying to the people in Serbia'' and to admit that ``we cannot
defeat NATO.'' Draskovic repeated the point in an interview with
CNN Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Equally interesting, the Associated Press reported from Belgrade
that Yugoslav Army units Monday took over Studio B, which had aired
Draskovic's comments. Such an act would suggest that his comments
may reflect a genuine fissure, and not, as some had initially
suspected, a propaganda gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   Another report over the weekend had Milosevic placing some of
his top military officers under house arrest. The implication here
would be that they may have been tiring of the NATO bombing
campaign _ which is slowly wrecking the Serbian Army _ and were
trying to foment opposition to Milosevic's policies or even his
rule.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a BBC interview Sunday, in which Milo
Djukanovich, the president of the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro,
said he would mount resistance to any coup attempt against him by
Milosevic's army.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro has come under heavy pressure to abandon pro-Western
leanings, to the point where talk is widespread of a ``creeping
coup'' mounted by Yugoslav troops, according to US officials. Some
officials find it significant that Djukanovich, who has been fairly
quiet on these issues, suddenly feels emboldened to talk about them
in public.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hitchner, director of the center for international
programs at the University of Dayton _ which, since the 1995 Dayton
peace accord, has developed extensive contacts on Balkan issues _
is one of several analysts, in and out of the government, who finds
these developments most interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody at every level is turning their heads a bit at
this,'' Hitchner said in a phone interview. ``You put it all
together, and it suggests there may be some instability high up in
the Yugoslav government.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he cautioned, ``This is all speculation. Clearly,
there's something going on, but what it is exactly, nobody over
here can really say.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchner said he has been ``skeptical'' of the notion _ put
forth by NATO and Pentagon officials _ that the bombing campaign
would drive a wedge between Milosevic and his cronies, who own some
of the factories and other assets being bombed. However, he said,
``You can't rule it out. Too many of these things are going on at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's comments are widely seen as the most intriguing, in
part for their substance, in part for their source. Draskovic used
to be the charismatic, nationalistic leader of the main Serbian
opposition movement to Milosevic. Milosevic had him arrested and
severely beaten in the early 1990s, which made it surprising last
year when the Yugoslav president appointed Draskovic deputy prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchner said that Milosevic was trying to appear amenable to
the West at the time. He wanted to join NATO's ``partnership for
peace'' program. The Western officials who had negotiated with him
on Bosnian issues found Milosevic charming as an individual.
Bringing an old foe like Draskovic into his government, Milosevic
believed, would earn him public-relations points.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Western-outreach is no longer on Milosevic's agenda,
the revival of a rift with Draskovic was considered inevitable. But
Draskovic's public dissent seems to suggest a rift that involves
more than just the two men, Hitchner and some US officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In his broadcast Sunday, Draskovic said the Serbian leaders must
tell their people the truth about ``what will be left of Serbia in
20 days if the bombing continues.'' On CNN Monday, he added that
Serbia is ``very, very alone'' in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Draskovic blasted the West as well. ``Serbia looks very
close to Hiroshima,'' he said on CNN, adding, ``I blame NATO'' for
the destruction, which amounts to ``collective punishment against
one small and innocent nation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a settlement should leave Kosovo as a part of Serbia but
acting ``with a very high level of autonomy.'' He also said all the
Kosovar refugees should return, and that an international force,
under UN auspices, should establish and protect the peace.
</P>
<P>
   US officials have said a UN peacekeeping force would be
acceptable, as long as NATO commanders were ``at its core.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
