<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4989 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTENEGRO-DEFY-BOS &LR;      04-27 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-DEFY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFIANT MONTENEGRO INSISTS IT COULD HOLD ITS OWN  
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CETINJE, Yugoslavia _ It's a tiny, poor region without an army
of its own, under increasing pressure from a better-armed,
more-populous neighbor with a recent track record of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   If Montenegro did the math, it might think twice about defying
Serbia, its larger, sister Yugoslav republic. Montenegro's
population of 600,000 is a mere fraction of Serbia's 10 million.
Its local police force _ estimated at 8,000 to 10,000 _ is without
the heavy-weapons arsenal and air fleet held by the Yugoslav
military.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Montenegrins are unfazed, insisting they could hold off
an attack, be it from NATO or their Serbian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to fight for Montenegro, and we are going to die,
if necessary,'' said Momo Strugar, a 23-year-old electrician in
Cetinje, the historical capital of Montenegro. ``We don't
surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the Balkan mentality, and its roots go back many
centuries. Call it pride or stubbornness, but the behavior of the
often-sparring Balkan peoples is the same: fight to the end, no
matter how formidable the enemy or horrific the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Montenegrins are a very proud people,'' Strugar said. ``And
we won't be the victims of the policies of Slobodan Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Balkan history is filled with stories of glorious battles, and
the tales continue to rally the region's ethnic groups _ even if
they lost.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1389 the Serbs lost to the Turks at Kosovo
Polje, ushering in a half-millennium of brutal Turkish rule.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Serbs still celebrate this failed battle every year, and
Yugoslav President Milosevic has successfully whipped up resentment
among modern-day Serbs to gain support for his behavior toward
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrins have a long war history, including 400 battles
in 1,000 years, many of them against the Turks, said Radoje
Pajovic, a historian at the University of Podgorica. But as nearly
any Montenegrin schoolchild can recite, tiny Montenegro was the
only territory that held off the Ottoman Empire, sometimes in
battles where the Turks outnumbered them by as much as 10 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   While the Montenegrins accepted the authority of Turkish rule
during the 16th and 17th centuries, the local ruling government was
made up of Montenegrins, Pajovic notes.
</P>
<P>
   The main museum in Cetinje, the historical heart of Montenegro,
is a celebration of the resistance against the Turks. Set in the
onetime home of King Nikola I, it displays 47 captured Turkish
flags, and a collection of seized weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   The Turks vastly outnumbered the Montenegrins, but the locals
``knew the land, knew the canyons and the mountains,'' said
Pajovic. A typical tactic was to lure the Turks into a valley,
surround them, and kill them, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of years have passed, and modern warfare tends toward
high-tech weaponry. The defiant Balkan mentality, however, endures.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army, a ragtag, civilian force outfitted
at first with only smuggled Kalashnikovs, took on the Serbs last
year despite being vastly overmatched by the Yugoslav military.
More than a year after open fighting began, Kosovar Albanians have
been run out by the hundreds of thousands, and their houses have
been burned.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the KLA survives and continues to recruit, its leaders
say, despite the overwhelming power of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the KLA's enemy, Milosevic, backed down in the face of
the greater military power of NATO. After a month of bombing,
Milosevic is still standing up against the most powerful military
force in the world, and among Serbs and Montenegrins, ``he is
getting stronger and stronger with each bomb that is dropping,''
notes Nenad Markovic, a 20-year-old Montenegrin civilian who says
he detests Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO ``wants to kill our dignity, but they won't succeed,'' said
a pro-Milosevic speaker at a recent demonstration here. ``We'd
rather lose our heads than our souls.''
</P>
<P>
   Big weapons don't seem to deter people in this region, who in
many ways still fight on a level that is centuries old.
</P>
<P>
   The Western military alliance leaders count their planes and
missiles, use advanced radar technology, and speak of ``degrading''
Yugoslav military ability. Modern Western warfare is characterized
by terms like ``surgical strike'' and ``collateral damage,'' a
phrase used to describe unintended civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a brutal intimacy to Balkan warfare. The battles of
this century _ even this decade _ are characterized by tales of
gouging out of eyes, mass graves, and point-blank executions.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, families in the northern mountains still participate
in blood feuds; if a family member is killed, the male head of the
clan is obliged to murder a family member of the first killer.
</P>
<P>
   With a war at their border and threatening to spill over,
Montenegrins don't talk about weapons technology, or a matchup of
troops and guns. Instead, they insist their determination and pride
alone is sufficient to fend off an attacker, be it NATO ground
troops or Yugoslav Army soldiers bent on bringing the local
Montenegrin police under their control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic needs an obedient Montenegro,'' said Radomir
Sekulovic, an adviser to the anti-Milosevic Montenegrin government
of Milo Djukanovic. But the republic will not give in, he said,
adding: ``The Montenegrin people _ civilians, also _ will defend
Montenegro from any aggression from Serbs, even from NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrins sound fearless in their defiance of the Milosevic
regime. Sekulovic called him ``a killer, a barbarian, a leader of
thugs,'' while the Montenegrin prime minister, Filip Vujanovic,
called Momir Bulatovic, Yugoslav's prime minister, mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Young men here openly evade the draft; the justice minister,
Dragan Soc, has refused conscription and gives a sarcastic salute
when he passes the military court on his way to work.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Army soldiers in Montenegro alone outnumber the
local police by as much as 4 to 1, sources said. But should a fight
break out, Montenegrin loyalists could be as successful as their
predecessors were against the Ottoman Empire, said Miodrag
Ilickovic, a member of Parliament from the Socialist Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 170,000 men,'' he replied when asked how Montenegro
could hold off bigger and more powerful foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Turks never conquered us,'' he said. ``Our way of fighting
is original. No one can fight better than Montenegro in the
mountains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
