<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-27 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WILL OF NATO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- To get pseudo-macho for a second, Slobodan
Milosevic has not cried ``uncle'' after one month of NATO's
initially limited and probing military campaign against his
murderous regime.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Milosevic has cried ``nephew'' _ far from good enough,
but revealing nonetheless. There's going to be a lot more of that
as NATO continues to remove the limits on the campaign and as a
flurry of diplomatic activity centered on Russia unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   As all this occurs, it will become even more clear how an
astonishing gathering of NATO and all of its official partners here
proved pivotal. Far from being a planned birthday bash that got
hijacked by horror, the summit was either an example or a harbinger
of what NATO can be if it lives out the meaning of its freshly
vigilant creed. Apart from the dinners, the interminable parade of
available big shots and the speeches, the success of the gathering
was driven home by three events that got far less attention _ a
private dinner, a phone call, and a testy meeting about Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner, on the eve of the summit's opening, from which many
of the alliance's next moves flowed, joined President Clinton and
Britain's Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   The phone call, also before the summit, linked Clinton and Prime
Minister Antonio Guterres of Portugal in an excellent example of
alliance politics in action.
</P>
<P>
   And the testy meeting was between Republican Representative Curt
Weldom of Pennsylvania and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbot.
It stopped an incipient attempt at amateur diplomacy involving
Russia and Yugoslavia almost on the eve of the announcement of
Talbot's own crucial mission to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, these events are a window on the key element in
NATO's campaign: will.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Clinton are not NATO's inner cabinet; the unity behind
this campaign is much broader and deeper than that. But they are
leading through some skillful agenda setting, Blair more publicly
and Clinton less so, as became apparent over last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The best example is the evolving strategy for the bombing
campaign and the preparations for possible use of ground troops in
Kosovo in some form of combat.
</P>
<P>
   With hindsight, it is clear that NATO could not have united all
at once behind an all-out air assault and the positioning of tens
of thousands of troops on the Albanian and/or Macedonian borders.
</P>
<P>
   It is also clear that it should not have. Clinton was right to
remark that it is obvious that no bomb, no matter where it is
dropped, can stop a thug from murdering a civilian. But it's also
true that an all-out assault after the breakup of the Rambouillet
negotiations in March would have been politically pointless as
well.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, it was Milosevic's mass murder and aggression
via refugees that demonstrated his true intentions. The escalation
that followed is on him, not NATO. It was no accident that after
Blair and Clinton met, the bombing intensified, military commanders
got more of the direct targeting authority they properly seek, a
halting but determined effort to deny Milosevic's military machine
its petroleum began, and the politics of ground troops changed.
</P>
<P>
   As British officials have said, an invasion a la Persian Gulf is
not the idea. Instead, planning has begun for the possible
insertion of 100,000 troops against Yugoslav forces, which have
been seriously battered from the air but not to the point where
Milosevic has formally met the NATO demand that he withdraw them.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the alliance together as all this moves ahead is
grinding daily work, as Clinton's presummit chat with Guterres
demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal is firmly aboard on Kosovo, but Portugal has other
concerns. In particular, it has been up to its ears recently in
helping negotiate a tentative deal for the separation of its
long-ago colony, East Timor, from its brutal annexors in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   For any deal to work, Indonesia's new rulers need to clamp down
on militias tied to it that are still violent. The United States
can help put pressure on, and should. Hearing Guterres out and
responding is part of what allies do for each other; good politics
and good diplmacy.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy, however, is not for congressional dabblers in the
middle of a crisis, as Weldon discovered. With buddies in the
Russian Duma, he was preparing to travel to Belgrade and Moscow
this week. For a skilled manipulator like Milosevic looking for
wedges and wiggle room, it would have been a major opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   And the Clinton administration was right to step on Weldon hard.
Subsequent events have only made the intervention by Talbot more
appropriate _ oil embargo dangers, Boris Yeltsin's long private
chat by phone with Clinton over the weekend, and Talbot's own
mission.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a responsible role for Russia in this madness _
in the Balkans directly and as part of the broader international
background at the United Nations as well. But that is a topic for
people who represent nations, not legislative factions.
</P>
<P>
   The picture that emerges from all this is not neat or always
completely clear, and it is maddening as the horror in Kosovo
continues.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a picture of will being applied relentlessly. And that
is why the cry of ``nephew'' has been heard, which will become
``uncle'' if the will is maintained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
