<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FURST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW GROWTH OF THE FRENCH RESISTANCE IS SUBJECT OF ``RED GOLD''
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RED GOLD 
By Alan Furst 
Random House, 258 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Furst's last novel, ``The World at Night,'' wasn't his
best, but it introduced his most compelling character: Jean Casson,
film director, sensual man, and almost-accidental patriot who finds
himself participating in the French Resistance even before it
really existed in any organized way.
</P>
<P>
   Furst's new book brings Casson back, and ``Red Gold'' may be
Furst's finest achievement to date. In this area of accomplishment,
Furst belongs in the select company of Charles McCarry and John le
Carre.
</P>
<P>
   Furst published his debut novel in 1976 and followed it up with
three others, which he no longer bothers to include in the list of
his works. In 1988 he discovered home ground with ``Night
Soldiers,'' which led to four successors, including ``Red Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Furst's great subject is Europe in the period just before he was
born, the years, beginning in 1938, that led to World War II.
Countless novels and films have made this familiar ground _ so
familiar that most contemporary genre writers have chosen to avoid
it, even though historians and memorists have recovered much
incident and detail that was unknown to writers like Eric Ambler
who staked out the territory in fiction at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge is therefore one factor in Furst's superiority. He
knows the players, the board, the language, the culture, the
tradecraft, the landscape, and, intimately, the interior weather.
He's also an excellent, understated, observant writer. There is a
gritty, gray reality in his work that is absent from the popular
collective _ and selective _ memory of the period.
</P>
<P>
   The point was brought home to Furst in 1990 when he wrote a
column for the International Herald Tribune commemorating the fall
of Paris to the Germans 50 years earlier. ``I got hammered for
it,'' Furst has said in an interview, because the article ``took
off its hat and tiptoed down the hallway of French history.''
Critical letters pointed out how many Frenchmen did actively or
passively collaborate with the Germans, and how long it took the
resistance to develop. It was this controversy that led him to
write ``The World at Night'' and now ``Red Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The World at Night,'' Furst may have wandered down a blind
alley when he tried to incorporate a doomed romance worthy of the
movies. That book ended when Casson, on a boat to safety, dives off
and swims back to France, where his love and destiny lie. ``Red
Gold'' opens in September 1941; Jews are being rounded up and
``deported.'' Casson is back in Paris, desperate for money, wanted
by the Gestapo, and entirely cut off from his old life in the world
of films, society, and commerce _ a world he can follow only in the
newspapers, which report that it is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Casson's colleagues had natures more accommodating, or
realistic, than his. ``Up in Passy, his former life went on.
Marie-Claire and Bruno, the Arnauds and the Pichards, would be
chattering over after-dinner drinks. Good talk, witty and dry _
life was irony. No doubt they would be talking about the affreux _
dreadful _ Germans. Not so affreux, of course, that one refused to
get rich off them.'' Casson, on the other hand, is a romantic, but
one without many remaining illusions.
</P>
<P>
   Casson is approached with a dangerous mission. Will he establish
contact with the Communists, whose members are well-placed to help
with sabotage operations? The Communists, deeply underground, have
no desire to be contacted by anyone; they are profoundly and justly
suspicious of their class enemies. What happens in the eight months
covered by the book, and why, is not something for a review to
reveal, but it's worth pointing out that the characters have a
strong grasp of political purpose, nuance, and expediency which
reflects that of their creator.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in Furst's superiority to the competition is a
novelistic ability that transcends the requirements of genre
fiction. He knows how to spin out a suspenseful story, but this is
not a mechanical process for him. Casson participates in a couple
of loosely related operations in ``Red Gold,'' and some other
operations are described because they play a role in what happens
to him. But Furst is not interested in a mechanically perfect plot.
What interests him instead is ordinary people and their response to
extraordinary events _ responses that reveal how extraordinary most
people are. Furst is not a sentimentalist, nor does he bother with
political correctness; his characters are complex mixtures of
qualities that make them capable of surprising us _ and surprising
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The five mature Furst novels are interlinked; the focus of each
book is different, but characters and places reappear. ``Red Gold''
is the first real sequel in the series, and there are welcome hints
that others will follow _ characters are carefully introduced who
have no real function beyond contributing to a texture of
dislocation and dread, at least yet. The book ends ambiguously with
the suggestion that a new adventure for Jean Casson might lie
behind a doorway, and let's hope it does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
