A4995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMOUS-FALL-BOS &LR;      04-27 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMOUS-FALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL MADE FAMOUS IN PHOTO STRUGGLING FOR A HAPPY ENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The image of a tiny girl and a young woman frozen in
midair _ arms awkwardly outstretched as they fell to the ground _
was burned into the memory of almost everyone who saw it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hot July day nearly 25 years ago when Diana Bryant, who
was only 19 years old, stood on the rusty fire escape of her
burning Back Bay apartment, clinging to a Boston firefighter and
trying to shield her godchild from the flames. They were only
seconds from safety when the fire escape collapsed, plunging Bryant
five stories to her death. The little girl, 2-year-old Tiare Jones,
whose fall may have been cushioned by Bryant's body, escaped
without serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Only moments before, Stanley Forman, a 30-year-old photographer
for the Boston Herald American, had arrived at the scene; he
captured the moment in a series of photographs that were so searing
they were published in 400 newspapers the following day and
ultimately won him a 1976 Pulitzer prize. Forman's pictures will be
among a handful featured in a TNT documentary this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Forman is now a WCVB-TV photographer, and he asks: How is Tiare?
``I always wondered how she made out.'' Forman, who would go on to
win another Pulitzer the year after photographing the accident,
hasn't seen her since a few days after the 1975 fire, when she
returned home from the hospital and he brought her a teddy bear.
</P>
<P>
   For Tiare Jones, her stunning survival and the brief moment of
public adoration that followed weren't portents of a happy life:
For many years, she continued to fall, eventually landing in a
halfway house from which she now is working to uplift herself.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the little girl in the picture is 26 years old and a
mother herself. Almost since the day she escaped death, her life
has been marked by pain. She has been in and out of foster homes
and has in the past dealt with substance and domestic abuse. Three
years ago, she was separated from her four daughters, ranging in
age from 2 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, though, Tiare (pronounced Tee-are-rah) Jones
has begun to remake a life that nearly shattered almost a quarter
century ago. And this time, she says, she is determined to succeed.
As a condition of regaining custody of three of her children that
were taken by the Department of Social Services, she is living in
the halfway house in suburban Boston. She already has custody of
her oldest daughter, Antoinette, 9, who has been living with her
since February.
</P>
<P>
   In a Framingham dental office, Jones recently showed Antoinette
a photograph of herself taken just days after the 1975 fire while
she was still in the hospital. Antoinette looked intently at the
picture and began to cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor mummy,'' Antoinette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a long time ago,'' Jones whispered, wiping her
daughter's tears.
</P>
<P>
   But Antoinette persisted, asking for more details about the fire
and about the woman who saved her mother's life: ``Was she a good
woman, mummy?''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, she was. Diana Bryant was a Boston hairdresser
who loved children. She was especially fond of Tiare and her
sister, Keysha, the two young daughters of Pat Jones, a 25-year-old
single mother who worked as a keypunch operator for Bank of Boston.
Bryant had volunteered to baby sit for Tiare for a few days at her
new apartment, giving Jones something of a break.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Jones was unaware of the fire at the five-story apartment on
Marlborough Street until she peered at someone's newspaper on the
trolley ride to work the morning of July 23 and saw her daughter's
eyes staring back at her from the front page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screamed: `That's my baby. That's my baby,' '' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She jumped off at the next trolley stop in a blur, and rushed to
her apartment in the Mission Hill housing development; soon after,
she was reunited with her daughter at New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so little, with all these tubes and machines connected
to her,'' recalled Tiare's sister, Keysha Jones, who is now 29.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was devastating to the Jones family, but the years
before the fire already had been difficult for Tiare's mother. She
was fairly new to the city, having recently moved from a small town
in Maryland, and she was struggling to find friends and build a
stable life for her two girls.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the unthinkable happened.
</P>
<P>
   Strangers tried to help, sending good wishes and money.
Eventually, the excitement around the little survivor died down,
and Pat Jones stopped talking about what had happened. For years,
Tiare Jones said, she remembered nothing about the experience. She
said she only learned about it when she was 12 years old and
stumbled across the Forman photo on a shelf in her mother's
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was too young, but I remember everything,'' said Keysha,
who was 4 in 1975. ``That fire was just the first of a downward
spiral for our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Ronnie, disappeared from her life, and then, only
two years later, the family lived through yet another fire; and
although there were no fatalities, the consequences were
devastating. In the midst of the 1978 blizzard, while their mother
was out shopping for food, Tiare and Keysha started playing with
matches in bed and set their Mission Hill apartment on fire.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Pat Jones was working two jobs _ one at Bank of
Boston and another at Boston Edison, where she still works today.
After the fire, she says she asked for help from DSS and in the
course of the agency's inquiry, DSS asked her to quit one of her
jobs so she could supervise her children more closely. She refused,
and soon afterward, her two girls were taken into DSS custody.
Tiare was 4 and Keysha, 6. The three never lived together
permanently again. The girls were in and out of foster homes for
most of the rest of their childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stupid. I didn't know the rules,'' said Pat Jones.
``That's why I plead to Tiare not to make the same mistake. There
are no shortcuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat never forgave herself for nearly losing her daughter twice.
To compensate, she showered her with all the material things a
steady job could offer. ``Whenever she fell again, I tried to
cushion her fall,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tiare felt alone, Keysha said. ``I tried to look after
her.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Tiare was smart, well-spoken, and good in English
and math, she never focused on her studies at Brighton High School.
Instead, she hung out with the wrong crowd, experimented with
drugs, and had a child at 16. By 25, she would have four children.
Through the years, Tiare said, she stayed in a relationship with a
man who was abusive.
</P>
<P>
   Her world fell apart when DSS took her children. Today, she
said, she and Antoinette ``never talk about the day DSS came.''
</P>
<P>
   But during the past three years, when she has had only limited
visits with her children, she began to see things differently.
After those visits, she would write down her feelings as she rode
home on the T, sometimes scribbling them on a bag from a doughnut
shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose to one day have a normal life,'' she said. ``I didn't
want to be a statistic _ black female, drugs, kids gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the picture Forman took of her almost 25 years ago has
taken on new meaning: ``Now, she says ``I could see how it must
feel to almost lose your own child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
