<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTS-RIGHTS-BOS &LR;      04-27 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR PARENTS RIGHTS OPENS A DOMESTIC DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Joanna Upton got fired from her job in 1993, she
said, because she refused to attend a business meeting when her boy
was sick or to work a 60-hour week. A single mother who sued her
employer for parent discrimination and lost, Upton is just the
woman the White House is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Harvey Schwartz, Upton's attorney in Boston, sent a
letter to Vice President Al Gore last week, as soon as he heard
about a new Clinton administration initiative aimed at making it
illegal for employers to discriminate against parents in hiring,
firing, and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls every day from people who've worked 10, 20, 30
years and think they are putting their job on the line if they go
to their child's hockey game,'' Schwartz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt the White House also wants to appear attentive
to the tensions between work and family obligations. It's a hot
topic around many American dinner tables, a big headache for job
recruiters, and a political issue candidates in 2000 will ignore at
their peril, pollsters say.
</P>
<P>
   But to some, this new idea of making ``parent'' a protected
class under the law, like race, gender, age, or religion, is an
overdose of legal Prozac to treat a personal and cultural anxiety
and an expensive political solution in search of an unmeasured
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether a working parent has to take time off to go to a
soccer game or stay home with a sick child isn't a legal issue.
It's a problem of life, and in a free society, life is full of
choices,'' said Roger Pilon, director of the Center for
Constitutional Studies at the libertarian Cato Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates insist the initiative isn't about giving a mother the
right to slap a lawsuit on a boss who makes her miss a ballet
recital, or letting a father haul an employer into court if he has
to work a weekend. It is not aimed at mandating companies to have
family-friendly policies, either, such as providing on-site day
care or no-overtime rules.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says this is about eliminating a more subtle
discrimination that punishes parents in the workplace. It happens
when an employer hires a nonparent over a parent, believing the
former will be more productive and require fewer benefits. It
occurs when a boss steers a parent off a path of career advancement
on the assumption that the applicant won't be able to handle the
extra travel or longer hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at overt discrimination by employers who,
through demonstrated hostility or mistaken belief, say parents
can't do a job,'' said Bruce Reed, President Clinton's domestic
policy adviser. ``This won't do any good for parents who don't
measure up or won't put in the hours'' to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Single mothers seeking their first post-welfare job are
particularly vulnerable to parent discrimination, some family
advocates say, but it also can be a worry for single fathers, the
fastest-growing segment of the parenting population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is getting at old-fashioned prejudice, and it doesn't
matter how much of that there is,'' said Donna Lenhoff, general
counsel of the National Partnership for Women and Families, a
private group. ``If it is there, it should be eradicated.''
</P>
<P>
   In a survey done last year for the National Partnership, 62
percent of the women and 55 percent of the men said finding time
for both work and family responsibilities has gotten harder in the
last five years. In the poll, 92 percent of the Democratic
respondents and 87 percent of the Republicans said employers and
businesses should do more to help working families.
</P>
<P>
   But are many parents really victims of discrimination? The White
House admits its evidence of the problem is mostly anecdotal. In
the eight states that do bar parent discrimination in employment,
``it has not been a hugely litigated issue,'' said a spokeswoman
for Senator Christopher Dodd, a Connecticut Democrat who intends to
introduce the White House initiative as legislation next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scratching my head,'' said Isabel Sawhill, a senior fellow
at the liberal-leaning Brookings Institution and a longtime
economic and employment policy maker. ``I don't know what the
problem is. I don't see a lot of evidence that employers are
discriminating against parents, particularly at this point in
history, when employers are competing to attract mothers into the
work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawhill said she puts antidiscrimination legislation far down
the list of things that working parents really need, such as
subsidized child care.
</P>
<P>
   ``But since there isn't a lot of money around for tangible
things, this proposal could be pure symbolism, because everybody
wants to be in favor of kids and parents these days,'' Sawhill
said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dodd has no GOP co-sponsors for his bill, but the Cato
Institute's Pilon said he expects the legislation to attract wide
bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of proposal is tailor-made for the Republican
family-values types,'' Pilon said. ``They will be hard-pressed to
oppose it because they will be shown to be either hard-nosed in the
defense of business or hypocritical in the defense of family
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, proposals aimed at easing the burden of working parents
are plentiful these days. The Clinton administration is pushing to
expand the 1993 Family and Medical Leave Act so it would apply to
businesses with as few as 25 employees. Currently, companies with
50 or more workers must provide up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave for
the birth or adoption of a child or for a family illness. Five
bills are pending in the Massachusetts Legislature that would
expand benefits under the act, including finding ways to pay for
now-uncompensated leaves.
</P>
<P>
   After he lost the Upton case, Schwartz lobbied the state
legislature to pass a bill barring job discrimination against
parents, but his efforts failed. If the administration's initiative
were law, Schwartz said, ``Joanna Upton would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court threw out Upton's suit
against now-defunct JWP Businessland because no law explicitly
prohibited workplace discrimination against parents. Still, the
court wrote in its 1997 opinion, ``we sympathize with the
difficulties of persons who have faced the challenge of reconciling
parental responsibilities with the demands of employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers without children aren't always sympathetic. They
sometimes feel exploited or discriminated against by employers who
seem to bend over backward to accommodate parents' needs. No one is
contemplating giving childless workers the right to sue for such
bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good family policy shouldn't divide the populace so privileges
go to parents, and employees who don't have families feel like they
are the ones being discriminated against,'' said Barbara Brandt of
Somerville, Mass., a national spokesperson for the Shorter
Work-Time Group, which advocates a shorter work week.
</P>
<P>
   Others find different faults with it. David Rubin, a Boston
lawyer who represents employers, said many companies are still
struggling to administer the Family and Medical Leave Act, and this
initiative would cause ``huge problems'' by creating new avenues
for costly and time-consuming litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Sawhill speculates that making parents a legal category could be
counterproductive. The more burdens parent-workers put on
businesses, the less likely employers may be to hire them, even
though that's what the proposal is designed to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the modern American dream: We can all get ahead by
filing lawsuits,'' said Allan Carlson, president of the Howard
Center for Family, Religion, and Society in Rockford, Ill. ``But if
you really believe that families are important and should be
uplifted in this society, then reducing parents to yet another
victim class is the radically wrong approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
