<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, April 28,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ The House is scheduled to vote
Wednesday on U.S. involvement in the Kosovo conflict, leaders said
Tuesday. Votes are planned on whether to invoke the War Powers Act,
which would start the clock on a withdrawal of U.S. forces, and on
a declaration of war against Yugoslavia. The House may also vote on
a bill requiring President Clinton to obtain congressional approval
before sending ground troops to fight in the Balkans. (Malone, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest in the continually
escalating U.S.-led NATO bombing of Serb military targets in
Yugoslavia. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHES _ TIRANA, Albania _ A folo on the crash of the
Apache helicopter on training mission Monday night. Developing.
(Albright, Cox News Service) 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ The latest developments in
the Kosovar Albanian refugee situation. Developing. (Kunstel, Cox
News Service) 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   USCHINA _ WASHINGTON _ The House committee investigating the
sale of commercial satellite technology to the Chinese will show in
a forthcoming report that spying by China was more pervasive than
previously believed and extended to more top-secret laboratories
than the incident in Los Alamos, the AJC has learned. (Carr, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BLACKS _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore Jr. may not
have the eloquence or understanding of political rival Bill Bradley
on racial matters, but Gore's personal ``connection'' to the modern
civil rights movement gives him a valuable calling card with
African Americans in his bid for the Democratic presidential
nomination. (Shepard, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-MINORITIES _ WASHINGTON _ Former Health and Human
Services Secretary Louis Sullivan and other experts release a study
showing that attitudes toward health care among blacks and
Hispanics contribute to the health gap between the races. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-SAFETY _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Commerce Committee holds
a hearing on effectiveness of the Office of Motor Carrier and Truck
Safety. (Dart, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS _ WEST BANK, GAZA _ PLO leaders meet to vote
on extending the deadline for declaring a Palestinian state and
continue peace negotiations with the Israeli government.
Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ARMENIAN-GENOCIDE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ My father, Nishan
Kalajian, had the misfortune to be born in the city of Diyarbakir
in southeastern Turkey in 1912, a desperate and convulsive time in
the disintegrating Ottoman Empire. He was 3 years old when the
soldiers came first to take the young men, including his father,
and then returned for all the other Armenians. The pattern was
repeated in village after village. The ensuing slaughter was
eventually given a formal name: The Armenian Genocide. The ghostly
survivors became almost as familiar to newspaper readers of their
time as the refugees from Kosovo are today. The starving Armenians,
as they were widely known, became an international cause. And then
they were forgotten so completely that the people who rule their
land today can blandly deny that anything so awful ever happened.
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-TENSION _ ATLANTA _ Tension is high at just about every
school in America. The last week or so has seen plenty of bomb
scares and rumors and scared moms and dads in metro Atlanta. There
are reports that one middle school has been evacuated each of the
last three school days. Two other schools were evacuated today,
including one where some pipe devices wrapped in duct tape and with
a fuse were found. School was dismissed for the day. At the other,
students went back to school. Within mintues, 100 or so parents _
some broken with fear _ gathered at make-shift information center,
waiting on news that they're kids were OK. Most acknowledge that
the events of the last week or so have left their emotional cups
full. This became overflow. ``Enough. We can't take anymore,'' one
parent said. This type fear built last spring. Now it's even worse.
(Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENT-VIDEO-GAMES _ AUSTIN _ What do Austin gaming companies
have to say about the critics who say their violent games
contributed to the Colorado massacre. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-ROBBER _ Follow to Forrest Tucker, the 78-year-old bank
robber: How many PBCo. bank robberies is he suspected of? There
were two guns found in his car. Were they loaded? What did the
Jupiter bank robbery victims think of him? Is his former
partner-in-crime, Mr. Green, still alive, and if so, does he have
anything to say? Who is his girlfriend and what does she have to
say? What's he do for money (assuming he can't live on bank booty)?
Does he get social security? Did he have a particular MO that would
tell us something about him? Like calling the tellers
``sweethearts'' or ``young lady''? (Mossman, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   LA-HOUSE _ METAIRIE, La. _ When former U.S. Cong. Bob Livingston
(R-La.) resigned amid scandal on the same day President Clinton was
impeached, folks from every walk of life rushed to fill his shoes.
Among the nine candidates in the May 1 special election: A wizard,
a virgin, and Monica. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LA-DUKE _ HAMMOND, La. _ ''People either love me or hate me,''
said David Duke, the former Ku Klux Klansman who is making his
sixth run for public office _ to replace U.S. Cong. Bob Livingston
in Louisiana's First Congressional District. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-SHELTER _ GREENE CO., Ohio _ For 20 years, the Greene
County Domestic Violence Project has closely guarded the secret
location of its shelter for battered women. The safe haven has been
kept so confidential that even victims who call for help are not
given the address until after they are directed to the police. But
the nonprofit agency plans to take a bold step out from the shadows
next spring when it breaks ground for a new shelter whose location
will be publicized deliberately to the community. (Kissell, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
