   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-BRIBE (Washington) _ A unanimous Supreme Court rules in
favor of strict interpretation of the illegal gratuity law. A
company, Sun-Diamond Growers, an agricultural cooperative, had been
convicted of giving improper gifts to Mike Espy, the former
secretary of agriculture. Sun-Diamond appealed and the court ruled
that such a conviction can only stand if there was an official act
in exchange for the gifts. This has no direct effect on the
corruption case in which Espy was acquitted on all charges. By
Linda Greenhouse. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CASINOS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court hears arguments
in a commercial speech case that challenges the federal law banning
TV advertisements for casinos. Plus a roundup of other court
actions. By Linda Greenhouse. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Washington) _ More details of Clinton's
gun-control proposal, including the president's actual words, which
will be watched carefully to see how forceful he is about the NRA.
By Katharine Q. Seelye. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-STRATEGY (Washington) _ A political memo on how
congressional Republicans are buoyed by internal polls showing that
the GOP has recovered from impeachment and that the Kosovo war is
doing what Monica Lewinsky never could _ drive down the president's
approval ratings. These developments help explain the GOP's
strategy for this year: do as little as possible and make no waves.
By Alison Mitchell. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-DRUGS (Washington) _ The drug and alcohol problem here is
more severe than in most cities in the United States, and not
enough is being done to help, according to a new report on drug use
and its impact on the community. (800 words)
</P>
