<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-GUTERSON-AZR &LR;      04-27 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GUTERSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SNOW' AUTHOR'S SENSE OF PLACE IMBUES NOVEL WITH CHARACTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(With sidebar, Book-Guterson) 
 
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first thing you realize during a conversation with David
Guterson is that he's not what the media have made him out to be.
</P>
<P>
   It's true he has helped them along. He has showed up for
interviews wearing flannel shirts, which reporters have parlayed
into a Guterson trademark. He has posed for dramatic photographs in
the forests near his home on Bainbridge Island, Wash., a short
ferry ride from Seattle and the model for the setting of his
bestselling first novel, ``Snow Falling on Cedars.'' He even smiled
for the cameras when ``People'' magazine named him one of ``The 50
Most Beautiful People in the World,'' noting his
``strong-shouldered'' looks and anointing him ``the thinking man's
Grizzly Adams.''
</P>
<P>
   He survived all of this with apparent good nature, but it's easy
to imagine him cringing in retrospect. Guterson speaks with a
methodical earnestness that makes him sound more like a professor
than a celebrity lumberjack, and he has handled the success of
``Snow'' _ it has sold more than 2.5 million copies, a miraculous
performance for a literary novel _ with a serenity that approaches
nonchalance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my temperament,'' he says. ``I'm pretty detached from it,
and it's really kind of divorced from my actual life. The truth is,
you can't just fall into the whirlwind. You have to stand outside
of it and learn to manage it. If you don't, if you just let it all
happen to you, you're in trouble. I'm fortunate that ``Snow Falling
on Cedars'' has done so well, but the important thing to me, and
the most enjoyable thing, is to be working on the next book.''
</P>
<P>
   That next book is ``East of the Mountains'' (Harcourt Brace,
$25), Guterson's much-awaited second novel, which was released this
past week. It's the story of Ben Givens, a 73-year-old retired
surgeon who has terminal cancer. The book begins with Ben's plan to
take his own life before the disease destroys him, but it turns
into an eventful journey to his childhood home amid the apple
orchards of eastern Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' this novel contains a character
that transcends all others: the landscape. It was fixed in
Guterson's mind long before he invented any of his human
characters, and it is one of the elements that always drives his
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I begin, always, with theme,'' he says. ``I engage in a
process of self-reflection, asking myself what it is that I care
about the most, what issues are foremost for me at a given time.
After that, what I want to evoke is landscape _ a sense of place, a
love of that place or at least very strong feelings for it. Then I
ponder what sort of character and what sort of conditions will
allow me to address these themes in this landscape. That's my
starting place for storytelling.''
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Snow,'' Guterson's new book is filled with the history
of its setting, the country along the eastern bank of the Columbia
River. In the early days, Ben Givens' father tells him, a
schoolhouse was pulled on skids from farm to farm each summer so
residents would share the burden of boarding the accompanying
teacher. Theirs was a stoic existence that produced people like
Ben's mother, who died when he was a boy but whose presence lingers
throughout the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a character in ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' Ishmael
Chambers' mother, who had something of the same feeling,'' Guterson
says. ``Both of these mothers are clear-headed, energetic people,
and powerful influences in their sons' lives. I admire women like
that, and I've felt a closeness to certain older women in my life.
It was like that with one of my high school teachers, and it's like
that with an editor I have right now. They're strong women, and I
guess that comes out in the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Guterson began writing ``East of the Mountains'' in 1993, just
after he completed ``Snow Falling on Cedars.'' Since then, things
have changed considerably for him. Before the success of ``Snow,''
which took eight years to finish, he taught high school English on
Bainbridge Island, rising at 4:30 each morning to work on his novel
before he moved on to his responsibilities. He, his wife and their
four children still rent the same modest house, but he no longer
teaches or struggles to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   He was reportedly paid more than $1 million for film rights to
``Snow'' ``Falling on Cedars.'' The movie, directed by Scott Hicks
(``Shin''e) from a screenplay by Ron Bass (``Rain Ma''n), will be
out this fall. Guterson helped scout locations in Alaska,
Washington and British Columbia, and he assisted in revising the
screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an author, you have to recognize that this is a different
medium with different artistic goals, that it can't possibly be
what the book is, nor should it be,'' he says. ``In other words,
you have to remind yourself that you're a participant in someone
else's artistic attempt. If you try to control it, you're in
trouble. It was a good experience for me. I've seen the film and
it's brilliant, and I hope people will respond well to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he never felt compelled to write a second novel that
would live up to the critical and commercial success of his first.
</P>
<P>
   What has been the most rewarding aspect of success?
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit down at my desk and write a story and it ripples out in
all directions and suffuses people's lives,'' he says. ``I find
students at high schools and colleges with hardbound editions of
the book that are ragged and marked with notes because they've been
thinking about it, talking about it, writing papers about it and
sort of being shaped by it. That's enormously gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   And the downside of success? When Guterson answers he sounds
genuinely uncomfortable, an amiable man who cannot find a way to
please.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unsettling that at readings there are often other writers
present, and they ask questions about how to accomplish your goals,
how to connect with readers,'' he says. ``If I could answer those
questions, I'd be grateful for the opportunity. But I don't know
the answers. I have no secrets. I sense that's what they want _
some mystery that I know the answer to and they don't. I just tell
them what they've heard before. Work hard, and keep on working. I
don't know what else to say.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
