A5016 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GUTERSON-AZR &LR;      04-27 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GUTERSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOUNTAINS' TAKES SENTENCE TO LOFTY HEIGHTS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(Sidebar to Author-Guterson) 
 
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Bass, who is known for writing stories marked by a profound
sense of place, once said that in reading fiction we should
remember that it's not just books that are important, but the
sentences within them.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to think otherwise, to judge a novel by the cohesive
effect of its story, and in many instances that's the way it should
be. But there are quiet moments in David Guterson's new book,
``East of the'' ``Mountains,'' that have nothing to do with what
happens in its pages, and everything to do with what happens in its
sentences _ in the patience and language with which they are
rendered, and in the power that simple description can have in the
hands of a deeply reflective writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``East of the Mountains'' is, at its core, a road trip. Retired
Seattle heart surgeon Ben Givens has terminal cancer and is
determined to spare his family the misery of his slow demise by
taking his own life before illness incapacitates him. Through a
series of mishaps, beginning with an accident that destroys his
car, he and his dogs are left far from home and dependent, for a
while, on the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   They meet several, and all are unremarkable _ if this succession
of minor characters was the best Guterson had to offer, his book
would be a disappointment. But Ben's journey is suffused with
memories of his youth, of his parents and his courtship of his
wife, Rachel (they were married for 50 years before her death), of
his experiences during World War II and, finally, of the orchards
of central Washington where he was raised.
</P>
<P>
   Guterson's descriptions of these people and places are written
with such patience that they seem lavish. There is one chapter, in
which he traces the history of the orchards and the Givens family,
that is a novel in itself. Ben's mother appears on Page 69 and
becomes so real by the time she dies on Page 77 that many readers
will turn weepy at seeing her go.
</P>
<P>
   Guterson's first novel, ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' was
lyrically written but not without problems, including a too-easy
resolution of the murder trial that was its climax. There is no
simple resolution in ``East of the Mountains,'' but the book's
appeal is not in the destination. It's in the getting there. That's
not a bad trade-off when you're in the company of a man who writes
sentences so well. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
