<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-BLACKS28-COX     04-27 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BLACKS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE CITES FAMILY'S HISTORY IN BID FOR BLACK SUPPORT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore is evoking his personal
``connection'' to the modern civil rights movement, giving him a
valuable calling card with African Americans as he pursues a
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gore name means something to the black community,'' Rep.
John Lewis, a Georgia Democrat who was at the forefront of voting
rights demonstrations in the Deep South in the 1960s, said in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Wednesday night in New York, Gore will be the subject of
a special tribute at the Black Leadership Forum's annual gala.
About 500 African American leaders will be on hand for the Gore
salute.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture comes as Democrats are trying to secure the backing
of a constituency vital to its hopes in next year's elections, and
as Gore battles Bill Bradley for the chance to compete as the
party's presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore benefits tremendously from the near-legendary rapport of
President Clinton with black voters and from the administration's
steadfast defense of affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president's most personal link to black America
came just three weeks before his eighth birthday.
</P>
<P>
   It was March 1956 and his father, then a U.S. senator, refused
to sign the ``Southern Manifesto'' calling on Southern lawmakers to
support their states in defying desegregation rulings by the
Supreme Court. Al Gore Sr. and fellow Tennessean Estes Kefauver
were the only two senators from old Confederacy states who did not
sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a speech Sunday night to the Detroit chapter of the
NAACP, paid tribute to his father's stands against racism, and in
doing so, subtly reminded African Americans of a political debt
owed to his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a connection to that struggle and to the NAACP in a
personal way,'' Gore said. ``My father was a United States senator
from the South who had courage. He fought against the poll tax in
the 1940s, and for civil rights in the '50s. He was one of only two
senators to refuse to sign the hateful Southern Manifesto. He voted
for the Voting Rights Act of 1965, and he voted against Supreme
Court nominees whose commitment was respect. And those brave stands
probably cost him his career.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Gore's career ended in 1970, for a variety of
reasons, some of which had nothing to do with his positions on
racial matters. But clearly, his progressive stands on race,
including a vote in his final term in the Senate against a ban on
using busing to integrate schools, endeared him to civil rights
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former U.S. senator from New Jersey, a basketball
Hall of Famer and Gore's sole rival for the 2000 presidential
nomination, has also stood with African Americans in times of
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Following George Bush's 1988 presidential election, a campaign
that featured the notoriously racist Willie Horton ad that
benefited Bush, Bradley delivered a speech to the National Press
Club drawing on his pro basketball career in an eloquent challenge
to the president to do more to improve race relations in America.
</P>
<P>
   And after the police beating of Rodney King in Los Angeles,
Bradley went to the floor of the Senate to condemn the brutality,
dramatically hitting the lectern with a pencil 56 times to simulate
the blows delivered to King's body.
</P>
<P>
   And in a speech last week, Bradley promised that racial
tolerance would be a key element of his presidency, if elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ronald Reagan was president, everyone knew that if you
wanted to please the boss, you cut taxes, increased military
spending and found communism,'' Bradley said. ``If I'm president, I
want one thing to be known: If you want to please the boss, one of
the things you'd better show is how in your department or agency
you've furthered tolerance and racial understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some African American leaders were ``put off by
Bradley's abandoning his Senate seat'' in 1996, said Julian Bond,
the former Georgia politician who is now chairman of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bradley ``seems to talk about ideals,'' Bond added
in an interview, ``but what is also needed _ and is much harder to
talk about _ is strong legal remedies'' to racial bias. And in
that, Gore benefits politically from Clinton's ``generally good
record on civil rights,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his speech Sunday night, sought to build on that
benefit, emphasizing the continuing need for affirmative action,
the anti-discrimination programs born that are under legal and
legislative challenge today as illegal ``preferences'' for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the critics of affirmative action,'' Gore said.
``They're in favor of affirmative action if you can dunk the
basketball or sink a three-point shot. But they're not in favor of
it if you merely have the potential to be a leader of your
community and bring people together, to teach people who are hungry
for knowledge, to heal families who need medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
