<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-SMOKING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO RAISES FINES FOR SMOKING SCOFFLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A sequence of increased fines for those who
repeatedly violate California's smoking ban in San Francisco bars
is expected to force tavern owners to discourage nicotine addicts
from lighting up.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Health Department spokeswoman Eileen Shields
announced Monday that Superior Court judges, at the urging of
health officials and the city attorney's office, agreed to change
the fine structure from a flat $77 per violation to penalties that
increase with each infraction.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons who caught smoking in bars will now face fines that jump
to $136 on the second violation in a year and $271 on the third.
The fines also pertain to bar owners or their employees who don't
enforce the ban.
</P>
<P>
   The new fines went into effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to have some effect on owners,'' said Thomas
Rivard, senior environmental health inspector. ``The chances of
citing a patron a second or third time are less likely unless you
stumble on the same patron. But owners are at much greater risks of
getting second and third violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, when health inspectors and the
police began cracking down on outlaw bars in San Francisco, 78
citations have been issued. While the majority of those cited for
smoking have been patrons, seven owners and one bartender have also
been fined.
</P>
<P>
   The anit-smoking law, passed in 1994, was intended to protect
restaurant patrons and employees from secondhand smoke. Bars were
forced to abide by the law in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Under state guidelines, penalties for bar owners who allow
smoking in their establishments can be $100 for the first offense,
$200 for the second and $500 for subsequent violations within one
year's time. After the third offense, the state Occupational Safety
and Health Administration may be asked to investigate, which could
result in a fine of up to $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows local governments to set fines for both bar
owners and patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was graduated (fines) all along,'' said Gary
Clayton, a bartender at the Hole in the Wall Saloon on in San
Francisco. ``Those bureaucrats can't help playing mother, can
they?''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said since the ban was imposed inside free-standing
bars, business has declined.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Joy of the American Lung Association in Daly City welcomed
the increased penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were hoping for higher fines,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   California is the only state that prohibits smoking in
free-standing bars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
