<P>
   EVOLUTION OF THE TELEVISION: Industry executives are crowing
over digital TV, but when will the rest of us start to care?
Despite the cost, though, HDTV is slowly but surely entering the
marketplace. (Includes one 4-column color illustration.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Just in time for the Year 2000 bug, comes a
software program called GoBack, that recovers files that have been
deleted or written over, lost from virus attacks or lost from
problems stemming from installation and system crashes. (Includes
1-column color photo.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: Over the years, writing a technology column,
I've urged you to rush out and buy faster modems, bigger computers,
more memory for the computer you own, scanners for your
photographs, shortwave radios and even a fancy telescope. Now I'm
going to tell you what not to buy: the Pentium III. (Includes
1-column color mug shot of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRENDS: It took only a glance at the 268-page program
guide for the spring Comdex/Windows World conference to see what's
going on in the computer industry: Computer hardware manufacturers
are stepping out of the limelight while Internet and on-line
networking services are taking center stage. (Includes 6 pica color
mug shot of Bill Gates.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   HIP ICELAND: Perhaps Iceland never crossed your travel radar. It
is, after all, way up on top of the globe. But it's become a hot
spot for young Americans, especially college spring breakers
trolling for an experience beyond the ordinary. Plus, the sights,
such as beaches made of volcanic lava, are awesome to behold.
(Includes 3-column color photo of partiers in bar, 2-column color
photo of aurora borealis and 1-column color photo of statue of
explorer Leif Ericson.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INFO BOX: Bring plenty of cash when traveling to Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ICELAND NIGHTLIFE: Always quick to ferret out the latest
hot spot, the media lately has developed a tic for painting
Reykjavik as an Arctic Bangkok, seething with the exotic and the
erotic. In truth, it's basically a small town that marries Euro
ultra mod and Old World quaintness, with residents who display both
Continental savoir-faire and British civility.
</P>
<P>
   ICELAND BEAUTY: Icelanders apparently do not feel the urge, as
Americans do, to put up billboards telling tourists where all the
cool stuff is. It's not hidden, but you have to know where to look.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: If you would like to rent a luxury car in
London, Avis has inaugurated a program that it says can guarantee
you the make and model you want within 24 hours of your request.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS, ONE COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY TITANS: Ernest Hemingway and Vladimir Nabokov could not
have been more different. To mark the 100th anniversary of their
births, there is a flurry of new and reissued books. (Includes one
3-column color illustration of Hemingway and Nabokov.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEMINGWAY: Ernest Hemingway once said he wanted no
biography of himself written while he was alive and preferably not
for a hundred years after he died. He was granted the first wish,
but not the second. (Includes 1-column color illustration of
Hemingway.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEMINGWAY LIST: A list of forthcoming books about
Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NABOKOV: On the centenary of his birth, Vladimir Nabokov
has never thrown off the criticism that his novels and stories were
those of a dilettante. (Includes 1-column color illustration of
Nabokov.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NABOKOV LIST: A list of forthcoming books on Nabokov.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: In a world focused on the conflict of
Kosovo, another book on Clinton's infidelities seems to matter less
every day. (Includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION, TWO COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD ALIENATION: The American teen-ager: yearning to stand out,
and desperate to fit in. Struggling to be a rebel, yet terrified of
losing status with the cool group. It is an age of alienation. A
sense of being on the outside looking in is ``typical in
adolescence, from 12 to 18,'' say experts who deal with teens. Such
alienation breeds feelings of rejection. What makes a troubled kid
cross the line into real anger, and real violence? (Includes
6-column color illustration of teen caught in whirlwind, 1-column
color photo of teens comforting each other.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BOOK EXCERPT: The ability of children to manage anger and
handle conflict is a topic of conversation in the wake of the
school shootings in Colorado. During the next five weeks, the
SCIHEALTH page will feature excerpts of a book that addresses the
conflict issue, ''Tired of Yelling.'' Part 1 will deal with
reflexive defensiveness _ a conditioned, rapid, automatic response
of resistance children develop that limits communication and shuts
down learning. (Includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
