<SLUG> BC-PAGEEXPRESS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PageExpress budget for the week of April 26, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
April 27.
</P>
<P>
   To be delivered on Friday, April 30, 1999, by 2 p.m.
 &UR; FOCUS (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., April 30) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOS OF AL GORE, INCLUDING ONE
OF VICE PRESIDENT SHAKING HANDS WITH SUPPORTERS AND ONE OF HIM
RELAXING WITH WIFE TIPPER.
</P>
<P>
   WHO IS AL GORE? Now is Al Gore's time to tell us who he is. The
vice president says he has a compelling vision of where we want to
go as a nation, how we can get there and how we can live better
lives when we arrive. For the next 18 months, Gore will tell us why
he wants to be president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., April 29) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SIX COLOR PHOTOS AND 2 COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE NELSON: Everybody doesn't like something, but nobody
doesn't like Willie Nelson. The ponytailed
songwriter-turned-singer-turned-star-turned-actor-turned-icon is,
in so many ways, a little of something for everyone: a one-man
democratic state. (Will include a 3-column color illustration of
Willie Nelson.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WILLIE FILE: A box outlining the life and music of Willie
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN: A 2-column color graphic,
``Countdown to `Star Wars,''' outlining the number of days
remaining until `The Phantom Menace' opens.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR FILE: Salma Hayek, the bewitching Mexican bombshell,
is a tad somber. Today, anyway. Legs tucked under her, she's
perched on a couch receiving reporters one at a time. Although a
childhood prankster, Hayek, 30, isn't one to make mirth, as if
being all business will make folks take her more seriously. (Either
that, or she's never been asked which Pop-Tart is her favorite.
It's strawberry). (Will include a 1-column color photo of Hayek.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: Reviews of ``Elizabeth,'' ``Happiness'' and
``Stepmom.'' (Will include a 2-column color photo from
``Elizabeth.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: On his first new album in seven years, Tom
Waits fancies himself a scarecrow: a kind of '40s film noir
scarecrow, from whose grimy black suit-coat tumbles a whiskey
bottle, a big soup bone, a pocket watch, a post horn and a sheet of
music.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR (Available by 5 p.m., Thu., April 29) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE COLOR PHOTOS, ONE 2-COLUMN TRACK ILLUSTRATION
AND TWO 6-PICA THUMBS-UP, THUMBS DOWN ILLUSTRATIONS.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR LEAD STORY: Topic to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP NOTES
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IN THE PITS:
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRACK GRAPHIC: A 2-column color illustration of California
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RACE AT A GLANCE: A preview of Sunday's California 500
presented by NAPA at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES 2 COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ETHNIC EATING: All the signs indicate that we will only continue
to stir ethnic cuisines into our daily eating habits. No place
bears witness to this trend better than the local supermarket.
(Includes one 4-column color photo of Peanut Noodle Salad and one
1-column color photo of man stirring a dish in a wok.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Chipolte Chicken Enchiladas, Peanut Noodle Salad.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE: If the thought of gritty hot dogs and
marshmallows on a stick has turned you against spending much time
in the great outdoors, think again. Camp-side gourmets have taken
up the challenge and have transformed typical outdoor grub into
camp-side cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPE: Skillet Cheddar Toasts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   FORD RANGER: Extra doors are the big deal these days for trucks
and vans, and Ford has taken that concept to the max with the '99
Ranger compact pickup. Just add $660 to the purchase price, and the
hot-selling Ranger becomes a four-door vehicle. (Includes 3-column
color photo of a Ranger Sport Supercab, 2-column color photo of
Ranger Sport Supercab's interior and 1-column detail photo of
logo.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box previewing the 1999 Ford Ranger
Sport Supercab.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING: It has rubber floor mats, no air bags, no
5-mph bumpers and a sticker price of $97,100. I've never felt safer
in any vehicle in my life. What is it? It's a Hummer, of course.
When offered the opportunity to test-drive the Hummer, I
halfheartedly accepted. But after a week with my competition yellow
civilian version of the same vehicle that our troops are using
around the world, I came away a fan.(Includes 1-column color
photograph of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS, 1 COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   EVOLUTION OF THE TELEVISION: Industry executives are crowing
over digital TV, but when will the rest of us start to care?
Despite the cost, though, HDTV is slowly but surely entering the
marketplace. (Includes one 4-column color illustration.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Just in time for the Year 2000 bug, comes a
software program called GoBack, that recovers files that have been
deleted or written over, lost from virus attacks or lost from
problems stemming from installation and system crashes. (Includes
1-column color photo.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: Over the years, writing a technology column,
I've urged you to rush out and buy faster modems, bigger computers,
more memory for the computer you own, scanners for your
photographs, shortwave radios and even a fancy telescope. Now I'm
going to tell you what not to buy: the Pentium III. (Includes
1-column color mug shot of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRENDS: It took only a glance at the 268-page program
guide for the spring Comdex/Windows World conference to see what's
going on in the computer industry: Computer hardware manufacturers
are stepping out of the limelight while Internet and on-line
networking services are taking center stage. (Includes 6 pica color
mug shot of Bill Gates.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   HIP ICELAND: Perhaps Iceland never crossed your travel radar. It
is, after all, way up on top of the globe. But it's become a hot
spot for young Americans, especially college spring breakers
trolling for an experience beyond the ordinary. Plus, the sights,
such as beaches made of volcanic lava, are awesome to behold.
(Includes 3-column color photo of partiers in bar, 2-column color
photo of aurora borealis and 1-column color photo of statue of
explorer Leif Ericson.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INFO BOX: Bring plenty of cash when traveling to Iceland.
</P>
<P>
