<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIAD-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS FIGHTER HAS A LIKE-MINDED DAUGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How many children does Muhammad Ali have?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.P., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Ali has eight adult children and a ninth, a son named Asaad,
who is 7 years old.
</P>
<P>
   His youngest daughter, 21-year-old Laila Ali, announced in
February that she's training to become a boxer and expects to
schedule her first bout this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ali's other children, in order of their ages, are Maryum, twins
Rasheeda and Jamillah, Miya, Muhammad Jr., Khalilah and Hana.
</P>
<P>
   Jamillah was a marketing executive for Muhammad Ali Rotisserie
Chicken in the mid-'90s, Maryum released a rap album, and Khalilah
had a part in the 1979 movie ``The China Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one of Ali's children isn't a boxing fan. ``I would
have it banned if I could,'' Rasheeda Ali told the ``New York Daily
News.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In what year did Bill ``Hopalong Cassidy'' Boyd die, and
where is he buried?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.L., Shrewsbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Boyd died on Sept. 12, 1972, at age 77 and is buried at
Forest Lawn Cemetery in Glendale, Calif., according to Find a Grave
at www.findagrave.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 1935 film ``Hop-a-long Cassidy'' was the first of 66 to star
Boyd as the character. Boyd acquired the rights to all of the
movies in the 1950s, and they're being sold today by Hopalong
Cassidy Enterprises at the Web site www.hopalong.com.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a fan club. For more information, write to Hopalong
Cassidy Fan Club International, 6310 Friendship Drive, New Concord,
OH 43762-9708.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Ted Turner?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.G., Prospect Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Turner at 1 CNN Center, Box 105366, Atlanta, GA
30348-5366.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who was ranked 19th on Forbes' 1998 list of the 400
richest Americans, is worth an estimated $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of Cable News Network and TBS, Turner sold his
broadcasting company to Time Warner in 1996 for $7.57 billion,
becoming the company's vice chairman and largest stockholder.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, Turner pledged $1 billion to the United
Nations for humanitarian causes, creating the United Nations
Foundation to administer the donation.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Turner reportedly told a group that he was ``very
serious about running for president,'' according to Newsday.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
