A5052 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENELOPE-CRUZ-LADN     04-27 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENELOPE-CRUZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH ACTRESS WON'T BE A STRANGER FOR LONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spanish actress Penelope Cruz is still adjusting
to the peculiarities of working in America _ the differences in
language, the longer hours, the bowling lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to bowl now; I really didn't have a choice,'' Cruz
says with a laugh. ``Billy Bob (Thornton) almost requires it if
you're in one of his movies, and it's actually kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz just finished filming Thornton's big-screen adaptation of
the Cormac McCarthy lyrical western best-seller ``All the Pretty
Horses'' in San Antonio. The film is her second cowboy picture.
Cruz played Billy Crudup's consolation-prize girlfriend last year
in Stephen Frears' little-seen ``The Hi-Lo Country.'' With Matt
Damon headlining, ``All the Pretty Horses'' should find a much
wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, who turns 25 today, is due for much wider recognition,
too. Already a star in Spain through movies like the Oscar-winning
``Belle Epoque'' and the recent favorite ``The Girl of Your
Dreams,'' Cruz will be seen by American audiences in at least three
films this year. In theaters now is the excellent psychological
thriller, ``Open Your Eyes''; coming in early June is ``Twice Upon
a Yesterday'' a smart and funny romantic fantasy in the vein of
``Sliding Doors.'' ``The Girl of Your Dreams,'' for which Cruz won
the Goya for best actress, should be in theaters by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Cruz will still be able to roam the streets here
largely unrecognized until ``All the Pretty Horses'' opens next
year. And that suits her just fine since the Spanish paparazzi have
been known to chase her all around Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot go on holiday there,'' Cruz says. ``Last summer, I
was lying on a secluded beach and they came up to me with a
television camera and microphone. I'm there in a bikini, totally
embarrassed. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Crazy that they found her on a secluded beach or crazy that the
beautiful Cruz was self-conscious in a swimsuit? Probably a little
of both.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Cruz talks about the good things Spain has to offer, why
she likes mysterious men and the advantages of being a foreign
actress in an American bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You spent more than a year going after your role in ``All the
Pretty Horses.'' What was the attraction?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: It's just so amazing, so rich and full of heart and soul.
I had to convince a lot of people that I was right for the part
because I have not made many movies in America. But it was worth
everything I did. It's going to be a beautiful movie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The film has a lot of horseback riding. Have you spent much
time on a horse?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: I have now! We began training four weeks before the movie
started. I rode bareback five hours every day for almost that
entire time. They gave us exercises that were supposed to help with
the soreness, but the first few days were terrible. I didn't think
my butt or my legs would ever recover.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Any secrets to bareback riding?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: Find a big horse. They're scarier, but once you're on,
they're easier to ride.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And how is Billy Bob as a director?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: Very interesting. He knows everything you're thinking so
he can surprise you a lot. Sometimes he gives you directions that
seem like the opposite of what you should do. But that's part of
his plan. He asks you to do something else in order to get what he
really wants. It makes you much more free and alert and in the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You didn't mind the bowling?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: It was a lot of fun. (Co-stars) Matt (Damon) and Henry
(Thomas) had lots of tips. All the guys did.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'll bet. Did you improve?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: Not really. Sometimes, at the end of the night, I would
take all the balls left over and go up and down the alley and roll
them all down. The owner would get a little mad, but I would shrug
my shoulders and pretend not to understand. That's when being from
Spain comes in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do love about your native country?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: I love the people here in America and the way they work.
But sometimes, when I was living in New York, I felt like people
were thinking too much about work and not taking care of the other
part of their life.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, we enjoy life better. Everything is closed from 2 to 5
in the afternoon and then reopens from 5 until 8. People work and
have what they need for living and at the same time, they take care
of their family and take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You were 17 when you made your first movie (``Jamon Jamon'').
The role was pretty sexy. Were you ready for that?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: It was a great part, but you're right, I wasn't really
ready for the nudity. But I have no regrets because I wanted to
start working and it changed my life. So even if I went through
some difficult things, I learned a lot. I saw what I wanted to do
and what I wasn't prepared for.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the biggest lesson you learned?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: Follow your heart. It doesn't always pay as much, but it's
not worth it to do a movie just for the money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you ever fall for an Englishman like you do in ``Twice
Upon a Yesterday''?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: My boyfriend is Czech. So I don't want to fall for anyone
else because I'm very happy with him. But he speaks English. He's
learning Spanish because Czech is too difficult. It would take me
15 years just to learn the basics.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the film, men and women seem often communicate on two
completely different levels. What about men remains a mystery to
you?
</P>
<P>
   CRUZ: A lot of things. But that's good because men don't
understand a lot of things about women. There has to be a little
mystery. Men say we're crazy, and we think they are the crazy ones.
In truth, all of us are crazy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
