<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUN-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY AND THE BEAST: HOW TO PROTECT THE SKIN FROM SUN'S RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the missive that wandered around the Internet
last year, one of the gems of life-advice was: ``Wear your
sunscreen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise words (they were falsely attributed to Kurt Vonnegut as his
commencement address to Vassar College, and actually written by a
Chicago-based journalist), given that skin cancer rates are
increasing at the rate of four percent a year, and one person in
every six will have some form of skin cancer during the course of
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sun is a major risk factor for skin cancer and melanoma. And sun
is the major cause _ along with cigarette smoke _ of premature
aging. Photoaging is what sun damage is called. The results are
brown sun spots, collagen collapse and deep lines and wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing, though. Sun damage is almost totally avoidable,
just by taking certain precautions: Stay out of direct sun when you
can and use sunscreen or sunblock to keep harmful ultraviolet
radiation from doing a little toxic dance on your skin.
</P>
<P>
   A number of dermatologists in this country have spent hours in
the lab, seeking ways to prevent sun damage and mitigate existing
problems.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Dr. Sheldon Pinnell, 62, the J. Lamar Callaway
Professor of Dermatology at Duke University in North Carolina. He
is the medical and scientific adviser to the SkinCeuticals skin
care line which specializes in topical Vitamin C (L-ascorbic acid)
skin products, including a line of moisturizers with sunblock.
</P>
<P>
   I am very reluctant to recommend any kind of beauty product. But
SkinCeuticals' moisturizers with sunblock are such good products
with no serious downsides that I can't resist.
</P>
<P>
   SkinCeuticals is not the kind of line you will find on counters
at department stores. It is one you will find at your
dermatologist's office or facialist's salon.
</P>
<P>
   But so many preparations, particularly the ``organic''
sunscreens, can be very occlusive (pore-clogging). The culprit in
this case is OMC or oroxymetho-oxycinnimate, an ingredient in most
over-the-counter products.
</P>
<P>
   If you have small pores or sensitive skin, this ingredient,
which screens out the harmful short ultraviolet rays that cause
sunburn, or UVBs, can make your skin break out. The ``physical''
blockers, usually Parsol (avobenzone) and titanium dioxide, are
designed to screen out the more insidious, longer ultraviolet rays,
the UVAs (or the ``agers.'') But they don't block out everything.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two or three years, the one physical blocker that
has taken care of both UVA and UVB rays is a product called Z-Cote,
a transparent form of zinc oxide, the noxious white stuff that
lifeguards wear on their noses. Pinnell and his research team have
been working with Z-Cote and as a result, SkinCeuticals put it in
their combination moisturizer and sunblock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't tell people to stay out of the sun,'' Pinnell said in
a telephone interview. ``If you tell people that, they'll think
you're nuts. People feel better when they've been in the sun. So I
am interested in people being able to be in the sun if they have a
way of protecting themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinnell said there were three things to remember about getting
sun exposure: ``The most important thing (for) protection is the
right clothing. Stay covered up. Secondly, stay out of the noonday
sun. If you're out of the sun between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m., you've
avoided 80 percent of the UVB radiation and 70 percent of the
UVA.''
</P>
<P>
   The third step is wear sunblock on your face, hands, ears, the
back of your neck and on the line of bare scalp where you part your
hair.
</P>
<P>
   SkinCeuticals products include a very high concentration of
Z-Cote. ``We're pushing the limits,'' Pinnell said. ``With SPF 30
in the Ultimate Sun Defense (cream), it protects people who are at
very high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   You're in this category if you are of Irish-English extraction
with white-white skin and freckles, or anyone with sensitive skin
or skin that sunburns easily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What I particularly like about this line is that the two
products, one with SPF 20 and the other with SPF 30, go on easily,
don't cause skin eruptions and provide a smooth base for foundation
makeup. Another plus: Unlike sunscreen products that wash off when
you swim or sweat, these creams do not need reapplication every two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Pinnell's other contribution to the SkinCeuticals line is the
Vitamin C or antioxidant products. His team at Duke University
found that L-ascorbic acid is the only form of Vitamin C that our
bodies can actually absorb through the skin and use. Since the body
cannot store Vitamin C, Pinnell and others have worked to develop a
topical formula that would allow Vitamin C to penetrate and protect
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   How does this work?
</P>
<P>
   ``When light hits the skin,'' Pinnell said, ``it bombards the
tissue and you have more damage than the body can repair or protect
against.''
</P>
<P>
   With products like SkinCeuticals' Vitamin C and sun-care lines,
damage from the sun can be kept at a minimum. In some cases, these
high-tech antioxidant products have reversed minor sun damage and
promote collagen production.
</P>
<P>
   To my mind, these products are ushering in a new age of hope in
a jar and truly are miracle creams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
