<BODY>
 AM-R-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, April 28.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ The Pentagon formally asks for
National Guard and Reserves; President Clinton is expected to sign
the order today. Other developments.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments on Kosovo: Strobe Talbott,
the deputy secretary of state, and Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian
special envoy, hold talks. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO's top commmander, Gen. Wesley
Clark, gives a briefing today, his first in some time. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Developments in the Yugoslav
capital: At least two Yugoslav officials are talking about a
negotiated deal; one says he hopes a framework could emerge in a
week or so. The Red Cross says the three U.S. POW's are in
``satisfactory'' condition. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Dateline to kum) _ More refugees cross the
frontier into Macedonia; 3,000 on Tuesday, 11,000 in the last five
days. There is no room for them in the existing camps, so the
refugees are being accommodated in sleeping bags under plastic
sheets. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ A month of war in Europe has already
brought deep changes to the continent, awakening a new sense of
European patriotism, rekindling tensions over ``American
imperialism'' and reviving the sagging fortunes of some leaders. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on the complexities of
assembling and deploying ground forces and stories of sexual
assaults on refugee women.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Gaza City, Gaza Strip) _ The Palestinian
Central Council meets to decide whether to proceed with or delay a
unilateral declaration of statehood on May 4. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S. (Tokyo) _ The lower house of Parliament on Tuesday
passed crucial legislation to improve military cooperation with the
United States, smoothing the way for Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's
departure Thursday for a summit meeting with President Clinton. By
Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Bangkok) _ President B.J. Habibie of Indonesia
announced Tuesday that a referendum would be held Aug. 8 in the
territory of East Timor to allow residents to choose whether to
accept a plan giving them autonomous status within Indonesia. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-BRIBE (Washington) _ A unanimous Supreme Court rules in
favor of strict interpretation of the illegal gratuity law. A
company, Sun-Diamond Growers, an agricultural cooperative, had been
convicted of giving improper gifts to Mike Espy, the former
secretary of agriculture. Sun-Diamond appealed and the court ruled
that such a conviction can only stand if there was an official act
in exchange for the gifts. This has no direct effect on the
corruption case in which Espy was acquitted on all charges. By
Linda Greenhouse. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CASINOS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court hears arguments
in a commercial speech case that challenges the federal law banning
TV advertisements for casinos. Plus a roundup of other court
actions. By Linda Greenhouse. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Washington) _ More details of Clinton's
gun-control proposal, including the president's actual words, which
will be watched carefully to see how forceful he is about the NRA.
By Katharine Q. Seelye. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-STRATEGY (Washington) _ A political memo on how
congressional Republicans are buoyed by internal polls showing that
the GOP has recovered from impeachment and that the Kosovo war is
doing what Monica Lewinsky never could _ drive down the president's
approval ratings. These developments help explain the GOP's
strategy for this year: do as little as possible and make no waves.
By Alison Mitchell. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-DRUGS (Washington) _ The drug and alcohol problem here is
more severe than in most cities in the United States, and not
enough is being done to help, according to a new report on drug use
and its impact on the community. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTING &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Ledeall on the
continuing investigation of the shootings as Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SANDERS (Littleton, Colo.) _ A look at how William
Sanders, the Columbine teacher, died; what efforts were made and
what happened. By Jodie Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHRINE (Undated) _ On the need to create shrines,
like the giant one growing even bigger in Littleton, Colo. People
still decorate the fence in Oklahoma City. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SWAT (Undated) _ Everybody watched what seemed like
a slow-motion deployment of a SWAT team in Littleton, raising a lot
of questions about the Littleton SWAT team and how well it
performed. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ARK-INDICT (Little Rock, Ark.) _ The U.S. attorney in Little
Rock shakes the Arkansas political establishment by indicting a
large number of current and former members of the General Assembly.
The lawmakers, along with several prominent lobbyists, are charged
with handing out state contracts and grants to relatives and
friends. Although long expected, the indictments represent the
biggest political scandal in Arkansas in years, exposing the cozy
relationships between lawyers, lobbyists and legislators. They stem
from a report in a weekly newspaper two years ago. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (`'f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T reports a 39 percent rise in
first-quarter earnings, surpassing Wall Street expectations, as
revenue from cellular phone, corporate phones and other services
more than offset a further decline in its flagship long-distance
business. The story will also look at the company's regulatory
hurdles and other obstacles to the MediaOne deal. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   PARKPLACE-STARWOOD (Undated) _ Park Place Entertainment, a
spinoff of Hilton, has agreed to acquire Starwood Hotels and
Resorts Worldwide's Caesars World Gaming unit for $3 billion in
cash. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   (See also SCOTUS-CASINOS, under WASHINGTON.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:55 p.m., the Dow was up 82 points, the
Nasdaq down 38 points. Elsewhere, stocks were higher in Europe,
with the FTSE 100 up 1.5 percent, Paris up 2.16 percent and
Frankfurt up 1.8 percent. In Japan, stocks were little changed,
while Hong Kong rose 1.8 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE-DISH-TV (Washington) _ The House passes a bill that
would allow satellite dish companies to offer local TV stations to
their customers. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SALIM (Jakarta) _ Anthony Salim, the chief executive
Salim Group, Indonesia's largest conglomerate, had both a success
and a setback Tuesday in his effort to salvage his tottering
empire. Salim's stutter-step progress is being closely watched here
as an indication of how Indonesia's corporate sector will climb out
from its crushing debt burden. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   G7-MEETING (Washington) _ The Group of Seven finance ministers
continue to meet. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties.''
</P>
