<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLLHOUSES-$ADV02-COX     04-27 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLHOUSES-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELABORATE DOLL HOUSES A GIFT TO D.A.R.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories for
release Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leonora Rocca Phelan delights in talking about her
``darling little homes.'' She revels in the delicate antique French
lace on the curtains and the unique period portraits decorating the
walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got most of the lace in the flea market in Paris. I would
find bits of old lace and old material,'' she said. ``And I framed
every picture you see.''
</P>
<P>
   The houses _ four in all _ took Phelan more than 20 years to
fill with precious items she found all over the world _ each one
small enough to hold with two fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could still play with doll houses,'' said the
great-grandmother of eight. ``I still love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelan was honored last week for donating the doll houses to the
National Society Daughters of the American Revolution (NSDAR).
During a ceremony at the group's annual meeting, she received the
Unity award, including a gold medal that she proudly wore around
her neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a marvelous group of women. What an honor,'' she said,
after the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan resides in Sabillasville, Md., and Palm Beach, Fla.,
where she is an organizing member of the Henry Morrison Flagler
Chapter of NSDAR. She was accompanied at the event by her friend
and housekeeper of fifty years, Annie Stuart, who worked
extensively with Phelan decorating the houses.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan said Stuart's steady hands were vital as they added
pieces to the intricate rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is faultless,'' said Phelan. ``I just knocked things over
with my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   While collecting miniatures for about four decades, Phelan
didn't start decorating and furnishing doll houses until 1975 as a
diversion when caring for her aging mother.
</P>
<P>
   She bought her first doll house _ the American Country House _
from Thomas J. Iocono after seeing some of his work at a fair in
Lancaster, Pa. ``I fell in love with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The house opens from the front in two sections revealing a
removable wing, a vintage bathroom and a primitive American country
kitchen. On the front exterior, an open porch crosses the house.
The interior includes a separate upstairs hallway, bedrooms,
parlors and a dining room.
</P>
<P>
   The furnishings include some pieces marked with original price
tags on the label of Woodward &AMP; Lathrop, a Washington department
store. It also features furniture made in Germany by Schneegass for
FAO Schwartz in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   All four doll houses feature hundreds of pieces _ many of them
rare and valuable antiques. The Cape May doll house includes a
collection of Carol Boyd dolls and several painted Elizabeth
Andrews pieces with an emphasis on chinoiserie.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas House, dense with charming details, features
miniature colored spools of thread in a sewing room and tiny tubes
of paint next to a miniature easel in an artist's studio. The
studio is a tribute to Phelan's late husband, Leo J. Rocca, in
whose memory the houses were donated.
</P>
<P>
   While Phelan has a hard time picking her favorite doll house,
she has a special attachment to the Georgetown House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the wedding house,'' she said. Phelan decorated the
house to match a special event in her own life, her granddaughter's
wedding. The 1880s house has an elegant bedroom where a bride is
getting ready for her ceremony. Downstairs in a dining room, a
banquet is set up for the celebration, while a baker in the kitchen
prepares dessert.
</P>
<P>
   ``See the little pie safe,'' said Phelan, her blue eyes
sparkling as she pointed to a tiny basket surrounding a miniature
pie. ``I forgot I had that,'' she said, with a giddy smile.
</P>
<P>
   The four houses are on permanent display at the NSDAR
headquarters in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1890, the NSDAR has nearly 3,000 chapters in all 50
states. The group also has chapters in Australia, Canada, France,
Mexico, Japan and the United Kingdom. NSDAR objectives include
``historic preservation, promotion of education and patriotic
endeavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelan said the well-visited headquarters is the perfect place
for her cherished doll houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an answer to a prayer,'' she said. ``They should be put
where everybody can see them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
