<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Bombs beat diplomacy as NATO forces
strike the headquarters of President Slobodan Milosevic's party for
the second time. Meanwhile, nothing concrete emerges from talks in
Moscow on a possible end to the conflict with Yugoslavia. By CRAGG
HINES.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Over objections from Republican
congressional leaders and the Clinton administration, the House
will vote on the Kosovo conflict Wednesday. The votes are being
forced by Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., whose resolutions call for
either declaring war or withdrawing U.S. forces from the Balkans.
By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Washington) _ The White House unveils latest
gun-control proposals, but Republican congressional leaders say the
Clinton administration's blueprint is not the answer to stopping
incidents such as the mass killings at a Colorado high school. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-DISABILITY (Washington) _ The Supreme Court struggles with
the unsettled issue of whether a physical problem that is kept in
check through medication qualifies as a disability under the
Americans with Disabilities Act. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GIFTS (Washington) _ In a ruling that stems from the
corruption probe of former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, the
Supreme Court rules that people cannot be convicted of giving an
illegal gratuity unless prosecutors prove the gift was linked to an
official act. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GAMBLING (Washington) _ Supreme Court justices take a
skeptical look at the White House push to ban television and radio
advertising for casinos. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-BOMBS-TEXAS (Houston) _ Since the mass killings at a
Colorado high school last week, a number of teen-age boys have been
arrested in Texas for making bombs or plotting other violence. A
Port Aransas man told authorities that his 15-year-old son had
obtained information on bomb-making from the Internet and
experimented with making napalm. In Wichita Falls, four teens were
arrested for experimenting with bombs. By THADDEUS HERRICK and
MELANIE MARKLEY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-DEATHS (San Antonio) _ At least 51 immigrants died last
summer in the Texas heat, most while trying to cross remote areas
of the U.S.-Mexico border. The Border Patrol reports on the latest
figures involving people who try to illegally cross the border,
then perish. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYER-FEES (Austin, Texas) _ The state Senate approves a bill
to clamp down on the attorney general's independence in hiring
outside lawyers to represent Texas in lawsuits. The legislation was
inspired by the controversy over the huge fees awarded to lawyers
hired to help fight the state's case against tobacco companies. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's BAAACK! That hardy perennial,
the minimum wage, is once again on the congressional agenda. A
House committee is rehashing the issue, with business opposed to
another increase and labor demanding a $1 boost to $6.15 an hour.
This is a family-friendly cause hard to resist as we near a
presidential election year. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Pitcher Shane Reynolds aims for his
fourth victory of the season as the Houston Astros try to make it
two in a row over the Arizona Diamondbacks. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-CLEMENS (Arlington, Texas) _ Roger Clemens will be shooting
for an American League-record 17th consecutive victory when he
faces the Texas Rangers in his first visit to Texas since joining
the New York Yankees. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ It's hard to overlook somebody as big as
Stanley Roberts, but the seven-footer has been the missing man for
the Houston Rockets this season. Is there a chance he could return
in time for the playoffs? By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
