<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Pooling my resources
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ My swimming pool made it through the winter in
fine shape.
</P>
<P>
   Drats.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, I was hoping the earth would open up and swallow
it.
</P>
<P>
   Serve it right, the way the swimming pool keeps swallowing my
money. I can't sleep at night for worrying what'll go wrong next.
</P>
<P>
   I've told you about my swimming pool before. I have a pet name
for it, Ol' Elephant Butt.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the big crack in the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   In past winters, the water has mostly drained out, in drips and
dribbles. Not so this year, thank goodness.
</P>
<P>
   I'm relieved. All of the town should be relieved.
</P>
<P>
   It was just after I had to refill my pool last year that the
city had to mandate water rationing.
</P>
<P>
   Could have been coincidence. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it takes a lot of water to keep a leaky elephant
watered.
</P>
<P>
   I've since had the crack patched. It's holding, so far, so good.
But that's about as far as it goes.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that's OK with a swimming pool is temporary.
</P>
<P>
   There's always the pump. It's not for nothing that it has the
appearance of a bomb-like apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, sooner or later it'll go ka-blooey.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it burned its insides up. Odd, wouldn't you think,
that a water pump could burn itself up.
</P>
<P>
   Something to do with ball bearings, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think it was the handle.
</P>
<P>
   The pump won't work cause the vandals took the handle? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Leastwise, I came by my swimming pool intelligently.
</P>
<P>
   It was already in the back yard when I bought the house.
</P>
<P>
   I have a friend who came by his swimming pool stupidly.
</P>
<P>
   He had it built, just last summer _ all the time, me telling him
not to.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, I tried to explain, you use a swimming pool only
three months out of the year _ a limited return on your investment
to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. He already had that part figured out.
</P>
<P>
   He was having his swimming pool heated.
</P>
<P>
   Good grief.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing worse than a swimming pool is a heated swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Heated pools are dangerous. Heated pools will drown you. Heated
pools will drown you in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you how long my friend heated his swimming pool:
</P>
<P>
   Hardly until the water got hot.
</P>
<P>
   Until the first heating bill arrived in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a cold day in July _ and probably not even then _ when
he fires up his pool heater again.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that wasn't all his problems. Sure enough, his pool
has a crack in it.
</P>
<P>
   But not to worry, he says _ the warranty covers it.
</P>
<P>
   Must be a heck of a good warranty to cover something the size of
an elephant's butt.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I'm just joking about my swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   What with the grandchildren, it's something we enjoy more and
more every year. Heaven knows, I can't imagine enjoying anything
less.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, I don't know what I'd do without it.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep better at night? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
