<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO OFFICIAL URGES ONE-DAY GAS BOYCOTT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A city supervisor has urged drivers not to buy
gasoline on Friday to protest the dramatic increase in prices at
the pump. San Francisco has the highest gas prices in the nation _
an average $1.74 per gallon for self-serve unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the 1999 version of highway robbery,'' Supervisor Michael
Yaki said Monday as he released estimates he made of how much money
oil companies made due to higher gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Gorell, a spokesman for San Francisco-based Chevron Corp.,
characterized Yaki's accusations of higher profits as ``bad math
times two,'' and said the city official ignored myriad production,
transportation and administrative costs, as well as a huge spike in
prices on the speculative markets where some of the fuel supply is
purchased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legitimate marketplace forces brought about these prices,''
Gorell said.
</P>
<P>
   Yaki, using figures from the California Energy Commission and
the American Automobile Association, calculated that oil company
profits over the past five weeks have increased $11 million in San
Francisco and $88 million in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Several surveys have indicated that the price of a gallon of
unleaded fuel has risen 40 cents in the past five weeks to $1.74
per gallon. The national average is about $1.10 per gallon of
self-serve gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The California Energy Commission and AAA figures ``shine a
glaring spotlight on the amount of money oil companies are raking
in due to the increase,'' Yaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Yaki is endorsing a gas boycott on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will have no economic impact on the oil companies, but
what I am hoping it will do is send a political message to
Sacramento and Washington, the only places where the playing field
can be changed for the oil companies,'' Yaki said.
</P>
<P>
   The oil companies attribute the higher prices at the pump to
rising prices on the world oil market and supply problems after two
recent fires at refineries in the San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding Yaki's contention of profit-taking, Chevron, the
nation's fourth largest oil company, last week reported
first-quarter operating income fell 36 percent as oil prices
plunged 20 percent and natural gas prices tumbled 22 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
