<HEADLINE>
ARTICHOKES AND SQUID: A MATCHMAKING SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this time of year, many restaurants on the Mediterranean
offer a traditional combination that is outrageously good and
completely foreign to Americans: artichoke bottoms with cuttlefish,
squid or octopus. The best artichokes mature in cool weather, and
the long, gradual spring of southern France and northern Italy
gives them perfect growing conditions. The catch of cephalopods is
also good in spring, and the marriage of these seasonal foods is
probably as old as fishing and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   It's a union that is easily duplicated here with the plentiful
and relatively inexpensive artichokes from California and the
steady catch of squid in springtime. (Cuttlefish and octopus are
harder to find.)
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients are braised in a base of good olive oil, garlic
and anchovy. Both the squid and the artichoke bottoms cook in about
30 minutes, so the timing is straightforward. The result is tender
but still chewy squid and creamy, sweet artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy and France, markets sometimes offer trimmed artichoke
bottoms, sitting in water with lemon juice or vinegar that keeps
them from turning brown. This convenience cuts the preparation time
by more than half, since most of the work involved in this dish is
in cleaning the artichokes. Unfortunately, I've never seen
artichoke bottoms sold this way here. (Don't even think about
substituting frozen specimens; they simply don't make the grade.)
</P>
<P>
   To trim an artichoke, first remove all the large outer leaves by
snapping them off at the base. Then cut off only the bottom inch or
so of the stem; leave the rest, as it makes good eating. Use a
paring knife or a good vegetable peeler to peel the stem and remove
the remaining tough bits from all around the bottom. Cut off the
conical top of the artichoke, about an inch to an inch and a half
from the top, then cut the artichoke in half from top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Use a spoon to completely dig out the choke, the tiny unformed
leaves in the center that may be tinged purple. These leaves will
stick in your throat, most unpleasantly, so be thorough. Whether
for this recipe or another, the bottoms should be immediately
plunged into acidulated water _ a bowlful with a half a lemon
squeezed in, or 10 parts water to one part vinegar _ to preserve
their color until cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning the artichokes is most of the work. You can buy cleaned
squid almost anywhere, even in supermarkets. All that's left to do
is to quickly color some garlic in oil, add the main ingredients
and cook.
</P>
<P>
   Although this dish is traditionally made with a little dry white
wine, squid contains so much water that additional liquid is
counterproductive. I've found that about halfway through the
cooking, you must uncover the simmering mixture and let most of the
liquid boil off.
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED SQUID WITH ARTICHOKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total time: 1 hour &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   4 large artichokes, trimmed (see text)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 anchovy fillets, chopped (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds cleaned squid, the bodies cut into rings
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Minced parsley for garnish.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut the lemon in half, squeeze the juice into a bowl of
water, and add the lemon halves. Cut the trimmed artichokes into 4
pieces each, and as they are done, add them to the lemon water.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a large skillet or broad saucepan over medium heat and
add 2 tablespoons of the oil; a minute later, add the garlic and
anchovies. Cook, stirring occasionally, until the anchovies break
up and the garlic begins to color, 3 to 5 minutes. Add the squid
and the artichokes, stir, cover and turn the heat to medium.
</P>
<P>
   3. Uncover and stir the mixture every 5 minutes or so. When the
squid and artichokes begin to become tender, after 15 or 20
minutes, uncover and cook until most of the liquid has evaporated
and the squid and artichokes are tender, about 10 to 15 minutes
longer. Season with pepper. It's highly unlikely this dish will
need added salt, especially if you use anchovies, but taste and
see. Stir in the remaining olive oil, garnish with the parsley and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
