<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF A BLEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trefethen Vineyards Cabernet Franc 1996, Napa Valley, Calif.
About $20.
</P>
<P>
   A little less fruity, a little lighter-bodied than cabernet
sauvignon, cabernet franc has made a name for itself in the Loire
Valley and in St.-Emilion, where it is the major component in the
wine of Chateau Cheval Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   In the Medoc and in Northern California, it's often blended into
cabernet sauvignon to add complexity and structure. In Chinon and
Bourgueil, in the Loire, it produces a red that is both fruity and
lean at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The Trefethen displays some of that restraint, but the 10
percent merlot and 7 percent cabernet sauvignon that have been
added tend to soften it a bit. A good wine and a nice break from
cabernet sauvignon, but it would nice to taste the cabernet franc
strictly on its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
