<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXES HAVE BITTER TASTE FOR THE OLD AND YOUNG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I suppose it was the expression on his face that first alarmed
me.
</P>
<P>
   When he left me moments earlier, he had been smiling and
exuberant, but now his abrupt return to the car was punctuated by
those stormy eyes and pursed lips. He looked like his father does
whenever I return from one of my infrequent but highly productive
shopping sprees. He hasn't quite mastered the furrowed brow yet,
but I suppose that will come with time.
</P>
<P>
   My hands instinctively grasped the steering wheel a bit tighter.
I felt my heart beat faster as my adrenaline and estrogen began to
combine like vinegar and oil in one of those green bottles at the
Italian restaurant. I wonder how often they clean those things?
They always feel really slimy and have those strange particles
floating around in there.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I was alarmed because my son was clearly upset. I didn't
know what had happened in there, but I was prepared to defend him
to the death or until the videotape from the surveillance camera
proved that my death would be in vain.
</P>
<P>
   I reached over to turn down the radio as he opened the passenger
door. One of my favorite songs was playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom,'' he said. ``I think this guy is trying to rip me off
because the sign said the comic book only costs 99 cents. He says
that I've got to pay $1.07 for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew! I let out a sigh of relief. This situation I could handle
from the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well give him $1.07. You've got to pay the taxes on it too.
Didn't we talk about this before?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You and Dad have been complaining about taxes for weeks, but I
didn't know you were talking about comic books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No son, not income taxes, sales taxes. You have to pay sales
tax on pretty much everything that you buy except food.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They use that money to build roads and schools, and to pay
teachers and police officers. They use the money for a bunch of
important stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He still looked skeptical, so I tried a new approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you remember the Boston Tea Party? Taxation without
representation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``When was this tea party? Were there any boys there?''
</P>
<P>
   I forget how young he is sometimes. I'm also pretty bad at
important historical dates so I said, ``Here, take this dime and go
pay the man. I promise you, it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he came back from making his purchase, I took the receipt
and pointed out the additional charge for the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to pay taxes every time I buy something?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep, that's pretty much the way it works.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All because of some tea party in Boston?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I promise you that next week I will explain that taxation
dates back centuries and blah, blah, blah, but just about the time
he asked me about that Celine Dion came on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I hardly ever get to listen to my station so I said,
``Yep, it was that tea party that did it.''
</P>
<P>
   He nodded solemnly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate tea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
