<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      04-27 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAROLOS PUT ON A FRIENDLIER FACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have to confess it had been a long time since I'd had anything
to do with Barolo, a treasure of Italian wine-making. You know how
it is: so many wines, so little time.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there had always been an excuse to drink something
else. Barolo had something forbidding about it. The Italians call
it the king of wines and, in fact, there is a regal quality to it:
words like monumental and powerful are used to describe it. The
wine writer Hugh Johnson once complained that Barolo ``gives the
palate a wrestling match.''
</P>
<P>
   To me, Barolo was a powerful, astringent wine, like Hermitage
and some old-fashioned California cabernets, that required years of
tasting to understand. It was also one that was expensive and
needed aging, usually about 10 years, to be drinkable. All reasons
to put it on the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   Then recently I heard that one of the better-known Barolo wine
makers, Pio Boffa, was coming to New York from the Piedmont region
to be the host of a tasting of the Barolos produced by his family's
company, Pio Cesare. It seemed a good time for a reassessment.
</P>
<P>
   First things first: Barolo is named after a town in the hills
southwest of Alba. Turin, some 45 miles to the northwest, is the
nearest big city. The official Barolo district covers 3,000 acres
in and around Barolo and includes communes like La Morra,
Castiglione Falletto and Serralunga d'Alba, whose names will show
up on Barolos made within their borders.
</P>
<P>
   Barolo is made exclusively from nebbiolo, a Piedmontese grape of
ancient heritage. Once, Barolo was a sweet wine. In the 1840s, the
French wife of a local nobleman hired a French wine maker, Louis
Oudinot, to transform Barolo into a dry wine in the French style.
The new style soon became the only style.
</P>
<P>
   Pio Cesare started his wine business in Alba in 1881, making
Barolo, Barbaresco, barbera and dolcetto. Boffa, his grandson,
heads the firm now and considers Barolo his signature wine. While
respecting the traditional methods, he, like most other Barolo
producers, has introduced some major changes over the last 20 years
to make his wine somewhat easier to drink.
</P>
<P>
   The results were clearly evident in the wines he opened here
last week, which began with the 1955 vintage and included 1964,
1974, 1979, 1982, 1985, 1989 and 1990. There were also samples from
the yet unbottled 1995, 1996, 1997 and 1998 vintages, plus four
examples of Ornato, his single-vineyard Barolo, from 1988, 1989,
1990 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, Barolo was made in large Yugoslavian oak casks,
some of them at least 40 years old. The grapes and their skins were
allowed to ferment in these casks for up to two months to extract
every bit of fruit, and tannin, which gives wines backbone. The
wines were aged in these casks for eight years then transferred to
large glass jugs to age further on the roof, in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting wines were inky-dark monsters. The wine makers
realized changes had to be made if they wanted to attract more
customers. By 1978, the Pio Cesare firm had begun installing
stainless steel fermentation tanks and cutting the amount of time
the juice and the skins were in contact, to reduce the amount of
tannin. Eventually, all the old Yugoslavian casks were replaced by
small French oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   In an article last year in International Wine Cellar, a consumer
newsletter, the wine broker Marc de Grazia said wine-making in
Barolo had improved so much in recent years that ``for the first
time, we can taste Barolos from 20 or 30 producers that are all
carefully crafted and taste radically different.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Boffa's wines varied considerably from the older to
the younger vintages. Both the 1955 and the 1964 showed a freshness
and vibrancy that few Bordeaux of the same age could ever muster.
They are exceptional wines. The control of tannins in the younger
ones produced richer, sweeter wines with none of the harshness once
associated with Barolo.
</P>
<P>
   Oak was evident in the Ornatos but it was hardly intrusive. In
fact, it helped fashion wines that combine unusual smoothness and
elegance with the dark, smoky character typical of good Barolos.
</P>
<P>
   De Grazia and other experts say that consumer interest has been
shifting away from Tuscany and the so-called super-Tuscan blends of
sangiovese with cabernet and merlot to the wine of the Piedmont. If
true, this is good for the Piedmont wine makers, but less so for
wine enthusiasts, because the Piedmont produces far less wine than
Tuscany: less than 600,000 cases of Barolo are produced in a good
year.
</P>
<P>
   Barolo may be more approachable than it once was, but don't be
fooled: it's still not a wine for casual drinking. Still, that
shouldn't scare you away from what could be a great experience.
</P>
<P>
   Other well-known Barolo producers to be found in the American
market include Aldo Conterno, with his magnificent Gran Bussia
Riserva; Bruno Giacosa, with his Falletto di Serralunga Riserva;
Angelo Gaja, with his Barolo Sperss, and Bruno Cerretto, known for
his Barolo Zonchera. There is also Elio Grasso, known for his
Barolo Vigna Casa Mate; Luciano Sandrone, for his Barolo Cannubi
Boschis, and Alfredo Prunotto, for his Barolo Monte Stefano, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Pio Cesare Barolos range in price from around $35 for the
regular 1993, now in stores, to around $90 for the 1993 Ornato.
Many of the best Barolos, made in tiny quantities, sell for well
over $100 a bottle, but for a newcomer to the wine it makes sense,
both economically and enologically, to start with a simple example,
like Grasso's Vigna Casa Mate 1993, at about $30.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
