<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5160 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILOSEVIC-ENEMY-RIVAL     04-27 2634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILOSEVIC-ENEMY-RIVALRY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC'S CLOSEST ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 FOR RELEASE: APRIL 25 or thereafter  
 By BLAINE HARDEN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Until Milo Djukanovic's new best friends in the United States
and Western Europe began to drop bombs on Montenegro in late March,
life had been going along swimmingly for the handsome young
president of this Yugoslav republic.
 &HT;    Just 37 years old, built like an NFL linebacker, packaged in
dark Italian suits, married to an attractive blonde and hailed by
voters as Milo the Blade, Djukanovic (djew-KAHN-oh-vich) has been
playing a deliciously wicked game of chicken with the Serbian
dictator Slobodan Milosevic.
 &HT;    Before bombs and cruise missiles began to rain on Yugoslavia,
the Montenegrin president even seemed to be winning.
 &HT;    For the first time since 1918, when Serbia annexed this
mountainous, Connecticut-size republic on the Adriatic Sea and
turned it into a perennial Yugoslav little brother, Montenegro was
moving toward an independent and democratic future linked to the
economies of Western Europe and the United States.
 &HT;    Milosevic, so tactically brilliant in using ethnic hate to
consolidate power, wasn't able to get a grip on the republic's
650,000 residents, even though he ruled 15 times as many people and
more than six times as much land and commanded the formidable
Yugoslav army.
 &HT;    The Montenegrin president has challenged Milosevic with an
impudent Balkan mix of populism, police muscle, cigarette smuggling
and wisecracks about Milosevic's wife. Instead of howling about
historical wrongs, whipping up nationalistic paranoia and ordering
ethnic cleansing, Milo the Blade has preached free-market
prosperity and eased ethnic tensions by securing the civil rights
of his republic's Muslim and Albanian minorities.
 &HT;    Although Djukanovic tested and taunted Milosevic, he took care
never to say or do anything anti-Serb. He never lost sight of who
had the tanks and stopped short of a direct confrontation that
could bring out the Yugoslav army.
 &HT;    Montenegro and Serbia are all that's left of the six republics
that once made up Yugoslavia. Under the federal Constitution, they
are supposedly equal, but larger Serbia has always dominated.
 &HT;    And Djukanovic has remained immune to Tin Pot Leader Syndrome, a
dizzying and endemic Balkan malady that infected his next-door
neighbor, Franjo Tudjman, the president of Croatia, whose
nationalist swagger terrified the Serb minority and helped provoke
a war with Serbia.
 &HT;    Djukanovic is no choirboy. He started out in public life 10
years ago as a Communist enforcer for Milosevic. As one of the Serb
leader's handpicked henchmen in Montenegro, he developed a
state-sponsored air-and-sea smuggling operation that,
paradoxically, gave him the financial resources to slip free of
Milosevic's iron grip and evolve into a Balkan rarity _ a democrat.
 &HT;    The U.S. State Department says it believes Djukanovic's
conversion is real, and so do the handful of long-suffering
human-rights activists who have watched him rise to power. His
bully-boy past is unsavory, even criminal, they say, but he came of
age in a very bad Balkan neighborhood where smart democrats with
popular support and the guts (and police power) to stand up to
Milosevic are hard to find.
 &HT;    The region desperately needs a hero, and Djukanovic is perhaps
the one leader whom the West can rally around.
 &HT;    Yet NATO bombs have changed all that. They have belied
Djukanovic's promise to voters that a turn to the West would
produce peace and wealth. Instead, the bombs have emboldened his
enemies who, with Milosevic's conniving, have already tried to
overthrow his government by force.
 &HT;    Many Montenegrins now consider it cowardly and traitorous to
turn their backs on their embattled Serb neighbors. The bombs mean
that before this story is printed Djukanovic could be put in prison
or killed.
 &HT;    I met him in the Montenegrin capital of Podgorica late on a
night in early April. He was holed up inside the Presidency
Building, which was encircled by Special Forces police officers
wearing camouflage combat uniforms and Israeli-made body armor and
carrying Israeli-made automatic weapons.
 &HT;    After passing through the police gantlet, the metal detector and
the passport review, I was kept waiting for about half an hour in a
barren room with a single fluorescent tube that flicked on and off.
 &HT;    The president's office was nicer. The lights worked. The
curtains were heavy; the rug, plush. Out on the street, nearly all
of the police had been strikingly tall, dark and beefy. So was
Djukanovic. He was also immaculately turned out, considering the
hour and the circumstances, in a starched white shirt and dark blue
suit. His brown hair was freshly trimmed and just barely flecked
with gray.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, he spoke in the stiff bureaucratic locution of the
young Communist that he once was, larding his sentences with
references to ``interlocutors'' and ``democratic structures.'' But
after a few minutes of conversation I noticed that, unlike other
Balkan leaders, he answered questions directly, without taking off
on insufferably self-serving rants about how his people have been
wronged and misunderstood for centuries.
 &HT;    The NATO bombings, the West's campaign to force Milosevic to
halt his army's assault on ethnic Albanians in the Serb province of
Kosovo, had started 12 nights earlier. Some of the strikes have hit
Montenegro, where the Yugoslav army has outposts. Whatever effect
those bombings were having in Kosovo, they were an unqualified
disaster for the man standing in front of me.
 &HT;    Before the bombs, two elections had shown that, by a narrow
margin, Montenegrins approved of Djukanovic's shift to the West and
of his prickly criticism of Milosevic. Now, though, the president
did not bother pretending that he still had the support of his
people. The bombs have already remade politics here.
 &HT;    On the evening he received me, more than 20,000 Montenegrins had
gathered just four blocks from the president's office for a
``Muzicki Hepening'' in the city's central square. The rock
concert, the largest public gathering here in years, was organized
by the pro-Milosevic Socialist People's Party to protest the NATO
strikes.
 &HT;    The noisy crowd carried framed photographs of Milosevic and
posters that read, ``Monica Fell to Her Knees Before Clinton, But
We Won't!'' They applauded speeches that glorified the Yugoslav
army's campaign against the Kosovars. Many Montenegrins were
clamoring for the president's head.
 &HT;    ``Djukanovic is a traitor,'' said Dejan Cvijanovic, a
28-year-old computer technician. ``There are a great number of
people who voted for him who now have turned against him. I hope
there is a coup soon.'' Djukanovic had been hearing the same
belligerent stuff, he told me.
 &HT;    Hundreds of his police officers had watched the concert from the
edges of the square. He had monitored it from his office, and said
he was concerned about similar gatherings that were scheduled for
the coming week. I asked if he was afraid of Milosevic.
 &HT;    ``No,'' he said. ``But I have no illusions. As long as Slobodan
Milosevic is in the political life of Yugoslavia, he will do all he
can think of both against Montenegro and against myself.''
 &HT;    But predicting what Milosevic might or might not do has always
been a fool's game. If there were a confrontation in Montenegro,
where nearly every adult male owns a gun, it could easily escalate
into a dreadful civil war.
 &HT;    It was all so much simpler before the NATO bombs began falling,
Djukanovic kept telling me in his bunkered office. All he had to do
was outfox a dictator who, in the words of the last U.S. ambassador
to Yugoslavia, Warren Zimmermann, is the ``slickest con man'' in
the Balkans.
 &HT;    The outfoxing began imperceptibly. Ten years ago, Djukanovic was
thought of _ if he was thought of at all _ as merely a young,
hard-line puppet of Milosevic. The Serb leader had plucked him from
the ranks of the League of Communists in Montenegro to help lead
something Milosevic called the ``antibureaucratic revolution.''
 &HT;    This was reform-sounding double talk for a power grab. Milosevic
pushed aside older Communists still loyal to Tito's version of
Yugoslavia, a place where Serb nationalism was crushed by the power
of the state. Djukanovic helped his Serbian mentor sweep away the
old gray cadres. In return, Milosevic crowned him in 1991 as prime
minister of Montenegro. Just 29, he was the youngest prime minister
in Europe.
 &HT;    The United Nations slapped economic sanctions on Yugoslavia in
1991 at the start of the Bosnian war. Djukanovic, an economist by
training and a pragmatist by nature, quickly figured out how to
profit from them. For a number of years, around 2 o'clock every
morning, several giant Russian-made transport planes landed at the
airport on the edge of the capital. The planes brought in American
and European cigarettes, which were trucked to the coast and
smuggled by boat to Italy.
 &HT;    Djukanovic's government imposed a ``transit fee,'' which,
according to Perovic, the foreign minister, added about $30 million
a year to the republic's coffers. That's not a lot of money by
European standards, but with an annual budget of just $270 million,
the Montenegro government was relying on smuggling for more than 10
percent of its revenue. (NATO bombing, of course, put an end to the
plane landings.)
 &HT;    Djukanovic funneled most of the money into government salaries
and pensions, which in the mid-1990s his government managed to pay
on time. At such budgetary games, he was more skilled than
Milosevic in Serbia, where pensions and salaries almost always ran
six to eight months late, despite equally rampant smuggling. While
Montenegrins widely believed that Djukanovic was creaming off some
of the profits, they didn't much care.
 &HT;    Unemployment was near 40 percent. A decade of war had ruined the
tourist industry. ``Everyone in Montenegro thought that finally
there was someone in government who knew how to create money,''
said Srdan Darmanovic, a former member of the Yugoslav Parliament
and a Montenegrin human-rights lawyer.
 &HT;    During these years, Djukanovic never said a disparaging word in
public about Milosevic, although he insisted in our interview that
he criticized him to his face in private meetings in Belgrade. Such
public loyalty, however, did not prevent members of the Milosevic
family from getting mad at Djukanovic, who was making money that he
wasn't sharing with them.
 &HT;    Milosevic's wife, Mirjana Markovic, attacked him in her weekly
newspaper column as the most notorious smuggler in Yugoslavia. It
was a bold and characteristically mendacious accusation. Her only
son, Marko, a gangster who carried a gun and routinely wrecked
expensive racing cars, ran a large cigarette, alcohol and fuel
smuggling operation in Serbia.
 &HT;    Playing to widespread resentment of Milosevic's wife, whom many
Montenegrins and Serbs regard as a low-wattage Stalinist shrew,
Djukanovic countered that she was an irrelevant woman whose
Chinese-oriented Marxist party, the Yugoslav United Left, was so
small that its entire membership could fit on a bus.
 &HT;    Djukanovic waited, however, until her husband seemed to be
losing power before announcing that he wasn't a fan of Milosevic.
In late 1996 and early 1997, when the Serbian leader was struggling
through three months of mass street demonstrations in Belgrade,
Djukanovic said that Milosevic was a politician of the past, that
he did not have a future in Yugoslavia and that Yugoslavia had no
future with him.
 &HT;    When I asked about the smuggling, Djukanovic vehemently denied
rising to power by illegality. Officials in his government, though,
openly concede that it was the only way to make ends meet under
sanctions. They said Djukanovic has tried to attract foreign
investment and legitimate business. Imitating post-Communist
leaders from Poland to Bulgaria, he has announced plans to sell off
state-owned industry. NATO bombings, of course, have put such
reforms on hold.
 &HT;    Besides building a financial power base, Djukanovic had to build
a political machine as well. He did this in a most un-Balkan way,
by advocating ethnic tolerance. The contrast with Milosevic was
nothing short of amazing.
 &HT;    As for Kosovo, Djukanovic has called Milosevic's campaign of
violent ethnic cleansing ``insane, autistic and autocratic.'' He
attributes the catastrophe there to what he has said were years of
neglect by the Serbian leader, during which he refused to negotiate
with moderate Kosovar politicians.
 &HT;    He told me that months before the NATO campaign began, he warned
Western governments that bombing would only make things far worse
for the Kosovars. He said he advised the West to support the
democratic opposition in Serbia and in Kosovo and to show some
patience.
 &HT;    Two nights after Djukanovic and I spoke, a few NATO bombs
exploded near Podgorica _ the first such attacks in Montenegro in a
week.
 &HT;    To find out why NATO was bombing there, I called Robert Gelbard,
the U.S. special envoy to the former Yugoslavia, in Washington, who
was eager to explain. Gelbard said he had already been on the phone
that morning with Djukanovic, reassuring him that the bombings were
merely a response to the Second Yugoslav Army, which had fired a
land-to-air missile at NATO planes flying over Montenegro on their
way to Serbia. The strike was not part of a new offensive campaign.
 &HT;    ``From the very beginning of the air campaign, we knew _ and we
let Djukanovic know _ that there were certain minimal army targets
that we were going to have to hit in Montenegro,'' he said.
 &HT;    Gelbard then shifted conversation away from the awkward matter
of bombing his friend and talked about what the Clinton
administration was doing to help Djukanovic. It had just decided to
give the Montenegro government $10 million to help pay for
pensions, salaries and social programs. American money, via the
United Nations, was also helping to pay for the care of the
estimated 35,000 Kosovar refugees who have poured into the
republic.
 &HT;    In addition, he said, Washington had exempted Montenegro from
economic sanctions growing out of the crisis and was urging
Congress to approve large business loans for the area. And it was
training Montenegrin diplomats and granting American landing rights
to Montenegrin Airlines.
 &HT;    ``We don't support secession or independence for Montenegro,''
he said, ``but we do support what Djukanovic is doing. He has
support at the highest levels in this administration. His politics
and his economic policies are a good model for all of Yugoslavia
and a particularly good model for the opposition inside Serbia.''
But Washington, he added, had cut no deal to bail out Montenegro in
case Milosevic's loyal Yugoslav army attacks.
 &HT;    Djukanovic's game of chicken was still on.
 &HT;     c.1999 Blaine Harden  
