<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THERMOMETER-GUN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUCK ROGERS RAYGUN FOR THE KITCHEN: POINT-AND-SHOOT THERMOMETER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Md., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MARTY KATZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my car overheated, the gas station guy pulled a big
gun-thing out of his tool chest, pointed it under the hood and
pulled the trigger. Obviously, he was putting the old '88 out of
its misery.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he was reading the temperature of the engine parts with
an infrared thermometer. The trigger sent a laser dot to mark the
spot being read, and the temperature was displayed on a little
window on the back of the gun.
</P>
<P>
   I immediately arranged to borrow it for the weekend. I read the
temperature of everything. Cold hands and cold feet. Ice. Stoves.
Coffee machines.
</P>
<P>
   I took this little point-and-shoot thermometer out to dinner to
show friends, and the chef came over, snatched it and ran off to
the kitchen. After a long time, he came back and said it was
perfect for reading baking bread, the freezer, prepared foods and
the grill. He wanted one. And he thought other food professionals
would, too.
</P>
<P>
   The company that makes it, the Raytek Corp. in Santa Cruz,
Calif., has recognized that potential. Raytek makes larger models
(pit crews at the Indy 500 point them at the asphalt to determine
which tires to use; heating and air-conditioning technicians check
pipes with them).
</P>
<P>
   But now the company has begun shipping two pocket-sized Minitemp
models that are perfect for a kitchen. They can outperform a
standard instant-read thermometer at everything but reading
internal temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   While other thermometers need to actually touch the item being
measured _ which is difficult with a whirling fan belts or hot
grill or boiling sugar _ infrared thermometers measure the energy
flowing out of any object and display its heat as Celsius or
Fahrenheit degrees. (Raytek says they will measure from 0 to 500
degrees Fahrenheit, but actually, mine went from minus 9 to a top
of 539.)
</P>
<P>
   The new models are about six inches long, light and small enough
for a shirt pocket. They work best from a couple of feet to a
couple of inches; at a foot away, they read the temperature of
two-inch circle.
</P>
<P>
   I was having fun with the thermometer, but chefs see its
usefulness. Jason Superczynski, a chef at the Black Olive in
Baltimore, told me he likes the quick-zap approach for searching
out the hot spots on his grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only drawback is that it doesn't read internal
temperatures,'' he said. There is no way, for instance, that it can
tell when a steak is rare or well done.
</P>
<P>
   But the infrared thermometer has other merits for home cooks.
For example, a griddle is deemed ready for pancakes when a drop of
water skitters across its surface, but my test with Raytek's
Minitemp showed water does this at a wide temperature range, from
about 320 to 420 degrees. Most cooking experts say the ideal
temperature is 350 to 370, which is where the Minitemp's accuracy
comes in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Another moment of truth is determining when a stove-top grill or
pan is hot enough to sear meat without sticking. That requires a
temperature of 450 to 500 degrees _ something many cooks find
difficult to gauge by eye.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Simpson, the director of education at Peter Kump's
Cooking School in New York, said: ``Some foods are ruined by a
too-cool pan _ 350 to 370 is ideal for frying,'' he said. ``As you
pass 400, you damage the oil because it breaks down. From 400 to
450, it may begin to smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said temperature is also critical in cooking with sugar.
``At 220, sugar relaxes to the soft-ball stage used in meringues
and icings, at 320, you reach the caramel stage for flavoring and
decorating, such as forming spun sugar. At 350, the caramel
darkens.'' But measuring with a candy thermometer is messy at best
and can actually cause the sugar to crystallize.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grimes, the corporate chef for Disney's new chain of
ESPNZone restaurants opening across the country, has his chefs
checking foods and storage conditions with the mechanic-sized
thermometers. Four times a day, they quickly read the temperatures
of a checklist of 60 items, from the walk-in refrigerator to the
salad greens.
</P>
<P>
   Raytek's Minitemp MT4, with laser for aiming, is $139. The
laserless MT2 is $99. They are in car parts and tool stores now but
could eventually begin appearing in cookware shops, said Bob Baden,
Raytek's national sales manager. (Meanwhile, Raytek can direct
customers to retailers: 800-866-5478).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies that carry the Minitemp and similar models
are the Cole-Parmer Instrument Co. (800-323-4340), Davis
Instruments (800-368-2516) and EPD Technology (800-892-8926).
</P>
<P>
   Other models that look a remote control are available, but they
are about an inch longer than the Minitemp and may not fit the hand
as well. And in my own side-by-side comparison, they were not as
much fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
