<SLUG> BC-FAT-COOKING-HOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINE ART OF COOKING WITH FAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With FAT-COOKING) 
(mk) 
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chefs know instinctively what to do with fat in any
form. But home cooks who have absorbed the idea that butter is bad
may need a refresher course in the fine art of cooking with fat,
especially with the kinds of fat chefs are using lately.
</P>
<P>
   These fats have serious flavor, but more important, like all
fats they convey the other flavors in a dish. The richness actually
helps you taste more of what you are eating by melding with other
ingredients and counterbalancing salty, sharp or acid notes.
</P>
<P>
   The foie gras fat turning up in restaurants all over town is
hard for home cooks to find, but duck fat is now sold in many
supermarkets and is easy to make yourself. The diced skin and fat
of the bird are cooked very slowly with water until the fat is
completely rendered and the skin crisps into cracklings that can be
strained out and eaten with salt. The fat keeps indefinitely in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Duck fat (or goose fat, for that matter) can be used just like
butter or olive oil for frying or roasting potatoes or sauteing
meats or shellfish as chefs do in France. It can even be melted and
poured over steamed vegetables. And it has a much headier flavor
than even the best butter.
</P>
<P>
   Duck fat is also used to make traditional confit, the leg of the
bird cooked slowly in its own fat, with more fat added. It can also
be used in a hot vinaigrette over a salad of sturdy greens with
duck cracklings as a garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken fat (a k a schmaltz) is rendered the same way as duck
fat and also sold in some markets. It's good for making chopped
liver and pates and for frying potato pancakes or frying onions to
top a steak.
</P>
<P>
   Butter seems tame by comparison, but many cooks are out of the
habit of using more than a teaspoon or so at a time. It can be the
base of any number of sauces, but you can't skimp.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best and quickest sauces for meat, fowl or fish is
made by simply deglazing the cooking pan with wine, water, beer or
broth, then whisking in a nugget of butter to add flavor, body and
shine. Brown butter is faster: Heat fresh butter gently until it
turns golden, with nutty-tasting browned bits, and pour it over
meat, chicken or fish.
</P>
<P>
   A beurre blanc is the kind of sauce that looks light on a plate
but is actually almost pure butter. Vinegar or wine is boiled with
shallots until the liquid is just a glaze, and then slices of
butter are whisked in until a thick sauce forms.
</P>
<P>
   An even easier trick is to make a compound butter: Soften a
stick, mix in fresh herbs and seasonings, then roll it into a log
and chill or freeze it for future use. Sliced and laid over hot
steak, chicken, fish, veal or vegetables, the aromatic butter melts
and spreads its flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is olive oil. Even the food police never banned
this time-honored fat. And even a nonstick saute pan needs a
little. But it can also be the finishing touch that transforms
something simple into something irresistible. Sprinkle a little
over a just-baked frittata or Spanish tortilla; as it warms on
contact it softens any hard edges and concentrates the good,
browned flavor of the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Herb-infused olive oils (either homemade or store-bought) are
even more powerful. They can be tossed with pasta and more herbs to
make the easiest sauce, and they can be drizzled over foccacia or
bruschetta to enhance the flavor. Just made, they add new depth to
plain soups and pureed vegetables.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
