<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAT-COOKING-ART-2TAKE     04-27 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAT-COOKING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAT'S A FRIEND TO CHEFS, A STRANGER ON THE MENU 
</HEADLINE>
   (with sidebar, FAT-COOKING-HOW)  
 (with recipes at end of article)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fat. For years, it's been a four-letter word. And yet
the best chefs know they can't be great without it. Sometimes they
use a lot, sometimes a little. Sometimes it's actually splashed on
by the ladleful, as just about any dish _ from fish to vegetables
to beef _ gets ready to emerge through the swinging doors.
</P>
<P>
   It often takes the form of butter, of course, a key ingredient
in some of the seemingly lightest dishes and sauces, like those
righteous vegetable-juice reductions created by Jean-Georges
Vongerichten and imitated all over. (And the seductive smoothness
in many a mashed potato dish comes from a remarkable ratio: two
parts potato, one part butter.)
</P>
<P>
   But there's a lot of poultry fat and lard around, too, as well
as the olive and canola oils that are the saints among the sinners.
</P>
<P>
   No one is campaigning for a diet dominated by artery cloggers,
but in the high-priced world of the occasional indulgence, where a
dish is valued most for its artistry, fat is the unspoken
ingredient cooks rely on more than most diners might ever imagine.
</P>
<P>
   In today's less repressive culinary climate, some restaurants
and their chefs are ready to be open about it. For instance,
Christian Delouvrier of Lespinasse is candid in conversation but
wary on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want good-tasting food you need to use a good amount of
fat,'' he said. ``It nourishes meats and seafood. It makes them
much more silky. I use duck fat to sear scallops and lobster since
it has a nice rich flavor. We don't advertise it on the menu,
because unfortunately people get nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   The poached halibut with Swiss chard and young ginger at Union
Pacific may sound abstemious, but it is actually submerged in a
quart of hot goose fat for 13 minutes. The menu doesn't mention the
poaching medium. ``People are afraid of fat,'' said Rocco
DiSpirito, the chef there. Nevertheless, he said, he wants them to
try different things. Poaching the fish in goose fat, he said, is
simply a way to protect its creaminess and texture, adding that the
fish ends up absorbing the same amount of fat as it would if it
were seared or pan-fried.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 Madison Park, Kerry Heffernan sautes his Gascon potatoes
in the fragrant fat exuded by a foie gras terrine. At JoJo, Chris
Beischer braises red cabbage and chestnuts in goose fat until they
become meltingly tender, then garnishes roast goose with the
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   At Alison on Dominick, Dan Silverman uses a variety of fats for
their individual characteristics. ``I can't cook without fat,'' he
said. ``Duck fat is intense, olive oil is peppery and fruity, and
butter adds a grassy nuttiness. People love fat. But they just
don't want it waved in their face.''
</P>
<P>
   The most skillful cooks are capitalizing not only on the
distinctive characteristics of their palette of fats but also the
singular ability of those fats to blend and carry the many flavors
in a dish so they permeate each mouthful.
</P>
<P>
   What separates the skilled cook from the short-order hack is the
ability to impart silkiness and essential moistness rather than
greasiness. The line between those characteristics is thin. Partly
it's a matter of technique: adding the fat correctly so that a
sauce emulsifies into a uniform creaminess, or cooking at the right
temperature so that the surface of the food is sealed by the heat
before the oil can be absorbed. It's also a matter of using the
right amount of fat: enough so that it complements the flavors and
textures in a dish but not so much that it dulls them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, every chef worth his Plugras (an extra-fat butter)
knows that the more fat used, generally the better the final dish,
since fat is a excellent carrier of flavor. If the chef is skillful
in balancing the fat with the right amounts of acid and salt,
there's room for a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how much is a lot? That's something chefs are still
reluctant to go on the record about. One, a former sous-chef at
Bouley Bakery, gave a typical example. ``Whenever we served a
vegetable,'' he said, ``it got reheated in about a tablespoon of
butter. So when someone ordered a vegetable plate, which had six
different vegetables on it, there was about six tablespoons of
butter on that plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the manager of a popular French restaurant in
Manhattan confided: ``People ask us all the time why our seared
fish tastes so much better than the fish they make at home. I tell
them it's because we can get the pan so much hotter than they can,
but the real reason is because we cook it with heaps of butter.''
</P>
<P>
   David Waltuck, the chef at Chanterelle, who never goes off the
record about his use of fat, put it this way: ``My food is
perceived as being lighter than it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical restaurant meal, many chefs agreed, could easily
contain more than eight tablespoons of fat. That's more than an
entire stick of butter. Given that the recommended daily allowance
of fat for a 2,000-calorie diet is about four and half tablespoons,
that's about twice a day's worth.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds frightening. But assuming meals like this aren't a
nightly occurrence, it isn't the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't go out to rich meals all the time,'' said Penny
Kris-Etherton, the Distinguished Professor of Nutrition at
Pennsylvania State University. ``High-fat restaurant food should be
the exception in people's diets and not the norm. I think it's
important to have a varied diet and to enjoy the food you do eat. I
believe in moderation, but on both sides of the fat question.''
</P>
<P>
   The fat with an image worse than Saddam Hussein's is lard. And
yet it is revered in some parts of the world known for their
beautifully wrought cuisine. Tuscany, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Every winter in Tuscany, pig fat is stacked in marble tubs and
marinated with salt, herbs, aromatics and wine. It might emerge as
a cooking medium or even as a warm little canape in the form of
slices of lard on toast.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, at Osteria del Circo, chef Alessandro Guintoli
serves his version of lardo drizzled with yet more fat: white
truffle oil. It is one of the most deliciously perfumed tidbits you
could ever hope to encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Lard also shows up in French restaurants. At Daniel, Daniel
Boulud uses bacon fat to flavor vegetable soup. In the restaurant
Serenade in Chatham, N.J., James Laird offers a traditional
Provencal pasta made with lard in place of eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the pasta incredibly supple,'' he said. This secret
ingredient, however, isn't on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's suet. At Avenue, Scott Campbell makes a
traditional holiday plum pudding seasoned with suet _ beef kidney
fat.
</P>
<P>
   During the rest of the year, he uses the fat scraped from marrow
bones to finish sauces for steak and fish (garnishing them with the
poached marrow). At the Dining Room, John Tesar wraps a
sophisticated dish of chicken breast and sweetbreads into a neat
little package using sheets of weblike caul fat, from beef
intestines. It's a traditional French technique that keeps the
chicken moist and holds the sweetbreads in place, then melts away
while cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one would ever know it was there,'' Tesar said.
</P>
<P>
   And since the waiters don't mention it when describing this
occasional special, no one ever does.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   SLOW-POACHED ATLANTIC SALMON
</P>
<P>
   WITH SPRING FAVA BEANS, RHUBARB AND BLACK TRUMPET MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Luc Dendievel, Bayard's
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes, plus 4 hours' chilling
</P>
<P>
   { cup plus 2 tablespoons kosher salt, plus more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of { lemon, { orange and { lime
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black peppercorns, cracked
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pink peppercorns, cracked
</P>
<P>
   4 6-ounce salmon fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk rhubarb
</P>
<P>
   \ cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds fresh fava beans, shelled and outer skin peeled
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces black trumpet mushrooms, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   5 cups extra virgin olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small bowl, combine { cup of the salt with the zests,
herbs and peppercorns. Mix.
</P>
<P>
   2. Line a baking pan with parchment paper; then spread half the
salt mixture on it in a rectangle 9 by 6 inches. Cover this with a
piece of cheesecloth and lay the salmon fillets side by side on
top. Top salmon with another piece of cheesecloth and spread the
rest of the salt mixture on top. Chill 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut rhubarb crosswise into \-inch slices. Place them in a
small saucepan over high heat and add 2 cups water and the sugar.
Bring mixture to a boil, turn off the heat and cover the pan to
keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   4. Puree a third of the fava beans in a blender, adding 2 to 3
tablespoons water to help the puree reach sauce consistency. Season
with salt and pepper. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. Have a bowl of ice water ready. Bring a small saucepan of
water to a boil and add the 2 remaining tablespoons kosher salt.
Plunge remaining fava beans into boiling water and cook 2 minutes;
then place in ice water 1 minute. Drain and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   6. Heat a skillet and melt 1 tablespoon butter. Add mushrooms
and saute until tender, about 5 minutes. Season to taste.
</P>
<P>
   7. In a medium-size straight-side saucepan, bring olive oil to
120 degrees. (Check with a meat or candy thermometer.) Remove
cheesecloth-salt cover from fillets and gently place fish in oil.
Poach 15 minutes, maintaining the temperature at 120 degrees.
Remove fish from oil and set on paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   8. Place beans and bean puree in a small pot over low heat and
warm through. Warm rhubarb in its cooking liquid, if necessary. Add
remaining butter to mushrooms and heat through over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   9. Divide fava beans and puree, along with drained rhubarb and
mushrooms, among four warm plates. Place a fillet on each and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   AVENUE'S POTATOES LOUIS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Scott Campbell
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 medium Yukon gold potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rendered duck fat
</P>
<P>
   Coarse sea salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   { tablespoon chopped parsley.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Bring a pot of salted water to a
boil. Add potatoes and cook until tender, about 5 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place duck fat in an 8-inch oven-proof skillet and melt it
over medium heat. Add potatoes and saute until crispy, about 20
minutes. Place pan in oven and bake 30 minutes, until crusty and
brown on bottom.
</P>
<P>
   3. Take skillet out of oven and place a plate that is bigger
than the skillet on top of it. Flip skillet over, watching out for
hot duck fat, and slide potatoes back into skillet, bottom up. Bake
15 minutes, until browned. Sprinkle with salt, pepper, garlic and
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
