<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Touring National Parks
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I would like to do a tour of national parks,
including Yellowstone, Arches, Bryce Canyon and Grand Canyon. Can
you help? _ Sy Hakim, Philadelphia &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Tour operators that combine in a single tour all four parks
you mention are the exception. A look at the map explains why:
Yellowstone and Grand Teton, with which it is often paired, are in
the northwestern corner of Wyoming. And that's a considerable
distance from Arches, Bryce and Zion, which are in the southern
half of Utah not far from Grand Canyon National Park.
</P>
<P>
   When selecting a tour, it's a good idea to review the itinerary
to be sure that the places you really want to see aren't being
scanted; more can sometimes be less. Here is a sampling of bus
tours _ the first two of which cover the four parks you mention _
with some highlights. All prices are per person, double occupancy;
air fare is extra.
</P>
<P>
   Trafalgar Tours: Scenic Parks Explorer, 14 days, 23 meals. Start
and end in Las Vegas. Zion, Bryce Canyon, Salt Lake City, Jackson,
Grand Teton, Yellowstone. Rapid City, Denver, Mesa Verde, Grand
Canyon. Every Sunday from May 9 to Sept. 26. $1,899. Bookings only
through travel agents; information (800) 854-0103.
</P>
<P>
   Vantage Deluxe World Travel: America's Magnificent National
Parks, 15 days, 25 meals. Start in Bozeman, Mont., end in Las
Vegas. Yellowstone, Grand Teton, Jackson, Salt Lake City, Arches,
Grand Canyon, Lake Powell, Bryce Canyon, Zion. Aug. 2 and 30 and
Sept. 13 and 20. $2,295 to $2,495, depending on date. Geared to
travelers aged 50 and up. Bookings directly or through a travel
agent; information (800) 322-6677.
</P>
<P>
   Globus: Parks and Canyons Spectacular, 13 days, 22 meals. Start
in Las Vegas, end in Denver. Grand Canyon, Lake Powell, Zion, Bryce
Canyon, Salt Lake City, Jackson, Grand Teton, Yellowstone, Black
Hills of South Dakota. Five trips a week from June 6 to Sept. 26.
$1,609 to $1,649, depending on date. Bookings only through a travel
agent; information (800) 241-9853.
</P>
<P>
   Mayflower Tours: National Parks of the Southwest, 10 days, 17
meals. Start and end in Las Vegas. Grand Canyon, Lake Powell,
Arches, Capitol Reef, Bryce Canyon, Zion. Fourteen trips from June
10 to Sept. 27. $1,498. Bookings directly or through an agent;
information (800) 323-7604 or (630) 435-8500, fax (630) 960-3575.
</P>
<P>
   Tauck Tours: Canyonlands, 8 days, 19 meals. Start in Phoenix,
end in Las Vegas. Sedona, Grand Canyon, Lake Powell, Bryce Canyon,
Zion. Four trips a week from March 30 to Oct. 30. $1,575. Books
directly or through an agent; information (800) 468-2825, fax (203)
221-6828.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to national parks who want to bike, hike or kayak will
find www.gorp.com a useful resource.
</P>
<P>
   Laptops at Airports
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you provide the definitive answer as to whether or not I
am injuring my laptop computer by sending it through airport
security scanners? _ James E. Tierney, Lisbon Falls, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   A. No one can give a definitive answer on anything concerning
computers, according to Stephen C. Miller, assistant to the
technology editor of The New York Times. Even so, he said,
significant anecdotal evidence strongly suggests that airport
scanners do not harm laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that in a recent three-month period he had been
through five airports (meaning 10 trips through the scanners) and
that he had not run into a problem at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I write a column about traveling with technology, I'm
always sending all kinds of electronic gadgets through the
scanners,'' he said. ``The vast majority of my fellow business
travelers carry laptops and I've never heard one of them complain
about the scanners' harming the data.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who are really concerned, Miller suggests, should hand
the unit to the security guard and insist that it be inspected
manually. If you do this, he said, make sure your battery is
charged because they are going to ask you to turn on the computer.
Dead batteries will delay you.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg Cruises
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there any short tours _ possibly even a three-day cruise
_ to St. Petersburg from Stockholm? _ John Moak, Somers, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you're taking a boat, the only way to get from Stockholm
to St. Petersburg is via Helsinki. That means an overnight trip in
both directions between those two ports plus four days of cruising
between Helsinki and St. Petersburg _ all of which adds up to six
days.
</P>
<P>
   You can whittle away at travel time by taking a one-hour flight
between Stockholm to Helsinki. The round trip air fare is about
$160 to $325 for a restricted ticket; an unrestricted ticket is
$326 and up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Viking Line vessel links Stockholm and Helsinki; outbound, she
leaves at 6 p.m. and arrives at 9 a.m. The fare one way is $131 to
$216 per person double occupancy, including dinner, breakfast and
port charges. With a whole day in Helsinki, you may want to take a
two-and-a-half-hour sightseeing tour of the city from the Viking
Line terminal. Tickets are $20 and can be bought aboard ship. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Between Helsinki and St. Petersburg, you will be aboard the
Kristina Regina, the only passenger liner linking the two cities,
according to B.J. Mikkelsen, owner and president of Eurocruises, a
cruise tour operator representing several European cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Kristina Regina, a Kristina Cruises ship, leaves Helsinki at
5:30 p.m. and arrives in St. Petersburg at 8:30 the next morning.
The round trip fare is $390 to $930, including all meals (dinner,
three meals each on the following two days and breakfast before
getting off) as well as port charges. The number of passengers is
limited to 200, Mikkelsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers do not need a visa and they get a half-day tour of
St. Petersburg. There are also tours that last about four hours,
cost $35 to $45 and include visits to the Hermitage, the Peterhof
(summer capital of the czars), the Kirov Ballet and Pushkin Palace
and such activities as singing and dancing. A shopping tour in St.
Petersburg is $10.
</P>
<P>
   The departure from St. Petersburg is not until 10:30 p.m., and
arrival in Helsinki is at 11:30 a.m. the next day. The boat leaves
Helsinki at 6 p.m., arriving in Stockholm at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Kristina Regina's departure dates this year are June 1 and
4, July 21 and 27 and Aug. 2, 8, 11 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Eurocruises, 303 West 13th St., New York, N.Y.
10014; (800) 688-3876 or (212) 691-2099, fax (212) 366-4747. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
