<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD RELIABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's BAAAACK!
</P>
<P>
   That hardy perennial, the minimum wage, is once again on the
congressional agenda. In truth, it never really went away.
</P>
<P>
   On the scale of grand national issues, this is barely visible.
But measured by its potential for political symbolism, it's a hot
one.
</P>
<P>
   A House committee rehashed the issue Tuesday, with business
still opposed to another increase and labor unions demanding a
higher minimum than the current $5.15 an hour. We have heard it all
before.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage level, although only one legislative tool in
the federal arsenal for fighting poverty, has always been an easily
defined political issue. That is part of its persevering charm.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a low-paid worker, you are naturally for a salary
increase. The minimum wage is believed to push up the incomes of
those who already earn slightly above that floor. If you are a
small-business owner with a narrow profit margin, you are naturally
opposed to having the government tell you how much you are required
to pay the unskilled workers you prefer to get on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 presidential campaign, Congress passed a
two-year 90-cent increase in the minimum wage, the first since
1991. Democrats in the House and Senate pushed it through with the
help of moderate Republicans worried about the negative impact of
House Speaker Newt Gingrich's pompous extremism and their party's
conservative, anti-government tilt.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showed that 81 percent of those surveyed supported the
increase, which directly affected an estimated 6.4 million workers
then getting by on smaller salaries.
</P>
<P>
   That was supposed to settle the matter for a while. But the
increase was so politically popular that it promptly stimulated
congressional appetites for a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Dire predictions from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and other
business advocates that a higher minimum wage would add to
inflation, force some employers to close their doors and reduce the
number of unskilled jobs available have not proved accurate.
</P>
<P>
   There is some anecdotal evidence that a few jobs in restaurants
and other labor-intensive industries may have been lost. But the
economy is prospering, jobs overall have continued to grow and the
unemployment rate of 4.2 per cent is the lowest in almost three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Last autumn Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., for several decades a
reliable champion of the minimum wage, tried to slip an increase to
$6.15 an hour into a Senate consumer bankruptcy bill. The Senate
quietly tabled the amendment on a party-line vote, with Democrats
for and Republicans against.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation proposed last year by House Minority Whip
David Bonior, D-Mich., a liberal from a union-dominated district,
never got out of a GOP-controlled committee.
</P>
<P>
   But here we go again. This issue is too good for Democrats and
moderate Republicans to pass up as we move toward another
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The narrowly divided House may well pass an increase, perhaps
larded with pro-business compensations like new tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, however, plays by different internal rules, and
conservative pro-business Republicans have firmer control. Senate
Whip Don Nickles of Oklahoma recently said, ``I don't plan on
letting it pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are unlikely to mind much if Senate Republicans are
willing to be tabbed as captives of wealthy employers reluctant to
pay a living wage to the nation's lowest-paid workers. This is
considerably more useful on the campaign trail as a continuing
issue than as a record of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has the virtue of simplicity and clarity, unlike the
complicated arguments over other, larger questions that affect our
lives like Social Security, Medicare and tax cuts. It reinforces
the Democratic image as the party of compassion for the little guy
and the GOP image as the party of selfish vested interests.
</P>
<P>
   It reminds voters that some GOP spokesmen, such as House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, not only oppose increasing the
minimum wage but would like to do away with the concept altogether.
If poor folks can't afford bread, let 'em eat cake. What a theme to
run on in a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   I confess a personal fondness for the minimum wage, which has
been periodically increased over the 60 years of its existence.
When I was a young Nebraska journalist working for pennies, such a
hike to $1 an hour gave me my first salary increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
