<HEADER>
A5176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SADE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-27 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SADE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MARQUIS DE SADE': FINDING THE BRIGHT SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Good Friday, April 2, 1790, when the 50-year-old Marquis de
Sade was released from the Charenton insane asylum after nearly 12
years in three French prisons, he vowed in a letter to his lawyer
that he would forever sanctify that day with ``moaning and
weeping.'' Every Good Friday, he wrote, ``I will get down on my
knees, I will pray, I will offer up thanks. ... I will make a
resolution to mend my ways, and I will keep to my word.''
</P>
<P>
   Sade, who gave his name to such words as sadistic and
sadomasochism, is not known for feelings of contrition or for
religious sentiment. And of course, there is the possibility that
he was speaking in bitter irony on the day of his release. Indeed,
far from mending his ways, he resumed his libertine's life as well
as the writing of the scandalous novels of human degradation that
would land him back in prison, where he died in 1814.
</P>
<P>
   And yet that scene on April 2 has a poignancy to it, a genuine
feeling of the tragic. It enables one to see Sade not only as
something close to an archetype, a kind of grotesque cardboard
figure, but as a man who is both contemptible and, in his way,
admirable. That complexity is one of the virtues of this new and
lengthy biography, ``The Marquis de Sade: A Life,'' by Neil
Schaeffer, a professor of English literature at Brooklyn College.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly possible to ask, as one sits down to read
Schaeffer's treatment of Sade, why another biography of this
notorious and already well-researched figure is needed. But
Schaeffer's book is a welcome addition to the literature. It is
both sophisticated and hardheaded about Sade; it has a definitive
quality to it.
</P>
<P>
   Central to Schaeffer's portrait is the idea of a strange,
stubborn greatness to Sade, both as a literary adventurer into
territory that no other writer had dared explore and as a champion
of an extreme libertarian philosophy. In Schaeffer's view, Sade's
life was a contest with authority in which sex was a kind of
argument, a provocation for ``a debate on individual freedom and
the limitations imposed by religion and government.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Sade, Schaeffer continues, was this: ``If Sade
meant his acts as a symbolic defiance of abstract authority, it was
real-world, actual authority (embodied in the police and in judges)
that would punish him, and quite severely.''
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer's new book continues a steady expansion of studies of
Sade, who does not lose his power to attract interest and
controversy as time goes by. Two other books have been published on
him in recent months _ ``At Home With the Marquis de Sade: A Life''
by Francine du Plessix Gray and ``Sade: A Biographical Essay'' by
Laurence L. Bongie. These books _ Ms. Gray's more or less
sympathetic to Sade, Bongie's morally hostile _ concentrated on
Sade's relations with the women in his life. Schaeffer has written
a more inclusive biography, one that does not stint on Sade's
almost amazing egotism, his monstrous and self-destructive
heedlessness of others, even as it highlights his stubborn courage.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, you may feel, as I did, that Schaeffer magnifies
Sade's importance; he calls ``120 Days of Sodom'' ``one of the most
important novels ever written.'' But he lays out the facts of
Sade's fascinating life and character and leaves it up to the
reader to judge.
</P>
<P>
   Sade's biographers agree that the Sade of real life may have
been sexually adventurous and perverse but that his behavior was
not all that unusual by the standards of the 18th-century French
aristocracy. Certainly the acts of murder, incest, coprophilia,
torture and mutilation that are the stuff of his books were not the
stuff of his real life. Schaeffer subjects both the books and the
life to close scrutiny, complete with psychological and literary
analysis. He recounts in elaborate detail the episodes that gave
Sade his first bout of notoriety: his debaucheries with prostitutes
who later complained to police of various acts of blasphemy and
sexual violence. He retells the strange story of Sade's redoubtable
mother-in-law, Marie-Madeleine de Montreuil, who persuaded the king
to throw Sade into the dungeon of Vincennes even after he was
acquitted of the prostitutes' charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Sade the monomaniacal sex fiend of myth, merely writing
down his own masturbatory fantasies in the Bastille?'' Schaeffer
asks, as he turns to an examination of his first major novel, ``120
Days of Sodom.'' ``Or is he bravely and purposefully attempting to
write the only book that will show the mind of man as no one
acknowledges it to be but as it really is? The answer must be yes
to both questions.''
</P>
<P>
   It needs to be remembered in this that ``120 Days of Sodom'' is
about a group of wealthy and unspeakably corrupt men who organize a
prolonged experiment in what Schaeffer calls ``truly horrifying
bloodshed and savage murder.'' Is there really greatness in such
literature? Schaeffer clearly believes that there is, and he makes
his case both bravely and intelligently, concluding that ``120 Days
of Sodom'' ``is a transcendent, darkly sublime novel, the most
extreme evocation of disillusionment and disappointment, the most
unconsoling exploration of the most irredeemable aspects of human
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is true; perhaps, as other critics have argued,
Sade's descent into imaginative degradation is less an exploration
of the hidden aspects of human nature and more an act of unredeemed
and therefore pointless ugliness.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the vision that Schaeffer creates is of Sade
pouring out what was for him a philosophical and political
testament while lying on the stone floor of a medieval prison,
writing on a secret, handmade paper scroll.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Sade spent 29 years in prison. There is something
powerful and moving in that fact alone, and it is the strength of
Schaeffer's biography that it makes Sade not just a notorious
figure but a credibly heroic one as well.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE MARQUIS DE SADE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Life'
</P>
<P>
   By Neil Schaeffer
</P>
<P>
   567 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
