<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-SPENDING-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MILITARY BUDGET DRAWS FIRE AS GOP REMEMBERS REAGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concerned that America's military might is
stretched too thin, many lawmakers are looking to beef up defense
spending beyond what President Clinton says is necessary to pay for
the bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already asked Congress to pass an emergency $6
billion supplemental spending bill to pay for the military
operations and humanitarian aid in the Balkans. Republicans want to
boost that figure by at least $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply paying to recoup the direct costs of operating the
force and for expended ammunition is necessary, but far from
sufficient,'' said Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., chairman of the House
Armed Services Committee. ``It does nothing to address our
vulnerabilities and shortfalls in other critically important and
dangerous regions of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Spence's comments are typical of many Republicans, who have long
complained that Clinton neglects the military. Defense spending has
indeed fallen under Clinton, but that dip began under President
George Bush and was precipitated by the decline of the Cold War and
the disintegration of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   As far as money is concerned, the military's golden years were
under President Ronald Reagan. At the height of the Reagan military
buildup, defense spending, when adjusted for inflation, reached
$424 billion, accounting for roughly 27 percent of the federal
budget.
</P>
<P>
   This year, President Clinton plans to spend $268 billion on
defense needs, roughly 15 percent of the federal budget. Spending
on defense will likely rise because of the NATO war against
Yugoslavia. Overall, defense spending has declined approximately 30
percent since the Reagan years.
</P>
<P>
   Some defense experts say that it's too simplistic and misleading
to look at the budget numbers and conclude that Clinton is
shortchanging the military. They point to the fall of the Berlin
Wall and the breakup of the Soviet Union as evidence that America's
traditional foes have weakened, thus undercutting the need for a
continued buildup of the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the end of the Cold War meant America had to
re-evaluate,'' said Steven Kosiak, director of budget studies at
the Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, an independent
think tank devoted to defense issues. ``It was prudent to make
reductions in the size of the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosiak and others also said that the decline in military
spending is also tied to the fact that programs such as Medicare
and Social Security are growing fast, grabbing a larger share of
the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Kosiak said the military may have some
shortfalls that the Clinton administration has only recently begun
to acknowledge. At hearings on Capitol Hill, various military
leaders have talked about problems in recruiting and retaining
skilled men and women, particularly pilots. They've also described
difficulty in maintaining the readiness of some equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In February, when Defense Secretary William Cohen unveiled the
administration's proposed $267 billion military budget for next
year, he talked about ``warning signs of potential problems,'' but
he said that the president's plan would address them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting and retention are increasingly difficult, readiness
harder to maintain, and weapons modernization tougher to fund
sufficiently,'' Cohen said. ``This budget will address these
warnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, are skeptical. They want to raise military
pay more than Clinton, believing it will alleviate the retention
problem. They say the crisis in Kosovo has underscored the Clinton
administration's willingness to deploy U.S. armed forces to
conflicts abroad without considering whether such actions weaken
this country's own defense capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a large and growing military commitment in the Balkans,
what happens if war breaks out in those regions of the world where
there is no question as to our national interest?'' Spence asked.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all their rhetoric about military needs, Republicans
rarely, if ever, detail where they would cut spending to pay for
the defense increases. In fact, most lawmakers are loathe to even
talk about cuts to Social Security and Medicare, which are among
the costliest programs in government.
</P>
<P>
   Kosiak said policy experts need to consider what kind of role
America's military should play in the world before anyone can
reasonably conclude how much to spend on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you have that kind of debate, you can't decide on
weapons systems or force structures,'' he said. But he's not
optimistic that will happen anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense budget is a heavily politicized issue,'' Kosiak
said. ``With a presidential election coming up, sometimes that's
not the most opportune time for thoughtful debate on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is a Washington correspondent for the New York
Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
