<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depictions of Lincoln Shown in Indiana
</P>
<P>
   Fort Wayne, Ind., is off the usual tourist track, but history
buffs and political junkies may just want to put it on their
itineraries this year. ``Lincoln From Life: As the Artists Saw
Him,'' at the Lincoln Museum there through Oct. 17, brings together
46 paintings, sculptures, photographs and sketches that Lincoln
posed for between 1860, when he was elected president, until his
assassination in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   Several works, which come from more than a dozen public and
private collections as well as the Lincoln Museum, have never been
lent before.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is designed to show how Lincoln pioneered the use
of the arts to enhance his public persona long before photography
and television made image-making a campaign necessity. He was a
willing subject, posing more often than has been previously
acknowledged, and he encouraged artists to make flattering
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Among the works on display are three important paintings that
have never been shown together before _ Alban James Conant's
``Smiling Lincoln'' from 1860; George Frederick Wright's campaign
portrait from 1860, the first portrait purchased by Lincoln
himself; and Edward D. Marchant's ``Great Emancipator,'' depicting
Lincoln in white tie, with symbolic broken chains beneath the feet
of the Liberty statue in the background. Lincoln's last portrait
from life, which Matthew Henry Wilson completed 11 days before the
assassination, is also on view.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Museum, 200 East Berry Street, has scheduled several
events with the exhibition, including a ball in October with period
music and costumes. Open daily except Monday. Admission is $2.99;
(219) 455-3864 or www.thelincolnmuseum-.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith H. Dobrzynski
</P>
<P>
   Belugas and Seals Move In at Mystic
</P>
<P>
   The Mystic Aquarium will continue its expansion this spring with
the opening of a new outdoor marine mammal habitat in mid-May.
Called the Alaskan Coast, the one-acre exhibit will be home to the
Aquarium's beluga whales and harbor seals.
</P>
<P>
   Rocks, plants and trees characteristic of south-central Alaska
surround the 750,000-gallon pool. Viewing stations offer the chance
to see the animals above and below the water's surface.
</P>
<P>
   In the shallow-water beach, visitors may get close to the whales
as they rub themselves on the cobble-covered bottom. The exhibit is
dedicated to beluga research and breeding as part of an
international conservation program.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium, at 55 Coogan Boulevard, Mystic, Conn., is about
125 miles from New York on I-95 (take Exit 90). Open 9 a.m. to 5
p.m.; until 6 p.m. July 1 through Labor Day. Visitors may remain in
the aquarium for an hour after closing. Admission is $15, $10 ages
3 to 12. Information: (860) 572-5955 or www.mysticaquarium.org.
</P>
<P>
   For the Eco-Conscious, Tours in Canada's Parks
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Canada's national parks can collect water samples in
streams and study breeding birds alongside professional researchers
in a program called Parks Canada Research Adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Operated by Good Earth Travel Adventures in Canmore, Alberta, in
conjunction with Parks Canada, the program is in its fourth year
and has been growing steadily. This year eight trips, from three to
seven days, are being offered through September. Groups are limited
to 10, and each trip will be led by at least one expert researcher.
</P>
<P>
   In Spring Bird Survey, June 25 to 29 and June 30 to July 4,
participants will listen for and identify breeding birds in
Waterton Lakes National Park in Alberta. Basic birding skills, such
as using binoculars and familiarity with common species, are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The price is $383 a person, which covers only the educational
program. Accommodations, food and transportation to the starting
point are extra, and packages for these are available.
</P>
<P>
   Other programs include Wildcats and Wildwater, focusing on
protecting water quality for the lynx in Yoho and Banff National
Parks, on Aug. 16 to 22, and Bears and Biodiversity, studying the
ecology of the two same parks, July 5 to 8, Aug. 9 to 15 and Sept.
13 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   Information or reservations: (888) 979-9797 or (403) 678-9358.
</P>
<P>
   _ Janet Piorko
</P>
<P>
   Tourist Help Line Set Up in Portugal
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese government has set up a new help line for
tourists in Portugal. Called the Green Line, the number is (800)
296-296.
</P>
<P>
   Operators furnish information about hotels, restaurants,
transportation, museums and special events, and in an emergency,
they can help with hospitals and the police. The Green Line is
available in four languages _ English, Portuguese, French and
Spanish _ Monday through Saturday 9 a.m. to midnight and on Sunday
9 a.m. to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The toll-free number is good anywhere in the country using
either a regular or a cellular phone. Tourist offices throughout
Portugal offer direct phones to the Green Line. It cannot be
reached from outside Portugal.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golfing in Italy, With Culture Thrown In &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new resort south of Verona, midway between Venice and Milan,
adds golfing in luxury to the pleasures of the Lake Garda region.
</P>
<P>
   Palazzo Arzaga, which opened March 21, includes a 15th-century
monastery and chapel with original frescoes in three rooms and
common areas. Besides two championship golf courses totaling 27
holes, designed by Jack Nicklaus II and Gary Player, and a golf
academy, the resort offers a Saturnia spa, with a holistic approach
to health, three restuarants and proximity to cultural outposts
like Cremona, where Stradivarius stringed instruments were made.
Classical music concerts are planned for the chapel, and the Verona
opera is a half-hour's drive away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The palazzo's 84 rooms include five suites. They are decorated
with 18th-century Venetian and 19th-century Lombardy furnishings.
Suites have fireplaces and marble bathrooms. All the rooms have
air-conditioning, satellite television, hair dryers and computer
jacks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other amenities include two tennis courts, a fitness center, a
driving range, outdoor and indoor pools, hiking trails and a
jogging track. Sailing is available on Lake Garda. Cooking classes
will be offered periodically.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The golf academy, which opened Saturday, offers three- and
five-night packages. They include three hours of lessons, unlimited
greens fees, an afternoon at the spa, and a single or double room
with breakfast for $725 to $1,470. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Arzaga's room rates for the first year start at $310 a night
for doubles and $665 for suites, including breakfast, taxes and
tips. Reservations: (800) 323-7500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ray Cormier
</P>
