<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV04-     04-27 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL STOP OUR GROUND WAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, May 4)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day of the killings in Littleton, Colo., a friend at work
couldn't rest until she called her teen-age daughter. ``I know
she'll say, `Oh, mom,' but I just have to,'' she explained, even
though her daughter was just across town at her high school in
Santa Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   I thought it was perfectly natural. When something this horrible
happens you need to touch your own, reassure yourself that their
world is still safe and intact.
</P>
<P>
   A Littleton father of triplets, freshmen at Columbine High
School, was waiting at the airport in Washington to take off for
Denver that day when the pilot announced there had been a shooting
at a Denver school.
</P>
<P>
   He got to a phone, called home and his older son, a college
student, answered. ``There were two things wrong. He wasn't
supposed to be home, and he started crying when he heard my voice.
But then he said, `Dad, the kids are fine.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from the lowest low to the highest high in a matter of
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   One child was at the opposite end of the school from the gunmen
and got out early. Another was helped to safety by a janitor who
said ``follow me and run for your life.'' The third was running
from the shooters when he turned and saw his friend shot point
blank, ``killed in the most vicious way,'' said the father.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman I know used to live in Littleton and that's where
her kids went to school, although it was the other high school from
where the massacre took place. Her kids are long out of school and
she now lives in Denver, but the reason they chose Littleton was
for the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wanted your kids to go to school in Jefferson County.
These schools are award winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Had it happened in Denver, she wouldn't have been as shocked.
She knows someone who quit teaching in Denver because the kids were
so abusive. He had a panic button under his desk to push if he felt
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   There goes another stereotype. Your nice, comfortable
neighborhood will not protect you. A superior school district will
not protect you. Kids with guns have become the great equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   We're running out of ways to rationalize these things, and
that's good. We tend to look for differences after this kind of
tragedy. What can we come up with to distance our community from
that one? Those kids from our kids?
</P>
<P>
   I don't like people turning kids in weird costumes into the
enemy. I know a ``Goth'' kid, maybe she's now an ex-Goth, since her
hair is lately close to natural and her fingernail polish more
glittery than black. She is definitely out of the mainstream, but
she is sweet and smart. The father of the triplets said his kids
had never mentioned any ``trench coat mafia,'' but he, too, is wary
of labeling a group.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too easy, and what does that lead to? Outlawing cults?
And then, what's a cult? Is the Lions Club a cult?''
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators have even tried to single out Colorado as
being gun-happy, calling it a hunter's paradise. That's too easy,
too, even though the governor was, until this week, all for
allowing everyone to carry concealed weapons. But I don't think we
can blame this on Colorado. Or on kids who wear black trench coats.
We can't even blame it on troubled children or our culture, as if
we were somehow not responsible for either.
</P>
<P>
   This is our national tragedy. Our Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the world now looks at our dead children and
our disbelieving faces and shudders. Foreign newspaper headlines
talk about gun-sick America.
</P>
<P>
   We have a ground war going on right here at home and we have to
intervene because we're the adults. I think we do whatever we can
to take away the guns and take away the message that violence is a
way to solve problems. If the NRA says it's not its fault and the
people who make murder/slasher/serial killer movies say it isn't
theirs, we bring them along to the negotiation table where we sit
down with kids and parents and teachers and find out what we can do
to stop the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Then we try to get to the root of the trouble that produces a
troubled kid by using all our school psychologists and family
dynamic experts. We find out what causes the rage, anger, despair,
resentment, boredom or self-loathing that moves a kid to shoot
another kid in the face because he doesn't like the color of his
skin or his hat or that he's on the football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were blowing them away,'' a Littleton survivor said.
</P>
<P>
   No, they weren't blowing them away. That's movie talk. They were
killing them without batting an eye.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks we've been looking at those terrible scenes in
Yugoslavia, asking how can human beings cause such misery and not
give a damn. This week's question is what makes a child run through
a school, laughing and shouting, ``It's a good day to die.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
