<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MISS-WOMEN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSISSIPPI LINKS UP WITH BIG-TIME GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CECIL HURT   
 Tuscaloosa, Ala., News   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ The course is lush and lovely, the
facilities luxuriant. Everything about the Old Waverly Golf Club
suggests that it will be a challenging course for the U.S. Women's
Open when it arrives on June 3-7.
</P>
<P>
   There is an obvious question, though, as even Mary Capouch,
chairwoman of the USGA Women's Committee, acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Mississippi? Why Old Waverly?'' Capouch said. ``To tell
the truth, we've been asked that a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Se Ri Pak, who was also on hand at the course
this week, summed up the perception problems.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, a native of Korea, wasn't familiar with Mississippi until a
few months ago. A friend gave Pak a succinct description.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said `very hot,''' Pak said. ``Hot and boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Added to that was the fact that West Point, a town of about
30,000 at the northern tip of the so-called ''Golden Triangle,''
isn't the biggest or the busiest town in Mississippi, lacking the
size of Jackson or the casino glitz of the Gulf Coast towns.
</P>
<P>
   George Bryan, the Bryan Foods heir who built Old Waverly in the
late '80s and almost single-handedly persuaded the USGA to bring
their marquee women's event to town, doesn't look at the setting as
a disadvantage. Instead, he thinks it will add to the growing
popularity of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we made the original proposal, we had some naysayers,''
Bryan said. ``There will always be people who think that you can't
make something work in a rural setting. But we didn't think we were
tackling something we couldn't handle. We researched this very
carefully. We saw that people will travel for an event like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the example of the area support given to last year's
tournament in the small town of Kohler, Wisc., more than an hour's
drive from Chicago and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like an event of this magnitude, a national
championship, was something that doesn't happen in this area very
often and that people would come to support it,'' Bryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that Old Waverly had the resources, and motivated by a
promise to his late father that he would pursue a championship
event, Bryan made his presentation to the USGA in 1995. Capouch
described Bryan's pitch as a ``wonderful presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten or fifteen years ago, you would not have seen a
presentation like that, which is a reflection of the tremendous
growth in the popularity of women's golf,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   USGA officials came to Old Waverly and green-lighted the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The time was right for this region. Capouch said that ``one of
the missions of the USGA is to take our championships to as many
geographical regions as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one major USGA event _ the 1976 U.S. Open in Atlanta _ has
been played in the Deep South. That event was won by Jerry Pate,
who coincidentally designed Old Waverly.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bryan's faith in the region has been borne out. An army
of volunteers has been raised from across eastern Mississippi.
Players have spoken glowingly of the course. Attendance projections
are good, though Bryan is pushing for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we've sold 85,000 tickets and we'd like to have
100,000 or 105,000,'' Bryan said. He said he expects to draw 3,000
to 4,000 at practice rounds early in the week and by the weekend
hopes to hit 30,000 or even 35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Local hotels are filled but rooms are available in Tupelo and
Tuscaloosa, Bryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Women's Open is enjoying a surge of popularity. Last
year's tournament, which ended in a 20-hole playoff between Pak,
the 20-year old sensation, and amateur Jenny Chuasiriporn, was the
most-watched event in women's golf. This year's event will be
televised by ESPN and, in the final two rounds, by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Glenn, the USGA manager of communications, said that last
year's tournament gave viewers ``a front row seat for history.'' By
moving the tournament to Mississippi, the USGA is guaranteed of
history again, regardless of the final results.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Womens Open is one of 13 national championships
conducted annually by the USGA. Other championships include the
U.S. Open, the U.S. Senior Open and 10 national amateur
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   (The Tuscaloosa, Ala., News is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
