<HEADER>
A5272 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CATALINA-$ADV0     04-27 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CATALINA-$ADV02-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUCH OF CAPRI OFF LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 2) 
(jt) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the clearest days it rises, as the old song says, ``26 miles
across the sea,'' an apparition barely visible from the beachfronts
of greater Los Angeles _ if not quite Bali Ha'i, certainly an
``island of romance.'' From the bubble of a speedy jet helicopter
bearing down on the picturesque harbor of Avalon, the crags of
Catalina Island rise more dramatically, like some Amalfi town
plopped into the Pacific off the coastal plain of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   When my wife, Dee Dee, and I stole away for Easter weekend this
year, we decided to try to make getting there half the fun,
eschewing the hourlong boat ride across an often choppy channel for
the 14-minute ease of Island Express Helicopter Service, which
leaves from Long Beach harbor, where the Queen Mary now floats as a
hotel, its red smokestacks intimating grander journeys.
</P>
<P>
   The vertiginous chopper ascent is a thrill all its own. Our ride
seemed to have barely begun on that windy Saturday afternoon when
the island came sharply into view and the pilot warned us we would
feel some bumps approaching the landing zone at Pebbly Beach, just
down the shore from Avalon, Catalina's only real town. As it turned
out, it was a good thing we flew; unusually high winds and waves
prompted gale warnings, and the red flags in the harbor meant the
day's last ferries would be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Because our pilot had radioed ahead for a taxi, one was there to
meet us for the five-minute drive to our room at the Hotel
Metropole, built about a decade ago amid a shopping courtyard in
the heart of town, a block back from the beach. And from the minute
we set foot on the broad, pedestrian mall of Crescent Avenue, the
main thoroughfare that curves around the small harbor, I felt a
continent away from the thrum and traffic of Los Angeles, almost as
if I were in an Italian coastal town. Dee Dee spent several summers
on the island as a Girl Scout camp counselor at nearby White's
Landing, and so couldn't quite share my momentary Mediterranean
reverie, but she generously indulged it all the same, and smiled at
familiar landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Catalina's great charm is its unusual blend of built-up pleasure
port and unspoiled, wild interior. It has been a resort destination
for more than a century, first as a virtual tent city of striped
canvas and genteel rocking chairs, and beginning in 1919 as the
more cosmopolitan preserve of William Wrigley Jr., the chewing gum
magnate who bought the controlling interest in the company that
owned the island. Wrigley built a splendid Art Deco ballroom and
movie palace on a point at the end of the harbor, and a sprawling
white mansion for himself on a promontory above it. For years
Catalina was the spring-training home of the Wrigley family's other
pastime, the Chicago Cubs, and the biggest bands of the '30s and
'40s played the circular Casino, as the oceanfront ballroom is
called. It is still the site of dances, weddings and concerts.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1975, the Wrigley family transferred ownership of nearly
90 percent of the 76-square-mile island to the Santa Catalina
Island Conservancy, which maintains the inland roads, a general
aviation airport and acres of back country, where boars and
descendants of bison brought for a movie shoot still roam. Cars are
banned for all but longtime residents (the year-round population is
3,200), and there is now about a 10-year waiting list. Custom golf
carts, with plastic wind curtains, are the transport of choice; the
only visitor vehicles allowed inland are sightseeing buses and
trams. Crammed in summer with blissed-out beachcombers, the island,
with its mild weather, is a year-round getaway for Southern
Californians, especially boaters.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Avalon, the only appreciable speck of civilization on
the island is Two Harbors, a rustic yachting port on a narrow
isthmus on the island's west end. All this careful management means
that Catalina still feels very much as it must have when Humphrey
Bogart sailed over in his yacht Santana, singing ``September Song''
with the likes of Frank Sinatra, or John Wayne arrived in his
converted minesweeper.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropole, a gray-and-white clapboard building with tiers of
balconies, is one of the newer hotels in Avalon and among the
nicest, and made a great jumping off point for our two-day visit.
It is named for the island's original grand hotel, which burned
down in a fire believed to have started in its kitchen, taking half
the town down in flames with it in 1915. The only fire we found was
the one in the gas fireplace in our clean, comfy, if unremarkable
king-bed room, and the tempting aroma of fried calamari wafting up
through the courtyard from the adjoining Channel House restaurant
seemed a danger of the purely caloric kind. Because of the wind and
weather, maritime amusements, like snorkeling, scuba diving, a
cruise on glass-bottom boat or a spin in a sea kayak, were out of
the question, so we contented ourselves with a walk around town,
strolling the side streets where frame bungalows were built row on
row atop the old tent pads, and shopping on Crescent Avenue. Dee
Dee found a sundress (for warmer days) at C.C. Gallagher, a
charming boutique with an espresso bar, sandwich counter and books
on meditation and healthy cooking, while I couldn't resist Lloyd's,
the island's venerable confectioner, for the first of two bags of
soft homemade saltwater taffy in assorted citrus flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Combining research and diversion, we decided to catch a 7
o'clock movie at the gorgeous 1,000-seat Avalon, an Art Deco movie
palace underneath the vintage 1929 Casino. The theater has been
lovingly preserved, and we were delighted by the giant outdoor tile
murals of underwater scenes that cover its loggia, and the painted
ones of California history and landscapes that spread around its
vaulting interior, complemented with rich wood trim and velvet
drapes. The movie, ``Cruel Intentions,'' was lamentable, but the
pre-curtain concert on the Page pipe organ originally installed to
accompany silent films was terrific. The organist pulled out every
stop, from ``Chattanooga Choo-Choo'' with wailing train whistle, to
``Lilli Marlene'' with muffled drums, while star-sized lights
twinkled in the ceiling. Finally, just before the red and green
houselights dimmed, came a majestic, thundering version of the Al
Jolson chestnut ``Avalon.''
</P>
<P>
   After the show, we repaired to Armstrong's Seafood, one of the
most popular waterfront restaurants, with its simple blue and white
checked cloths, harbor view and in-house fish market. It is run by
a local salt and sport-fisherman named Russ Armstrong, whose
mother, Hazel, presides at the front desk and bakes the delicious
homemade carrot cake (``no raisins, extra walnuts''). After a bit
of a wait amid the Saturday crowds, we had martinis and appetizers
of cracked crab claws and chunks of superb smoked albacore tuna,
but the real treat was the fresh sand dabs, caught a mile from
shore at 5:30 that afternoon. This small, succulent fish _ a
beloved local specialty _ tastes a bit like flounder and cleans out
to something about the size of a thin bar of soap; our waitress
expertly filleted each delicious, sauteed piece tableside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Too lazy and cold to brave a sunrise Easter service in the hills
above town the next morning, but too conditioned to skip church on
that day, we joined Dee Dee's fellow Catholics at St. Catherine's
Church for a peaceful Mass at 9 a.m., and promptly returned to sin
with an artery-clogging stop at Sally's Waffle Shop. We both had
the specialty of the house, Dee Dee with pecans and I straight up,
plus a perfectly basted fried egg, bacon and plenty of good coffee
in a simple storefront where booths surround a square counter with
stools.
</P>
<P>
   Since the wind was still stiff and boating impossible, we took a
gentle mile-and-a-half walk up Avalon Canyon Road, which stretches
behind the town, to the Wrigley Memorial and Botanical Garden. The
130-foot-high Spanish style memorial to William Wrigley Jr., built
almost entirely of native materials in 1934, affords a commanding
view of the ocean and the garden. The 37-acre grounds were the
project of Wrigley's widow, Ada, and its plants include succulents,
native cherry trees that once fed the Indian inhabitants and the
deadly wild tomato, whose purple-black berries are highly
poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   As the day became gloriously sunny, we determined to strike out
on our own off-road adventure. We turned left on our way out of the
garden at the Hermit Gulch campground and took a well-marked trail
leading into the hills above town for what we thought would be an
easy six- or seven-mile hike. All went well enough as we climbed
switchbacks, finally reaching a ridgeline that gave panoramic views
of both sides of the island and the ocean beyond, and a sense of
how it all must have looked to the Gabrieleno Indians who lived
here in pre-colonial times.
</P>
<P>
   But we had only a sketchy map, and when we sought a junction
that would bring us back around the hills to Avalon _ a route we
later saw marked as ``Indian Trail''_ we found ourselves on a
suddenly steep, slippery, shale-covered trace that skittered down
ridges uncomfortably close to high-voltage power lines. At last,
relieved, we stumbled onto a old dirt road leading into town, and
only later realized that our entire expedition had probably been
illegal: we never stopped for the free permit from the Santa
Catalina Island Conservancy required for hiking outside Avalon. By
this point, the wind had died down enough to allow for steamed
mussels and more smoked albacore with Virgin Marys on the outdoor
deck at Armstrong's and a sunset spin in a gas-powered golf cart
from the fleet at Island Car Rentals near the ferry dock.
</P>
<P>
   The etiquette of these conveyances is complex, and a good sign
of island byways and priorities. Visitors are not permitted to rent
them for longer than an hour or two at a time, though some rental
houses come with the use of one, as does a stay at the Inn on Mount
Ada, the former Wrigley mansion, now a deluxe bed and breakfast,
its white facade overlooking the town the way a castle must have
hung above a medieval village. We drove past its gated driveway,
and around the upper rim of the town, admiring a chime tower also
built by Mrs. Wrigley, and Zane Grey's former home, a pueblo-style
building that's now a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   As we looped back into town above the Casino, we spied the
beautiful parklike stretch of Descanso Beach, on the northwest edge
of town, a perfect spot for renting a sea kayak had the weather
been better. Another grand old hotel once stood on this spot, but
it fell on hard times and was torn down in the mid-'60s, leaving a
wide greensward for picnics, games and seaside weddings. We hustled
back just as the rental shop closed, and soothed our aching hips
and calves in the hot tub on the Metropole's rooftop deck as the
sun set.
</P>
<P>
   For our last dinner, we turned to the Ristorante Villa
Portofino, in the waterfront hotel of the same name, which locals
assured us was the island's most ambitious restaurant, with
mainland prices and Italian specialties. We dined well, in part
because bad weather had kept away expected holiday crowds and, the
waiter confided, had left a surplus of seafood. Dee Dee's cioppino
and my linguine al frutti di mare were both bursting with clams,
green-lipped New Zealand mussels, sea bass, salmon and calamari.
</P>
<P>
   Monday dawned sunny and still, inviting us to stay. It helped to
remember that when we long for an island, there's one close by
where we know we'd like to be.
</P>
<P>
   Just 26 miles across the sea &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Catalina Island Visitors Bureau, Post Office Box 217,
Avalon, Calif. 90704, (310) 510-1520, www &QL; 
.catalina.com, has information about rooms and activities. You can
book a room at some hotels at its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Catalina Island Company, (800) 633-4423, fax (310)
510-7254, offers package tours, camping, boat rides and
back-country tours. A Discovery tour ($9, $4.50 for children)
includes the Casino and Avalon Theater; call (310) 510-8687.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Catalina Island Conservancy, 125 Claressa Avenue in
Avalon, (310) 510-2595, offers Jeep eco-tours, free hiking permits
(mandatory) and, in summer, free nature walks and campfire talks.
</P>
<P>
   Catalina Island Vacation Rentals, Post Office Box 426, 119
Sumner Avenue, Avalon, (310) 510-2276, fax (310) 510-8375, books
accommodations in cottages and condos.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels are filled most summer weekends; most require two-night
stays, three nights on holiday weekends. Rates drop October to
April.
</P>
<P>
   Avalon theater movies ($7) are nightly at 7, and 9 p.m.
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The Wrigley Memorial and Botanical Garden is open daily 8 a.m.
to 5 p.m.; admission $3. Getting There
</P>
<P>
   Catalina Express runs the fastest passenger boats, about one
hour from Long Beach and San Pedro to Avalon, with up to 28 daily
departures in summer. Seating is airline-style, with cocktail
service. Round-trip fares: $38, $34.50 ages 55 and older, $28.50
ages 2 to 11, $2 under 2. Reservations (required) at (800) 618-5533
or (310) 519-1212.
</P>
<P>
   Island Express Helicopter Service leaves from Long Beach and San
Pedro, from 8 a.m. to sunset, with departures about every 45
minutes for the 14-minute flight. Fares: $66 each way, $121 round
trip. Reservations: (310) 510-2525, fax (310) 510-9671. Scenic
flights available. Baggage limit: 25 pounds a person. Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Metropole, Post Office Box 1900; (800) 541-8528, fax (310)
510-2534. Attractive faux-Victorian lodging a block from the beach;
48 rooms and two-bedroom cottage. Summer rates $125 to $345,
cottage $895, with passable Continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Snug Harbor Inn, 108 Sumner Avenue, Post Office Box 2470; (310)
510-8400, fax (310) 510-8418. Six-room beachfront inn above a
corner drugstore in the heart of town, all rooms with at least a
partial ocean view. Summer rates: $195 to $325, with morning coffee
and muffins and evening wine and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Inn on Mount Ada, Post Office Box 2560; (310) 510-2030, fax
(310) 510-2237. The former Wrigley mansion and the grandest spot in
town. Six rooms, with ocean and harbor views, some with fireplaces.
No children under 14 except in the Grand Suite. Summer and weekends
$300 to $580, with breakfast, light deli-style lunch, evening
appetizers, wine and champagne, fresh-baked cookies and cart. Where
to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's Seafood, 306 Crescent Avenue; (310) 510-0113. Fresh
fish, full bar, outdoor deck. Dinner for two with wine or cocktails
and the most expensive fish, a plate full of fresh sand dabs, just
under $100.
</P>
<P>
   Sally's Waffle Shop, 501 Crescent Avenue; (310) 510-0355. Homey
breakfast joint with superlative waffles and a variety of omelets.
Breakfast for two under $20.
</P>
<P>
   Ristorante Villa Portofino, 101 Crescent Avenue; (310) 510-0508.
Upscale Italian, with veal, pasta and chicken specialties, plus
plenty of seafood. Dinner for two with wine about $100.
</P>
</TEXT>
