<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASKS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE KING OF MASKS': BRIDGING LONELINESS DESPITE THE DISGUISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The King of Masks'' is a Chinese film with pageantry, a magic
act and adorable children to recommend it. And the pet monkey
doesn't hurt, either. Its story is told gently and without excess
sentimentality, even if that story proves less exotic than the
setting (provincial Sichuan in 1930) suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The film, a winner of multiple Oscar-like Golden Roosters in
China, works nicely as the simple tale of a lonely old man, the
child he befriends and the cross-dressing that affects everyone in
various ways.
</P>
<P>
   This film by Wu Tianming presents an old man named Wang (Zhu Xu)
who earns the title nickname for his magician's skill. He appears
able to switch facial masks with lightning speed, a talent that has
made him a popular street performer.
</P>
<P>
   He is so good, in fact, that a male opera star who specializes
in women's roles tries to hire him. But Wang comes from a long
tradition of street performers and he doesn't want to change.
</P>
<P>
   What he does want is an heir, which brings the film to its
indignation over sexual discrimination in the China of this era. It
goes without saying, at least in Wang's mind, that the only fit
protege for him must be a little boy. And in a startling scene, he
buys one who is offered to him on the black market. The child is 8,
and is held by the seller on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   Wang is much kinder than that, of course. (The film's attitudes
are familiar enough to be predictable, in ways perhaps linked to
the filmmaker's four and a half years in the United States.) He is
kindly to the child, though the relationship is such that they call
each other ``Boss'' and ``Doggie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor little melon, tossed in with a black-hearted turnip!''
Wang says, in the film's colorful idiom, when talking about the
cruel way in which Doggie was sold. Wang is reasonably sympathetic
even when he learns, to his vast disappointment, that Doggie is a
girl.
</P>
<P>
   The child's role is played charmingly by Zhou Ren-ying, who
herself was sent away by her impoverished family to join an
acrobatic troupe at age 3. And her rapport with Zhu is the film's
strongest ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The King of Masks'' watches them form a close friendship only
to be plagued by hardship once an accident destroys Wang's career.
The movie is foremost about kindness, and so warm and understated
that that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE KING OF MASKS'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Wu Tianming; written (in Mandarin, with
English subtitles) by Wei Minglung; director of photography, Mu
Dayuan; music by Zhao Jiping with score by Chen Wengui; released by
Samuel Goldwyn Films. Running time: 101 minutes. This film is not
rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Zhu Xu (Bian Lian Wang), Zhou Ren-ying (Doggie), Zhang
Riuyang (Tien Che) and Zhao Zhigang (Liang Sao Lang).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
