<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANDSLIDE-LIFE-ART-NY     04-27 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDSLIDE-LIFE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDSLIDE: LIFE IN EL NINO'S AFTERMATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STARSHINE ROSHELL   
 SANTA BARBARA, CALIF., NEWS-PRESS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ What if you had to climb a 50-foot-high
hill every time you wanted a quart of milk? Or navigate a
treacherous plywood bridge just to pick up your mail?
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Ranchito Vista Road in the Sycamore Canyon area of
Santa Barbara County surmount a staggering obstacle every time they
leave their homes _ a massive, active landslide that has been
inching forward daily since the heavy El Nino rains of February
1998 first sent the mass of mud slipping down the hillside.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow, dead-end road once led to nine homes with
breathtaking views of Sycamore Canyon; at least one sold about two
years ago for nearly $1 million. But since October, the road has
been buried under a pile of dirt 50 feet high, 200 feet wide and
1,000 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to drive in or out of the neighborhood, homeowners must
hike as far as a quarter of a mile uphill from the bottom of the
slide to their front doors, often carrying groceries, dry cleaning
or office paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no end in sight. Since Ranchito Vista Road is
privately owned by its residents, the county is under no obligation
to help, and county supervisors have signaled they won't get
involved. The homeowners themselves can't afford the exorbitant
costs of removing the slide. So, for now, they are simply waiting,
and trying to stay above the emotional quicksand of despair.
</P>
<P>
   The mud engulfed and destroyed one home in March 1998, and
recently has crept to the edge of another. The slide moves about 2
inches a day. The residents of the dwelling most recently
threatened, George and Carol Goebel, abandoned their home three
weeks ago after the building was declared unsafe. A county
inspector said that when the slide had come to within 30 feet of
the Goebels' house, the foundation began to show signs of stress.
</P>
<P>
   No big surprise. Signs of stress abound in the quiet enclave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I wake up in the morning and I go outside and I look
at this and I just burst into tears,'' said Gerrie Shapiro, an
artist.
</P>
<P>
   She and other residents rarely leave their homes these days
because of the incredible effort it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the lucky ones because I can physically withstand
it,'' said Shapiro, 42. ``But there are other people up this road,
my heart breaks for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro wonders, with fire season approaching, whether emergency
vehicles could reach her property. She frets that underground water
lines could snap as the ground moves. She fears that her dream
house, purchased three years ago, is worth almost nothing now. She
hates that even if she wanted to move, she couldn't get her things
out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, she and neighbors worry about their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what to do,'' she said. ``It just seems like
nobody cares.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some folks care plenty. Utility companies have rerouted
power lines, and the Montecito Fire Department has made special
plans to get access in case of fire.
</P>
<P>
   But county officials have been less helpful, noting that they
aren't liable for the private road.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Breckenridge, a building official with the county, said
geology and stability reports are now required in order to build on
steep slopes. But he guessed that most of the homes on Ranchito
Vista Road were built before that requirement was instituted.
</P>
<P>
   The county had an opportunity to help the Ranchito Vista
residents in September, but declined when the board of supervisors
voted not to apply for federal money to buy the homes from their
owners and then demolish them. The supervisors said the application
process was too expensive, homeowners would receive very little for
their properties and the county didn't want to be liable for the
unstable land.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the residents of Ranchito Vista are left to deal with
the slide. If it reaches Sycamore Canyon Road, the state and the
city of Santa Barbara will have to manage the mess. And if it
eventually crosses the road into Sycamore Creek, it could become
the county flood-control division's problem.
</P>
<P>
   County geologist Brian Baca calls the landslide a ``massive wall
of goo.'' Trying to stop it, he said, would be like trying to stop
flowing lava.
</P>
<P>
   While not accepting responsibility for the problem, county
officials have suggested a few courses of action for the residents.
They could have the slide removed, but it would cost the homeowners
an estimated $1 million and take at least nine months, with 50
truckloads hauling dirt away every day.
</P>
<P>
   They could also buttress the slide for hundreds of thousands of
dollars. Or they could grade it and install drainage systems for
around $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   But even if they could come up with that kind of cash _ which
residents said is unlikely _ there's no guarantee that such methods
would create a safe, stable slope for the remaining homes.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara, Calif., News-Press is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
