<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE29-COX     04-27 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stir-frying goes way beyond Chinese
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Thursday, April 29.
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a winter of stews, roasts and heavy soups, this may be the
perfect time to dust off that wok and get into some serious
stir-fry. Piles of crunchy, colorful vegetables paired with savory
bits of marinated meat or fish can be just the thing to brighten a
tired culinary routine and segue into the salad days of summer.
</P>
<P>
   The wok was part of Chinese cooking for 3,000 years before it
managed to show up as something ``new'' in American kitchens just a
few decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans recognized stir-frying and the wok as an ideal
way to deliver fast, low-fat, economical and tasty meals and
embraced it as a regular part of their at-home menus. For others,
it never quite took hold.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you don't need a wok to produce great stir-fry; a
large frying pan will do. But using a wok adds greatly to the
esthetics of the process, and it comes down to being just plain
fun. There is, however, some basic information you need to know for
successfully using a wok and stir-frying.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never used a wok or want to add to what you already
know, a few minutes on the Internet can go a long way toward a
great season of stir-frying.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ``Art of Stir Fry'' at www.ivillage.com
</P>
<P>
   /food/articles/0,3035,3252(tilde)70,00
</P>
<P>
   .html is an overview of the basics, the benefits and the process
of stir-frying, plus recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At ``Wok Around the Clock'' at recipes.wenzel
</P>
<P>
   .net/h/howt(tilde)xv.htm you will find stir-fry lessons that
suggest you tie a tea towel around your head while stir-frying and
make noise like a samurai warrior.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For straightforward information and tips on how to be a
successful stir-fry cook and the care and feeding of a wok see
soar.berkeley.edu
</P>
<P>
   /recipes/hints/stir-fry1.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take a lesson in using a wok, chat with other cooks at ``Wok
Talk'' and delve into about 4,000 Asian stir-fry recipes at
www.chopstix.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other sites include ``A Stirring Site'' at
www.cookinglight.com/food/focus/focus.html and information on how
to season a wok at www.artattak.com/ctips/curewok.html.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get the basics of the process, the fun is just
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that stir-frying in a wok limits you to Asian
dishes, think again. Search ``stir-fry recipes'' and you will find
pages and pages of single recipes offering an unlimited choice of
dishes from all over the world using every possible ingredient with
maximum creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Just nibbling around the edges we found:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Italian stir-fry using chicken, olives, artichokes and
seasonings at www.thebabynet.com/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Russians were represented with a chicken and paprika
stir-fry at www
</P>
<P>
   .barricksinsurance.com/1056.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mexican stir-fry recipes abound. Try
www.neosoft.com/recipes/beef-veal
</P>
<P>
   /stir-fry-fajitas.html or www.ivillage.com
</P>
<P>
   /food/articles/0,3035,3252(tilde)70,00.html for a quick trip
south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See recipes.wenzel.net/m/mediterranean
</P>
<P>
   -stylebeefstirfry.html for a variety of Mediterranean stir-fry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Call up www.ilovepasta.org and search ``stir-fry'' for 10
terrific pasta ones.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kosher stir-fry? You bet. See www.kashrus
</P>
<P>
   .org/recipes/chinese.html
</P>
<P>
   For more Asian recipes and information on Asian cooking take a
look at:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.chinavista.com/culture/cuisine
</P>
<P>
   /recipes.html, which features an easily understandable intro to
Chinese cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a list of Chinese, Japanese and Vietnamese vegetables that
you may not be familiar with and for the most part are readily
available at supermarkets, see www.boldweb.com/greenweb/asianveg
</P>
<P>
   .htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Also check www.cs.cmu.edu/mjw/recipes
</P>
<P>
   /ethnic/chinese/stir-fry-coll.html and
www.ivu.org/recipes/chinese.html for more recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Saving the best for last:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure you see chineseculture.miningco
</P>
<P>
   .com/msub523.htm?pid &QC; 2745&AMP;cob &QC; home which offers a wealth of
information and recipes about Chinese cooking and this bit of
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``A well-prepared Chinese dish should taste rich to those who
like strong flavors, but not overspiced to those who seek a milder
taste. It should seem sweet to anyone who has a sweet-tooth and hot
to those who like a piquant flavor. A dish that is all of these
things to all of these people is a truly successful dish.''
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Stir-Fried Beef With Sweet Peppers in Oyster Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 to 7 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A simple stir-fry dish _ use any vegetables you like, such as
snow peas, baby sweet corn and bean sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon corn starch
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice wine or sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sirloin steak, trimmed and sliced crosswise in fine
strips
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sunflower oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 red pepper, cored, seeded and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow pepper, cored, seeded and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions, cut in short lengths
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine the corn starch, sugar, soy sauce and
rice wine or sherry. Mix well. Add meat and stir to combine; set
aside to marinate for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heat the oil in a wok or large frying pan until very
hot. Add the ginger and garlic and fry until fragrant. Add the beef
and stir-fry for 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the peppers and green onions and stir-fry for 2 to 3
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   You may need to add a splash of water.
</P>
<P>
   Add the oyster sauce and sesame oil and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 305 calories, 29 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 9 grams carbohydrates, 81
milligrams cholesterol, 869 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Fried Rice
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 to 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, well beaten
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced, leftover cooked meat or seafood
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peas or diced, cooked vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a wok until very hot. Add eggs. Stir to scramble
lightly and add rice. Continue cooking and stirring constantly.
</P>
<P>
   When all rice grains are separated, add salt and green onions,
then meat and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, stirring, until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 438 calories, 16 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 24), 65 grams carbohydrates, 122
milligrams cholesterol, 643 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.s
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
