<HEADER>
A5282 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-POACHEDCHICKEN29     04-27 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POACHEDCHICKEN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A slow and steady simmer signals delicate flavor of meat to
emerge from a pot of water, aromatic herbs and spices
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Thursday, April 29.
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There are preparations that make mouths water in
anticipation. Fried potatoes. Caramelized onions. Roast chicken.
</P>
<P>
   And there are those that don't. Boiled potatoes. Creamed onions.
Poached chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a Pavlovian response. After all, we live in the age
of big flavors and heat-browned food. Cooking magazines love to
show flames licking chile-rubbed chicken breasts on the high-tech
patio grill. Trendy restaurants set burnished roast chicken halves
on beds of truffled mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody says take out an old pot, fill it with water, and in no
time at all you'll have a juicy, perfectly cooked bird.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't considered poaching a chicken since the days of
mom's Bisquick dumplings, now's the time.
</P>
<P>
   Any cut of bone-in or boneless meat benefits from a good simmer.
One stay-at-home dad who posts his day's activities on the Internet
is a veteran poacher. Since supermarket fryers don't have much
flavor, he routinely poaches whole birds to keep the meat around
for stews, pot pies, sandwiches and salads. When he wants a
flavorful roast chicken, he gets a farm-raised bird from a butcher.
</P>
<P>
   Diet-conscious cookbook writers, like Viana la Place and Martha
Stewart, have found that boneless, skinless chicken breast poached
in a pungent liquid absorbs the flavors and gives more bang for the
low-cal buck.
</P>
<P>
   We also like poaching chicken in a court bouillon. Water
acidulated with wine and lemon juice and scented with aromatic
herbs and spices gives the chicken a delicate, just-barely-there
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   As much as we prefer poaching whole chickens, we found that
bone-in chicken breast quarters tasted no different from boneless,
skinless breasts, so we went with the latter for convenience.
</P>
<P>
   We did, however, find something interesting. Hot poached
chicken, fresh from the pot, can seem a bit mealy, but the texture
keeps improving the closer it gets to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   And then we found that velvety slices of white chicken poached
with herbs from the garden, onions and spices had a gentle,
permeating flavor that was just right with a fresh parsley sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Is your mouth watering yet?
</P>
<P>
   MORE INSIDE:
</P>
<P>
   Poached chicken is the centerpiece of a popular
Chinese/Singaporean quick meal served with rice made from the
poaching liquid and a wicked chile sauce. We've tested and
rewritten this recipe with home cooks in mind. That's just one
poaching technique we played around with.
</P>
<P>
   On Page H6, we also offer methods for:
</P>
<P>
   -- Perfect deli-style chicken salad
</P>
<P>
   Sliced breast meat drizzled with a fragrant herb sauce
</P>
<P>
   Roll-ups filled with a Cajun stuffing
</P>
<P>
   Oven-poached chicken flavored with raisins and balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   A Moroccan-inspired dish in which wine-poached chicken breasts
are served over couscous and topped with cumin-scented charmoula
sauce
</P>
<P>
   Styling by JOHN KESSLER WILLIAM BERRY / Staff
</P>
<P>
   A chicken cooked with vegetables and herbs yields main-dish
delights or meat for sandwiches and salads.
</P>
<P>
   90
</P>
<P>
   T
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
