<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5283 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-POACHEDCHICKEN2N     04-27 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POACHEDCHICKEN2NDTAKE-REC </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Cold Poached Chicken With Green Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 10
minutes
</P>
<P>
   We admit it. This is little-old-lady food. No trendy restaurant
would be caught dead serving something this fussy and potentially
flavorless.
</P>
<P>
   But as generations of lunching ladies can attest, there are
myriad pleasures to cold poached chicken. It is velvety on the
tongue. It tastes faintly of the aromatics in the poaching liquid.
Its pale ivory color fairly demands your best bone china.
</P>
<P>
   And with an herbal drizzle of green sauce, it tastes of spring.
</P>
<P>
   For the chicken:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon whole black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 whole boneless, skinless chicken breasts (12 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   For the green sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup packed flat-leaf parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon drained capers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot, bring water, wine, bay leaves, thyme, onion,
parsley, peppercorns and lemon juice to boil. Submerge chicken
breasts, reduce heat to medium-low and simmer uncovered until
chicken is done, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove and wrap tightly in plastic film. Chill. Slice just
before serving and serve with a drizzle of green sauce.
</P>
<P>
   For the green sauce: Combine parsley, basil, garlic and capers
in food processor. With motor running, add olive oil in a thin
stream. Scrape down bowl and add vinegar, lemon juice and salt.
Chill well.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 316 calories, 30 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 3 grams carbohydrates, 80
milligrams cholesterol, 78 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Rolled Chicken Breasts
</P>
<P>
   With Crawfish/Andouille
</P>
<P>
   Stuffing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   We know you have 365 ways to cook boneless, skinless chicken
breasts. But we bet you never thought to butterfly it, stuff it
with a deconstructed jambalaya and roll it in plastic to poach. We
did, and can vouch that this rolled chicken is: a) perfectly
suitable for company you want to impress with a cool kitchen
technique; b) easy on the budget; and c) slightly time-consuming
but easy enough to get the hang of.
</P>
<P>
   If you get the chicken rolls and garnishes prepared, you can
poach them in 10 minutes just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with Spanish rice and a thick tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons butter or oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 green bell pepper, cored, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 andouille sausage, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   A few grindings of pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound cooked, peeled crawfish tails
</P>
<P>
   2 whole boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet over medium heat, warm butter or oil. Add onion,
pepper and garlic and saute until soft. Add sausage and fry for 2
to 3 minutes, until fragrant. Add salt, pepper, oregano, thyme and
crawfish tails; stir to combine. Transfer to large metal mixing
bowl to cool. Cut chicken breasts in halves and remove small filets
from the middle of the undersides. With small knife, scrape out
white tendons from center of the filets and discard. Place small
chicken filets in food processor and pulse to chop. Scrape down
sides of bowl. With motor running, add cream in a steady stream to
make chicken mousse. When crawfish/sausage mixture is cool, add
mousse and mix well. Carefully butterfly breasts lengthwise with
sharp knife and open up like books. Place one in center of an
18-inch length of plastic wrap (not Saran Wrap, which tears too
easily). Spoon enough stuffing into center to fill amply. Roll up
chicken around filling and roll tightly in plastic film. Twist ends
like taffy wrappers to make a taut 6-inch roll with 6-inch lengths
of film on either side. Bring together ends and tie them in knot so
roll holds its shape. Repeat process with remaining breast. In
5-quart pot, poach rolls in 2 quarts of gently simmering water for
12-15 minutes. Allow to rest at room temperature for 5 minutes
before unwrapping and slicing. Serve hot with a cream sauce or
tomato sauce; or chill and serve with a mayonnaise-based sauce and
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 304 calories, 34 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 50), 2 grams carbohydrates, 116
milligrams cholesterol, 578 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken
</P>
<P>
   in Balsamic Vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here, the chicken is poached in a pan of liquid in the oven.
This is a great dish to put on a buffet table with salads. Serve at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   4 whole chicken breasts, skinned, split, boned, and fat trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fruity white wine, or water
</P>
<P>
   Parchment or wax paper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup fruity olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh tarragon, or 1 teaspoon dried tarragon leaves,
crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1 small lemon, removed with a vegetable peeler
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons raisins, plumped in hot water for 15 minutes and
drained
</P>
<P>
   Arugula leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Slightly flatten the chicken
breasts with the palm of your hand. Place in a lightly oiled,
shallow roasting pan. Lightly salt and pepper. Add the wine or
water to the pan. Cover with lightly oiled parchment paper or wax
paper cut to just fit the pan. Bake for about 10 minutes or until
cooked through. Let the chicken cool in the pan. Whisk together the
vinegar and olive oil in a bowl. Add the tarragon, lemon zest and
raisins. Arrange the chicken breasts in 1 layer in a shallow dish
just large enough to hold them. Pour the dressing over the chicken.
Cover with plastic wrap and marinate in the refrigerator at least
12 hours, turning the chicken occasionally. Before serving, return
to room temperature. Place the arugula leaves on individual plates
or on a platter and arrange the chicken on the leaves. Garnish with
the raisins and lemon zest, and drizzle a little of the marinade
over the chicken. _ From ``Cucina Fresca'' by Viana LaPlace and
Evan Kleiman
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 398 calories, 47 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 5 grams carbohydrates, 128
milligrams cholesterol, 113 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
