<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5284 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-POACHEDCHICKENIS     04-27 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POACHEDCHICKENISTTAKE-REC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poaching makes for tender, juicy chicken
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Thursday, April 29.
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All over Singapore and Malaysia are restaurants that
specialize in quick meals of chicken and rice. As soon as you slide
in front of a Formica tabletop, the server brings a platter of
tender poached chicken and a bowl of magnificent, pale brown rice
that gets its color from chicken broth and gobs of shallots. Help
yourself to a spoonful of the sweet but hotter-than-hell chile
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   We played around with published recipes until we devised one
suitable to American home cooks. Our surefire way to poach chicken
without overcooking is to bring the poaching liquid to a boil,
immerse the chicken, bring it back to a boil, turn heat off and let
it sit for one hour in the pot with a tight-fitting lid. No
peeking. Make sure to choose a small fryer (no more than 3 1/2
pounds), and don't be alarmed if the chicken is still a little pink
at the bone. The meat is safely cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Since this method produces a weak broth _ too weak to make the
rice interesting _ we added some prepared broth to the poaching
water. We also changed the rice preparation into a straightaway
pilaf. Traditionally, the raw rice is wok-fried, then cooked
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the chile sauce is easy to whip up, but you can find a
bottled version in Asian markets (called ``sauce for chicken'' and
packaged in bottles that look like they should hold fifths of Jack
Daniel's). Or you can use your favorite prepared sauce. This tender
poached chicken will taste just fine in anything you care to dip it
in.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the three-part recipe, along with several others in
which poached chicken is the central ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Hainanese Chicken and Rice
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 80 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the chicken:
</P>
<P>
   1 small fryer (about 3 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, peeled and smashed
</P>
<P>
   1 (1-inch) length ginger, peeled and smashed with a heavy knife
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, washed and tied into a knot
</P>
<P>
   2 (14 1/2-ounce) cans chicken broth, plus about 3 quarts water,
to cover chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 tablespoons sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Sliced cucumber, sliced tomato and cilantro sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   For the rice:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 heaping tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 cups jasmine rice
</P>
<P>
   4 cups broth reserved from poaching chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   For the chile sauce:
</P>
<P>
   8 small dried red chile pods, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large shallot, chopped (about 1/4 cup)
</P>
<P>
   3 large garlic cloves, chopped (about 2 tablespoons)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peeled, minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup hot chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lime or lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Wash chicken and remove knobs of tail fat. Sprinkle inside of
chicken with salt, and insert garlic, ginger and green onion.
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot (8-quart is best, but one that's at least 5
quarts will do) bring broth and water to a boil. Add chicken,
breast side down, submerging completely, adding more water to
submerge if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Bring water back to a rollicking boil. Remove the pot from heat
and cover with a tight-fitting lid.
</P>
<P>
   Leave undisturbed for one hour. Do not peek. We mean it. After
one hour, remove chicken and drain broth from the body cavity. Keep
broth for later use.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken under tap water for 2 minutes to stop the cooking
process and to tighten the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Drain, rub some sesame oil over skin and let the chicken cool to
room temperature. Meanwhile, prepare rice as directed below.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the chicken into pieces. The best way is like this: Cut down
through the breastbone. Cut along both sides of the backbone and
discard. Cut into breast and leg quarters. Remove rib bones and
wing tips from breast. Cut through the meat into inch-thick chunks.
Cut the leg quarters into thighs and drumsticks. Remove chicken
skin as you see fit.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange pieces of chicken on platter and garnish with sliced
cucumbers and tomatoes. Decorate the top with cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with rice and chile sauce.
</P>
<P>
   For the rice: Heat vegetable oil over medium heat in a medium
pot with a tight-fitting lid. Add shallots and stir-fry for 1
minute till fragrant. Add garlic and stir-fry for 1 minute. Add the
rice grains and stir-fry for 3 to 4 minutes, until shallots begin
to darken. Add the chicken broth and salt. Bring to a boil over
high heat; lower heat to medium-low and cover. After 8 minutes,
lower heat to low. After another 10 minutes, turn off heat, leaving
pot covered to continue steaming. After another 10 minutes, uncover
and fluff with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   For the chile sauce: Pulse chiles, shallot, garlic and ginger in
food processor to grind. With motor running, add the hot chicken
broth in a thin stream. Add remaining ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Cool and let sit at least one hour before serving. Sauce can be
stored in the refrigerator for 4 to 5 days.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 778 calories, 44 grams protein, 29 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 33), 81 grams carbohydrates, 111
milligrams cholesterol, 1,698 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Tender, White-Meat Chicken Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a trick they do teach in cooking school: For soft,
deli-style chicken salad, immerse still-hot poached chicken in the
dressing. As the salad cools to room temperature, the dressing
swells into the cooked meat and leaves it utterly tender. Tasty,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Here, we use all white meat, dice it into small cubes and fold
it into a minimum of mayo. We season it with some good mustard,
Asian sesame oil, green onions and capers. You might wish to omit
the capers and add some toasted, sliced almonds. Or perhaps stir a
little curry powder into the mayonnaise and toss in some halved
seedless red grapes. If you do add raw veggies or fruit, wait until
the salad cools before folding them in.
</P>
<P>
   2 (14 1/2-ounce) cans chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 whole boneless, skinless chicken breasts (about 12 ounces
each)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mayonnaise (plus more if needed)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, slivered
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   A few grinds black pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot, bring broth to boil. Submerge chicken breasts in
broth, reduce heat to medium-low and simmer uncovered until chicken
is done, 10-12 minutes. Meanwhile, in a large bowl, combine
mayonnaise, mustard, sesame oil, green onions, capers, salt and
pepper. When chicken is ready, remove to a cutting board and dice,
using a fork to steady it as you cut. (Reserve broth for another
use.) Combine hot chicken with mayonnaise mixture and stir to
combine. If salad looks dry, add a spoonful of additional
mayonnaise. Let cool to room temperature before refrigerating.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 208 calories, 25 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 1 gram carbohydrates, 72
milligrams cholesterol, 278 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
