<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The moving man was tallying my possessions as I led him through
my Upper West Side apartment _ ``this bookcase, that bookcase,
sofa, four chairs, table, that bookcase ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``So what's your new address?'' he asked, pencil poised.
</P>
<P>
   I named an Upper East Side building and he cocked a skeptical
eyebrow. ``You won't live there long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This observation from a stranger took me aback and I asked him
what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're obviously a West Sider _ you've got more books than
clothes,'' he said. ``East Siders have more clothes than books.''
</P>
<P>
   That was two years ago. This month I hired him again to move me
back to the West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Johanna Keller
</P>
<P>
   All the construction going on in Manhattan jogged Nadia
Koutzen's memory of an incident when an old Columbia University
building on West 60th Street was being demolished. She stopped to
watch as the crew was removing doors and windows before swinging
the wrecking ball. A man leaning against a nearby fence called out,
``Why don't they take the bottom out first, and then the whole
thing'll go down.''
</P>
<P>
   I was at Pennsylvania Station to catch a train to Long Island on
a recent Sunday when I saw a police officer approach a musician who
had a guitar, microphone and speakers. I thought I was going to
witness a ``quality of life'' arrest but instead, the officer
pointed to the microphone and with a nod from the musician, picked
it up and started to sing. Unaccompanied, but perfectly in tune, he
sang an Elvis Presley ballad.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow passengers had also stopped to listen and, like me,
were smiling. It was a real boost to the spirit.
</P>
<P>
   I know the problems the New York City Police Department is
having with the public cannot be fixed with a song, but it seemed a
good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Schogol
</P>
<P>
   The two very chic women, who apparently had not seen each other
in some time, exchanged effusive salutations. One of the women had
a small poodle. Camilla Harris was nearby as the friend bent down
to pet the dog and gushed, in typical doggy and baby language,
``What a sweet little doggy you are _ how old are you now?'' There
was, of course, no reply, but the dog owner felt she should explain
why. ``You'll have to speak up,'' she said. ``She's hard of
hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple in Astoria, Queens, who wish to remain anonymous moved
a backyard grape vine to a new spot and started a compost pile to
help it along. Last fall, they had a bumper crop of grapes. When
the wife was turning over the compost recently, she found a bottle
of Viagra that had disappeared. The bottle had fallen out of a
cabinet into the container where the compost was collected. The
bottle was still capped but the two are convinced that its very
presence _ and osmosis _ account for the vine's stunning result. It
proves, the husband said, that ``even Father Nature needs help.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day, while in the Park Avenue offices of Bloomberg
Financial Markets, I went to the men's room.
</P>
<P>
   Standing right next to me was another man who, out of the blue,
said, ``What did you say?''
</P>
<P>
   Surprised, I turned slightly and asked, ``What did you say?''
</P>
<P>
   There was no response for a couple of seconds and then he said,
turning farther away from me: ``Listen, I've got to go. I'll call
you back.''
</P>
<P>
   Then I heard the beep of a cell phone being turned off.
</P>
<P>
   I know we are all more pressed for time these days and it's
pretty hectic at Bloomberg, but I had to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Thomas
</P>
<P>
   I was on a northbound M104 bus recently, seated in the back row
next to the window. As I was gathering my things to get off, I
heard a clink _ my house key had fallen into the slot under the
seat. My attempts to retrieve it were unsuccessful. I informed the
driver and he told me he would stop at 96th Street to inform his
dispatcher. The dispatcher advised him to take me to the garage at
the last stop where he thought the seat could be taken up by
maintenance workers.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher had radioed in by the time we got to the garage
and the maintenance crew was waiting. They retrieved the key and
the driver delivered me back to my stop. It made me proud to be a
New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Lee Prospero
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Greenfield takes no credit for this poem. The words boomed
through a microphone held by a young preacher at 42nd Street and
Broadway on a recent rainy Sunday and Ms. Greenfield took them down
and arranged them.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Krasnow enjoyed this sign in the window of a SoHo shop:
``Reality Sandwich has moved to Harry's Burritos.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Judith Zabar was visited at her studio by Jackie Gray,
of Key West, and two of her friends who were spending a few days in
New York. In the course of conversation, they asked about getting
theater tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zabar told them about TKTS, the ticket booth at 47th Street
and Broadway, and advised them to get on line at 11 a.m. for a
matinee and 4 P.M. for an evening performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have my computer with me,'' Ms. Gray replied.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``on line'' obviously means different things to
different people these days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL TAMMEUS &LR;  &QC;  Have you noticed? A lot of the news nowadays
seems to be about who's doing what to prevent what's already
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace and humanity will prevail in Kosovo,'' Mr. Clinton says.
Even if no one is left there to enjoy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in Kosovo,'' says Mr. Clinton, ``because we want to
replace ethnic cleansing with tolerance and decency.'' And because
we didn't know what else to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of Europe,'' the president says, ``is coming together
today.'' Except, of course, for those places being blown apart.
</P>
<P>
   Although the weather in the nation's Heartland has been rainy
and overcast for days, the good news is that it makes us safe from
NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``America,'' says Al Gore, ``is a good and decent place.'' Yes,
but sometimes it seems as if it could use a few more bouncers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No society,'' Gore says, ``will ever be perfect.'' The
freshness of this news is on a parallel with the discovery that
most of the ocean is wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why human beings do evil,'' says Gore, ``I do not understand''
_ despite being in an office where he observes a fair amount of it
up close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure your children know you care about what they're
doing,'' Mr. Clinton says. Even if you prefer they not know about
some of what you're doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``We must pledge ourselves to the task of putting an end to the
culture of violence,'' says Mr. Clinton. Dark days ahead for
defense contractors?
</P>
<P>
   Here's another bad idea for how to reform Social Security: Allow
people to start drawing checks when their pets hit 65 in dog years.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore says parents have ``got to talk to our children.'' Or at
least leave occasional messages on their answering machines.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton is proposing new gun-control legislation. That's a
relief. We worried that he was crossing the church-state line with
a nun-control law.
</P>
<P>
   The new Clinton gun law would require child safety locks on
weapons. If they work like child-proof caps on drugs, only kids
could unlock them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that God's hand has touched the United States of
America,'' Al Gore says, but he didn't specify whether with a
gentle palm or the back of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts think Gore is vulnerable and Bill Bradley has a
chance to beat him. It doesn't hurt to be known as a Bill who can
keep his pants on.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky, feeling ``emotionally drained,'' will do no
more interviews in the U.S., her publisher says. Finally, this
scandal produces good news.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA has named its headquarters the George Bush Center for
Intelligence. There was no chance the name would be applied to Dan
Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have found the fossils of two previously unknown
species of dinosaurs in Utah. No, neither used to play for the
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in Massachusetts have cloned three goats. Goats?
Enough of this waste of time. Let's get cracking on cloning
chocolate cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have cloned both sheep and goats. Will the Bible now
have the Lord putting ``the cloned sheep on his right and the
cloned goats on his left''?
</P>
