</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-NUKES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL ONCE IN CHARGE OF NUKES HAS BECOME WARRIOR FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By BEN HELLWARTH   
 Santa Barbara News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ In the past 15 years, the Nuclear Age
Peace Foundation has presented many of its annual peace awards to
leaders with household names, including Ted Turner, Jacques-Yves
Cousteau, Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the Dalai Lama, Helen Caldicott
and Carl Sagan.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer people will recognize the name of retired Air Force Gen.
Lee Butler, who will receive the Santa Barbara-based foundation's
1999 Distinguished Peace Leadership Award on Friday. Butler, who
once oversaw the nation's nuclear arsenal, has never sought the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   After attaining the rank of general in 1991, during the waning
days of the Cold War, Butler became commander-in-chief of the
Strategic Air Command, which put him in charge of the Air Force's
nuclear weapons. He then rose to commander-in-chief of the U.S.
Strategic Command, a post that brought all of the nation's nuclear
weaponry under his supervision and made him a principal adviser to
the president.
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1994, after 33 years in the military. Two years
later, Butler stated publicly that nuclear weapons should be
abolished, which also happens to be a central goal of the Nuclear
Age Peace Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Butler is a man who believes in security, and he has
come to believe that nuclear weapons, in any form, cannot provide
that security. It takes courage, given his background, to speak out
in this way,'' said David Krieger, president of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit foundation will honor Butler on Friday at its 16th
annual peace award dinner. The award will be presented by actor
Michael Douglas, who has become a United Nations peace messenger
and has joined the movement to abolish nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, who lives in Omaha, Neb., does not frequently give
interviews. He declined to speak prior to the speech he will give
upon accepting his award, but when the retired general has spoken,
he has not mince words about his anti-nuclear stance.
</P>
<P>
   On a philosophical note, Butler has said in the past: ``Nuclear
weapons play on our deepest fears and pander to our darkest
instincts. They corrode our sense of humanity, numb our capacity
for moral outrage, and make thinkable the unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   About the transformation of his own thinking, he has said:
``Much of what I took on faith was either wrong, enormously
simplistic, extraordinarily fragile, or simply morally intolerable.
What I have come to believe is that the amassing of nuclear
capability to the level of such grotesque excess as we witnessed
between the United States and the Soviet Union over the period of
the 50 years of the Cold War, was as much a product of fear, and
ignorance and greed, and ego and power, and turf and dollars, as it
was about the seemingly elegant theories of deterrence.''
</P>
<P>
   And on a spiritual note: ``We escaped the Cold War without a
nuclear holocaust by some combination of skill, luck and divine
intervention, and I suspect the latter in greatest proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler began to make such bold statements after joining the
Canberra Commission, an elite group of world leaders assembled by
the Australian government to ponder nuclear policies and issues
related to fostering peace.
</P>
<P>
   Krieger first met Butler and heard him speak out against nuclear
weapons alongside former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev, at the
State of the World Forum in 1996. That San Francisco-based
organization, also intent upon eliminating nuclear weapons, is
headed by former Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who will be among
the anti-nuclear dignitaries seeing Butler receive his award and
taking part in the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation's daylong strategy
meeting that will precede the awards.
</P>
<P>
   During his military career, Butler was a classic Cold Warrior,
and a firm believer in the cat-and-mouse game of nuclear
deterrence, said Cranston. When the Cold War ended with the
dissolution of the Soviet Union, the general hoped to see
substantive changes with regard to nuclear weaponry, ``but he
became alarmed that there was no change in nuclear policy, either
by us or by the Russians,'' Cranston said.
</P>
<P>
   By December 1996, Butler had taken his stand in favor of
eliminating nuclear weapons with a high-profile speech to the
National Press Club, which came as he and 60 retired generals and
admirals from the United States, Russia, Britain, France and 12
other countries issued a joint statement calling for a permanent
global ban on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Butler's military peers were quick to question his new
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the announcement went public, they were pretty critical
of it, and did the patronizing thing of saying, `He means well but
he doesn't understand the problem,''' said Adm. Eugene Carroll, who
oversaw 7,000 nuclear weapons in Europe while serving under Gen.
Alexander Haig and was among the retired officials to sign the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a man who committed his life's work, as it were, to
preparing for war and was responsible for the United States'
nuclear war plans and the execution of those plans,'' said Carroll,
who retired in 1980 and is now with the Center for Defense
Information. ``And the process convinced him that he had to speak
out against it. That takes intellectual honesty and personal
courage to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ben Hellwarth writes for the Santa Barbara (Calif.)
News-Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
