<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, April 28, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golf ball-sized hail fell near Columbia, S.C., on Tuesday as a
front draped over the area acted as a focus for showers and
thunderstorms. Additional strong to locally severe storms are
likely Wednesday near the front over east Georgia and South
Carolina. Gusty winds and large hail are again possible, especially
in the afternoon as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   A more tranquil rain with embedded rumbles of thunder will fall
to the north of the front from southern Virginia to Missouri. Since
the rain will be falling on already saturated ground, minor
flooding is possible, mainly in southern Illinois and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and isolated strong thunderstorms will percolate in the
afternoon heat over Florida. The showers will not be widespread
enough, however, to provide relief from the drought plaguing the
state.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, fair weather will dominate over much of the Great
Lakes States and the Northeast. Ample sunshine will mix with only a
few clouds, though it will be chilly in the Northeast as a
persistent flow of cool air from Canada persists. Some showers will
dampen eastern Maine as a sluggish ocean storm circulates moisture
and clouds westward.
</P>
<P>
   Developing low pressure will instigate showers and potent
thundershowers in the valleys of the interior West. Heavy snow will
fall in the Bitterroots and Tetons this afternoon as low pressure
aloft passes overhead. Very gusty winds will blow in California and
Nevada in the low's wake, though widespread sunshine will grace
areas west of the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Derecho
</P>
<P>
   Violent winds of up to 90 mph tore across east Texas and the
southern Mississippi Valley Tuesday. The strong winds resulted from
a cluster of thunderstorms that produced what meteorologists call a
derecho. The word ``derecho'' is Spanish and its literal
translation means ``straight ahead''. Powerful straight-line wind
gusts, not the twisting currents of tornadoes, are the derecho's
primary arsenal for damage. The turbulent gusts develop as
downdrafts within the thunderstorms accelerate rapidly toward
earth, spreading out in a destructive barrage upon reaching the
surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
