u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOWLES-FILM-REVIEW-NY     04-27 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWLES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LET IT COME DOWN': CASTING NIHILISTIC PEARLS FROM HIS LOFTY
PERCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His cold, hooded eyes gazing calmly into the void, traces of a
bitter smile flickering around his withered lips, the author Paul
Bowles, in Jennifer Baichwal's compelling documentary portrait,
dispenses pearls of nihilistic observation like a sadistic oracle
whose purpose is to extinguish fleeting hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people are planets, floating spheres,'' he
declares in a patrician New England drawl dripping with hauteur.
``If they touch, they just touch at one tiny point. In general they
don't touch at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there's a glint of gallows humor. ``It's impossible to
be dead, because to be is the opposite of death,'' he cracks.
``Whatever is alive has to die. Maybe that's the meaning of life.
The meaning of life is inevitable death.''
</P>
<P>
   These remarks, offered at the end of the film ``Let It Come
Down: The Life of Paul Bowles,'' underscore the dispassionate,
Darwinian vision of a universe of predators and prey that the
author, now 88, has distilled in novels like his 1949 masterwork,
``The Sheltering Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, which opens Wednesday in New York City, is
interspersed with grim little slivers from Bowles' fiction read by
the Canadian actor Tom McCamus, often accompanied by gorgeous shots
of the arid desert landscape around Tangier where Bowles has lived
for most of the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   His lean, dry, elegant prose from which emotion has been drained
away looks at human experience from a perspective that suggests a
scientist examining tiny poisonous reptiles under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles says most of his tales are ``varieties of detective story
in which the reader is the detective.'' He is quietly outspoken in
his loathing of the Bernardo Bertolucci film adaptation of ``The
Sheltering Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   The portrait that emerges is of a man who grew up estranged from
cold, pleasure-denying parents and fled his background to become a
world traveler. After making a modest name for himself as a theater
composer in the 1940s, he forsook composition for writing.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s, he bought a house in Tangier that became a
bohemian mecca visited by the Beats, Tennessee Williams, Truman
Capote, Ned Rorem, Francis Bacon and many others.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to Jane Auer, a fellow writer, in 1938 lasted until
her death from a lingering illness in 1973. Their complicated
marriage was more of a collaborative friendship (Jane Bowles'
fiction has as many admirers as her husband's) than a romantic
union.
</P>
<P>
   After 1950 Bowles' primary love was Ahmed Yacoubi, a Moroccan
artist with whom he had ``a romantic mad love affair,'' recalls one
observer. Bowles would disagree. He dismisses romantic love as ``an
obsession'' and calls it ``abnormal.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few moments in the film when Bowles bristles is at
accepting the label homosexual. In rejecting it, he quotes Gore
Vidal's insistence on distinguishing between what you are and what
you do.
</P>
<P>
   After Bowles became attached to Yacoubi, his wife began a
lifelong lesbian relationship with Amina Bakalia, a Moroccan woman
also known as Cherifa, who was rumored to have poisoned Jane to
death. Cherifa laughingly denies the rumor.
</P>
<P>
   One of the coups of ``Let It Come Down'' is a reunion of Bowles
with William Burroughs and Allen Ginsberg filmed in 1995 when
Bowles visited New York (for the first time in 35 years) to attend
a concert of his music at Lincoln Center. Burroughs, despite his
respect for the author, has some needling criticisms of his sexual
subterfuge and suggests that Bowles' 1972 autobiography, ``Without
Stopping,'' would have been more accurately titled ``Without
Telling.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their differences, Burroughs (who died in 1997) and
Bowles emerge as kindred spirits: grand old bohemian men of
letters, touched with paranoia, loftily looking down at the human
race and its pathetic illusions of religion and romantic love with
a sepulchral contempt.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   LET IT COME DOWN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Life of Paul Bowles
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jennifer Baichwal; director of photography, Nick de
Pencier; edited by David Wharnsby; music by Paul Bowles, performed
by the Eos Orchestra and Moroccan music performed by various
artists; produced by de Pencier and Ms. Baichwal; released by
Zeitgeist Films. Running time: 73 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Paul Bowles, William Burroughs, Phillip Ramey, Jonathan
Sheffer, Ned Rorem, Gustavo Romero, Marguerite McBey, Joe
McPhillips, David Herbert, Mohammed Mrabet, Mohammed Choukri, Allen
Ginsberg and Amina (Cherifa) Bakalia; readings by Tom McCamus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
