   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS _ WEST BANK, GAZA _ PLO leaders meet to vote
on extending the deadline for declaring a Palestinian state and
continue peace negotiations with the Israeli government.
Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ARMENIAN-GENOCIDE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ My father, Nishan
Kalajian, had the misfortune to be born in the city of Diyarbakir
in southeastern Turkey in 1912, a desperate and convulsive time in
the disintegrating Ottoman Empire. He was 3 years old when the
soldiers came first to take the young men, including his father,
and then returned for all the other Armenians. The pattern was
repeated in village after village. The ensuing slaughter was
eventually given a formal name: The Armenian Genocide. The ghostly
survivors became almost as familiar to newspaper readers of their
time as the refugees from Kosovo are today. The starving Armenians,
as they were widely known, became an international cause. And then
they were forgotten so completely that the people who rule their
land today can blandly deny that anything so awful ever happened.
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-TENSION _ ATLANTA _ Tension is high at just about every
school in America. The last week or so has seen plenty of bomb
scares and rumors and scared moms and dads in metro Atlanta. There
are reports that one middle school has been evacuated each of the
last three school days. Two other schools were evacuated today,
including one where some pipe devices wrapped in duct tape and with
a fuse were found. School was dismissed for the day. At the other,
students went back to school. Within mintues, 100 or so parents _
some broken with fear _ gathered at make-shift information center,
waiting on news that they're kids were OK. Most acknowledge that
the events of the last week or so have left their emotional cups
full. This became overflow. ``Enough. We can't take anymore,'' one
parent said. This type fear built last spring. Now it's even worse.
(Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
