<HEADER>
A5304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-0     04-27 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-0428-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PALESTINIANS SEE STATEHOOD AS A MATTER OF TIMING
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip While Yasser Arafat and leaders of the PLO
Tuesday debated whether to declare Palestinian statehood, a mother
a few miles away held the answer in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   Zakia Abbas clutched two Palestinian passports for her children
that had been issued by the Interior Ministry of the temporary
Palestinian government. While they allow travel, the passports are
for people without a country. But Abbas and her husband see them as
signs of progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The establishment of the state is inevitable,'' said the
husband, 40-year-old Mohammed Abu Bari. ``But, we have to be
prepared (first) and there are political pressures on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Those pressures surfaced Tuesday in a closed-door meeting at
Arafat's seaside offices, where leaders of the PLO began
discussions on the inflammatory question of whether Arafat should
declare statehood on May 4, or accede to U.S. requests to delay the
announcement and settle for accelerated peace talks with Israel.
The decision could affect the outcome of Israeli elections on May
17.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat told the 124-member PLO Central Council that they should
delay the call for statehood. ``We are going through a very
delicate period in the history of our people, a period during which
we cannot afford making any mistakes,'' Arafat said, according to
the official Palestinian news agency WAFA.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting will resume Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   May 4th is the original target date for a permanent peace
agreement with Israel, as set out in the Oslo Peace Accords, signed
by the Palestinians and Israel in 1993. The Palestinians feel they
have received much less land from Israel than they expected under
the accords, and therefore claim the right to declare a state on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israelis assert that the May 4 deadline was merely a goal
and that the process should continue. Any statehood for
Palestinians, they say, should be negotiated and include limits on
any prospective Palestinian military and Israeli control over who
enters the area.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has threatened military action to retake areas already
given to Palestinians and threatened to incorporate into Israel
large disputed portions of land in the West Bank. U.S. officials
want Arafat to delay a statehood announcement in order to avoid a
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Arafat's aides have tried to build political cover by
stating that the world community largely recognizes Palestinian
rights to statehood. They say the question of statehood, similar to
how Zakia Abbas felt holding her passports, has moved from ``if''
to ``when.''
</P>
<P>
   But, members of the Central Council on Tuesday were more
strident, indicating they might defy the world community and their
own leader's apparent wishes and go ahead with the declaration on
May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they were dissatisfied with the mild promises of
support offered by the United States and other officials seeking
delay. They also seemed unconcerned that a declaration might work
to the favor of Israel's hard-line Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in his May 17 re-election bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to declare statehood on May 4th,'' said council member
Marwan Barghouti, leaving the meeting during a break. ``(The
council) is frustrated. We heard there were going to be many
guarantees (from foreign countries). There are no guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the council, stacked with Arafat supporters,
could run for days or weeks. One major topic is sure to be a letter
that President Clinton sent to Arafat Monday, offering to speed up
the peace process and criticizing Israeli housing construction on
disputed lands.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders Tuesday said it did not go far enough in
backing their desires for statehood. Even some Arafat supporters
back the May 4 call for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But opinion in Palestinian streets seems divided. A poll
conducted last week by the Palestinian-run Center for Palestine
Research and Studies showed 48 percent favoring a postponement in
the statehood declaration and 43 percent favoring a declaration May
4.
</P>
<P>
   What many Palestinians note when opposing statehood now is that
their actual powers are still very limited. Their borders are still
controlled by Israel, for example.
</P>
<P>
   While Arafat's leaders met by the shore, scruffy teenage
tacticians on the streets of the sprawling Beach Refugee Camp held
their own deliberations on statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Several boys in tattered pants huddled together while their
younger bare-footed siblings stood by, literally learning
Palestinian strategy in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in a hurry for (statehood), but it is better to do things
through peaceful ways,'' said Mahmoud Abu Shagfeh, 14. He added an
important question, ``How can we have a state without Jerusalem?''
Palestinians claim the Israeli capital as their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to build our own institutions,'' said 12-year-old Noor
Sallah Abu Shagfeh, no relation to Mahmoud, who wants to be a
lawyer. ``But we cannot give Israel a reason to attack us.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
