<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUIXOTE-BALLET-REVIEW     04-27 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUIXOTE-BALLET-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DON QUIXOTE': A GALA WITH HEROES TO SPARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Opening its season at the Metropolitan Opera House on
Monday night, American Ballet Theater tried out a festive novelty:
a hero and heroine in ``Don Quixote'' multiplied by three.
</P>
<P>
   Paloma Herrera and Angel Corella, as the ballet's young lovers,
led off in Act I and were suddenly transformed into Susan Jaffe and
Jose Manuel Carreno in Act II, while Act III had Nina Ananiashvili
and Julio Bocca, in the same roles, delivering the goods in the
celebrated final pas de deux.
</P>
<P>
   It was a glittering showcase for virtuosic dancing even if
dramatic coherence was not on the table. Rather short on
continuity, this gala gimmick reminded one of the old joke about
the genre of experimental French novel known as the nouveau roman;
namely, that you could shuffle the pages in the narrative without
anyone knowing the difference.
</P>
<P>
   A different pair of principals in each act rather than one pair
in three acts is not an idea whose time has come. Every act seemed
interchangeable with another. Nonetheless, Ballet Theater artistic
director Kevin McKenzie succeeded with his one-time event in
showing off his own dancers rather than guests, and he managed
marvelously to put most of the company onstage.
</P>
<P>
   The performance was preceded by onstage remarks by McKenzie,
Caroline Kennedy and Tipper Gore, the wife of the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   As Hillary Rodham Clinton did last year, Mrs. Gore urged support
of the arts and singled out Ballet Theater for its ``standard of
excellence.'' ``I'm honored to be here,'' she said after praising
the company's educational and outreach activities.
</P>
<P>
   The gala benefit, which opened a season that runs through June
19, had Ms. Kennedy and Blaine Trump as co-chairwomen. Ms. Kennedy
urged all to bring a child or a young friend to Ballet Theater to
instill a love of the arts. ``I grew up on the company,'' she said,
recalling that she had seen it as a child at a performance at the
White House in 1962 and that she had watched rehearsals with her
mother, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, who was a company trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Once the curtain rose, it was clear that McKenzie, who has
previously presented gala programs of bits and pieces, had chosen
the right production for his new formula. As the most raucous comic
ballet to come out of Russia in the 19th century, ``Don Quixote''
is first and foremost a machine for dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The current production, staged in 1995 by McKenzie and Susan
Jones, is on the tame side, especially in its crowd scenes, but it
preserves the set pieces that have kept the work alive.
Choreographed originally by Marius Petipa in 1869 and revised by
Alexander Gorsky in 1900, 1902 and 1906, ``Don Quixote'' has
survived through sheer dance power.
</P>
<P>
   This was especially true when the Bolshoi Ballet came to town in
the 1960s. Plot was not that important, but stars like Yekaterina
Maksimova and Vladimir Vasilyev could make us care about Basil, an
impoverished Spanish barber, and Kitri, his sweetheart, as they
outwitted Kitri's father when he tried to marry her off to a rich
fop, Gamache. Minor characters in ``Don Quixote,'' Cervantes'
novel, Kitri and Basil came to the fore in the ballet. The Don, in
a walk-on role and in love with love, helps the young couple out.
Victor Barbee as the Don and Gil Boggs as Sancho Panza were,
incidentally, anything but negligible in these roles Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless it is bravura rather than characterization that
colors any ``Don Quixote'' today. Too many dramatic details have
either eroded or are played to broad effect to make for a stylish
whole. Act I, full of Spanish character dances, introduces the
lovers and Espada, the bullfighter, and Mercedes, the street
dancer, depicted with winning exuberance here by Maxim
Belotserkovsky and Irina Dvorovenko. Act II includes an
introductory scene in a gypsy camp but also a classical
divertissement in the Don's vision scene.
</P>
<P>
   In this special tripartite performance, McKenzie cast his
different couples appropriately. Corella's astounding virtuosity
could not get full play from the choreography in this act, but his
trademark multiple pirouettes gave a hint of the full-length
performance he will give this week. Ms. Herrera's energy level was
low at the start, but by the end of the act she executed a perfect
diagonal of pirouettes and the thrilling leap made famous by Maya
Plisetskaya of the Bolshoi (back leg bent up to the head).
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie rightly chose the company's three most classical
ballerinas for the vision scene. Ms. Jaffe's form in her solo was
exemplary in its purity, especially in her sudden and difficult
plunges into arabesque. Ashley Tuttle, as the cupid figure, married
pertness and precision, not least in her delicious scurries on toe.
As the Queen of the Dryads, the nymphs in this dream kingdom, Julie
Kent made a quick recovery after her ankle gave out in a releve
(rising on toe) and she did wonders with the solo sometimes seen as
part of ``Le Corsair.'' Carreno, earlier in the same act, was his
noble self.
</P>
<P>
   As for Act III, it all built up to the pas de deux that Ms.
Ananiashvili, vivacious as usual, and Bocca, toning down his usual
flash but dazzling nonetheless, performed with their usual
professionalism and virtuosity. Ermanno Florio conducted Jack
Everly's arrangement of the Minkus score.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALESMAN-THEATER-ART-     04-27 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALESMAN-THEATER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALESMEN ON STAGE: CRIES OF ANGUISH FROM THE FRONT LINES OF
CAPITALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Attention must be paid.'' Linda Loman's plea
resounds through ``Death of a Salesman,'' but in fact attention has
long been paid to America's salesmen. The problem for them is not
being ignored but being kidded or put down.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the attention comes from academics or journalists or a
playwright or two, the salesman is most commonly a figure of
mockery, particularly if he is a traveling man (did you hear the
one about Hickey's wife and the iceman?), or he may be a peddler of
all that is most tawdry about the free market. Or perhaps he's just
a desperate case, on the psychological edge, but never _ except
maybe at trade banquets, where worth is measured by the bottom line
_ is his calling held up as an exemplar of high aspirations or
edifying values.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the presence on Broadway stages of American drama's two most
powerfully drawn salesmen once again compels attention. Is Willy
Loman a victim of the system or of his own weak character? Is
Hickey mad or is he an all-American prophet?
</P>
<P>
   Critics down the years have agreed on one thing: the salesman's
goods, whether his valise holds hardware or underwear, turn out to
be cheap stuff, with sorry consequences for himself and the
synthetic faith he epitomizes.
</P>
<P>
   Even in good economic times, as Frederick Lewis Allen reminded
us in ``Only Yesterday,'' his amiable chronicle of the 1920s, when
salesmen, those ``angels and evangels'' of business, reveled in the
Coolidge prosperity, they were under relentless pressure to
perform. Their lot was always precarious. They were at once
exhorted and threatened by quotas and other humiliating management
spurs and whips. Never could they be their own men.
</P>
<P>
   Allen reported on a method of goading salesmen, ``which for
sheer inhumanity probably set a record'': A company ``gave a
banquet at which the man with the best score was served with
oysters, roast turkey and a most elaborate ice; the man with the
second best score had the same dinner but without the oysters; and
so on down to the man with the worst score, before whom was laid a
small plate of boiled beans and a couple of crackers.'' For anyone
who judged himself by the way others rated him, a definition of
salesmanship, it was an exquisite form of cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, when ``The Iceman Cometh'' and ``Death of a
Salesman'' were first produced, the salesman was a punching bag for
the intellectual set. When we meet Willy Loman, he is already
feeding emotionally on boiled beans and crackers. By the play's
end, his friend, Charley, is delivering the salesman's eulogy: ``He
don't put a bolt to a nut, he don't tell you the law or give you
medicine. . . . a couple of spots on your hat, and you're
finished.'' Willy has been beaten down by a system he thought he
had mastered. He and Hickey, the hardware drummer, are both
dreamers without usable skills, struggling with ultimately
destructive dreams.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that critics of capitalism or
consumerism should proclaim the salesman as exhibit No. 1 of what
the authors of ``The Lonely Crowd,'' published in 1950, described
as the ``other-directed'' character type. Erich Fromm had already
drawn a picture of the ``marketer'' and C. Wright Mills of the
``fixer,'' but it remained for David Riesman, Nathan Glazer and
Reuel Denney to put a catchy name to a growing class distinguished
and demeaned by ``an exceptional sensitivity to the actions and
wishes of others.'' These corporate servitors, in the authors'
view, were empty vessels for the opinions and attitudes of their
bosses and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Riesman and company took care not to overstate their case. They
noted that with the increased importance of technical skills in
companies like IBM, glad-handing alone could not sell a line. Yet
the salesman remained the prototypical glad-hander, the most
visible exponent, along with advertisers, of consumerism. The word
``salesman'' is still shorthand for the other-directed person, the
fellow who doesn't know what he thinks until he figures out what
others expect him to think.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the appearance of ``The Lonely Crowd,''
psychologists had diagnosed the emotional cost of
``other-directedness,'' which deprives a Willy Loman of any footing
when things turn bad. He keeps grasping for a faith or a fantasy
that is bound to fail.
</P>
<P>
   But Hickey is a different, harder case, a man battling at a
profound level to awaken from the dreams that have kept him afloat.
Where Miller, with his whiff of Marxism, attacks the cruel grip of
society, O'Neill probes a soul in extremis. To try to place the
characters in ``The Iceman Cometh'' in sociological categories is
as reductive as applying Freudian or Marxist formulas to a
metaphysical predicament.
</P>
<P>
   Hickey remains a salesman to the end, only his product is no
longer hardware, but peace. His condition is out of the
sociologists' depth. When Willy's son Biff, says that Willy ``had
the wrong dreams, all all wrong,'' he implies that there is some
sort of right dream for Willy, maybe tending his garden or moving
out West.
</P>
<P>
   But what the discerning Larry, Hickey's pal, learns is that for
him and for all the other sodden losers in Harry Hope's saloon
there is no right dream, certainly not the revolutionary gabble of
a few of the old-timers. ``Be God,'' Larry concludes, ``I'm the
only real convert to death Hickey made here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s are an oddly upbeat time for two such downbeat works,
shadowed by doom and death, to make it as Broadway hits. Today,
America is a nation of winners. Salesmen are doing smashingly well;
the ever-rising stock market is their answer to the naysayers. Yet
as their Broadway reception confirms, Willy and Hickey still reach
us with a despair that cannot be measured on the NASDAQ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
