<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding Drama in Basketball &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fontana and Barry Levinson have found groundbreaking
television drama inside a Baltimore homicide squad in NBC's
``Homicide,'' and a maximum-security prison in HBO's ``Oz''; but
when they went looking for a new arena for drama they took
``arena'' rather literally.
</P>
<P>
   As in basketball arena. Starting in July, ``Hoop Life,'' the new
drama series from the Levinson/Fontana Co., to be presented on
Showtime, will take a hard-edged, tough-talking, behind-the-court
look at the life of professional basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   The league mentioned in the show will not actually be called the
National Basketball Association. To avoid any legal entanglements,
the league will be called the UBA. But the connection is not likely
to be missed by viewers, especially with real NBA players like
Eddie Jones of Charlotte and Brevin Knight of Cleveland showing up
regularly for cameos.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana said he and Levinson developed the series from an
original script by Sean Jablonski. ``It started out as a two-hour
movie for Showtime,'' Fontana said, ``and it's grown into a order
for 22 episodes.'' The series is to begin on July 4 and is expected
to be on every Sunday night after that.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cacaci, a longtime friend of Fontana, who is the show's
executive producer, said the show would ``get into the lives of the
players in a serious way, though there will also be a heavy dose of
dark comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   If that description sounds like HBO's breakthrough drama ``The
Sopranos,'' Showtime surely won't object. The other pay cable
channel is also looking to get into weekly drama, and it has the
same advantages HBO has: freedom with both language and sexual
situations as well as an approach to series television that allows
writers to pursue their own vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Showtime and HBO trust you,'' Fontana said. ``Their support
for your original idea never varies.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Hoop Life,'' Cacaci said the series will not
flinch from examining what he called the ``over the top behavior''
of some basketball stars. The main characters include a married
player who is an uncontrolled womanizer, a young hotshot player who
loses himself in the big easy money he begins to make, a female
team owner, even, in the most ``Soprano''-like touch, a female
sports psychologist who is called on to do therapy with some of the
players.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Dan Lauria as the coach and Mykelti Williamson
as the star player. Fontana and Cacaci said casting was less a
problem than they expected, even though basketball skill was a
requirement. ``A lot of these guys can really play,'' Cacaci said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bill Carter &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The `Meeting' Format &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Littleton, Colo., high school killings last week got far
more attention from the major television networks than previous
school killings, and more than twice as many minutes (144) on the
6:30 evening newscasts than coverage of the crisis in Yugoslavia
(63) that week.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy also prompted a new round of televised ``town
meetings,'' a format that has become almost a reflexive response in
coverage of troubling news stories. ABC's ``Nightline'' anchor Ted
Koppel conducted a town meeting on Thursday in Jonesboro, Ark., the
site of a middle-school shooting that left five dead last year, and
had parents there talking to parents in Littleton; Tom Brokaw and
Jane Pauley are to lead a town meeting in Westfield, N.J.,
Wednesday night on the MSNBC cable network (10 p.m.), and CNN's
Jeff Greenfield will lead one Thursday night in Champaign-Urbana,
Ill. (7:30 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what television can do, act as a large electronic
living room for the country,'' Brokaw said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   His town meeting will include panelists ranging from a prominent
psychiatrist to an expert on teen-agers' Internet use to Gov.
Christine Todd Whitman of New Jersey and Vice President Al Gore
(via satellite). CNN's town meeting will eschew experts but will
feature interviews of high school students in 15 states by peers
who are journalists in CNN's Student Bureau. Both will have
participation by a ``just folks'' audience on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Do such large-group discussions really provide any new
information or insights on such complicated stories?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the value is that you can get smart, reasonable people
talking to each other,'' Brokaw said. ``The experts will learn from
the audience as much as audience will learn from the experts.''
</P>
<P>
   Koppel's town meeting on the subject did poorly in the Nielsen
ratings last week, but Brokaw said that should not deter networks
from doing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought since well before Littleton that there is too
little connective tissue in the country anymore,'' he said.
``Everyone's shouting at each other; there's too little attempt to
find common ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing I believe,'' he added, ``is that this subject,
Littleton and what happened there, is in the fabric of America
right now and it's what people are talking about. There are so few
answers, but maybe we can move it forward some, give people
something else to think about.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawrie Mifflin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Striving for Sensitivity &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC found itself in something of a predicament last week after
the school shootings in Colorado. The network's big mini-series for
the May sweep, a two-part movie called ``Atomic Train,'' revolved
around a threat that the city of Denver would be blown up by a
nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Several networks changed series episodes or news segments last
week because of concerns about offending viewers in the aftermath
of the Littleton catastrophe. But ``Atomic Train'' posed some
special problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb references were a worry for NBC because bombs were
involved in the school attack. But the main issue was the
connection to Denver. NBC was worried enough that several
executives viewed the film last week to see if it would be possible
to change all the references in the film from Denver to Salt Lake
City. They decided that it was impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The network finally concluded that enough time will have elapsed
by May 16, the movie's broadcast date, that no one will find the
references to bombs and Denver insensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carter &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
