<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPLIFE-NYT &LR;      04-27 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG DREAMS AND SHORT SHORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's administer a test. In the spring and summer,
major record companies roll out records by their latest pop
contenders, hoping that by Christmas they can turn a newcomer into
a superstar. Below are a few such up-and-coming acts executives say
they are banking on this year, investing from hundreds of thousands
to millions of dollars in promotional campaigns in hopes that
record buyers will take notice.
</P>
<P>
   Some are record-label priorities because of their success abroad
(Texas, Robbie Williams); others already have strong followings in
the United States that executives feel can be greatly expanded
(Insane Clown Posse, Limp Bizkit); a few are new to American pop
fans (Billie, Macy Gray), and a couple are already so famous that
it would be a shock if their albums weren't smashes (Ricky Martin,
Jennifer Lopez).
</P>
<P>
   So, let's see just how good the labels are at gauging the taste
of record buyers. Hold onto this list until Christmas, then examine
it again to see who has become a pop star and who can't get their
record companies to answer their phone calls. If the labels are
right, the pop scene will be even more dominated by Hispanic pop
singers, English media darlings, obnoxious white rappers and perky
teen-agers than it is already. If they're wrong, they'll have
scores more pop contenders waiting in the wings for next spring.
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL FREDO, ``Introducing'' (Warner Brothers, in stores late
summer) and C NOTE, ``Different Kind of Love'' (Epic, May 18): Here
are two new teenybopper pinups from Louis J. Pearlman, the former
blimp-company executive who brought you the Backstreet Boys,
Britney Spears and 'N Sync. Michael Fredo is a 19-year-old popster
who looks 12 and is the opening act for Ms. Spears; C Note is New
Kids on the Block version 3.1. This Hispanic boy quartet is all
cheesy come-ons and recycled pop hooks with Latin flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   INSANE CLOWN POSSE, ``The Amazing Jeckel Brothers'' (Island, in
stores May 11): It's stupid, immature and strewn with profanity. In
other words, it has all the makings of a hit. Full of gleeful
misogyny and grisly murder scenarios, this new record by two masked
rappers from America's new white rap capital, Detroit (home to
Eminem and Kid Rock), is music to upset parents by.
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER LOPEZ, ``On the Six'' (Work, June 1): The transition
from film to pop is a difficult, but executives are betting that
the star of ``Out of Sight'' has the right ingredients: slick
production, smooth diva vocals, a mix of bedroom ballads and
dance-floor churners, Latin spice, a collaboration with Puff Daddy
and short shorts.
</P>
<P>
   BILLIE, ``Honey 2 the B'' (Virgin, May 18): Signed simply
because she ``looks like a star,'' 16-year-old Billie Piper is an
English Britney Spears with early Madonna dance moves and several
No. 1 hits in her home country. And she's naughty: she says
``damn'' in her single ``She Wants You.''
</P>
<P>
   JT MONEY, ``Pimpin' on Wax'' (Priority, May 25) and Ja Rule,
``Venni, Vetti, Vecci'' (Def Jam, May 4): Between the former Poison
Clan member JT Money's shout-along single ``Who Dat'' and Ja Rule's
too-catchy ``Holla Holla'' (plus his appearance on Jay-Z's hit
``Can I Get a . . .''), here are two rap debuts that couldn't be
better set up.
</P>
<P>
   ROBBIE WILLIAMS, ``The Ego Has Landed'' (Capitol, May 4): The
former singer in Take That is very witty and very successful
abroad; he performs very good pop and is being very intensively
promoted. But his singing, his style and his humor are also very,
very British. So add it all up, and you have a very big question
mark.
</P>
<P>
   MACY GRAY, ``On How Life Is'' (Epic, July 20): With a voice like
Rod Stewart on helium, Ms. Gray may seem like one of the most
unlikely aspirants being touted by the labels. But with a terrific
debut full of spirited, free-flowing funk and soul, she may find
success as well as a career ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS, ``Hush'' (Universal, May 18): Unlike the other superstars
trying to cross the Atlantic, the Scottish group Texas has already
released four albums. On its fifth, the personable singer Sharleen
Spiteri finds common ground between classic American
rhythm-and-blues and gliding Europop.
</P>
<P>
   BUCKCHERRY, ``Buckcherry'' (Dreamworks, available now): Sure,
this album has been stuck at the bottom of the charts since its
release a few weeks ago, but executives are still hoping that these
tattoo-covered hard-rockers and their lyrics about fast cars, easy
girls, bountiful cocaine and the kind of self-destruction that
looks very good in the mirror will make bring back the glory days
of Los Angeles glam-metal.
</P>
<P>
   RICKY MARTIN, ``Ricky Martin'' (Columbia, May 11): It doesn't
take a genius to predict huge success for the first
English-language album from this former Menudo singer in light of
his spectacular Grammy performance, his chiseled looks and a hit,
``Livin' la Vida Loca,'' that makes everyone in the vicinity feel
as if they have a fire in their pants. Columbia is betting that he
will sell 300,000 to 400,000 copies of his album in the first week
and that he will also pave the way for dozens of other Latin pop
crossovers.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOFFATTS, ``Chapter 1: A New Beginning'' (Capitol, June 8):
At ages 15 and 16 _ and in the wake of Hanson _ this Canadian band
of triplets plus one older brother has decided on a career change,
switching their style from country music to classic pop-rock and
enlisting the help of Alanis Morissette collaborator Glen Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   LIMP BIZKIT, ``Significant Other'' (Interscope, June 22): Full
of hip-hop-inflected monster rock, a few songs toned down for radio
and atrocious rapping, this album is a giant step up for an already
successful band. Even music industry executives not affiliated with
Limp Bizkit say that it could outdo Korn.
</P>
<P>
   Other Hopefuls:
</P>
<P>
   Canadian pop diva Lara Fabian, salsa superstar Marc Anthony,
Colombian pop-rock ingenue Shakira, solo Spice Girl Geri Halliwell,
trip-pop songwriter Dido, Nine Inch Nails spinoff Filter, ``Mulan''
singer Christina Aguilera, persevering rap metalheads Shootyz
Groove, gospel-cum-country singer Susan Ashton, English popsters
Boyzone and rockers Muse and rap supergroups Ruff Ryders and 504.
</P>
<P>
   Grrrl Powers
</P>
<P>
   The all-female Lilith Fair announced the dates and performers
Tuesday for its final tour. Appearing on various dates will be the
tour's founder, Sarah McLachlan, as well as the Dixie Chicks,
Sheryl Crow, Indigo Girls, Monica, Cherokee, Shawn Colvin, Cibo
Matto, Pretenders, Beth Orton, Cree Summers, Kelly Willis, Me'shell
Ndegeocello and dozens more. The tour begins July 8 in Vancouver
and will reach the New York area via shows at Jones Beach in
Wantagh, N.Y., on Aug. 6 and at the PNC Bank Arts Center in
Holmdel, N.J., on Aug. 7 and 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
