 By SUSUMU SAITO  
 c.1999 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month has passed since the allied air forces of NATO members
began bombing Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the intention of the Clinton administration and its
NATO allies to force the Serbian government to quickly end the
massacre of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, the bombing so far has only
resulted in the exodus of hundreds of thousands of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have already suggested that the bombing will
continue well into the summer unless the Serbian government gives
in.
</P>
<P>
   Some people such as Henry A. Kissinger, who had criticized the
Rambouillet agreement as unsustainable, now unwillingly suggest
that NATO countries will have to introduce ground forces to settle
the Kosovo issue and maintain NATO credibility.
</P>
<P>
   He also warns that the disappearance of Serbia from the Balkan
equilibrium may risk a wider Balkan war.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, there is a high likelihood that the war will drag
on much longer than anticipated until a sustainable political
solution is worked out and imposed.
</P>
<P>
   This prospect calls for an examination of the economic
implications of the Balkan crisis if a sustainable political and
military solution requires substantial economic resources from the
United States and its NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, wars and business cycles have been very closely
interrelated.
</P>
<P>
   The downward phases of business cycles have caused economic
dislocation of peoples and ruptures within society. In particular,
in the downward phase of a long business cycle, or the period known
as depression years, economic dislocation has been severe enough to
cause ruptures and ultimately wars between nations and states.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century depression years (1873-1895) coincided with the
rapid colonization of Asia and Africa by European powers to gain
``markets'' for their surplus products and secure a supply of raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the United States as latecomers followed the European
powers to claim their shares of the pie in Asia around the turn of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate consequence of the rivalry among the great powers
was World War I.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th-century Great Depression of the 1930s led to exclusive
economic blocs by the British and the French, as well as Germany's
pursuit of the Lebensraum (political and economic expansion) and
Japan's Great Asia Co-prosperity Sphere.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate consequence was the unprecedented devastation of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. economy, far from the war front, could emerge
from the Great Depression because of wartime demand, its citizens
were obliged to shed their blood.
</P>
<P>
   Wars have turned economic depressions and deflation into booms
and inflation, or have solved economic depressions in a brutal way.
</P>
<P>
   The victor and the bystander (or the neutral) have gained
economically. And the defeated countries have often suffered
economic devastation and hyperinflation: Germany after the two
world wars and Japan after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, wars fought during the upward phase of
business cycles had quite different economic implications.
</P>
<P>
   A typical example is the Vietnam War. For the first half of the
1960s preceding the escalation of the war, the U.S. economy was
booming, with an unemployment rate of just around 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mobilization of more economic resources for the
escalating war in the second half of the 1960s, the Johnson
administration, which had campaigned for the ``Great Society,''
sought a policy of guns and butter at the same time. The shortage
of economic resources was filled by increasing imports in exchange
for paper dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of such a policy were the sharp deterioration
of the U.S. external balance of payments and the abandonment of the
gold standard by the Nixon administration in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying more paper dollars to finance the Vietnam War was the
root cause of the escalation of worldwide inflation in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike during the Persian Gulf War period (1990-1991) when the
U.S. economy was in recession, the U.S. economy for almost a decade
has been near full employment with record high stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   This record boom, however, has also resulted in a sharp
deterioration of U.S. external balance of payments, or a record
level of external deficits. In short, the boom has been financed by
huge borrowing from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the economic crisis in the rest of the world for the
past two years, especially in Asia, Latin America and Russia, has
helped prolong U.S. growth with subdued inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The depreciation of currencies in economically depressed regions
has worked to provide the U.S. economy with imports at much cheaper
prices than before.
</P>
<P>
   The unstable European political situation has already resulted
in a sharp weakness of the euro against the dollar. It will work
further to widen the external imbalance of the U.S. economy and the
exodus of capital from Europe to the United States to push up the
New York stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of much cheaper imports, however, will be detrimental
to the earnings of U.S. corporations in the home market. The rising
stock prices and subdued corporate earnings will be an incompatible
proposition before long.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Yugoslavia, if escalated into a muddy ground battle,
will be a very costly proposition for the U.S. economy already
working at full capacity, not to mention the cost to reconstruct
the afflicted region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, policymakers and investors worldwide need to keep a
close watch on the development in the Balkans. An escalation of the
war in the region could be the last straw for the U.S. economy,
which appears to have been overstretched for some time. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Susumu Saito is director of Trilateral
Institute (Sankyoku Keizai Kenkyusho), a private economic
think-tank based in Tokyo.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this pithy 950-word commentary from the Asahi News
Service, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
