<HEADLINE>
OVERSEAS WEDDINGS AN EYE-OPENER ON GLOBALIZATION  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This intriguing ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS 950-WORD
ARTICLE OFFERS THREE OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 225 WORDS, AT 375,
750 AND 850.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By YOICHI FUNABASHI  
 c.1999 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I attended an international conference at a Sydney hotel, I
noticed a big blackboard in the lobby that listed the flights
between Tokyo's Kansai International Airport and Sydney. The list
was in Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese receptionist who was sitting in front of the
blackboard told me that the sign was for three Japanese couples
from the Kansai area who were holding wedding ceremonies in Sydney.
It was also there to help Japanese guests in the wedding parties.
</P>
<P>
   The receptionist said the brides and grooms were accompanied by
their parents, relatives and close friends in the package tour from
Japan. The flight to Australia takes nearly 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the couples are having weddings in Australia. Isn't that a
bit extravagant?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that some foreigners who see such people question
whether Japan is really undergoing a recession,'' she said. ``But
it costs less to have weddings here than in Japan because you have
far fewer guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, it's much less troublesome to have overseas
weddings,'' she said. Dropping the sound of her voice, she offered
the following explanation:
</P>
<P>
   In Japanese weddings, newlyweds usually are obliged to invite
their superiors at work even when they are uncertain about whether
it would cause their bosses problems. When they invite their
colleagues, they rack their brains over who to invite.
</P>
<P>
   But if they hold weddings abroad, they don't have to worry about
such matters. All they have to do is ask to be pardoned since
they're getting married in a faraway place.
</P>
<P>
   Getting away from worldly trouble. That makes sense, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   The woman lowered her voice again and said: ``Before, lifetime
employment was nothing special. But now, you never know when you'll
lose your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, indeed. I found her logic convincing.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation intrigued me and led me to call the tourism
bureau of the Australian government to find out more.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official in charge, Australia is now the second
largest market for overseas weddings next to Hawaii. Since it is a
promising area, the tourism office is putting a great deal of
effort into luring foreign couples, the official said. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 375) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The official also suggested that the recent surge in overseas
weddings may have to do with the Japanese trend of holding simple
wedding ceremonies. Overseas weddings seem to be an economical
alternative to elaborate domestic weddings, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the official said that Australia has seen a sharp
drop in the number of churchgoers in recent years and many churches
now stand virtually idle. That is why they welcome large numbers of
Japanese couples for church weddings, the official said.  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While explaining the situation, the official repeatedly
mentioned the name Watabe, which prompted me to call Takao Watabe,
president of Watabe Wedding Corp., a Kyoto-based wedding service.
</P>
<P>
   The company triggered the trend for overseas weddings when it
started organizing them on a commercial basis 26 years ago.
Currently, it boasts a 60-percent share of the world market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overseas weddings are not a phenomenon unique to Japan,''
Watabe said. ``It is a global trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 20,000 German couples tie the knot in Las Vegas
every year,'' he claims. ``The Swiss go to Jamaica and the British
go to Disney World in Florida to get married. The trend is
spreading. The reason is the same anywhere in the world: Couples
don't want to be fettered by obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Britain, more than 10 percent of all newlyweds are holding
overseas ceremonies,'' Watabe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, the national average is 6 percent. In Tokyo, Osaka
and other urban areas, the percentage tops 10. I expect the
percentage to eventually hit 30 in Japan as well as in the United
States and Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Watabe's latest venture is overseas wedding tours targeted at
Chinese couples that he started organizing last spring. According
to Watabe, Bangkok is a favorite destination among Chinese brides
and grooms from Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``China lifted the embargo on overseas travel for the general
public,'' he said. ``Since the population is so large, I wish to
attract as many couples as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Japan, there will be fewer weddings starting in 2002 to
2003 because of a decline in the younger population. That's why
global business development is needed,'' he said. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 50 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, very few foreigners come to Japan to hold weddings.
</P>
<P>
   ``With such high prices, Japanese weddings are unaffordable,''
Watabe said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the price of Japanese weddings went down nearly 40
percent from the peak of the asset-inflated economy, it is still
double the average of U.S. weddings, according to Watabe. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Globalization gives people a much wider selection to choose from
in any given area. The process of making a choice also allows
people to make decisions about economic obstacles in the form of
market barriers and also social restrictions such as local custom. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 850; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Overseas weddings promoted price destruction of domestic
weddings and changed stereotyped wedding receptions. They are also
about to change the wedding culture itself.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered the following words of the receptionist at the
hotel lobby: ``The relatives accompanying the newlyweds say that
the trip gives people who hardly exchanged words before a chance to
get to know each other better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some couples seem happy that they were able to play golf
together day after day after a long time. They seem to be enjoying
themselves.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Yoichi Funabashi is an ``Asahi Shimbun'' senior
staff writer and foreign affairs columnist.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
