<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALLE-RITUAL-2TAKES-N     04-27 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALLE-RITUAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW RITUALS CAN CREATE A RELUCTANT ARTIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ From an early age, Sophie Calle organized her life
around rituals. She gave her goldfish and pet birds elaborate
funerals, with music and tiny coffins. She demanded to be awakened
with a glass of orange juice when her mother returned home from a
party, no matter the hour. In the week before her grandfather's
birthday she would mail him countdown letters daily.
</P>
<P>
   Later, sometimes much later, these rituals became stylized
performances and turned her into one of France's best-known
Conceptual artists. But even now, Ms. Calle, who is 45, invents her
games primarily for herself. Variously intrusive, humorous,
nostalgic, provocative, exhibitionistic, even erotic, they give
both drama and structure to her life. They may translate into works
of art, but this, she says, is a secondary function.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work is linked to improving my life,'' she said over coffee
in her sunlit studio in a converted factory on the outskirts of
Paris. ``I organize rituals to satisfy a specific need, to deal
with fear of being alone, to get married, whatever. I have
organized many that I never expected to exploit. Sometimes I used
the material years later. Some I have never gone back to.''
</P>
<P>
   She is evidently not one for throwing things away. From 1980 to
1993, her ritual was to invite a number of guests equal to her age
to her birthday party. (Her need was to have company on her
birthday.) She then put all the presents into storage. Finally, at
the Tate Gallery in London in 1998, she displayed them by year in
glass-faced cabinets in an installation called ``The Birthday
Ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Calle's studio, where she also lives, is itself something of
an installation. She is watched over by a lively black-and-white
cat and a veritable zoo of stuffed animals _ a fox, a couple of
eagles, several owls and two bulls' heads _ as well as by photos,
drawings, embroideries and statues of the Virgin Mary collected on
her travels. Her work area is neat: A current project about pain is
spread over three tables, but past material for future projects is
carefully stored in drawers and boxes.
</P>
<P>
   On one wall of her studio, there is a photograph of a blind man.
In the 1980s, setting out to ask people blind from birth for their
definition of beauty, she worried about being insensitive. But the
first person she queried, she said, freed her to create the texts
and photographs of ``The Blind.'' ``The most beautiful thing I have
ever seen,'' the man in the photograph answered, ``is the sea going
so far that you lose sight of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Conceptual and autobiographical, Ms. Calle's work is
anything but abstract. Often she simply seeks out a different way
of viewing ordinary behavior. In 1979 she was briefly a stripper in
a Pigalle nightclub, watching those who were watching her. A
photographer captured her routine as she cast off everything but
her black shoes, a fox fur collar and a blond wig. (Again, ``Le
Striptease'' was exhibited only years later.) On another occasion,
she invited 28 people to sleep for one night in her bed. She
photographed them (and was herself photographed asleep), and it
became ``The Sleepers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always curious,'' said the artist, dark-haired and
primly dressed, as she sat beneath a large rubber tree in her
studio. ``And I found a way of being able to ask questions from
behind the shield of art. I could watch people sleep when even
their wives didn't, because it was art. Now it is a way of life. I
no longer ask myself what I am doing. But I'm not obsessed with
whether it really is art and what will remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, interest in her work is growing. Over the winter
she had large exhibitions at the Centre National de la Photographie
in Paris and the Camden Arts Center in London. At a current show at
the Museum of Modern Art in New York, ``The Museum as Muse,'' she
has an installation recalling the famous art theft at the Isabella
Stewart Gardner Museum in Boston in 1990. At the Jewish Museum in
New York starting on June 20, she has an installation called ``The
Eruv,'' with photographs of private spaces in Jerusalem that permit
activity outside the home on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it was never Ms. Calle's ambition to become an artist.
In fact, she recalled, as a rebellious teen-ager, she was alienated
from art because her physician father was a collector. After high
school she fled France, spending seven years traveling and living
abroad. Eventually, while staying with a photographer in California
in 1978, she visited a nearby cemetery and took pictures of
tombstones inscribed with single words, ``father,'' ``mother,''
``brother,'' ``sister.'' ``I liked them and thought, `Why not
photography?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to Paris and, at 25, discovered that photography
added an interesting dimension to her games. By chance, after ``The
Sleepers,'' her first photo ritual, one participant showed the work
to her husband, who was organizing a show of young artists in
Paris. He liked the results and invited her to be part of the
exhibition at the city's Modern Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember asking myself whether I wanted the photos to be
regarded as art,'' she said. ``Do I want to be an artist? I had not
asked myself that before. And if I remember rightly, I'm not sure I
wanted to take that step. I'd never been that interested in the
world of art. I always thought I could do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue came up again in an unexpected way. Out of loneliness,
she took to following strangers around Paris. One evening in early
1980 she met a man who was leaving for Venice by train and, without
his knowledge, she followed him there, photographing him and
jotting down his movements. When she thought to include this ritual
in her first book, however, shelearned that the New York artist
Vito Acconci had done it over a decade before she did.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, I was confronted with the idea that there
were others,'' she said. ``How could I show something that had
already been shown? I went to see Vito Acconci to ask his
permission. Of course, he said. What I had done was different. For
him, what counted was the gesture of following. I had all my
feelings. My way was more sentimental, his more Conceptual. So he
sort of blessed me.''
</P>
<P>
   For a second time, then, someone else had decided that she was
an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Feelings were even more central to one of her strangest
projects, a 1994 film called ``No Sex Last Night,'' in which she
and a boyfriend drove across the United States with camcorders,
stopping in Las Vegas to get married. Ms. Calle said her only goal
was to hold onto a man she feared she was losing, while the man,
Greg Shephard, an aspiring filmmaker, saw a chance to make a movie.
In the end, Ms. Calle lost Greg, but together they made a
well-received art-house movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Game,'' her latest large work, seen in Paris and
London, included her most complicated set of rituals. In 1990 the
director Michael Radford (``Il Postino'') was planning a feature
film inspired by Ms. Calle's bizarre life, and he invited Paul
Auster to write the screenplay. The film plan did not prosper, but
Auster based a character in his 1992 novel, ``Leviathan,'' on Ms.
Calle and her rituals, adding a few more from his own imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Amused by the notion of obedience, Ms. Calle decided to live out
the rules invented for Auster's character, Maria, like eating food
of a single color on different days of the week and living out a
letter of the alphabet for an entire day. For B, for example, she
was photographed in bed as a ``big-time blond bimbo'' surrounded by
her stuffed animals; for C she spent the day at Montparnasse
Cemetery beside her future tomb, which she decorated with the words
ciao, ciao.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Calle also asked Auster to swap roles: Instead of his
appropriating her life, he would invent ``a fictive character whom
I would attempt to resemble.'' Auster balked at the responsibility,
but instead sent her ``Personal Instructions for S.C. on How to
Improve Life in New York City (Because She Asked).'' ``Smile when
the situation doesn't call for it,'' began the five pages of
instructions, which also included talking to strangers, giving
sandwiches to beggars and homeless people and ``cultivating a
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Through photographs and texts, ``Double Game'' brings together
the rituals that Auster borrowed from Ms. Calle's life and those he
invented for her. For her Manhattan ``spot,'' she chose a phone
booth on the corner of Greenwich and Harrison Streets, which she
cleaned and improved with flowers, a chair, a notebook and pencils,
an ashtray, a magazine and a sign saying, ``Have a Nice Day.'' In
the main, she said, New Yorkers liked it. ``It's a good
humanitarian gesture,'' one man said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she does wonder at times whether she is too intrusive, as
when she found a man's address book in a street, called his friends
and asked them to describe him, then published the results _
without his name _ in the Paris daily Liberation. (His revenge was
to send a nude photograph of Ms. Calle to the paper, and it was
published as a right of reply.) Similarly, voyeurism is clearly the
appeal of ``The Hotel,'' a series of photographs of empty but
rented rooms in a Venice hotel where she was a chambermaid in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fact that she reveals herself encourages others to do
likewise. When she sat at a desk on the final day of her recent
shows in Paris and London to hear suggestions for her next project,
she was struck by how visitors wanted to share their secrets with
her. Ms. Calle waved toward two foot-high stacks of letters she
received during these shows. In Paris one young woman gave her a
book and hurriedly wrote a dedication: ``Sophie, this is the most
precious thing I have on me, my diary. You can read it, I'm giving
it to you. I never imagined I would dare come up to you. That is
always the problem with artists: We live with them but they do not
know us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Freud Museum in London through Sunday, Ms. Calle has an
``intervention'' called ``Appointment,'' comprising texts and
unlikely objects (like her stripper's wig) placed on the desk,
couch and bookshelves that surrounded Freud during his final years
in London. Since many texts are funny and self-deprecating, she
worried that some visitors might consider them irreverent, but the
show has proved immensely popular.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are invited to comment and one notebook has already
been filled. ``I'm touched when I read what people write,'' Ms.
Calle said. ``One likes to be loved.'' She opened the notebook to
its last page. In pencil, an anonymous visitor had written: ``Thank
you very much _ I think my life may change because of you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
