<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS PAY LITTLE HEED TO PLO DEBATE ON WHEN TO DECLARE
STATEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip, _ Several miles from the seaside compound
where Palestinian leaders locked themselves away Tuesday to
deliberate the timing of a declaration of statehood, Motee and Ali
Anan sat shrugging amid porcelain toilets in their luxury-bathroom
store on the main boulevard in town.
</P>
<P>
   The Anans, uncle and nephew, are not hanging on the outcome of
the meeting of the 120-member Central Council of the Palestine
Liberation Organization. They are barely curious; few people here
seem to care. It seems clear to them that under international
pressure, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has already decided to
delay the declaration he once promised for May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is only a show,'' Ali Anan said, gazing at a $1,000
toilet, sink and bidet set. ``It is theater, and we don't have to
wait for the curtain to come down to know how it will end.''
</P>
<P>
   If the meeting was theater, it seemed to be a rehearsal of a
democratic process, with the Palestinian leaders reportedly
engaging in fiery debate. But despite guest appearances by such
opponents as Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the Islamic fundamentalist, Arafat
seemed to be guiding the council members toward a scripted
conclusion: A statehood declaration must be postponed, and
negotiations with the Israelis must continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going through a very delicate period in the history of
our people, a period during which we cannot afford to make any
mistakes,'' the official Palestinian news agency WAFA quoted Arafat
as saying. ``We don't need to affirm our state because we are
actually exercising statehood.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the Oslo peace accord, May 4 is the day when
the Palestinians' transitional government is to expire and a target
date for the conclusion of final peace talks between Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But because the peace effort is frozen, and the final-status
negotiations have barely begun, Arafat had said he would make a
unilateral declaration of statehood on that day. In the Palestinian
areas of the West Bank and Gaza, May 4 became a rallying cry: It
would be the day when the Palestinians would break free of Israel
and of the American peace brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, it seems unlikely that anyone will be dancing the
debka, the Palestinian dance of celebration, next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The council meeting may take many days, even weeks of what Nabil
Amr, the Palestinian minister of parliamentary affairs, said would
be ``hot, long, serial sessions.'' It may drag past the Israeli
elections on May 17 _ so that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
could not take credit for a decision to postpone the declaration,
some Palestinian leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The time will be used by Arafat to soothe internal dissent,
which _ partly because of incompetence and corruption and abuses by
his security forces _ has grown during the five years of
Palestinian self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   Even for the pragmatic among the Palestinian leaders, a deferral
of statehood would be a particularly piquant disappointment, and
Arafat must work hard to persuade them that their interim autonomy
will not become a long-term limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat must confront the frustration of Palestinian legislators
like Marwan Barghouti, a leader of his Fatah Party, who are fed up
with peace talks. ``The Palestinians will not get their state from
the negotiating table but should take the decision to declare one,
even if the declaration provokes a clash with the other side,'' he
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Netanyahu government has said it would respond harshly to a
unilateral declaration, possibly by suspending the Oslo accords or,
more drastically, by annexing parts of the West Bank. But like
Barghouti, many Palestinians are prepared to play chicken with the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel tried to use violence against us in the past, and it
did not work,'' said Jamal Shati al-Hindi, a Palestinian legislator
from Jenin, on the West Bank. ``The world should understand that
Israel did not fulfill its commitments and stop pressuring us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a total breakdown of the peace effort and an outbreak of
violence, American, European and Arab leaders have pressed Arafat
to defer his declaration and to negotiate statehood with the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   To garner international support, Arafat has been traveling the
world at a breakneck pace. In the last month, he has visited the
leaders of 25 countries, including outposts like Burkina Faso and
Kazahkstan.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian journalists joke that the biggest news Tuesday was
that Arafat was actually home. But his travels have borne fruit.
The European Union declared last month that the Palestinians have
``an unqualified right to self-determination, including the option
of a state'' and that Israel does not have a ``veto'' over that
right.
</P>
<P>
   And President Clinton, in a letter Arafat brought to the meeting
Tuesday, said he supported ``the aspirations of the Palestinian
people to determine their own future on their own land,'' his
strongest endorsement yet. He also promised to help start
final-status negotiations immediately after the election in Israel,
and to encourage their completion within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said the letter had been shared with Israel
beforehand. ``I can tell you that they talked to us ahead of time,
and we agreed that this is a reasonable target,'' he said on Israel
Radio, referring to the one-year time frame.
</P>
<P>
   Many Palestinians say bitterly that their fate seems to lie in
the hands of the Israelis and the Americans, not in Arafat's. Some
see his intention to defer statehood as capitulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our destiny will be imposed on us,'' said Motee Anan, 68, the
owner of the bathroom store.
</P>
<P>
   But while a recent poll by the Center for Palestinian Research
in Nablus found that 43 percent of those Palestinians surveyed
favored a unilateral declaration now, 48 percent preferred a
deferral.
</P>
<P>
   One who prefers deferring a declaration is Kanan Abu Shaban, who
was scooping sticky yellow and pink sherbet into plastic cups in
his ice-cream parlor here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the leadership will take into consideration that a
declaration would lead to no changes except negative ones,'' he
said. ``The Israelis would instantly impose on us the most simple
and effective punishment: barring Palestinian workers from
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Down Omar el-Mukhtar Street, the main thoroughfare of Gaza, the
Anans agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis can close our borders and we suffer a lot,''
Motee Anan said. ``Our bread, our sugar, our cigarettes, our petrol
comes from them. We have to be realistic and not ask for the
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   His nephew added: ``We have waited to be independent since
1948,'' the year Israel was founded. ``You think we cannot wait
another six months?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
