<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5328 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREEN-LEGISLATOR-HNS &LR;      04-27 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-LEGISLATOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN PARTY CANDIDATE BREAKS GROUND IN STATE CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Audie Bock has just cast the deciding vote
on one of the most important bills in the Legislature, giving
terminally ill patients the right to die. She switched her vote _
from no to yes _ in a single, understated movement and made it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, journalists are following the Green Party
assemblywoman down a Capitol hallway and into the back stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps smiling, her head down a bit. Tentative, restrained is
how some lawmakers describe her.
</P>
<P>
   No questions right now, though. The new lawmaker for Oakland,
Alameda and Piedmont _ on the east side of the San Francisco Bay _
needs a respite.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we're going to get a cup of tea,'' says Michael
Twombly, her chief of staff, Green Party organizer and former
lobbyist, her only permanent full-time employee so far. ``No. After
a cup of tea.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if she didn't think about the vote, Bock says later.
She went to sleep dreaming of a Japanese film about unwanted
grandmothers left to die on mountaintops, picked dead by crows.
</P>
<P>
   She had to go against Ralph Nader, the eminence grise of the
left-leaning Green Party, and all those angry people in wheelchairs
inside the committee room afraid the bill would lead to
state-sponsored euthanasia of the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   She began to believe the bill had enough protections, and she
thought of her grandmother, who once asked to die. So she switched
her vote, saying later she had no idea it would change the course
of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A curiosity to the 119 other lawmakers in Sacramento, Bock
describes her first three weeks in the Assembly as ``parachuting
in.''
</P>
<P>
   No time for tea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of thing where people greet you nicely, and you
eat a sponge cake,'' said Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San
Francisco, who also came to Sacramento after a special election, in
the middle of chaos. ``And a minute later you're a stranger left to
negotiate the hallways.''
</P>
<P>
   Bock arrived in the Assembly on April 5, after defeating Elihu
Harris in a special election. Harris, who was expected to win, is a
Democrat who was the former mayor of Oakland and a former
Assemblyman.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the nation's first state official from the Green Party is
quickly trying to set up her district office _ in the gleaming new
Elihu Harris State Building in downtown Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, Bock has a fifth-floor view of towering redwoods
outside the Capitol. It's one of the smallest offices in the
building: three tiny rooms and a reception area decorated only with
a weathered ``Bock for Assembly'' sign and a yarn sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Bock landed in town after the deadline to introduce bills and
three weeks before the deadline for those bills to pass committee.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of her time has been spent absorbing and actually showing
up at her committee meetings, unlike other members, sitting
dutifully at her desk in the far north of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things Bock learned is that there are fellow
travelers in the Legislature, which is dominated by Democratic and
Republican lawmakers, of course, but has a working staff of 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   `There are Greens working in the building,'' Bock said almost
conspiratorially, ``and they're not working in my office.'' She
laughed. ``They come over and whisper, `I'm a Green.' We've got a
lot of closet Greens here.''
</P>
<P>
   A movie distributor and former translator for the late film
director Akira Kurosawa, Bock was forced to abruptly cancel two
college teaching jobs and inform Harvard University that once again
she would not be taking up her doctoral thesis on another Japanese
filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   A single parent, Bock, 53, struggled at first with the daily
commute to Sacramento. She asked her mother to help watch her
14-year-old daughter. ``I don't think either of us have adjusted
yet,'' Bock said. ``We're still scrambling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bock has abandoned, out of temporary necessity, her
environmental altruism when it comes to commuting.
</P>
<P>
   For the first week, Bock got up at 4:30 a.m. for the train to
Sacramento. But since the last train leaves for home at 5:30 p.m.,
far too early, she requested an electric or natural-gas-powered
car.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are still scrambling to find her a car that will
make the 90-minute trip. They even drove her route home but ran out
of energy in the middle of the test run. Bock gets $400 a month to
lease any American car she wants, but she's been using a
gasoline-powered car from the Capitol pool.
</P>
<P>
   Greens worry about these things; Bock nearly apologized for
owning a 14-year-old Nissan parked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Audie is kind of stunned, as all the rest of us were
the first couple of weeks that we were here,'' said Assemblywoman
Sheila Kuehl, D-Santa Monica, adding: ``She may not have
particularly expected that she would have to work in Sacramento or
be in Sacramento every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the right-to-die vote, Bock is back to virtual
anonymity amid the most chaotic day of the year. She sits patiently
in an oppressively stuffy room waiting to present her first bill
before an obscure Assembly committee.
</P>
<P>
   The labor-supported bill was given to her by a Democratic
lawmaker who had been holding it for Harris, the man bock beat.
</P>
<P>
   Bock gladly accepted AB1653, which sets up a resource center on
workplace safety for children and teen-agers. Groups opposed: None.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
