<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5334 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS28-COX     04-27 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secret to Hawks playoff success might be Blalock
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mookie Blaylock is pretty bright. He knows what he
must do to keep the Hawks winning. He knows , but there are too
many times when he plays in denial and his team goes belly up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the key,'' coach Lenny Wilkens says, ``but sometimes we
have to help him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock leads the Hawks in shots attempted and in assists made,
but often he has too many of the former and not enough of the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   He leads the team in defense, as well _ although for the first
time in four years he will not lead the NBA in steals, as he ranks
12th with a week to go.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Blaylock's role in the offense that determines the
success or failure of the team because it's his ball. Over the last
five games, he has been at his best _ shooting 48 percent and
averaging 18.8 points and 6.8 assists _ and the Hawks have won them
all. But Blaylock is only shooting 38 percent for the season,
dragged down by 29.8 percent on three-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Intellectually, Blaylock knows that when he stands still and
launches those momentum-killing 23-footers, he is shooting his team
in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I bring energy to the game, when I'm moving, catching the
ball in rhythm, it's all the difference in the world,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then why fire away?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when my legs are heavy, I don't bring that energy
to the court. My body won't respond. Then, we all stand around, and
it don't work so good.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he doesn't want to take all those shots. ``It's a
natural thing when nobody's moving to throw the ball back to the
point guard. The clock's going down. I've got the rock. I've got to
shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock admires Blaylock for his hard
play and his energy. ``He really gives us a lift when he's on his
game,'' Babcock says. Yet. ``Sometimes you'd like Mookie to be a
little more patient.''
</P>
<P>
   With New York coming to town tonight, the Hawks are about to
clinch home-court advantage for at least one playoff round and at
28-17 can win the Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   But the closer the Hawks get to the top, the more tainted they
are by outrageous lapses at home early this season. And Blaylock's
fingerprints are on those lapses _ losses to Chicago (he shot
3-for-13, with only 3 assists), Washington (2-for-8, 4 assists) and
Toronto (1-for-6, 3 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to such games, Wilkens cites the need for a point guard
at his active best.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to get off to a great start this season,'' Wilkens
says, ``but his shooting wasn't there. You can attribute that to us
being off for so long, but I also thought he was anxious and trying
to make it happen too quick. And he really got out of rhythm. I
spoke to him about slowing down, catching, getting set. When he's
in rhythm, he's really good, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Mookie's playing right now, he could take us a long
way. Could we win a championship with Mookie the way he's playing
now? I'd say, yes, I believe we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens, a Hall of Fame point guard, says Blaylock's excesses do
not stem from willfullness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mookie's not a natural point. I've coached other guys like
him. They're scorers in college, and when they come into the NBA
they have to make the adjustment. Mookie's done a pretty good job
of that, but, yeah, there are times when he relies too much on his
jump shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The lockout and abbreviated training camp made Blaylock's task
more difficult, Wilkens says, because there was little time to get
acquainted with such new or unfamiliar players as LaPhonso Ellis,
Chris Crawford, Anthony Johnson and Roshown McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to learn what they like to do and what they can do
best, and he's got to mesh that with his game,'' Wilkens says. ``At
the same time, he's always got to make sure Dikembe (Mutombo) is
involved. I played point guard in this league for a lot of years.
Believe me, it isn't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the statistics don't show a definitive line, Wilkens
says Blaylock started to find his groove in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to me because he was worried, and I said, 'Look, you
have to take care of your teammates, but you also have to take care
of yourself. From here on out, why don't you just play
basketball?''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens also has taken to calling plays for Blaylock down the
stretch of close games. ``He seems to want it and I think it makes
his job easier,'' the coach says.
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock confirms as much. ``I like knowing what coach wants.
That way, we're all on the same page, and I can just go out there
and execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens nods. ``I told him to let me do the worrying. A guy with
his ability, it surprises you that sometimes he gets a little down
on himself. So I just try to be positive, (saying), 'Come on you
can do it; we know you can do it. We're not going anywhere without
you, so come on.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know what? It's true and he is doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
