<HEADER>
A5335 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIRACY-PC-COX     04-27 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRACY-PC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Software companies seek to stop piracy
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Microsoft and the rest of the software industry are
trying harder to get you to stop stealing what they make.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 27 percent of the software used by businesses in the
United States was illegally obtained, according to Microsoft.
Microsoft estimates that most of the pirated software, 65 percent,
is used by small- and medium-sized businesses, so that's the group
they're going after. Home users only account for about 15 percent,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the enforcement activities of the industry lobbying
group, the Business Software Alliance, collected $10 million in
fines from companies using software for which it did not have
licenses. The settlements are up from $6 million in 1996. Earlier
this month, a Massachusetts company, Intertek Testing Services,
agreed to pay $78,500 to the BSA for having unlicensed software,
including copies of Adobe, Lotus, Microsoft and Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   The money is put back into the BSA to pay for more enforcement
efforts. As the industry has cracked down on pirated software, the
enforcement staff has shot up. The BSA's staff of 35 has almost
tripled since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials, in Atlanta last week as part of last week's
Microsoft Explorer 99 exhibition, are starting an anti-piracy ad
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The lost sales cut into Microsoft's bottom line, it claims. The
company last week said it made $1.92 billion in the last three
months on sales of $4.33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft says the use of illegal software hurts everybody.
Flawed counterfeit software can corrupt the information entrusted
to it.
</P>
<P>
   The company has taken things a step further, placing the impact
of software piracy in your pocket. According to Microsoft, the use
of illegal software cost Georgia, for example, $157 million in
salaries and close to $23 million in tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The figures come from a study by the Redmond, Washington, branch
of International Planning &AMP; Research, a consulting firm for the
high-tech industry. IPR arrived at its tax estimates by multiplying
the typical number of software programs on a PC by the estimated
number of PCs shipped in Georgia in 1997, according to IPR's David
Fay, who worked on the study.
</P>
<P>
   IPR took that figure and subtracted the estimated number of
software applications software companies shipped in 1997. The
difference between the two figures was considered to be the number
of software programs illegally acquired. IPR took that number,
multiplied it by a typical retail price for software and used that
to determine the estimated losses in sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   But the estimated tax loss assumes the money not spent buying
software the legal way was not spent at all, Fay said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a valid assumption, said Donald Ratajczak, director
of Georgia State's economic forecasting center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is trying to say this is a big problem, and that's
valid,'' he said. ``But any numbers for individual states are total
estimates and it doesn't really wash one way or the other. Is there
anyone in their right mind who thinks the companies would be doing
less on software because of the pirating?''
</P>
<P>
   Ratajczak said there are legitimate moral issues involved with
the idea of using pirated software. But the economic impact is
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One wonders why Microsoft is worried about this. I continue to
wonder at who is making the corporate decisions at Microsoft: what
to put on email, how to approach the public. One wonders,'' he
said. ``They know how to market software, they sure don't know how
to market themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
