<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5339 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SC-GRAHAM-KOSO     04-27 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SC-GRAHAM-KOSOVO-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      GRAHAM LEADING THE OPPOSITION TO GROUND TROOPS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ron Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 27 -- South Carolina Republican Lindsey Graham
is leading the charge in Congress against deploying American ground
troops to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Graham is circulating a letter to House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., stating his position. He hopes to deliver the
letter by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly support President Clinton's policy against the use
of ground troops,'' the letter reads. ``Introducing American ground
troops in the middle of a bitter civil war is politically
unfeasible and militarily unwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, and some Democrats, are urging the Pentagon to
deploy ground forces to Yugoslavia as a way to increase pressure on
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and move the conflict toward
its end.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday afternoon, Mr. Graham's letter had signatures from
35 congressmen, including House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas,
and House Republican Conference Chairman J.C. Watts, R-Okla. DeLay
and Watts are the third- and fourth-ranking Republicans in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Republicans Charlie Norwood and Bob Barr, and South
Carolina Republicans Floyd Spence, Mark Sanford and Jim DeMint have
all signed.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Graham said Democrats have asked to join the letter, but he
wants it to be a vehicle for Republicans to let their leader,
Speaker Hastert, know where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   The letter claims a ground invasion would have three serious
pitfalls:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The possibility that coalition partners -- in particular
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greece, Macedonia and Germany -- would balk at escalation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The danger of casualties from facing a Yugoslav Army that
</P>
<P>
   &UR; would have near parity with NATO forces on the ground, as
</P>
<P>
   &UR; opposed to the NATO air campaign's vast superiority.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The threat of reigniting a Cold War relationship between the
</P>
<P>
   &UR; United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Mr. Graham warns the American military, ``which is
already stretched thin,'' would be overextended.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the introduction of American ground troops as part of an
invasion force in Yugoslavia, our capabilities will be put into
further question,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Graham began his campaign after returning from a
congressional delegation trip to the Balkan region. Members met
with U.S. and NATO commanders, American servicemen and Kosovar
Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I heard or saw in the Balkans convinced me that the
way to ease the suffering of the Kosovar Albanians is by placing
American troops on the ground,'' Mr. Graham said. ``Right now we
don't have a clear objective, strategy, or means for exiting the
conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
