</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE LAWMAKERS PASS BILL TO IMPROVE MILITARY TIES WITH U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The lower house of Parliament passed crucial legislation
Tuesday to improve military cooperation with the United States,
smoothing the way for Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's departure
Thursday for a meeting with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been pressing for the legislation, which
would make it easier for Japan's military to cooperate with the
United States in any security crisis in East Asia. Washington has
been concerned that if a crisis erupts _ a war with North Korea is
the one most mentioned _ Japan would wring its hands but do little
else.
</P>
<P>
   The new bills are expected to become law after being passed by
the less important upper house of Parliament, probably in May. They
will allow Japan to do more to back up U.S. military action by
sending ships to evacuate civilians abroad, supplying fuel and
spare parts, making airports and hospitals available to U.S. forces
and conducting rear-area search-and-rescue operations for U.S.
troops.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the new military guidelines, Japanese forces would
not fight alongside U.S. troops, and there are doubts about how
quickly and how fully Japan would respond in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines are deliberately ambiguous about whether they
apply to the Taiwan Strait, and some Japanese officials acknowledge
that if there is a war over Taiwan, they do not know whether Japan
would risk the wrath of China by allowing the United States to use
U.S. bases in Japan to intervene on behalf of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The three bills passed Tuesday were submitted by the government
to Parliament a year ago, but they have been controversial because
they run into sensitive questions about whether they are compatible
with Japan's ``peace constitution'' imposed after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was Washington that forced the peace constitution on
Japan, in recent years the positions have been reversed. Many
Japanese, particularly those on the left, are deeply pacifist and
want to stay out of any military crisis. But many U.S. officials
would like to see Japan play a greater military role to insure
regional security.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions and peace groups held rallies near the Parliament
building Tuesday, denouncing the legislation and warning that it
could make war more likely. China also criticized the bills, saying
they could harm regional security.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said Monday, after
the bills passed out of committee, ``We are confident that this
legislation, when finally enacted, will enable the U.S. and Japan
to respond quickly and flexibly to any contingencies that might
arise.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Japanese Prime Minister Obuchi presumably is delighted
that the bills passed in time to set a positive note for his visit
to Washington, to achieve this he had to sacrifice some key
elements. In particular, Obuchi agreed to lay aside one of the
essential parts of the bills _ Japan's willingness to take part in
ship inspections to enforce international sanctions _ because it
was controversial and was delaying passage of the other elements.
</P>
<P>
   A separate bill on ship inspections will be hammered out in the
coming weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
