<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0428-     04-27 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0428-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR RELOCATING KOSOVAR REFUGEES, NO ROOM AT THE CAMP
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-CLINTON-0428.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PESHKOPI, Albania _ Ten Kosovo refugees scrunched into a NATO
helicopter blanched Tuesday seconds before take-off, when three
armed soldiers flung open the door and jumped inside, armed to the
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   They were friendly fighters, it turned out, just Swiss guards in
green camouflage, with lightweight automatic rifles in their arms,
pistols on their hips and knives secured in belt holders. They were
defending the refugees, United Nations refugee agency operatives
and a couple of journalists. From what these NATO troops were
defending is uncertain, but clearly they could have done some
damage.
</P>
<P>
   That was the start of a largely misguided trip here to Peshkopi,
one of the towns in south Albania where UN relief agencies and
Albanian officials are trying to convince 100,000 refugees to
relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The departure point was Kukes, the northern border city where
refugees now are crammed in tents and tractors and homes. It is a
city that authorities fear may be a target of war any day, a
community under physical and social stress.
</P>
<P>
   The excursion sounded good -- a means to convince Kosovo refugee
leaders there are safe, comfortable places for their families to
move. And a few did seem convinced by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But others asked why they hadn't been shown actual places that
would be available to them and their townspeople, and wondered
where were the medical and food and general relief services so
important to people who have travelled in haste and in fear. They
may come around, but it will take some serious debate and
assurances.
</P>
<P>
   What they saw here was tempting. In a secondary school
dormitory, families each had a room with foam mattresses, shared
running water in communal bathrooms and were fed from a group
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard you are suffering much more in Kukes,'' said one
resident refugee. ``We are better off here.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions clearly were superior to the cold, wet tents in Kukes
surrounded by mud ponds from days of rain, where refugees use
smelly chemical toilets lined up outside and normally don't get hot
meals.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was no room for newcomers at the dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   On to an old hotel, which also had separate rooms for families
and plumbing, but it, too, seemed filled to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The third site was a thermal springs rehabilitation center that
not only had sunlit rooms and water, but boasted hot water.
Unfortunately, there was no space there, either.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee group finally did visit a family wanting to host
some Kosovars in need, but could accommodate only three or four.
Most of these families come in bunches of six to 16 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Finally they saw a spacious, clean empty house in a village
about four miles from the center of Peshkopi. They heard that more
such houses are available in other outlying villages, and more
families willing to open their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen these are places in good conditions, but is there
enough room for 6,000 people here?'' asked Rexhap Morina, who was
speaking on behalf of the total population of his tent camp in
Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel is very nice, but what about the places we will be
staying? You will send us to remote areas and then we'll need a
horse to ride,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The response came from Staffan DeMistura, the UN agency's
special envoy here and the man largely responsible for talking
Kurdistan refugees down from the mountains where they fled after
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we talk about survival,'' he said. ``You have to look at
things with reality. Look with your eyes, then compare what you
have in Kukes, then you compare with the situation in Kosovo. You
can't only look for the ideal situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Several refugees remained adamant that they did not want to move
so far from the border, where they are close to the family members
they left in Kosovo. Men there also can more easily link up again
with guerrilla independence fighters, once they have their families
settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this town was near to Kukes, I would bring my family,''
said Shaip Hadjari, who said he expected to go back into Kosovo to
fight. He also said there isn't enough assistance here, citing the
lack of medics and other aid supplied in Kukes by international
relief groups.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Dr. Avni Fejza said he was impressed with the
houses and the people who would be hosting relocated refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a positive view,'' he said. ``I will recommend they
come here. Compared to conditions in the tents, especially with bad
weather, I would say finding shelter here would be better.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
