u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RAPE-NYT &LR;      04-27 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN WOMAN TELLS OF SEXUAL ASSAULT BY SERBIAN SOLDIERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Her tormentor told her she was chosen for
her beauty. But it is her determination that sets her apart.
</P>
<P>
   Sherife Alickaj, 18, is one of a small group of ethnic Albanian
women willing to say openly that they were sexually assaulted by
Serbian soldiers during the chaotic exodus from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alickaj said the attack occurred a month ago when she, her
sister and four female friends studying at the University of
Pristina fled their apartment in Pristina after NATO bombing began.
Their landlord warned them that Serbian soldiers were expelling
people from nearby homes.
</P>
<P>
   She, her friend Teuta Elshani, 20, and a third woman, who
requested anonymity, gave matching accounts of the attack in
separate interviews. They said Serbian policemen stopped the group
at a nearby checkpoint and ordered them to produce identity cards.
</P>
<P>
   But the six young women hesitated. They were all from the
Drenica region in northern Kosovo, the birthplace of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, the guerrilla group battling Yugoslav forces, and
feared retaliation. They said they did not have their identity
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Several officers then ordered them into a nearby building and
searched their bags. Relieved when they were allowed to quickly
exit the building, a sense of dread fell over the group when two of
the policemen announced they would escort the young women back to
their apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Alickaj and the other two women said that after following
them into their living room, the policeman ordered the women to
turn over all the money in the house. When the women said they had
none, they tore a necklace from one young woman's throat, and
ordered all six to go into a small room.
</P>
<P>
   The living room had no curtains in the window, Ms. Elshani said.
``They were afraid someone would see us.''
</P>
<P>
   The policemen, saying they were conducting another search,
ordered all six women to take their clothes off. Five burst into
tears as they undressed. Ms. Alickaj maintained her composure and
tried to reason with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you do this?'' she asked. ``Don't you have sisters?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have sisters, but they don't want a republic,'' one
policeman retorted, referring to some Kosovar Albanians' demands
for an independent country.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the women were menstruating, the young women said, and
the police tried to force those who were not into another room.
When they began to scream, the police relented.
</P>
<P>
   One of the policemen then ordered five of the women to get
dressed and leave. Ms. Alickaj was told to stay with him in the
apartment. ``We are letting the other girls go because you are the
most beautiful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The five young women, escorted by the other policeman,
reluctantly left the apartment. The officer, Ms. Alickaj said, then
forced her to perform oral sex. ``I was lucky to not be raped in
another way because I was having my period,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The policeman hurriedly left the apartment after the attack, Ms.
Alickaj said, and she ran to her uncle's home. Her friends returned
to the apartment later that day, found Ms. Alickaj gone, and feared
her dead. The group reunited the following day and joined the
exodus to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights investigators and medical aid workers say that so
far relatively few women are reporting sexual assaults, but that
does not mean they are not occurring. The intense social stigma
that accompanies rape in Kosovar Albanian society, particularly for
women from small villages, may be leading victims to simply not
report attacks, they said. The process of coming to grips with the
trauma of such assaults can take weeks, they added, and crowded
refugee camps makes it difficult to discuss such matters with
strangers or even relatives in private.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vincent Iacopino, an expert on torture and rape who heads a
Physicians for Human Rights team surveying refugees here, said the
scope of the attacks may not be known for months.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too early to tell,'' he said. ``Some of the people who
are experiencing the worst may still be trapped inside Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Few other issues have become as highly charged as rape in the
former Yugoslavia. During the war in Bosnia, Serbian forces were
accused of systematically raping women as a deliberate tactic of
war, a particularly cruel means, human rights investigators said,
of terrorizing and demoralizing one's enemy. Bosnian Serbs were
accused of operating ``rape camps'' where Muslim women were held
captive and repeatedly assaulted by Serbian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But Bosnian Serb officials vehemently dismissed such charges as
propaganda. They accused women of inventing the attacks and
journalists and human rights investigators of exaggerating their
scope.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, NATO officials said they had evidence
corroborating allegations that the Hotel Karagac in the town of Pec
in Western Kosovo was being used as a ``rape camp'' where young
Albanian women were repeatedly assaulted by Serbian soldiers.
Reports of rape have also emerged from refugees fleeing a handful
of other towns, particularly refugees from western Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The International War Crimes Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia,
the first such body to classify rape as a war crime, has experts on
sexual assault. Investigators from the tribunal have been
interviewing refugees in Albania and Macedonia, but tribunal
officials declined to comment on the status of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   As she told her story last week, Ms. Alickaj spoke in a calm,
matter-of-fact tone. Her face flashed anger at times, but she
seemed determined to not be debilitated by what had occurred. She
freely gave her name and talked openly what the Serbian police had
done to her.
</P>
<P>
   But even for Ms. Alickaj, a young woman described by her friends
as unusually strong, admitting such an attack is both trying and
dangerous. Her female friends discussed the attack without
mentioning what happened to Ms. Alickaj until she arrived and
disclosed it herself.
</P>
<P>
   A male friend who knew of the attack angrily shooed away a
middle-aged man eavesdropping on the conversation. And in a seeming
effort to protect her, the young man blurted out in English ``he
made her do oral sex'' so it would not be understood by other
Albanians nearby.
</P>
</TEXT>
