<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, April 28. The NYT frontpage advisory, with
layout description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News
Service Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Washington) _ A Military Analysis: Despite
spending billions of dollars through the '90s on ships and aircraft
meant to give the American military rapid global reach, the
Pentagon's effort in the Balkans has still struggled to overcome
the obstacles inherent in moving military might hundreds or
thousands of miles. By Eric Schmitt and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Five weeks of increasingly
intense NATO bombing has still not been able to keep the Serbs
inside Kosovo from getting reinforcements or continuing offensive
operations against the ethnic Albanian population of the province,
NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark says. By Craig Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SPEED (Jenkintown, Pa.) _ Much-hyped and long-delayed,
high-speed Internet access is coming to the home, with predictions
that 10 to 16 million households will sign up by 2002. The
experience of the early users offers a glimpse at the Internet's
next frontier, where waiting is rare, dialing in is unnecessary,
and local communications monopolies are for the first time vying
for customers. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Ledeall on the
continuing investigation of the shootings as Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   or:
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SANDERS (Littleton, Colo.) _ A look at how William
Sanders, the Columbine teacher, died; what efforts were made and
what happened. By Jodie Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VOUCHERS _ First state-wide voucher program passed in
Florida _ a program that would give tax money to students at the
worst public schools to get a private or parochial education. By
Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-BRIBE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court unanimously
rejects the expansive legal theory behind an independent counsel's
prosecution of former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy and of those
who bestowed favors on him. Simply giving gifts to a federal
official, without any demonstrated connection to the official's
actions, does not violate the law, the court rules. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
