<SLUG> BC-UPS-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS continues overseas profit gains
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the heels of its first-ever annual profit from
international service, United Parcel Service kept up the momentum
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   International operating profit quadrupled from a year earlier,
contributing to a 42 percent jump in overall profit for the Sandy
Springs-based delivery giant.
</P>
<P>
   Net income climbed to $499 million in the January-March quarter,
up from $352 million a year ago. Revenue rose to $6.33 billion, vs.
$5.86 billion. UPS stock is owned by employees and doesn't trade
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits from international business rose to $44
million from $11 million, which UPS attributed to growth in express
delivery volume in both Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw impressive growth in our express products in most
corners of the world,'' said Chairman and Chief Executive Jim
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter gains also reflected UPS's efforts to expand
its e-commerce products, build overall volume and control costs,
Kelly said. Slightly lower fuel prices helped.
</P>
<P>
   UPS began a steady international expansion 11 years ago, mainly
by acquiring local companies. But it lost money on the expansion
until last year, when it posted international operating profits of
$56 million, reversing a $67 million loss in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   UPS now is well-positioned throughout much of Europe but faces
new challenges as national postal agencies offer competing
low-priced domestic service, most notably in Germany. UPS has
responded by de-emphasizing German domestic service and focusing on
cross-border European business.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter U.S. domestic package operating profit rose to
$765 million from $594 million on a 2.7 percent volume increase.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits from non-package operations fell to $25
million for the quarter from $35 million a year earlier, despite a
26.6 percent gain in revenue for the sector.
</P>
<P>
   Non-package operations includes such areas as truck leasing and
supply-chain management services offered by UPS Logistics Group.
Spokesman Norman Black, however, said the profit decline was due to
start-up expenses for unannounced new products and services rather
than ongoing business.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
