<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-RAFTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rafter relishes relaxed reputation
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The seventh of nine children, Patrick Rafter grew up
in a three-bedroom house on a farm in Australia. He slept in the
same room as his brothers, with five beds lined up in a row.
</P>
<P>
   And now that the fourth-ranked player on the ATP Tour can afford
a place or two of his own, he still can't always get the privacy he
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk behind him, you see the people staring at him,
so he tries to limit his eye contact,'' said Paul Kilderry, one of
Rafter's closest friends on the tour. ``In Australia, people come
up to him all the time, at restaurants and bars, and because he's
such a nice guy, he's never rude, so they think he likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, the No. 1 seed at this week's at the AT&AMP;T Challenge at
Atlanta Athletic Club, is most relaxed as just one of the mates
drinking a couple of beers after a match. He's never been fully at
ease with the money or attention that goes with a pair of U.S. Open
championships. His popularity grew beyond just the tennis public
two years back when People magazine featured him in their 10
Sexiest Men issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, who was scheduled to play Martin Rodriguez in a night
match Tuesday, prefers a lower profile. He donated $500,000 to a
hospital for terminally ill children after his 1997 U.S. Open
victory and didn't let anyone know about it. A brother squealed on
him some months later. Earlier this year, Rafter started a charity
in Sydney to combat drug addiction among teenagers and said there
was too much money in sports. Rafter tempered those remarks this
week, struggling to make sense of his unexpected fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably something I might take back to an extent,''
Rafter said. ``Only for this reason: We get paid the way we do
because we can't have a private life. You've got eyes on you all
the time. Giving up your life, your identity, is a big price to
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   At tournaments, however, Rafter enjoys the public affection. He
made extra time this week to sign autographs and meet children in a
local tennis program for at-risk youth. His status as a sex symbol
embarrasses him at times, but he concedes, ``I quite like that.
It's a fun thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's really nothing new, only magnified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always sort of there, going back to '94 and '95,''
Rafter said. ``I just sort of knew that if I ever did well,
something like that might happen. Tennis has always had a glamour
boy, but they didn't have one at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilderry said jokingly, ``It's amazing how much better you look
when you win the U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's friends have been known to search his bags for notes
and mail from admiring women, Kilderry said. Once at a tournament
in the Netherlands, one of the players found a letter from a woman
who'd left her phone number. The player called her and left a
message, saying he was Rafter, and gave her Rafter's number at his
hotel. The naive Rafter returned the call.
</P>
<P>
   Kilderry, who wouldn't reveal the prankster, said,''There would
be a number of guys who'd do it and get great pleasure out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter says he's not given to that sort of temptation, adding,
``I never, ever get distracted from my tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter has been dating Lara Feltham, an Australian model, for
more than a year and credits their stable relationship with
enhancing his tennis, especially last summer when he surged to four
hardcourt titles, culminating in his second U.S. Open win.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a little bit older, 28,'' said Rafter, who's 26. ``I've
dated some younger girls where it's been an ordeal and it can't
stand the test of touring. I don't want a lot of complications
going on in my head while I'm on the tennis court. It's a maturity
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Feltham occasionally joins Rafter on tour, but he usually
doesn't have an entourage, not even a coach. His brother Steve
manages his business affairs from Australia, and brother Peter
joins him for the hectic Grand Slam fortnights. Usually, you can
just find Rafter with his Aussie friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the other top guys stick with their own,'' fellow
Aussie Jason Stoltenberg said. ``Pat will go to dinner with the
other players. He's kept his feet on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
