<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-LOGGING-975&AMP;AD     04-27 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LOGGING-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO FACES THREAT OF DEFORESTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EJIDO PINO GORDO, Mexico _ The shepherds of this remote mountain
settlement till the earth behind oaken plows and grind their corn
between smooth stones. They have no television, telephones or
electricity. Yet by one standard, the village enjoys vast wealth:
It is surrounded by magnificent forests.
</P>
<P>
   So when outsiders recently bulldozed a logging road and began
applying chainsaws to hundreds of 200-year-old trees, villagers
panicked. Men, women and children walked for 36 hours across a
canyon to board buses for the Chihuahua state capital, where they
held a sit-in at the governor's palace this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want our forests felled,'' a Raramuri-speaking Indian
leader, Francisco Ramos, told authorities through an interpreter in
negotiations that followed. ``We didn't plant the trees, God did,
to collect water from the rain and give homes to the animals. The
trees are not our property. We're just taking care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials were stunned by the Indian protest and the
news coverage it prompted, and Chihuahua state officials recently
announced a halt to the illegal logging around the village in the
Sierra Madre, about 850 miles northwest of Mexico City, at least
for now. But a federal official denied that any decision had been
made. Conservationists said they hoped for an environmental
victory, but it was only one skirmish in a war for Mexico's
beleaguered forests.
</P>
<P>
   All across Mexico _ from Chihuahua in the north, to the central
woodland preserves that are wintering grounds for North America's
monarch butterflies, to the tropical jungles of Chiapas in the
south _ timberlands are being cleared at a devastating rate.
Poachers are even cutting the few surviving forest preserves around
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deforestation is pushing us toward environmental collapse,''
said Sen. Adolfo Aguilar Zinser, who has proposed legislation to
create a National Forestry Commission with broad powers to confront
what he calls an emergency. ``The government should declare a
national forestry disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The country has destroyed half its forests in four decades and,
unless the devastation slows, will finish them off in half a
century, Aguilar said in an interview. Mexico's forests still cover
an area larger than California. But since it is mountainous, Mexico
needs extensive timberlands to capture rain water and prevent
flooding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, wildfires that sent smoke clouds drifting into
Florida and Texas focused American attention on the crisis. But far
more trees are lost every year in Mexico to timber clearing or to
the cultivation of crops than are lost to fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illegal logging is out of control,'' said Leticia Merino, an
anthropologist at a branch of the Autonomous National University in
Cuernavaca, south of Mexico City, who is studying timber poaching.
</P>
<P>
   Some trees are felled by poor farmers who use the timber to
build homes or to sell to firewood vendors. More destruction is
caused by companies who engage in large-scale illegal logging,
often in collaboration with corrupt officials, she said. Sometimes
drug traffickers muscle in, using sawmill operations to launder
drug profits.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican forest policy has been marked by zigzags. In the 1930s,
land reform gave 9,000 Indian and farming communities control over
80 percent of the country's forests, a higher percentage than
anywhere else in the world. The communities, called ejidos, took on
the role played by the Forest Service in the United States:
fighting fires, planting trees and managing the harvest of timber.
</P>
<P>
   But successive governments encouraged thousands of rural poor
people to clear forests for the grazing of cattle. The most
damaging of such projects were abandoned in the last decade, but
one farm program still pays rural people an annual subsidy for each
acre of forest cleared for farming.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Mexico's entire budget for all forest-related
programs totals only about $90 million, Aguilar said.
Responsibility for enforcing forestry laws across Mexico lies with
just a few dozen inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Forestry laws passed in recent years encourage ejido communities
to divide forests into plots and to sign timber-harvesting deals
with logging companies. But many forest communities that sign
timber contracts end up in peonage, owing increasing sums to
logging companies each year, despite the harvest of entire forests.
</P>
<P>
   In one Chihuahua village, for example, a logging company
harvested 103 million cubic feet of lumber in 1992, yet at year's
end the village owed $16,000 more than when the year began,
according to village records.
</P>
<P>
   David Barton Bray, an environmental studies professor at Florida
International University in Miami, said that 17 million people
still live in Mexico's woodlands. Policies should help them earn a
livelihood from the forests even as they manage and conserve them,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many peasant and indigenous people, forests are not only
an economic resource, but also a spiritual wellspring and a source
of ethnic identity,'' Bray said. Such is the case of the Chihuahua
Indians who speak a language called Raramuri. They are often called
Tarahumara by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forests are fundamental to their cosmic vision,'' said Isela
Gonzalez Diaz, an anthropologist who helped advise the Pino Gordo
villagers during the recent negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Pino Gordo lies next to Coloradas de los Chavez, a rival village
of Spanish-speaking people. Coloradas leaders are privatizing their
village forests, and last year the federal government issued a
permit allowing the village to sign contracts with a logging
consortium.
</P>
<P>
   But the loggers soon jumped the boundaries of Coloradas, cutting
roads into Pino Gordo's forests and felling trees there. Pino Gordo
villagers complained to authorities, but got no response until the
recent protest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the negotiations, one Indian leader asked why the
government would issue a permit to Coloradas de los Chavez to cut
forests that are habitat for endangered fauna, including the
thick-billed parrot and the jaguarundi wildcat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to restrict the cutting of forests wherever there
is fauna in danger, we'd risk being in the same situation as the
United States, where most forest lands are now off limits to
logging,'' responded Leonel Iglesias, an official from the federal
Environment Ministry based in Chihuahua. ``Mexico has economic
needs that are different than the developed countries. We need
greater flexibility in our forest management.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities insisted repeatedly that there was no illegal
logging in the Pino Gordo region and that the Indians were simply
confused about their village boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   But as the talks proceeded, journalists and environmentalists
who traveled to Pino Gordo found men with chainsaws and hydraulic
winches felling trees on Pino Gordo's hillsides. One logger,
Curberto Bustillo Acosta, said each man in his crew had been
cutting 200 trees a day in the area.
</P>
<P>
   As the Indian protest drew news coverage, government officials
eventually agreed to send surveyors and other state and federal
officials to Pino Gordo. By the time they arrived, the loggers had
fled. But, seeing hillsides covered with stumps, state officials
said they had ordered the suspension of logging that had already
stopped. Federal officials said they were still studying the
dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
