<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, May 2,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-HOUSES-EXPENSES (Undated) _ There is no other company like
it, and yet the Metropolitan Opera may end up a model for the
future. In the season just closed and the one to come, the Met
continues a practice of self-sufficiency and free enterprise that
is largely unfamiliar to the international opera world. But now we
see the free-spending ways of government-subsidized opera houses
being strenuously curbed. Indeed, the adventurous, the innovative
and sometimes the reckless are no longer automatically underwritten
by generous European ministries of culture. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILMMAKERS-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Although the University of
Southern California opened the nation's first film program in 1929,
the Hollywood studios provided their own educational system until
the 1960s: would-be directors worked their way through the ranks
from entry-level jobs. The path is still followed today. But with
the collapse of the studio system, film schools began to take over
the training of young filmmakers. Today, the most common route to a
directing career starts in the academy, with a master's degree in
filmmaking. By Margalit Fox.
</P>
<P>
   CALIGULA-FILM (Undated) _ This summer, the movie that became
infamous for going too far will go even further _ about 12 minutes
further, according to its producer, Bob Guccione. ``Caligula,''
called by Newsweek ``a two-and-one-half hour cavalcade of
depravity,'' will now run nearly two-and-three-quarters hours. By
Ted Loos.
</P>
<P>
   FLOCKHART-FILM (Los Angeles) _ There were those in the team of
British hair and makeup experts hired to give her the fairy-tale
makeover for Michael Hoffman's adaptation of ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' who expected nothing good from Calista Flockhart. And they
told her so. Cast as the lovesick Helena, the television star was
going to pop over from America and proceed to be finicky, imperious
and exasperatingly unaware of just how horribly she was mangling
the Bard's words. Hoffman's version of ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' which opens May 14, is contemporary in spirit while being
conscientious about theme, text and Elizabethan diction. By Margy
Rochlin.
</P>
<P>
   NOTTING-HILL-FILM (Hollywood) _ Surveying the summer-movie
landscape, Universal studios had at first intended to open its
high-profile romance ``Notting Hill,'' starring Julia Roberts and
Hugh Grant, a month after the release, on May 19, of George Lucas's
``Star Wars: Episode One _ The Phantom Menace,'' one of the most
anticipated films in years. But then Universal executives sat down,
took a second look and decided on a more innovative, if riskier,
plan: move ``Notting Hill,'' which is about a Hollywood star and a
British bookshop owner who fall in love, right into the eye of the
storm. Now, it will open only one week after the new ``Star Wars,''
when frenzy over the science-fiction film is likely to be at a
peak. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SELL (Undated) _ How quaint to recall the days when
doubting a movie's honesty meant wondering whether its hero was
standing on a box. Now there are more important things to question:
whether the box is virtual or real, and whether it contains
anything that the film might want to sell. With the growing
prevalence of the many-tentacled corporate concept known as
vertical integration, we've seen ever more ingenious ways to
undermine what appears on screen. Would-be hits on the summer
horizon offer an invitation to visit the Web site, buy the toys,
wear the T-shirt, hear the soundtrack and play the video game. Oh,
if there's time left over, see the movie too. By Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   HUGH-GRANT-FILMS (London) _ Is Hugh Grant, 38, the very model of
a modern English gentleman? He certainly seemed that way in ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral,'' a hugely successful confection of a film
kept afloat, in large part, by his bachelor character's diffident
charm, self-deprecating wit and endearing sense of chronic personal
embarrassment. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   DEEP-BLUE-SEA-FILM (Hollywood) _ For ``Deep Blue Sea,'' the film
director Renny Harlin has assembled more than 300 tracks of
recorded sounds, so that an essentially noiseless sea creature can
chew through metal and flesh _ and, with any luck, the summer box
office after the film's July 30 release _ in deafening Dolby
digital. By Bruce Newman.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SEQUELS (Undated) _ The days of the sequel are numbered. Or
rather, Roman numeraled. ``Lethal Weapon,'' the Mel Gibson vehicle
that went from zero to IV in 11 years, will have no '99 model.
Rocky Balboa's five-bout film career ended in 1990, after a savage
critical beating that left him, and moviegoers, with collateral
brain damage. Arnold Schwarzenegger, whose most famous film line
is, ``I'll be back,'' won't be: The Terminator's term limit was
two. Thank goodness, because the sequel and prequel have become
cinematic Nyquil, putting audiences to sleep with their metronomic
monotony. By Franz Lidz and Steve Rushin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PICKER-MUSIC (Undated) _ It was a signal moment in the rebirth
of tonality. When the curtain rose on Tobias Picker's first opera,
``Emmeline,'' in 1996, the orchestra conjured an atmosphere of grim
foreboding, circling endlessly around a single, brooding chord. As
if to emphasize his immersion in the dark realm of B flat minor,
Picker, 45, prefaced the score with a device long scorned by
modernists: a key signature. Picker's embrace of tonality, though
particularly unambiguous, is hardly unique. Today, it seems, every
composer is eager to be portrayed as a lapsed modernist, newly
liberated from the shackles of Serialism. On Friday evening, the
Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center in New York offers the
premiere of Picker's Cello Suite, performed by the cellist Lynn
Harrell and the pianist Anne-Marie McDermott at Alice Tully Hall.
By K. Robert Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   REVUELTAS-MUSIC (Undated) _ In the calendar of saints, the last
day of the year belongs to St. Sylvester, and it was on that day in
the last year of the 1800s that the Mexican composer Silvestre
Revueltas was born. Now, several months before his centenary, Sony
Classical has released an exhilarating Revueltas album, with
Esa-Pekka Salonen conducting the Los Angeles Philharmonic and its
New Music Group, and other new releases round out the picture. By
Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JUNKYARD-SCULPTOR (New York) _ Ms. Nancy Rubins, 46, a sculptor
who creates monumental works out of oversize junkyard debris is in
the Rolodex of certain suppliers of airplane parts. They call her
when something special comes in, like a dismembered fuselage, a
severed wing or a battered engine. For her show that opened
Saturday at the Paul Kasmin Gallery, Ms. Rubins has created an
extravagant aluminum-and-stainless-steel sculpture out of a few
thousand pounds of colorful airplane parts, as well as 600 pounds
of wire. By Elizabeth Hayt.
</P>
<P>
   MATRIX-FILM-ARCH (Undated) _ Despite fortune cookie dialogue and
a dubious Nietschean subtext, ``The Matrix'' is a film that
deserves to be a classic. It will certainly become one for those
who value the power of sci-fi movies to crystallize moments of
urban sensibility. ``Metropolis,'' ``Alphaville,'' ``The Tenth
Victim'' and ``Blade Runner'' are also classics of this genre. By
Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   SCULPTURE-FURNITURE (New York) _ The Public Art Fund, a
nonprofit organization that supports projects around New York, is
backing an independent curator Amy Wolf's, ``Comfort Zone:
Furniture by Artists,'' an engaging exhibition of sculpture that is
also furniture. The show remains on view at PaineWebber building
through June 25. The exhibit includes pieces designed by 36 artists
over the last 60 years. By Paula Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOP-40-RADIO (Los Angeles) _ ``American Top 40 With Casey
Kasem'' has been on the air, under slightly different titles but
with virtually the same format, for nearly 29 years. Currently, the
four-hour-long show, heard in most markets on Saturday or Sunday
morning, is broadcast on more than 350 stations nationwide and
heard at any one point in his show by an audience that averages
approximately 1.1 million listeners over age 12. By Andy Meisler.
</P>
