<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5372 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-BRIBE-NYT &LR;      04-27 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-BRIBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT REBUFFS INDEPENDENT COUNSEL'S BRIBERY DEFINITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday unanimously rejected
the expansive legal theory behind an independent counsel's
prosecution of former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy and of those
who bestowed favors on Espy.
</P>
<P>
   Simply giving gifts to a federal official, without any
demonstrated connection between the gifts and the official's
actions, does not violate the law against illegal gratuities, the
court ruled in a case involving a California agricultural
cooperative that was convicted under the gratuity law of giving
Espy tennis tickets, luggage and other gifts worth some $5,900.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the federal appeals court in Washington overturned
the conviction of Sun-Diamond Growers of California. The justices
Tuesday affirmed that decision in a ruling on an appeal brought by
Independent Counsel Donald Smaltz.
</P>
<P>
   Espy himself, who was acquitted by a federal jury in December,
no longer had a direct legal stake in the case. But coming less
than five months after the acquittal of the principal target of
Smaltz's four-year, $17 million effort, the court's pointed ruling
nonetheless had symbolic as well as practical importance, marking
an effective end to a high-profile investigation that was a
lightning rod for criticism of the independent counsel statute.
</P>
<P>
   Most lawyers on Smaltz's staff have left, and he announced
months ago that his work was largely complete after having
collected more than $12 million in fines, penalties and
restitution. Sun-Diamond itself remains convicted on other charges,
including mail fraud and illegal campaign contributions, that were
not part of the Supreme Court case.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's decision was more than a historical footnote. The
ambiguities in the gratuity statute, which dates to 1962, have
confused courts and prosecutors for years. Among those actively
interested in the court's interpretation of what it means to give,
offer, or promise ``anything of value'' to a public official were
lobbyists, who viewed the independent counsel's broad
interpretation as a threat to the normal conduct of their business.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Buffone, who filed a brief for the American League of
Lobbyists on Sun-Diamond's behalf, praised the court's decision in
an interview Tuesday and said that lobbyists would no longer ``have
to look over their shoulder at an aggressive independent counsel
who can pursue criminal prosecution in this politically sensitive
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffone noted that aside from the gratuity statute, ``there are
a lot of regulations out there,'' a fact that played an essential
role in Justice Antonin Scalia's opinion for the court. Scalia said
that in light of the numerous other laws and regulations
``littering this field,'' it was clear that Congress knew how to
write, and often had written, ``precisely targeted prohibitions''
involving gifts to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``Given that reality, a statute in this field that
can linguistically be interpreted to be either a meat axe or a
scalpel should reasonably be taken to be the latter. Absent a text
that clearly requires it, we ought not expand this one piece of the
regulatory puzzle so dramatically as to make many other pieces
misfits.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the federal bribery statute, which requires proof of a
quid pro quo, the more open-ended gratuity statute prohibits the
gift or promise of ``anything of value'' to a public official ``for
or because of any official act performed or to be performed by such
public official.''
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of Sun-Diamond's trial in 1996, Judge Ricardo
Urbina of U.S. District Court in Washington accepted Smaltz's view
that the law did not require proof of a connection between the gift
and any specific act. It was enough to show that the cooperative
gave Espy gifts ``simply because he held public office'' or to
build a reservoir of good will, Urbina instructed the jury.
</P>
<P>
   In overturning Sun-Diamond's conviction, the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit said the instructions
reflected an erroneous view of the law. ``The giver must intend
either to reward some past concrete official act or acts, or to
enhance the likelihood of some future act or acts,'' the appeals
court said.
</P>
<P>
   In the decision Tuesday, United States vs. Sun-Diamond, No.
98-131, the court agreed. Scalia said that the law's ``insistence
upon an `official act,' carefully defined, seems pregnant with the
requirement that some particular official act be identified and
proved.'' Although Sun-Diamond's members had interests in two
regulatory issues before the Agriculture Department, Justice Scalia
noted that the prosecutor made no effort to link the gifts to any
particular action that Sun-Diamond wanted to encourage or reward.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Smaltz's broad view would produce ``peculiar
results,'' like potentially criminalizing ``a high school
principal's gift of a school baseball cap to the secretary of
education, by reason of his office, on the occasion of the latter's
visit to the school.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling applies beyond the independent counsel context to the
government's general prosecutorial authority under the statute.
While Smaltz's office handled its own appeal, the Justice
Department filed a brief as a friend of the court, supporting his
position in most although not all respects. Under the department's
interpretation, the law would be violated by a gift motivated by
``the recipients capacity to exercise governmental power or
influence in the donor's favor,'' without requiring proof of
connection to a particular official act. The court Tuesday rejected
that formulation as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by his office Tuesday, Smaltz said he was
``disappointed that the court chose to adopt a rule governing the
gratuity statute that, in my view, allows too much latitude to
those who would attempt to buy governmental favor.'' However, he
said he was glad the court ``has now articulated a single,
understandable rule'' in place of the confusion that had previously
existed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
