<SLUG> BC-WARPOWERSVOTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS TO TAKE RARE VOTE ON DECLARING WAR, BUT IT'S EXPECTED TO
FAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time since World War II, Congress
will vote on a declaration of war Wednesday. But the showdown is
likely to bear little resemblance to the historic session after
Japan's surprise attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by a maverick Republican, the House will take up a
simple, one-paragraph resolution declaring war on the government of
Yugoslavia. Although the vote comes five weeks after U.S. warplanes
began bombing the Balkan nation, no one expects it to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Even the resolution's sponsor, Rep. Tom Campbell of California,
plans to vote against it. But Campbell contends that Congress has a
constitutional obligation to take a stand on the commitment of U.S.
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at war in Kosovo. We're bombing now, and I believe it
won't be long before ground troops are sent in,'' he said. ``The
Constitution gives this decision to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell forced House action by invoking the War Powers Act, a
Vietnam-era law that was intended to give Congress more say over
the use of troops in conflicts that fall short of an all-out war.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring pleas from House leaders who had hoped to avoid the
issue, Campbell will also force a vote on an alternative resolution
directing President Clinton to end U.S. involvement in the NATO
bombing campaign. The withdrawal resolution is also expected to
fail because even some of Clinton's harshest critics are reluctant
to pull the plug on a military operation that is well under way.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, after weeks of criticizing Clinton's handling of
the conflict in Yugoslavia, the Republican-controlled House will,
in effect, endorse it. House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving,
said lawmakers have little choice now that U.S. forces are in the
air against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choices are too stark,'' Armey said of the declare-war or
get-out options. ``The president is commander in chief, and the
president, working with NATO, has made this commitment. We try to
be respectful of that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's critics do not want to take any step that gives
comfort to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, Clinton's
supporters do not want to take the giant step of declaring war.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has declared war only five times in the nation's
history: the War of 1812 against Britain, the war with Mexico in
1846, the war with Spain in 1898 and World Wars I and II.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't ready to make a final statement at this point,''
said Rep. Martin Frost of Dallas, who presided over a closed-door
meeting of House Democrats on the topic late yesterday. ``It's
clear that the majority in Congress is willing to be patient and
give the military a chance to show what it can do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, lawmakers in both parties seem to agree that
Clinton should not use ground troops without congressional
permission. Armey predicted that Congress will approve a third
proposal Wednesday that would require Clinton to come to Congress
before resorting to ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has repeatedly said that he does not believe ground
troops will be needed to achieve his goal of ending Yugoslav
aggression against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. The president also
opposes the declaration of war, arguing that it is unnecessary and
would only complicate the NATO effort.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, the last time Congress declared war, Franklin Roosevelt
rallied a stunned nation the day after Pearl Harbor with a speech
to Congress predicting that the sneak attack would ``live in
infamy.'' Minutes after the speech, the House and Senate approved a
war declaration with only one dissenting vote.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the issues are not nearly so clear-cut for most
members of Congress. Rep. Joe Barton, R-Ennis, said he may vote to
declare war even though he opposed the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I vote for it, it's not because I want to go to war. It's
because we are already bombing,'' he said. ``Now that we are
bombing, if we cannot stop it, we ought to at least acknowledge
that's what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
