<P>
   The New York Times is planning 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ The military commander of NATO
acknowledged Tuesday that five weeks of intensive bombing had
failed to reduce the size of the Serbian force in Kosovo or its
operations against Albanians there. Addressing a press briefing,
Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO commander, insisted that the bombing had
crippled the air defenses of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, and was gradually wearing away the resources Yugoslav
army and police forces needed to carry on their attacks. But Clark
said persistently unfavorable weather conditions had kept the NATO
bombing from having full effect on the Serb forces on the ground in
Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton ordered today a
call up 33,102 reservists to serve up to nine months of active
military duty in the Kosovo air campaign, the biggest military call
up since the Persian Gulf War. Other Developments. By Elizabeth
Becker.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Washington) _ Despite spending billions of
dollars through the 1990s on ships and aircraft meant to give the
American military rapid, global reach, the Pentagon's war effort in
the Balkans has still struggled to overcome the obstacles inherent
in moving military might hundreds or thousands of miles. By Eric
Schmitt and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments on Kosovo: Strobe Talbott,
the deputy secretary of state, and Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian
special envoy, hold talks. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Developments in the Yugoslav
capital: At least two Yugoslav officials are talking about a
negotiated deal; one says he hopes a framework could emerge in a
week or so. The Red Cross says the three U.S. POW's are in
``satisfactory'' condition. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Dateline to kum) _ More refugees cross the
frontier into Macedonia; 3,000 on Tuesday, 11,000 in the last five
days. There is no room for them in the existing camps, so the
refugees are being accommodated in sleeping bags under plastic
sheets. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ A month of war in Europe has already
brought deep changes to the continent, awakening a new sense of
European patriotism, rekindling tensions over ``American
imperialism'' and reviving the sagging fortunes of some leaders. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
