<SLUG> BC-THEATER-WEST-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDONAGH'S GRUESOME COMEDY MAKES A SPLASH ON BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The Lonesome West,'' a perverse battle of two Irish
Catholic brothers, made a fierce late entry Tuesday night into a
Broadway season filled with Irish and British imports. It's a
bleakly funny return to the boggy turf of playwright Martin
McDonagh's ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane.''
</P>
<P>
   The black comedy at the Lyceum Theatre joins fellow Irish native
Conor McPherson's ghost-haunted ``The Weir,'' British phenom
Patrick Marber's sex comedy ``Closer'' and senior statesman David
Hare's ruminative ``Amy's View'' as possible contenders for a 1999
Tony Award. Hare, for good measure, is performing ``Via Dolorosa,''
a monologue about the Middle East, on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonesome West'' is situated firmly in the remote Irish village
of Leenane. Rain is so commonplace here it falls in great long
sheets through the second act and never gets mentioned. The
characters are too busy with their own private storms to notice.
</P>
<P>
   McDonagh turns his eye and faultless ear for insult on a pair of
consummate losers, Coleman and Valene Connor. They're played to
rank perfection by Maeliosa Stafford and Brian F. O'Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   One of the brothers has just killed their father, and it wasn't
an accident. Coleman didn't like what his dad said about his hair,
so he shot him. Valene has blackmailed his brother out of the
inheritance, which consists of the dreary cottage they share and
very little else.
</P>
<P>
   Father Welsh (David Ganly) is the brothers' hopeless spiritual
keeper. ``God has no jurisdiction in this parish,'' he laments,
between belts of home-distilled spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Despair is like the rain, unrelenting, and McDonagh is merciless
about the Catholic church's failure to relieve it. The brothers'
violent slapstick curdles into a parody of confession and
absolution in the second act. It's a Laurel and Hardy routine run
wildly, theologically amok. Father Welsh is the sacrificial lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lonesome West'' lacks the devilish flair for plot the
playwright flashed in ``Beauty Queen.'' But it does have some
hilarious dialogue, a more deeply subversive outlook and
distinctive McDonagh devices from the earlier play, including a
crucial letter and a gruesome hand-scalding scene. This one,
fittingly, involves a pot of molten plastic saints. The church is
in dangerous meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Hynes directed, with the same appetite for humor and shock
she brought to ``Beauty Queen.'' Hynes and two excellent Broadway
casts have helped make Leenane the unforgettable Irish capital of
family murder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
