A5385 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-DISABILITY-HNS &LR;      04-27 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-DISABILITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WEIGHS WHO SHOULD BE CONSIDERED DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court struggled Tuesday with the
unsettled issue of whether a law protecting disabled workers from
discrimination also covers someone whose physical problem is kept
in check through medication.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the first of three this week being considered by the
court that will eventually define who is protected under the 1990
Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA): the severely disabled, or
millions more who take medicine or use contact lenses, hearing aids
and other medical aids that allow them to lead normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   The law forbids job discrimination against ``a qualified
individual with a disability.'' It defines disability as a
``physical or mental impairment that substantially limits one or
more major life activities.'' It includes among the disabled those
``regarded as having such an impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   The law has been used for removing physical barriers in public
places and for opening job opportunities to people with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite simply, my client has a disability, and he was fired
because of it,'' said Stephen McAllister, representing a mechanic
named Vaughn Murphy, who was dismissed from his job for medical
reasons because of high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   With medication, Murphy is able to reduce his blood pressure
from a dangerous 260/160 to 186/124.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1994, Murphy began working for United Parcel Service
in Topeka, Kan., and was required to drive to different locations
to work on trucks. A month later, a nurse noticed on his medical
chart that Murphy's blood pressure was too high under Department of
Transportation regulations, which requires commercial truck drivers
to have blood pressures below 160/90. UPS fired him, saying his
condition made him unfit to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming his high blood pressure constituted a disability,
Murphy sued UPS under the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   Although a federal district court and appeals court rejected
Murphy's suit, other lower federal courts have accepted similar
claims, giving the Supreme Court an impetus to clarify the scope of
the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   Congress did not list the precise conditions or diseases meant
to be covered by the act. Also left ambiguous was whether a person
would be covered by the law before or after medication or other
corrective measures, such as eyeglasses, were taken into account.
Those issues helped trigger a flood of lawsuits involving the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister urged the justices to rule that the effects of
medication should not be considered when deciding whether a
person's medical condition qualifies as a disability.
</P>
<P>
   But his position drew a number harsh responses from several
justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we accept your argument, why shouldn't we look at it as if
every person who needs glasses to see is disabled?'' Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor asked.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 152 million Americans are nearsighted enough to
need glasses, according to the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister said that these people should be considered disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia retorted, ``It's very comforting to think
that most Americans can claim a disability ... (but) it just
doesn't square with what Congress intended with the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen Breyer told McAllister that if his argument is
accepted, ``I don't see how to get (the ADA) to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department attorney James A. Feldman joined McAllister,
arguing that medication and medical aids, such as glasses, should
not be considered when deciding whether a person has a disability.
</P>
<P>
   But UPS lawyer William Kilberg said that Congress meant for the
law to include the use of medication and protect those using it but
still suffering serious conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress was looking at epilepsy, diabetes and other
conditions that require medication but that still leave
difficulties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kilberg said the only reason UPS fired Murphy in 1994 was that
his blood pressure exceeded federal regulations for drivers.
``There is simply no evidence that UPS ever regarded Mr. Murphy as
disabled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing with Kilberg's argument, Scalia added, ``It's hard to
understand how UPS is at fault for following the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The other ADA cases, to be heard on Wednesday, were brought by:
</P>
<P>
   _ Karen Sutton and Kimberly Hinton, twins licensed as pilots in
Colorado for commuter airlines who sought to apply for jobs with
United Airlines but were rebuffed because they are very
near-sighted and were unable to meet United's requirement for
uncorrected vision of at least 20/100.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hallie Kirkingburg, an Oregon truck driver who was fired when
his employer, supermarket chain Albertson's, discovered that he is
legally blind in one eye. He argues he has an unblemished 20-year
driving record and that his brain has learned to compensate for his
vision deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Employers have won 92 percent of the 700 ADA cases resolved in
court from 1992 to 1997, according to a study by the American Bar
Association. But now many employers fear that if the workers win in
the current Supreme Court cases, another slew of lawsuits will
follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
