<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5389 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CANES-ROBERTS-BOS     04-27 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CANES-ROBERTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERTS RETURN TAKES HIM TO 'CANES LEADERSHIP ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He's vague about the date. Why would he want to
remember it, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 1994, I think,'' said Gary Roberts. ``Or was it '93? It
might have been '92.''
</P>
<P>
   The details are another matter. They're indelibly etched in his
mind, like the surgical scars on his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Rouse in Toronto hit me from behind,'' said Roberts. ``I
had just dumped the puck in and was headed to the bench for a line
change. That started it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. Actually, it merely brought to Roberts's
horrified attention a degenerative condition known as foraminal
stenosis. It's a constricting of the nerves in the neck that
eventually can cause muscles to atrophy and severely limit arm
movement _ a rather dire impediment for a certified NHL sniper who
had produced 50- and 40-goal seasons with the Calgary Flames. The
condition wound up hounding Roberts into retirement, an ordeal he
somehow overcame by getting a second hockey life with the Carolina
Hurricanes, for whom he has proven an inspiring force in this
Eastern Conference quarterfinal series against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rouse is not the villain of the piece. The damage to
Roberts's neck was the cumulative result of years of abuse, the
punishing hits that are the price an NHL goal scorer pays. But that
hit remains a handy reference point, and Roberts never will forget
the feeling _ the lack of it, actually _ that night in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to cut the uniform off me,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He mentions this as a matter of fact, but it also could serve as
a metaphor for his lingering miseries. Roberts is a fitness zealot,
as his coach, Paul Maurice, reverently attests: ``What can you say
about Gary Roberts and his work ethic that a man can go that hard
all the time? You can see the work he puts in in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   But that fanatic desire never to shed the uniform ultimately
betrayed Roberts. To relieve the condition, he underwent operations
on both sides of his neck, surgeries he considers successful _
except that the patient didn't recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing for it is rest,'' said Roberts. ``But you know
how it is _ you end the season, you start preparing for the next
one, then you're back playing. I never really gave it time to heal.
I tried to come back to play 12 weeks after both surgeries, which
was the dumbest thing I could do and the dumbest thing the Calgary
Flames could have let me do.''
</P>
<P>
   So the symptoms, and the consequences, persisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burners,'' said Roberts, who has become a reluctant expert
both in technical and layman's language involving the neck.
``Football players get them. The problem for me was that they'd
last three or four minutes at a time and go all the way down my
arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Which rendered the arms useless for alarming stretches. It
reached the point where Roberts would raise an arm to shoulder
level _ and watch it flop lifelessly to his side. By the 1994
playoffs, a seven-game series against Vancouver, Roberts was
wearing a neck collar and his wife had to cut his food. She
expressed wonder _ and concern _ that he could continue to play
with such a condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her they said it wouldn't get any worse,'' said
Roberts. ``Of course, they didn't tell me it wouldn't get any
better.''
</P>
<P>
   By June 1996, after having played only eight and 35 games the
previous two seasons, Roberts finally got the message. Just turned
30, the left wing announced his retirement, realizing that his
problem no longer involved merely controlling a wrist shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to lead a normal life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He got a bonus. Five months after he quit hockey, a friend put
him in touch with Michael Leahy, a Colorado Springs chiropractor
who advocated a treatment called active release technique that
involved tearing down scar tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a week,'' said Roberts, ``I was feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   There was still much room for improvement, and a physical
therapist associated with Leahy, Charles Poliquin, provided it by
making Roberts his personal project.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked with me every day from Nov. 21 to Sept. 1 the next
year,'' said Roberts. ``He taught me how to train, how to eat
properly, everything. He basically took a year out of his life to
work with me in Phoenix. I had decided to hide out there because I
figured everyone would have known if I was rehabbing in Calgary.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, Roberts remembers, there was a feeling in his
spine he hadn't experienced since before the Rouse hit _ shivers of
anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the gym one day,'' said Roberts, ``and Charles said
to me, `You know what? You're going to play again.' It was
unbelievable to hear that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, he returned to the ice that September when training
camp opened. But not in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was best to make a change,'' said Roberts. ``In Calgary,
there would have been the extreme pressure of everyone asking,
`How's the neck?' every day.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 26, 1997, the Hurricanes took a flier, acquiring Roberts
and Trevor Kidd from the Flames for Andrew Cassels and
Jean-Sebastien Giguere. Roberts has been a fixture in the Carolina
lineup since. And Monday night at the FleetCenter, he capped his
comeback by scoring his first playoff goal in five years, launching
the Hurricanes toward a 3-2 victory and a 2-1 advantage in the
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really exciting to come back like that, to be back in the
Stanley Cup playoffs,'' said Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   His goal was no artistic triumph, but Roberts wasn't being
fussy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a pass to (Jeff) O'Neill and followed it up,'' he said.
``I saw the puck between (Dmitri) Khristich's legs and just whacked
at it. When I saw it on (Byron) Dafoe's chest, I knew it was in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those lucky bounces. I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can quibble? He's entitled to one by now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
