<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-27 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LOSING THE FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Yes, indeed. The Bruins are down, two games to one.
It's in the books.
</P>
<P>
   They coulda/shoulda lost Game 1, but they didn't. They
coulda/shoulda won Game 2, but they didn't. They coulda/shoulda won
Game 3, but they didn't. There is no deep, dark mystery involved in
all this, but that doesn't mean people aren't looking for one.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the boos that accompanied them as they skated off the
ice at the conclusion of Monday night's game, I'd say some of the
fans are panicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the media, too,'' chuckles Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   With us, Byron, it's not so much panic as a desperate need to
find The Answer. It can't be anything as simple as the fact that
these are two reasonably equal hockey teams and sometimes you win
and sometimes you lose, can it?
</P>
<P>
   Um, maybe. At any rate, players have to leave the panicking to
the fans and media. Being down, 2-1, is a problem, not a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stay calm,'' Dafoe points out. ``If there were 20
panicking guys here in this dressing room, they'd all be flying
around hitting somebody and being out of control. We've lost two
games by one goal. Obviously, whatever we're doing, it isn't
enough. We've got to step it up, yes. But we can't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, in case you haven't heard, is the goalie on this outfit.
He is as much individually responsible for the Bruins even being in
the playoffs as anyone in the room. I'm not as big a Most Valuable
(i.e. Indispensable) Player guy as I am a Player of the Year (i.e.
who simply played the best, regardless of surrounding
circumstances, such as a quality backup, and team placement, etc.)
guy, but on the basis of what-if-he-weren't-there? value to his
team, Dafoe was a serious MVP candidate. He had 10 shutouts. He was
immense down the stretch, as the Bruins went from thinking about
those early tee times to a sixth-place finish in the East.
</P>
<P>
   And right now Dafoe can hardly catch a break. He's not crying
about it or anything. That's my job. And I'm more than happy to
point out that the Puck God, or whoever, is currently doing some
nasty stuff to Mr. Byron Dafoe. I mean, Ray Sheppard's OT
game-winner in Game 2 came while Dafoe was kissing the ice after a
scramble. And then there were goals 1 and 3 in Monday's setback.
You can't say they actually were scored as much as they somehow
materialized. Not that the second goal was a hockey Rembrandt,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pass hit Hal Gill's stick and went right to Sheppard,'' says
Dafoe. I'll fill in the rest: the right side of the goal was open.
Sheppard didn't miss. He could have. Guys do it all the time,
generally on teams you root for and often in OT. But Sheppard
didn't, because he is a hot man now and Dafoe isn't.
</P>
<P>
   No one respects the ebb and flow of good fortune more than the
goalkeeper. Even Dominic Hasek, playing in Nagano for the
fatherland, needed some luck now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' maintains Dafoe. ``When you're going well, a
puck will hit the post when you need it, or it will hit you and you
don't even know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins easily could be down, 3-0, right now if Dafoe had not
been Haseklike in the opening minutes of Game 1 in Greensboro.
Carolina came on like, well, a hurricane, as soon as the puck was
dropped, storming the net and putting Dafoe to a supreme test. The
crowd, as Dafoe himself put it, sounded like 25,000. It was a big
moment, all right, and Dafoe came up huge. Did he use up all his
good karma, right then and there? Who knows? Surely not Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   What he does know is that the post isn't necessarily his very
best friend any more and that he was beaten in Game 3 by, and I
quote, ``three freaky goals,'' one of which took place 65 ticks
into the game. That alone might have unnerved a less mature goalie.
But Dafoe hung in there and was actually sitting on a 2-1 lead in
the middle of the second period before the Hurricanes made a few
things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Dafoe isn't running around tugging the sleeves of those
toting notebooks, tape recorders, and cameras begging for sympathy
in his time of need. He's just a polite guy answering some
questions. If anything, we're all making things unnecessarily tense
for him by planting some bad thoughts in his head. He's been around
long enough to understand that a game is a game and a streak of
luck is a streak of luck (good or bad) and a series is something
else entirely. It really isn't over until it's over, and please
remember that this is the only league in which someone (two
someones, in fact) actually has come all the way back from an 0-3
series deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a seven-game series,'' reminds Dafoe. ``Over the course
of seven games, many things can happen. If we go out ... and play
our game and get a break or two, it will be 2-2. We can't put too
much pressure on ourselves, but we do have to play with a sense of
urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, yeah, that does sound cliche, but that happens to be
the truth. Nothing has happened in this series to make the Boston
Bruins lose faith in themselves, just as nothing has happened that
suddenly makes the Carolina Hurricanes into the 1959 Canadiens or
1981 Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Hurricanes a technical problem for the Bruins? Yup. They
are big and they have a frustrating way of forechecking
relentlessly while being able to tend to business in their own end.
There are a lot of experienced guys on that team. They are in front
because they deserve to be. Luck is, always has been, and always
will be, a part of this game. Let's remember that all this luck
took place in front of the Boston net, not at center ice.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hurricanes are still a team that finished the regular
season with 5 fewer points than the Bruins. We are talking about
two half-decent, just OK hockey clubs; nothing more, nothing less.
If all the technicalities cancel each other out, then luck just
might be the determining factor in any one game. But then there's
luck, and there is, shall we say, forced luck born of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make your own luck.'' Who said that? Who didn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no secrets.'' Who's been saying that? Pat Burns;
that's who.
</P>
<P>
   And there aren't. So drop the puck. As Dirty Harry might say,
we'll see who's feeling lucky tonight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
