<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0429-     04-27 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0429-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE TO CONSIDER WAR POWERS, GROUND TROOP AUTHORITY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington, (i) international categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. House of Representatives, which has stood
on the sidelines for more than a month of an intense air war, will
be forced Wednesday to take a formal position on the fighting in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., the lawmakers
are to vote, under the War Powers Act, whether to order a
withdrawal of American forces from hostilities, or make a formal
declaration of war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Neither proposal is expected to pass, but the Campbell
resolutions have prodded a reluctant Republican leadership to allow
a formal debate on the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, GOP leaders have assigned both the responsibility and
any potential blame for the conflict to President Clinton, while
promising to support the troops with emergency funds. House
Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., Tuesday
proposed $13 billion for the Balkan conflict, more than double
Clinton's request.
</P>
<P>
   For Wednesday's debate, House leaders have staked out a middle
ground that would neither challenge the war nor give it their stamp
of approval. Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., and Rep. Bill Goodling,
R-Pa., are sponsoring a bill that would require the president to
seek approval from Congress before ordering a ground offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and his advisers began this war on their own,
and have conducted it for the last month without the involvement of
Congress,'' Fowler said. ``It would be an abuse of his office and
show a total lack of regard for the Constitution for the president
to escalate this war with the introduction of U.S. ground forces
without the express approval of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   She gave her remarks even as the president was authorizing the
Pentagon to call up 33,102 reservists either to assist in the
Balkans or shore up U.S. forces that have been stretched thin
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Fowler led an unsuccessful effort to bar the use of
U.S. ground troops as part of any NATO operations in Yugoslavia,
even as peace keepers in Kosovo. Her toned-down proposal Wednesday
has stronger backing, including that of House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Texas, who predicted it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that will be controversial,'' Armey said, noting
that Clinton has said he would not use ground troops in the Balkan
hostilities and that he would take the proposal to Congress if he
changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the House prepared to take up the Balkan conflict,
Republican leaders continued to keep their distance from
decision-making on the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has had a kind of a record of presenting us with
fait accompli,'' Armey said. ``He gets troops in there. He gets the
air war on and then comes back and briefs us ... We're stuck,'' he
complained, repeating a refrain of Republican lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Tuesday that he
would consider a follow-up debate after the House vote. But Lott
has consistently said he opposes a ``divisive debate that could
give aid and comfort'' to Yugoslavia's President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said he hoped the House debate would be ``professional and
cordial.''
</P>
<P>
   On paying for the war, House and Senate leaders have promised to
complete a supplemental spending bill by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Young's bill includes $11 billion for the Pentagon, more than
double the amount Clinton sought, plus funds for NATO construction,
diplomatic installations, and disaster assistance in the Balkan
region.
</P>
<P>
   Because the money would be designated ``emergency,'' the
spending would not be required to fit under the budget spending
limits. It would come entirely from the ``surplus'' from this
year's Social Security tax collections, despite promises from
lawmakers and the White House to reserve those funds.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said he did not know if
Clinton would veto such a the spending bill and seek one closer to
his $6 billion original request.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
