A5396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      04-27 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS NEED TO   CAPITALIZE ON THEIR CHANCES, BURNS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As bad as things might be, and as bad at they could
become, the Bruins haven't been all that bad in the first three
games of the playoffs. They're in trouble, because two losses in a
seven-game series allow little room for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, and we broke down the tape _ it's right there on
the tape _ we outchanced them,'' said Boston coach Pat Burns
following a tale-of-the-VHS review of Monday night's 3-2 loss to
the Hurricanes at the Vault. ``And you may laugh at this, but we
also outhit them.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's gone wrong? Why are the Bruins in a 2-1 hole again,
standing two hours from elimination, in the opening round of the
postseason? What must they do better in Game 4 Wednesday when the
series resumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finish,'' said Burns. ``We get there. We get our chances. We
even get more chances than they do. But the problem is, we don't do
anything with those chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Finish can be a fateful thing. Ask a contractor to build you a
house, and it's no home if he forgets to build the front steps or
shingle the roof. In hockey, teams can take pride in passing,
shooting, puck possession, winning all the fights (nothing but
shoving matches in these three games), and dishing out the most
checks, but all that really matters is who gets the puck in the net
most often. Everything else is just a stocking stuffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do more of our game,'' said winger Rob DiMaio,
among the most reliable and effective Bruins forwards in the
series. ``Our game is to get the puck behind their defense and
create off that. We've got some big, strong guys and we should be
able to do it. Our game's not tic-tac-toe passing. It's bang,
grind, and get to the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it Carolina's design to pass the puck around and shoot
off the rush like the mid-'80s EuroOilers come back to life. In
fact, their game is even less refined than Boston's, not that style
matters, of course. They have set and carried the tone for the
series with an up-tempo forechecking game _ something Rick Pitino
would relish _ and haven't been overly concerned with how they
attack the net. Many, if not most, of their shots just kind of
happen, after enough mashing in the corners and bumping behind the
net produces an opportunity. Their goals don't come as a product of
X's and O's, but rather through a large dollop of effort and a
pinch of serendipity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be a little quicker on the puck,'' mulled Burns,
``and we have to get some breaks. It seems every time we're in
position to get the puck, there are three red sweaters on us.''
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the Boston defensemen have done an admirable
job of dealing with that red tidal wave. Don Sweeney has been
especially effective, his game taking a giant step forward in the
postseason. The blue line corps lost Dave Ellett (strained neck and
back) in the early going Monday night and Burns did an effective
job of rotating his five backliners and keeping the score close
down to the last seconds. It could have been far worse. Wednesday,
Mattias Timander will move in for the injured Ellett.
</P>
<P>
   As for the forwards, and the need to get them to finish their
chances, Burns will roll out his same struggling dozen and hope for
different results. He will not pull the exasperatingly ineffective
Dmitri Khristich in favor of either of his spare forwards, Cameron
Mann or Ken Baumgartner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that going to make us a better team?'' was Burns's
rhetorical answer to a question about making any changes up front.
``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Khristich, with one shot in three games, barely got on the ice
in the latter stages of Game 3. He is not the sole disappointment
up front, but he is the most obvious, because his accurate, searing
shot is the kind of touch and finish the Bruins so desperately
need. Steve Heinze, Anson Carter, and, to a lesser extent Sergei
Samsonov, all have been in a funk around the net. But it's
Khristich, who between shifts can be spotted on the bench with
shoulders hunkered and head down, who is so profoundly out of sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I do?'' offered Burns. ``I've got to keep him in
there and just hope he gets it going.''
</P>
<P>
   On the upside of the offense, the Bruins have seen marked
improvement in both Ken Belanger and Landon Wilson, both of whom
have played their best hockey of their careers over the last three
games. If Belanger and Wilson keep crashing and some of their
fellow forwards find their hands, then the series easily could be
knotted Wednesday. Don't forget, too, that netminder Byron Dafoe
had a league-high 10 shutouts in 1998-99. He could blank the 'Canes
and the mood in the Boston dressing room takes a dramatic upswing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, we have to play now with a sense of urgency, and
that includes me,'' said Dafoe. ``Our backs aren't completely
against the wall, but we are getting pushed in there.''
</P>
<P>
   While the players showered and dressed after the workout,
assistant coach Jacques Laperriere, master of the minute detail,
sat stoically, almost hypnotized, in the coaches' office and rolled
through video of the series. Lappy, as everyone calls him, clicked
back and forth on the VCR, scrutinizing each frame as if it were
forensic evidence. He occasionally called a player in for a brief,
private chat, the way a professor would review a term paper with a
student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to find something,'' said Burns's loyal partner. ``I
find the positive and show that to them.''
</P>
<P>
   As bad as things might be . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
