A5404 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-TALKS-BOS &LR;      04-27 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US, RUSSIAN OFFICIALS TALK ABOUT YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ NATO put into play Tuesday a plan to work with Russia
to solve the Yugoslavia crisis, but talks between an American envoy
and senior Russian officials appeared to produce no immediate
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, the first of
several Western diplomats to visit Moscow this week, said after a
series of closed-door talks Tuesday that he better understood
Russia's position and that talks between Moscow and Washington
would continue.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself was something, given Washington's desire to avoid
confrontation with the world's other major nuclear power. Relations
with Moscow have hit a post-Cold War low after five weeks of NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders have expressed hope that Russia would use its
unique access to Yugoslavia's leaders to negotiate a compromise.
Brokering an end to the Balkans war also appeals to Russia as a way
to buff up its status as a world power, tarnished by nearly a
decade of political upheaval and economic decline.
</P>
<P>
   But while Talbott called his talks ``very constructive, serious
and frank,'' there was no sign Tuesday that he had made progress
toward getting Yugoslavia to withdraw its forces from Kosovo,
NATO's primary condition for stopping its airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that Russia and the United States are
working together on this problem,'' Talbott told reporters after
talks with former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, who is
heading Russia's peace effort. ``The problem is extremely
complicated. It is important that our urgent work continues and it
will continue in the days to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin hinted that NATO and Belgrade had edged closer on
the critical issue of whose troops would monitor a cease-fire in
Kosovo. But he repeated Moscow's stance that NATO would have to
stop bombing before negotiations could start, a position the
Western alliance has already rejected as unacceptable. Chernomyrdin
also seemed to rule out participation by NATO troops in the force
that would implement a peace accord in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has agreed to an international presence in Kosovo
under UN auspices, only from those countries that it names and with
Russia's big participation. . . . I think NATO will not be fully
satisfied, but we can work further. . . . We can discuss the
international presence,'' he told Russian television.
</P>
<P>
   One of Talbott's goals was to better understand what Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic told Chernomyrdin in Belgrade talks
last week. The Russian envoy later made contradictory statements
about the results of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned even more about Russian perceptions of the
situation,'' said Talbott, who also met with Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott is the first senior Western official to visit Moscow
since the bombings began. His visit, following a lengthy
conversation Sunday between President Boris N. Yeltsin and
President Clinton, kicks off a flurry of diplomacy involving
Moscow. The foreign ministers of Greece and Canada, as well as UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan, are also due in Moscow this week for
talks on the Kosovo crisis, and Russian Foreign Minster Igor Ivanov
plans to visit London May 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Russia to be part of the solution,'' British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing Serbia cannot go on forever,'' commented privately
owned NTV television. ``Both Brussels and Belgrade realize this,
but they need Russia as a translator.''
</P>
<P>
   But this strategy has already run into several snags. Russia has
so far been unable in several high-level diplomatic missions to
Belgrade to extract any significant concessions from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   And Moscow has shown little desire to act merely as the West's
messenger. While Russian officials have quietly expressed growing
impatience with Milosevic, Moscow has gone out of its way to
embrace the Serb leader.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Russian President Boris Yeltsin Tuesday sent a note to
Milosevic, saying that Russia ``deeply sympathizes with the
fraternal people of Yugoslavia, the victim of NATO airstrikes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Russia disagrees with NATO over the bombing not just because
of Moscow's wounded pride over its lost superpower status, and not
just because of the cultural and religious affinity Russians feel
for Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   From senior officials down to ordinary citizens, Russians are
worried about the NATO airstrikes. Many Russians believed NATO
leaders, who assured Russia after the Cold War that the alliance
was a strictly defensive organization; now these Russians feel
betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   From Russians' perspective, NATO has consistently ignored their
objections.
</P>
<P>
   At the 50th anniversary summit in Washington last week, where
NATO leaders emphasized the need to get Russia involved in the
search for a solution in Kosovo, they also agreed to a strategic
doctrine that may open the way for the alliance to take action in
future conflicts without the backing of the UN Security Council, of
which Russia is a member.
</P>
<P>
   That does not go over well in Moscow, where NATO's refusal to
seek UN approval for its airstrikes is one of the main objections
raised by Russian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this forces Russia to reconsider many provisions for
ensuring its own military security,'' Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev commented on the summit to reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian newspaper Izvestia reported Tuesday that Moscow was
considering maintaining strategic forces, including
intercontinental ballistic missiles, strategic bombers and nuclear
missile submarines, that had been marked for scrapping this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin, anxious for new loans from the West, has played
down rumblings in the military and rejected calls to send Belgrade
weapons. Tuesday, First Deputy Prime Minister Yury Maslyukov was in
Washington for talks with the International Monetary Fund on a new
multibillion-dollar credit.
</P>
<P>
   While staking out a tough position on Kosovo, Moscow has found
ways to avoid confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott and Chernomyrdin also reportedly discussed NATO calls
for an oil embargo on Yugoslavia. Russia, which is a leading
supplier of oil to Belgrade, has said it would not honor such a
blockade. The possibility of NATO warships halting Russian tankers
in the Adriatic has caused some commentators to point out that wars
begin that way.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow has also said it suspended oil deliveries when the
bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
