u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-OSHA-PA     04-27 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-OSHA-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        MANY PA WORKERS GET HURT ON THE JOB HELPING PATIENTS, OSHA
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 27 -- Twenty percent of the workplaces in
Pennsylvania with the highest injury or illness rates are nursing
homes or personal care facilities, according to a federal report
released this week.
</P>
<P>
   Occupational Safety and Health Administration [OSHA] officials
said awkward movements involved in moving or lifting patients often
caused workers injuries on the job at a growing number of health
care facilities around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've recognized nursing homes and care facilities as an area
where a lot of occupational injuries occur,'' said Michael
Fluharty, an OSHA spokesman. ``There are workers lifting people and
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   OSHA released a list this week of 12,500 workplaces with the
highest injury or illness rates from around the nation. Of the
1,102 workplaces listed from Pennsylvania, 229 are health care
facilities. Other businesses on the list from the state were:
packing, groceries and manufacturing companies.
</P>
<P>
   The employers on the list reported the highest lost workday and
illness rates to OSHA in a 1997 survey of injury and illness rates
at 80,000 workplaces. For every 100 workers, the businesses on the
list reported eight or more injury or illnesses that resulted in
lost work days. The national average is 3.3, according to OSHA.
Construction sites were not included on the list, because they are
temporary, OSHA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA sent letters to the employers on the list encouraging them
to make their workplaces safer and will conduct inspections on
2,200 of them by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Health care industry officials said there is training for
workers on how to lift or move patients, which accounts for most
injuries on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk for a worker lifting a patient because it is not a
dead weight, which can be very stressful on the back,'' said Tom
Burke, a spokesman for the American Health Care Association, which
represents 11,000 nursing homes and assisted living facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said there is equipment that can help workers lift
patients, but it frequently isn't used.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are machines to help workers -- a sling someone wold sit
on to help them out of a bathing situation,'' Burke said. ``But
patients object when someone wants to crank them out on a sling. It
becomes a dignity issue. A patient wants to be helped by a person
not by a machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke recommended that nursing care companies encourage workers
to ask a colleague for help when lifting someone.
</P>
<P>
   But Fluharty, of OSHA, said there may be more injuries at
nursing care facilities simply because there are more of them than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the population gets older, there are more of these
facilities,'' Fluharty said. ``There are therefore more injuries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
