<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, April 28. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
RANCHERS (Douglas, Ariz.) - Dale Cureton's voice turned soft and
wistful as he recalled the good old days here on the sprawling
Rocker M Ranch, just a jackrabbit sprint from the Mexican border.
He spoke of a time when the same handful of deferential Mexican
farmworkers repeatedly used his place as their first stopoff point
on their way north. Today, an endless stream of illegal immigrants
- as many as 10,000 a month - take on this arid minefield of
rattlesnakes and thickets of prickly pear, mesquite, agave,
ocotillo and cholla spines that tear the flesh. By MARK SHAFFER and
DENIS WAGNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BIG BROTHER-GUNS (Phoenix) - Steven Haynes wants to be a Valley Big
Brother, to be a much-needed friend and mentor to a fatherless boy.
</P>
<P>
   His credentials seem in order: a single man with clean record,
employed for 12 years in a responsible job where he's now a
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   But Valley Big Brothers Big Sisters says no.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Haynes is a Phoenix police sergeant who, like
many officers, typically carries his gun while off duty. Valley Big
Brothers Big Sisters says kids and guns don't mix. By WILLIAM
HERMANN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ The thing is, it was really
comfortable. No self-respecting American man would ever wear one in
public, of course. I wouldn't even walk out of a fitting room with
one on. But the bikini-bottom bathing suit I had wedged myself into
felt . . . good. Nice snug fit, without turning me into a soprano.
Support in spades. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the
``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTHOR-GUTERSON (Undated) _ David Guterson's sense of place imbues
his novels with a character that transcends all others. An
interview by correspondent ANNE STEPHENSON. (With sidebar) Story
moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOK-GUTERSON _ (Sidebar) There are quiet moments in David
Guterson's new book, ``East of the Mountains,'' that have nothing
to do with what happens in its pages, and everything to do with
what happens in its sentences _ in the patience and language with
which they are rendered, and in the power that simple description
can have in the hands of a deeply reflective writer. By
correspondent ANNE STEPHENSON. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOK-EVERYMAN (Undated) _ Jeremy J. Stone's memoir, `` `Every Man
Should Try': Adventures of a Public Interest Activist,'' shows the
longtime president of the Federation of American Scientists to be,
at once, a royal pain in the neck of the establishment and,
surprisingly, detached enough to describe his major failures and
egotistical moments. By PAUL SCHATT. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS-NEW (Undated) _ Capsule reviews of new and notable books. By
correspondent ANNE STEPHENSON, Special to the Republic. Story moved
in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
