<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINE-ARAFAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT BACKS AWAY FROM INDEPENDENT PALESTINE GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY _ At a meeting of the leadership of the Palestine
Liberation Organization Tuesday, Yasser Arafat began a careful
climb-down from a diplomatic high-wire act in which he had promised
to declare an independent state on May 4.
</P>
<P>
   In a session of the 124-member mini-parliament, the Palestinian
Central Council, Arafat took the first steps to delay the
declaration, analysts and observers agreed. The council is now
expected to postpone any action on statehood until at least after
the Israeli general election on June 1, and possibly longer by
extending peace talks with Israel for another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going through a very delicate period in the history of
our people, a period during which we cannot afford making any
mistakes,'' the official Palestinian news agency WAFA quoted Arafat
as saying. ``We don't need to affirm our state because we are
actually exercising statehood.''
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations are expected to continue through Thursday, but
members of the PLO body, which is stacked with hand-picked Arafat
loyalists, were indicating which way the process was headed even
before Arafat's statement.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, the PLO leader had referred to May 4 as a
``sacred date'' for the Palestinian people to declare sovereignty _
unilaterally, if necessary. The date marks the end of the five-year
interim period of the Middle East peace process and was the
deadline set for a permanent accord between Israelis and
Palestinians when they signed the historic Oslo agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has put intense pressure on Arafat to
postpone a unilateral declaration of statehood, most recently in a
letter from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erekat, the chief Palestinian peace negotiator, quoted the
letter as saying that Clinton supported ``the Palestinian people's
right to determine their own future on their own land.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter has not been released, but if the word ``right'' was
used, it would bring the United States closer to supporting
Palestinian self-determination than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Ronni Shaked, a journalist for the newspaper Yediot Aharanot who
specializes in Palestinian affairs, said, ``Arafat knows that the
key to his future is the United States. He knows the US can save
him and give him the legitimacy to build a state. He realized that
he would be a fool to risk that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has played this whole statehood drama out over months and
done it masterfully,'' Shaked added, refering to a just-completed
56-nation tour in which Arafat worked to build support for
Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to back off the May 4 declaration, for now, has also
come from Arab and European states that have expressed fears that
such a move would wreck any prospect for a renewed push for a final
peace agreement after Israel's election and boost the reelection
bid of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, whose campaign rhetoric has taken a hard-line stance
against a Palestinian state, has threatened to permanently annex
Israeli-occupied land if Arafat proclaims independence of his own
accord.
</P>
<P>
   The scene Tuesday at Arafat's headquarters, informally known in
Arabic as ``muntada'' or ``the club,'' was classic Palestinian
political theater.
</P>
<P>
   There was the dramatic appearance of Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, the
ailing spiritual leader of the Islamic resistance group Hamas, who
arrived in a Land Rover with his wheel chair. The arrival of Yassin
as an ``observer'' suggested that Arafat was welcoming even the
most ardent opponents of the peace process to take part in the
debate over declaring statehood.
</P>
<P>
   There were small and tightly controlled protests demanding
statehood, and a man dressed in traditional Islamic garb was
shouting ``Long live freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics pointed to glaring indications that the appearance
of a democratic process at the meeting was more superficial than
substantial.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was closed to outsiders and the media. Palestinian
television and radio did not carry the speeches live; as they took
place, Palestinian TV aired an animal show that featured alligators
devouring their prey in African swamps.
</P>
<P>
   The council has no parliamentary rules for making decisions. It
is expected that debate will continue over for two more days, but
no one knew for sure. And it remained unclear Tuesday whether there
would be any vote, or recommendation from a committee, specifically
on delaying the statehood decision.
</P>
<P>
   Marwan Barghouti, the council member for the Fatah political
organization, said, ``We are waiting for a courageous decision, a
brave one which is declaring a Palestinian state on May 4 and not
submitting to international pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahmud Zahar, a political adviser for Hamas, which opposes the
peace process, made veiled threats of a return of violence if there
is no declaration of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Arafat) decides to postpone it,'' he said, ``it is his
responsibility for what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
