<HEADER>
A5414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHALE-DIES-BOS &LR;      04-27 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-DIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHALE'S DEATH ATTRIBUTED TO SHIP IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a surveillance plane watching from the sky and a special
state warning for boaters to avoid them, one of the rare Northern
right whales in Cape Cod Bay was apparently struck by a boat before
she died last week, according to preliminary autopsy results
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said the female whale, nicknamed Staccato, had five
broken vertebrae as well as a broken jaw, all injuries consistent
with a collision with a ship. The researchers said the injuries
probably did not kill the whale immediately, but she may have died
of a combination of injuries and disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our task now is to determine whether pre-existing illness made
this animal vulnerable to the traumatic injuries she sustained,''
said David St. Aubin of Mystic Aquarium in Connecticut, who
directed the autopsy on a Wellfleet beach last week. ``This degree
of trauma might not have killed an otherwise healthy animal.''
</P>
<P>
   National Marine Fisheries Service officials have launched an
investigation to find out who struck the animal _ a violation of
the Endangered Species Act _ but they admit it's an uphill task.
Only once in 14 ship strikes have investigators found the boat
responsible for killing a right whale.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Staccato, found floating five miles off Wellfleet
on April 20, dealt a blow to the survival hopes for the species
because she was a prolific breeder, the mother of six of the 300 or
so remaining right whales. Underscoring the loss, the environmental
magazine E rates right whales among the 10 species worldwide that
are most likely to go extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, conservationists said Staccato's death casts doubt on
the adequacy of government efforts to protect the whales. After
all, they said, Staccato died in spite of an aerial survey intended
to keep an eye on the whales as they feed in Cape Cod Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Some called for a dramatic increase in the $1 million National
Marine Fisheries Service budget to protect right whales.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before Staccato's death, the state had issued its
first-ever right whale alert, cautioning boaters to be on the
lookout for at least 20 right whales in eastern Cape Cod Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never saw (Staccato) in the water until it was dead.
Their little observation program is full of crap,'' said Max
Strahan of the group Green World and an outspoken critic of federal
and private efforts to protect the whales.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service said
Staccato's death may illustrate the difficulty of preventing rare,
far-flung tragedies. Although ship strikes are the leading
human-induced cause of whale death, such collisions occur once or
twice a year in thousands of square miles of ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have animals that extend anywhere from Cape Cod Bay to
Great South Channel (off Nantucket, Mass.),'' said Chris Mantzaris,
head of the protected resources division at the National Marine
Fisheries' Gloucester, Mass. office. ``It is very difficult to
cover all those areas in one aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantzaris also stressed that his agency and others are stepping
up the right whale campaign, noting that ships will soon have to
report to shore whenever they enter an area where right whales are
gathered.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mantzaris said he is frustrated by the limited federal
money available to protect right whales. His eight-man team has to
protect all marine mammals from Maine to Virginia, leaving the
staff spread extremely thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably feel frustrated every day of my life working here
because I can never get enough resources to do what I want to do,''
said Mantzaris.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Kraus, a leading right whale researcher at the New England
Aquarium in Boston, said the National Marine Fisheries Service has
to experiment with more effective strategies than aerial
surveillance _ which he called ``Neanderthal'' _ and public
education, which may not affect boaters' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Kraus called for more research into improved sonar that would
allow ships to detect right whales in front of them, and he also
called for more research into the use of acoustics to alert the
whales when ships are approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires a fairly aggressive approach if you want this
animal to be around in 100 years,'' said Kraus, who has been
working with shipping companies to persuade Congress to boost right
whale funding significantly. ``It's not unreasonable to do this to
save one of the great whales.''
</P>
<P>
   Lab analysis of Staccato's bones and tissue is expected to
continue for the next two to three weeks as researchers try to
assess Staccato's health at the time she sustained the broken
bones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
