A5416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JACKSON-NYT &LR;      04-27 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS GROUP, LED BY JESSE JACKSON, PLAN TRIP TO BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Texas)  (nk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of religious leaders led by the Rev. Jesse
Jackson plan to leave Wednesday on what they call a humanitarian
mission to Belgrade, where they hope to persuade Yugoslav officials
to free three captive American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither NATO nor the United States has sanctioned the trip, and
the administration has distanced itself from the effort. A senior
White House official said on Monday that Jackson was acting as a
private individual and would not be used by the government to carry
any message to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who helped negotiate the release in 1984 of a Navy
pilot shot down over Syria and hundreds of Europeans and Americans
held hostage in Iraq in 1990, said his group's goal was to create
an opening for a diplomatic solution to the conflict in Yugoslavia
by persuading the government to free the servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations are left to governments, but both governments are
locked in their political positions, and while they say it's a
diplomatic solution they want, they are looking for a military
victory,'' he said in an interview at his Rainbow/PUSH Coalition
office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group that will make the trip includes representatives of
the American Muslim Council, a rabbi and clergy from several
Christian denominations, among them the Rev. Joan Campbell, the
general-secretary of the National Council of Churches, an
organization of 35 Eastern Orthodox and Protestant church groups.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said representatives of the Yugoslav government had
assured him that the group would be allowed to visit the three
soldiers, who were captured along the Kosovo-Macedonia border on
March 31 and received their first visit from the International
Committee of the Red Cross only on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers are Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich.; and Specialist Steven M. Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
