<HEADER>
A5427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      04-27 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE TO CONSIDER BILL TO HALT U.S. ROLE IN YUGOSLAV CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Wednesday is likely to defeat
legislation that would require President Clinton to withdraw U.S.
forces from the air campaign against Yugoslavia or declare war on
the Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
   The votes are being forced by Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., who
wants Congress take a firm position on the U.S. role in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at war,'' Campbell said Tuesday. ``That's the truth and
we ought to admit it and proceed or we ought to pull the troops
back.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the House International Relations Committee defeated
the bills, one to withdraw American forces from the NATO-led air
assault, the other to declare war.
</P>
<P>
   The full House must still debate and vote on the measures, but
the committee's action, coupled with pressure from Republican
leaders for Campbell to withdraw his bills, indicate likely defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders and the Clinton administration are
concerned that the wrong signal would be sent to Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic if Congress entered into a divisive debate about
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on the panel complained that Campbell's resolutions
gave them too stark a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., called the resolutions ``extreme''
and said they offered lawmakers the choice of either validating
Milosevic's attacks against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo by
withdrawing the U.S. military presence, or declaring an all-out
war.
</P>
<P>
   He and other lawmakers argued that if the United States declared
war against Yugoslavia, it would disrupt the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and further alienate the Russians who are opposed to
the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   House International Relations Chairman Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y.,
urged the panel to vote against withdrawing troops. ``Now is not
the time to cut and run in the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who favors withdrawing U.S. forces, said he proposed
the resolutions to force Congress to take a position on the war in
Yugoslavia because the Constitution empowers the House and Senate
to declare war.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution also makes the president commander-in-chief,
which presidents have argued allows them to send troops into battle
without consulting Congress.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. forces have gone into battle more than 200 times while
Congress has declared war just five times: the War of 1812, the
Mexican War in 1846, the Spanish-American War in 1898, World War I
and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the Vietnam conflict, Congress adopted the War
Powers Act. The 1973 law says that unless U.S. troops are under
attack, a president must obtain congressional approval before
deploying troops. In the event of an emergency, the president has
48 hours to consult with Congress on the military deployment and to
remove troops within 60 days if Congress does not declare war.
</P>
<P>
   That law has not stopped president from sending troops into
action in scattered conflicts. Before the Persian Gulf War began in
1991, Congress did vote to authorize the use of military force,
although the troops had already been sent to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he may petition a federal court to make a ruling
on the law if the House does not vote to authorize the military
action in Yugoslavia, which began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said lawmakers would
vote on the two Campbell resolutions, along with two moderate
alternatives, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Republican-sponsored alternative is expected to require
Clinton to obtain congressional permission before sending any U.S.
ground forces to the region. The bill may also cut off funding if
Clinton were to commit land forces without consulting Congress.
Clinton has repeatedly said he has no plans to send in combat
troops, but would send a land force as part of a peace-keeping
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are expected to offer a resolution supporting the
air campaign. The Senate approved a similar resolution last month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, House Appropriations Committee Chairman C.W. Bill
Young, R-Fla., introduced a $12.9 billion spending bill to fund the
Kosovo operation through Sept. 30. The measure is double the $6
billion the Clinton administration requested.
</P>
<P>
   Young's proposal includes $2 billion to fund a 4.8 percent
across-the-board pay increase for military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill recognizes the we are more deeply involved in Kosovo
than we were led to believe and that unless Milosevic has a major
change of heart, our involvement will be longer and deeper than
anticipated,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said he expected the House and Senate would approve the
Kosovo spending bill next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
