<HEADER>
A5436 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPS-EARNINGS28-COX     04-27 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-EARNINGS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overseas profit gains continue for UPS
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the heels of its first-ever annual profit from
international service, United Parcel Service kept up the momentum
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   International operating profit quadrupled from a year earlier,
contributing to a 42 percent jump in overall profit for the Sandy
Springs-based delivery giant.
</P>
<P>
   Net income climbed to $499 million in the January-March quarter,
up from $352 million a year ago. Revenue rose to $6.33 billion, vs.
$5.86 billion. UPS stock is owned by employees and doesn't trade
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits from international business rose to $44
million from $11 million, which UPS attributed to growth in express
delivery volume in both Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw impressive growth in our express products in most
corners of the world,'' said Chairman and Chief Executive Jim
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter gains also reflected UPS' efforts to expand
its e-commerce products, build overall volume and control costs,
Kelly said. Slightly lower fuel prices helped.
</P>
<P>
   UPS began a steady international expansion 11 years ago, mainly
by acquiring local companies. But it lost money on the expansion
until last year, when it posted international operating profits of
$56 million, reversing a $67 million loss in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   UPS now is well-positioned throughout much of Europe but faces
new challenges as national postal agencies offer competing
low-priced domestic service, most notably in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   UPS has responded by de-emphasizing German domestic service and
focusing on cross-border European business.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter U.S. domestic package operating profit rose to
$765 million from $594 million on a 2.7 percent volume increase.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits from non-package operations fell to $25
million for the quarter from $35 million a year earlier, despite a
26.6 percent gain in revenue for the sector.
</P>
<P>
   Non-package operations includes such areas as truck leasing and
supply-chain management services offered by UPS Logistics Group.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Norman Black, however, said the profit decline was due
to start-up expenses for unannounced new products and services
rather than ongoing business.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0428-C     04-27 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0428-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEEK FIVE OF NATO BOMBING, CLINTON ESCALATING INSTEAD OF WINDING
DOWN
 &HT;    800&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0428; KOSOVO-APACHES-0428.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five full weeks into NATO's air campaign against
Yugoslavia, the United States is plunging deeper into a conflict
that has no visible endpoint, with President Clinton poised to
deploy hundreds of additional warplanes and 33,100 fresh reservists
in the largest such call up since the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged and escalating war of attrition is not what Clinton
had in mind on March 24, when he led the world's mightiest military
alliance to launch air strikes against a third-rate Balkan
mini-state, citing a ``moral imperative'' to halt ethnic
repression.
</P>
<P>
   As the imperative shifts from moral to strategic, with U.S. and
NATO credibility at stake, the addition of forces and firepower to
the fray will surely increase the pressure on Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It will do little, though, to change the allies' fundamental
challenge: how to bring a determined dictator to heel with a
campaign constrained by the limits of air power and the politics of
coalition warfare in the television age.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder Clinton is gearing up for the long haul -- and
calling for patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're sort of at the top of the third inning here,''
said former Pentagon official David Ochmanek, an air power expert
at RAND, a strategic think tank based in Santa Monica, Ca. ``Our
team is several runs down, but we've got a deep bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent in fresh players on Tuesday, giving the Pentagon
approval to call up to 33,100 reservists into action supporting
Operation Allied Force. The first tranche of 2,100 reservists will
go to help support 30 additional refueling tankers as early as this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is also working with the NATO commander, U.S. Army
Gen. Wesley Clark, on a plan to deploy some 270 additional
warplanes and support craft, to enable Clark to expand his
around-the-clock attacks on military targets across Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also plans to begin a naval blockade -- as early as this
weekend -- to choke off Yugoslavia's oil imports.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Clark said Tuesday, the alliance has tripled the size
of its air armada -- roughly 1,000 planes strong -- since air
strikes began. His request would raise the force by another third
on top of that.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor his generals will say so publicly, but the
dramatic widening of the NATO offensive underscores an obvious
point:
</P>
<P>
   ``We underestimated Milosevic's staying power and what it would
take to get him to see things our way,'' said Lawrence Korb, former
assistant secretary of defense in the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   Now the alliance is struggling to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   As early as last summer, NATO began bracing for a confrontation
with Milosevic over the issue of Serb repression targeting the
ethnic Albanian majority in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   By fall, the allies had decided not to send ground troops to
fight a shooting war against Serbs, but to rely instead on NATO --
mostly U.S. -- air power. The hope was that Milosevic would
capitulate in the face of NATO's overwhelming air power.
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes had long since faded by this weekend, when NATO
leaders gathered here for a 50th anniversary summit and reiterated
their reliance on the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a ground option, though, has undercut the air
operation.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, with no ground campaign to fear, Serbs haven't
been forced to defend their border, the sort of tactic that pins
down large concentrations of troops and weapons. Massed troops are
far easier to hit from the air -- as Iraqi forces learned during
the Gulf War -- than thinly deployed armies dispersed across the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Without advancing troops to flush them out, moreover, Serb
forces can survive -- apparently for some time -- simply by
hunkering down and hiding in bombed-out villages, farms and woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of a NATO ground force in Kosovo is allowing the
Serbs to choose the time and place of their operations. They can
sit when they need to sit and they can move when they want to
move,'' said Ochmanek. ``It allows Milosevic to retain the
initiative, and it makes us predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, NATO air strikes have made life miserable for Serb
forces on the ground inside Kosovo. Scores of tanks, armored
personnel carriers and trucks have been blown up, supplies of food,
ammunition and fuel have become scarce and direct communications
between fielded forces and their senior commanders have been
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air campaign is working,'' Clark told reporters Tuesday in
Brussels. ''There's more to be done. And, there should be no doubt,
more will be done.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, though, it remains up to Milosevic to decide when
he's had enough to say uncle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you a prediction,'' said Clark, ``on how long he
is going to endure this kind of punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Under the best of circumstances, air strikes alone stood little
chance of physically stopping small groups of Serb forces,
operating cheek by jowl with civilian populations, from rampaging
across Kosovo, shelling villages, burning homes and executing
victims at will.
</P>
<P>
   For NATO pilots, bedeviled by poor bombing weather during two
out of every three days of the campaign, these have not been the
best of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 4,400 NATO combat sorties flown as of Tuesday, hundreds,
perhaps thousands, have been scrubbed in mid-air due to heavy
clouds and fog, which NATO military spokesman Konrad Freytag called
``The best ally for Mr. Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on relatively clear days, the Air Force, a frighteningly
efficient tool for attacking and destroying armies, has brought
only limited influence to bear upon the sort of roving hordes of
gunmen that have forced an estimated 1.5 million Albanians to flee
their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have regular military forces in any sense of the
word,'' said a senior Air Force pilot with extensive combat
experience in the Balkans. ``Six thugs in the back of pick-up
trucks going to a village and burning it down, you can't just
target that situation from the air, particularly with the
collateral constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO pilots are instructed to do all they can to avoid injuring
or killing civilians, including not dropping bombs unless they're
certain to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   Turning that virtue to their advantage, Serbs have, predictably,
billeted even moved troops and equipment alongside civilians -- a
violation of the Geneva Conventions -- forcing NATO pilots to make
split-second cockpit decisions at high altitude over whether they
are targeting soldiers or refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy appears to have resulted in tragedy at least once,
when NATO warplanes mistakenly bombed a convoy containing refugees
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the damage television footage of such disasters can
do to public support for the air campaign, NATO is going to pains
to avoid a reprise of that incident, making it all the more
difficult for U.S. and allied pilots to strike effectively at Serb
convoys and fielded forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do,'' said the Air Force official, ``is nibble at
the margins.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
