<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMORESE TO VOTE ON AUTONOMY IN INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INDONESIA-ELECTION) 
(mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ President B.J. Habibie of Indonesia
announced Tuesday that a referendum would be held on Aug. 8 in the
territory of East Timor to allow residents to choose whether to
accept a plan giving them autonomous status within Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   If they reject the plan, Habibie said, the former Portuguese
colony, which Indonesia invaded in 1975 and annexed in 1976, is
free to become an independent nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will accept whatever they decide, whether it be integration
or separation,'' Habibie said after a meeting on Bali with Prime
Minister John Howard of Australia. Habibie said he would announce
the result of the vote on Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   He added that a six-nation team would supervise the balloting
and that U.N. advisers would help police maintain security.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has grown in the territory of 800,000 people since
January, when Habibie raised the possibility of independence. Many
experts are concerned that the losers in the referendum will not
accept the results.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for an irregular militia that opposes independence
told The Associated Press that he opposed a referendum, which many
Timorese believe will favor independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will never solve the conflict in East Timor,'' the
spokesman, Florencio Viera, said. ``East Timor with greater
autonomy is our choice, and that's final. The East Timorese are
blind when it comes to politics. If the ballot is carried out, the
winners will be proud and the losers won't accept that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
