<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT &LR;      04-27 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER YUGOSLAV OFFICIAL SUGGESTS COMPROMISE POSSIBLE OVER
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A senior Yugoslav government official,
the second this week, spoke optimistically Tuesday about the
possibility of a negotiated settlement to the war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this will be the week in which the basic
outline of an agreement on Kosovo can be firmed up,'' Goran Matic
said on Tuesday. Matic, a minister without portfolio, is from the
Yugoslav United Left party of Mirjana Markovic, the influential
wife of President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The other Yugoslav official seeking a compromise over Kosovo is
the more liberal deputy prime minister, Vuk Draskovic, the former
leader of protests against Milosevic. Draskovic, who is outside of
ruling circles, first came out in favor of a negotiated settlement
in an interview on Sunday on Belgrade's Studio B television. He
continued to press Tuesday for a compromise that would involve a
peacekeeping force led by the United Nations that could include
troops from NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   While Draskovic maintains that Milosevic would back his
initiative, he conceded Tuesday that he had not talked with the
president specifically about an armed U.N. force containing NATO
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Matic said that diplomacy, with the help of Moscow, was
advancing. He maintained that Yugoslavia, under more than a month
of NATO air attacks, would like to see them stopped, but not at any
price. ``We have a national interest in this,'' he said in an
interview Tuesday. ``But it's in America's interest as well, and at
one point our interests will intersect.''
</P>
<P>
   While much work remains to be done to bring the two sides
together, he said, Yugoslavia would insist only on two things: ``We
won't give up Kosovo or allow armed troops into Kosovo. Everything
else we'll give NATO for their victory.''
</P>
<P>
   But even on the question of armed troops, Matic was careful.
``That is our official position,'' he said when pressed, but
conceded that any peace settlement would have to involve
negotiation and compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the idea of some form of international protectorate
for Kosovo, as NATO is now proposing, Matic said flatly: ``No one
can sign an agreement that allows the secession of the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Tuesday, Draskovic, the most liberal member
of the relatively weak federal government, pulled back from his
threat to lead street demonstrations if Belgrade's television
station, Studio B, remains under army censorship.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that a military officer is controlling footage about
the army on the news for security reasons, but is not otherwise
interfering with programming, which is in any event subject to
wartime censorship from the Serbian Information Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted the censors out of Studio B. If the military
does interfere further with Studio B's programming, he said
Tuesday: ``We'll take the action that we decide.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Matic was politely patronizing about Draskovic,
seeming to reflect a government decision to ignore his challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite normal for him to have such outbursts,'' Matic
said. ``Mr. Draskovic is free to express his views. But if you
follow him closely, he did not abandon the basic position of unity
and of the defense of the country, and that is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, in an interview Sunday that Belgrade's intellectuals
and democratic opposition largely applauded, called on the
government to speak realistically to the nation about the war and
its costs, and not to pretend that Yugoslavia could defeat NATO or
be saved by Russian military aid. He also pressed for a U.N. force
to monitor any Kosovo agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts think Draskovic is probably right, but even his
proposal falls short of NATO's demands for an armed ``international
security force'' with NATO troops as its core, so that ethnic
Albanian refugees feel that it is safe to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade also wants to keep larger numbers of its security
forces in Kosovo than NATO is willing to allow, but most diplomats
consider that issue, too, subject to negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic also asserts that Yugoslavia is willing to allow
international human-rights investigators access to Kosovo as part
of a settlement, but Milosevic has previously refused such access
outright.
</P>
<P>
   Matic, 40 and telegenic, was the federal information minister
until Draskovic's liberal Serbian Renewal Movement joined the
government. Draskovic's party, which controls the Belgrade city
government, took over the Information Ministry, while Matic became
a minister without portfolio. But he has taken a more assertive
role in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   On other matters, Matic said that ``no massacres and no
atrocities'' have been committed by Serbian forces in Kosovo as the
West alleges, but he confirmed a statement by Draskovic that the
federal government has set up a special investigative committee to
gather evidence on allegations of criminal acts committed against
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Matic said that NATO propaganda appeared to be following ``the
Bosnia script,'' with ``unprovable assertions'' about mass graves,
concentration camps, rapes and other atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the NATO bombing campaign had moved from military
targets to civilian ones in a vain effort to demoralize ordinary
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main attempt of the air campaign is to promote psychosis
and defeatism in the population, and to panic people so we will
accept anything,'' he said. ``But that is impossible,'' because of
the Serbian ``primordial attachment to Kosovo and refusal to break
the state apart,'' and because of ``the huge number of civilian
casualties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
