<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-MAROONED-BOS &LR;      04-27 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MAROONED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAROONED BROTHERS RESCUED FROM HARBOR ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM AND JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- From now on, the brothers Diaz will be casting their
fishing lines from dry land.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning Manuel Diaz, 56, and German Diaz, 54, both
from Dorchester, and Efrain Diaz, 44, visiting from Puerto Rico,
had launched German's 14-foot motor boat into the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't meant to be much more than a three-hour tour. Four or
five, tops.
</P>
<P>
   But almost 24 hours later, after a cold, wet, hungry night on
inhospitable Lovell Island in Boston Harbor, they were being
hoisted by helicopter onto a Coast Guard vessel.
</P>
<P>
   And for a while there in between, their plight was looking
dangerously similar to that of the gang from the S.S. Minnow, but
without the movie star part.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, all skippers who had fished together often in
Puerto Rico, set out at 11 a.m Monday from the Old Colony Yacht
Club in Dorchester Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no fish, and there was a lot of wind,'' Efrain said
at his Dorchester home Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At about 3 p.m., the net they were using got tangled in the
motor's blade. A piece of the motor broke off. ``And that was it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers had taken no food or drink on their trip. No
blankets, no two-way radio or other means of communicating to
shore.
</P>
<P>
   And in an oversight worthy of Gilligan himself, they had flares
but no matches to light them, and one flashlight with dying
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no radio. We could not communicate with anybody. We
were just there, floating around. We hoped a boat would pass by,
but none did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At around 5:30 p.m., the wind and cold picked up, the current
began pushing the boat out, and two of the brothers began rowing,
aiming for the only thing they could see _ Lovell Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were wet and freezing. We had lifevests on, and light
coats. We were still very cold,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the brothers jumped out of the boat into the surf to
guide the craft to the island's shore around 6:15 pm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it began to rain hard,'' Efrain said, chuckling at their
bad luck. ``Everything went badly for us.''
</P>
<P>
   They did have a waterproof tarp they set up with pegs as a
shelter to block the wind and rain. They huddled under it for
warmth, sitting on the bare ground.
</P>
<P>
   The island _ 1,500 by 400 yards _ was too big to allow them to
see to the other side. Efrain said it was windswept, with small
tress and undergrowth, and what appeared to be an abandoned cement
shack. He said they didn't explore much, because they were tired
and worried.
</P>
<P>
   Though they were only four miles from downtown Boston, they did
not know where they were.
</P>
<P>
   They remained stoic. ``We did not think we would die, but we
talked about how we could survive'' if rescue did not happen soon,
Efrain said. ``We kept saying `Tomorrow is another day.' '' He said
he felt their relatives would report them missing, and that someone
would begin searching for them.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers slept on and off, leaning against each other in the
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, relatives in Dorchester were frantic. They went to
the police at 10:30 p.m., said Elba Diaz, German's daughter. The
Coast Guard began a search at 12:50 a.m., using a helicopter and a
night-sun spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting by the phone all night,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At about 5:30 a.m., Efrain said he heard the hum of a helicopter
overhead. They all jumped to their feet, shouting ``Thank God.''
The helicopter airlifted them onto a Coast Guard vessel and within
hours they were back in Dorchester, sleeping off the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he and his brothers would go fishing again after
this, Efrain laughed and said ``No, no more fishing for me.'' At
least, not from anything floating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
