<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mindspring profits reflect growth
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First-quarter profits at MindSpring Enterprises more
than doubled as sales surged on strong growth in subscribers, aided
by acquisitions and internal growth.
</P>
<P>
   Operating income, excluding acquisition-related expenses, jumped
to $4.7 million, or 16 cents a share, against $2 million, or 8
cents a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street had expected operating earnings of 13 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues of the Atlanta-based Internet services provider nearly
tripled to $61.6 million from $21.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Including amortization associated with acquisitions, MindSpring
posted a net loss of $3.3 million, or 12 cents a share, against net
income of $860,000, or 4 cents a share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The loss breaks a string of five profitable quarters.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts aren't concerned. They knew MindSpring is on a
buying spree to expand its subscriber base. For example, the
company last February completed its $245 million acquisition of San
Jose-based Netcom Online Communication Services, adding 371,000
individual accounts and 45,000 Web-hosting accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase made MindSpring the nation's fourth-largest
Internet services provider. It now has 1,157,000 subscribers, up 67
percent from the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   President and chief operating officer, Michael S. McQuary, said
the company is further along integrating Netcom into its operations
that it had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exceeded the expectations of the analysts that follow our
company,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, such as Jeff Sadler of FAC Securities in New York,
lauded the results and the company's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profiability for the business was much stronger than I
anticipated,'' Sadler said. It was a ``very, very strong quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said the challenge facing MindSpring is to continue to
successfully integrating Netcom. But he said he believes management
is up to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a growing and developing business, they're still way ahead
of the game,'' Sadler said. ``MindSpring continues to show they can
control a sense of profitability and generate cash instead of
losing it, and that's good corporate government.
</P>
<P>
   `` Charles (Brewer, chairman and chief executive) has always had
his eye on the shareholder,'' Sadler continued. ``The company's
core values and beliefs might sound quirky, but it does make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MindSpring Enterprises fell along with many other
Internet-related issues, finishing at $116.31 1/4, down $8.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
