<HEADER>
A5465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHRINE-AR     04-27 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHRINE-ART-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PUBLIC MEMORIAL GIVES WITNESS TO PRIVATE GRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (With COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR and JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the week since two teen-agers killed 13 people at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo., thousands of mourners have gone to
a public park nearby, carrying flowers, memorial cards and banners,
stuffed animals and balloons, building a rambling, multicolor
memorial that spreads out across the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening in Robert F. Clement Park offers testimony
both to an ancient human impulse, to honor the dead, and to a far
more recent cultural phenomenon, in which private emotions are made
vividly public.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to connect in visceral ways, and one of the ways
to do this is to leave things,'' said Edward T. Linenthal, a
professor of religion and American culture at the University of
Wisconsin at Oshkosh, who is writing a book about the memorial to
victims of the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Linenthal said that the recent creation of popular shrines at
the sites of mass deaths might come from people's desire to
overcome feelings of powerlessness and to experience a sense of
unity, a ``community of bereavement,'' that transcends race,
ethnicity and other distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   Rituals of public mourning have always been important in the
United States, going back to the elaborate funerals of the
Puritans. But the response to recent violence has taken on an
individualized cast in a way not seen even three decades ago, at
the times of the funerals of President John F. Kennedy, his brother
Robert and the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   What prevails now is an acceptance, even expectation, that
personal feelings may be freely exposed, that women and men alike
can freely cry in public.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Farley, a psychologist at Temple University in
Philadelphia and a recent president of the American Psychological
Association, said that people were feeling a greater sense of
permission to express themselves, not least through the inspiration
of television and radio programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you follow daytime television, there's a lot of weeping and
public revelation of emotion, a lot of grieving,'' Farley said.
</P>
<P>
   Therese Rando, a clinical psychologist who is director of the
Institute for the Study and Treatment of Loss, in Warwick, R.I.,
said memorials like the one outside Columbine High School responded
to a sense on the part of some people that society has become
``deritualized,'' lacking sufficient formal outlets for grief and
other emotions.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Ms. Rando said, she has seen a rise in the
number of roadside shrines, with flowers, candles and handmade
signs, at the sites of fatal accidents. Makeshift shrines for
victims of violence in cities like New York have also become almost
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   And referring to events like the Oklahoma City bombing, the
death of Diana, princess of Wales, and the Colorado shooting, Ms.
Rando said, ``There is more the need to give expression to our
grief at the senseless deaths of young people in their prime.''
</P>
<P>
   A young woman in Clement Park, Morgen Warner, 17, who led about
100 students on a nine-mile walk to the park on Monday, said that
visiting the memorial ``was just such a unifying experience.
</P>
<P>
   Linenthal said a change in public expressions of grief became
visible after the Vietnam Veterans Memorial was opened on the
Washington Mall in November 1982. Visitors have left mementos at
the V-shaped wall, including flags and family photographs, boots
and jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial outside Columbine High began to take shape on April
21, the day after the shooting. People have strung up paper chains
between trees with messages for the victims. Some have planted 13
crosses, one for each victim, in the grass, and set out 13 teddy
bears, with one slightly larger than the others to honor William
David Sanders, the only teacher killed.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the site, 4-year-old Alexa Sharp-Wiley arranged a pair
of pinwheels beside a Winnie-the-Pooh doll. Her grandmother, Jo Ann
Schlegel, 62, said, ``I wanted her to see the reality of how to
serve others by going in and paying tribute to the lives that were
lost.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For some, just going to see the memorial meant feeling a
connection to the dead. ``This is moving me more than the TV did,''
said Frances Stall, 62, from nearby Lakewood. ``This is making me
feel part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after a bomb-laden truck destroyed the Alfred P. Murrah
Federal Building in Oklahoma City on April 19, visitors flocked to
the chain-link fence around the site. Many left handwritten prayers
and poems. Children hung drawings. And some people peeled off their
T-shirts and left them on the fence.
</P>
<P>
   One observer, the Rev. Nick Harris, senior pastor of First
United Methodist Church, which sits across the street from the
Federal Building and was itself damaged in the explosion, said, ``I
think it's a way to do something physical and tangible to make sure
you never forget this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have always built shrines to that which is
overwhelming and that which is transcendent,'' Harris said. ``You
enshrine things that you cannot explain.''
</P>
<P>
   A permanent memorial is being built at the Oklahoma City site.
Another is going up at Westside Middle School in Jonesboro, Ark.,
where two boys killed a teacher and four girls in March 1998. That
project will include an amphitheater, a garden and a sculpture of a
white ribbon with the victims' names. Before construction began,
people came by to leave personal items.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Young, superintendent of the Westside Consolidated School
District, said he remembered the expressions on the faces far more
than anything they left. ``You could tell there was a bond,'' Young
said. ``It's a way for them to connect and share and put meaning to
the feelings you're having.''
</P>
</TEXT>
