<HEADER>
A5474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDNEY-COX     04-27 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Easier transplant technique gives hope to
patients
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ There really is no easy way to ask a brother for
one of his kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gut-wrenching,'' said Jill Reffner of Hillsboro. Her
family was close, everyone knew she would need a kidney transplant
sometime and both of her brothers agreed to be donors without
hesitating, but still _ this wasn't just a pint of blood that she
needed.
</P>
<P>
   At the time she asked, Reffner knew kidney donors must undergo
painful surgery that knocks them out of work for six to eight
weeks. She didn't learn for two or three more months that her
brother, David Wilmer, would have the tri-state area's first
laparoscopic kidney removal for a transplant, cutting recovery time
by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   The new technique could help many of the 41,000 Americans
waiting for kidney transplants by making it more practical for
living relatives to donate a kidney, say doctors who performed the
operations at The University Hospital in Cincinnati. Kidneys from
living donors have better survival rates than kidneys from
cadavers, and they can be transplanted before the patient's health
declines while waiting for a kidney.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for patients to say they'd rather stay on
dialysis than ask a relative to miss two months of work, said
Wilmer's surgeon Dr. James Whiting, last November. ``Now we've
already had a couple of times where they've said, 'Well, if it's
not going to be so bad, let's do it.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The conventional operation is safe and reimbursed by insurance,
but as Reffner said, ``They pretty much cut your body in half.'' A
12- to-18-inch incision goes from the belly button toward the
spine, where a rib often must be removed to take out the kidney.
The recipient's operation, with the new kidney placed in the
abdomen, is much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Laparoscopy requires just a 3-inch incision just above the belly
button for removing the kidney, plus four holes of less than half
an inch along the ribcage for inserting miniature surgical tools
and a tiny camera to guide the surgeon. He watches a video monitor
to detach the kidney, and then it is pulled out through the
abdomen. Wilmer's was fished out in a pouch, but Whiting's team is
doing it more often by hand now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt worse when I had the flu,'' said Wilmer, retired
from Delphi at 52 and living in Fletcher in Miami County. He
started eating the next day, never took so much as an aspirin, left
the hospital after three days instead of two weeks and returned to
all his normal activities in six weeks ``instead of probably six
months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do it again,'' Wilmer says. ``But you've only got one to
spare. I'm kind of done.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Wilmer's kidney, Reffner would be on dialysis by now,
waiting more than a year for a transplant because of her tissue
typing. Instead, the 44-year-old Dayton native is back to work
three days a week at Reffner Photography Studio in Beavercreek
while her retired military husband, Wayne, tends the farm they
bought four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reffner found out at 17 she was born with only one kidney, and
it gradually stopped working over the past two years. ``Basically,
it's just been overworked all these years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting a year ago February, her kidney function and energy
declined steadily. She had surgery to install a port for dialysis
in July, when Dr. Gordon James of Wright-Patterson Medical Center
referred her to University Hospital, which has been doing kidney
transplants for 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati doctors said she should talk to her brothers in
early August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either one of us would have done it,'' said Wilmer, whose
tissue typing was the better match. ``We didn't want to see our
sister go through dialysis every other day for the rest of her life
until she got another kidney.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Wilmer said, ``I was scared to death, to tell
you the truth.'' He had never been in a hospital, hadn't even seen
a doctor for 20 years. ``Even just going to the doctor gives me the
willies,'' he said. ``With this, I was afraid if they put me to
sleep, I wouldn't wake up again.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have backed out any time during the tests and
conferences in the next several weeks. And he certainly didn't have
to be the hospital's first laparoscopic patient, knowing it was a
more intricate procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Laparoscopy evolved during the 1980s from arthroscopic joint
surgery, the first use of camera-guided miniature surgical tools.
Gynecologists used the scopes for examinations and by the late
'80s, surgeons used them for the relatively simple chore of
removing gall bladders. ``Sort of like picking a cherry off a
tree,'' Whiting said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maryland and Johns Hopkins Medical School in
Baltimore pioneered laparoscopic kidney removal and trained
Whiting, who expects it to be standard procedure in three or four
years. Only the Maryland hospitals and Mount Sinai Medical Center
in New York have done more than 100, he said, with another 12 to 20
starting in the past several months. University has done about a
dozen transplants, still requiring donors to be thin and healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to do,'' Whiting said. ``You can't just say,
'Let's start doing this.' '' The kidney and blood vessels have to
be preserved intact by remotely maneuvering instruments in an area
visible only on a wall-mounted screen.
</P>
<P>
   That part didn't bother Wilmer. It looked to him as if doctors
flew in from all over the country to watch Whiting's procedure,
``so if something went wrong, one of them was bound to know what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything went smoothly. ``I thought it would be a lot more
painful, and also more traumatic,'' Reffner said, but she calls
herself ``fortunate'' to have just the slightest of side effects.
She takes 15 pills a day now, down from 69 at first, and she talks
with her brother more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot closer,'' she said. ``I feel more of a
connection, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
