<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BEEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING OF CLONED BEEF DISTURBS JAPANESE CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Japanese government says at least 66 head of cloned
cattle have been slaughtered and sold on the beef market in Japan,
raising concerns among consumers about the safety of the meat.
</P>
<P>
   The cattle had been produced as part of Japan's advanced
research into the cloning of animals. Japan has gone farther than
most countries in cloning livestock, and those that were butchered
and sold were no longer needed for research.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said they did not have any health concerns about the
meat _ which is, after all, identical genetically to the meat of
the natural cattle that were cloned. But some consumers are
apprehensive about the idea of eating cloned animals.
</P>
<P>
   After acknowledging earlier this month that it had allowed the
sale of cloned beef, the government mounted a campaign to persuade
the public that eating cloned beef is safe. Last week, Shoichi
Nakagawa, the agriculture minister, ate cloned beef at a tasting
party to dispel anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the meat also underscores the potential of cloning,
which could drastically change the way meat is produced in this
country, consistently developing the best beef-producing cattle
specimens and thus driving down Japanese beef prices, the highest
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bio-engineering is not as divisive an issue in Japan as in
Europe and the United States. But some Japanese still are alarmed
over the ethical issue of raising cloned animals, even if they are
domesticated animals bred for slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the cloning technique becomes possible, to manipulate
life and to go beyond God's control _ we need to think carefully
whether to accept this or not,'' said Setsuko Yasuda, a spokeswoman
for the Consumers Union of Japan. ``This discussion is lacking in
Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the news came out also unsettled some consumers. They
were told about the cloned beef only after it had been sold and
eaten, and it was never identified as cloned when it was sold.
Moreover, the government at first had said that it knew of only two
cattle clones that had been sold; then, last Friday, it
dramatically raised the figure.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the meat from at least 66 cloned cattle, and
possibly as many as 144, had found its way to the marketplace,
along with the milk from four other cloned cows. Since 1990, Japan
has cloned 461 cows, mostly using the technique in which the
divided nuclei of fertilized eggs are transplanted into
unfertilized eggs. The result is that the cloned cow is like a
twin.
</P>
<P>
   The cloned beef was inspected and approved by inspectors and was
graded as ordinary beef, according to Hayato Iwamoto of the
Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries. Scientists have
reassured the public that eating cloned beef is safe, but people
are still wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew it was cloned beef, I'd hesitate to eat it,'' said
Nobuko Hiwasa, a spokeswoman for the National Liaison Committee of
Consumer Organizations. ``We would like information on what exactly
cloned beef is. Is it safe?''
</P>
<P>
   Yukio Tsunoda, a cloning scientist at Kinki University, said
that hormonal experiments on cattle breeding may be of more concern
than the risks of eating cloned beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``If excessive debate has aroused too much anxiety among the
public, there is a role maybe for the Agriculture Ministry to
investigate, clarify and carry out an awareness campaign before the
beef is shipped out,'' said Tsunoda, who has eaten cloned beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ordinary meat,'' she added. ``It is not that any genes
are manipulated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
