<HEADLINE>
WHERE CAN YOU FIND TONI MORRISON?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The corporate policy at Borders bookstores, says the latest
Mother Jones, is to shelve just about all books by black authors in
an African American literature section. This means that if you're
looking for a novel by  &UR; James Baldwin  &LR; or  &UR; Terry McMillan &LR; , or
 &UR; Toni Morrison &LR; 's latest, you probably won't find it in the general
literature section. According to the magazine, ``if a book's writer
is black, it gets coded as African American literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Although individual stores are permitted by the corporation to
cross-reference books, Mother Jones surveyed several and found that
10 out of 11 had failed to cross-reference Morrison's ``Paradise,''
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Several African American authors sounded off to Mother Jones:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Edgar Wideman &LR;  called separate shelving ``an implicitly
destructive practice.'' The notion that there is ``an intellectual
or aesthetic reason for putting black books in one place and white
books in another place perpetuates a lot of false ideas about
race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I profoundly resent the fact that my race is causing me to be
isolated and ghettoized,'' said  &UR; Shelby Steele &LR; . ``It hurts me as a
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all were outraged. ``I have mixed feelings about it,'' said
 &UR; Terry McMillan &LR; . ``On the one hand, you don't have Jewish American
sections or Irish American sections. So it's insulting and
flattering at the same time that we get our own special section. On
the other hand, since we are trying hard to eliminate color lines,
we should all just be included in literature.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sinead O'Connor &LR; , who once tore up a picture of the pope
during a TV broadcast, has been ordained a priest in the Latin
Tridentine Church, which is described as a ``Roman Catholic
splinter group'' in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor will use her new name,  &UR; Mother Bernadette Mary &LR; , in her
music career, too. ``Anyone who knows me knows that what I have
done makes perfect sense for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Judd Winick &LR; , who was the cartoonist on the third season of
MTV's ``The Real World'' _ it was based in San Francisco that year
_ will write a memoir about  &UR; Pedro Zamora &LR; , a fellow cast member
who died of AIDS. The book, which will be presented in cartoon
form, will be published by Henry Holt in the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Carol Handelman  &LR; forwards a photograph of the Gray Line
station at the Transbay Terminal, where English is listed as one of
the options in the ``Foreign Language Deluxe City Tour.'' And
continuing in the English-as-a-foreign-language theme, San
Francisco Supervisor  &UR; Mark Leno  &LR; calls the class' attention to the
remarks of departing Superintendent of Schools  &UR; Bill Rojas &LR; , as
quoted by Matier and Ross on Monday: `` &UR; Gray Davis  &LR; has got four
education bills and no money. I'd like to see more money and less
bills.'' FEWER bills, Mr. Educator, please.
</P>
<P>
   _ Matters of taste: The first call that Oritalia received Monday
in response to a New York Times travel piece the day before that
had named and described the ``five best new restaurants in San
Francisco'' _ MC-squared, Oritalia, Black Cat, Delfina and Oodles _
wasn't for a reservation. A woman in New York wanted to know where
she could buy the Venetian silk chandeliers the story had said were
in the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Billionaire  &UR; George Soros  &LR; has pledged $10 million to Brill's
Content, reports New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ A lawsuit filed by Working Wildlife, an L.A. agency that
handles animal talent, claims that the owners of  &UR; Gidget &LR; , the Taco
Bell dog, haven't been giving the agency its fair share of its
profits from ads in which the dog appears. The suit, quoted in the
New York Post, says that the ads' success ``is not attributable to
Gidget in particular, which does not actually speak _ the `speaking
dog' is actually a computer-generated effect _ and which is a
typical, nondescript Chihuahua dog.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEAR OLD DAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Forbes magazine asked a handful of captains of industry ``what
business lessons they learned from their fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a contemptible man,'' said  &UR; John Sperling &LR; ,
founder and CEO of the Apollo Group. ``I owe my success to not
following in his footsteps. He was lazy; I work very hard. He
frittered away his talent, and I nurtured mine. He was poor as a
church mouse, and I'm worth $550 million.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole `sensitive young artist' myth is bull.
Everyone I know who has any amount of success can be a real
bastard, and I certainly include myself that wild generalization.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eric Stoltz, quoted in Rolling Stone.
</P>
