<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GAMBLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT WEIGHS CASINO ADVERTISING CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, in a case with free-speech
implications, considered Tuesday whether Congress has violated the
First Amendment by prohibiting private casinos from broadcast
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ennis Jr., a lawyer for broadcasters, argued that the
Communications Act not only impinges on the free-speech rights of
private casino owners but hurts their businesses because gambling
houses on Indian reservations _ a fierce source of competition _
remain free to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy U.S. Solicitor General Barbara Underwood called the
statute a valid governmental effort to combat compulsive gambling
while allowing Indian tribes, which are sovereign, to continue to
advertise without federal interference.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices, however, appeared unconvinced that the ban is
really an effort to stop compulsive gambling. They said the
government allows broadcast advertisements of lotteries, horse
racing and other forms of addictive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The case the high court considered was an appeal by the Greater
New Orleans Broadcasting Association after a federal court and the
5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled the law constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis said the law is ``so riddled with exceptions'' that it
cannot achieve the government's legitimate interest. Ennis cited
the law's allowance for Indian tribes to advertise their casinos,
which, he said, cater to all kinds of gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said the government could
reasonably conclude that most compulsive gambling occurs at private
casinos and that the law is, therefore, a narrowly tailored,
constitutional method for reducing that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis said the government can constitutionally reduce compulsive
gambling without restricting free speech, such as by imposing
dollar limits on wagers at casinos and prohibiting gambling on
credit.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the government cannot constitutionally restrict
advertising of a legal activity _ an argument that drew fire from
several justices, who cited legal restrictions on cigarette
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood, the government's lawyer, argued that the federal
restriction on advertising is a legitimate method for reducing
compulsive gambling while ensuring that financially strapped Indian
tribes have access to the airwaves to advertise their casinos, a
lucrative source of income.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Stephen G. Breyer said the government could not
argue they were fighting compulsive gambling while they permit ads
that encourage people to wager at Indian casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The only justification the government can have is that ``you
want the money to go to a very worthy group,'' Breyer said,
referring to the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But Breyer, with Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, said he had
difficulty finding constitutional a law that restricts advertising
by one group while permitting its competitor to advertise freely.
</P>
<P>
   The Newspaper Association of America and other media
organizations urged the justices to rule the federal law
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
