<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BELLSOUTH-ATT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth, AT&AMP;T expect to suffer little
 &HT;    (EDS: This version replaces CoxNet-budgeted story,
BELLSOUTH-FINGERS.)
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth and AT&AMP;T have completed a series of joint
tests the companies say show their telephone systems are secure
from the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   Both systems passed with flying colors, demonstrating that
BellSouth and AT&AMP;T will suffer little, if any, loss of service when
computer systems reach Jan. 1, 2000, the companies say.
</P>
<P>
   ``These joint tests confirm the results of an enormous amount of
preliminary Year 2000 testing we have conducted internally _ that
call completion should not be affected by the century date
change,'' said Rick Harder, BellSouth's vice president with overall
responsibilities for the company's Year 2000 compliance program.
``This testing also shows how the telecommunications industry is
collaborating on an unparalleled level in addressing the Year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The tests were designed to see whether Atlanta-based BellSouth's
local telephone system will continue to connect reliably with
AT&AMP;T's long-distance network and vice versa after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In five interconnected labs, the companies ran 500 tests across
the country. The companies tested wireline-to-wireline telephones,
wireline-to-wireless and wireless-to-wireless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most comprehensive Year 2000 testing
efforts between a local exchange carrier and a long-distance
carrier to date,'' said Harder.
</P>
<P>
   Added John Pasqua, vice president of AT&AMP;T's Year 2000 program,
``We view preparing for Year 2000 as a cooperative effort, not a
competitive issue. We are publicly sharing what we have learned,
because our objective is to make the arrival of the new year
transparent to all telephone customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest successful tests reflect years of advance planning on
the part of both companies. The current project began in September
of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The recent test covered the most critical aspects of providing
local and long-distance telephone service, said the companies. They
said the testing included 911 emergency systems, local calls,
long-distance calls, toll-free calls, operator assistance, credit
cards and international calls.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is a $23 billion Baby Bell that serves the
Southeastern states. The company also provides wireless telephone
service, Internet access and wireless digital television service.
AT&AMP;T is the country's largest long-distance carrier but also
provides wireless telephone service and soon will offer cable TV in
some markets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
