<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
33,000 US RESERVISTS ON TAP FOR BALKANS DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Tuesday deepened US involvement
in the Balkan conflict by authorizing 33,102 reservists for active
duty, as a US envoy reported no breakthrough in talks with Russian
leaders in Moscow aimed at ending the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's move cleared the way for the largest mobilization of
US reserve forces since the Gulf War in 1991. In the first wave of
the deployment, the Pentagon immediately called up more than 2,100
members of the Air Force Reserve and Air National Guard from units
in eight states.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the additional 31,000 reservists, from every branch
of the military, are expected to be activated ``over the coming
days and weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The development was one of several indications that NATO's
assault on Yugoslavia, now in its fifth week, is unlikely to end
soon.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott reported
no significant progress in his talks with Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov and Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
Both sides were trying to bridge the vast diplomatic gulf between
NATO and Yugoslavia's embattled president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign the US government foresees no quick exit from
the conflict, Republicans in Congress were preparing to double
Clinton's request for $6 billion to fund the US role through
September in the NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
   The moves came as the United Nations for the first time
described the teeming refugee camps in Macedonia as ``hopelessly
overcrowded'' and Russia estimated the NATO campaign has already
destroyed $100 billion in Yugoslav property.
</P>
<P>
   These other developments unfolded on the 35th day of the NATO
airstrikes:
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO jets pounded Serb forces in round-the-clock attacks, and
one struck a civilian community in southern Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Local authorities in Surdulica, 200 miles south of Belgrade,
said at least 17 people were killed and 11 wounded when NATO
missiles struck the agricultural community Tuesday afternoon. The
dead and injured included women and children. Rescuers were
searching the rubble for more victims.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press reporter, taken to the scene by Serb police,
saw 50 destroyed homes and 600 damaged. Rescue workers said 11
people, including five children, were believed trapped in the
basement of one house.
</P>
<P>
   Explosions also rocked the Belgrade suburbs of Topcider, Senjak,
Resnik and Rakovica early Wednesday, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO leaders claimed that morale among Milosevic's troops has
grown so dismal that several hundred troops a week are deserting
their units and that the special police are going door to door to
roust reserve troops who have balked at calls to mobilize. And five
retired Yugoslav generals, apparently at odds with Milosevic,
reportedly have been placed under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO siege ``is adding to the chaos of war that Milosevic is
now suffering,'' said British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook. ``It is
creating confusion throughout his forces and adding to the stress
that is mounting on daily in the minds of his military commanders
and putting doubt in the mind of his forces on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Clinton administration prepared to impose an embargo on
all US exports to Serbia other than humanitarian supplies. The move
comes after reports that US oil companies have been delivering fuel
to Yugoslavia at the same time the US government has been trying
unsuccessfully to coordinate a global embargo against oil shipments
to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   -- The House International Relations Committee unanimously
rejected a resolution that would compel the United States to
declare war against Yugoslavia or withdraw from the conflict.
Another resolution calling for the United States to pull out of the
NATO operation entirely was defeated, 30-19.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures will be debated Wednesday by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rebuffing warnings from the White House, Reverend Jesse
Jackson said he will leave for Yugoslavia Wednesday with a
delegation of US religious leaders who hope to secure the release
of three American soldiers. The delegation includes Reverend
Raymond Glen Helmick, a Roman Catholic priest from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a perilous journey,'' Jackson said. ``If God be with us,
we'll succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said the group's safety cannot be
guaranteed and expressed concern that Milosevic would use their
mission for propaganda purposes. ``Ultimately, the decision is
theirs to make,'' said David Leavy, the White House national
security spokesman. ``Our responsibility, from our vantage point,
is to make clear the risks.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A Red Cross doctor examined the three US soldiers and found
them to be in satisfactory condition. Red Cross officials also
picked up letters home from the soldiers: Staff Sergeant Andrew A.
Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Staff Sergeant Christopher J. Stone of
Smiths Creek, Mich.; and Specialist Steven M. Gonzalez, 21, of
Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   -- Russia and China, which oppose the NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia, blocked the United Nations Security Council from
issuing a strong statement on the refugee crisis in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   In a related matter, the Pentagon confirmed that the first wave
of 20,000 Kosovar refugees who will be placed with relatives in the
United States will be processed and possibly housed temporarily at
Fort Dix in New Jersey. There was no indication when the refugees
will begin arriving.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees fleeing from
Milosevic's campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo descended on
six refugee camps, which already are clogged beyond capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian leaders, appealing for urgent financial aid from the
European Union, expressed fear that an additional 150,000 Kosovar
refugees will pour into their struggling nation, which will be too
destitute to provide any more help.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 140,000 refugees already have fled to Macedonia, a
fraction of the 1.4 million ethnic Albanians who have been driven
from their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hope for a swift settlement to the crisis had risen in recent
days after Chernomyrdin and a Yugoslav deputy premier, Vuk
Draskovic, each indicated Milosevic appeared open to negotiating a
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Chernomyrdin, after meeting Tuesday with Talbott and Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, said NATO ``will not be fully
satisfied'' with Milosevic's demand that he approve which countries
would participate in a peacekeeping mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
