<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKPLACE-STARWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK PLACE TO BUY CAESARS CASINOS FROM STARWOOD FOR $3 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a deal that will reshape the gambling business in Atlantic
City, N.J., and Las Vegas, Park Place Entertainment agreed Tuesday
to acquire the Caesars casino operations of Starwood Hotels &AMP;
Resorts for $3 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will create a serious rival in Atlantic City to Donald
Trump, where Park Place will have three casinos with nearly as much
gambling space as Trump's, while casinos owned by Park Place
Entertainment in Las Vegas will dominate three of the four corners
at the Strip and Flamingo Boulevard, the most valuable gambling
real estate site on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Park Place, a recent spinoff from Hilton Hotels,
jumped nearly 25 percent Tuesday, closing at $11.375, up $2.25,
while Starwood fell 68.75 cents, to $34.3125.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Park Place's cash flow, or earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization, will be about $1.3
billion, nearly twice that of the next largest gambling company,
Harrah's Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   For Starwood, the world's largest hotel company, the cash
payment will allow it to reduce its $8 billion of debt by more than
one-third, lowering interest charges enough to increase earnings by
about 7 cents a share in the first year, said Jim Gallagher, a
Starwood spokesman. ``This will bring us much closer to our goal of
being able to issue investment grade debt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the $3 billion price ``might represent a small loss''
for Starwood on the price it paid plus improvements to the casino
properties, which it acquired just 17 months ago. Others estimated
the loss at more than $500 million based on the purchase price and
investments Starwood made.
</P>
<P>
   Park Place chief executive Arthur Goldberg said: ``By acquiring
the Caesars brand name and related customer data base, we plan to
heavily cross market between our destination resorts. This will
boost revenues and expand the markets where we operate.''
</P>
<P>
   He projected savings of $50 million a year in operating costs, a
figure that two analysts said was probably low given Goldberg's
record of cutting costs in previous deals by as much as twice what
he promised.
</P>
<P>
   The deal to sell the casinos comes less than four months after
Park Place was created by spinning off Hilton's gambling
properties, including the Flamingo in Las Vegas and the Bally
casinos in Atlantic City and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is a triumph for two casino executives known for making
smart deals who joined forces in December 1996 when Hilton Hotels
acquired Bally Entertainment. One is Goldberg, who was a New Jersey
trucking company owner before 1990, when he took over Bally
Manufacturing, a debt-ridden maker of slot machines and operator of
casinos and health clubs. The other is Stephen Bollenbach, the
chief executive of Hilton and chairman of Park Place Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly all of 1997, the two men tried to buy the casino and
hotel properties of ITT Inc., the conglomerate run by Rand Araskog.
But Hilton dropped out of the bidding in December 1997, with
Bollenbach saying that the price ITT wanted was to high. Starwood
was the winning bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal leaves them gratified that they were right and that
this was the wrong acquisition for Starwood at the wrong price,''
said William Moore, an analyst at Forum Capital Markets in Old
Greenwich, Conn. ``This deal shows that they were justified that
they walked away when the price was too high, especially since the
guy who paid too much has to come back and sell to them. And Steve
Bollenbach likes to be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst, Jason Ader of Bear Stearns, said the deal
``could be a positive for the Atlantic City market because you will
have a greater concentration within fewer companies and are less
likely to have foolish marketing decisions'' such as big coin
giveaways to lure slot machine gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bad for the value gambler, good for the investors,''
Ader said of the expected tight rein on giveaways to customers.
</P>
<P>
   It cost 11 percent more to gamble at Bally's Park Place than
next door at Caesars, which was more willing to extend
complimentaries like free drinks for blackjack players and private
jets to fly in high rollers, a 1990 study by National Economic
Research Associates showed.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bally's Park Place, an extension of its gambling area called
Wild West and Caesars will be owned by the same company. Park Place
Entertainment also owns the Atlantic City Hilton, formerly the
Golden Nugget, at the south end of the Boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   These three Atlantic City properties will have 27.6 percent of
the gambling floor space, compared with 29.9 percent for the three
Trump casinos, according to records of the New Jersey Casino
Control Commission.
</P>
<P>
   On the Las Vegas Strip, Park Place will acquire Caesars Palace.
It already owns three casinos across the Strip from Caesars: the
Flamingo Hilton, Bally's Las Vegas and Paris, which is scheduled to
open in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal closes, the company will have 15 percent of the
casino space on the Strip and 18 percent of the hotel rooms, said
Adam Brecht, a spokesman for PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was a loss for Mirage Resorts Inc., which owns casinos
on each side of Caesars Palace in Las Vegas that its chief
executive, Steve Wynn, wants to connect with a monorail.
</P>
<P>
   Park Place is also acquiring Caesars casinos in Lake Tahoe,
Nev., riverboat casinos in Mississippi and Indiana, slot machines
at Dover Downs Race Track in Delaware and interests in various
gambling operations from Canada to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Park Place did not buy Starwood's Desert Inn, which, with its
own golf course on about 35 acres, is one of the large tracts of
developable land left along the Strip in Las Vegas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
