<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS 33,000 RESERVISTS CALLED UP FOR KOSOVO CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Pa., Mich., Calif., Ala., Wis., Ind., Kan.)  (See also KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA) 
(nk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton ordered a call-up of 33,102
reservists Tuesday, to serve up to nine months of active duty in
the Kosovo air campaign. It was the biggest military call-up since
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The first group of 2,100 air reservists and guard members who
are part of refueling tanker crews will be sent quickly to the
region. They are drawn from air bases in Arizona, Pennsylvania,
Michigan, California, Alabama, Wisconsin, Indiana and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   In authorizing the call-up, Clinton said in a statement Tuesday
that the remaining reservists would be sent in the coming days and
weeks ``from all branches of the service to fill critical support
positions in our humanitarian and combat operations in and around
the former Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank each reservist, their families and loved ones, and
their employers here at home for their service and sacrifice,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The call-up was set off by NATO's request for 300 more planes to
allow Gen. Wesley K. Clark, NATO's top military commander, to
expand the air campaign against Yugoslavia to a 24-hour operation
and to broaden the range of targets that NATO forces can attack in
Kosovo and the rest of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Refueling tankers that can keep the airplanes flying day and
night are essential to the operation. The first reservists include
the crews for 21 more KC-135E refueling tankers from the reserves.
Six more tankers will be sent to Kosovo from active duty.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of these 300 aircraft, the U.S. contribution
to the Kosovo air campaign is approaching the level of aircraft
used in a major war and could soon require nearly half of all of
the Air Force's refueling tankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be over the level of aircraft we had in Desert Storm,''
said Maj. Gen. Michael Kudlacz, deputy chief of staff for air and
space operations for the Air Force, referring to the operation
during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   A major review of American defense capabilities undertaken in
1997 concluded that the United States must be prepared to fight two
major wars as well as several contingency missions. The Kosovo air
operation began as the smaller type of mission, but has been
growing.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Clinton authorized the Air Force to enact an order
that prevents pilots and other critical service members from
retiring or leaving the Air Force before the Kosovo air war ends.
The Air Force will put the order into effect in the next several
days, said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new tankers will be based in Hungary, whose prime
minister said on Sunday that his nation _ the newest NATO member
and the only one bordering on Yugoslavia _ would open up its three
airfields to NATO aircraft for the war. An agreement was reached
between Hungary and NATO on Monday that allows the Pentagon to send
the new tankers and with them, the reserves being called up.
</P>
<P>
   In requiring the reservists to serve until next January, the
Pentagon said it was hoping to avoid the problems that arose during
the Gulf War, when some of the reservists were required to extend
their initial terms of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, we hadn't given enough days in the call-up and they
had to extend,'' said Maj. Gen. Jimmy Sherrard, commander of the
Air Force Reserve. ``That created real difficulties for them and
their families.''
</P>
<P>
   The call-up during the Gulf War also caused problems for the
employers of the reservists, leading to changes in the way the
reserve operates. Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said Tuesday that he
would introduce legislation that would help small businesses
employing reservists who are called up by providing loan deferments
and low-interest loan assistance from the Small Business
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The total call-up includes up to 25,000 reservists from the Air
Force, 892 reservists from the Navy, 1,000 from the Marines, 10
from the Coast Guard, and the rest from the Army, Kudlacz said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said, ``We'll move up to that total in a relatively quick
time.''
</P>
<P>
   With reservists already reporting for duty Tuesday at their
bases across the country, the Pentagon hoped to have the first
reservists off to Italy and Hungary by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the reservists put on active duty Tuesday were already
serving in the air operation as volunteers, said Sherrard. They
will be allowed to return home and make necessary preparations for
a return to active duty in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
