<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAKES NEW PUSH FOR RESTRICTIONS ON GUNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Plunging into a politically nettlesome issue in the
wake of last week's shooting at a Colorado high school, President
Clinton on Tuesday made a renewed push for a series of gun control
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by sympathetic lawmakers, the president offered his
gun initiatives, many of which have previously met with little
success in the GOP-controlled Congress. Republican leaders quickly
dismissed the president's proposals as a simplistic answer to
school violence. They proposed instead a national conference on
youth and culture.
</P>
<P>
   The key White House proposals are:
</P>
<P>
   Requiring background checks for those who purchase firearms at
gun shows and for those who buy explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Imposing felony penalties on adults who knowingly allow children
to gain access to guns that are used to cause injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the age of the youth handgun ban from 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Mandating safety locks on all guns.
</P>
<P>
   Requiring a three-day waiting period before the purchase of
guns. A waiting period had been required under the Brady Law, but
it had expired when instant background checks became available.
</P>
<P>
   Banning the importation of all large-capacity ammunition
magazines that allow the firing of more than 10 rounds of
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   In rolling out the gun initiatives, both the president and first
lady conceded that the killing of 12 students and a teacher in
Colorado by two students was the result of a complex mix of
factors, including violence in the media and on video games. But
they said access to guns was clearly part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is criminal how easy it is for children in America to
obtain guns,'' said Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``Guns and children are
two words that should never be put together in the same sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, however, reflected on the political resistance to
gun control, explaining that many Americans, including those in his
home state of Arkansas, are resistant to laws they unreasonably
fear would restrict their ability to hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the culture of violence that has to change; it's
the culture of hunting and sport shooting that has to stop
financing efforts to frighten their members, who are good,
God-fearing, law-abiding, tax-paying citizens out there, into
believing that every time you try to save a kid's life, it's a
camel's nose in the tent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that gun control should be compared to metal
detectors at the airport in that it is a necessary inconvenience
that ensures safer travel.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to criticism that gun control doesn't work, the
president said, ``we've got to get out of this crazy denial that
this won't make a difference Just because it won't make all the
difference doesn't won't mean it won't make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's gun control proposals have fared poorly in Congress
since the Republicans took control in 1994. And there was no
indication that GOP leaders would be more receptive this time
despite the Colorado shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., dismissed the
president's plan, calling it a ``typical knee-jerk reaction. Oh,
goodness, we've had a crime, therefore we need gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land, accused the
president of trying to exploit the high school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only say to the president that your legislation, no
matter how well it polls, will not solve the problems we face,''
DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to change the subject from gun control, Lott and House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, D-Ill., said they would commence a National
Conference on Youth that would turn to experts to examine a number
of issues facing students, including video games, drugs in schools
and parental involvement.
</P>
<P>
   While opposition to gun control has been strongest within the
Republican Party, even some Democrats have been wary of embracing
the issue that hurts their lawmakers from rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The top two Democrats in Congress, Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D. and House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.,
did not attend the White House event.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, who represents a largely rural state, said earlier this
week that he wasn't sure gun legislation was the answer to the
latest school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Even gun control proponents who attended the president's
announcement voiced skepticism that the measures would move through
Congress without strong public pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go to the congressional hearing. They'll say we'll look
at it and that will be the end until the next shooting,'' said Rep.
Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., whose husband was killed in a shooting on
the Long Island Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   However, McCarthy is an example of how gun control can be a
potent issue in the suburbs where many swing voters frown on GOP
resistance to restrictions on firearms. McCarthy beat a Republican
incumbent who opposed gun control.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
