<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING SUSPECT'S GIRLFRIEND BOUGHT GUNS, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The young woman who accompanied Dylan Klebold
to the senior prom purchased at least two of the four weapons used
in the April 20 massacre at Columbine High School, police said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Anderson, 18, who friends say is an honor roll student and
respected Klebold's quick wit and sharp mind, was interviewed by
police and released without being charged Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Anderson _ whom they identified as a witness and not
as suspect _ was not at school on the day of the shooting. But they
believe a semiautomatic pistol and a rifle used in the rampage were
purchased by Anderson at a Denver-area gun show late last year.
</P>
<P>
   As Littleton buried more of the victims Tuesday, Jefferson
County police continued pursuing the more than 350 tips they have
recieved since Klebold and Eric Harris carried out their deadly
assault on classmates.
</P>
<P>
   A Colorado Springs gun dealer, Mel Bernstein, phoned police
shortly after the shooting to say he recognized Harris as one
member of a group of teens who tried to buy guns in his store in
early March. Tuesday, police said a surveillance camera in
Bernstein's Dragon Arms store apparently did not capture Harris or
his friends on tape, but they do not discount his report.
</P>
<P>
   The information could prove valuable if Bernstein eventually can
identify acquaintances who were aware of the planned attack or were
involved in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them you had to be 21 years old'' to purchase a
handgun, Bernstein said in a telephone interview. ``That's when the
girl spoke up,'' Bernstein recalled, adding that he believed it was
Anderson, but wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Well I could by it for them,' '' Bernstein said.
But he said he asked the group of youths to leave the store before
they bought anything.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said he remembers Harris because he did most of the
talking for the group of teens, some wearing long black trench
coats, and that he asked most of the questions about the powerful
assault rifles for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has hired an attorney to represent her throughout the
investigation. She could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, an 18-year-old person can buy a rifle, but
not a pistol, from a federally licensed gun dealer. But Colorado
allows an 18-year-old to buy a handgun in a private sale, such as
those in gun shows. However, the buyer could not provide the
handgun to a person younger than 18.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold was 17, and Harris turned 18 earlier this month.
Anderson was 18 last November.
</P>
<P>
   Police also said Tuesday that they have confirmed that Harris
and Klebold both shot and killed themselves, clearing up questions
about whether they died in a murder-suicide or not. Police also
disclosed that they have now recovered more than 60 homemade
explosives from the hallways of the high school, and from several
vehicles in the school lot.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Sheriff's Department spokesman Steve Davis said
investigators believe it is ``likely'' that Harris and Klebold had
help planting the explosives and carrying four weapons, including
two sawed-off shotguns, to school.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said police continue to theorize that Harris and Klebold,
who both attended the junior-senior prom on the night of Saturday,
April 17, spent time prowling the hallways and hiding explosives
while their classmates danced in the gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   The boys killed 12 students and one teacher, and wounded 20
others. Ten students remain hospitalized, and Monday, 18-year-old
Valeen Schnurr was released from the hospital, a homecoming that
freiends called a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Schnurr was, like her friend Cassie Burnall, asked by one of the
presumed killers whether she believed in God. Moments after she
replied that she did, she was shot four times. She survived, though
her close friend Burnall, who is being remembered as a Christian
martyr for confirming her faith to the gunmen, did not.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine High School students will resume classes Monday. They
will share Chatfield High School with their peers, with students
from each of the schools attending clases for a half-day.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday at 11:21 a.m. there was a city-wide moment of silence
marking the one week that has passed since Harris and Klebold
declared war on Columbine High. Investigators continue to use a
diary dicovered in Harris's bedroom to help lead them to friends
and acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   In the diary, Harris refers to himself under the code name
``Rebel'' _ apparently lifted from Columbine High School's Rebels
athletic teams. And he refers to Klebold with the moniker
``Vodka.''
</P>
<P>
   One of their victims, Dan Rohrbugh 15, was buried Tuesday, and
several students in this sprawling high school who had never met
him stepped to a podium to recall how he held a school door open
while hundreds escaped, only to be shot just as he was stepping to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Tuesday at the funeral of Kyle Velasquez, 16, the Rev.
Wayne Lagrone urged mourners to look for answers to widespread
societal violence within themselves and to fight against evil.
Lagrone said: ``There is no doubt in my mind those two young
assailants were acting under satanic intervention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
