<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood takes outing in stride
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The difference for Kevin Millwood came down to two
inches. That's how much he shortened his stride on the mound Monday
night, which freed up his delivery and resulted in his most
effective start not only this season but perhaps over his last 16
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret that Kevin has a tendency to get spread out all
over the place, especially when he reaches back for something
extra,'' said pitching coach Leo Mazzone. ``That will throw him off
target.''
</P>
<P>
   With a slightly shortened stride at Florida, Millwood limited
the Marlins to four hits in 7 1/3 innings, his lowest hit yield
dating back to July 4th, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just shortened (his stride) a little bit,'' Millwood said.
``I really wasn't even thinking about that while I was pitching. I
was just trying to slow down, throw a lot smoother. Try to be more
free and easy.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. After the Marlins nicked him for two runs in the
fourth, Millwood retired the next 12 men he faced. He allowed just
one hit to the last 15 batters. He was only charged with the third
run after reliever Kevin McGlinchy walked consecutive batters to
force in Bruce Aven, who has singled off Millwood to open the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the lineup
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko made his first start at first base in 13 days while
nursing a sore right hamstring. He had just one at-bat in the last
nine games entering Tuesday night, interrupting a strong 11-for-27
start from the season-opening homestand.
</P>
<P>
   But while Klesko used nearly two weeks to recover, third baseman
Chipper Jones was back in action after sitting out just one game
with a strained left adductor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel it's bad enough to keep me out,'' Jones said. ``I
feel I could do some damage to it but I'm not going to sit by and
watch. Can't do it. Go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   No hurry
</P>
<P>
   Though right-hander Russ Springer has pitched effectively on his
re-hab assignment at Class AAA Richmond, the Braves aren't
comfortable enough to activate him. After a pair of extended spring
training appearances, he has pitched in three Richmond games,
retiring nine of the 10 men he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bounced back and is throwing the ball very well,''
general manager John Schuerholz said. ``He's very, very close. In
fact, he is ready. It's just a matter of being certain that we
protect him and protect ourselves. Because that's a substantial
operation the guy had.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely three months have passed since Springer had parts of a
herniated disk removed from his lower back. He should be activated
by the second week of May.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves stole 19 bases in their first 18 games. The club did
not reach 19 last season until the 33rd game, on May 6. . . The
Braves opened the night with a .281 team average, 44 points higher
than when they left town April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
