<SLUG> BC-GUNS-YOUTHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN SHOWS JUST ONE EASY SOURCE FOR GUNS, OBSERVERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The law of the land is that a person must be at
least 18 to buy a rifle or a shotgun, and 21 years of age to
purchase a handgun. But reality tells a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Buying firearms, including a sawed-off shotgun, is sometimes as
easy for a teenager as buying a pack of cigarettes, gun control
advocates say and federal agents privately confirm. It is as easy
as surfing the net or the newspaper for ads, finding a pal to buy a
gun for you, or going to one of the more than 5,000 gun shows
annually.
</P>
<P>
   There, minors can find an unlicensed dealer to unwittingly or
uncaringly sell them a firearm without having to worry about
background checks, waiting periods, paper trails _ or coming under
the scrutiny of federal agents who have an unwritten policy of not
attending such shows unless they believe an illegal transfer is
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say a woman identified as Robyn K. Anderson, the
18-year-old girlfriend of Colorado high school gunman Dylan
Klebold, apparently attended a Denver-area gun show late last year
where she apparently bought at least two of the weapons used to
kill a dozen students and a teacher last week.
</P>
<P>
   State laws on possessing and transferring firearms are more
lenient than laws governing firearm purchases by minors. In some
states, such as Texas and Wyoming, an individual does not have to
be 18 _ or even 15 or 10 _ to possess a handgun. And in almost half
the states, there is no minimum age requirement for minors
possessing a rifle or a shotgun, according to a review of state
laws by Handgun Control Inc. That includes the Hi-Point 9mm
semiautomatic rifle gun-control advocates say has the features of a
military-style assault weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's law made it legal for Anderson to give the shotguns,
if their barrels were not sawed off, and the rifle she apparently
bought shortly after her 18th birthday to Klebold, as long as she
did not know that the weapons would be used in a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has not been arrested and appears to be cooperating
with authorities, who stopped short of describing her as a suspect
but who are now reportedly trying to determine whether she had
knowledge of the planned massacre.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in a speech Tuesday implored Congress to pass
legislation closing the ``gun-show loophole,'' which allows
hobbyists and gun collectors _ some of whom are actually dealers _
to sell guns without filing any paperwork or conducting background
checks. Guns can literally disappear without a trace at these
shows, which agents from the Bureau of Alcohol Tobacco and Firearms
say are popular among criminals as well as law-abiding citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Such a measure even has the backing of the gun industry's
lobbying group, the American Shooting Sports Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ASSC board of directors supports increased funding for the
ATF and ... the concept of background checks and a paper trail for
those purchasing guns at gun shows,'' said Jack Adkins, the
association's director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike gun shows, little is known about the use of the Internet
to buy weapons, but gun control advocates warn that it has the
potential to become an unregulated arms bazaar that is vulnerable
to fraudulent transations and is attractive to teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet provides instant access to a wide variety of
guns,'' said Kristen Rand, director of federal policy at the
Violence Policy Center in Washington, a gun-control research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has an endless source of ads and opportunities to buy guns.
But the real danger is that the Internet is completely blind: The
seller can't see the buyer and evaluate if that person looks young
or unbalanced or suspicious. Gun laws are designed for face-to-face
transactions, which the Internet erases, and that is really
dangerous,'' Rand said.
</P>
<P>
   The other alleged gunman, Eric Harris, may have been among five
teenagers who last month tried to buy an MP-5 automatic rifle and
an M-60 machine gun from a gun dealer who said he refused to sell
the firearms because the group appeared to be under age, according
to news accounts. Federal agents, however, have said the videotape
provided by the gun dealer was inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, it is illegal for anyone to buy a machine gun
without applying for a license, filling out an application, and
paying a tax to the ATF.
</P>
<P>
   But most states have dramatically tightened restrictions on
buying and possessing sawed-off shotguns. There is, however, a
healthy ``secondary market'' for automatics like machine guns and
the high-capacity magazines they require, according to the ATF and
gun specialists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
