<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-TENSIONS-COX     04-27 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-TENSIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Threats of violence in abundance after school shooting
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A week after the bloody attack at a Colorado high
school, a wave of bomb threats and rumors at Georgia schools has
frayed nerves even further, leaving communities tense and nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a level of apprehension everywhere,'' said Alan Wood,
principal of Newnan High School in Coweta County.
</P>
<P>
   Across the U.S., scores of students have been suspended for
calling in bomb threats, threatening classmates and teachers, and
wearing black trench coats like those worn by the two Columbine
High School seniors who killed a dozen classmates and a teacher
before turning their guns on themselves. On Tuesday, all 146 public
schools in Washington, D.C., were evacuated after a caller warned a
bomb would go off in one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes of high school evacuations are also repeating across
metro Atlanta. Since the April 20 massacre in Littleton:
</P>
<P>
   _ Babb Middle School in Forest Park, Ga. was evacuated Thursday,
Friday and Monday due to bomb scares.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Tuesday, Brookwood High School in Snellville and Norcross
High School were evacuated after bomb threats. Norcross students
returned after police, accompanied by a bomb-sniffing dog, searched
the building. Those at Brookwood, where a fake pipe bomb was found,
were sent home for the day.
</P>
<P>
   _ DeKalb county police arrested a 15-year-old Cedar Grove High
School student Monday who told school officials he was going to
blow up the school. Police searched his house with his parents'
permission but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the grounds of Brookwood High filled with
nervous agitation as 2,700 students were evacuated and more than
100 scared parents descended on the school. Parents watched
anxiously, some crying with each other, a few gathering for a
prayer. Several parents who found their children hugged them
dearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent four days crying for those children'' in Colorado,
said Deb Callewaert, who has two daughters at Brookwood. ``Now I
have to wonder if it's going to happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Adam Mailliez was standing in front of the school,
waiting for a field trip to the Gwinnett jail to begin, when police
cars screamed into the parking lot and officers ordered students
into an outdoor stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are all paranoid now,'' he said, adding he figured it
was a hoax from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the students took it lightly. As freshman Cassie
Callewaert walked out of her classroom she locked arms with a
friend. ``You're my bodyguard,'' she told him, stressing they must
stay together.
</P>
<P>
   Once assured of their children's safety, parents' anger toward
the prankster came out. ``I want to wring that person's neck,''
said Joan Kline.
</P>
<P>
   At Norcross High School, where 2,000 students waited 90 minutes
on the football bleachers, the upset was made worse by the slaying
Saturday in Atlanta of a popular social studies teacher. A
makeshift memorial to Philip Rau stood near the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy. One day a teacher dies and the next there's a bomb
scare,'' said Melissa Reyes, a 19-year-old senior.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, students and educators seemed at a loss to explain the
rash of anti-social acts, coming at a time of national mourning and
healing. Many said they're shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as though every crazy person in the world has come out
after Columbine,'' said Brookwood parent Teresa Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened sense of vulnerability has spurred many people to
action. School phones have been ringing off the hook as parents
call inquiring about security measures. Cobb County schools are
reporting high levels of absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, which usually declines to
report on bomb scares, has noted the recent threats and the
accompanying unrest.
</P>
<P>
   A hastily organized group in Norcross, which calls itself the
National School safety Advocate Association, says it has 500
signatures supporting more police in county schools.
</P>
<P>
   School security has risen to the top of many communities'
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Daniel Elementary School in Dacula has taken to locking its
back doors to ensure visitors enter only though the front of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Alpharetta City Council member Debbie Gibson has asked
police Chief Dana Davis to offer free security checks at local
schools. ``School administrators and parents are not experts in
security,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even seemingly minor school incidents are receiving significant
attention.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, Cherokee County police have arrested a handful
of students for threatening other students or teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's society, and in light of what just happened, you
can't take anything too lightly,'' said Cherokee Sheriff Roger
Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   A Cobb County second-grader was suspended for a day when he
brought a bullet to school. The boy told the principal that he
found it on a playground in Atlanta. School officials met with the
boy's mother.
</P>
<P>
   But as people scramble for news, rumors are quickly taking on
the ring of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, rumors among students of a bomb hidden on the
grounds at Lovejoy High School in Clayton County prompted an
evacuation. Again, nothing was found.
</P>
<P>
   In Cherokee, rumors of a bomb spread quickly on morning buses,
reaching panicked parents who called the police. Detectives did not
find a bomb, but the rumors spread so fast that National Public
Radio had called the sheriff's office within five hours.
</P>
<P>
   So numerous have been the rumors that Pope High School principal
David Shumake sent a letter to Cobb parents stressing that rumors
are being investigated and that none have proven to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened unrest is also revealed in the diary of
10-year-old Roger Garza, a student at Canton Elementary School in
Cherokee whose mother offered her son's thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so scared coming to school after what happened to the
high school,'' Roger wrote. ``I need to stop worrying about it.
Watch over me please.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Schneider writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Don Plummer, Bill Montgomery, Kimberly Byrd, Mark
Bixler, Diane Stepp, Jennifer Brett, Ralph Ellis, Michael Weiss,
Rick Badie, Robin McDonald, Gabriella Boston and Delbert Ellerton
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
