<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT REFUSES TO BAN GIFT-GIVING BY LOBBYISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A unanimous Supreme Court on Tuesday dealt a
victory to lobbyists who wine and dine federal bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   In its 9-0 ruling, the court said U.S. law allows people to give
gifts to officials so long as they are not given in return for or
in expectation of a favorable act by the officials.
</P>
<P>
   The decision marked another defeat for independent counsel
Donald Smaltz, whose lengthy investigation and prosecution of
former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy resulted in Espy's acquittal
in December on 30 counts of accepting illegal gifts from
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Sun-Diamond Growers of California was caught in Smaltz's
investigation, having been found guilty by the U.S. District Court
in Washington of illegally treating Espy to 1993 U.S. Open Tennis
Tournament tickets, $2,427 worth of luggage, $665 in meals, and a
framed print and crystal bowl worth a total of $524.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court, agreeing with the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Washington, overturned the conviction. The justices
ruled that the federal law prohibiting the payment of gratuities to
U.S. officials did not apply to Sun-Diamond's gifts to Espy unless
Smaltz could show a link between them and a specific ``official
act'' Espy had performed or that Sun-Diamond wanted him to perform.
</P>
<P>
   In their decision, the justices said the district court had
erroneously interpreted the statute as barring people and companies
from giving gifts to an official simply because of his or her
official position.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz, in a prepared statement, expressed disappointment with
the high court's decision, saying it ``allows too much latitude to
those who would attempt to buy governmental favor.'' The
independent counsel, however, said he would ``respect'' the high
court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who believe that no one should be allowed to give
gifts to public officials to purchase goodwill or curry favor,
regardless of the specificity with which the desired official acts
can be identified, any future refinement of this law must come from
Congress, or from the Office of Government ethics, whose
regulations govern the behavior of governmental officials in the
executive branch,'' Smaltz said.
</P>
<P>
   The American League of Lobbyists, which represents more than 500
government-relations professionals, hailed the court's decision for
recognizing that in Washington lobbyists and officials ``interact
all the time'' for social and political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, not all gifts are intended to be a bribe,
said Thomas Susman, the league's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
