u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NYT &LR;      04-27 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA POISED TO PASS SCHOOL VOUCHER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In a move that critics say will cause an exodus from
struggling inner-city schools but one that advocates believe will
save them, Gov. Jeb Bush and leaders in the Florida Legislature
have agreed to allow children in the lowest-rated schools to attend
private institutions with state-paid tuition.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which was a cornerstone of Bush's campaign for
governor, will make Florida the only state to use public education
funds for vouchers that will pay the way for students to attend
private schools. including religious schools.The measure is
expected to pass in the House and Senate this week, perhaps as
early as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the State House and Senate, both controlled by
Republicans, worked out an agreement on Monday on a bill that Bush
will sign ``with a smile on his face,'' said Nicolle Devenish,
press secretary to the Republican governor, who is also frequentlty
mentioned as the party's most attractive presidential candidate in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which is also intended to pay the way for children in
failing schools to attend higher-rated public schools, will assign
every state public school a grade _ A, B, C, D or F _ based on
standardized test scores. Students who attend schools rated ``F''
can, on the request of their parents, be awarded vouchers of about
$4,000 _ called ``opportunity scholarships'' _ no matter what a
student's grades are.
</P>
<P>
   It is an issue that has consumed much of Bush's first term, as
he put the issue ahead of all other business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half our kids graduate from high school,'' said Bush. ``Half
are reading below basic levels in the fourth grade. This is vital
for our long-term competetiveness as a state, vital for restoring
our civil society. It pushes the resources and attention where it
needs to be. It will improve public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which will begin in September with four schools that
have tested poorly in the past _ one near Orlando, one outside
Tallahassee and two in Pensacola _ and gradually be expanded to
include all 3,000 public schools in the state, is seen by
proponents as a bold initiative to reform a system that has been
held back by teachers' unions and school administrators afraid of
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child in a failing school will now have the option to go
to a school where he or she can learn,'' said State Representative
Alex Diaz de la Portilla, a Republican from Westchester in
Miami-Dade County who is one of the plan's strongest proponents.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the plan said it violates the constitutional division
of church and state. And here in south Florida, where many
inner-city schools are expected to score low in the planned
standardized testing, they say it will worsen things by taking
their best students, and their state financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you will have is a massive exodus of students leaving the
public schools,'' said State Rep. James Bush, a Democrat from Miami
whose district, which includes Liberty City, Overtown and Opa
Locka, is the poorest in the state. ``You're going to lose
teachers,'' as enrollment drops and tax dollars dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   Other states, including Texas and Pennsylvania, are considering
such a plan, and some cities, including Milwaukee and Cleveland,
already have such systems in place, said Jeanne Allen, president of
the Center for Education Reform, a non-profit research group based
in Washington. Maine and Vermont have long-standing voucher
programs that allow a small number of students in rural areas who
do not live near schools.
</P>
<P>
   Other school systems, including the New York City system, have
considered using vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes this unique,'' said Ms. Allen, ``is that it is not
a simple program that pulls kids out of school. It puts schools on
notice that they will lose their good students unless they are
quality schools.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it is the first time a state has laid down ``immediate
consequences for pitiful results.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan would increase financing for schools that improve, as
it decreases financing to failing ones, as enrollment drops. While
state officials are unsure how many of Florida's 2 million students
would be affected, ``this could potentially be in the tens of
thousands or hundreds of thousands,'' said Ms. Allen.
</P>
<P>
   In cities that have voucher programs, anywhere from 5 to 30
percent of students take advantage of the program, said Brewser
Brown, chief of staff for Lt. Gov. Frank Brogan.
</P>
<P>
   There is not special allocation for the vouchers themselves,
just a re-distribution of state tax money already earmarked for
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money follows the child,'' said Brown. If a private
school's tuition is less than the amount _ about $4,000 _
earmarked, that money goes back into the state treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Under this legislation, public school students from the third
grade through through the 10th would be tested every year under a
vigorous new state test called the Florida Comprehensive Assessment
Test, and those cumulative scores would be used to rate the school.
De la Portilla said as many as 160 of the state's 3,000 schools
could get a failing grade.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Yarger, dean of the Scool of Education at the University of
Miami, said the plan ``very viable, politically,'' but one that
breaks down in the realities of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you allow vouchers,'' Yarger said, ``the students who
voucher out of public schools will be those whose parents care
about them,'' because they will have to provide transportation and
make other arrangements for their children, said Yarger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids who are left behind are the kids who are poor, whose
parents don't have the concern,'' he said. ``They will be left in
the school. That residual student body will demonstrate more
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bush said it is unfair to grade all schools by
the same standards. ``Traditionally, most inner-city schools don't
receive the resources that they should to catch up with schools
that have adequate books and computers and support staff and those
things that give some schools an upper hand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Small schools, which hold a warm place in the history of their
communities, would just disappear, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said another aspect of his education reform _ including
a $500 million increase in the education budget to tutor students
in those schools that were at risk of receiving a failing grade _
would make the eventual implementation of the program in inner
cities and rural areas more equitable.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle over the plan has raged, largely along party
lines, some private school principals have said they do not know if
they can accept the students or if the $4,000 voucher will cover a
year's tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle could be its legality. ``This will definitely
end up in court,'' Ms. Allen said. But provisions in the plan that
bar mandatory prayer in the class could help in pass its challenge
in the courts. ``This is about choice, not about religion,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
