</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-NATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S BOMBING OF CIVILIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NATO bombing of Serbia's state-run radio and television
headquarters in Belgrade last week, which killed at least 12 people
_ 20 more bodies may be buried in the rubble _ was unwarranted and
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing to defy the Geneva Conventions protecting civilians
and journalists in a war zone, NATO not only tempts Slobodan
Milosevic to retaliate against the many foreign journalists
covering the Balkan conflict; it loses moral ground in its stand
against the Yugoslav president's butchery.
</P>
<P>
   Misha Glenny, a Balkans expert, sees ``no tangible benefit''
from the strike, noting that TV was back on throughout Serbia
within five hours. ``The whole operation gave Milosevic a boost,''
says Glenny. ``Like so much of this campaign, it was ill-conceived,
arrogant, and counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO justifies the bombing by insisting that state-run media
constitute a propaganda machine that spreads hate and
misinformation and so should not be afforded the protections
guaranteed a free press. But that logic is ethical hair-splitting,
for while reporters presenting outright lies as fact deserve
contempt, they certainly do not deserve to die.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the NATO summit meeting in Washington on Sunday,
President Clinton attacked Milosevic for the ``murder of innocent
people'' and for knowing ``only one way to achieve his aims _
through force.'' The West exhibited a similar, one-track,
militaristic mind-set in bombing the broadcasting center.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was particularly troubling because NATO officials
gave assurances earlier this month that broadcasting transmitters,
not journalists, would be targeted, according to Amnesty
International and the Committee to Protect Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations, the Internet, and information air drops provide
ample opportunity to counter the heinous spin Milosevic puts on the
murder of innocents. The United States and its allies would be most
credible in their battle to defend human rights if they blasted
this poison with the firepower of the truth, not bombs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
