<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-ART-900     04-27 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-ART-900 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T PROFIT SURGES 42 PERCENT ON COST CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
 &AMP;ADD-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as it continued its flurry of deal-making, AT&AMP;T Corp. on
Tuesday reported strong financial results for the first quarter
that exceeded analysts' expectations. But investors did not rush to
buy AT&AMP;T's shares amid continued uncertainty about the company's
unsolicited $58 billion bid to acquire MediaOne Group Inc., the big
cable television company.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for AT&AMP;T, the nation's biggest communications company,
rose 42 percent over the first quarter of last year, largely
because of an aggressive cost-cutting campaign by C. Michael
Armstrong, the company's chairman of 18 months. More important,
AT&AMP;T showed signs of finally emerging from the revenue funk it had
been stuck in for years, boosting sales by more than 6 percent over
the comparable period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, AT&AMP;T also announced a partnership with Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone, the world's biggest phone company, to
provide comprehensive packages of communications services to
multinational corporations in Japan and perhaps other parts of
Asia. AT&AMP;T has formed a separate joint venture with British
Telecommunications PLC, and if AT&AMP;T can work well with both
partners, it will have gone a long way toward realizing its global
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   But it is AT&AMP;T's ambitions in the United States that continue
both to invigorate and worry investors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main questions facing Wall Street, not to mention
MediaOne's board, which had already agreed to sell its company to
Comcast Corp., is how feasible AT&AMP;T's offer really is from a legal
and regulatory perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, those are questions that also preoccupy Comcast,
which needs to gauge AT&AMP;T's offer before deciding whether to make a
serious counterbid of its own. Executives close to Comcast said
Tuesday that while that company had weighed a variety of options,
it had not yet decided how to respond to the AT&AMP;T bid.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal development for Comcast would be for William Kennard,
chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, to denounce
AT&AMP;T's plan for MediaOne as ``unthinkable,'' just as Kennard's
predecessor, Reed Hundt, did when AT&AMP;T tried to merge with SBC
Communications Inc., one of the Bell local phone companies, in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But that seems unlikely, and not just because Kennard is more
diplomatic than Hundt. The regulations governing concentration of
ownership in the cable television industry are in limbo, and it is
not clear that anyone in the industry, even Comcast, necessarily
wants them resolved in a way that would prevent AT&AMP;T from acquiring
MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Congress directed the FCC to draft rules to prevent the
cable television industry from becoming an oligopoly. In response,
the commission issued regulations saying that generally, no one
company could own cable systems that covered more than 30 percent
of homes in the United States in which cable television was
available. These days, cable is available to about 95 million of
the nation's roughly 100 million households.
</P>
<P>
   A loophole in the rules said that a company could expand its
stake to 35 percent if it did so by acquiring cable companies
controlled by members of racial minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's rules were challenged by Daniels Cablevision
Inc., which persuaded a federal judge in Washington to declare that
the law requiring the FCC's concentration rules violated the cable
carriers' First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   In response to that decision, the commission suspended its
rules. Since 1993 the case has been sitting before a federal
appeals court in Washington, where it could drag on for another
year.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows what, if any, restrictions on cable
concentration will eventually be implemented and upheld. And that
makes it difficult to determine the relative regulatory merits of
AT&AMP;T's and Comcast's bids for MediaOne. In fact, both bids might be
in violation of the original rules.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast, including its deal to acquire Jones Intercable, owns
cable systems offering service to about 9.4 million homes. MediaOne
offers service to about 8.5 million homes. Together that is about
18 million homes, considerably fewer than the 28.5 million that
would form 30 percent of the nation's 95 million cable-accessible
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The potential problem is MediaOne's 25.5 percent stake in Time
Warner Entertainment, a venture that includes most of Time Warner
Inc.'s cable operations. The stayed FCC rules say that any active
investor that owns more than 5 percent of a cable operation must
count all of the homes potentially served by that operation in
calculating their 30 percent limit. Time Warner may pass as many as
18 million homes. Including those systems would boost Comcast's
reach to as many as 36 million homes, far above the old limit.
</P>
<P>
   For AT&AMP;T, the potential problem is much worse. With its purchase
of Tele-Communications Inc., AT&AMP;T already owns cable systems that
pass 18 million homes. Add in MediaOne and Time Warner and the
figure becomes as high as 44.5 million. And that does not even
include TCI's myriad affiliates, which pass another 13 million
homes.
</P>
<P>
   So in the battle for MediaOne, both AT&AMP;T and Comcast need
whatever new rules that emerge to be quite a bit more lenient than
the current regulations. For Comcast, the trick is to have the
rules relaxed a bit, so it can acquire MediaOne, but not enough to
enable AT&AMP;T to do the same thing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As complex (and potentially moot) as the stayed cable rules are,
Time Warner Entertainment could pose yet another potential problem
for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   When Time Warner acquired Turner Broadcasting System Inc., John
Malone, who was then chairman of TCI and who had a big stake in
Turner, agreed not to acquire any more Time Warner stock. Comcast
could contend that Malone's agreement now applies to AT&AMP;T and that
AT&AMP;T would violate that deal by acquiring MediaOne and assuming its
stake in Time Warner Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's response to that possibility is that the Malone agreement
applies only to Liberty Media, the programming operation that is
publicly traded as an AT&AMP;T tracking stock but in which AT&AMP;T has no
economic interest. That leaves AT&AMP;T itself free to invest in Time
Warner Entertainment (or Time Warner Inc., for that matter), AT&AMP;T
says.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about AT&AMP;T's MediaOne bid (which also include concerns
about the deal's dilution of AT&AMP;T's future earnings) may have
obscured a robust quarterly financial report for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Including the effects of a recent 3-for-2 stock split _ but not
including one-time charges and the effects of the TCI acquisition,
which was completed last month _ AT&AMP;T earned $1.78 billion, or 67
cents a share, up from $1.25 billion, or 46 cents a share, in the
comparable period last year. That beat the 63 cent average estimate
of analysts polled by First Call, a financial research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Including the effects of the TCI deal and special charges, AT&AMP;T
earned $1.08 billion, or 38 cents a post-split share, down from
$1.3 billion, or 48 cents a share, in the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Propelled by strong gains in the company's wireless unit and in
sales to business customers, AT&AMP;T's revenue, excluding TCI,
increased by 6.1 percent, to $13.61 billion from $12.83 billion
during the comparable period last year. Including TCI, revenue
increased almost 10 percent, to $14.1 billion from $12.83 billion.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's stock closed Tuesday at $53, up 6.25 cents on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
