<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FORESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROADS TO RUIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration can improve its already strong
environmental record if it presses ahead with restrictions on road
construction in 33 million National Forest acres that are open to
logging and mining. It has already placed an 18-month moratorium on
road building, but conservationists are concerned that the
prohibition will be eased following an in-house study of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The road ban effectively blocks logging and mining operations
and preserves the natural character of the forests. The 33 million
acres represent about a sixth of the entire National Forest acreage
but are little over half the 60 million acres that environmental
groups like the Heritage Forest Campaign have identified as
deserving permanent protection from invasive activities.
</P>
<P>
   The areas, primarily in the West and Alaska, are important not
only as forests but for watershed protection. Wilderness roads,
usually unpaved, create erosion problems in hilly terrain. Over the
years, nearly 400,000 miles of them have been built, giving access
to forest areas otherwise beyond the reach of loggers or miners.
</P>
<P>
   Setting aside the entire 33 million acres permanently would not
deprive lumbering interests of all logging opportunities. Nearly
100 million acres have been logged over the years, and in time they
will produce commercially useful timber again to supplement acreage
in private hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service's chief, Michael Dombeck, has built a good
reputation for restraint during his tenure despite constant
pressure from industry and congressional supporters of maximum
economic development. He deserves support from Clinton
administration officials who have staked out strong stands on
environmental issues _ notably Vice President Al Gore, Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman, and Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt.
Without such backing, the danger is that the Forest Service might
yield to demands that these forest areas, which belong to the
American people, be sacrificed to short-term business interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
