<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NUHN-COL-SCONNIE-     04-27 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUHN-COL-SCONNIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Penn stays for family
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Coaches say it, commentators say it, columnists
say it.
</P>
<P>
   But you wonder if the kids listen.
</P>
<P>
   You fear they don't. You fear the words go off into the
atmosphere and dissipate like smoke.
</P>
<P>
   But now, on Tuesday, here was Scoonie Penn saying it. Standing
deep inside the Schottenstein Center, he said he was staying at
Ohio State to play basketball his senior year for a number of
reasons. ``One of the most important things,'' Scoonie said, ``is
that I get to walk across the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, walk across the stage and grab his diploma as if it's a
long rebound come home to roost. Become the first member of his
family to do so. ``That's something my family wanted to see,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I reminded him that several times this past season he told me he
didn't like studying. I had told him I was the same way when I was
in school, that that feeling wasn't limited to jocks.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him how hard that was when he was making his decision
not to put his name into the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too hard,'' he said. ``I know what's important. I know
what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   So, if all goes well, he will graduate after winter quarter next
year with a degree in sociology, and he will not be dependent on
his considerable basketball skills to get him through life.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone open his eyes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``It just came with maturity. You grow
up and all your focus is on your dreams, your goal _ to become a
professional athlete. It was hard to see anything else, and that's
all I wanted. I still want it, but I realize there are other things
in life.''
</P>
<P>
   He has set a standard for more than his family. He has set a
standard for other college athletes thinking of leaving school
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took some time to realize how important education is,'' the
kid from Boston said. ``As you grow up, you always hear a lot about
it, but as you grow older, you watch guys go into the NBA and other
professional sports and you see how their lives turn out. And after
their sports, they really don't have much to fall back on. You
know, it makes you think.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he did.
</P>
<P>
   Think.
</P>
<P>
   In the four weeks since OSU's season ended with a loss to
Connecticut in a national semifinal game, Penn has spent a lot of
time discussing it with his family, his teammates and his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was his life. His decision.
</P>
<P>
   Well done.
</P>
<P>
   With head coach Jim O'Brien on vacation, assistant coach Rick
Boyages put Scoonie's decision into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very unique,'' Boyages said. ``Very very mature. Very
responsible. Very mentally strong. Tough. I'm not surprised that
wanting a degree would factor in more for him than for the normal
college athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, a couple of us stood out in the arena with Scoonie. The
wooden floor was gone and we stood on concrete. He was wearing a
Boston Red Sox baseball cap, so the conversation flowed into
baseball. He said he had been a diehard New York Mets fan in fourth
grade and when that ball went through Bill Buckner's legs in the
1986 World Series, while the rest of Boston cried, he jumped up and
down screaming in joy.
</P>
<P>
   Then the converstion turned back to basketball and he got
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm staying,'' he said, ``because I know an NBA career isn't
that long. It might be 10 years, but it might be 10 days. I look at
that, and I know I'm going to have something to fall back on.''
</P>
<P>
   You hope other kids are listening.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
