s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PICKER-MUSIC-ART-2TAK     04-27 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICKER-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMPOSER FREED BY OPERA TO BE TONAL AND TUNEFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
(af) 
 By K. ROBERT SCHWARZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a signal moment in the rebirth of tonality. When the
curtain rose on Tobias Picker's first opera, ``Emmeline,'' in 1996,
the orchestra conjured an atmosphere of grim foreboding, circling
endlessly around a single, brooding chord. As if to emphasize his
immersion in the dark realm of B flat minor, Picker prefaced the
score with a device long scorned by modernists: a key signature.
</P>
<P>
   Picker's embrace of tonality, though particularly unambiguous,
is hardly unique. Today, it seems, every composer is eager to be
portrayed as a lapsed modernist, newly liberated from the shackles
of Serialism. For some, this conservatism smacks of opportunism.
But for Picker, 45, it represents another step in a long and
unpredictable compositional journey.
</P>
<P>
   Its catalyst was opera, which has quickly become Picker's
obsession. And a narrative approach has rubbed off on his
instrumental music as well. On Friday evening, the Chamber Music
Society of Lincoln Center offers the premiere of Picker's Cello
Suite, performed by the cellist Lynn Harrell and the pianist
Anne-Marie McDermott at Alice Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   When Harrell requested a work for cello and piano, Picker
delivered a set of five character pieces, three inspired by poetry,
the five together tracing a story of love won and lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a little opera,'' Picker said recently. ``There's a
dramatic scenario that goes from movement to movement. These are
not just five contrasting pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   His transformation into a traditional opera composer becomes
even more remarkable when one considers his background. As an
adolescent, Picker came to realize, he said, that one of his prime
personality traits was ``total irrationality.''
</P>
<P>
   So he sought out teachers who would encourage compositional
discipline and discourage freewheeling self-expression. With
remarkable single-mindedness, he studied with three pillars of
American rationalism: Milton Babbitt, Elliott Carter and Charles
Wuorinen.
</P>
<P>
   Picker got the discipline he yearned for, along with heady doses
of Serialism and systematic atonality. At Princeton University, he
absorbed the prevailing modernist esthetic but ignored its
scientific trappings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a background in mathematics,'' he said, ``so I
never had the faintest idea what they were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   But he had a clear idea of the kind of music he wanted to write,
and it didn't always conform to prevailing doctrine. When writing a
12-tone piece, he might choose a row so rich in tonal allusions
that further turns toward tonality could be justified. His works of
the 1970s and early 80s showed a persistent conflict between
modernist rationality and Romantic irrationality.
</P>
<P>
   Picker's music resembled that of his teachers in its disjunct
lines, atonal harmonies and irregular rhythms. But a barely
controlled explosive streak would erupt unexpectedly, piercing the
systematic canvas with bursts of intuitive passion. It is tempting
to find a parallel in the neurological disorder with which Picker
was born, Tourette's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a condition that leads people to make involuntary
movements, or tics, and sometimes noises,'' the noted psychiatrist
Oliver Sacks, who helped Picker deal with the outward
manifestations of the syndrome, said recently. ``There may also be
sudden bursts of thought or feeling, which may take the form of
unusual ideas. It provides a certain energy that is distracting and
destructive on one hand but is generating and stimulating on the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to control the symptoms is to focus all energy on a task
at hand, like a performance. ``Tobias conducted a long concert of
his works, and he had nary a tic for two hours,'' Sacks said.
``Everything flowed into the performance, which may have been
infused with some of the energy of the Tourette's syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Might Picker's music in some way reflect the syndrome? ``If an
artist has a condition like this,'' Sacks said, ``it is very
possible it may enter into his art or creativity in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Westchester County, Picker was, by his own
account, a ``strange, unhappy little boy.'' He poured himself into
the piano with fearsome intensity and developed a virtuoso
technique.
</P>
<P>
   At 8, inspired by attending one of Leonard Bernstein's Young
People's Concerts at the New York Philharmonic and hearing Gian
Carlo Menotti's ``Amahl and the Night Visitors'' on television, he
decided to be a composer. At 9, he saw Puccini's ``Girl of the
Golden West'' and knew that he, too, would one day write an opera.
</P>
<P>
   But his rigorous academic training turned him toward abstract,
instrumental music. (Program music, considered naive and
unsystematic, was discouraged.) He composed chamber and orchestral
pieces, including two symphonies, a violin concerto and two piano
concertos. In his early works, short breathless phrases, amorphous
rhythms and dissonant harmonies were the rule.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the balance began to shift. In the piano concerto
``Keys to the City'' (1983), Picker burst out in an exuberant
boogie-woogie cadenza; in the melodrama ``The Encantadas'' (1983),
based on the diaries of Melville, he wrote vividly pictorial music,
and in ``Old and Lost Rivers'' (1986) he explored static tonality.
</P>
<P>
   For Picker, all these works were rungs on a ladder that led to
opera. ``Opera was lurking all the time,'' he said. ``I was totally
involved in the other music I wrote, but I was always aware that
opera was what I was meant to do. I started searching for a subject
in the 1980s. When I discovered `Emmeline,' it just spoke to me,
and I became an automaton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmeline,'' set in early 19th-century New England, is an
Oedipal tale of a young woman who unwittingly marries her
illegitimate son. Drawn from a novel by Judith Rossner, the opera
is tragic in tone yet human in scale, and it erased the last of
Picker's creative inhibitions. `` `Emmeline' enabled me to write
the kind of music I always wanted to write,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although his background was primarliy in instrumental music,
Picker showed a real knack for shaping long, soaring vocal lines.
Driven by a motoric pulse, ``Emmeline'' saves dissonance for
moments of high drama and frenzied action. Straightforward in its
narrative presentation, keen in its musical characterization,
visceral in its passion, ``Emmeline'' was a superlative if
surprisingly traditional achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The work won popular and critical acclaim, bringing Picker to
wide notice. Its premiere, at the Santa Fe Opera, was taped for
national telecast in PBS's ``Great Performances,'' and an audio
recording was released by Albany Records. A New York City Opera
production was widely praised. Picker was soon showered with three
opera commissions, including one from the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some miss the astringent manner of the atonal modernist
and wish that Picker's embrace of tonality had been less complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he doesn't make a standstill or a regression into
placid tonality,'' said Christoph Eschenbach, the music director of
the Houston Symphony, of which Picker was composer-in-residence
from 1985 to 1990. ``I always liked the pieces most where his
musical language had more edge to it, and I hope he doesn't forget
that he has a very expressive voice in this direction as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The pianist Ursula Oppens, who has championed Picker's music for
more than 20 years, takes a more measured view: ``I really loved
his atonal music. But when Tobias writes a melody in `Emmeline,' it
is so beautiful and irresistible. That's what composers have for
too long been afraid of. In that sense he is a leader and a
follower of our time. But `Emmeline' is not the last word, and
things still might change a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Picker speaks cautiously and deliberately, one
occasionally glimpses a tempestuous interior. When he discusses
opera, he exudes a palpable, almost maniacal intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opera freed me to convey complex emotions of character and
situation and drama,'' he said. ``If a dramatic situation calls for
a 10-minute scene in B flat minor, that's what I write.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmeline'' was followed by ``The Fantastic Mr. Fox,'' based on
a Roald Dahl tale, which received its premiere at the Los Angeles
Opera last December. Ostensibly a children's opera, the lean,
nimble ``Fox,'' like Prokofiev's ``Peter and the Wolf,'' speaks
just as well to adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therese Raquin,'' inspired by a Zola novel, will have its
debut at the Dallas Opera in 2001. And an American novel yet to be
announced will form the basis for a Met production in 2003, ``the
very first Met commission of the 21st century,'' Picker noted with
pride.
</P>
<P>
   Instrumental music, it appears, has become a secondary pursuit.
The Cello Suite will be followed by a cello concerto and perhaps
another violin concerto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telling a story in music with real characters who come to life
onstage is much more involving emotionally than writing an abstract
piece,'' Picker said. ``When I'm telling a story, I'm a much
happier composer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
