<HEADLINE>
DOW AND S&AMP;P 500 HIT NEW HIGHS IN BUSY SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed Tuesday in fairly heavy
trading. Two major market averages rose to new highs even as
investors took profits in bellwether technology and Internet
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In general, it was a good day for so-called cyclical stocks,
like Alcoa and DuPont, a group that until earlier this month had
been neglected. But with the exception of IBM, it was not a
positive market for computer and technology shares, which over the
last week have rocketed higher.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as they surveyed the action many traders and analysts
said the market looked tired, and might need a correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big stocks were better, the tech stocks were yuck and the
small caps went nowhere,'' said Bill Allyn, head of listed trading
at Jeffries &AMP; Co. ``The market is searching for leadership. For
right now, the market is having a problem reestablishing itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by big gains in American Express, United Technologies,
Chevron and Alcoa, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 113.12, or
1.1 percent, to a record 10,831.71, eclipsing the previous high of
10,727.20 set Thursday. American Express, a big loser Monday,
gained 4 11/16, to 139, while United Technologies rose 4 1/2, to
143 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index also set a record, rising
2.76 or 0.20 percent to 1,362.80, helped by gains in Coca-Cola,
BankAmerica and Royal Dutch Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   But the NASDAQ composite index fell 49.64 points, or 1.87
percent, to 2,602.41.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 4, to 84. Intel dropped 2 3/16, to 62 1/4. Dell
Computer declined 1 5/8, to 43 3/16. By the closing bell, the index
had lost 49.64, or 1.9 percent, to 2,602.41. And TheStreet.com's
Internet stock index fell 17.30, or 2.4 percent, to 696.97.
</P>
<P>
   America Online slumped 5 5/16, to 154 9/16. After the market
closed, the company released earnings results that beat Wall Street
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   As Allyn suggested, small cap stocks, which have been inching
higher lately, did very little Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small cap stocks gained 0.21, or 0.1
percent, to 435.18.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, whose vertiginous rise over the last two weeks has been a
big reason the Dow has gained nearly 400 points during that period,
had another good day. Since April 19, IBM shares have risen more
than 27 percent. According to analysts at Birinyi &AMP; Associates,
during that period IBM's gain has accounted for than 202 Dow
points.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the opening the company announced it was
increasing its dividend and that it planned to buy back up to $3.5
billion worth of its shares. The stock gained 2 1/8, to 212.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is tired, and it should be,'' said Al Goldman,
chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards Inc. in St. Louis. ``The
main thing that has gotten the market in gear over the last month
has been corporate earnings, which have been much better than
people expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Goldman said, ``I think the odds favor a little time out
and a decline of four or five percent in the averages before we
turn again. It is a very tough thing for a long-time bull like me
to say, but I would be keeping some powder dry at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   A better-than-expected first-quarter earnings report helped lift
DuPont, another Dow stock, which climbed 1 5/8, to 68 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Oil company shares also did better. Royal Dutch, an S&AMP;P
component, gained 1 11/16. And BP Amoco gained 3 3/4, to 110 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclical stocks as a whole had a very good day.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan Stanley Cyclical index gained 1 percent, its best
performance in more than a week. Since the beginning of April, the
index has risen by more than 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the beating technology shares took, there is little
doubt that interest, if not hysteria, in the Internet remains
extremely high.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Razorfish Inc., a company that designs websites for
online businesses more than doubled in price Tuesday, rising 17
1/2, to 33 1/2, in its first day of trading. The stock was
initially priced by investment bankers at Credit Suisse First
Boston on Monday night at $16 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
