u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REYNOLDS-THEATER-COX     04-27 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REYNOLDS-THEATER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reynolds' dinner theater on auction block
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ The doors are shuttered at an up-and-down
playhouse most recently known as the Carousel Jupiter Theatre.
Workers are converting the place for a fall opening of Christ's
Church of the Palm Beaches.
</P>
<P>
   But before church officials can welcome what they hope will be
thousands of parishioners, they have to evict Burt Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday they will host ``The Longest Yard Sale.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10:30 a.m., Jay Sugarman Auctioneers will sell the
picked-over remains of what opened in 1979 as the Burt Reynolds
Dinner Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials now own everything inside the Indiantown Road
building. They have uncovered kitchens full of industrial cooking
equipment. Theater props, slightly used light bulbs, Christmas
ornaments and other inexplicable baubles have been pulled from
every dusty corner and prepared for display.
</P>
<P>
   But the stars of Tuesday's show will likely be the stars who
once came to the theater; there are dozens of framed photographs
and drawings of 1970s-era stars who added luster to the productions
at the house that Burt built.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will want to see the shrine,'' said D. Cooper Getschal,
director of worship and programming for the church. He jokingly
refers to virtually everything inside the building as once
belonging to Reynolds. He speaks of ``Burt's piano'' and ``Burt's
adding machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Getschal takes visitors through a side entrance, where stairs
lead to a room marked: ``Burt Reynolds Private Box.'' Inside, the
walls are lined with faces that could have come from a cast party
for Cannonball Run.
</P>
<P>
   There are photographs autographed to Reynolds from Woody Allen,
Myrna Loy, Jackie Gleason, Mae West and Dean Martin, to name just a
few.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will pay good money for this stuff,'' Getschal said.
``We're counting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much it will bring is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sugarman, president of the Miami-based auction house, said
Tuesday he had no idea what the total take might be. Getschal said
the church has estimates of the value of the restaurant equipment,
though he declined to name a figure.
</P>
<P>
   It is much more difficult to calculate the worth of memorabilia
peculiar to the theater, such as posters and autographs. And
collectors say it is impossible to put a price on things that are
just plain peculiar _ a black-and-white still photo of Reynolds and
the pope, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, pictures that have been autographed to you or I are
less valuable than those without personal messages,'' said Joseph
Rubinfine, a West Palm Beach autograph dealer. ``But these that
have been autographed to Burt Reynolds may have some market
precedence.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime theater-goer Eleanor Shubert said she has fond memories
of the place. When told of the auction, she said she might go
bargain hunting, though she wasn't sure how to tell a good price
for a photo of Reynolds lounging in a bubble bath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she said. ``He's still alive, isn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   At 63, Reynolds is alive and well, though he didn't immediately
return telephone calls placed through his publicist on Tuesday.
Last year he emerged from bankruptcy proceedings without his
Jupiter Farms ranch, but still in possession of a $1.17 million
home in Hobe Sound. Renolds sold the former dinner theater to
developer Otto (Buzz) DiVosta in 1996. It later became the Carousel
Jupiter Theater.
</P>
<P>
   What if Reynolds should come forward and ask for the return of
his personal items?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Gary Templeton, senior minister for the
church. ``I don't think we have any preconceived notions of what
might happen then.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
