<HEADER>
A5537 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOP-40-RADIO-ART-2TAK     04-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOP-40-RADIO-ART-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 29 YEARS, STILL COUNTING DOWN THE HITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Maine, Mich., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
(af) 
 Andy Meisler's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the series ``Dilbert.''  
 By ANDY MEISLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Cahuenga Boulevard, near Universal Studios,
there is a landmark of sorts: a medium-size office building whose
upper stories, mirrored in the fashion of the 1980s, angle outward.
The structure adjoins the busy Hollywood Freeway; passing motorists
get a swift, startling glance of themselves as they speed past.
</P>
<P>
   On the fifth floor of this building are a number of small
recording studios. In one of them, on a recent weekday, sat Casey
Kasem, the disk jockey. A medium-size, neatly dressed man of 67, he
sat behind soundproof glass. Illuminated by a single desk lamp, he
read with energetic earnestness from a thick sheaf of script pages
in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   He says: ``Inching back up a notch to No. 13 is a band that
features a gifted guitarist named the Edge. When the Edge was
growing up, his family couldn't afford to buy him a guitar, so the
talented teen built one! Here's U2 and `Sweetest Thing'!''
</P>
<P>
   A few bars of the beginning of the song, just to help mate the
introduction with the music, were played. Then silence.
</P>
<P>
   Kasem turns the page and begins reading another sound bite. In
the next few hours he reads dozens more, including numerous
vanilla-flavored biographical tidbits, upbeat comments on the
record ratings race and several heartfelt ``long distance
dedications'' _ a teen-ager to her late boyfriend, killed in a car
crash; a daughter to her hard-working, financially distressed
father.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, enough spoken words are recorded to begin editing
the actual music into Kasem's weekly pop and rock music countdown
show.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly the most riveting spectacle, except when you
realize that ``American Top 40 With Casey Kasem'' has been on the
air, under slightly different titles but with virtually the same
format, for nearly 29 years. Currently, the four-hour-long show,
heard in most markets on Saturday or Sunday morning, is broadcast
on more than 350 stations nationwide and heard at any one point in
his show by an audience that averages approximately 1.1 million
listeners over age 12.
</P>
<P>
   In the supposedly volatile worlds of radio and popular music,
Kasem's longevity matches that of personalities like Dick Clark and
Paul Harvey. To put it another way: his tenure has extended from
the era of Melanie and the Moody Blues through Donna Summers and
the Police through Madonna and Milli Vanilli and, at last glance,
the likes of Alanis Morissette, Courtney Love and Hole, Garbage,
and the Goo Goo Dolls.
</P>
<P>
   His show is at the center of mainstream America's connection
with its pop and rock-and-roll music and artists: a rather warm and
fuzzy relationship quite unfamiliar to readers of the angst-, rage-
and pharmaceutical-filled articles in much of the mainstream rock
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so simple,'' says Kasem in an interview after the
recording session. ``What do people love? Plato said it best:
`People who tell the stories rule society.' And we tell the
stories, and people love to hear the stories. Of course we've got a
tremendous responsibility to be accurate with those stories. And in
most cases to be wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   By this, Kasem adds, he means that if, say, a song holds the
record for consecutive weeks on the chart for a female recording
artist born in Britain _ the kind of inside information he has
learned his listeners like to hear _ he and his staff will make
sure that the statistic is completely accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if any biographical anecdote involves drugs or alcohol, it
will almost certainly be about the artist's rehabilitation and
subsequent career comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think magazines like Rolling Stone go into much more depth
and, um, critique,'' says Kasem. ``Where we don't really get into
that. We just tell the story as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People listen to the show on their way to church,'' says David
Kantor, senior vice president of Chancellor Radio Networks in
charge of AMFM Networks, the Dallas-based company that currently
distributes ``American Top 40 With Casey Kasem,'' in a telephone
interview. ``Our audience tunes in at the same time each week and
gets a show that is always different, but also always the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Poleman, program director of New York's WHTZ-FM, which
broadcasts the show on Saturday from 5 to 9 a.m., says: ``Casey
attracts a lot of core audience, from 18 to 34, and also the people
who grew up listening to him over the years. It's one of the few
shows parents can listen to with their kids. He's a true mass
appeal D.J.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Stone, 38, a South Portland, Maine, resident and
single parent whose long distance dedication, to a foster child,
was read on the air recently, says: ``I've been listening to
`American Top 40' for four or five years. It's the only radio show
I really listen to regularly. When Casey read my name I went sort
of nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stone also reports that she particularly enjoys listening to
the singer Jewel and the Australian pop group Savage Garden. Since
both have had several songs in the contemporary hit records
rankings issued by Radio and Records, a trade publication (a list
hewed to religiously by ``American Top 40''), both groups have been
well represented on the show. Hence, automatic listener
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never have to work to find our audience,'' says Kasem. ``It
finds us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasem, now well into his fifth decade in the music business,
cheerfully admits that he no longer makes judgments about _ or
indeed, regularly listens to _ the music he plays on his show.
Which makes it all the more interesting that most observers credit
his warm and familiar voice with much of the show's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Detroit, the son of a Lebanese-American mother and a
Lebanese immigrant father, Kasem was a popular disk jockey in his
hometown; in Oakland, Calif., and in Los Angeles before beginning
``American Top 40'' on July 4, 1970. Many elements of its format
were admittedly borrowed from older shows like ```Your Hit
Parade.'' (``That was `Teach Your Children,' a debut from Crosby,
Stills, Nash and Young. It's heavy stuff, and you expect heavy
stuff from them.'')
</P>
<P>
   While all has been tranquil on the listeners' side of the radio,
Kasem's show has experienced some bumps and bruises behind the
scenes. A significant threat to the franchise has been the drastic
fragmentation of pop music radio: In the 1970s and earlier, the
strongest station in each market would almost invariably play Top
40; in recent years formats like urban and alternative rock have
shoved them aside.
</P>
<P>
   To service a wider range of stations Kasem's show is now
programmed in three versions based on three somewhat different play
lists: contemporary hit radio, roughly equal to the old Top 40;
adult contemporary, slightly milder, and hot adult contemporary,
slightly edgier. These alternative versions are packaged as Top 20
shows, as is a shortened version of '`American Top 40.''
</P>
<P>
   The show has experienced several changes in ownership: In 1989
Kasem left his longtime employer, ABC Radio, to throw in his lot
with the Westwood One network, now owned by CBS. For a time ABC,
which retained the rights to the name ``American Top 40,''
countered with a show that had the radio and television personality
Shadoe Stevens as host, while Kasem's was called ``Casey's Top
40.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC eventually canceled its show; last year Kasem, amid a flurry
of lawsuits, left Westwood One for AMFM and the show reassumed its
name.
</P>
<P>
   These days Kasem, who works two days a week, has no plans to
retire _ or to be retired. ``The great thing about radio is that
nobody really knows how old you are,'' he says. ``People `see' who
they want to see. They're seeing what radio allows their mind to
create.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
