<SLUG> BC-FLA-BUDGET-VOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida ``turkey'' budget passes
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A record state budget stuffed with a record
$665 million in ``turkeys'' unanimously passed the Legislature
Tuesday, on its way to a dubious governor who warns lawmakers to
expect some ``discomfort'' over what he intends to do.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in both chambers congratulated themselves for
allocating $1 billion more for schools, giving back $1 billion in
tax cuts and setting aside $1 billion for the Lawton Chiles
Endowment for youth and elder programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of this budget,'' said House Speaker John
Thrasher, R-Orange Park, of the $48.9 billion, inch-and-a-half
thick document, noting that the 119-0 vote in the House and 40-0
passage in the Senate marked the first time since 1984 that the
state budget passed without dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial anti-budget vote Rep. Rob Wallace, R-Tampa, even voted
yes this time, pointing out that the 1999-2000 budget eliminates
646 state government positions. ``That's the first time we've done
that before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Democrats, outnumbered nearly 2-1 in the legislature, found
praise. ``I just want to say how impressed I am with your
commitment to education,'' Sen. Betty Holzendorf, D-Jacksonville,
told Senate President Toni Jennings, R-Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   What went almost unmentioned though, was the $664.8 million in
hometown projects lawmakers have inserted for such things as a
shooting range in Alachua County, eradicating gnats in Sanford and
``safety resurfacing of the slide and glide playground'' in Coral
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Only once was the word ``turkey'' mentioned on either floor: by
Rep. James Bush, D-Miami, who said he hoped in the future poor
districts like his get more of them. He added that he was grateful
for those he did get, including $50,000 for the Miami-Dade Police
Athletic League, and that he hoped Gov. Jeb Bush doesn't veto them,
as he has promised he will do for projects that do benefit the
whole state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the governor will not view these as turkeys when they
hit his desk,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The big, seven and eight-figure projects among the 913
identified in a Palm Beach Post analysis went disproportionately to
the two chambers' presiding officers and budget committee and
subcommittee chairs. Indeed, those fourteen lawmakers account for
$346.2 million of all the member projects _ 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
