<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-BUSH-BUDGET-COX     04-27 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BUSH-BUDGET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legislators, lobbyists think Bush's budget-slashing won't fly
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Despite repeated warnings that Gov. Jeb Bush
will unmercifully slash ``turkeys'' from the state's $48 billion
budget, many lobbyists and lawmakers insist that Bush will be
forced to leave most of them alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a balance of power question,'' says Sen. Tom Rossin,
D-West Palm Beach. ``You can't just have the governor imposing his
view of the world on the legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have chaos next year if he goes too far,'' said a
prominent lobbyist of 20 years who does not want to get on Bush's
bad side. ``The members will revolt and he will have problems
governing if he kills their projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists that any member project that does not fill a
legitimate state need will be vetoed and he will not show
favoritism toward lawmakers who have supported his legislative
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important that we establish a precedent for the
future,'' Bush said Tuesday. ``If that means I have to veto the
projects of my friends, even though I don't like to disappoint my
friends, I will veto it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Moffitt, a former House speaker who now lobbies the
legislature, said he thinks Bush will find it much more difficult
than he thinks to veto some member projects. ``He has to have a
good working relationship with the members and he's going to have
to be responsive to their needs if he wants them to help him in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   A Palm Beach Post review of the budget has found $664.8 million
in hometown projects in the budget. That total includes $36 million
for Palm Beach County projects and nearly $44 million for Martin
and St. Lucie counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that some of these things get called
turkeys,'' said Rossin. ``I have a waste water system for Pahokee
that will cost $850,000. They desperately need it and they can't
afford it as a city. I think that makes it a legitimate state need.
There are all kinds of projects like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, while not commenting on any specific project, said he
doesn't expect to veto every member project but that the criteria
he will use will be much more stringent than the legislature has
been accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has done a good job of protecting his right to veto,''
said lobbyist Jim Krog, who worked as Gov. Lawton Chiles' chief of
staff. ``A governor has to take a real hard stand or he'll get run
over. I think he's going to get his way. I don't see a Republican
legislature trying to override the veto of a Republican governor
just to save some hometown projects. I think he's got a free
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Herb Morgan, who was House budget chairman for 10 years and
fought huge battles with Gov. Bob Graham, thinks Bush could go too
far. ``If he ticks off too many people he could get into trouble.
The legislature has the right to determine how the state's money
should be spent and I think they would want to protect that right
if they think a governor is going too far with his vetoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that many Republicans voted for school vouchers
only because Bush asked them to do so. If he in turn vetos their
projects these same members will feel betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they feel that way,'' said one former lawmaker, ``you
have a hard time getting them to support you on the next tough
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
