<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-ART-900 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T PROFIT SURGES 42 PERCENT ON COST CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
 &AMP;ADD-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as it continued its flurry of deal-making, AT&AMP;T Corp. on
Tuesday reported strong financial results for the first quarter
that exceeded analysts' expectations. But investors did not rush to
buy AT&AMP;T's shares amid continued uncertainty about the company's
unsolicited $58 billion bid to acquire MediaOne Group Inc., the big
cable television company.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings for AT&AMP;T, the nation's biggest communications company,
rose 42 percent over the first quarter of last year, largely
because of an aggressive cost-cutting campaign by C. Michael
Armstrong, the company's chairman of 18 months. More important,
AT&AMP;T showed signs of finally emerging from the revenue funk it had
been stuck in for years, boosting sales by more than 6 percent over
the comparable period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, AT&AMP;T also announced a partnership with Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone, the world's biggest phone company, to
provide comprehensive packages of communications services to
multinational corporations in Japan and perhaps other parts of
Asia. AT&AMP;T has formed a separate joint venture with British
Telecommunications PLC, and if AT&AMP;T can work well with both
partners, it will have gone a long way toward realizing its global
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   But it is AT&AMP;T's ambitions in the United States that continue
both to invigorate and worry investors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main questions facing Wall Street, not to mention
MediaOne's board, which had already agreed to sell its company to
Comcast Corp., is how feasible AT&AMP;T's offer really is from a legal
and regulatory perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, those are questions that also preoccupy Comcast,
which needs to gauge AT&AMP;T's offer before deciding whether to make a
serious counterbid of its own. Executives close to Comcast said
Tuesday that while that company had weighed a variety of options,
it had not yet decided how to respond to the AT&AMP;T bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
