<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-BOSS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NOTHING TOYLIKE IN MATTEL CEO'S COMPENSATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbie was a tough sell in 1998, but Jill Barad had a good year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barad, the chairman and chief executive of Mattel, the maker
of Barbie, was received $4.75 million, according to a recent filing
with securities regulators. Her salary, $1.26 million, and her
bonus, $500,000, were 14 percent higher than in 1997, her first
year leading the giant toy maker. She also received $2.86 million
in long-term incentive pay last year and $131,756 in other
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   But by almost any measure, last year was disappointing for
Mattel shareholders. Revenues from the Barbie brand fell as Toys
``R'' Us cut back on all its inventory, causing Mattel's profits to
sink and its stock to tumble 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Barad had either the good luck or the foresight to take
options grants back in 1997 intended to carry her for several years
_ grants not subject to renegotiation. Mattel's board awarded her
special options grants whose value was estimated at $24 million at
the time and brought her total compensation for 1997 to $26.3
million. After lumping all the options in that year, her
compensation this year appears modest in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   While the increase in her base salary may raise eyebrows given
Mattel's dismal performance last year, the total compensation was
far more reasonable this year, said Graef Crystal, an
executive-compensation critic and editor of the Crystal Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you threw her pay package on a scale, all the springs would
have fallen out'' in 1997, Crystal said. ``It looks like they went
on a pay Weight Watchers all during 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Barad's base salary is 60 percent higher than that of
chief executives running companies of similar size, by Crystal's
calculation. After factoring in her bonus for completing the
acquisition of Tyco Toys Inc., Ms. Barad's pay is 29 percent above
the market average, he found. Her total compensation, including
long-term incentive pay, is 13 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter of last year, Mattel reported a 67 percent
decline in earnings on lower revenue. For the year, its profits
rose 16 percent, to $332.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The problems have continued this year. Earlier this month,
Mattel reported a $17.9 million loss, or 7 cents a share, for the
first quarter of 1999 and said revenue fell 2 percent, to $692.1
million. The company also said that it would dismiss about 3,000
employees, or 10 percent of its work force, and close some
factories and offices. The stock fell from $37.25 to $23.50 last
year and has since languished. It closed at $25.8125 Tuesday, up
6.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mattel said neither Ms. Barad nor the company
would comment on her compensation or that of any of other senior
executives.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.86 million in long-term incentive pay was for meeting
certain three-year financial targets, though the company declined
Tuesday to say whether it was the maximum she could have earned for
reaching the strategic goals.
</P>
<P>
   On her short-term goals, Ms. Barad missed the mark. She did not
qualify for a bonus of up to 150 percent of her base salary tied to
meeting certain internal financial targets. She also did not get
any new stock options.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the value of her existing options has declined
along with Mattel's stock price. Ms. Barad exercised options for
224,453 shares last year, but still held those shares, with a paper
profit of $6.4 million, at the time of the filing.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Barad's total pay package, David Leibowitz, a stock
analyst with Burnham Securities, said he expected some of the
initiatives she put in place in 1998 to begin paying off this year
and, therefore, did not consider her compensation out of line. In
particular, the company's pending acquisition of The Learning
Company, a leading software maker, should make Mattel more
competitive in interactive toys, Leibowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is clearly keeping step with the times and is
trying to get ahead of the curve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the acquisitions, Ms. Barad has shuffled management.
Mattel's regulatory filing also shows that Bruce Stein, who
resigned as chief operating officer and president of the company's
worldwide operations in March, received a salary of $760,390 and a
bonus of $350,000 for 1998. He also received $1.6 million as part
of the long-term incentive package and $69,000 form the company's
personal investment plan.
</P>
<P>
   He received a $1 million signing bonus when he joined the
company in 1996. His severance package was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
