<HEADER>
A5546 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-27 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB COUNT GROWS IN COLORADO, AND A WOMAN IS LINKED TO GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: An expanded version of this story is scheduled to move by
9:45 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mb) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ An 18-year-old woman who attended the senior
prom with one of the killers at Columbine High School bought at
least two of the firearms used in the attack, the authorities
confirmed on Tuesday as they announced that 51 pipe bombs _ nearly
twice as many as first mentioned _ had been found.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Robyn Anderson, who did not respond to requests for
comment, was interviewed by the police on Monday and released. She
bought two shotguns at a local gun show she attended recently with
the two gunmen, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, her prom date, and
is currently being considered a witness, not a suspect. Ms.
Anderson could face criminal charges if she knew how her friends
intended to use the weapons, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we feel she has committed a criminal act,'' she will be
returned to custody, said Sgt. Jim Parr of the Jefferson County
Sheriff's Department. ``As far as I know, she's still
cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr and Steve Davis, a spokesman for the Sheriff's department,
declined to say how many of the pipe bombs had been detonated or
which ones had been found in the school, the adjacent parking lot,
or Harris' home.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of the additional bombs came on the one-week
anniversary of the rampage here, which left one teacher 14 students
_ including the two gunmen _ dead and a community in shock and
mourning. This middle-class suburb south of Denver, and indeed much
of Colorado, came to halt at 11:21 a.m. on Tuesdayday to mark the
moment the shooting began, with a blackout on local television and
radio stations as church bells tolled 15 times, one for each of the
slain. Two more students were buried on Tuesdayday in tearful
funerals that drew thousands, part of an overflowing calendar of
grief that will continue through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the first hints of normalcy began to appear, as
teachers met to plan next week's return to classes for Columbine's
nearly 2,000 students, and the girls' soccer team played the first
interscholastic athletic event since the devastating attack on the
school.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though the parents of the two young men who
plotted the massacre for at least a year remained in seclusion, a
new details began to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who kept a journal outlining plans for the attack and
appears to have been the mastermind of the plot, had hoped to join
the Marines but was rejected because of a medical reason just days
before he and his best friend stormed onto campus carrying guns and
bombs, officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a retired Air Force pilot, Harris was recruited as
part of a routine telephone canvass and did well at a preliminary
interview, but was nixed after a meeting at his home April 15, when
his ``parents divulged a medical factor,'' according to Lt. Jeff
Sammons, a spokesman for the Marine Corps Recruiting Command in
Quantico, Va. The Marines would not disclose the medical reason,
but the parent of a friend of Harris' said the young man had been
on psychiatric medication, which can be disqualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Eric's case, the system worked,'' Sammons said. ``We caught
someone who didn't qualify for the Marine Corps.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reliance on certain prescription drugs, reasons
for a medical disqualification include asthma, flat feet, and some
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Good, whose son Nathan Dykeman was a friend of both
youths said that Harris had been seeing a psychiatrist. ``Eric did
have a few problems, Eric was in counseling,'' Good said in an
interview on Tuesday. ``When we heard about it we were like, so, so
he's seeing a psychiatrist? So the parents think he needs someone
to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Good said that he has known Klebold and his parents for years,
and that no one could have predicted the attack. ``Now everyone
wants to point fingers, at the parents, at the schools _ the
Sheriff's Department should have known something, the school should
have known something,'' he said. ``The most horrifying thing of
this that people should be horrified and scared to death of, is
that these kids did not show any signs of this. It's terrifying. We
knew a different Dylan.''
</P>
<P>
   Good praised Susan and Thomas Klebold as excellent parents, and
criticized the politicians _ from President Clinton to the local
sheriff _ who have questioned their responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was no broken family, this was no abusive family, no
anything,'' he said. ``These people spent time with their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The elderKlebold considered his two sons his best friends, Good
said, nboting that earlier this month he spent five days with Dylan
touring the University of Arizona, where the 18-year-old senior
planned to enroll in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked about the future and everything,'' he added.
``This guy knew his kid, and loved his kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three days before the attack, Dykeman attended the prom
with Klebold as part of a group of four couples who shared a
limousine, and saw Harris at the post-prom party. ``They all had a
great time,'' Good said. Though the parents of both shooters have
remained in seclusion, Good said he had spoken to the Klebolds on
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're forgetting that family _ those two families are by
themselves,'' he said. ``Their life has been forever turned upside
down and it will never heal. They're looking for explanations,
they're looking through everything: Was that a sign, was that a
sign, did I miss something? They're second-guessing their entire
lives.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
