<SLUG> BC-COUNCIL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COUNCIL'S NEW PRESIDENT IS FIRST TO COME FROM MEDIA
BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For only the fourth time in its 57-year history, the
Advertising Council has a new president.
</P>
<P>
   The council, the nonprofit organization that has coordinated
public service campaigns for Madison Avenue since 1942, is naming
Peggy Conlon as president, succeeding Ruth Wooden, effective June
1. Ms. Wooden announced in January that she would leave the New
York-based council after serving as president since November 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conlon, 48, is the first president to come from the media
industry. Since 1992, she has been vice president and group
publisher for the Broadcasting &AMP; Cable Group at Cahners Business
Information in New York, part of the international media
conglomerate Reed Elsevier. Before that, she spent a decade
overseeing trade newspapers at CMP Publications in Manhasset.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conlon, who supervises eight publications like Broadcasting
&AMP; Cable, Digital Television and Television Latin America, was
selected from among five finalists for the president's post by a
search committee composed of 12 of the 85 board members of the
council, which represents advertisers, agencies and media
companies. The committee was assisted by Gilbert, Farlie in New
York, an executive search company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for somebody with Ruth's enthusiasm, passion
for the mission and ability to work with a lot of different
constituencies,'' said Gregory Coleman, the 1998-99 chairman of the
council and president for U.S. magazine publishing at the Reader's
Digest Association in New York. He discussed the selection at a
breakfast Tuesday where he was joined by Ms. Conlon and Ms. Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   The changing of the guard comes at a crucial time for the
council, which has taken on ``social marketing'' causes that range
from buying War Bonds and preventing forest fires to fighting drug
use and encouraging mentors for children.
</P>
<P>
   While the amount of commercial time and advertising space
donated to campaigns produced by the council reached a record level
last year, rising 21 percent, to an estimated $1.2 billion,
compared with $995.8 million in 1997, members have an even more
ambitious goals: to persuade media outlets to donate time and space
worth $2 billion by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason to select as the next president someone with
media industry experience, Ms. Wooden said, because the
fragmentation of media outlets is making it more difficult to reach
the intended audiences for the council's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conlon, who worked for two advertisers and an agency before
entering the publishing field, said: ``For the last six and a half
years, we've broadened our coverage at Broadcasting &AMP; Cable to
include the full scope of television, Internet and technology. As a
result, in a very competitive category, we were able to more than
double revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Another issue facing the council is the propensity for the
television networks to favor paid cause-related marketing campaigns
they create in partnership with advertisers over pro bono ads from
the council.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wooden described that as ``a problem that's turned into an
opportunity'' as the council has begun collaborating with networks
like ABC, CBS, Comedy Central and NBC on campaigns centered on
topics like teen-age pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conlon, who recently completed a two-year term as chairwoman
of the International Radio and Television Society, cited another
potential problem: ``There's the ability of new consumer
electronics devices to skip forward through commercials. So we need
to have the relationships with the media to make sure our messages
get in front of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wehling, the 1997-98 chairman of the council who was the
head of the search committee, said in a telephone interview:
``Peggy stood out in terms of the breadth and quality of her
industry contacts. In particular, she has good relationships with
key broadcast and cable leaders. That's important as we attempt to
significantly increase our visibility in those media.''
</P>
<P>
   Wehling, who is the corporate officer for global marketing,
market research and government relations at Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. in
Cincinnati, praised Ms. Conlon as an ``all-around excellent''
choice who will help insure ``years of future growth'' for the
council.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Ms. Conlon bypasses the council's No. 2
executive, S. Murray Gaylord, who joined in June 1997 after working
at agencies like Scali, McCabe, Sloves and TBWA/Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman declined to discuss whether Gaylord, the council's
executive vice president and chief operating officer, had been
considered for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did Gaylord, who when asked about his plans in a
telephone interview Tuesday said, ``I'm not ready to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Conlon said she hoped that Gaylord would stay on.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wooden, 52, will work with Ms. Conlon for a month and then
join the National Parenting Association in New York as president,
effective July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wooden's predecessors at the council were Theodore Repplier,
who served from 1942 to 1966, and Robert Keim, who served from 1966
to 1987.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
