<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JOHN FRANCO SAVORS HIS HOME PLATE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On his rare forays into the hinterlands, John Franco
has made an amazing discovery. The pizza is not as good in the
suburbs, and neither is the bread. It's a fact. Something about
being outside the five boroughs curdles the dough, or spoils it, or
whatever it is that goes wrong with dough.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason alone, Franco cannot leave. He is a true prince
of the city. He made the schlep across the ``Saturday Night Fever''
Bridge from Brooklyn to Staten Island in search of a back yard for
his two children, but that's as far from Bensonhurst as he cares to
live.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is the greatest city in the country, in the world,''
Franco said Tuesday, displaying normal New York moderation.
</P>
<P>
   For that plug alone, Franco deserves an award from New York, but
Tuesday Franco was given the key to the city. The son of a
sanitation worker, the kid from the projects, the St. John's boy
who came home was honored for his rather exciting body of work as
the ace relief pitcher of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Franco reached 400 saves a couple weeks ago, and had 404 going
into Tuesday night's game with the San Diego Padres at blustery
Shea Stadium. His total was the second highest in major league
history, behind the 478 of Lee Smith, now retired.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to acting as the unofficial spokesman for the
countless pizzerias and delis of his hometown, Franco has also done
wonders for the cardiology profession, inducing thousands of
late-hour calls from patients shouting, ``Doctor, Doctor, I've got
arrhythmia,'' only to have the cardiologist say, ``Relax, Johnny'll
get the next guy,'' which he does, more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   Even Franco saw the humor of his epic ninth innings while Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani was reading a tribute to Franco inside City Hall,
in front of Mets officials and Franco relatives and pals from the
old neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four hundred times under that kind of pressure, where there's
almost no room for error,'' the mayor intoned.
</P>
<P>
   Franco twitched noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more pressure there is, the better he pitches,'' the mayor
continued.
</P>
<P>
   A nervous grin crossed Franco's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never given Mets fans a dull moment,'' added the
notorious Yankee fan.
</P>
<P>
   Franco raised his eyes to the heavens, as if to say, ``Man, you
got that right.''
</P>
<P>
   The key ceremony ended, and segued immediately into a mayoral
news conference. While the Mets' contingent was filing out, news
reporters began questioning Giuliani on why he had suggested the
city's school system be ``blown up,'' surely an interesting choice
of words given the recent tragedy in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   While this typical New York bombast was going on, Franco stood
in the hallway and recalled his childhood in a housing development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was lower-middle class, sure,'' Franco said with immense
pride. ``We'd wear sweatshirts and sweatpants to bed in the winter
because the heater didn't work, and there was no air conditioning
in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was about 10, he and his older brother, Jimmy, would
collect the tops of Borden's milk containers and exchange them for
Mets tickets _ 20 containers for a ticket was the going rate, he
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would take the B train to Times Square and change to the 7
train to Flushing,'' he said. ``We'd sit in the upper deck.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite player was Tug McGraw, the ebullient lefty
reliever. Now another hyper lefty has become the all-time Mets
relief pitcher, in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough place,'' Franco admitted. ``When I came in here
with Cincinnati in 1986, you'd see the standing ovations for the
Mets. It was great. But you need a thick skin to play here.''
</P>
<P>
   He has heard the cheers, and he has heard the yowls when he let
a lead get away, and a few times he has seemed to aim a glare or
the odd gesture at the mob. But he understands.
</P>
<P>
   He wishes his parents could see all this, but Mary Franco died
of ovarian cancer in 1986, and 14 months later Jim Franco died of a
heart attack while driving his sanitation truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to buy him a condo and a car in Florida, so he
could go to spring training with me,'' Franco said. ``I get a tear
in my eye when I think about them. I can see losing one, but losing
two within 14 months. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Life goes on. He met his wife, Rose Morrone, when they were 15,
at a discotheque, in Brooklyn. There were house-hunting expeditions
to New Jersey and Long Island, ``but it just didn't feel right,''
Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   He's a city kid, who dreamed of playing for the Mets, and now he
does, and that feels right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
