<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5558 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICEO-SFCHRON &LR;      04-27 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICEO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Quick-Fix CEOs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
iCEO is not your typical temp agency or executive search firm.
Instead of placing accountants or human resources experts into
companies for a few days or weeks, the new Woodside company plans
to drop veteran chief executives into fast-growing, high-tech
companies for short stints.
</P>
<P>
   The company, whose name is short for interim chief executive
officer, is the latest sign of the times at the epicenter of
innovation: securing talented managers in a hot industry.
</P>
<P>
   The time it takes to develop e-products and get them to market
before another entrepreneur beats you to it has never been shorter.
Meanwhile, there is a shortage of experienced CEOs, and the time it
takes to recruit them has never been longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest lament of venture capital firms is not money or
good ideas, which are infinite,'' said Rich Brenner, founder of the
Brenner Group of Cupertino, another Silicon Valley management and
financial services firm that provides temp CEOs for startups. ``The
biggest constraint on growth is lack of qualified management
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bengston, director of Emerging Company Services at
PricewaterhouseCoopers in San Jose, suggests that typical CEO
searches in the valley ``take about five months if you can get a
headhunter to take an assignment at all; the best ones are
booked.''
</P>
<P>
   Part-time CEOS are the natural next step in the mushrooming
outsourcing industry as companies increasingly turn to private
consultants and outplacement firms to meet their hiring needs and
cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dun &AMP; Bradstreet's annual outsourcing survey, the
North America market accounts for 60 percent of worldwide revenues
for all temporary employees and consultants. For the 12 months
ending this month, that amounted to about $141 billion, up 21
percent from $116 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest growth area, says D&AMP;B, is information technology,
which accounts for 28 percent of all outsourcing expenditures and
is anticipated to grow by 26 percent this year. There also is
strong demand for outside finance and personnel services.
</P>
<P>
   Many venture capital firms have employed so-called
entrepreneurs-in-residence to help lead companies they invest in.
But these free-lance executives often stayed just long enough to
land a permanent job at one of the VC-backed startups.
</P>
<P>
   However, the new breed of corporate samurai don't always want to
make a long-term commitment to one corporate master.
</P>
<P>
   ICEO, which quietly started three months ago, is the brainchild
of Ron Coleman, 43, who built and then sold a medical software
company and became an angel investor, and his friend David Powell,
62, who founded an executive search firm of the same name in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   After working with venture capital firms to find permanent CEOs
for their high-tech startups, David Powell Inc. added permanent and
part-time financial services, including bookkeepers and chief
financial officers, and then human resource professionals.
</P>
<P>
   With Powell as chairman and Coleman as CEO, iCEO's mission is to
match proven CEOs with VC-backed startups that need bridge
leadership as much as bridge financing. Coleman maintains that
fill-in work suits many business leaders, who at 45 to 65 recently
retired or plan to do so but want to stay involved without making a
five-year commitment.
</P>
<P>
   That, in essence, sums up Coleman's recent predicament. After
earning a Ph.D. in microbiology in Ireland, Coleman did
post-doctorate work at Harvard, where he ran the university's first
automated DNA synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn by the siren song of the biotech business boom, he then
got a Stanford MBA on a fellowship and founded de Medici Systems in
1989. Six years later, he sold the medical software company for an
undisclosed fortune and became an angel investor.
</P>
<P>
   But playing golf and puttering around his homes in Los Altos and
Carmel were not enough. ``I love the pace of business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His and Powell's idea is to represent executive stars much the
way International Management Group markets sports stars like Joe
Montana and Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The ``poster boy'' for interim CEOs, according to Coleman, is
Steve Jobs, who tackled Apple Computer while also leading Pixar.
While Jobs is not on iCEO's roster, Coleman said seven well-known
CEOs have signed up.
</P>
<P>
   The company is not yet ready to disclose their identities.
Coleman would only divulge that they have broad experience in five
different disciplines: the Internet, software, semiconductors,
networking/telecommunications and medical/biotech.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit for iCEO part-timers is that the company is working
with a stable of blue-chip venture capital firms including Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, Mayfield Fund, Sequoia Capital and Sutter
Hill on their most promising newborns.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of betting on the success of just one, iCEO's band
of honchos will get to share in the success of all the startups
they help nurture.
</P>
<P>
   Just as venture firms spread their bets, iCEOs will participate
in what Coleman calls ``a diversified stock fund.'' Even though
each executive will work only one to five days a week for a few
months at each company, the daily fee will be a mix of cash and
stock. Each executive will keep half of the equity portion with the
other half going into a pool to be shared by all the iCEO
principals.
</P>
<P>
   ICEO's concept and innovative profit split is ``major cool,''
said financial consultant Jim Horan of El Sobrante, whose Web site
is &LR;  www.rentacfo.com &LR; . ``A lot of entrepreneurs have great ideas
but they are not long on life or business experience. Lots of
``dot-com'' and other startups are looking to buy or rent some gray
hairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Interim CEOs offer a variety of advantages for companies looking
for CEO help. Powell said that at any given time, Silicon Valley is
hunting for 200 CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said it can take nine months to land ``a full-time,
world-class'' chief executive, and many startups and their
investors don't feel comfortable waiting that long. Interim CEOs
also can address a host of urgent problems such as refining
marketing and financial strategies, signing joint venture
agreements or filling out the management team.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, iCEO expects to have 50 interim chief
executives on board. Some may get recruited for permanent jobs. If
that happens, iCEO, like traditional executive search firms, will
receive one-third of the salary and bonus in the first year of the
placed executive.
</P>
<P>
   ICEO isn't the only Silicon Valley management and financial
services firm. The Brenner Group also provides temp CEOs to
startups.
</P>
<P>
   The Brenner Group has 50 employees in Cupertino, including five
interim CEOs who coach high-tech companies and occasionally fill in
as acting bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Rich Brenner said the typical hourly fee of $250 to $400
an hour is often a mix of cash and stock, which, like iCEO's
format, is shared by the interim CEO and the firm's other
principals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hire people who have made a lifestyle change and fall into
one of two categories,'' said Brenner, who started the company in
1987. ``Some have reached for the brass ring, gotten it and want to
slow down a little. Others have worked for a variety of companies
and have realized the brass ring is elusive and they want a more
stable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Tom Tomasetti has been one of
Brenner's roving CEOs. After toiling to turn around three faltering
high-tech companies, the last one Consilium Inc., Tomasetti was
ready for a change. ``It was a tough way to live,'' he said. ``I
was burned out.''
</P>
<P>
   At Brenner, he has coached a dozen companies and acted as
interim CEO at several of them, the most recent of which is Lumina
Decisions, a Los Gatos financial management software company.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Tomasetti began working two days a week at Lumina,
helping it better define and market its different software and
consulting businesses. Now the company is spinning off part of its
business to Ask Jeeves, a Berkeley search engine company, and
Tomasetti will be interim CEO of the core business.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Murdock, founder of San Jose's Murdock &AMP; Associates which
also provides interim and full-time executives to venture-capital
backed startups, suggests ``the jury is still out on interim CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The function is so critical _ it's the core of the company _
that I'm not sure you can outsource it.'' But if it's only to tide
a company over until it can land a full-time chief, Murdock said
interim CEOs could be ``a great business model.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
