<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Robert Mondavi Believes His Company's Shares Are Poised  to
Surge 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Has Robert Mondavi been tasting too much of the family grape?
</P>
<P>
   The senior vintner of Napa Valley tells Street Smarts that
shares of the publicly held company that bears his name are going
to surge ``during the next 12 to 15 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi, who is chairman, says investors ``will begin to
understand the company much better, and (Mondavi) shares will
reflect that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our profits are going to be better, (and) we have great depth
with all of our international investments in Chile, Italy and
France,'' giving Mondavi broader brand diversification than many
privately held wineries, Mondavi said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   1999 has not been a vintage year for shareholder return. Mondavi
shares have turned sour, slipping 10.7 percent for the year. In
fact, yesterday they closed down $1.50 a share at $36.50. The stock
has been trying to rebound after having been crushed in August.
That's when Mondavi's Woodbridge brand ran into some severe
inventory problems causing shortages and weaker revenues.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Street likes Mondavi (no surprise there).
Eight out of the 10 sell-side analysts who follow Mondavi rate the
stock a ``buy,'' including Bonnie Kramer Tonneson of Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Tonneson upgraded her rating on Mondavi in December after the
company underwent some fundamental changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has been evolving into a more professional
organization, putting in some of the checks and balances expected
from a public company,'' Tonneson says. For example, management
shifted the responsibilities of Michael Mondavi, Robert's son, from
daily operator to that of a long-range strategist and brand
builder. What's more, Mondavi created brand teams similar to those
found at food companies and soap sellers, hoping to prevent
disastrous brand shortages such as the Woodbridge debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They, like the Beringers of the world, are focused on brand
building &UR;  &LR; _ which is a new phenomenon for the premium winemakers,''
says Tonneson, referring to Mondavi's primary publicly held
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premium wines, to date, have not been heavily promoted and
marketed to consumers. (Now) that they are, it gives consumers
confidence that they are making the wise choice,'' Tonneson says.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Beringer, the St. Helena winery reported quarterly
earnings yesterday that beat Wall Street's consensus estimates by 2
cents, according to Bloomberg. Earnings for its third quarter ended
March 31 were released after the close of the market. Beringer's
shares jumped almost two bucks to $44 in anticipation of the news.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Kraus, an analyst for First Security Van Kasper in San
Francisco, thinks Beringer's strong showing could help lift Mondavi
and other wine stocks. ``Wine stocks have been pretty flat,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, Kraus is still somewhat bearish on Mondavi.
She's one of the two analysts who rate the stock a ``hold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why the company's stock should trade above its
growth rate,'' meaning that the company's shares are expensive
compared to projections for future growth, Kraus says. Mondavi's
forward-looking price-to-earnings ratio is about 17, according to
Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   Wine companies have been able to raise prices at abnormally high
levels during the past two years, and they've managed to get away
with it, Kraus says. Now that there are fears of a grape glut,
vineyards have been slow to pass along lower costs to wine
drinkers. Thus, wineries need to focus on trimming their costs in
the event that the economy hits a speed bump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're in an extremely strong economy where people
are willing to spend a few extra bucks a bottle. But if the economy
should (falter), that could change,'' Kraus says.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Robert Mondavi contends that his company is doing
the things that Wall Street has asked of it, and now is time for
shareholders to taste the fruits of the company's labor.
</P>
<P>
   When Mondavi went public in 1993, ``we had to sell
(institutional investors) on this thing that we were a family
business,'' Mondavi recalls. Now, the Mondavi family has to
convince the Street that it knows how to manage its business _
period, he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CORRECTION: &LR;  Yesterday's Street Smarts published the wrong market
valuation for eBay. The online auctioneer has a market
capitalization of $26.14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
