<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Rising Rents Hit Small Businesses
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I am a Canadian citizen currently working for a U.S.
company as a TN alien, which is a special nonimmigration visa
category for Canadian and Mexican professionals entering the
country under the North America Free Trade Agreement. With a few
friends who have permanent resident status, I am planning to set up
a biochemical business in California. How do I get a visa and gain
U.S. resident status?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  If you abandon your job, which gives you your current
TN (transnational) status, you lose your right to work in the
United States, according to San Francisco immigration attorney
Steve Shaiken. TN status is designed to help American companies
compete, not allow self-employed professionals from Canada or
Mexico to work in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But you have other options. One possibility, if you don't need
any sleep, is to stay in your current job and do the biochemical
business on the side.
</P>
<P>
   A better choice might be to file an ``alien entrepreneur''
petition (Form I-526) with the U.S. Immigration &AMP; Naturalization
Service ( &LR; www.ins.usdoj.gov &LR; ). If you invest enough money and hire
enough Americans _ generally $1 million and 10 employees _ you can
probably win a permanent visa. Shaiken says that you would need to
own at least 51 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is applying for a ``nonimmigrant investor''
visa, which allows citizens of other countries to manage or direct
a business in the United States if they have made a ``substantial''
investment. This amount is not specifically defined, but often
requires at least $150,000 to $200,000, according to Shaiken. This
type of visa is usually good for five years and can be renewed
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Before starting your biochemical company, you would be well
advised to consult with the INS and a knowledgeable immigration
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
