<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: THE LOW-KEY PLEASURES OF MEDIUM-SIZED, OUTLYING
AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (Duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
 (bl)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big-city airports like to advertise themselves as vibrant,
exciting transportation centers. But most business travelers
collect and compare horror stories, not fond memories, about major
airports, which tend to offer the ambiance of federal
minimum-security prisons _ without the amenities.
</P>
<P>
   But there are alternatives, especially for business travelers
with flexible flying schedules. At many medium-sized airports on
the edges of metropolitan areas, passengers are still treated more
like desirable customers than potentially dangerous detainees.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, John Wayne Airport, which handles about 8
million passengers a year in Santa Ana, Calif., in Orange County
about 35 miles south of Los Angeles International Airport (which
gets about 62 million passengers a year).
</P>
<P>
   Arriving there on a recent business trip to Los Angeles was like
going back in time to Pleasantville. Time elapsed, from landing on
a Continental flight from Newark, N.J., to driving a rental car off
the premises after getting directions to Los Angeles from a
courteous, red-coated airport volunteer: 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm in a train station instead of an airport,''
one businessman at a nearby table remarked last week over breakfast
in the main terminal's Orange Bar &AMP; Grille. Unharried passengers
sat leisurely at nearby tables set into cozy nooks, reading or
chatting as the sun streamed through a vaulted glass ceiling. The
coffee and tea were served in china cups, with free refills, by a
cheerful waitress who said she had worked there since the modern
terminal opened nine years ago ``and the place never changes, even
though it's busier every year.'' The tab for a sit-down breakfast
for two, including bran muffins, fresh fruit salad, tea and coffee:
$8.29.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terminal was actually designed to subtly evoke the airy,
welcoming look and feel of a train station,'' said Nghia Nguyen, a
spokeswoman for the airport, which did a survey showing that about
half of its passengers were business travelers. ``I'm glad to hear
that someone noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a 9-foot bronze statue of John Wayne himself inside the
terminal. The Duke is wearing a cowboy hat, purposefully striding
into the sun, looking as if he had a nice trip, wherever he went.
</P>
<P>
   Lire to Go
</P>
<P>
   It's always convenient to have a little local folding money in
your pocket when you land at a foreign destination. Now AAA, the
auto club, and American Express have a service, Travel Funds
Direct, that can deliver 65 different foreign currencies to your
home in cash or in American Express traveler's checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's convenient for tips and cabs when you first arrive,''
said Janie Graziani, the manager of public relations for AAA. Not
all AAA offices offer the service; she suggests calling your local
office to check. The only charge connected with the service is for
shipping, and that depends on how quickly you want the money
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Try Harder
</P>
<P>
   The scene: Miami International Airport, the Avis Rent a Car
counter. At 5:40 a.m., on March 21. about 75 travelers have already
dropped off their cars and are waiting anxiously for the shuttle
bus to the terminal for early flights. Still waiting at 6 a.m., two
worried customers go inside the office to make inquiries. ``I don't
drive the bus! Somebody else drives the bus!'' growls the young
woman on duty behind the counter. (The bus lumbers in 10 minutes
later).
</P>
<P>
   Side Trips
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than half of the drivers who use cell phones to call for
emergency road service can remember their own cell phone numbers
when asked, the AAA says.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel amenity most desired by business travelers? A
newspaper at the door in the morning, according to Lodging
Hospitality, a hotel trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers took children along on more than 32 million business
trips last year, according to the Travel Industry Association of
America. That is up 32 percent over 1997, but the jump isn't
because business travel has become more leisurely. Schedules for
both parents and children have become so tight that what used to be
family vacation time is now often tacked on the tail end of
business trips.
</P>
<P>
   Haute Cuisine
</P>
<P>
   For guests unhappy about airline food, some hotels are selling
fancy boxed lunches to take along. The Boca Raton Resort and Club
in Boca Raton, Fla., for example, will send you on your way with a
sandwich, pasta salad, fruit and cookie _ for $17. ``As the
airlines cut back more and more on their meal services, we began
actively encouraging our guests to order these meals for their
journey home,'' said Todd Shallan, the hotel's food and beverage
director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
