<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5567 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-CUTLER-SPI &LR;      04-27 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-CUTLER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE MAKES MOVE TO BREAK U.S.-CANADIAN SALMON IMPASSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON AND JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Tuesday named his one-time legal
counsel, Lloyd Cutler, as a special representative to help break
the lengthy impasse in U.S.-Canada salmon negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment marks the most vigorous effort yet by the White
House to revive the U.S.-Canada salmon treaty, which has been mired
in impasse and controversy for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks we have to get it resolved this year, and that
there is a window of opportunity,'' said George Frampton, director
of the White House Council on Environmental Quality. Cutler will
report to Frampton.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing controversy has frequently disrupted U.S.-Canada
relations. Canada imposed an $1,100 ``licensing fee'' on
Alaska-bound fishing vessels in 1994. In 1997, a blockade by angry
Canadian fishermen kept the Alaska ferry ``Malaspina'' from leaving
Prince Rupert, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, controversy has impeded a binational effort to
conserve salmon that return from the north Pacific to spawn in
rivers of both countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dispute the Clinton-Gore administration wants to see
ended,'' Frampton said. Cutler voiced hope for an agreement by the
start of the salmon fishing season at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler is a specialist in arbitrating international disputes and
brings a long career of experience in high-level problem solving to
the table. He is also an experienced angler who has fished for
salmon in British Columbia's Campbell River and Alaska's Bristol
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Gov. Gary Locke said it is ``great news'' that
President Clinton has tapped ``a high-level person'' to oversee
efforts to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia Premier Glen Clark said in an interview: ``It
is good news that a `friend of Bill' has been named to head up the
negotiations. There has been a problem in lack of upper-level
involvement by the U.S. federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House also hopes that Cutler's prominence as an elder
statesman will bring increased pressure on Northwest governors and
tribal officials to reach a deal with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler, 81, served as counsel to Presidents Clinton and Carter,
and he has served in senior or advisory capacities in five
administrations on issues ranging from urban housing to nuclear
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows what a high priority this administration places on
bringing these negotiations to a close,'' said Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash. ``If we do not get an international agreement over fishing,
everything else (in salmon conservation) is for naught. This is
absolutely a critical part of saving salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   Frampton agreed. ``We really need to settle issues with Canada
in order to make progress on U.S. domestic salmon restoration,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler will not lead the U.S. negotiating team, but rather will
serve as the White House liaison to the governors of Alaska,
Washington and Oregon, the 24 Treaty Indian tribes, and Congress.
He will be in contact with Canada's fisheries minister and will
help the American states settle what concessions each must make.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler will work with Congress to help pass any agreement, or
get money to help restore salmon runs in river systems along
Canada's Pacific Coast as well as the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The actual negotiations are being done by U.S. Negotiator James
Pipkin of the Interior Department, Deputy Negotiator Larry Rutter
of the National Marine Fisheries Service, and representatives of
the states and tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have been under way since January and are expected
to continue over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler said he expects to get to work immediately, and to visit
the Northwest in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that the negotiations are going quite well, that
the parties are close, and that there's at least a hope that at
long last this can be finished off in a way that satisfies all
three states, two federal governments, and the Indian tribes,'' he
said. ``They'd love to finish it by the time the salmon season
starts, but I'm in no position yet to say whether that's
feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Frampton added that ``for the first time ever, the three
governors and the tribes are all involved and engaged with the
administration in seeking a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's Minister of Fisheries and Oceans, David Anderson,
called last year's talks ``dysfunctional,'' saying that at one
point there were 140 people meeting in seven separate rooms in
Portland, Ore., trying to forge an agreement on implementing the
treaty. But, speaking at a luncheon Tuesday at the Canadian Embassy
in Washington, he expressed optimism about this year's talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fishing season is fast approaching and for many of the
threatened salmon stocks, time is, in fact, running out,'' he said.
``Neither the patience of Canadians nor the health of the resource
will support the status quo ... for even another year.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said one remaining obstacle is the allocation of the
chinook harvest. He said it is a ``political impossibility'' that
Canada could accept a deal in which Alaska harvests the bulk of
chinook that spawn in Canada and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has steadily reduced its harvest of Northwest-bound
chinook, but still continues to catch the salmon at levels
considered excessive by Canadian and many Northwest fisheries
experts.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has been a major stumbling block. At the White House,
Frampton acknowledged that getting an agreement ``will be
difficult. I don't think anyone thinks not.''
</P>
<P>
   But major progress was made last year, largely through
conservation cutbacks imposed on Canadian fishermen, and a set of
informal deals between Locke and Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians allowed greater numbers of chinook and coho salmon
to reach rivers in northern Puget Sound. In turn, U.S. fishermen
held off fishing for the early Stuart run, sockeye salmon that
migrate more than 800 miles upstream to spawn in a tributary of
Canada's Fraser River.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our ad hoc agreements last year have given greater
impetus for everyone to reach a comprehensive settlement this
year,'' Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton praised Canadian officials for their initiatives last
year. ``They did some very significant things,'' he said. ``When
one party steps into the water, it becomes easier for others to
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark argued that ``British Columbia had to bear all the costs
of conservation'' in last year's informal agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that in the rush to an agreement, Canada will
capitulate as it did in 1998,'' he said. Clark applauded Anderson
for taking a more forceful position on preserving Northwest-bound
chinook salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Canada talks are occurring as the Northwest gears up to
respond to the listing of multiple salmon species as threatened or
endangered. Congress is debating whether to approve a new fund that
to help the states conserve salmon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
