<HEADER>
A5569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-ARCHDEACON-DERBY-     04-27 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ARCHDEACON-DERBY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Valhol will get to race
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The decision was electrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you won't find any of the jubilant racing folks using
that word around the Churchill Downs' stall of Valhol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just say it's put a real smile back on my face,'' Valhol owner
James Jackson said by phone from an Arkansas court room before
catching a flight to Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a Pulaski County (Ark.) Circuit Court ruling Tuesday
evening, Valhol _ a chestnut gelding some think is a horseflesh
version of the Energizer Bunny _ will run in Saturday's Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   And that gives this year's race a buzz like few others in the
storied 125 years of the event. Not that that's something racing
wants, because it involves the distinct possibility of cheating and
animal abuse and highlights an unseemly side of a sport trying hard
to polish its image.
</P>
<P>
   The taint here involves Valhol's shocking triumph in the
Arkansas Derby _ and whether jockey Billy Patin used an illegal
shocking device to jolt a 30-1 horse that never had a victory
straight into the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Before the April 10th Arkansas race, no one gave Valhol much
thought. He had raced just twice before and was yet to break his
maiden. His owner, trainer and especially Patin _ who never had won
a graded stakes race in 20 years of racing _ were all small-timers,
mostly from the lesser known tracks of Louisiana and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol went off at 30-1, but from the gate, Patin was able to
keep him on the flank of the pace setter. On the far turn, Patin
moved his horse to the lead and quickly opened a four-length lead.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the stunning finish was nothing compared to the shock of
what ESPN recorded just afterward. As Patin eased Valhol beyond the
finish line into turn one, cameras caught a small object dropping
from the vicinity of Patin's hand near the horse's left shoulder.
Soon after an employee on a tractor found an electrical device in
the dirt on the track's first turn.
</P>
<P>
   Called buzzers or ``machines,'' these crude devices are the size
of a disposable lighter. Made with a pair of taped-together AAA
batteries, some wires and two exposed prongs, they shock a horse
when a jockey - with the buzzer hidden in his palm _ rubs them
across the animal's neck as part of the riding motion.
</P>
<P>
   Though the practice is banned, it's more prevalent than you
think. According to statistics from the Association of Racing
Commissions International, there have been 242 instances over the
past 25 years where commissions have investigated the use of
buzzers by trainers, grooms, exercise riders and jockeys _ a few
with prominent names. Violators can be banned for life.
</P>
<P>
   With all that was at stake, the Arkansas Racing Commission held
up payment of Valhol's $300,000 winner's purse until a hearing on
May 5. Although done supposedly to give Patin's lawyer the extra
time he requested to provide a defense, the hearing date hurt
Jackson and trainer Dallas Keen because it would come four days
after the running of Saturday's Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol needed that $300,000 by this morning when entries are
drawn for this year's race. With 23 horses vying for the maximum 20
starting positions, the deciding factor will be each horse's graded
stakes earnings. Without the Arkansas cash, Valhol had just $38,400
_ last of all hopefuls. With the $300,000, he's a Derby certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's lawsuit cited a state law that said the Arkansas
commission had to distribute prize money within 96 hours of the
race. The court agreed and ordered the money be paid immediately.
</P>
<P>
   While the financial roadblock has been lifted, the taint on
Patin _ and possibly others _ has not. As to who did what, who knew
and who did not, it's all part of a growing Derby debate.
</P>
<P>
   When the charges first came to light, Patin told the Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette: ``I swear to God that I never did that.''
Initially, Jackson and Keen were vocal in their support of the
36-year-old jockey _ ``I don't think he used a buzzer,'' Keen said
late last week .''There are no marks on our horse.'' _ and Patin
was scheduled to ride Valhol in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   He exercised the horse during last week's early morning workouts
at Churchill, but as the controversy grew _ and the taped replays
of the race finally made Jackson say ``It looks absolutely bad,'' _
the owner said someone else would be in the irons should the horse
make the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a dark cloud over Billy, I had to tell him not to
bother to come to the barn anymore,'' a glum Keen said early
Tuesday morning as he stood in the rain outside Barn 42. ``It's too
bad because Billy's really a good guy, the kind who would give you
his last $10. He believes in this horse so much. He's walked it,
groomed it and sold me on it. He's done anything he could to get it
on its road to glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the first accusations came, I was crushed. It's turned
this whole trip here into something terrible. We shouldn't be in
the predicament we're in now. The instinct would be to point the
finger...but I won't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Patin makes an easy target. For 20 years, the Beaux Bridge, La.,
jockey has carved a meager living on small tracks for little money.
Along the way, there have been three suspensions in Louisiana and
one in Texas for violations of substance abuse rules.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, K.C., another jock with drug and alcohol problems,
was shot and killed outside of a New Orleans housing project.
Younger brother, Joseph Jr. was suspended six months by the
Louisiana Racing Commission in 1995 for possession of two
electrical buzzing devices found in his trunk in a jockey room.
</P>
<P>
   Buzzer incidents have occurred all over the racing world,
including Churchill Downs, where there were strong suspicions that
jockey George Atkins used an electrical device on 10th-place
finisher Hallieboy in the 1950 Derby. Two weeks later Atkins was
caught with a buzzer on another Churchill mount and suspended nine
years. In recent years there have been nearly twice as many buzzer
incidents in Louisiana as in California, New York and Kentucky
combined.
</P>
<P>
   There is a theory _ originally knocked about by Patin's own
lawyer _ that the jockey may have had a buzzer with him at the
Arkansas Derby, but ironically never used it when he found he was
on the ride of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``True vindication will come when we get to run on the first
Saturday in May,'' Jackson said Tuesday night. ``That's when Valhol
will show why we wanted him in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Patin meanwhile is in exile in Chicago, awaiting his May 5th
hearing. Not long after the Arkansas victory, he asked Keen for the
blanket of flowers that had been draped over Valhol in the winner's
circle. He took them to Louisiana where he put them on his
brother's grave.
</P>
<P>
   And now that they've become a funeral wreath, that's where they
belong. Thanks to Tuesday's court ruling, Valhol's Derby dream is
very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
