<HEADER>
A5576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-27 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES: MEL CARNAHAN, WILLIE BROWN, HAROLD STASSEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Missouri, Religion And Politics
</P>
<P>
   Back in January when Gov. Mel Carnahan of Missouri spared the
life of convicted murderer Darrell Mease, he explained that he did
so because he had received an ``extraordinary'' plea for mercy from
Pope John Paul II, who was then visiting St. Louis. The commutation
was a ``one-time act,'' the governor said, pointing out that in his
seven years in office he had approved more than two dozen
executions.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's explanation seems to have raised as many questions as
it answered _ no great surprise since he has set his sights on John
Ashcroft's seat in next year's U.S. Senate race, a contest that
could go either way.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls indicate that Carnahan, a moderate Democrat, is
within striking distance of Ashcroft, a Christian-right Republican.
But the polls also indicate that the governor's decision to commute
a murderer's death sentence to life imprisonment may have cost him
four times as many votes as he gained.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, another possible major factor in the race _
Ashcroft's early call for President Clinton to resign or be
impeached and convicted because of the Lewinsky matter _ appears to
have been a wash in terms of votes.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is a Southern Baptist in a state with large numbers
of Baptists and Roman Catholics, many in each group strong and
passionate supporters of the death penalty. That being the case,
mercy, not politics or religion, might very well have been the main
factor in his commutation decision, as he insists.
</P>
<P>
   But religion and politics, all mixed together, have since
entered the picture in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, who supports the death penalty but initially said
little about the governor's decision, has been increasingly
critical, declaring that a plea from a religious leader, no matter
how well intentioned, should not be allowed to change a court
decision or order.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, supporters of the senator, who opposes
abortion, have lately begun asking the governor, who supports
abortion rights, what he would do if the pope called on him to
condemn abortion.
</P>
<P>
   His answer: He remains his own man and a supporter of abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Come Saturday, Ashcroft will journey to St. Louis to hold a
hearing on victims' rights, with the star witnesses being members
of the family of the man Mease was convicted of murdering.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office contends the hearing is ``shameless
political exploitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator argues that its sole purpose is to guarantee that
the rights of victims are ``taken more seriously than they are at
present.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's Shadow In San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, when term limits were about to force him out of
his job as speaker of the California Assembly, Willie Brown
professed to have no interest in returning to his hometown, San
Francisco, to run for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street lights, dog doo and parking meters are not my cup of
tea,'' he demurred after 15 years of holding down the speakership,
the second most powerful elective office in the nation's most
populous state.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown, consummate master of the political game, has never
been known to say never and truly mean it. And so we find him today
in his fourth year as mayor of the City by the Bay, running hard
for the right to serve four more years.
</P>
<P>
   Street lights, dog doo and parking meters are now very much his
cup of tea _ along with such other quality-of-life urban bothers as
loitering homeless people, public drunkenness, poky urban transit
and, more recently as the election campaign has heated up,
panhandling, jaywalking and speeding drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an all-out war on people who do bad things,'' Brown
declared recently when he announced that some of the 200 new police
officers he plans to put on San Francisco's mean streets will go
after jaywalkers and speeders.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like a page from Rudy Giuliani's New York City playbook?
</P>
<P>
   Brown is leading in the polls. But those polls also show that
many of his constituents are fed up _ tired of sidestepping the
homeless who confront them daily on the sidewalk and in parks,
tired of the litter in the gutter, tired of traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, a Democrat, counters that he is cracking down. Is he
also following the lead of the mayor of New York, a Republican
whose critics say he is overdoing the quality-of-life thing?
</P>
<P>
   There has been no contact between the two, Brown's office
insists.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Boden, the executive director of the San Francisco
Coalition on Homelessness, is not persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's head-over-heals enamored with Giuliani's policies,''
Boden said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   For Harold Stassen, There's No Giving Up
</P>
<P>
   He turned 92 this month and he makes his home at an
assisted-living center near Minneapolis. But don't count Harold
Stassen out, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   He first ran for political office in 1930, winning a job as a
county attorney in Minnesota and then going on in 1938, at the
tender age of 31, to become governor of the state, the ``Boy
Wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Stassen, a Republican, has run for president 10
times _ or is it 11? _ obviously unfazed by the fact that his first
run, in 1948, was his best run and that each succeeding run has
drawn almost as many titters as votes.
</P>
<P>
   So what about the year 2000?
</P>
<P>
   In March, he said he was ``leaving the option open.'' Then a few
days ago, he qualified that a bit, saying: ``I'm not running for
anything. I'm only walking.''
</P>
<P>
   But he qualified that, too. He threw in a ``right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
