<SLUG> BC-TEEN-BOMBS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS' BOMBS AND THREATS OF BOMBS RAISE CONCERNS ACROSS TEXAS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week after the high school killings in Colorado, authorities
across Texas are reporting a spate of incidents that involve
violent threats by students and crude efforts to manufacture bombs.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven teen-agers are being held in Wimberley and
Wichita Falls alone, all of them on suspicion of making explosives,
some of which officials say were to be used to attack a school.
</P>
<P>
   In Port Aransas, high school officials suspended a teen-ager for
threatening a teacher. The boy's father then turned him over to
police after he found that his son had gathered bomb-making
information off the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Houston area, a half dozen or so students are being
detained or disciplined for everything from plans to detonate bombs
on campus to threats to poems that employ violent prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as school administrators can only take this very
seriously,'' said David Simmons, superintendent of the Wimberley
school district. ``The fact of the matter is that we realize what
the implications could be if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   If the massacre at Littleton's Columbine High School has yielded
at least some copycat tactics, it also has given way to vigorous
responses by school administrators and authorities. But while
communities around the state seem to be applauding the zero
tolerance policies, others see the crackdown as a threat to kids'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to go after those people who can't defend
themselves,'' said Greg Gladden, a Houston lawyer and president of
the American Civil Liberties Union of Texas. ``And as a class,
juveniles cannot defend themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladden predicted that the aggressive actions on the part of
administrators and authorities across Texas would eventually
backfire, making rebels out of teen-agers who otherwise might learn
to resolve their differences with society.
</P>
<P>
   Childhood specialists, meanwhile, warned that such pre-emptive
strikes against youths might distance students already on the
fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids who will be harassed are the ones who are quite
alienated,'' said Jeffrey Arnett, a visiting professor and human
development specialist at the University of Maryland. ``This will
only deepen their alienation.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Arnett said he understands how school
officials are feeling in the wake of one of the worst school
tragedies in the nation's history, and that ``I can't criticize
them for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen people died in the Littleton ambush, including one
teacher, all at the hands of two disaffected students who showed up
at school April 20 armed with guns and explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparent escalation in incidents involving kids and
bombs, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms reports that the
number of juvenile bombings dropped significantly between 1993 and
1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the Wimberley case, which involves four eighth-graders, it is
unclear how serious the teens were in their plan to carry out an
attack on the town's junior high school. A gag order has been
issued, but not before Hays County Sheriff Don Montague appeared on
national television saying the kids planned to kill nine people.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear how sophisticated the explosives were. A defense
attorney for one of the teen-agers, Ray Green, said a description
of the bomb as essentially a firecracker emptied into a pillbox was
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In Wichita Falls, four boys were found last weekend with
bomb-making materials in the back seat and trunk of their car. On
Tuesday a judge ordered that three of the four remain in custody.
The boys say they were experimenting with explosives but did not
intend to harm anyone.
</P>
<P>
   A bomb threat closed one of the city's three high schools
Tuesday, the second such threat to close a Wichita Falls high
school since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to Houston, a judge on Tuesday ordered a 12-year-old boy
to remain in custody while police investigate reports that he
planned to set off a bomb at an intermediate School in Montgomery
County's Willis school district.
</P>
<P>
   The boy is being held in the County Juvenile Detention center
after allegedly warning two classmates last week not to attend
classes because he planned to bomb Hardy Intermediate School, a
school district spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy's 680 students were sent to a neighboring school, but a
sweep of the building failed to turn up any explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, two 16-year-old Sugar Land boys also were being
detained after explosive devices were found in the trunk of their
car Friday outside Clements High School in the Fort Bend
Independent School District.
</P>
<P>
   In the Baytown area, a 13-year-old was expelled from school
after administrators recovered a poem he found on the Internet,
which included a line that asks for the courage to ``hide the
bodies of those I had to kill today.'' The boy now faces charges in
the juvenile system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this can't be taken lightly,'' said Dick
Duggan, principal at Highlands Junior High School, where the
incident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it should be taken so seriously as to pursue criminal
charges is to some a fair question. After all, they say, kids say
all sorts of things they don't mean.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, the development specialist, said that violent fantasies
among kids are highly unlikely to become violent acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not to exaggerate this,'' said Arnett. ``There
are millions of kids appalled by what happened in Colorado, just
like you and me.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
