<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     04-27 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: HOCKEY PIONEER TAKES THE SPORT TO ANOTHER LEVEL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Willie O'Ree sat in a glass-enclosed conference room
at National Hockey League headquarters, holding his own place in an
emotional and expectant week. Wayne Gretzky had retired the
previous Sunday, the Stanley Cup playoffs were beginning, and the
64-year-old O'Ree was in the midst of an East Coast swing,
preaching the hockey gospel.
</P>
<P>
   He would give the commencement speech for Ice Hockey in Harlem's
12th graduating class, then attend a two-day ice hockey tournament
in Newburgh, N.Y., as part of an initiative by the NHL and USA
Hockey diversity task force to help economically disadvantaged
students discover education through hockey. Thanks to O'Ree, who
was named director of youth development for the NHL in 1998, the
Harlems of the world are not as removed from the NHL as they once
were. He is a historic marker of the game, and for too many years
he was a missing mark.
</P>
<P>
   Who is Willie O'Ree and why is he important?
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, O'Ree's significance is recorded by two
crowning moments. The first and arguably the most significant
occurred on Jan. 18, 1958, when O'Ree became the first black man to
play in the National Hockey League. There was no drum roll, no
yearlong buildup as there had been 11 years earlier when Jackie
Robinson integrated Major League Baseball. The NHL, typically some
might argue, was a decade behind the other major sports. Canada's
hockey's divisions involved English vs. French, and the percentage
of blacks in the country was very small. But O'Ree said that there
were Canadian black players before him who were denied the
opportunity to play because of race.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Ree's historic moment was muted by a sport that, in the
1950s, was mostly an all-Canadian affair.
</P>
<P>
   O'Ree, a left wing with the Quebec Aces, was summoned by the
Boston Bruins as an emergency recall to meet the team in Montreal
for his first NHL game. He was 22 at the time, and didn't grasp the
significance of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, there are still incidents that remind us of the
racial divide in sports, even one so marginally integrated as
hockey. The latest came Monday night when Sandy McCarthy, a Flyers
forward who is part black and part Canadian Indian, accused
Toronto's Tie Domi of directing a racial slur at him during a
playoff game. Domi denied it, and said McCarthy spit at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about the NHL was that they don't tolerate
those things anymore,'' O'Ree said.
</P>
<P>
   But back then, all O'Ree knew was that he was fulfilling every
Canadian boy's dream. In O'Ree's mind, the team's 5-3 victory at
Montreal was a far greater accomplishment than the individual act
of integrating the sport. He played one more game with Boston, then
returned to the minor league team, where he stayed for almost three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got the second call. On New Year's Day 1961, he scored
his first professional goal; it was also the first goal by a black
player in the NHL &UR; . &LR;  In one of those moments of a lifetime, Boston
Garden fans gave O'Ree a two-minute standing ovation to commemorate
the occasion. This time, O'Ree savored the moment; he practically
dove into the net to retrieve the puck.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, O'Ree thought he would be a Boston Bruin for life.
He would not. He finished out the season, playing in 43 games and
scoring four goals. Boston traded O'Ree to Montreal after the 1961
season and Montreal assigned him to their farm team, establishing
the pattern of a career that would last for 22 years and encompass
11 teams, though only one in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   O'Ree played in the American Hockey League, the Central Hockey
League, the Eastern Professional Hockey League, the Quebec League
and the Pacific League. Where there was hockey, there was O'Ree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just loved the game,'' he said. ``It gave me so much. All I
ever wanted to do was be a hockey player, then give something back
when I retired.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Ree was born in Fredericton, New Brunswick, in October 1935,
the youngest of Rosebud and Harry O'Ree's 12 children. As a boy,
O'Ree played five sports. Baseball was his best sport after hockey,
and he played shortstop and second base. When he was 14, his team
in Fredericton won the Westend championship and earned a trip to
New York. The Canadian boys were taken to Brooklyn and saw Jackie
Robinson play; this was 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about baseball, we didn't talk about hockey,'' O'Ree
recalled. ``He asked me how I liked baseball, I said fine. I said,
`I like playing hockey too,' '' O'Ree recalled. He also remembers
the quizzical look Robinson gave him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said: `There aren't any black hockey players; they play
football or baseball,' '' O'Ree said, recounting that conversation
of some 50 years ago. ``I said, `There are some blacks playing in
Canada.' That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, O'Ree integrated the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   But the defining moment of his life happened before O'Ree turned
pro and had nothing to do with race or racism. It, too, was a test
of spirit and character and determination.
</P>
<P>
   He was 19, playing with the Waterloo Kitchener Junior Canucks.
During a game in Quebec, O'Ree was in front of the net when a slap
shot was deflected and hit him in the face, breaking his nose, his
jaw and shattering the retina of his right eye. Two days later,
doctors told O'Ree that he would never play hockey again.
</P>
<P>
   O'Ree said he refused to accept the verdict: ``I was telling
myself: `How can he stand there and tell me what I can or cannot
be? He doesn't know how I feel inside. He doesn't know the goal I
set for myself and what I really want to do.' I was determined to
play hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could think about was that I hadn't obtained my goal,''
O'Ree said. ``I was going to forget about what I can't see and deal
with what I can see.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Ree did play professionally. Poor eyesight, perhaps
exacerbated by racial issues, made his 1961 trip to the NHL his
last, but Willie O'Ree enjoyed a vibrant career in a sport he
loved. He now tells his story to students, not to boast, but to
bring home the importance of hard work and resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hockey League lost a legend recently when Wayne
Gretzky retired, but is fortunate to have rediscovered a treasure
before it was lost. In O'Ree, the NHL recaptured part of its
history. The league is stronger because of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
