<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-ITALIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA, INTENT ON DEUTSCHE TELEKOM DEAL, REJECTS OLIVETTI 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Telecom Italia took new steps Tuesday to thwart hostile
suitor Olivetti SpA, formally rejecting its $65 billion offer and
selling control of a pay-television subsidiary that the rival
telephone company had assumed would be part of any takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The formal rejection of Olivetti's offer was made necessary when
Olivetti's bid was accepted for shareholder consideration last week
by Italian stock regulators. In a statement, Telecom Italia's board
said it would convey its decision to the regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Though the statement contained no hint of the decision, people
close to the company said the bid had been rejected in a 50-page
document that would be released to the public later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The same people said Telecom Italia would push ahead with plans
to merge with Deutsche Telekom in a stock-swap deal valued at $82
billion, which was negotiated last week as part of an attempt by
Italy's largest telephone company to frustrate Olivetti's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia also announced Tuesday that it is selling 65
percent of its pay-per-view television operation, Stream, to a
group of companies including Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti, in a statement, protested that deal as an interference
with its planned bid, which formally begins on Friday and runs for
21 days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a bid by Murdoch to acquire 80 percent of
Stream failed after the Italian government passed a law blocking
News Corp.'s right to bid for Italian soccer broadcasting rights.
</P>
<P>
   If Tuesday's deal is made final, News Corp., Italy's Cecchi Gori
media group, and four Italian soccer teams will obtain the
broadcast rights to games of the four teams for a six-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Telecom Italia will retain 35 percent of Stream,
while gaining the strength of News Corp. to help it compete against
strong European rivals, like France's Canal Plus, which controls
Italy's leading pay-per-view company, Telepiu.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is typical of arrangements that Telecom Italia's chief
executive, Franco Bernabe, has proposed to reduce losses and
strengthen Telecom Italia through alliances. Under the deal,
Bernabe will have the right to appoint Stream's chairman, while
Murdoch will appoint the executives who run day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe's main concern this week has been the continuing
objections of the Italian government to his planned merger of
Telecom Italia with Deutsche Telekom. Rome has expressed deep
concern about the continued German government stake in Deutsche
Telekom, which will remain at 40 percent even after the combined
company is formed.
</P>
<P>
   Italian government officials, including the chief economic
adviser of Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, met German officials in
Frankfurt Tuesday to discuss the differences. Later this week,
Italy's treasury minister, Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, is expected to
take time out from international monetary meetings he is attending
in Washington to discuss the problem with Germany's finance
minister, Hans Eichel. Ciampi is chairman of the International
Monetary Fund's interim committee.
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to bet Tuesday that Bernabe and the Deutsche
Telekom chief, Ron Sommer, would fail in their effort to bring the
governments closer. On the Frankfurt exchange, Deutsche Telekom's
share price closed up 5.6 percent, at 37.90 euros, or $40.17, as
investors wagered that the merger would fail; in Milan, Telecom
Italia closed up 1.4 percent, at 9.94 euros.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema now finds himself in the curious situation of wielding
the Italian government's 3.4 percent `'golden share'' in Telecom
Italia as a weapon to interfere with management strategy because he
objects to the German government stake in Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a written assurance last week by Bonn that German policy
excludes interference in Deutsche Telekom management affairs,
Italian officials are seeking more explicit limits on German
government voting rights in the future company to assure parity
between Italian and German interests, and some kind of formal
commitment by Bonn to divest itself of Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Tuesday, Eichel said that Bonn could not speed the
sale of its stake in Deutsche Telekom `'in such a way that we put
pressure on the share price.'' But officials of the German and
Italian companies said the efforts of both governments to reach
some form of compromise reflected a fundamental interest in seeing
the merger proceed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
