<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5592 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-BOS &LR;      04-27 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIAN MILITARY LARGELY UNSCATHED BY BOMBING, NATO SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After five weeks and 4,400 sorties, NATO's
bombardment of Yugoslavia appears to have had little effect on Serb
leader Slobodan Milosevic's control over his military forces, or on
his ability to wage war and terror in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the upbeat rhetoric, Tuesday's news briefing in Brussels
by NATO commander General Wesley Clark presented, wittingly or not,
the gloomiest picture to date of how far the air war has yet to go.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody said so explicitly, but the numbers Clark recited
indicate that:
</P>
<P>
   --Serbia has more than enough petroleum to keep its army
operational.
</P>
<P>
   --Milosevic is still able to communicate with his people and
command his troops in the field.
</P>
<P>
   --The strength of his forces in and around Kosovo may be
growing, not shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   --The morale of his troops may be down a bit, but not
disastrously so.
</P>
<P>
   It may nonetheless be true, as some US officials have recently
said, that political cracks have opened within Milosevic's ruling
circle. It may even be true that these rifts, if they exist, have
been caused by the bombing, especially of political and economic
targets.
</P>
<P>
   However, NATO's own numbers suggest that, as a military
campaign, the air war has fallen far short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   US and NATO officials have been emphasizing the attacks on
Serbia's oil refineries and storage sites, noting that a modern
mechanized army will eventually grind to a halt without oil.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clark said Tuesday that 10 tankers a day have been
steaming into the Yugoslav port at Bar, offloading oil ``24 hours a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The general said NATO planes have destroyed 33 percent of the
military's oil reserves, but that leaves two-thirds intact. And, he
added, ``I don't think anyone truly knows how much oil is present
in Yugoslavia. . . . It's probably squirreled away in many, many
locations.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes have dropped many ``smart'' bombs on Serbian command
and control sites along with communications targets, but Clark said
Tuesday that Milosevic's command system is ``very hardened and
redundant.'' It makes use of a wide array of technology, including
fiber optic cable, high-frequency radio communication, and
microwaves, all of it interconnected. There are also ``more than
100 radio relay sites around the country,'' he said, making it hard
for airstrikes to knock out transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are having trouble communicating,'' Clark said, but he
also conceded, ``They're working through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark also acknowledged that Milosevic is moving more and more
troops into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been reinforced in the last three or four days by an
influx of newly mobilized reservists to replace combat
casualties,'' he added, ``and they've also been reinforced by the
continuing assistance and movement of elements from the Yugoslav
2nd Army, which is based in Montenegro.''
</P>
<P>
   These troops are fighting the guerrillas of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, herding displaced ethnic Albanians still in Kosovo
around the region, and stengthening defensive positions along the
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Serb troops stop moving when NATO planes fly
overhead, and ``the pace of their activities has been appreciably
affected'' as a result.
</P>
<P>
   However, he concluded, ``If you actually added up what's there .
. . you might actually find out that he's strengthened his forces
in there. And that's going to be the phenomenon until we can
further cut the lines of supply and go more intensively against his
forces. And we intend to be able to do that as we bring in more
assets and as the weather clears.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in ``more assets'' _ meaning more attack planes _ seems
to be taking a long time. In Washington Tuesday, Defense Secretary
William Cohen was asked about the status of the 300 additional US
aircraft that NATO requested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Cohen replied, ``we're waiting for General Clark to
provide a detailed analysis of exactly how many aircraft he will
need, what types, where they'll be bedded down, and so forth. That
has not _ I have not received that yet. . . . The mix of the
aircraft is still being worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   At his briefing, Clark repeated the claim, made several times in
recent days, that the Serbian army's morale has been sinking, as
evidenced by reports of desertions. However, when asked for details
about the desertions, he said, ``It's right now not a crushing
problem, but it is a significant problem. And I think we'll see
more of that in the weeks to come.''
</P>
<P>
   For William M. Arkin, a former US Army intelligence officer,
Clark's time estimate was the key point. ``If Milosevic's forces
are still going to be around long enough for us to continue seeing
desertions for several more weeks, then it's not a serious
problem'' for Milosevic now, Arkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark blamed the weather for some of NATO's difficulties,
noting, ``On about two-thirds of the days, we've had more than half
of the strike sorties canceled'' because of poor visibility. ``So
when I show you the results, I'd ask you to keep this in mind.''
The bombardment to date, he said, has been ``only a fraction of
what is to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
