A5594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PCORDER-EARNINGS-COX     04-27 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PCORDER-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PcOrder results please stock analysts
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ PcOrder.com passed its first test as a public
company _ pleasing financial analysts with its first quarterly
results.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin company, which makes software that manages the
purchase of personal computers and hundreds of related products
over the Internet, reported 70 percent revenue growth from the
first quarter a year ago and a smaller-than-expected net loss.
</P>
<P>
   The company lost $2.8 million, or 20 cents a share, on revenue
of $7.7 million, compared with a loss of $13,000, or less than 1
cent a share, on revenue of $4.5 million in the first quarter of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exciting start to a great stock,'' said Robert
Schwartz of SG Cowen Securities in Boston. ``They have a great
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are off to a flying start,'' said Lise Buyer with Credit
Suisse First Boston in Palo Alto, Calif. ``They did a terrific job
of keeping the top line (revenue) growing.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly results were the first for the company since it
raised $47 million by selling 2.53 million shares in its initial
public offering on Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Ross Cooley said the company expanded sales by
gaining new customers, forming strategic alliances and continuinged
development of its electronic commerce products. ``As the computer
industry grows Internet sales volumes, pcOrder.com will help set
the agenda for moving the industry to the Web,'' Cooley said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, pcOrder released ContentSource, a
subscriber-based system that enables large customers to gain access
to one of the industry's largest collections of product data and
prices from many companies.
</P>
<P>
   Egghead.com and Club Computer signed contracts for ContentSource
during the quarter. The company also sold its e-commerce systems to
two large resellers, Sarcom and Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The results were released after the close of stock market
trading. PcOrder's stock closed at $74 a share, up $2.31 1/4 in
Nasdaq trading. The stock has risen 252 percent from its $21
offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Ladendorf can be reached at kladendorfstatesman.com or
445-3622.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-04-27-99 2129E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
