<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYER-FEES-HNS &LR;      04-27 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-FEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATE PASSES BILL TO CURTAIL ATTORNEY GENERAL'S HIRING OF
PRIVATE LAWYERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Minus the passion that inflamed much of the
debate over the high legal fees in the tobacco case, the Senate
Tuesday gave almost routine approval to a bill to curtail the
attorney general's independence in hiring outside lawyers in major
state suits.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which now goes to the House, was approved on a
voice vote after only brief discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 113 by Sen. Troy Fraser, R-Horseshoe Bay, would
require key legislators to approve contingency contracts that the
attorney general negotiates with private lawyers for suits in which
the state's potential recovery is more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   It also would set limits on contingency fees and require that
all the money, including lawyers' fees, won by the state in a
lawsuit be deposited in the state treasury and appropriated by the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, it would require outside lawyers to keep time and
expense records and provide that those records would be subject to
public disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser said his bill would provide ``full disclosure and
accountability'' over the attorney general's dealings with outside
lawyers. It wouldn't affect the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   ``No elected official should have the authority to unilaterally
award these types of lucrative contracts without legislative
approval,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser was one of several state officials, including Gov. George
W. Bush, who fought former Attorney General Dan Morales last year
over the $3.3 billion eventually awarded five private lawyers hired
by Morales to sue the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the governor nor anyone in the Legislature challenged
Morales when he filed the suit in 1996 and announced the fee
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor, several lawmakers and John Cornyn, then a
Republican candidate for attorney general, challenged the fees as
excessive after it became obvious the lawyers were going to reap a
huge payday.
</P>
<P>
   The suit ended with cigarette makers agreeing to pay the state
$17.3 billion during the next 25 years and to separately pay the
five lawyers' fees, which were set by a national arbitration panel.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, in a recent interview, said that he opposed the bill
and that the suit may never have been filed if his ability to hire
the outside lawyers had been compromised.
</P>
<P>
   But Cornyn, who succeeded Morales on Jan. 1, has endorsed the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said he had concerns about the constitutionality of
contingency fee contracts signed by the attorney general without
legislative oversight. He said damages recovered by the state in a
lawsuit should be subject to legislative appropriation.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser's bill initially would have empowered the governor and
the lieutenant governor to approve contingency contracts. But he
amended the measure on the Senate floor to give the oversight role
to the Legislative Budget Board.
</P>
<P>
   The LBB is chaired by the lieutenant governor and includes the
House speaker and eight other key lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
