<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT     04-27 1852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/27/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) EL SEGUNDO, Calif. -- April 27, 1999 --
MATTEL-BOSS-MARKETPLACE, 4-27 -- Barbie was a tough sell in 1998,
but Jill Barad, in her office during a recent interview, had a good
year. While demand for Mattel Inc.'s biggest brand, Barbie, fell
and its stock tumbled 37 percent last year, the salary and bonus
paid to the toy maker's chairman and chief executive rose 14
percent to $4.75 million. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- April 27, 1999 --
LANDSLIDE-LIFE, 4-27 -- Patrick Hund clears a roadway on his
property last week in what has become almost a daily chore.
Residents of Ranchito Vista Road in the Sycamore Canyon area of
Santa Barbara County surmount a staggering obstacle every time they
leave their homes - a massive, active landslide that has been
inching forward daily since the heavy El Nino rains of February
1998 first sent the mass of mud slipping down the hillside. (Rafael
Maldonado/Santa Barbara News Press)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) CHIHUAHUA, Mexico -- April 27, 1999 -- MEXICO, 4-27 --
Protesters, many of whom walked for two days from their village to
reach the state capital, march against the illegal cutting of pine
trees in their forest last week. Stunned by the protest and the
news coverage it prompted, Chihuahua state officials recently
announced a halt to the illegal logging around the village in the
Sierra Madre, about 850 miles northwest of Mexico City. The banner
reads: ``Without Land or Resources, There Is No Future.'' (Wesley
Bocxe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- April 27, 1999 -- OBIT-HIRT-B&AMP;W, 4-27 -- Al
Hirt at the Jazz club Fat Tuesday's in 1984. Hirt, whose power and
technique made him ``The King of the Trumpet'' in the 1960's when
he won a Grammy for his hit ``Java,'' died Tuesday at the age of
76. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) JENKINTOWN, Penn. -- April 27, 1999 -- INTERNET-SPEED,
4-27 -- Cable modem owner John Drees, left, and his next door
neighbor Brian Bamberger, a phone modem user, pose while holding
wires belonging to their respective communication devices in front
of Drees' computer. Much-hyped and long-delayed, high-speed
Internet access is finally coming to the home, with research firms
predicting that10 to 16 million households will sign up by 2002.
(Tim Shaffer/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) KUKES, Albania -- April 27, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
4-27 -- Ethnic Albanian children, refugees from the violence in
Kosovo, pick flowers near a plant being used to dry clothes at a
refugee camp near the border with Kosovo on Tuesday. A total of 464
Kosovar Albanians arrived on Monday in Albania, including women who
claimed to have been molested by Serbian forces, the UN refugee
agency UNHCR said. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 27, 1999 --
SUB-COLO-SHOOTING-SHRINE-3, 4-27 -- Mourners gather around one of
many makeshift memorials near Columbine High School on Tuesday.
Thousands of flowers, posters and messages have been left near the
school where 12 students and a teacher were slain last week by two
students who committed suicide following their shooting rampage.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 27, 1999 --
COLO-SHOOTING-SHRINE-2, 4-27 -- Mourners gather around one of many
makeshift memorials near Columbine High School on Tuesday.
