to fill with precious items she found all over the world. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KUKES, Albania -- April 27, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 4-27
-- An ethnic Albanian refugee from Kosovo, who says he was hit in
the face with the butt of a rifle by a Serbian soldier expelling
him from his home, at a refugee camp just over the Kosovo border on
Tuesday. A total of 464 Kosovar Albanians arrived on Monday in
Albania, including women who claimed to have been molested by
Serbian forces, the UN refugee agency UNHCR said. (Edward
Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- April 27, 1999 -- FAT-COOKING-2, 4-27 --
Halibut that has been poached in a quart of hot goose fat at Union
Pacific. Fat. For years, it's been a four-letter word so repugnant
to many of us that it only required three. And yet the best chefs
know they can't be great without it. (Michael Rogol/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 27, 1999 -- FAT-COOKING-1, 4-27 --
Rocco DiSpirito, the chef at Union Pacific, prepares halibut that
has been poached in a quart of hot goose fat. For years, fat has
been a four-letter word so repugnant to many of us that it only
required three. And yet the best chefs know they can't be great
without it. (Michael Rogol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 27, 1999 -- WEST-THEATER-REVIEW, 4-27
-- Brian F. O'Byrne, left, and Maeliosa Stafford play battling
brothers in Martin McDonagh's ``Lonesome West,'' which opened
Tuesday night. What you see at the start is what you get for the
rest of the evening, and it all starts to seem as repetitive as a
Tom and Jerry cartoon. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- April 27, 1999 -- SALESMEN-THEATER, 4-27 --
Brian Dennehy, left, in ``Death of a Salesman,'' and Kevin Spacey
in ``The Iceman Cometh.'' The presence on Broadway stages of
American drama's two most powerfully drawn salesmen once again
compels attention. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- April 27, 1999 --
BKN-KINGS-WILLIAMS, 4-26 -- Many young black youngsters who turn up
to see Jason Williams play say he is the coolest white player they
have ever seen, and they view White Chocolate (his controversial
nickname) as evidence of Williams' embrace of, and acceptance in,
the hip-hop culture. Williams' game, though, is not merely about
flair. He is averaging 13 points, 6 assists and 3 rebounds a game,
and his production as a first-year player is rivaled only by
Toronto's Vince Carter. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 27, 1999 -- WHALE-FLOATER, 4-27 -- Rudy
Valencia cleans the tail of the life-size replica of a Blue Whale
hanging over the Hall of Ocean Lifebiology at the American Museum
of Natural History on Tuesday. The whale is a 94 foot fiberglass
rendering of a female blue whale captured in 1925 off South Georgia
Island, east of Tierra del Fuego, an archipelago at the southern
tip of South America. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PELHAM, N.Y. -- April 27, 1999 -- SATELLITE-DISH-TV, 4-27
-- Paul Falla, an employee with a local satellite dish installation
company, fine tunes the positioning of a dish on Tuesday for a
client. The House of Representatives on Tuesday approved
legislation to allow satellite television services, for the first
time, to carry local broadcast stations. (Richard L. Harbus/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- April 27, 1999 -- CLINTON-GUNS-2, 4-27 --
From left, Sen John Chaffee, Reps. Steven Rothman and Carolyn
McCarthy, join President Clinton and his wife in bowing their heads
during a moment of silence in memory of the victims of last weeks
shootings at Columbine High School at the White House on Tuesday.
Clinton addressed a group of Senators and Congressmen about the
need to enact gun control legislation. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- April 27, 1999 -- CLINTON-GUNS, 4-27 --
Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., hugs President Clinton after he
addressed Congressional leaders about the need to enact new gun
control legislation on Tuesday at the White House. First lady
Hillary Clinton looks on at right. Clinton's statements came a week
after 15 students where killed at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo. Rep. McCarthy's husband was killed and a son
injured by a gunman on a New York commuter train in 1993. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 27, 1999 -- AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS, 4-27 -- C.
Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T chairman, during a news conference earlier
this year announcing the company's intention to acquire
Tele-Communications, Inc. (TCI). AT&AMP;T reported a 39 percent rise in
first-quarter earnings on Tuesday, surpassing Wall Street
expectations. The jump in revenue was attributed to cellular phone,
corporate phones and other services which offset a further decline
in its flagship long-distance business. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GAZA, GAZA STRIP -- April 27, 1999 --
ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS, 4-27 -- Protesters call for the leadership of
the PLO to declare statehood next week during a demonstration
outside Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's office on Tuesday.
Arafat convened the PLO leadership on Tuesday to decide whether to
declare a Palestinian state on May 4 or extend peace talks with
Israel for another year. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- April 27, 1999 -- THERMOMETER-GUN, 4-27 -- A
thermometer which uses infrared light to sense heat. Raytec, which
has produced such devises for auto mechanics to determine engine
temperatures, has now produced a smaller version for the kitchen.
(Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
