<SLUG> BC-TEX-CAPITOL-REPORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Senate OKs database of gang members
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service Staff
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas would establish a statewide database on
suspected criminal street gang members _ including people who
haven't been arrested _ under a bill that won Senate approval
Tuesday in the wake of school violence in Colorado and alleged
threats in this state.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which is part of an anti-gang package and now heads to
the House for consideration, was developed long before last week's
Colorado school shootings by two students.
</P>
<P>
   But a senator who supports the measure referred to the massacre
in Colorado and to recent allegations that junior high students in
Wimberley were planning an attack on their Central Texas school
with homemade bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the events in Colorado . . . the nation is searching for
answers, and we're all taking an introspective look at what we
do,'' said Senate Criminal Justice Committee Chairman Ken
Armbrister, D-Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one simple thread that constantly runs through. . . .
That single thread is shock. How could this exist in our community?
What we did today will go a long way to educating the people of
this state to the real problems of crime,'' Armbrister said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, including Gov. George W. Bush, said the measure
would provide an important tool for law enforcement officers around
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed unanimously after an amendment was narrowly
defeated on a 15-15 vote. It would have required a vote of the city
council or county commissioners court for a local law enforcement
agency to participate in the statewide database.
</P>
<P>
   Activists: Old factories foul air Smog-causing pollution from
Texas' older industrial plants can travel hundreds of miles by air,
affecting urban areas already struggling with air-quality problems,
environmentalists said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty old industrial plants in Texas are not just fouling
their own nest,'' Texas Sierra Club Director Ken Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   A plan pushed by Gov. George W. Bush _ and already approved by
the state Senate _ would allow companies to volunteer to reduce
emissions at their ``grandfathered'' older plants, which are exempt
from some state pollution regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say pollution reductions should be required by
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through air pollution carried by wind currents, these
grandfathered air polluters are adding to the air-quality problems
of Texas cities and suburbs over a hundred miles from the plants,''
Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Bike helmet bill gets initial OK Children under 15 years old who
live in cities with populations of 200,000 or more would be
required to wear bicycle helmets under heavily amended legislation
given preliminary approval by the Texas House.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE OF THE DAY
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call this the Barney Fife amendment.'
</P>
<P>
   _ Senate Criminal Justice Committee Chairman Ken Armbrister,
D-Victoria, while debating gang legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
