<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET INCOME TRIPLES AT AMERICA ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Signaling a continuation of its vigorous growth, America Online
Inc. on Tuesday reported profits of $420 million for the first
three months of the year, a figure that included a number of
one-time items.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the special items, the company earned $117 million in
the quarter, up 200 percent from the comparable period a year
earlier. That comes to 11 cents a share, 20 percent higher than the
9 cents analysts had estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The special items included a one-time pretax gain of $567
million from the sale of shares in Excite Inc. And AOL took a
charge of $103 million related to its acquisition of Netscape
Communication Corp., which was completed in March.
</P>
<P>
   The company's flagship online service added 1.8 million
subscribers in the three months, bringing the total to 16.9
million. The service continued to occupy more of members' time,
with the average account in use 55 minutes a day, up from 46
minutes a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both membership and advertising revenue was higher than I
expected,'' said Stephen Case, the company's chairman. The winter
months are always strong for the company as people who receive
computers for Christmas sign up for the service. Still, membership
is accelerating, Case said, adding, ``More and more people can
afford PCs as the prices come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising and payment from companies doing business on America
Online's services increased 119 percent, to $210 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company released its earnings report after the close of the
market. The shares had dropped $9 during the day to close at $153.
In after-hours trading, the shares rose as high as $157.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted that for the first time in recent years, America
Online's advertising revenue grew faster than that of Yahoo Inc.,
the largest advertising-supported Web service.
</P>
<P>
   America Online dominates the market for home users, while
services like Yahoo are used mostly by people in offices. ``If you
want nighttime coverage for your message, AOL is your only
choice,'' said Brian Oakes, an analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``If
you want to reach people in the daytime at their businesses, you
can choose from a lot of portals.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Braverman, an analyst with Nationsbanc Montgomery
Securities, said America Online had a backlog of $1.3 billion in
advertising sold for future periods. ``That comes out to $133
million a quarter for the next two and a quarter years,'' he said.
``That means that they essentially have half their nut covered
already.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, analysts said, the company is showing increasingly
strong financial performance. Its gross profit margin, Oakes said,
rose from 38 percent in the last quarter of 1998 to 41 percent in
the most recent quarter. ``They had a big kick in revenue and they
are running their network more efficiently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the company reported revenue of $1.3 billion, up 66
percent from a year ago. The bulk of that was $869 million in
subscription fees, which increased 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Case said that the company's Compuserve service had begun to
show a small increase in its base of 2 million subscribers after
years of steady declines. Still, the company has yet to come up
with a marketing message for a major promotion for the service, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Case declined to comment on reports that America Online was
considering backing Comcast Corp.'s battle with AT&AMP;T to buy
MediaOne Group, the cable company. Still, he indicated that America
Online wanted access to cable systems in order to offer high-speed
access to homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do things that support our strategy of building a
more ubiquitous medium,'' Case said, adding that the company had
the ability to make another big acquisition, even as it
incorporates Netscape. ``We have the management bandwidth, but we
will only do things if they make sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
