<HEADLINE>
CALBASAS WOMAN HONORED FOR BUSINESS ACHIEVEMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lauren Raissen's husband loved pickles but she
didn't care for his breath afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to drive me absolutely crazy,'' said the 34-year-old
native South African who now lives in Calabasas northwest of
downtown Los Angeles. ``I told him it's the pickles or me.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the breath fresheners on the market worked. So the
Raissens set out to develop a better product.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Raissen is the president and chief financial officer of
Breath Asure. The Calabasas company markets five different breath
products and enjoys $25.5 million in annual sales. Not bad for a
mother of two and accountant who started the company out of her
garage.
</P>
<P>
   Working Woman magazine noticed. Raissen was named one of its top
500 businesswomen in the country in 1999. It's her second year to
be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   Her company ranked 291. She was listed alongside Oprah Winfrey,
Martha Stewart and Katherine Graham of the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The listings underscore the progress achieved by female-owned
businesses. Working Woman's 500 top companies generate nearly $72
billion in annual revenues; in the past decade, women-owned
businesses increased by 78 percent, according to the National
Foundation for Women Business Owners. Women provide jobs for one
out of every four workers, according to Working Woman.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, other honorees include Margaret Sahroian of Foothill
Nissan of La Crescenta, Herminia Dilbeck of Dilbeck James R. Gary &AMP;
Co. in La Crescenta, Lynda Resnick of Roll International in Los
Angeles and Dineh Mohajer of Hard Candy in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Raissen started the company when she was 27, hoping to build a
home-based business so she could stay home with her children. At
the time, her husband had an electrical contracting business where
she was second in command. When the family's second business,
Breath Asure, was launched, she told her husband that she didn't
want to play second fiddle this time.
</P>
<P>
   Since the company was founded in 1992, it has taken off.
First-year sales of $40,000 have soared to over $25 million
annually with 37 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Breath Asure became so successful that it eclipsed the family's
electrical contracting business, leading to the decision to
discontinue that venture.
</P>
<P>
   Raissen believes her greatest contributions have been keeping it
on a conservative growth track, creating a good working environment
and emphasizing teamwork and joint decision-making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
