<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HEALTHCARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE-PAYER HEALTH PLAN SAVES MONEY, REPORTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Two independent groups commissioned by the
Massachusetts Medical Society to explore switching the state's
current health care system to a Canadian-style single-payer
approach have found that between $170 million and $1 billion a year
could be saved while coverage is extended to hundreds of thousands
of uninsured residents.
</P>
<P>
   The reports are notable not only for their findings, but also
for who commissioned them. The medical society, along with the
American Medical Association and other professional groups, has
long opposed a single-payer system.
</P>
<P>
   And in another twist: While the AMA rejected a 1996 request by
some members to even study the single-payer issue, the
Massachusetts society commissioned two such reviews in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The closely guarded reports, which have not been publicly
released but were obtained by the Globe, are slated to come up at
the Massachusetts society's annual House of Delegates meeting in
Boston next week.
</P>
<P>
   Some society members and other physicians say the reports'
findings support what they consider to be an urgent need to revamp
the current health system, given the rising number of uninsured and
still-escalating health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not working, and I think that doctors as a whole are
going to have to rethink their position,'' said Dr. Arnold S.
Relman, emeritus editor-in-chief of the New England Journal of
Medicine and a member of the society's House of Delegates.
</P>
<P>
   So closely guarded are the reports that Relman at first refused
to discuss them, until he was told the Globe independently obtained
copies and was preparing a story anyway. The two groups that did
the reports, a consulting firm known as the Lewin Group and a team
of researchers from Philadelphia and Boston University School of
Public Health, have also been asked not to talk about the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are not going to be satisfied. They're simply not
going to settle for what they have now,'' said Relman, who has long
supported a single-payer approach. ``It's just a crazy system.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David U. Himmelstein of the Physicians for a National Health
Program said the reports' findings do not surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to cover everybody in society at a reasonable
cost, the only way to do it is single payer,'' said Himmelstein, a
Harvard Medical School associate professor. ``The savings are on
administration and waste. Basically, you get more health care and
less bureaucracy from a single-payer system than from any other
alternative. That's why we've advocated it for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients and providers who have had to contend with the
patchwork quilt of multiple health insurance plans in this state
and the nation know about the costly paperwork they generate,
according to single-payer supporters. Each plan has its own set of
co-pays, deductibles, list of covered procedures and complicated
rules, as well as its own stack of claim forms.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 Massachusetts residents fed up with the
multiple-payer system here rallied on the State House steps in
support of a single-payer bill Tuesday, just before a Joint Health
Care Committee hearing on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Trimming the administrative overhead by creating one payer would
save about $3.6 billion in 1999 in Massachusetts, according to the
high-end estimate in the report by consultants Solutions for
Progress of Philadelphia and Alan Sager and Deborah Socolar of the
Boston University School of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   That figure, plus aggressive savings elsewhere, add up to a
total $5 billion reduction out of the current $36 billion that
Massachusetts spends on health care each year, under this model.
</P>
<P>
   And it would cost only about $4 billion out of that $5 billion
saved to cover all the uninsured and expand health benefits to
those who already have insurance _ hence the high-end estimate of
an immediate $1 billion a year in savings from a single-payer
system in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   On the low-end, the Lewin Group report estimates a 1999 savings
of about $2.5 billion in Massachusetts from eliminating the extra
administrative expense of having multiple insurers, and few savings
from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that lower savings figure, the Lewin Group report
estimates it will take until the year 2005 before an overall
reduction is achieved from going to a single-payer system and
expanding coverage to everyone. The savings that year are estimated
to be about $170 million, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of the Massachusetts Medical Society and the
American Medical Association said their organizations, while
supporting measures to provide universal access to care, continue
to back a multiple-payer, or pluralistic, approach as the best way
to give Americans choice and preserve quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pluralistic, multipayer system, has been the preferred
policy. . .mostly because of the members' belief that patients
should have a choice of health insurance options,'' said Frank
Fortin, communications director for the 17,000-plus member state
medical society.
</P>
<P>
   Fortin said he could not comment on the contents of the
consultants' reports. It is up to the House of Delegates to decide
whether to publicly release the reports, which are considered
informational and not the basis for policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy Dickey, president of the AMA, said that while there
may be administrative savings from a single-payer system, the
experience in Canada and other countries shows certain
disadvantages. ``Virtually all of them are privatizing a piece of
their system,'' Dickey said. ``They have a substantial waiting line
as they attempt to control expenditures of funds. They do so by
rationing the amount of care that they give.''
</P>
<P>
   While she said she ``looks forward to reading'' the studies
commissioned by the Massachusetts society, the AMA is ``currently
opposed to a single payer system'' while it is ``in support of
every American having access to care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Association of HMOs did not return a phone
call Tuesday seeking comment on the reports on the single-payer
system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
