<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5621 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-GOOGLIOTTA-A     04-27 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-GOOGLIOTTA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOGS EXPECTS THE BOOS IN MINNESOTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ When Denver's Antonio McDyess made his first visit
to America West Arena this season, Phoenix forward Tom Gugliotta
had to laugh at the cascade of boos rained down on McDyess by the
fans that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get that in Minnesota,'' Gugliotta said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Gugliotta makes his first return to the Twin Cities,
where he played four seasons and blossomed into the Minnesota
Timberwolves first NBA All-Star in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But like McDyess, Gugliotta spurned his old team _ despite
having to take less money to leave than he could have gotten to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   So Gugliotta figures he won't hear that familiar
``Goooooooooogs'' from the Target Center crowd tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably get booed, I would think,'' Gugliotta said. ``As
nice as those people are, they'll probably still boo me _ just
because of the fact that I made the decision to leave there.''
</P>
<P>
   And just as Phoenix followers wondered why McDyess would leave
the Suns for less money, Minnesota fans asked the same questions
about Gugliotta's decision. But Gugliotta said it was more about
winning games, and where he fit into the club's plan, than about
money.
</P>
<P>
   Was there anything the Timberwolves could have done that would
have convinced him to stay?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Gugliotta said. ``It was a tough decision, but
there probably wasn't anything they could have really done to
convince me. I felt there was a better opportunity, long term, here
(in Phoenix).''
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, the club was being built around forward Kevin
Garnett and point guard Stephon Marbury. After four years,
Gugliotta wanted to see more done to win immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt at times maybe I was just a holdover until KG and
Marbury were in their prime,'' said Gugliotta, who is 29 years old.
``I didn't want to play for something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'm 33, 34 years old, they're in their prime and I'm on
my way out _ if they don't trade me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think there was an urgency to win now. A couple years
ago (in the playoffs), Terry Porter was playing great for us, but
he didn't get any minutes because they wanted Steph to come along.
I'm like, `What about winning right now?' I can't blame them for
thinking that way. I just didn't want to be part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that Gugliotta didn't like playing with
Marbury. He has denied there was a problem, but he doesn't deny
that he suspected Marbury was not committed to the franchise for
the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always talked about how he wanted to play in New York, or
at least in a bigger market,'' Gugliotta said. ``He always talked
about that and about being closer to his family in New York. He was
young, and you couldn't always pay attention to some of the things
he was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Timberwolves eventually realized that Marbury wasn't
going to remain happy in Minnesota. He wanted to be paid more money
than Garnett, a dynamic and versatile big man. Marbury made it
known he wouldn't be satisfied as the second-highest paid player on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves traded him to New Jersey in a three-way deal
that sent Milwaukee point guard Terrell Brandon to Minnesota and
New Jersey playmaker Sam Cassell to the Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he's got a lot of confidence in his ability,''
Gugliotta said of Marbury. ``He didn't think he should be second
highest (paid), but that's the way the rules were. There was
nothing else they could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gugliotta doesn't expect the Target Center crowd to
understand all of that, or care. He's prepared for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's if Gugliotta is even introduced. He missed
Monday night's game in Utah because of an ankle sprain and is
questionable for tonight's game. He also missed a game against his
former team April 7 in Phoenix because of a hyperextended knee.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta knows how these things work. He was traded by
Washington to Golden State after two seasons, then sent from the
Warriors to the Timberwolves in the same season. When a player is
traded, fans usually blame the team and there is a warm reception
on that first return.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is (different) because I made the decision to leave,''
Gugliotta said. ``They're proud people, and I don't think they
liked that very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gugliotta said he has fond memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed playing there, especially being there at the
beginning when the team wasn't any good and going through the
process, helping the organization win, seeing people come along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first city I got attached to. In D.C., I was there
for two years, but that was so long ago, I forget how I felt.
Golden State, I was dying to get out of there. The people were
fine, but I didn't want to stay with that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Minnesota, I played some of my best basketball. I've got
great memories. It was a good city and the people really took to
basketball. We were lucky. Pro sports there, you never know if a
franchise is going to succeed. They lost hockey. But there's a big
following for the T-Wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fellow they called ``Googs'' will likely hear from them
tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
