<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TILLMAN MOVING TO STRONG SAFETY DURING MINICAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals second-year pro  &UR; Pat Tillman will learn
a new position this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He is moving to strong safety from free safety and will work
there for the first time Friday morning at the start of a three-day
minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   With Tillman moving to strong safety, veteran  &UR; J.J. McCleskey,
who played cornerback and strong safety a year ago, will switch to
free safety. McCleskey also will continue to work at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told Pat that with a year under his belt, he has to learn
the other safety, and the best way is to have him practice there,''
secondary coach  &UR; Larry Marmie said. ``We feel he has a pretty good
grasp of free safety. Now he needs to learn strong safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillman, a seventh-round draft pick a year ago out of Arizona
State, said the switch is fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool,'' said Tillman, who started the first 11 games at
free safety last season before losing the job to  &UR; Kwamie Lassiter.
``I couldn't care less where I am. I just want to play. Certain
responsibilities will change. I know there is a little bit more man
coverage at strong safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals two safety spots are interchangeable, but at
strong safety, Tillman will be involved more in covering the tight
end.
</P>
<P>
   Marmie said he thinks McCleskey is more suited for free safety
because of his strong coverage skills ``in space'' and on deep
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter where I line up,'' McCleskey said. ``During
games, I play free safety, strong safety and cornerback. So, I have
to know everything. I'm a jack of all trades.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will open training camp with Lassiter as the
starter at free safety and  &UR; Tommy Bennett as the starter at strong
safety. &QL; 
Irving released
</P>
<P>
   When the Cardinals didn't protect outside linebacker  &UR; Terry
Irving in the expansion draft, he knew his job on the team wasn't
secure.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals released Irving on Tuesday, making him an
unconditional free agent. The Cardinals also released veteran
cornerback  &UR; J.B. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Irving, a sixth-year pro, was inactive in nine of 16 games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   With his departure, the team saves his salary of $520,000 for
1999. But his signing bonus of $166,700 this season and next will
count against this year's salary cap. &QL; 
Back in the saddle
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defensive tackle  &UR; Bernard Wilson signed a one-year deal
on Tuesday. Details weren't disclosed, but it is believed to be
worth $400,000
</P>
<P>
   He will compete for a backup job behind starters  &UR; Eric Swann and
 &UR; Mark Smith. &QL; 
The only veteran defensive lineman unsigned is Smith, a third-year
pro whose rights are exclusively owned by the Cardinals. &QL; 
Fast starter
</P>
<P>
   Second-year wide receiver  &UR; Andy McCullough is tied for the NFL
Europe League lead in catches with 12.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, who plays for Frankfurt, is second in receiving
yards with 189 and also second in touchdowns with two.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough had seven receptions for a team-high 101 yards in
last weekend's 17-13 loss to Amsterdam. &QL; 
Great expectations
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months before next year's draft, the first mock draft is
out, and it has the Cardinals picking 30th, meaning they will make
it to the Super Bowl as NFC champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Springfield Draft'' publications has the Cardinals getting
University of Washington defensive tackle  &UR; Jabari Issa with the
30th pick.
</P>
<P>
   The only team picking behind the Cardinals is Jacksonville, the
projected Super Bowl winner.
</P>
<P>
   Two local players were picked to go in the first round _ Arizona
State running back  &UR; J.R. Redmond to New England at No. 18 overall
and Northern Arizona running back  &UR; Ronney Jenkins, an
underclassman, to San Francisco at No. 26. &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Second-round draft pick  &UR; Johnny Rutledge of Florida will line up at
a backup left linebacker spot when Friday's minicamp opens. He will
play behind free-agent acquisition  &UR; Rob Fredrickson in  &UR; Jamir
Miller's old position.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie free-agent linebacker  &UR; Robert Smith of Cumberland has
decided not to sign with the team.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bob Ferguson, team vice president-player personnel, was the
NFL's guest in a chat room Tuesday and was in demand. More than 60
people participated in the 30-minute session and there were still
175 questions to answer when the chat ended. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
