<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH POOL OF TALENT AWAITS WNBA DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rich will get richer. The poor will get much richer.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is going to win in the WNBA draft except the collegiate
senior class. Other than expected No. 1 pick Chamique Holdsclaw,
collegians will be an afterthought in the four-round, 48-player
selection, originally scheduled Tuesday and now likely to be held
early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike 1997 and '98, when the battle between the American
Basketball League and WNBA was to sign the premier collegians, the
war now is over. Except for a five-state investigation into
possible unfair competitive practices by the NBA leading to
bankruptcy for the ABL in December, the WNBA has clear sailing once
its players ratify a four-year collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And the 12-team league, which expands to 16 in 2000, is about to
benefit from an influx of talent that will not be seen again.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the ABL left 32 Kodak All-Americans, several of
those with U.S. Olympic or World Championships experience, out of a
job. Even those who haven't played overseas boast ABL seasoning,
which likely means the first round of the draft will go
collegiateless after the Washington Mystics select Holdsclaw.
</P>
<P>
   It can even be argued that the 6-foot-2 Holdsclaw, only the
fourth four-time Kodak All-American, is not the best value in a
draft that includes ABL posts Yolanda Griffith and Natalie
Williams, plus Natalia Zassoulskaia, who carried Russia past the
United States at the 1992 Olympics and almost did the same at the
'98 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Zassoulskaia's agent confirmed that the 6-4 forward will be in
the draft, although the league will not release a draft list until
it can formally sign players.
</P>
<P>
   But the 3-27 Mystics were not accorded nine national television
appearances, one more than league runner-up Phoenix, based solely
on its WNBA-leading attendance (15,910 average) and market size.
NBC, ESPN and Lifetime expect Holdsclaw, a three-time NCAA champion
at Tennessee with marquee appeal, to be the Mystics' choice as
first reinforcement for Nikki McCray, who defected from the ABL
after being that league's Most Valuable Player in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Draft Chamique Holdsclaw,'' one reader told the ``Washington
Post'' last week. ``The Mystics already raised my season tickets by
25 percent. I might as well get something for my money.''
</P>
<P>
   At least in the first and second rounds, there will be plenty of
bang for the buck, especially since ABL players will be subject to
the rookie pay scale ($25,000 minimum, more for high draft picks)
for one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coaches are like kids in a candy store,'' said Maura
McHugh, who coached Long Beach to a near-upset of Columbus in the
1998 ABL Finals, then worked in ABL personnel after the league
folded the StingRays. The former Arizona State coach now is an
assistant with the WNBA Sacramento Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual to have this number of experienced players
available in the draft, especially in the third year of a league.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Monarchs, 8-22 last season without injured
all-league guard Ruthie Bolton-Holifield last season after going
10-18 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   If neither Griffith nor Williams is allocated to one of the two
expansion teams before the draft, Sacramento will take one,
probably Griffith, with the second pick. The Monarchs then can come
back in the second round with the 14th pick overall to take a
starting caliber wing player.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Mercury opens its season with back-to-back games
against Sacramento, it will not be the same opponent Phoenix has
whipped eight times without a loss. Instead, the Monarchs lineup
could feature WNBA assist leader Ticha Penicheiro dishing to the
6-4 Griffith, the 1998 ABL Most Valuable Player runner-up;
Bolton-Holifield, second in WNBA scoring in 1997; and another
former ABL All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 40 of the 132 WNBA players this season can be from the ABL
under terms agreed to between the league and the Women's National
Basketball Players Association. The 10 existing teams can have a
maximum of three each, while expansion Minnesota and Orlando can
include as many as five on their 11-woman rosters.
</P>
<P>
   Count on Minnesota using all of its ABL slots. Lynx
Coach-General Manager Brian Agler won consecutive ABL titles in
Columbus and, some think, will create Columbus North in Minneapolis
by reuniting the Quest perimeter of Katie Smith and Tonya Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   A persistent rumor is that both expansion teams asked for Quest
point guard Shannon Johnson as their second allocated player,
forcing a coin flip that was won by Orlando. So the Miracle
received the first choice in allocation, expected to be Johnson,
and Minnesota likely will get Smith, now running short sprints on
her way back from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson, Smith, Holdsclaw and Griffith are off the board when
Utah picks third overall, the Starzz are faced with a dilemma
similar to last year's. Go with need, clearly a point guard, or
with a can't-miss inside force in Williams, the 1998 ABL Most
Valuable Player who was a high schooler in Salt Lake City?
</P>
<P>
   Utah opted for 7-2 Margo Dydek with the 1998 first overall pick.
Though ``Large Marge'' led the league in blocks and was fourth in
rebounding, she couldn't lift the Starzz (8-22) from the Western
Conference cellar.
</P>
<P>
   With the muscle of 6-2 Williams, Utah Coach Frank Layden could
trade 1997 WNBA All-Star Wendy Palmer and still have an improved
front line that includes Dydek; 6-5 Elena Baranova, the 1998 World
Championships MVP; and 6-2 Olympia Scott-Richardson, getting back
into shape after the birth of a daughter on April 7.
</P>
<P>
   And with its second-round pick, 15th overall, Utah still could
get an ABL point guard to push Tammi Reiss, perhaps Niesa Johnson
or Andrea Nagy.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran point guards will at a premium if 34-year-old Teresa
Edwards and Jennifer Azzi, 30, do not sign with the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   The pair recently declined invitations to the U.S. National Team
camp that continues through Tuesday in Colorado Springs, a surprise
decision from Azzi, one of six core-group members through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Should Azzi and Edwards bypass the WNBA, teams such as Utah, if
it goes small, Charlotte (No. 9 pick) and two-time defending
champion Houston (No. 12), which must cover for cancer-stricken
starter Kim Perrot, would be scrambling for Dawn Staley, 28, or
Debbie Black, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles (No. 4) covets Staley, in no small part because of
her friendship with center Lisa Leslie. Tonya Edwards, although
more of a shooting guard, could also go in the first six picks if
there is a run on guards.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the first round _ Detroit (No. 5), New York (No.
6), Phoenix (No. 10) and Cleveland (No. 11) _ inside players such
as Clarisse Machanguana, DeLisha Milton, Adrienne Goodson, Shalonda
Enis and Taj McWilliams are likely candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury, deepest of all WNBA teams despite the loss of
Brandy Reed in the expansion draft, needs perimeter scoring and
post depth due to the pregnancy of Michelle Griffiths. After the
first round, Coach-General Manager Cheryl Miller might opt for
collegians, both to make her team younger and tap into a pool too
inexperienced for those with greater immediate needs.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Holdsclaw, the premier collegians will include shooting
guard Dominique Canty of Alabama, posts Tamika Whitmore of Memphis
and Angie Braziel of Texas Tech, small forward Amanda Wilson of
Louisiana Tech and point Ukari Figgs of Purdue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
