r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-KLEINE-AZR &LR;      04-27 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-KLEINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE MAY AVOID DISCIPLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Although Utah's Karl Malone has a long history of
taking opponents out with flying elbows, it isn't likely he'll be
disciplined for sending Phoenix center Joe Kleine to a plastic
surgeon Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kleine flew with the Suns to Minneapolis after the Suns beat the
Jazz Monday night, but he returned to the Valley Tuesday after
determining that he wouldn't be able to play either tonight against
the Timberwolves or Thursday night in Denver against the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' veteran backup center was not available for comment,
but an NBA spokesman said the league is not likely to take action
against Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like it,'' said Evan Silverman, manager of the
NBA's sports media relations division. ``I don't think any action
will be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   But Silverman said Rod Thorn, the NBA's senior vice
president-basketball operations, was attending to personal business
in West Virginia Tuesday. Thorn, who determines disciplinary
actions taken by the league, also could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, a muscular 6-foot-9, 260-pound forward, has a history of
injuring players and has been accused twice this season of
attempting to intentionally injure.
</P>
<P>
   Houston guard Brent Price accused Malone of attempting to injure
him.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also collided with Phoenix center Luc Longley while
attempting to draw a foul, crashed his leg into Longley's and
hyperextended Longley's left knee. After viewing a replay, Longley
later said Malone's action ``looked pretty bloody flagrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said after Monday night's incident that it wasn't
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I supposed to do, not shoot?'' he said. ``That's just
the way I go up. That's the way I play. I don't try to hurt
anybody. But that's the way I've played for 14 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley and Phoenix guard Jason Kidd each said that Kleine
described the play as a cheap shot before being taken to a
hospital. Longley said Kleine isn't easily upset, but he was fuming
over Malone's play.
</P>
<P>
   Kleine was injured late in the first quarter of the Suns' win at
Utah when Malone went up with the ball. He slammed his left elbow
and upper arm into Kleine's face, then scored with his right hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
