<HEADLINE>
HERBERT YOUNG, 112, WORLD WAR I VETERAN RECENTLY HONORED BY
FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Mass., Jamaica)   (bl)  
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Herbert Young, who was decorated by the French
government in February for his service in World War I, died April
22 at his home in Harlem. He would have turned 113 next week.
</P>
<P>
   Young, a retired mechanic, was considered the oldest New Yorker
by the city's Department for the Aging.
</P>
<P>
   He was awarded a medal, which made him a knight in the Order of
the Legion of Honor, on Feb. 22 by the French consul general in New
York, Richard Duque, in the French consulate general in Manhattan.
Young saluted while ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' was played and
later raised a glass of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   France began awarding the medal that Young received last year to
living veterans of World War I to mark the 80th anniversary of the
end of the war.
</P>
<P>
   In France, Young was in a Pioneer Infantry regiment that was one
of the black U.S. Army units that served under the French flag in
World War I in what has been called an expression of racial
segregation by the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in March , he said: ``I went in the Army in the
last part of 1917, enlisted because I was lonely. All the rest of
the boys had gone to the service. When I went to France, they put
us with the French army; the U.S. Army didn't want us because we
were colored.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians Arthur E. Barbeau and Florette Henri wrote in their
book, ``The Unknown Soldiers: Black American Troops in World War
I'' (1974, Da Capo), that for the black Pioneer Infantry regiments
sent to that war, the U.S. military ``does not seem to have
seriously contemplated combat service; the pared-down infantry
training they were given indicates rather that their true function
was work.''
</P>
<P>
   With age, Young's vision became imperfect and he acquired a
hearing aid. But his memories of World War I remained vivid. In an
interview after the medal ceremony, he said that during long-ago
battles in France, ``I was scared all right, and anyone who says
otherwise is fibbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw boys die right in front of me, some of my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   His 76-year-old son, Oscar, said that his father was resentful
after the war ended. ``After all he did, he came back home, and a
black man couldn't do nothing,'' Oscar Young recalled. ``So he's
real proud today, and so are we.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's granddaughter Martha Jones said: ``It's a big honor.
Something he's waited for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Young was born in Kingston, Jamaica, in 1886 and was brought to
the United States as a baby by his mother, and grew up in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Young was a corporal in 1918, when he served in a crucial Allied
counteroffensive in France that pushed the Germans back toward the
east. The Allied gain of terrain was precious, but also costly in
terms of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was about 350 men in our outfit,'' the 807th Pioneer
Infantry regiment, he said in the March interview, ``and I guess
about 12 came home, including me. God didn't want me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the 807th was not a combat unit, and ``we went to the
front and built bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   But Young said in the interview that ``a lot of our men died
fighting,'' although most of the deaths in his unit came from
disease. He said he himself wielded bayonets against the enemy, and
was made sick by German poison gas. After World War I ended in
1918, he had to stay in Europe for nine months, and his duties
included burying the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Then he returned to Massachusetts and worked as a civilian auto
mechanic. He first arrived in New York in the Depression and
managed to find work as a used-car mechanic for Pontiac. A
quarter-century ago he married his wife, Grace, when he was in his
late 80s and she was in her mid-20s. She survives.
</P>
<P>
   More information about survivors was not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters asked Young in March how he had managed to live
so long, he said modestly, ``I took care of myself and stayed out
of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   After he received his French medal, he said he would give it to
his great-great-great-granddaughter Jasmine Holmes, who is 11. She
promised she would hand it on to her descendants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
