<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-27 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB COUNT GROWS IN COLORADO, AND A WOMAN IS LINKED TO GUNS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ An 18-year-old woman who attended the prom
with Dylan Klebold three days before he and Eric Harris carried out
the assault at Columbine High School bought at least two of the
firearms used in the attack, the authorities said Tuesday as they
announced that 51 pipe bombs _ nearly twice as many as first
mentioned _ had been found in and around the school and at the
Harris home.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Robyn Anderson, who did not respond to requests for
comment, was interviewed by the police on Monday and released. She
bought two long guns at a local gun show she attended recently with
the two gunmen, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, her prom date, the
police said, and is being considered a witness, not a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson could face criminal charges if she knew how her
friends intended to use the weapons, officials said. ``If we feel
she has committed a criminal act,'' she will be returned to
custody, said Sgt. Jim Parr of the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department. ``As far as I know, she's still cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr and Steve Davis, a spokesman for the Sheriff's Department,
declined to say how many of the pipe bombs had been detonated or
which ones had been found in the school, the adjacent parking lot,
or at Harris' home.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sowell, a salesman at the Hugh M. Woods hardware store
here, said in an interview with KMGH, the local ABC affiliate, that
he had sold bomb-making materials, including propane tanks, screws
and nails, to Klebold and Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Sowell said they came in as many as a dozen times, wearing
trench coats and heavy boots, and once copied some keys. ``When I
asked them what are you using it for, they said, `school,''' Sowell
said. ``Maybe if I pushed it a little further, I would have learned
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of the additional bombs came on the one-week
anniversary of the rampage here, which left one teacher and 14
students _ including the two gunmen _ dead and a community in shock
and mourning. This middle-class suburb south of Denver, and indeed
much of Colorado, came to halt at 11:21 a.m. on Tuesday to mark the
moment the shooting began, with a blackout on local television and
radio stations as church bells tolled 15 times, one for each of the
slain. Two more students were buried on Tuesday in funerals that
drew thousands, part of an overflowing calendar of grief that will
continue through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the first hints of normalcy began to appear, as
teachers met to plan next week's return to classes for Columbine's
nearly 2,000 students, and the girls' soccer team played the first
interscholastic athletic event since the devastating attack on the
school.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though the parents of the two young men who
plotted the massacre for at least a year remained in seclusion, new
details began to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who kept a journal outlining plans for the attack and
appears to have been the mastermind, had hoped to join the Marines
but was rejected because of a medical reason just days before he
and his best friend stormed onto campus carrying guns and bombs,
officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a retired Air Force pilot, Harris was recruited as
part of a routine telephone canvass and did well at a preliminary
interview, but was rejected after a meeting at his home April 15,
when his ``parents divulged a medical factor,'' according to Lt.
Jeff Sammons, a spokesman for the Marine Corps Recruiting Command
in Quantico, Va. The Marines would not disclose the medical reason,
but the parent of a friend of Harris' said the young man had been
on psychiatric medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Eric's case, the system worked,'' Sammons said. ``We caught
someone who didn't qualify for the Marine Corps.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reliance on certain prescription drugs, reasons
for a medical disqualification include asthma, flat feet, and some
allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Good, whose son Nathan Dykeman was a friend of both
Harris and Klebold, said that Harris had been seeing a
psychiatrist. ``Eric did have a few problems, Eric was in
counseling,'' Good said in an interview on Tuesday. ``When we heard
about it we were like, so, so he's seeing a psychiatrist? So the
parents think he needs someone to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Good said that he has known Klebold and his parents for years,
and that no one could have predicted the attack. ``Now everyone
wants to point fingers, at the parents, at the schools _ the
Sheriff's Department should have known something, the school should
have known something,'' he said. ``The most horrifying thing of
this that people should be horrified and scared to death of, is
that these kids did not show any signs of this. It's terrifying. We
knew a different Dylan.''
</P>
<P>
   Good praised Susan and Thomas Klebold as excellent parents, and
criticized politicians and law-enforcement officials who have
questioned their responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was no broken family, this was no abusive family, no
anything,'' he said. ``These people spent time with their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Klebold considered his two sons his best friends, Good
said, noting that earlier this month he spent five days with Dylan
touring the University of Arizona, which the 17-year-old senior had
hoped to enroll in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked about the future and everything,'' he added.
``This guy knew his kid, and loved his kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three days before the attack, Dykeman attended the prom
with Klebold as part of a group of four couples who shared a
limousine, and saw Harris at the post-prom party. ``They all had a
great time,'' Good said. Though the parents of both shooters have
remained in seclusion, he said he had spoken to the Klebolds on
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're forgetting that family _ those two families are by
themselves,'' he said. ``Their life has been forever turned upside
down and it will never heal. They're looking for explanations,
they're looking through everything: Was that a sign, was that a
sign, did I miss something? They're second-guessing their entire
lives.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Agony was also on display at the funerals for Matthew Kechter, a
16-year-old sophomore on the football team, and Corey DePooter, 17,
a fly-fisherman who, like one of his killers, hoped to join the
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   DePooter was described as ``virtuous, selfless and heroic,'' and
said to have brought ``joy, happiness and occasional hilarity''
into those of the lives around him. The crowd sang, ``We Shall
Overcome,'' declaring, ``We are not afraid, we are not afraid, we
are not afraid today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the neatest guy,'' said Jenny Davis, who sat in front
of DePooter in language arts class. ``It hurts a lot that he's
gone, but I know he's always going to be here in spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kechter's funeral Mass, many of the mourners wore ribbons
with his football number, 70, on their lapels. A poster of John
Elway and several football jerseys were part of a floral shrine to
his memory in the church entranceway.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty burly boy-men stood as the Rev. Ken Leone urged the
Columbine High football squad to adopt Matthew's younger brother,
Adam, as their own. They recalled his smile, his sense of humor,
his hard work and his generous love for others. ``He had tremendous
pride in being a Columbine Rebel,'' Kechter's parents wrote in a
letter read at the service by his aunt and uncle. ``The best gift
you can give to Matt is finding the courage and the strength to
rebuild your school and your community.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the many funerals, school officials have decided to
restart classes on Monday rather than Thursday, as originally
planned. The students will attend their rival Chatfield High
School, which is three miles away, in an afternoon session, while
Chatfield students squeeze their day into five morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   With many of the students' backpacks and teachers' grade books
still inside Columbine, which is locked as a crime scene and said
to resemble a war zone, it is unclear how much academic work will
actually get done between now and graduation on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very sad, very tired, but they are very anxious to
get back with their students,'' Barbara Monseu, a school district
administrator, said of Columbine's 158 teachers. ``It's a very
important next step in the process of healing. They need to be back
together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Monseu said it would be up to teachers whether to have tests
and assign papers, or simply hold bonding sessions and try as best
as they can to factor the disruption into grades. ``I believe it
will be a very smooth transition,'' she said. ``It will be a very
special graduation for these students.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition had already begun on Tuesday afternoon, where
about 75 fans gathered to watch the girls' varsity soccer team beat
the Golden Demons, 3-0. There was a moment of silence before
kickoff and the flag remained at half-staff on the field, where
there was increased security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put all this into perspective and get back to
normal,'' said Jeanne Carrone, 17, a junior. ``It seems like the
longer we all spend thinking about it, the harder it will be to go
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Crawford, a 16-year-old junior, agreed. ``I'll be glad
when we can all go to games and dances,'' Crawford said, ``and not
be thinking about everything that's happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
