<SLUG> BC-TIMES-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORK TIMES BANS CIGARETTE ADS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joining a small group of newspapers, The New York
Times will ban cigarette advertising in its pages, effective
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper decided to impose the ban because of concerns
about the harmful effects of cigarette smoking, said Nancy Nielsen,
a spokeswoman for The New York Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deciding on the acceptance of advertising often means we have
to weigh the pros and cons of competing and sometimes conflicting
values,'' Ms. Nielsen said, adding that ``we don't want to expose
our readers to advertising that may be dangerous to their health.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year cigarette advertising amounted to less than 1 percent
of the newspaper's $1 billion in advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The last cigarette ad in the Times _ a full-page color
advertisement for Carlton cigarettes, made by the Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco unit of British American Tobacco PLC _ was
published on Monday in the Metro section of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy comes as the tobacco industry faces a prohibition
on cigarette billboard advertising this month, part of a $206
billion agreement the industry reached with 46 states to resolve
the states' claims for health costs. Some tobacco companies have
begun to look for other advertising alternatives, including
magazines and newspapers. They are already barred from television
and radio advertising.
</P>
<P>
   With the ban, the Times enters the anti-smoking side of a
long-running debate within American journalism. Most American
newspaper publishers contend that it is their duty to maintain a
free flow of information that requires they adopt as few
restrictions as possible on the advertising of legal products.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Smith, a spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson, said that The
Times' actions have symbolic, rather than practical, weight,
because it is a large national newspaper. More than a dozen other
American newspapers refuse cigarette advertising, among them The
Seattle Times, The Deseret News of Salt Lake City, and The
Christian Science Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder issued guidelines in 1995 to its chain of papers,
suggesting they avoid cigarette ads that use cartoon-like
characters or catchy slogans like ``alive with pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Times' new policy ``pathetic,'' Smith said, ``Isn't
it ironic that a publication that trumpets freedom of the press
would trample on the freedom of commercial expression?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new policy, the newspaper will still accept tobacco
company advertisements that do not promote smoking _ such as an ad
for a festival a company is sponsoring.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also does not accept advertising for a variety of
other legal products, like handguns, Mace or tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   The ban only applies to The New York Times, not any of the
company's other newspaper properties, which include The Boston
Globe. ``All of our newspaper properties have the autonomy to make
decisions about the advertising they accept,'' Ms. Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur O. Sulzberger Jr., publisher of the Times and chairman of
the company, said that he did not consider cigarette advertising a
free-speech issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment gives the press the right to publish what
it chooses to,'' he said. ``It doesn't force the press to publish
something, whether that's a news story or an advertisement. We
continue to support the right of other publications to run any
advertisement they feel is appropriate for their audience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
