<HEADLINE>
MAYOR DEFENDS ATTACK ON SCHOOLS BUT SAYS HE MEANT TO HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reacting to Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew's charges
that he was being ``reckless'' and ``destructive'' in attacking the
school system, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Tuesday that he was
trying to save the system, not destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, speaking to reporters at City Hall, said he did not
regret his remarks last week that the school system was
``dysfunctional'' and ``should be blown up.'' But he said that his
meaning had been misunderstood, that he was using a common
expression that had been used by Robert F. Wagner Jr., who was a
widely admired president of the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, in an uncharacteristically subdued mood, seemed to be
trying to tone down the war of words that has erupted in recent
weeks between him and Crew.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor did not give ground on the issues that have so
angered Crew: Giuliani's campaign to dismantle the Board of
Education, and to establish an experimental program of school
vouchers for 3,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am focused completely on how can we reform the school
system,'' Giuliani told reporters at City Hall. ``And so far, the
response of the chancellor and the school system has been a very
rigid defense of the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani defended his intentions a day after Crew issued a
passionate letter to 600 civic, educational and political leaders,
calling on them to fight the mayor's proposals and accusing
Giuliani of engaging in ``rhetoric of destruction'' that was an
insult to the school system and everyone in it.
</P>
<P>
   Crew declined to comment Tuesday on the mayor's remarks. But a
spokeswoman, Karen Crowe, said he hoped to talk to the mayor
privately and ``initiate a constructive dialogue about meaningful
change in the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
