A5653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT &LR;      04-27 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYDAY FOR VALHOL GIVES HIM DERBY SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Valhol, the Arkansas Derby winner whose jockey
may or may not have used an illegal electric device during the
race, will get to run in the Kentucky Derby after all, although not
with the same jockey.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, Ark., Monday, Pulaski County Circuit Judge John
Plegge ordered the Arkansas Racing Commission to pay Valhol's
owner, Jim Jackson, the $300,000 winner's purse from the Arkansas
Derby despite arguments by the commission that the Kentucky Derby
would be tainted if Valhol ran in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol will now have sufficient stakes earnings to qualify for
Saturday's Kentucky Derby, which is expected to have a full field
of 20 horses for its 125th running.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas racing officials had withheld the $300,000 from Jackson
while they investigated whether Valhol's jockey, Billy Patin,
applied an illegal electrical device to the horse to make it run
faster in the April 10 race at Oaklawn.
</P>
<P>
   Plegge admitted he knew nothing about horse racing, but said
that state racing officials were denying Jackson a chance at the
Kentucky Derby when there was ``absolutely no evidence'' that he
had done anything wrong in the Arkansas Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge said it pretty plain,'' said Valhol's trainer,
Dallas Keen, who remained here training the horse while Jackson was
in Arkansas. ``We've got the money and will enter the horse. We're
glad this is finally over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson could not be reached for comment, though one of his
lawyers, Jeff Kuebler, described him as ecstatic. With the money
from the Arkansas Derby, Valhol vaults from 22d to 12th on the
earnings list of probable starters. Because more than 20 horses
appear ready to enter the Kentucky Derby, stakes earnings becomes
the cutoff to determine who gets in and who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   As Wednesday's entry deadline approaches, the fate of Etbaur,
who is the 21st horse on the earnings list, is in the hands of Bob
Baffert, who is trying to win an unprecedented third consecutive
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert will enter two colts, General Challenge and Prime
Timber, who are the probable favorites in the race. But he said he
may also enter the filly Excellent Meeting. The filly is already
slated for the Kentucky Oaks on Friday as the likely second choice
in the race, but she might run against the colts instead, depending
on the post position draw.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if Excellent Meeting is entered in the Derby and
then scratched, it wouldn't help Etbaur or its owners, Kaaren and
Hays Biggs of Springdale, Ark. Once the field is drawn Wednesday,
Churchill Downs does not allow replacements for scratched horses.
</P>
<P>
   One definite is that Valhol's jockey, Patin, won't be riding in
the world's most famous race. He has a hearing before Arkansas
racing stewards on May 5 dealing with the buzzer allegations and
has returned to his native Louisiana to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Willie Martinez will ride Valhol, and Tuesday he was
aboard for a crisp 49-second workout over four furlongs. ``Our
horse worked real good today and he did it easy,'' Keen said.
``Willie was excited. I was excited. Jackson is excited. We're
ready for the race.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
