</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LUKAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKAS EMBRACES ELECTION INTO HALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ It was maybe 10 years too late by his own
reckoning, but the trainer D. Wayne Lukas was finally elected to
thoroughbred racing's Hall of Fame Tuesday _ as he was preparing
two horses for his 19th consecutive Kentucky Derby, three of which
he has won, and as he was approaching the historic pinnacle of $200
million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Ten gray years became the center of a dispute in recent years,
even while Lukas was yielding his role in the center of the Derby
spotlight to Bob Baffert. The Hall of Fame stipulates that a
trainer must be licensed for 25 years to qualify. Lukas insisted
that he was training both quarter horses and thoroughbreds in the
middle '60s, when he was also coaching basketball in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute became moot Wednesday at Churchill Downs, where
Lukas won the Kentucky Derby in 1988 with Winning Colors, in 1995
with Thunder Gulch and in 1996 with Grindstone, and where he will
shoot the works again on Saturday in the 125th Derby with Cat Thief
and Charismatic. So, were bygones at last bygones?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think bitter is kind of a harsh word,'' said Lukas, dressed
in his best winner's-circle style and, at 63, looking as fit as his
race horses. ``The Hall of Fame is bigger than any individual. I
had my reasons for being upset. But this is an honor. And I think
now that I'm in, I'd be less of a person if I didn't embrace it.''
</P>
<P>
   Length of service apart, Lukas has achieved more than any other
trainer in history: he has trained 19 national champions and won 13
Breeders' Cup races; both are records. He has led all trainers in
earnings in 14 of the last 17 years. He won six consecutive Triple
Crown races, starting in 1994 and ending in 1996. He has won the
Preakness four times and the Belmont three times. And he has won 7
percent of all graded stakes run in North America over the last 20
years, 513 entering this year.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974, when the Hall of Fame started counting, Lukas has
saddled 20,038 horses and won 3,725 times. When he finally appeared
on the ballot this year, for the first time, he was swept into the
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   At the induction ceremony in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., on Aug. 9,
Lukas will be joined by Russell Baze, the Northern California
jockey who led the nation's jockeys in victories five years in a
row, and by three star horses from the past: Exceller, Miesque and
Gun Bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hall of Fame is the Hall of Fame,'' Lukas said. ``Their
read was that I didn't train horses in the early 1960's. Yes, there
were some breaks when I was training both quarter horses and
thoroughbreds. But they date my work from 1974. So be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he basked in the glow of his work, which revolutionized the
sport. He trained horses on a national scale with stables at major
tracks run by deputies who became clones of the well-dressed,
well-spoken master back in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody got here by themselves,'' he said. ``I had some great
clients, and they gave me their horses and backed it up with their
bankrolls. There also were six of my guys, our alumni, out there on
their own now: Mark Hennig, Kieran McLaughlin, Dallas Stewart,
Bobby Barnett, Todd Pletcher and Randy Bradshaw. I'm proud of them.
Two of them are going to lead horses against me Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant Stewart, with Kimberlite Pipe, and Barnett, with Answer
Lively. But the trainer most feared by Lukas and everybody else is
Baffert, who won the last two runnings of the Derby, missed a third
by a nose and approaches this Derby with the two favorites, General
Challenge and Prime Timber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's on a ride,'' Lukas said of the trainer who now
overshadows him. ``He's enjoying the best, and so be it. It's
difficult to get here, and more difficult to sustain. We had a
great ride, too. We got on a run in the Triple Crown. But these
things run in cycles. Nobody gets here by themselves. You need the
clients. You need to give them a chance to get their money back.
Most of all, you need the horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was asked about the possibility that the already loaded
Baffert might also start the standout filly Excellent Meeting in
the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I wouldn't run Excellent Meeting in the Derby,'' Lukas
said. ``It's one thing to have a filly cruising in front of 19
colts. It's another to surround your filly with 19 colts for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never just went to the Derby with a filly; we tested them
against colts at Santa Anita. I like horses who've been tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not money. It's not some genius on a computer figuring
marriages made in heaven. It's the horse. You've got to have the
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
