<SLUG> BC-DEPUTY-BANKROBBER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida deputy arrested for bank robbery
 &HT;    By Lillian Weis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Palm Beach County sheriff's deputies
followed the license tag of a bank robbery suspect to a suburban
Lake Worth home Tuesday, and found a Broward County deputy already
there _ with red dye on his clothes and in his car.
</P>
<P>
   Broward Sheriff's deputy Ramon Notario, 40, was arrested on one
count of bank robbery and was being held at the Palm Beach County
Jail Tuesday night without bail.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said a man entered a NationsBank branch at about
12:30 p.m. He told tellers he had a gun. He demanded money.
</P>
<P>
   They handed him a bag of cash with a dye pack, timed to explode
onto the bills and the suspect. He drove away, but a witness wrote
down the tag of the man's beige Toyota, Palm Beach County Sheriff's
spokesman Paul Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County Sheriff's deputy Christine Kimball was waiting
in line at a nearby McDonald's drive-thru when the police radio
announced the robbery. She left the line, sped to the bank, then
radioed the tag to dispatchers.
</P>
<P>
   Other deputies spotted the car, stained inside. Notario was at
home with dye-stained clothes, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Notario, a road patrol deputy who covers southern Broward
County, was suspended Tuesday, Broward Sheriff's spokesman Kirk
Englehardt said. He will be paid only for the next three days, in
accordance with a union contract, Englehardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Notario, a Broward County deputy for 10 years, had been on paid
sick leave since September for medical reasons, Engelhardt said. He
would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Notario was injured in a diving accident several
months ago and has stayed at home since then.
</P>
<P>
   They described him as helpful and friendly, lending tools to
others, for example, and helping one neighbor with computer
problems. He was quiet, they said, spending much of his free time
with his wife and young son and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   About three years ago, Notario sold vacuum cleaners to others in
the neighborhood, neighbor Luis Ramos said. He told some neighbors
he wanted to leave police work, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that prompted anyone to think he would do
anything like that,'' he said. ``Especially someone like him who's
been in the police force. It's shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Weis writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
