<HEADER>
A5658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENT-VIDEO-GAMES-C     04-27 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENT-VIDEO-GAMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Violent games come under fire after Colorado shootings
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The shooting deaths of 14 students and a teacher
at a high school in Littleton, Colo., last week is fueling a
renewed focus on violence in video games after it was learned that
the two teen-agers responsible for the attack were avid players of
Doom and Duke Nuke 'Em, popular ultra-violent games.
</P>
<P>
   Game companies, including some of Austin's largest, are keeping
quiet in an effort to avoid fanning the controversy, although a
spokesman said the industry is being scapegoated in the search for
a rational explanation for a terrible event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Video games didn't teach these kids to be neo-Nazis. They
didn't teach them to make pipe bombs,'' said Doug Lowenstein,
president of the Interactive Digital Software Association.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Hertzler, chief executive of Blue Byte Software, a
local game company, said the industry has gone too far. ``I think
that the game industry is pushing it. It's almost like game makers
are trying to make a name for themselves by making content more
violent and twisted than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Hertzler, whose company creates fantasy and strategy games, said
the violence and gore in some games push the limits beyond even the
worst horror movies.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Origin Systems, Digital Anvil in Austin and
Acclaim Entertainment, parent of Iguana Entertainment here, said
they had received numerous phone calls in the wake of the Littleton
shootings but declined to comment. Some of the imagery and sound in
games like Doom, Requiem: Avenging Angel, Unreal and Quake II, a
genre of games called ``first-person shooters,'' rival the most
nightmarish work Hollywood special-effects artists can conjure. A
minimal story line often masks the true purpose of the game:
navigate dark gothic tunnels, sewers or airbases destroying nearly
everything that breathes in your path. Torsos are shredded by
bullets and plasma rifles. Limbs are shot out of their sockets.
Heads are blasted off like golf balls from tees.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate reward is often escape or a final battle with a
nearly unbeatable monster. The games are fast-paced and slick,
designed to quicken the player's pulse, horrify the senses with a
feeling of impending doom and throw the meanest and ugliest
monsters at the user. They make Mortal Kombat, which inspired
congressional hearings in 1993 and a voluntary industry rating
system, look like Ms. Pac Man.
</P>
<P>
   The game industry has soared to $5.5 billion on sales of 200
million games a year. Lowenstein said the outcry over the
first-person shooter games is disproportionate to the genre's place
in the market. He said such games account for only 8 percent of the
market, lagging behind racing games, flight simulators and strategy
games. The best-selling CD-ROM game of all time is Myst, a
relatively non-violent fantasy. However, few games of that type
have duplicated its success or that of the multiple incarnations of
Quake, Doom and Duke Nuke' Em.
</P>
<P>
   Origin Systems has tried to compete with shooters by offering
games in which virtues beyond brute strength are celebrated and
violence has an identifiable consequence. But when Origin launched
an elaborate interactive world called Ultima Online about two years
ago, the game was plagued for months by players who banded together
and killed others, disrupting the balance of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Colorado shootings, game makers were bracing for
another round of criticism: Two weeks ago, parents of three girls
killed in a 1997 Kentucky high school shooting filed a $130 million
lawsuit against several game companies and the producers of the
film ``The Basketball Diaries,'' which they say influenced Michael
Carneal to commit the murders. Acclaim is one of the defendants
named in the suit over games it publishes including Turok: Dinosaur
Hunter, another first-person shooter. Many players, however, see
the games as mindless escape and say they can separate the gruesome
fantasies from reality.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Jackson, a student at Our Lady's Family Center, an Austin
organization for at-risk youth, has been playing video games since
he was 7. Some of his favorites are Duke Nuke'Em and Doom, the same
games played by Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, the teens
responsible for the Colorado killings.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says he doesn't think video games contributed to the
Colorado attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play them all the time, and they don't do anything,'' the
17-year-old said. ``It's just an excuse to blame it on. People can
be influenced by a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years, U.S. Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-. Conn., has
released a yearly ``video game report card'' alerting parents to
violence in games. Few studies, however, have examined the
long-term effects of violence in games on children.
</P>
<P>
   That may change this fall, when University of Texas at Austin
researchers release their findings from a new study. UT's Center
for Research on the Influences of Television on Children conducted
a survey on the effects of 700 video games on 3,500 children in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Professor John Wright, director of the center, said that
although the study is not yet concluded, the group has found
parallels between video game violence and television violence,
which past studies have shown encourages aggression in kids. ``The
general findings with television is absolutely rock solid,'' he
said. ``The link between television and violence is as strong as
the link between smoking and cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright points out, however, that video games and television
violence alone are not enough to compel a child to violence. ``The
main cause undoubtedly is something more powerful than that. But
(video games and television) are natural amplifiers. Out on the
edge, there's a handful of people who are over the threshold and
ready to commit an act of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright favors parental control over censorship. But he worries
that Littleton won't be the last incident of its kind and that
video games play a part, however small, in the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bit in Mortal Kombat in which you beat up a woman,
are told to 'finish her' and then stick your hand through her chest
and pull out her heart. Then you are congratulated. That is just
about as formulaic a recipe for psychopathy than anything I've
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Becky Taylor, president of Terrace Mountain Systems, an Austin
software consulting company, said she keeps violent games away from
her 8-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   She lets him play games like Flight Simulator, which ``engages
your brain'' and teaches dexterity, but Star Wars is as close to a
shoot-em-ups as she permits.
</P>
<P>
   Working in software, Taylor said she's been disappointed that
other genres have not matured as rapidly as the popular, violent
games. ``I think attention needs to be paid to this blurring of the
line between reality and the computer generated realm. The energies
and fantasies reinforced by some of these games are not positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Taylor feels she's responsible for what's on her
son's screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buck stops with mom and dad,'' Taylor said. ``My son
doesn't even know what Doom is.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: ogallaga(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
