<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CAO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAO HUOXING, 75; WROTE PATRIOTIC CHINESE MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cao Huoxing, a Chinese farmer's son who wrote a Communist song
that has become familiar to hundreds of millions of Chinese, died
April 16 in Tianjin, in northern China, the official New China News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   He was 75 and had been chairman of the Tianjin Municipal Bureau
of Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Cao was born in Pingshan county in Hebei Province, in northern
China. He was a composer from the age of 16 and reportedly wrote
more than 1,500 songs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943 he wrote the song for which he is best known, ``Without
the Communist Party, There Would Be No New China.'' At that time,
during World War II, China was divided into areas controlled by the
Japanese invaders, the Nationalist government and Communist forces.
The Communists won a civil war with the Nationalists and took power
in all of mainland China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The words are somewhat less impassioned than the text of the
song by Tien Han and Nie Erh that was approved as the Communist
national anthem in 1949. The anthem, originally a call to arms
against the Japanese, includes the lines, ``For we throw ourselves
with courage on the enemy/Forward, forward, forward!''
</P>
<P>
   The words of the more solemn song that was adopted in 1929 as
Nationalist China's national anthem, based on words spoken by Sun
Yat-sen with music by Cheng Mao-yun, include, ``Be earnest and
brave, your country to save/One heart, one soul, one mind, one
goal!''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 Cao set off with 25 artists of the China Tianjin Song
and Dance Troupe to appear at music festivals in Britain and
elsewhere outside his homeland. The troupe's repertory included the
nonpolitical dance numbers ``Flower Drum Dance'' and ``Merry Golden
Fish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-TAXCUTS-COX     04-27 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-TAXCUTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Representatives square off on tax cuts
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Republican legislators backing a plan to
increase teacher pay and cut school property taxes are misleading
Texans when they say the proposal would cut taxes by $1 billion, a
key House Democrat said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul Sadler, who's overseeing similar proposals in the
House, said the GOP proposal scheduled for Senate debate today
would actually cut taxes by no more than $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money, Sadler said, might prevent future tax
increases, but won't cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it can _ by any definition _ be called $1
billion in tax cuts,'' Sadler, from Henderson, said of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The amount and nature of the tax cuts is key because Gov. George
W. Bush, who's expected to seek the GOP presidential nomination,
has been pushing for $2 billion in property tax cuts. He's likely
to tout his tax-cutting efforts in the presidential race should he
decide to run.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, a spokeswoman for the governor, said whether the
pending Senate bill cuts taxes by $1 billion or not is a matter
between Sadler and Sen. Teel Bivins, the bill's sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, she said, is that Bush wants to cut property
taxes and still backs his $2 billion proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins, R-Amarillo, is standing behind his bill, Senate Bill 4,
and its $1 billion in property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler late Monday outlined a plan to cut local school property
taxes by about $500 million, giving more money to schools and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said he's unlikely to support any plan with less than $1
billion in property tax cuts, in part because fellow Senate
Republicans wouldn't back it.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's optimistic about a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But the differences between the proposals could have
far-reaching implications, said Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount
Pleasant. He raised the possibility that the issue won't be decided
before the end of the session May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of issue that has all the ingredients of
special session,'' he said. ``Already Bivins feels they have
compromised as far as they can go. (Sadler's) plan would imply
having to compromise more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said his plan is only an idea and the numbers in it could
change. But he believes senators are amenable to a plan that has
less than $1 billion in property tax cuts because that is what is
in Senate Bill 4.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said many of the so-called tax cut measures in Bivins'
bill might prevent local school property taxes from going up, but
wouldn't lower taxes. He added that those measures can be called
tax prevention or tax relief, but not tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins originally filed a plan to cut local school property
taxes by about $1.35 billion and to increase teachers' take-home
pay by $1 billion through an increase in the state's share of
teachers' retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That plan couldn't muster the support needed to get to full
Senate debate and Bivins agreed to the pending proposal. He says it
puts $1.7 billion in additional money toward teachers' compensation
and $1 billion toward local school property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said only a portion of the tax cut plan actually cuts
existing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the property tax portions of Senate Bill 4 would
work:
</P>
<P>
   $600 million would help schools pay debt related to existing
school buildings. Sadler says that counts as true tax cuts because
districts with high tax rates would have to lower them by an amount
equal to the new state dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Districts that have relatively lower tax rates also would have
to reduce their rates, though not by a dollar-for-dollar amount,
Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   $150 million would help schools with new building debt. Sadler
said lawmakers in 1997 put $200 million toward new building debt,
but didn't call it tax cuts. Bush this year proposed another $200
million for the program and listed it as new education spending,
not tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   $125 million, contained in the proposed state budget, would
prevent schools from losing local tax dollars because of declining
property values. That is related to the drop in oil and gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   $100 million would keep schools from losing money because of a
higher homestead tax exemption enacted in 1997. Sadler said
lawmakers approved similar spending in 1997 and didn't call it tax
cuts. He also said the program prevents tax increases but doesn't
cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   $50 million would go to help schools that are growing more
quickly that others. Sadler said that helps districts avoid raising
taxes but doesn't cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler applauded the ``old debt'' portion of the bill because
it's likely to help hundreds of districts.
</P>
<P>
   He warned, however, that the rest of the ``tax cut'' measures
don't cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a right to his opinion,'' Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
