<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, MAYOR LOSES HIS GRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will not be doing any
gladhanding for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, it seems, injured his hand while _ what else? _
shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday that a man with a too-firm grip had aggravated a
two-week-old injury he had been trying to ignore. ``I injured it
walking out of the bathroom,'' the mayor said Tuesday. ``I didn't
do anything about it, and I kept shaking hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As any elected official would.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened is, on Sunday, at Yankee Stadium, while I was at
the Joe DiMaggio memorial, I shook about 100 hands, and it started
swelling up,'' the mayor said. ``One particular man actually did
this to me,'' the mayor said. ``I don't know who he is.'' But he
knew the man's too-firm handshake the moment he felt it. ``He
grabbed my hand in exactly the place it had been injured and I
virtually made a slight little moan and almost fainted.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had a doctor examine his hand on Monday. The
diagnosis, as relayed by the mayor: ``Something happened to the
ligament.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor's advice was to forgo heavy handshaking for a while.
Giuliani, a former prosecutor, had his own lawyerly strategy for
what to do until he gets his grip strength back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thinking of putting in a workman's compensation claim
because part of my job description is that I have to shake hands,''
the mayor said. He added, ``I can't say that I was injured in the
act of shaking hands, but my injury was substantially made much
worse by shaking hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Glamour Amid the Stacks
</P>
<P>
   It has been 75 years since the Morgan Library first opened its
very heavy doors to the public. On Monday the Morgan celebrated its
anniversary by handing out magenta feather boas and gardenia
boutonnieres and escorting its newly accessorized A-list guests in
for drinks (martinis, Manhattans, cosmopolitans and Champagne) and
hors d'oeuvres (oysters, tiny savory pastries and caviar).
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women shed the boas along the way, but not Marian
Frelinghuysen, a longtime donor to the Morgan. She said she was
keeping hers to give to her granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   At the dinner that followed, one table became the
everybody-loves-Brooke table, as in Brooke Astor, the nonagenarian
philanthropist. Charles Pierce, the director of the Morgan, said,
``Brooke was extraordinarily kind to Barbara and me when we first
moved to New York.'' Frederick A. Melhado, sitting next to Mrs.
Astor, observed, ``It's still Edith Wharton's town. Nothing has
changed. Everybody still knows everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer stopped by (on his fourth engagement of the
evening) and chatted with Mrs. Astor for a few minutes. Then, after
he made a short speech about the Morgan (``This library has been a
jewel for all of New York''), the music started. Several couples
demonstrated the Charleston. Mrs. Astor and Melhado danced a few
turns of a somewhat slower step, and left.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the Curtin
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly the most formidable dressing room I've ever
been in,'' the playwright and performer David Hare said.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, it was his own dressing room after the Monday
evening performance of his one-man show, ``Via Dolorosa,'' at the
Booth Theater on West 45th Street. Two women who figured in his
performance, Leah Rabin and Judi Dench, had been in the audience
and had gone backstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Via Dolorosa'' touches on the assassination of Mrs. Rabin's
husband, Yitzhak Rabin, who was the Prime Minister of Israel. ``The
audience did not know she was there,'' Hare said, ``but the most
extraordinary respectful silence fell over the house. I think they
sensed my own feeling about what an extraordinarily moving moment
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Miss Dench, Hare usually mentions her in the opening
minutes of the show. The line usually gets a laugh. On Monday, it
drew applause. That tipped off Hare, who had not known that she
would be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been saying to me for some time now that I must write a
play in which we can act,'' he said. After seeing ``Via Dolorosa,''
though, she seemed to have cooled on that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Mmm, I don't think I want to be in a play with you.
You don't act. There's not a single choice you make in the course
of an evening that any professional actor would make. It's moving,
but I don't feel that what I do and what you do have any
professional kinship.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
