<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S REDSHIRTS BLOOM IN SPRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The safeties are struggling, no quarterback has
emerged, and two players have retired. But it hasn't been a lost
spring for UCLA, not at all, because several redshirt freshmen from
the heralded class of '98 have impressed coach Bob Toledo:
</P>
<P>
   _Defensive end Rusty Williams. Playing for the suspended Santi
Hall, Williams has continued the highly charged play that made him
scout-team defensive player of the year in '98. His energy is
limitless _ the coaches say he has ``a great motor'' _ and it's
contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been real impressed with Rusty,'' cornerback Marques
Anderson said. ``He brings a lot of positive energy.''
</P>
<P>
   _Offensive tackle Blake Worley and guard Mike Saffer. Worley was
handed Kris Farris' former spot because of attrition and injuries,
and he's made the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the season started today, he'd be the starting left
tackle,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Saffer is merely UCLA's most gifted lineman since Jonathan
Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   _Defensive tackle Steve Morgan, who has made a smooth conversion
from guard. At 295 pounds, he gives the Bruins four massive
defensive tackles _ more than they've had, combined, in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _Cornerback Joe Hunter, who has recovered from a tentative start
to challenge for a spot in the rotation. He has good speed and hits
harder than his 170-pound frame would indicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times early in the the spring when he was a little
unsure and played softer than we'd like,'' defensive coordinator
Bob Field said. ``But as he builds confidence, you can see he'll be
a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   _Defensive tackle Sean Phillips. He redshirted last season while
classmates Anthony Fletcher and Ken Kocher played as true freshmen.
But the discrepancy in development had nothing to do with ability
and everything to do with age: Phillips did not turn 18 until
January, making him UCLA's youngest player by four months.
</P>
<P>
   Stronger and more mature emotionally, Phillips has shown the
form _ albeit inconsistently _ that made him a Parade All-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made (begin ital)a lot(end ital) of progress,'' Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees: Ramogi Huma, a junior linebacker, was forced to quit
because of lingering hip problems. Mark Verti, a junior fullback,
has a herniated disc in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Both departures leave the Bruins thin at those positions. Huma
is the second linebacker to quit since last season, following
oft-injured Mike Wiley. Without Verti, the Bruins are searching for
a reserve fullback behind starter Durell Price.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Stanley and Adam Geitner are the only candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both have made a lot of progress,'' Toledo said. ``They're
good blockers and they can catch the ball, and they're good on
special teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
