<HEADER>
A5672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES-CO     04-27 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    26,990 see Braves blow lead in 8th
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most dependable component of the Atlanta bullpen
shifted Tuesday night. Rudy Seanez coughed one up.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Pirates stopped a four-game losing streak at
Seanez's expense, scoring three times in the eighth inning for a
5-3 victory in an unceremonious opener to a nine-game homestand.
The Braves lost for just the third time in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by a run, Pirates tied it 3-3 in the eighth when Mike
Benjamin drew the night's first walk off starter Odalis Perez to
lead off the inning. Benjamin stole second and subsequently scored
on pinch-hitter Keith Osik's single up the middle. Perez was pulled
two outs later with men on first and second, having allowed seven
hits with two walks (both in the eighth) and five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez threw just one pitch, which Kevin Young singled to left
to bring in Pat Meares for a 4-3 lead. Jason Kendall, staggering
through an 0-for-15 slump, drove Seanez's third pitch into left to
score Brian Giles for a two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   The game was played before 26,990, the smallest crowd in Turner
Field's three-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Schmidt, who had beaten the Braves only once in five
starts since Atlanta sent him to Pittsburgh in the Denny Neagle
trade, pitched well early. He limited the Braves to two hits (both
by Brian Jordan) through the first five innings, no little feat
against a club that just hit .305 on its recent extended road trip.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves got to him in the sixth with three straight
singles. The second, which broke an 0-for-10 streak by Bret Boone,
moved Otis Nixon to third, where Chipper Jones drove him in for a
2-1 lead with a chopper up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates might have avoided further damage when Javy Lopez
hit a potential inning-ending double play ball to third baseman Ed
Sprague. But he threw the ball into right field for his sixth
error, allowing Boone to score a a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan got the Braves started by continuing with his torrid
start. He doubled in the second inning and tripled in the fourth,
giving him 14 extra-base hits in his first 19 games as a Brave.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
