<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990427.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATECRIME-COX     04-27 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATECRIME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas lawmakers approve controversial hate crimes billBy Scott
S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After an emotional debate that held lawmakers
spellbound, the Texas House on Tuesday for the first time approved
a hate crimes bill that specifically mentions the groups it is
designed to protect.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of the bill, spurred in part by last June's grisly
slaying of James Byrd Jr., would stiffen penalties for crimes
motivated by bias against a person's race, religion or national
origin. It also would cover crimes based on ``sexual preference,''
which may signal a sea change in a House that in the past has
balked at protecting homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of that category may create a sticky situation for
Gov. George W. Bush: Signing the bill almost surely would open him
up to attacks from the right as he seeks a middle road to the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The House, which gave tentative approve to the bill Tuesday, is
expected to give final approval today. It is pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked out on the House floor in 1991 with people moving
their desks because they wouldn't sit next to me, and people saying
they didn't want to have their pictures taken with me in the
picture,'' said Austin Rep. Glen Maxey, the only openly gay member
of the Legislature. ``It's amazing to me, the demeanor of this
Legislature _ it says very good things about Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, filed House Bill 938 in
memory of Byrd, the black man from Jasper, Texas who was dragged to
his death behind a pickup truck manned by two white supremacists.
The bill would stiffen penalties and allow civil damages for crimes
motivated by prejudice. It also would require the attorney general
to assist counties in prosecuting such crimes, provide grants to
help them pay for such cases, and require specialized training of
peace officers in the investigation and documentation of such
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Verrett, a nephew of the slain man who watched Tuesday's
debate from the House gallery, said he is convinced the legislation
will make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I'm very proud to be a Texan,'' Verrett said. `` I'm
very proud to be here in person to see this outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 83-61 vote, Thompson said Byrd's slaying ``had the
greatest impact on the passage of this legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has said he is undecided whether to support a hate
crimes measure but opposes special rights based on sexual
orientation, appeared no closer to a decision on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I supported hate crimes legislation last session,'' Bush said
in Dallas. ``I just want to see how the bill goes. It's early in
the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-two percent of Texans support harsher penalties for
crimes motivated by hate, according to a recent Texas Poll, and 76
percent of them believe homosexuals should be covered by a hate
crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's vote was a first for the House. In 1993, the Texas
Senate passed hate crimes legislation covering race, color,
disability, religion, national origin, ancestry and sexual
orientation. But House members refused to sign off on the sexual
orientation protection. Rather than exclude that group, supporters
eliminated all mention of categories and instead pushed through a
bill covering ``crimes motivated by bias or prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   The House in 1995 killed a bill similar to the one approved
Tuesday, and the 1993 law is still on the books.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, who is carrying
Thompson's bill in the Senate this time around, said Tuesday's
House action should give it a boost. Senate supporters are still
scrambling for the votes to bring that legislation to the Senate
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Usually when the House debates a bill, dozens of members are
talking on their desk phones, milling in the aisles or lounging
around the edges of the chamber. Not this time: members were rooted
silently to their seats for the duration of the debate, which
lasted longer than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   For many supporters, the debate was personal. Rep. Steve Wolens,
D-Dallas, talked about the insults he endured as a Jewish kid
growing up in the 1950's in tiny Corsicana, Texas. Rep. Pete
Gallego, D-Alpine, recalled a boyhood lesson on the term
``greaser,'' a pejorative term for Hispanics. And Rep. Harold
Dutton, D-Houston, said his son recently told him about a racial
slur directed at him at school.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul Moreno, D-El Paso, suggested that some lawmakers
opposed the bill because they had never encountered prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have never experienced discrimination _ never. In this
beautiful city of Austin, Texas, when I was in my third year in UT
law school, I was denied a home simply because I was a Mexican.
Don't tell me that doesn't hurt,'' Moreno said. ``Discrimination is
very very difficult to understand unless you have experienced it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Suzanna Hupp, who opposed the bill, also had a personal
tale to tell. Hupp, whose parents were among the 22 people killed
in a 1991 massacre in a Killeen Luby's, said she was offended by
the idea that a court could weigh the deaths of the individual
victims differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time believing that any person's life in that
restaurant that day was worth more than anyone else's,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Wayne Christian, R-Center, who represents Jasper, said
differentiating between groups was the root of the tragedy there.
Christian, referring to the subsequent removal of the fence
dividing the black and white graves in the town's cemetery, said
lawmakers were ``erecting fences'' by singling out specific groups
for protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not within the power of us in the Legislature to stop
hate,'' Christian said. ``Only God can change the heart of man _
not legislation.'' Rep. Joe Nixon, R-Houston said lawmakers
``cannot mandate nor prosecute thoughts or feelings.'' Nixon argued
that it is illogical to separate crimes motivated by hate from
those spurred by greed, jealousy, ignorance or lust. He also
contended that the legislation infringes on free speech and
violates the U.S. Constitution's equal protection clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill creates and provides disproportionate protection to
special classes of victims and inequitable punishments for a
special class of offenders,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dutton noted that the Civil Rights Act of 1964 also singles
out certain groups for protection. And Wolens insisted that the
bill ``will protect the speech of hate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill does not deal with the deed of the word or
propaganda, but with the deed of the act,'' Wolens said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and other supporters of the bill pointed out that the
Legislature has already passed laws that distinguish between the
victims of the same crimes, increasing penalties for the murders of
public servants, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The House cleared its traditional sexual orientation hurdle
surprisingly easily. Rep. Warren Chisum, R-Pampa, added an
amendment substituting the term ``sexual preference'' for ``sexual
orientation,'' saying the change made it clear that heterosexuals
as well as homosexuals would be covered. Supporters of the bill,
who were hard-pressed to define the difference between the two
terms, didn't object.
</P>
<P>
   There was little opposition when Rep. Charlie Howard, who
opposed the bill, amended it to add ``status as a pregnant woman,''
and gender to the list of categories covered under the bill. But
when the Sugar Land Republican, citing the recent Littleton school
shootings, attempted to add ``status as a student athlete'' to the
list, supporters pounced on him for trying to make a mockery of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
