<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO HITS MILOSEVIC'S HEADQUARTERS AGAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
and GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO struck again Tuesday at the headquarters of
Slobodan Milosevic's Socialist Party as alliance leaders suggested
that diplomatic overtures by Russia would not change the peace
terms for the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to insist on the conditions that NATO has set
out,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen said. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott met with a special Russian envoy, but no
concrete results were reported.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO continued to revisit targets hit earlier in the
monthlong bombardment against Milosevic's forces, an errant strike
apparently hit a residential area in southern Serbia, killing at
least 17 civilians and destroying up to 50 homes.
</P>
<P>
   As earlier requested by the Pentagon, President Clinton
authorized the call-up of 33,102 reservists.
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday is expected to defeat a call to declare
war against Yugoslavia but could pass a measure demanding that
Clinton seek authorization if he decides to commit ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders readied a $13 billion spending
bill to finance the Balkan fighting, more than twice the amount
Clinton sought.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the reserves called up were from Air Force units that
can help ready U.S. warplanes for pounding Serb targets. None was
from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The three U.S. soldiers held captive in Yugoslavia were examined
Tuesday by a doctor from the International Committee of the Red
Cross and were allowed to send out messages that Red Cross
spokesman Chris Bowers said would be delivered ``straight to their
families.''
</P>
<P>
   The captives are Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville;
Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; and Staff Sgt.
Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers said a Red Cross representative met with the men in
private, as called for in the Geneva Conventions on treatment of
war prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights activist Jesse Jackson said he would visit Belgrade
to seek the servicemen's release, despite signs from the Clinton
administration that his intervention was not welcomed and could be
dangerous. The White House refused to guarantee Jackson safe
passage.
</P>
<P>
   In military action in Yugoslavia, NATO hit for at least the
second time the 23-story Usce Center building in Belgrade, which
houses offices of Milosevic's Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   When the building was struck last week, NATO called it the
``nerve center'' of Milosevic's autocratic regime. It is also the
site of a television transmitter, which apparently was struck in
the latest attack.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman acknowledged that a Yugoslav army barracks in
the southern Serbian city of Surdulica, 200 miles south of
Belgrade, also was targeted Tuesday. But said he had no information
on whether any of the bombs went astray.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported up to 600 houses were damaged
there by a missile attack that missed the barracks, and several
children were among at least 17 dead, the worst civilian toll since
the NATO mission began.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather continued to hamper NATO air attacks, but allied
military spokesmen said attrition is taking a toll on Milosevic's
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these attacks are cumulatively starting to add up,'' U.S.
Air Force Major Gen. Charles Wald said. ``His forces are starting
to take a pretty good hit, in the field particularly. But you add
that up to the fact that he can't sustain the force, he has no
ammunition, his command and control is going down.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's top military commander, said
Milosevic faced ``increasing numbers of desertions and declining
morale among the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook said in London that ``desertion is now running at several
hundreds per week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The response of the (Yugoslav) reserves to mobilization has
been so poor that the special police are now going from door to
door,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark said at the daily NATO briefing in Brussels, Belgium,
that Serb reinforcements are arriving in Kosovo regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The allies also put a squeeze on Milosevic's personal finances.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said the European Union had
decided unanimously to freeze any personal bank accounts in its
territory belonging to Milosevic ``and his cronies.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Talbott reported no breakthroughs and said talks with
Russian leaders would continue. He spoke in person or by phone with
Viktor Chernomyrdin, the former prime minister who is President
Boris Yeltsin's special envoy for the Balkan fighting, Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Foreign Minister Ivan Ivanov.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton's call-up order was his first formal activation notice
since February 1998, when he summoned forces because of
developments in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The extra forces were needed, the Pentagon said, because of the
recent addition of U.S. refueling aircraft to NATO's Balkan
contingent.
</P>
<P>
   The reservists will be in place, either in the United States or
Europe, for when better weather arrives as expected in the summer.
They will join about 1,000 reservists who have volunteered since
the Balkan campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said the first units affected by the call-up are in
Alabama, Arizona, California, Indiana, Kansas, Michigan,
Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said Clinton ``fully recognizes this
disrupts lives, but this is what reservists train for. This is what
their mission is. From time to time, they are called.''
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Republican appropriations chiefs prepared to
offer bills that would more than double Clinton's emergency request
of $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact on military readiness of the pace of operations in
and around Kosovo is significant, and those funds must be
replenished,'' said Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska, arguing for the $13 billion figure.
</P>
<P>
   White House budget chief Jacob Lew argued that Clinton's $6
billion proposal ``does protect military readiness in the Balkans
and around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
