</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TO PAY $2.75 MILLION TO A MAN WHO SAID POLICE BEAT HIM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giuliani administration has agreed to pay $2.75
million to a man who said he had been beaten on his way to work by
at least five police officers because he fit the profile of a black
suspect they were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The city agreed to the unusually large settlement with Harold
Dusenbury, 42, of Willingboro, N.J., even though prosecutors said
at the time that the officers had committed no wrongdoing in the
1996 case and the Police Department concluded that the officers had
done nothing to warrant being disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   City lawyers denied Tuesday that the settlement had anything to
do with the politicized environment in New York City since the
police shooting of a West African immigrant, Amadou Diallo, in
February.
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer for Dusenbury disputed that view, saying the Diallo
case was ``one of the things that drove the settlement,'' along
with the compelling facts of Dusenbury's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to go to trial, with this case in this
atmosphere,'' said the lawyer, Jonathan C. Moore, ``particularly
with Harold Dusenbury, who is the most shining example of somebody
who was just trying to do the right thing all his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusenbury, an electrician, commuted each morning from his home
in Willingboro, about 20 miles south of Trenton, to a construction
site in Greenwich Village, where a Kmart store was being built. On
his 40th birthday, July 25, 1996, Dusenbury arrived in the city
about 6:45 a.m. and was walking on Eighth Street, wearing a T-shirt
and dungarees and carrying a plastic bag containing his work
clothes and his tools.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the police were broadcasting a description of
a fleeing suspect, a ``black male in T-shirt and jeans,'' who had
brandished a knife in Washington Square Park. A police car that was
cruising along Eighth Street jumped the curb and forced Dusenbury
to stop, the lawsuit said. One officer leaped toward him and
slammed his forehead against a metal security gate, then tried to
handcuff him, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, the suit asserted, at least four other officers
arrived and crowded around Dusenbury, striking him and kicking his
head and calling him a drug dealer and using racial slurs, the
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit Dusenbury filed against the city claimed that he had
suffered permanent physical harm, including brain injuries, and had
been unable to resume work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a racist issue first,'' Dusenbury said in a
telephone interview Tuesday. ``Otherwise, there would have been
some degree of respect, as indicated on their automobiles _
respect, professionalism, courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael L. Spiegel, another lawyer for Dusenbury, said the
evidence pointed to ``profiling carried to its most dangerous
extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When this officer assaulted Harold,'' he said, ``the only
possible explanation was that he was in a state of such racist rage
that he selected the only black man that he saw on the street to
assault.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a police spokeswoman, said Tuesday night that all
of the officers had been cleared of misconduct by the Police
Department and the Manhattan district attorney's office. She added:
``Nobody would argue that this wasn't a tragic mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office closed its investigation after
concluding that the police had made a mistake _ ``a regrettable
one,'' as a senior prosecutor, Daniel J. Castleman, said at the
time, ``and they acknowledged that from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached Tuesday, Castleman, the chief of investigations for the
district attorney, said that based on the evidence his office had
seen, the civil settlement ``seemed to be the appropriate venue for
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter A. Lerner, an assistant corporation counsel for the city,
said the city would admit no wrongdoing by the police. He said that
if the suit had gone to trial, the city would have shown that
Dusenbury resisted orders by the police, and that the seriousness
and permanence of his injuries was ``a cloudy issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
