<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5806 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-CX     04-27 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-CX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT GOES FOR HISTORIC WIN
</HEADLINE>
 CX-BAFFERT IS 46-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Bob Baffert says he doesn't think about
history. He's a jokester, a 46-year-old party boy, living from one
turf-club champagne toast to the next. Or so the world's hottest
thoroughbred trainer would like you to think.
</P>
<P>
   But whether he thought about it or not, Baffert took a major
step Tuesday, the penultimate step of the long winter and spring,
toward Kentucky Derby history.
</P>
<P>
   Between rain showers at Churchill Downs, the two Derby favorites
splashed through their final serious tuneups for Saturday's race,
in which they'll try to make Baffert the first person to win the
classic horse race three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge and Prime Timber didn't record the fastest
workouts of the morning, but they danced off the soupy track
afterwards in apparent health and fitness. If Baffert had been the
least bit nervous behind his Hollywood sunglasses, he could heave a
sigh of relief after watching that from the grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over. Now we can start partying down and
enjoying the festivities,'' he said after driving to his
backstretch barn. ``From here on it's just a matter of keeping 'em
happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in position to win another one,'' declared Baffert, who
won the past two Derbies with Silver Charm and Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Baffert's work is not quite done. He must finally
decide in the next two days whether to run one of his two star
fillies in the Derby or keep both with their own sex in Friday's
Kentucky Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said Silverbulletday, the champion 2-year-old filly of
'98, will settle for the Oaks, though her owner Mike Pegram pointed
out that ``he's been known to change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram _ who has already won a Derby with Real Quiet _ said he's
leaving the choice on Silverbulletday to Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe,'' Pegram admitted, ``I might have the
favorite in the Kentucky Derby and not run her.''
</P>
<P>
   The other filly, Excellent Meeting, has worked out so well here
that it's hard for Baffert to say no to the Derby for her. But
owners John and Betty Mabee have said they're ``90 percent''
against subjecting her to that strain. Baffert expected to discuss
it with the San Diego couple again after they arrived in Louisville
later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The best guess is that they'll put up an extra $30,000 to enter
Excellent Meeting in the Derby as well as the Oaks, but scratch her
from the Derby unless something unforeseen knocks out the Mabees'
General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the decision is fraught with potential regret.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when it comes to double-edged decisions, Baffert has
been juggling knives since the start of '99, when he counted an
unwieldy roster of six Triple Crown candidates in his Santa Anita
barn.
</P>
<P>
   After his success with Silver Charm and Real Quiet _ which
followed Cavonnier's unlucky second in '96 _ Baffert is the trainer
of choice for rich owners with Derby dreams. This year so many
signed on that it was as if the Derby became his to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert never believed that. Having also experienced hard
losses, like Cavonnier's Derby and like Silver Charm's and Real
Quiet's Belmont Stakes, he knew that all he could do was prepare
the horses for the race. The rest would be up to the horses. And
luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't really think about winning it,'' he said. ``You
think about getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   There were moments along the way when he appeared to feel the
pressure. Like when he shoved Chris McCarron's agent in an argument
over Baffert's abrupt switch to Gary Stevens as the rider for
General Challenge before the gelding won the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I snapped,'' Baffert told a Daily Racing Form interviewer
recently.
</P>
<P>
   So, since arriving in Kentucky a couple of weeks ago, Baffert
has returned to his quipster roots, joking to deflect the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the barn Tuesday, he walked briskly past a
crowd of reporters, then did a stagy double take and said, ``There
something goin' on here?''
</P>
<P>
   Only this: Baffert trying to do what four other trainers, four
jockeys, four owners and six breeders have failed to do in 124
years, which is to turn back-to-back Derby victories into
threepeats.
</P>
<P>
   Friends here say he's (begin ital)very(end ital) confident of
his chances to make history Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He'd prefer they didn't put it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think about history. I didn't think I'd get this
far,'' said Baffert, who grew up with horses in Arizona, learned to
train with quarterhorses at Los Alamitos Race Course in Orange
County, and started with one thoroughbred 10 years ago. ``I haven't
thought about the future. I don't set goals. You've got to keep the
excitement down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's going to be hard to do. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
