<HEADER>
A5817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS     04-27 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE'S HIGH COURT REJECTS BID TO USE SCHOOL VOUCHERS FOR RELIGIOUS
SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Fla., Ohio, Vt.)  (With FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS) 
 (nk) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Maine Supreme Court has denied a constitutional
appeal by five families who wanted to use taxpayer money to send
their children to church-affiliated schools. In a 5-1 decision, the
court upheld the state's policy of restricting publicly financed
vouchers to nonreligious schools.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, the most recent from a flurry of school choice
cases across the nation, could bring the issue a step closer to the
Supreme Court. The ruling comes almost a year after the Wisconsin
Supreme Court came to a different decision on the voucher issue,
ruling that a Milwaukee program can allow parents to use vouchers
to pay tuition at church-affiliated schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This now creates a split in authority among state supreme
courts on the constitutionality of school choice that makes it much
more likely that the United States Supreme Court will take a case
and resolve the issue,'' said Clint Bolick, litigation director for
the Institute of Justice, a libertarian public policy law firm that
represented the Maine parents.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, parents who live in towns without public schools can
use publicly financed vouchers to attend private schools that are
not church affiliated. Five families from rural Raymond, Me., which
has no high school, sued their school district for the right to use
vouchers to send their children to a private, all-male Catholic
school in Portland. They maintained that the program violated their
freedom of religion and other rights. An appeals court denied the
request, and the state Supreme Court upheld the decision on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choice alone,'' the decision said, ``cannot overcome the fact
that the tuition program would directly pay religious schools for
programs that include and advance religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the principle of the separation of church and
state, the decision continued, ``None of the Supreme Court's
decisions to date have ever intimated that such direct subsidies of
religious schools could survive an Establishment Clause
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Both opponents and supporters of vouchers are hoping this case _
or one of the others in litigation in Vermont or Ohio _ will reach
the highest court and lead to the creation of a national standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the case,'' said the Rev. Barry Lynn, executive
director of Americans United for Separation of Church and State,
``more than any other that makes it crystal clear that vouchers aid
religious schools and that violated the Constitution. It says it
directly and without any fudging or equivocation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bolick called this court's interpretation of constitutional
law ``an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 14,000 students in about half of Maine's school districts
attend public schools outside their own districts and approved
private schools under the $70 million tuition program. In August, a
federal court ruled against a group of families in Minot, Me., in a
similar school voucher case. That case is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs have 90 days to decide whether to appeal the case
to the U.S. Supreme Court. Bolick said an appeal was likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very anxious for the Supreme Court to remove any
lingering doubt about the constitutionality of school choice
programs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 state legislatures have dealt with proposals on school
vouchers, scholarship programs, tuition tax credits and other kinds
of aid involving religious schools this year, Lynn said. ``This is
probably the most ever.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Wisconsin Supreme Court upheld a program allowing
low-income students to use vouchers at religious schools. In
November, the U.S. Supreme Court declined to review the decision.
</P>
<P>
   State supreme courts in Vermont or Ohio have heard arguments on
school voucher cases, and the Florida Legislature is poised to
approve the first statewide school choice program, a program that
libertarian groups have vowed to fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-27-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
