<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-EXCLUSIVE-COX     04-27 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EXCLUSIVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chinese spying `pervasive,' panel's report will reveal
 &HT;    (EDS: Cox News Service EXCLUSIVE _ please credit. Also moved to
(a) General news category.)
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chinese spying at American nuclear laboratories has
been more widespread than originally believed and aroused
suspicions in the Energy Department earlier than previously
reported, according to the chairman of a special House committee
probing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pervasive,'' said Rep. Christopher Cox (R-Calif.), who
was appointed by former House Speaker Newt Gingrich last summer to
investigate whether sensitive technology was transferred to the
Chinese during the launches of commercial satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Cox says the committee will spell out in its
yet-to-be-declassified 700-page report that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Spying at the Los Alamos laboratory, where the atomic bomb was
developed, was first suspected by a Department of Energy
intelligence officer in 1992, three years earlier than previously
reported and four years before the White House was briefed on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   _ In addition to gathering sensitive information at Los Alamos,
spies working for the People's Republic of China obtained
classified U.S. nuclear weapons information at four other American
laboratories. Cox declined to identify the labs.
</P>
<P>
   _ China has obtained design information on nuclear warheads in
addition to the much publicized acquisition of information about
the Trident II (W-88), the most sophisticated weapon in the U.S.
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Interagency conflicts among the Justice Department, the CIA
and the Energy Department led to delays in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Loose controls over sales of supercomputers have resulted in
the Chinese obtaining sophisticated technology to conduct ``virtual
weapons tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich selected Cox to investigate American technology
transfers to China after allegations surfaced that the Chinese had
made campaign contributions to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But 75 witnesses and 24 hearings later, the findings are less
about the Clinton administration and more about how the Chinese
have infiltrated American laboratories, taking with them top secret
information about how to manufacture nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The committee unraveled a trail of espionage and national
security concerns that date back to the Carter administration and
continued throughout Reagan, Bush and Clinton administrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an investigation of the Clinton administration;
this was an investigation of espionage by the People's Republic of
China,'' Cox said. ``It happens that the espionage has gone on
through several administrations and continues on to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee recommended the administration conduct an
overall assessment of the espionage damage.
</P>
<P>
   A one-page, declassified summary of that assessment, which
contains few details, concluded: ``China obtained, by espionage,
classified U.S. nuclear weapons information that probably
accelerated its program to develop future nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox and ranking Democratic Rep. Norm Dicks of Washington gave
their findings to the president last week during a 90-minute
briefing in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   George Tenet, the director of the CIA, and Robert Walpole, a CIA
expert on strategic and nuclear programs, briefed House and Senate
members on the threat of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Samore, a senior official of the National Security Council
who was at the briefing, said there is good evidence that China
obtained nuclear weapons information from U.S. laboratories in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that this might be ongoing, which is why the
president ordered that security be strengthened at the labs,''
Samore said.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's findings leave unanswered questions about
U.S. policy toward China, according to Cox.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Energy Department more than a year before it heeded
the FBI's 1997 recommendations to strengthen security at weapons
laboratories and restrict the Chinese suspect's access to
classified information.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics contend the Clinton administration hesitated
because it was trying to craft trade policy with China and did not
want to hear about possible lapses in security at nuclear labs.
</P>
<P>
   The White House flatly disputed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are trying to use this to undercut our policy
toward China,'' said Jim Kennedy, special counsel to the president.
``The two issues are not connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Samore points to a presidential directive from February 1998
ordering strengthening of security at laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   But that directive was too late, Cox said. It is an example of
how the departments did not communicate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a number of dysfunctions'' between agencies, Cox
said. ``The Justice Department does not share information with the
intelligence community really as completely as it should.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the Los Alamos espionage case as an example, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Espionage was first suspected in 1992 by Notra Trulock, an
intelligence official at the Energy Department, who alerted
superiors. Trulock was subpoenaed to testify several times before
the Cox committee.
</P>
<P>
   During that testimony, the committee learned that Trulock did
not share evidence of spying with the FBI until late 1995 and early
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department and the FBI began an investigation. By
April of 1996, they had enough information to brief Sandy Berger,
who at the time was President Clinton's deputy national security
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Samore said Berger's briefing in April 1996 was focused on the
loss of information pertaining to the Trident II (W-88). Soon
afterward, the Justice Department opened an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In July of 1997, Trulock delivered a more expansive briefing at
the White House, Samore said. As a result, Clinton ordered security
tightened at all labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acted very appropriately, very decisively,'' Samore said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox's committee has drafted a batch of 10 bills that he hopes
Congress will enact to improve national security and clamp down on
the Chinese spy network.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee has drafted other recommendations on the
espionage problem, among them a call for the president to deliver
an espionage assessment to the leadership of the House and the
Senate every six months.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have warned about the transfer of technology to China
say the report's recommendations should be stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are clearly moving in the direction of having
hundreds of warheads aimed at the U.S. _ all mounted on systems
that will be much more difficult for the U.S. to target or
defend,'' said Henry Sokolski, executive director of the
Nonproliferation Policy Education Center, a nonprofit, nonpartisan
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese will also have the capability to improve their
weapons reaching throughout Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger question _ if the milk is spilled, how do we deal
with the consequences?'' Sokolski said. ``I don't know how we will
clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
