<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-27 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-N     04-27 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS GLADLY ACCEPT GIFTS FROM BARRASSO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ In the previous two seasons, the Devils were
frustrated during the playoffs by the goaltending of the Rangers'
Mike Richter and Ottawa's Damian Rhodes. Tuesday night, they
finally ran into an ineffective goaltender as the Penguins' Tom
Barrasso allowed a couple of soft goals in the Devils' 4-2 victory
at the Civic Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils evened the four-of-seven-game opening-round series at
two games each. Game 5 will be played in the Continental Arena on
Friday night and Game 6 here Sunday. If a seventh is necessary, it
will be held in New Jersey next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils ended a streak of seven consecutive road playoff
losses that began with their surprising 1997 second-round ouster by
the Rangers and extended into last year's first-round elimination
by the Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rolston, Randy McKay, Sergei Brylin and Scott Stevens beat
Barrasso.
</P>
<P>
   Jaromir Jagr, the Penguins' star, was sidelined for the third
straight game with a strained groin. Center Martin Straka, who
scored three goals in the Penguins' 4-2 victory in Game 3, was
knocked off the puck nearly every time he touched it. Martin
Brodeur, the Devils' goalie, had a rather easy night, but allowed
goals to Jan Hrdina and Rob Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur faced only 18 shots while Barrasso faced 39.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils scored 1 minute 38 seconds into the game when
Rolston's blistering shot from just inside the blue line went in
between Barasso's pads with the Penguins on a power play. It was
Rolston's sixth short-handed goal of the season and the league-high
15th allowed by Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, we got some big breaks tonight,'' Rolston said.
``I was surprised that I beat him from so far. We wanted to throw
pucks at him and force him to make the saves.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston's goal, which came while the Devils were killing a
holding penalty to McKay, provided the first sign that Barrasso
would not be stealing a game for his team.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Bombardir, a Devils defenseman, said: ``We challenged
ourselves before the game to raise it to a higher level and we came
out and played hard. Now we've got to get the momentum back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hrdina brought the Penguins even just 72 seconds later when he
beat Brodeur from close range on the left after a cross-ice pass
from Brown during the same penalty to McKay.
</P>
<P>
   McKay atoned for his penalty with 42 seconds left in the period.
Standing in front of Barrasso, McKay deflected Brylin's shot into
the net, then seemed surprised that the puck went in.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-one seconds after the first intermission, the Devils
extended their lead to 3-1 when Brylin's shot from the left circle
beat Barrasso on another soft goal.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur wasn't much sharper at the other end on Brown's first
goal in the series. His glove reaction was slow as Brown's shot
from the left circle sailed into the net at 7:28.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens restored the Devils' two-goal lead in the third period
by scoring three seconds before the end of a power play on a shot
from near the blue line on which Barrasso was screened by McKay.
That goal, at 2:50, followed a penalty on Pittsburgh for having men
many men on the ice after during a poor line change.
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso's best moment came with 9:44 left when he denied Brylin
on a breakaway and then covered up Holik's rebound by falling on
his back. But the damage had already been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between today and Sunday was that we played for
60 minutes,'' said Bobby Holik, the Devils' center, who had three
assists. ``We got a good effort from everybody and it makes us
happy. Now we have to carry the same effort to our home ice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
